<SLUG> BC-BUSH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ACCUSES GORE OF `WASHINGTON DOUBLESPEAK' ON DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS with 10 new grafs bgng `Gore's camp...' New material includes
reporting on Bush's remark re Times reporter.)  
(With CAMPAIGN-DEBATES, GORE) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROMEO, Mich. _ Declaring ``it's time to elect people who say
what they mean,'' Gov. George W. Bush swept through two hotly
contested states Monday and derided Vice President Al Gore for
rejecting his proposal for three handpicked debates.
</P>
<P>
   As the presidential campaign entered the critical period that
begins on Labor Day, Bush hammered at Gore's honesty and
credibility, tying him to some of the evasions of the Clinton
years. Before a pompom and placard waving crowd in the Chicago
suburbs, Bush reminded enthusiastic throngs of Gore's defense for
making fund-raising calls from his White House office in 1996: that
``no controlling legal authority'' barred such activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to get rid of all those words like `no controlling
legal authority,''' Bush said, campaigning in shirt sleeves with
his running mate, Dick Cheney, at his side. ``We need plain-spoken
Americans in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after Bush rebuffed a schedule set up by the Commission on
Presidential Debates, a bipartisan group that has sponsored debates
since 1988, and put forth a plan of his own, he recounted how Gore
had once said he would debate ``anytime, anywhere,'' and then
rejected Bush's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, the words about anytime, anywhere don't mean
anything,'' Bush said, calling Gore's rejection of his debate
proposal ``an interesting example of kind of the Washington
doublespeak.'' Bush repeated like a mantra, ``It's time to get some
plain-spoken folks in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   The throngs gathered in a schoolyard in Naperville, Ill., began
chanting, ``No more Gore. No more Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, ``When we tell you something, we mean it. When we say
we're going to do something, we're going to do what we say. That's
what America hungers for. America wants leadership that lifts its
spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his aides flatly rejected Bush's proposal on Sunday,
saying the Republican nominee was trying to limit viewers, instead
of accepting the three 90-minute debates proposed by the
commission, which would be broadcast by all three major television
networks. Two of Bush's suggested hourlong appearances would be on
talk shows that rival networks have said they would not broadcast.
Bush did agree to one presidential debate sponsored by the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's camp, of course, has a different view of the debate
issue. Gore has frequently said he would debate anytime, anywhere,
and his campaign has boasted that he has accepted more than 40
debate offers, without qualification.
</P>
<P>
   But on Air Force Two early Monday, Gore said he had accepted the
debates only on the condition that Bush accept the three debates
sponsored by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said some time ago, the condition is we have to have the
commission debates,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday morning on NBC's ``Today'' show,'' Matt Lauer, the
co-host, said to Gore that he had not set such a condition in July
when he accepted a debate offer from Tim Russert of ``Meet the
Press,'' a program that Bush has also agreed to debate on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Gore replied, ``back in March I suggested we debate
twice a week and get rid of all the TV commercials, but he's turned
all that down. But here's the point, Matt. This is not about what
is best for George W. Bush or what is best for Al Gore. It's about
what's best for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush started off the day with the rally at Naperville North High
School. While waiting to speak, he leaned over to his running mate,
Dick Cheney, and used an obscenity to describe a New York Times
correspondent, Adam Clymer, who was in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, his aides said, thought he was speaking privately. But his
words were picked up by a television microphone, though they were
barely audible to the crowd. Asked later about the comment, Bush
said, ``Well, I regret that a private comment I made to the
vice-presidential candidate made it to the public airwaves.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he wanted to apologize, Bush repeated that he was
sorry the comment had been heard. Bush's director of
communications, Karen P. Hughes, said of Clymer, ``There's been a
series of articles that the governor has felt have been very
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lelyveld, the paper's executive editor, said: ``This is
at least Adam's eighth campaign. He knows what he is doing. His
work is both fair and accurate. The Times has never heard from the
Bush campaign about Adam. If they have a complaint, they should
convey it to us and we will review it as we do all serious
complaints about our coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign pounced on the incident to portray Bush as
mean-spirited. A spokesman for Gore, Mark Fabiani, said that Bush
had ``portrayed himself as a person who wants to change the tone
and has broken his promise twice, with negative ads and by using an
expletive in referring to a New York Times reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's rally on the grounds of the Naperville North High School
began a Labor Day swing that carried him through Illinois, Michigan
and Pennsylvania, all states that President Clinton carried four
years ago. Recent polls have shown Gore pulling ahead in all three.
</P>
<P>
   At Bush's rally, a spirited crowd hoisted placards like
``Hunters for Bush'' or ``Gore in Hand is Worth Half of a Bush.''
Bush then marched in a Labor Day parade that was led by fire trucks
and emergency vehicles with sirens wailing.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he spoke at the peach festival here in Romeo, once again
needling Gore for refusing to debate ``anytime, anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, that must depend on what the definition of `anytime'
is,'' Bush said, in an allusion to Clinton's evasive use of the
word ``is'' when questioned about his affair with a White House
intern. ``Or maybe that depends on what the definition of
`anywhere' is.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush was off to Allentown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday he plans to give out more details of a prescription
drug plan while barnstorming across Pennsylvania. Karen Hughes,
Bush's communications director, said he was focusing on swing
voters and noted that Romeo was in Macomb County, the original home
of the so-called Reagan Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again Monday, Bush tied his Democratic rival to
Washington and to big government. ``My opponent and the folks up in
Washington want to empower bureaucrats and make the health
decisions for America,'' he said. ``They want more power in
Washington. They want the planners and deciders, the folks that are
telling you how to think, in power.''
</P>
<P>
   He also contrasted the two men's approaches to tax cutting and
the federal surplus. ``We understand the surplus is not the
government's money,'' he said. ``The surplus is the people's
money.'' Bush has proposed a sweeping tax cut of $1.3 trillion
across 10 years while Gore has called for tax cuts of less than
half that and more spending on social programs like college
education and home health care.
</P>
<P>
   To dramatize his points, Bush held up four dollar bills as he
spoke, and ticked off how he would use a projected federal surplus
of about $4 trillion over a decade. Just two weeks ago, Bush
stumbled over his explanation as he made similar remarks. Monday,
too, he initially seemed uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would devote $2 trillion to Social Security and he
took away two dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Next he said that he would allot $1 trillion to ``making sure
that our defense is strong,'' even though he has called in the past
for roughly $45 billion of the surplus to go to the military over a
decade. But then after talking about defense for a few more
sentences he caught himself and said that the $1 trillion covered
both military and domestic priorities like education and a Medicare
prescription drug plan.
</P>
<P>
   And when Bush got to his tax cut, he handed one of the dollars
to a man in the crowd. ``I want 1 trillion, roughly a quarter of
the surplus, to go back to the people that pay the bill,'' Bush
said. ``I want the working families to put their money in their
pockets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
