<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' STARTERS GOOD, FOR THE MOST PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Steve Dilbeck  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Anyway, the Dodgers really had been getting
outstanding starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Until Darren Dreifort ran into quick trouble Monday, the
Dodgers' recent surge easily could have been traced to an old team
stable _ strong starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   If you toss out the fifth spot in the rotation _ Carlos Perez,
are you listening? _ the Dodgers had been receiving consistently
impressive outings.
</P>
<P>
   Perez aside, in their last seven starts entering Monday, the
rotation's ERA was a combined 1.40.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the fifth spot (including Matt Herges' last start),
over their last 13 games, the team starting pitchers' ERA was 1.98,
which includes an Ismael Valdes start in which he gave up five runs
in four innings. Yet, they won that game, and 10 of the 13.
</P>
<P>
   In the three games they just completed against the Phillies, the
rotation did not allow an earned run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phillies offense has been sputtering, but we did pitch
good,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The overall staff ERA is 4.23, which, although disappointing by
Dodgers' traditional standards, is still third in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   GET READY FOR SOME OFFENSE: Perez is scheduled to make his third
start since going back into the rotation tonight.
</P>
<P>
   He has been hanging on all season, but the Dodgers have been
unable to find a decent replacement. In his last start, Perez (5-7,
5.39 ERA) gave up five runs in two innings.
</P>
<P>
   But Perez can find encouragement tonight from an opponent whose
struggles have been even more severe.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates right-hander Jose Silva (8-9, 5.58) has lost five of his
past six decisions and failed to last at least six innings in any
of them. He gave up eight runs in 3 innings in his last start
against the Giants. In five career appearances against the Dodgers,
Silva is 0-3 with an 11.37 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   OUTFIELD STILL THIN: With outfielders Devon White (strained left
quad) and Bruce Aven (strained left oblique) both still a week away
from returning, Johnson has no true reserve outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing he has is backup catcher Paul Loduca.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good athlete, but he's not really someone to send out
as a defensive replacement,'' Johnson said. ``I like to rest Sheff
(Gary Sheffield), give him a blow at the end. He's not 100 percent
(from the flu).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we got talking the other day about (Loduca
playing) second base, third base, left field. He's a good athlete
and can get by, but I mean, that ain't my idea of a comfort zone,
having him at second base turning two with the game on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: For those who have flashed on the unthinkable, if
inevitable, veteran broadcaster Vin Scully's current contract with
the Dodgers has another season left to run. The Dodgers, however,
still expect to sign the 72-year-old icon to another contract. ...
Shortstop Kevin Elster, on the disabled list since Aug. 23 with a
strained left hamstring, will be activated today. ... Johnson said
relievers Mike Fetters (sore back) and Terry Adams (stiff shoulder)
were both available. ... Sheffield's pursuit of Duke Snider's team
home-run record of 43 has been stalled. Including the 11 games he
missed with the flu, the slugger has gone a season-high 17 games
since hitting home run No.40. His previous high was 11 games,
although he played in each.
</P>
</TEXT>
