<HEADLINE>
PEYTON'S PLACE IS WITH ALL-TIME GREATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ How good is Peyton Manning?
</P>
<P>
   This is a rhetorical question.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is as good as there is in the NFL these days. He is the
best third-year quarterback ever.
</P>
<P>
   Manning has become so Montana-esque good that his performances
sometimes are under appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Take Sunday in Kansas City. Manning completed 22 of 32 passes
for 273 yards with one touchdown and one interception against the
Chiefs. He handled the heat, the pressure and the noise to win his
first start at Arrowhead Stadium, 27-14.
</P>
<P>
   So what, you say, it was only the Chiefs?
</P>
<P>
   Consider that Troy Aikman, Dan Marino, John Elway, Drew Bledsoe,
Brett Favre and Steve Young are among the quarterbacks who lost
their first trip to Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It is the loudest stadium in the NFL. The Chiefs have led the
NFL in attendance for six consecutive seasons, including 1999 when
they averaged 78,693. Kansas City's 12th man makes it hard on
opponents, who lost 78.8 percent of the time at Arrowhead Stadium
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs had 78,357 crazies on their side Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With Arrowhead Stadium in mind, the Colts practiced using a
silent snap count during their exhibition game against the
Pittsburgh Steelers in Mexico City. Against the Chiefs, it was as
easy as 1-2-3 as Indianapolis had only two false-start penalties
and no delay of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That takes a lot of poise and composure and execution by the
offense, and you know, Peyton running the show there makes a big
difference,'' Colts coach Jim Mora said.
</P>
<P>
   Manning comes as close as any quarterback in the league to
calling his own plays. He calls a play in the huddle, but he then
has two additional options after he gets to the line of scrimmage
and assesses the defense. He can check off to a running play or to
a passing play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handles that extremely well,'' Mora said. ``He's unique. We
can do those kind of things with Peyton Manning. He can go in there
and recognize the best play to call and call it at the line of
scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning burned up the 45-second clock Sunday, walking up and
down the line yelling out the play to the other 10 players. On a
second-and-7 from the Kansas City 27 in the third quarter, Manning
switched to a screen pass after reading the linebacker blitz, and
Edgerrin James scored to give the Colts a 14-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Offensive coordinator) Tom (Moore) gives me some freedom, but
everything is kind of what we worked on during practice,'' Manning,
24, said. ``In other words, I'm not going to call a play at the
line that the offensive line is going to be surprised by. That's
kind of what Tom says, `Don't surprise me. Go with what the game
plan is.' ... For the most part, I thought we handled the crowd
noise and executed on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   There were those who thought Ryan Leaf was the better
quarterback in the 1998 draft when the Colts took Manning with the
No. 1 choice and the San Diego Chargers traded five players,
counting three draft picks, to move up to take Leaf second overall.
That comparison is laughable now.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf is 3-7 in his 10 starts, having completed 128 of 284 passes
for 1,469 yards with two touchdowns and 18 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is 17-16, having gone 679-for-1,140 for 8,147 yards with
53 touchdowns and 44 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Leaf didn't do in his first two seasons was ruin
his career. The only thing Manning didn't do in his first two
seasons was win the Super Bowl, and the Colts might take care of
that this season.
</P>
<P>
   So just how good can Peyton Manning be?
</P>
<P>
   He looks like a pimply faced teen-ager. He plays like a future
Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   He has intelligence, size, arm strength and a quick release.
Now, he has experience to go with playmakers James and Marvin
Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   We just might be watching the greatest ever.
GRADING THE NFL Duce Staley: A Staley had only one carry _ for 60
yards _ in the fourth quarter against the Cowboys. He finished with
201 rushing yards, which was four yards short of Steve Van Buren's
team record and 74 behind Walter Payton's NFL record. If Buddy Ryan
still was the Eagles coach, Staley would have run straight into the
record books. Buffalo Bills: A Revenge never tasted so sweet.
Stephen Davis: C Is he the best running back in the NFL? No, but
he's now the highest paid. The $90 Million Man better have a
record-setting season for the Redskins. Fred Beasley: F They might
want to test the water in San Francisco. After rushing for 10 yards
on five carries in the 49ers' 36-28 loss to Atlanta, Beasley said
San Francisco was capable of reeling off 13 or 14 victories in a
row on its way to the Super Bowl.
Williams' Top 5 1. St. Louis Rams 1-0 2. Indianapolis Colts 1-0 3.
Tampa Bay Buccaneers 1-0 4. Buffalo Bills 1-0 5. Baltimore Ravens
1-0
Williams' Bottom 5 27. Pittsburgh Steelers 0-1 28. Arizona
Cardinals 0-1 29. San Francisco 49ers 0-1 30. Cincinnati Bengals
0-0 31. Cleveland Browns 0-1
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
