<HEADLINE>
DON'T JINX DAVIS, OR WINNING STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
CHICAGO _ Don't change the underwear. Don't wash the
champagne-soaked socks. Have the same thing for breakfast.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any deviation from normal routine would only blow it for
everybody. The Rangers are on a roll, and this is no time to jinx
the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   Getting another encouraging performance from one of their young
starters, the Rangers beat the Chicago White Sox, 5-4, Monday at
Comiskey Park, giving them an actual two-game winning streak for
the first time in more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit different now,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``Unfortunately for us, this is just another game in early
September watching young kids perform and do well. If there was one
game to go and needed a win to clinch, then you'd have to check
more than my underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates will have to settle for continued progress from two young
pitchers. Doug Davis followed Ryan Glynn's performance in Detroit
on Sunday by holding the American League's highest-scoring offense
to two runs on eight hits through six innings. He is 2-1 with a
1.52 earned-run average in his past four starts and is showing
Oates he belongs in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Oates was wondering before Davis got on this roll. Put Davis
together with Glynn, and the Rangers might salvage something out of
this wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching is hard to find, and to have a left-hander (Davis)
and a right-hander (Glynn) to come around at the same time with
their future ahead of them, that's exciting,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   If Glynn and Davis continue to pitch well, the Rangers could
have be set with their rotation for next season. They could go into
spring training with Rick Helling and Kenny Rogers back at the top,
Glynn and Davis right behind and Justin Thompson and Darren Oliver
battling for the final spot. That would allow the Rangers to devote
more resources _ through trade or free agency _ to their many other
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' previous three starts were against some pretty good
competition: Boston, New York and Toronto. But the White Sox lead
the majors with 845 runs scored, including 35 in their three
previous games.
</P>
<P>
   They also threw an all right-handed lineup against Davis, but he
foiled that strategy with his newly revived cut fastball. When
thrown by a left-hander, the cut fastball moves in hard on
right-handed hitters. Andy Pettitte of the New York Yankees uses it
effectively and so did Davis on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He jammed a lot of us, and we're not used to that,'' White Sox
center fielder Jeff Abbott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I broke about four or five bats,'' Davis said. ``I was
able to establish inside, and that opened the outer half of the
plate. I definitely need to keep that pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox got a couple runs off him early. Ray Durham
doubled and Frank Thomas singled for one run in the first, and the
White Sox opened the second with singles from Carlos Lee, Herbert
Perry and Paul Konerko to take a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis got out of the jam by getting Abbott to ground out,
striking out Charles Johnson and getting Durham on a grounder.
Starting with those three hitters, the White Sox were hitless in
their last eight at-bats against Davis with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got starter stuff,'' Oates said. ``I'd much rather have
him start than pitch in relief. He's more valuable there. I'm glad
to see these last four starts. I wasn't sure what I was seeing
before.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
