<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0895 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     09-05 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
 
McCANN LOOKS TO TAKE ADVANTAGE OF HIS OPPORTUNITY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Billy Witz  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first full day of the Ryan McCann era began
appropriately enough. He drove from his West L.A. apartment complex
Sunday to his parents' home in Westlake Village and, after watching
the afternoon NFL games, headed down the street for the 5 o'clock
Mass at St. Jude's Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone needed time to reflect and say a few hosannas it was
McCann.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, McCann went from baseball-cap-wearing,
clipboard-toting cheerleader to the man who will hold UCLA's future
_ as well as his own _ in his hands when he lines up as starting
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He held onto both quite nicely Saturday, taking over when Cory
Paus was sidelined with a separated right (throwing) shoulder and
leading the Bruins to a stunning 35-24 upset of then-No.3-ranked
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Paus expected to miss the next three games, McCann
will have the opportunity to do what he couldn't do at the end of
last season or in fall camp: win the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   There was a reason Paus beat out McCann last month _ he threw
more accurately, made fewer mistakes and had better command of the
offense. But if the Bruins beat Fresno State, No.3 Michigan and
Oregon with McCann at the helm, even UCLA coach Bob Toledo conceded
it would be hard to take the sophomore from Agoura Hills High out
of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do everything I can to help the team win,'' McCann
said. ``Whatever they ask of me I'm going to do. I'm going to do my
best. I'm going to try to keep the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cory's going to be like a bad cold he's always going to come
back. He'll be there, so I've got to stay on top of my game. ...
Coach Toledo told me I had to be patient and be ready for your
opportunity when it comes. When it did happen, he told me, `Here's
your chance. You wanted an opportunity, here it is.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now that it is here, McCann plans to go at it with the same
determination he's shown since he came to UCLA. He began last
season as the Bruins No.4 quarterback but ended up starting against
USC when Drew Bennett was moved to receiver, Paus was injured and
he beat out Scott McEwan.
</P>
<P>
   After Toledo cut short this year's competition two days earlier
than he planned because Paus was clearly ahead, McCann lived up to
his vow to continue working. He is the last person off the practice
field virtually every day, working an extra 15 to 20 minutes with
freshman receiver Tab Perry. He was out there again after practice
ended Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the majority of the reps in practice this week will
help, but what will help McCann the most, he says, is the game
experience.
</P>
<P>
   He's taken significant snaps in just three games, but they were
all big ones. He relieved the injured Paus and led UCLA to an
overtime win over Washington and threw three interceptions in a
loss to USC last season. Against Alabama, he overcame a critical
mistake _ a 91-yard interception return for a go-ahead touchdown by
Reggie Myles _ by responding with the game-winning score, a 46-yard
touchdown pass, the first of his career, to Freddie Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt mentally prepared, but I didn't know how physically
prepared I'd be,'' McCann said of the Alabama game. ``You actually
have to do it, you have to play. That's the thing I need the most
to mature as a QB is the experience, the playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo made it clear that while he's handing McCann the keys to
the car, McCann needs to do a better job driving it. McCann's
numbers against Alabama looked solid (14 of 24 for 187 yards with
one TD and one interception), but he took some unnecessary sacks
and didn't throw the long ball accurately. In fact, he was lucky
not to have two more balls picked off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan needs to continue to improve,'' Toledo said. ``He needs
to work on some accuracy. He needs to complete some balls that are
there, and he needs to pull the trigger. He has a tendency to get
sacked sometimes when guys are open because he wants them more
open. They're not always going to be that open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a couple of mistakes operating the offense. He still
has to learn some things, but we'll continue to coach him hard.
He's a very coachable kid. He needs to continue to improve. It's
going to be on-the-job training. He does have an awful lot of
potential and athletic ability. Sometimes he looks like a Heisman
trophy candidate and other times he struggles.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann downplayed his situation Monday, saying he didn't want to
overemphasize the importance of each play and each game. However,
he does remember that Cade McNown became the starting quarterback
midway through his freshman season and never returned to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a big window for him,'' said receiver Jon
Dubravac, McCann's roommate since they were freshmen. ``It comes up
in my conversations with him and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible way to get the job, but you're not going to
complain. If (Brian) Poli(-Dixon) got hurt, it would be terrible
but I'd have to show I can fill his shoes. It's a huge door that's
opened for Ryan and he realizes it. It's a second chance for him to
do something for himself and shine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
