<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUS TO MISS NEXT THREE GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Billy Witz  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cory Paus, his right arm in a sling, stood on the
sidelines in shorts, a T-shirt and a baseball cap and watched
practice Monday. The quarterback felt just as he did when he
separated his throwing shoulder on the first play Saturday against
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a pansy,'' Paus said. ``It looks like I'm
fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus is expected to miss the next three games for UCLA with what
doctors determined was a 1- to second-degree shoulder separation.
It is the fourth time in 12 games at UCLA that he has been knocked
from the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Paus suffered bruised ribs, a separated left shoulder and a
broken collarbone last season. Then, on the first play of this
season, Alabama defensive end Jarret Johnson blew into the
backfield and hit Paus from behind. Johnson drove Paus into the
turf after he released the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another test for me,'' Paus said. ``I'll have to work
extra hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus is in an uncomfortable position: He wants the Bruins to do
well, although he is well aware that success under Ryan McCann
could cost him his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I want the team to be undefeated,'' Paus said.
``The rest is up to the coaches. I don't have any control over
that. I can't lose any confidence in myself. I just have to keep
doing what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo had plenty of empathy for Paus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel for him,'' the coach said. ``He got hurt (last
season), worked so hard and it happens again. He's got to be
asking, `Why me?' I keep stroking him and tell him it's going to
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   LATE HIT: Toledo filed a complaint with Verle Sorgen, the
Pac-10's coordinator of football officials, over Johnson's hit. He
claimed it should have been called a late hit with a penalty
assessed.
</P>
<P>
   POLLING DATA: UCLA was ranked 16th by the writers and 17th by
the coaches, but in both polls the Bruins were behind Alabama
something that miffed Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   However, one voter tickled Toledo: Jake Curtis of the San
Francisco Chronicle, who voted the Bruins No. 1. It was the only
such vote among the 71 writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I phoned in my Top 25 (to Associated Press headquarters),
the guy said, `You've got UCLA No. 1? Are you sure you want to do
that?''' Curtis said. ``(But) who's had better results this season?
I don't understand why so much weight is put on preseason polls.
They're nothing but speculation. I wipe the slate clean every week.
If Alabama loses to Podunk U. next week the whole thing could
change.''
</P>
<P>
   COMINGS AND GOINGS: Paul Nelson, a receiver who quit the team
two weeks ago over concerns about playing time, plans to enroll and
begin practicing today at San Diego State. Nelson, who also
considered UNLV, will be a junior next season.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Santi Hall, who was dismissed from the team three
weeks ago, is at Sacramento State and receiver Ryan Smith, who left
the team, has returned. Also, defensive tackle Doug Whiting, who
didn't figure to play this season, was dismissed for violating team
policy, according to Toledo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0897 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATE-NYT &LR;      09-05 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS AND ABC OBJECT TO BUSH'S PROPOSAL FOR DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two television networks that were left out of Gov. George W.
Bush's plan to impose his own schedule of debates declared Monday
that they had no intention of carrying presidential debates
sponsored by rival networks.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush proposal, announced on Sunday after intense
negotiations with officials of six cable and broadcast networks,
has thrown into turmoil the work of the Commission on Presidential
Debates, the panel created in 1987 by the Democrats and the
Republicans to avoid squabbling over the debates. Since the
creation of the panel, no candidate has gone so far as Bush has
gone to circumvent its work.
</P>
<P>
   But on the campaign trail Monday, Bush said that by rejecting
his proposal, Gore was ducking debates and going back on his word
to face off with him at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp countered that Mr. Bush was trying to tailor the
debates to his own liking, then blame Mr. Gore for rejecting them.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Brown, the commission's executive director, said that the
panel has asked officials of both the Bush and Gore campaigns to
meet in Washington this week to work out an agreement under which
Bush would consent to the commission's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe our proposal is the best one,'' Brown
said. ``I believe the campaigns when they say they want to debate
in a way that reaches the maximum number of people, and the way to
do that is to implement the commission's plan.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, the commission announced its plans for three
90-minute debates in October on college campuses in Boston,
Winston-Salem, N.C., and St. Louis, a plan that Vice President Al
Gore quickly endorsed. On Sunday, Bush unveiled his own proposal,
which would include the commission-sponsored debate in St. Louis,
but would substitute the others with two one-hour encounters, one
next week on a prime-time edition of ``Meet the Press'' with Tim
Russert on NBC, and the other on Oct. 3 on CNN's ``Larry King
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission was established not only to eliminate this sort
of jockeying, but also to ensure that the debates could be seen by
the most viewers across as many channels as possible. In one debate
in 1992, for instance, 92 million viewers tuned in.
</P>
<P>
   But executives of networks that were turned down by Bush made it
clear that they would not devote air time to what they viewed
chiefly as promotional opportunities for Russert and King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it might be in the interest of some of the
parties involved to call them debates, but these are basically
versions of existing talk shows, and we don't normally air other
people's talk shows,'' said Andrew Heyward, the president of CBS
News.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Friedman, the executive vice president of ABC News, echoed
Heyward, saying, ``It's very unlikely we would cover other
networks' programs, and that is essentially what they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Both NBC News and CNN said Monday that they would make their
debates available to competing networks in what is known as a
``clean feed'' _ a transmission that leaves off the originating
network's identifying symbol in the corner of the screen. In
addition, NBC and CNN said they would carry each other's debate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush continued to batter each other with the debate
issue Monday. While aides to Gore called Bush arrogant for his
rejection of the commission plan, the Bush camp reminded reporters
that the vice president had agreed to debate the governor anywhere,
anytime. Gore has said he would do the debates on ``Meet the
Press'' and ``Larry King Live'' if Bush agrees to the commission
debates.
</P>
<P>
   And though Gore insisted he would never agree to Bush's
conditions, aides to Bush said they remain convinced that if
pressure were brought to bear on the vice president to appear with
Bush on the two programs, other networks would be compelled to put
the debates on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do suspect that if Al Gore were to show up on `Meet the
Press,''' said one top Bush official who demanded anonymity, ``all
the networks, with their dedication to public service, would be
hard-pressed not to cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear, however, that many of the networks were feeling
slightly uncomfortable over any role they might be playing in
subverting the work of the debate commission. Privately, some
broadcast journalists expressed outrage at what they viewed as the
networks allowing themselves to be used by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on here is a maneuvering for position, and
journalists should be very wary of getting roped into that,'' said
Heyward of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, CBS was among the networks that made a pitch to
Bush for a debate on ``Face the Nation.'' Heyward explained,
however, that he made it a condition that such a debate could only
happen if the commission's plan fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to get drawn into where the network broadcasts
were used as bargaining chips,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In its offer letter, CNN wrote both campaigns that its debate
would ``encompass a typical `Larry King Live' format.'' The network
proposed two coin tosses _ ``one for seat preference and one for
question order'' _ and asserted that the program would not take
viewer calls or use video clips.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Wheatley, vice president of NBC News, said his network had
long ago made an offer to both camps for a ``Meet the Press''
debate. ``And in recent weeks,'' he added, ``as it became clear
that there was going to be further discussion on the nature of the
debates, we pressed home that request, saying that `you could have
a `Meet the Press' in prime time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, NBC found itself in the position of being championed by
the Bush campaign over the debate issue. In an e-mail message to
reporters Monday, Ari Fleischer, a Bush spokesman, said Gore was
now ``backpedaling'' from a commitment made months ago to debate on
``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush believes the first debate should allow for more
than just sound bites; it should feature an in-depth discussion of
the issues and have tough questioning,'' Fleischer wrote. ``Having
the first debate on `Meet the Press' will allow such an exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley, however, brushed aside any suggestion that the Bush
campaign was using NBC as a means of undoing the commission. He
added that scheduling the program in September would be a service
to viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that our proposal gives the public an opportunity
to give these men a chance to debate a month earlier,'' he said.
``Otherwise, the commission debates don't begin until October.''
</P>
<P>
   For the debate commission, the Bush plan is a potentially
serious disruption of its mission. ``All the debates have been in
communities, on campuses, or in towns,'' Brown said. ``These are
the single set of political events that the public still thinks
belongs to them. We believe taking them to communities where
thousands of young people can participate is a very good thing that
can't take place if you do two debates in television studios.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she hopes to be able to convince Bush's aides that
the commission plan is an enhanced version of the proposal they
have offered. ``We think campuses are preferable to studios,'' she
said, ``and we belive that six networks are preferable to one or
two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
