<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0911 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-ARMY-CINCINNATI-N     09-05 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARMY-CINCINNATI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI BEATS ARMY, 23-17 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ They had something old _ an 0-4 record in season
openers away from West Point. They had a bunch of new stuff _ a
head coach for one, Todd Berry, who brought a one-back,
multiple-spread offense to put the ball in the air. They had
something borrowed _ a gray stripe added to each jersey sleeve to
represent the U.S. Corps of Cadets, as well as the uniforms worn by
its championship teams of the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the new-look Army Black Knights had something to be
blue about, though, as their multiweapon attack came up short
against their Conference USA rival Cincinnati, 23-17, before 23,311
here at Nippert Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   While the Black Knights were intent on showing the new wrinkles
in their offense, the Bearcats, behind running backs Ray Jackson
and DeMarco McCleskey, rolled up a ground game like the Army of
old. The twosome combined for 198 yards, and Jackson blew threw the
middle of the Black Knight defense for a 37-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Cincinnati's quarterback, Deontey Kenner, who undid
Army with a time-killing nine-play, 78-yard drive that ended with
his rolling right and slinging a 12-yard pass to a wide-open Jason
Collins Baker in the end zone to give the Bearcats a 20-17 lead
with six minutes left in the game. Kenner, a senior, was 18 of 29
for 239 yards as he continued his pursuit of virtually all of
Cincinnati's career passing records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense was rolling,'' said Army linebacker Brian
Zickefoose, who had 10 tackles. ``We just didn't get it done on
defense. Those two big backs wore us down late, and their passer
picked us apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, the Army Athletic Association, after a
marketing study, unveiled a new logo _ a sleek knight on horseback
over the word Army _ and a plan to build a consistent brand image.
The Army athletic teams would always be called the Black Knights,
and the once preferred use of the ``Cadets'' discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change, however, was made the previous year, when
coach Bob Sutton was replaced after back-to-back 3-8 seasons. In
came Berry, who in 1999 had taken Illinois State to the best finish
in school history, 11-3, and the semifinals of the DivisionI-AA
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things the 39-year-old Berry did was scrap the
earthbound wishbone offense that had rolled Army to four national
rushing titles. Despite the cosmetic homage to history _ the gray
stripe worn by the Heisman Trophy winners Doc Blanchard and Glenn
Davis and the jerseys without names _ Army started its 111th season
a thoroughly modern team.
</P>
<P>
   Its first two plays of the game were passes, though quarterback
Chad Jenkins failed to connect with receivers. And, after
Cincinnati place-kicker Jonathan Ruffin booted his third field goal
of the day, a 26-yarder with 31 seconds to play, the Black Knights
tried a cross-field, backward pass on the ensuing kickoff return.
The play went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fired every bullet we had and didn't leave anything in our
bag,'' Berry said. ``At times, you could tell our guys weren't
completely comfortable with everything we were doing. I've got very
bright young men out there, and they're going to get better. I
think you could see that they were having fun out there.''
</P>
<P>
   There were also many encouraging performances turned in by Army
players, though the team's 243 yards of total offense was far below
the 323 rushing yards they averaged last year in the wishbone.
After a 2-of-8 first half, Jenkins, a junior, went 12 of 21 and led
scoring drives of 80 and 95 yards. He spread the ball to four
receivers and showed a deft touch when he found the junior Omari
Thompson on a 31-yard crossing pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins even gave Army a 17-13 lead early in the first quarter
when he rolled right and tossed a swing pass to running back
Michael Wallace, who rushed for 894 yards last year but had never
caught a pass in his career at Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great,'' Wallace, a senior, said after his first
reception turned out to be a touchdown. ``I like running the ball,
but it's nice to be swung out wide and have a chance to get it and
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, tight end Clint Dodson smiled. He had a reason to. He
had six catches for 44 yards _ five more than he had all of last
season. The new logo, new uniform and especially the new offense is
fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost today, and it hurts,'' he said, ``but once we figure
this all out I think we're going to be a dangerous team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
