<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT ROYALS, 4-3, WITHOUT WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ An inning or two passed before all of Bernie
Williams' teammates realized that he had been removed from Monday
night's game after he strained his rib cage again. They will all be
fully aware of his status, however, if the injury lingers into next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees believe he will recover before the postseason, but
rib-cage injuries are delicate and another setback could be
serious. They won without Williams Monday night, 4-3, barely
holding their slim lead against the Kansas City Royals through
anxious moments in the eighth and ninth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte improved his record to 17-7, Jorge Posada had
three hits and increased his batting average to .301, and David
Justice drove in a run, his 100th of the season. But the Yankees
(77-57) tend to think big picture _ as in the playoffs and the
World Series _ and Williams' status seemed to dominate the thoughts
of manager Joe Torre after the game. ``At this time,'' Torre said,
he does not think Williams' injury will linger. ``If it goes a week
and he's still hurting, then you wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitting Williams initially strained the right side of
his rib cage on Aug. 18 and missed little more than a week before
returning to the lineup _ primarily as a right-handed hitter,
because the strain bothered him more while batting from the left
side. Williams said Monday night that when he returned, he felt
strong and he was swinging hard; Torre wondered aloud after the
game if Williams might have been more sore than he was letting on.
</P>
<P>
   Batting in the first inning, Williams swung at and missed Mac
Suzuki's first pitch, a split-finger fastball, and felt a pain in
his side. Torre did not notice Williams' physical reaction to the
discomfort, but the trainer Gene Monahan did, and when Williams
returned to the dugout after playing defense in the bottom of the
first inning, Torre cornered Williams and essentially forced him
into confessing his pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' Williams said. ``It's certainly very
bad timing. We'll see how I feel tomorrow. I'm taking it on a daily
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams figures to miss at least the next five games, when the
Yankees face right-handed starters, and probably more, in light of
the Yankees' six-game lead over Boston in the American League East
and Torre's dedication to getting the team prepared for the
postseason. He has stressed to all his players that they must be
honest about their ailments now. ``We don't have time to get
something well, if we have a major problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte said it ``would be a huge blow to us'' to lose Williams
for a long time, ``banged up as it is in the outfield.'' Right
fielder Paul O'Neill is limping with a hip pointer, and Justice,
the left fielder, is playing despite a strained right groin.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' injury will almost certainly end his bid to surpass
one of Mickey Mantle's notable achievements. Mantle drove in 130
runs in 1956, setting a major league season record by a
switch-hitter, and San Diego's Ken Caminiti tied that mark in 1996.
Williams had 80 runs batted in over 83 games at the All-Star Game
break, and now he has 111 RBIs with 28 games to play _ and he will
miss some or most of those games.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte can still reach a personal milestone, now that he is
within three victories of 20 for the season, but Monday night's
victory did not come easily. Working quickly, Pettitte allowed
eight hits in seven innings, six of those to the No. 3 and No. 4
batters for Kansas City, Mike Sweeney and Jermaine Dye.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led, 4-2, in the eighth. Johnny Damon doubled to
lead off, however, and after Pettitte struck out Carlos Beltran,
Sweeney and Dye were due to hit again. Torre went to the mound.
``What are the odds?'' Pettitte asked about the chances of allowing
more hits to Sweeney and Dye, but Torre was unimpressed, calling on
Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, one of those chastised by George Steinbrenner last week,
allowed Damon to score on Sweeney's infield single and prompted
separate meetings with Posada and the pitching coach Mel
Stottlemyre before striking out Joe Randa to end the eighth. Nelson
lurched off the mound happily, waving his arms; Nelson needed that
outing, Torre mused.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera took over for the ninth, and his relative
vulnerability was apparent again. There were a leadoff single and a
two-out walk, and the pinch-hitter Wilson Delgado _ formerly with
the Yankees this season _ beat out an infield hit. Bases loaded,
Sweeney at the plate. Rivera opened with a high fastball, and
Sweeney hacked confidently at it, fouling it off, an
uncharacteristically aggressive swing against the Yankees' closer.
With two strikes, Sweeney smashed a liner to center, directly at
Clay Bellinger, who had replaced Williams in center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
