<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
UT's BROWN TO DELAY MAKING A CHOICE AT QB (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram AUSTIN _ In an effort to minimize distractions and prolong the
evaluation process, Texas football coach Mack Brown said he does
not plan to select a starting quarterback until minutes before
Saturday's 11:30 a.m. kickoff against Louisiana-Lafayette.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We'll make the decision some time before game time and we
probably won't tell anybody except the two quarterbacks. I don't
think the team will know until they run out on the field,'' Brown
said Monday during a news conference. ``There's absolutely no
reason for me to do this'' before Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Following a different course of action, Brown said, ``would be
disruptive to me and the players this week,'' because it would
trigger more questions from the media.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's decision to delay a decision on whether Chris Simms or
Major Applewhite will open at quarterback for the sixth-ranked
Longhorns will allow Texas fans to continue an eight-month debate
on the merits of the respective players.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite, the 1999 Big 12 offensive player of the year,
underwent reconstructive knee surgery in January. Since reporting
for fall drills, the junior has not experienced swelling in his
knee. But he has not been exposed to contact since tearing his
anterior cruciate ligament Jan. 1 in the Southwestern Bell Cotton
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Simms, a sophomore, was the nation's top-rated quarterback
signee in 1999 and was the star of spring drills while running the
first-team offense. The son of former New York Giants quarterback
Phil Simms, the 6-foot-5, 222-pound left-hander has worked
exclusively with the first-team offense during fall drills.
Applewhite has split snaps with the first and second units.
</P>
<P>
   Both quarterbacks said they expect to play Saturday and will
accept whatever decision Brown makes about dividing playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite, who threw for a school-record 3,357 yards and 21
touchdowns last season, said he has had mixed emotions about
working primarily with the second unit during the fall. On one
hand, he said it's ``a tough pill to swallow'' for an incumbent. On
the other, he said practicing against the Longhorns' No. 1 defense
on a daily basis has made him a better player.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what, you have to prepare yourself as if you'll be
the starter,'' Applewhite said. ``It wouldn't surprise me if he
(Simms) starts. It wouldn't surprise me if I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms said he has no problem waiting to learn of his status
until Saturday, but hinted that Texas coaches mightbe close to
reaching a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they have a little idea in their mind,'' Simms said.
``They let us know the deal. I think we're both comfortable right
now with everything and that's all that matters. The coaches have
done a real good job of making us both feel good. Coach Brown is
real cool under this kind of pressure. I trust that he'll do the
right thing.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
