<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNEE INJURY SHELVES GALLOWAY FOR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
IRVING _ The Cowboys found out Monday it can get worse.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adding injury to insult, the aftermath of the Cowboys'
confidence-rattling, season-opening 41-14 loss to the Philadelphia
Eagles at Texas Stadium on Sunday came with the grimmest of news:
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Joey Galloway will miss the remainder of the
season with a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee. The
much-anticipated, new timing-based offense was to be centered
around Galloway, who instead saw his season end on a play with less
than three minutes left in a 27-point blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman is listed as ``questionable'' as well as
``day-to-day'' with what has been diagnosed as a ``mild
concussion,'' after a four-sack, 0-for-5 passing game in which
Aikman was on the field for 15 plays _ and on his back no fewer
than eight times.
</P>
<P>
   The concern for Aikman, 33, heightens because of his history
with concussions (eight with the Cowboys, including three in his
past 10 games) and the fact that Sunday's head injury didn't
involve a helmet-to-helmet or open-field hit.
</P>
<P>
   The results of a CT scan administered at a hospital Sunday were
negative. Aikman will be monitored closely for the next several
days, according to team officials.
</P>
<P>
   Backup quarterback Randall Cunningham, who is expected to be
Sunday night's starter at Arizona if Aikman is not cleared to play,
has a sprained thumb on his throwing hand. The last time
Cunningham, 37, started a game was Oct. 17 at Detroit as a member
of the Minnesota Vikings. The key to success will be Cunningham's
grasp of an offense in which he has little game experience, as well
as his grasp on the ball because of the thumb injury.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, no one could remember the last time there has been this
much carnage, devastation and uncertainty circling Valley Ranch,
all of which took place within a span of about 18 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But stiff upper lips and reminders that there still is a season
to play were in full force at the complex on ``Black Monday.''
Personal concerns for Aikman were mixed with positive wishes for
Galloway to make a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Among those still standing was Emmitt Smith, who had exactly as
many carries as rookie Micah Knorr had punts Sunday (seven apiece).
</P>
<P>
   When Galloway awkwardly fell out of bounds after a hard tackle
by Eagles cornerback Al Harris, Smith recalled watching from the
sideline: ``I was kind of in disbelief when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones, while speaking of injuries being part of the
game and the Cowboys having depth at wide receiver, was visibly
shaken when Galloway's MRI results became known Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing the cost (two first-round draft picks and $12.5 million
in up-front money on Galloway's seven-year, $42 million contract)
and the loss, Jones said, ``I don't know how to describe to you how
disappointed I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Momentarily, words got stuck in Jones' throat as he explained
that he might take a few days ``to dwell'' on the loss of Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have made the commitment we made to bring Joey here and the
type of impact that we all felt he could have on this offense, I
don't know that I've ever had to make the kind of adjustment we're
trying to make (so immediately after) such a commitment,'' said
Jones, who added that he did not have a problem with the decision
to leave Galloway in the game late in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Aikman's concussion was ``not to the degree'' of his
Oct. 31 concussion in Indianapolis, which was followed eight days
later by a concussion in Minnesota. Aikman sat out the next two
games after visiting two neurosurgeons.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was concerned about the cumulative effect of
concussions on his teammate and friend, Smith said, ``My concern is
more for his protection. We, as players, have to do a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he phoned Aikman on Monday morning and left a
voice-mail to the effect that he deeply cares about and fully
supports his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs some time to get away and think,'' Smith said. ``Troy
is astute enough, smart enough, to know whether or not he can get
back on the field and perform at his best, and whether or not he's
willing to take the risk.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
