<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS OUTLAST BRONCOS, 41-36 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The St. Louis Rams threw a pregame party Monday
night. It featured eight cannon shots, each one sounding like a
stick of dynamite being detonated. There were fireworks, rock music
and the St. Louis owner, Georgia Frontiere, raising the Lombardi
Trophy above her head and giving it a smooch.
</P>
<P>
   It was a beautiful scene for the sellout crowd at the Trans
World Dome until Denver Broncos coach Mike Shanahan nearly ruined
everything with a masterful game plan of aggressive offense and
relentless, ball-hawking defense.
</P>
<P>
   Led by quarterback Brian Griese, the Broncos took a 1-point lead
with six minutes left. But the speed of the Rams _ overpowering and
practically unstoppable _ helped them avoid an embarrassing
season-opening loss. St. Louis beat Denver, 41-36, in one of the
most exciting regular-season games in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis looked as if it might cruise after a gorgeous 72-yard
touchdown run by Marshall Faulk and a dazzling 80-yard touchdown
catch by wide receiver Az-Zahir Hakim. The score was 35-20 with 4
minutes 2 seconds remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Griese showed why he might do just fine in his second year
as John Elway's replacement. He threw a 7-yard score to Desmond
Clark to make the score 35-27, and then Denver managed a 36-yard
field goal by Jason Elam to cut the score to 35-30.
</P>
<P>
   Then disaster struck for the Rams. Kurt Warner, last season's
most valuable player, tried to squeeze a pass on the left sideline
to Torry Holt. The throw was intercepted by cornerback Terrell
Buckley, who returned it untouched 32 yards for a touchdown. Denver
led by 36-35.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk made another spectacular run, this time for 30 yards,
which put St. Louis at the Denver 1-yard line. Fullback Robert
Holcombe ran it in from there and, after a failed 2-point
conversion, the Rams led by 41-36 with 2:58 left.
</P>
<P>
   Griese finally ran out of miracles. On third-and-21 at Denver's
27-yard line, he was sacked by defensive lineman Kevin Carter for a
12-yard loss. Then on fourth down, Griese was hit in the back by
defensive end Grant Wistrom, which rocked Griese so hard the ball
went fluttering into the air and landed harmlessly on the ground.
Game over.
</P>
<P>
   Warner completed 25 of 35 passes for 441 yards and three
touchdowns, two of them covering 152 yards in the third quarter on
throws in the flat.
</P>
<P>
   Griese was 19 of 28 for 307 yards, throwing for two touchdowns
and running for a third.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, who missed 12 games games last season with a knee
injury, rushed for 34 yards on nine carries before leaving the game
in the second quarter with a twisted left knee. His replacement,
Olandis Gary, rumbled for 80 yards on 13 carries.
</P>
<P>
   For a defending champion, the Rams have received surprisingly
little respect. Many in football, and the news media, believe
Washington and Tampa Bay might be better than St. Louis and are
picking one of those teams as top candidates to reach the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The early part of the game showed how difficult it is for a team
to defend its title. Defensively, Denver used a mixture of
secondary coverages, including a healthy dose of man-to-man, always
dangerous against the game's fastest fleet of wide receivers. The
Broncos did not seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Denver was even more aggressive. On its first
touchdown drive, there was a lot of Davis, but Shanahan also took
the shackles off Griese, allowing him to throw deep. The Broncos
took a 7-0 lead when Griese scored on an 8-yard bootleg with 10:05
left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That trend continued later in the game when Griese launched a
perfect long pass to wide receiver Rod Smith for 47 yards after
Smith had beaten double coverage. The play led to a 32-yard field
goal by Elam, which was important, because on the previous series,
Hakim scored on a blistering 86-yard punt return that was keyed by
terrific blocking.
</P>
<P>
   Last year during the Rams' championship run, such a play would
have deflated most teams and started a St. Louis point-scoring
buffet. The Broncos, however, refused to be intimidated, even with
Davis on the sideline with a twisted left ankle. When St. Louis
scored on an 89-yard drive that ended in a Faulk 5-yard touchdown
run, making the score 14-10, Griese countered with his best set of
plays of the night. On a third-and-8, he kept the offense on the
field with a 26-yard scramble.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the drive, with the Denver churning along smoothly, St.
Louis went with an all-out blitz to disrupt Griese's timing. Griese
read it the way the man he replaced _ Elway _ would have. He made
the correct hot read to Smith, who caught the quick pass at the
20-yard line and then burst up the middle for the 25-yard touchdown
and 17-14 Denver lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
