<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX 
MAVERICKS' ROOKIES FADE TO BACKGROUND (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram DALLAS _ This summer was hailed as the Mavericks' greatest draft
since they plucked Mark Aguirre, Rolando Blackman, Jay Vincent and
Elston Turner out of the 1981 NBA Draft pool.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time, the Mavericks drafted power forward Etan Thomas,
shooting guard Courtney Alexander and power forward Donnell Harvey
in the first round and small forward Eduardo Najera in the second
round. Many national publications gave the Mavericks an `A' grade
for their choices.
</P>
<P>
   However, with the wave of quality veterans the Mavericks have
acquired in trades this summer, how much playing time the four
rookies receive this season remains in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like our rookies,'' Mavericks coach/general manager Don
Nelson said. ``But like any rookie, it takes time for rookies to
develop and understand what's going on. We like the skills of our
rookies, but I've got a good veteran team. I've got enough veteran
players where I don't have to worry about playing rookies.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas comes into training camp Oct. 3 as a backup to Gary
Trent, while Alexander backs up Michael Finley and Hubert Davis.
Harvey is no better than third on the power-forward depth chart,
and Najera backs up Dirk Nowitzki at small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, Alexander and Harvey are in Los Angeles working out with
Mavericks developmental coach Kiki Vandeweghe.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has reason to be enthusiastic that the Mavericks were
able to trade for veterans Howard Eisley, Christian Laettner, Terry
Mills, Dana Barros and Bill Curley. He explained that those
additions allow him to bring his rookies along at a slower pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my team, and if (rookies) can help me, then I'm going
to play them,'' Nelson said. ``If not, then we'll develop them in
the practice setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson likened the Mavericks' situation to the Boston Celtics of
the 1960's, who used to have a nice mix of young and veteran
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're deep at every position to where we have a lot of
talented good young players and veteran experienced players,'' he
said. ``By the time these veterans get too old, these rookies will
be ready to take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's similar to what Boston had when they had the Jones boys
(K.C. and Sam) backing up Bob Cousy and Bill Sharman. They had
these young guys step right in and they never missed a beat, and
that's kind of what we hope will happen to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rookies are able to help us win games, then I'm playing
them. We need to win and we need to get to the playoffs, so that's
what we're going to do.''  &LR; subheds:Spotlight returns With the
Rangers fading fast and the Cowboys' immediate future not looking
too bright, Mavericks owner Mark Cuban is hoping local fan
attention turns to his team.
</P>
<P>
   Because of all the wheeling and dealing Cuban did over the
summer, the Mavericks have stayed in the national news since the
NBA Draft on June 28. That's certainly unheard of for a team that
was the NBA's worst during the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Cuban said. ``Dallas is really a basketball town.
We just needed to give them something to talk about and have some
fun doing it.''  &LR; subheds:Plenty of interest With the tremendous
amount of wealth he has accumulated, Mark Cuban was asked how much
interest does he earn on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' said Cuban, who earned $1.5 billion when he
sold his portion of Broadcast.com last summer. ``Maybe $200k if I
were to guess.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
