<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 OPEN NOTES-TEX 
PIERCE'S BID FOR ANOTHER GRAND SLAM WIN ENDS (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ Mary Pierce's bid to win her second
Grand Slam event of the year ended Monday because of a shoulder
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, the French Open winner, was forced to withdraw because
of rotator-cuff irritation after dropping the first set against
Anke Huber, 4-6. The No. 4 seed called it quits after
double-faulting twice to give the set away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sore from the first serve I hit,'' Pierce said. ``With
each one, it just kept getting worse. I started compensating with
other areas and other muscles in my shoulder, and other things
started hurting. I didn't feel like I had control over my arm. I
hit a lot of double faults because I just couldn't control my arm
to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury gave the 10th-seeded Huber an excellent chance to
advance to the semifinals of a major for the first time since the
1998 Australian Open. Her quarterfinal opponent is unseeded Elena
Dementieva, who advanced with a three-set victory against Lilia
Osterloh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity, but I'd better not think about it,''
Huber said. ``If I think it's a good draw, and it's a good
opportunity, I won't put the ball in.'' Dokic gracious in defeat
Jelena Dokic had a chance to gain an early edge against Serena
Williams when she held a set point in the first-set tiebreaker, but
lost it when a backhand down the line that she thought was a winner
was called out.
</P>
<P>
   Dokic questioned the call and the crowd jeered, but there was no
overrule. She went on to lose the tiebreaker and the match.
</P>
<P>
   But Dokic graciously refused to blame the loss on the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``That linesperson was closer to it than I was, but it was very
close,'' she said. ``It could have gone either way. It was a very
close call at 6-5 in the tiebreaker. But it was something that was
called, and you have to go on to the next point. It was still
6-all. I still had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, on the other hand, professed ignorance when asked
about the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember getting a bad call in the tiebreak when the ball
was out,'' she said. ``Is that the one you're referring to? There
was a ball she hit that I was sure was out. You win some, you lose
some, and that's the way it is.'' Hingis unhappy with boyfriend
Martina Hingis was tempted to root against her boyfriend, Magnus
Norman, when the men's No. 3 seed fell behind Max Mirnyi by two
sets Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rain delays had backed up the schedule, and Hingis couldn't
begin her fourth-round match against Sandrine Testud until Norman
and Mirnyi were finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to win, but he was two sets down,'' Hingis said.
``In a way I was like, `Finish this match up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Norman, though, came back to win in a long five-setter. Hingis
didn't get on the court until after 10 p.m. New York time, and
didn't get a chance to finish the match before more rains came.
Weather report After four consecutive days of rain delays, today's
schedule should proceed as planned. The weather forecast calls for
sunny, but windy, conditions, with a high of about 70.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's 70, as in 30-plus degrees cooler than in Texas.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
