<SLUG> BC-TEN-U.S. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SISTERS ON COLLISION COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN WOMEN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ A United States Tennis Association
official provided confirmation of the ruling order of the women's
game Monday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the postmatch interview, Mary Pierce, the fourth seed at the
U.S. Open, was discussing the shoulder injury that forced her to
default her match to Anke Huber after dropping the first set.
Serena Williams was due in the room, and Pierce was about to
intrude on her time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to wait before,'' Pierce lamented. ``That's not
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Right or not, that's the way it is in women's tennis these days.
No one slows down the Williams sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams defeated Jelena Dokic, 7-6 (7), 6-0, Monday to
join older sister Venus in the quarterfinals and remain on a
collision course to meet in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four matches down, three to go,'' the defending champion said.
``I just hope to make it there. I think I have a great chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two women seem to have any kind of chance to prevent a
Williams family reunion Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Top-seeded Martina Hingis is one. She finished off Sandrine
Testud, 6-2, 6-1, in a completion of a match that was suspended
from Sunday night because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Davenport is the other. The No. 2 seed defeated Justine
Henin, 6-0, 6-4, to advance to the quarterfinals against Serena
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis is on top of her game. She has lost only 10 games in her
four matches so far. Davenport is the only one of the Big Four to
drop a set in the tournament, but she's one of the few women with
the power to hit with the sisters and looked on top of her game in
beating Henin.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the sisters are seeded third (Venus) and fifth
(Serena).
</P>
<P>
   Seeds, though, mean little. The Williams sisters went into the
tournament as the players to beat, and nothing has happened in the
first eight days to change that perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus and I have definitely raised the bar in tennis,'' Serena
said. ``Everyone wants to beat a Williams sister now. We're the
ones to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Dokic looked as if she had a chance to do just that for a while,
holding two set points in the tiebreaker in the first set.
</P>
<P>
   Williams saved the first one with a forehand volley. She saved
the second when Dokic ripped a backhand down the line that was
called out. Williams cruised from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd won the first set, maybe I'd have won the match in two
sets,'' Dokic said. ``You get on a roll, and the pressure would be
on her because she's the defending champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe not. Williams raised the level of her game in
the second set, making only two unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never give up,'' she said. ``If I had lost the tiebreak, I
would have come out even stronger in the second set. I tend to play
better when I'm down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis didn't need to raise the level of her game against
Testud. She held a 6-2, 1-0 lead when play was halted Sunday and
made quick work of the No. 11 seed when play resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis is hitting the ball harder than she ever has, because the
need to keep up with the Williamses forced her to add more power to
her all-court game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before it was like everything was slower; you had more time to
prepare for your shots, mix it up more, slow it down, make it
faster,'' Hingis said. ``Now you have to hit every ball as hard as
you can. There's no more time to play games.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. With the fast, powerful Williams sisters around,
everything is faster these days.
</P>
<P>
   Including postmatch interviews. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
