<HEADER>
A0922 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYSNOTES-TEX     09-05 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX 
CUNNINGHAM PROMISES TO BE READY (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram IRVING _ Backup quarterback Randall Cunningham didn't promise a
better performance if has to start in place of the injured Troy
Aikman against Cardinals on Sunday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   However, he said there's no question that he will be better
prepared than when he took the field against Eagles two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always ready,'' Cunningham said Monday. ``As a backup, I
prepare myself like I'm going to play. The main thing that's going
to change is that I will get more reps in practice this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who is still learning the Cowboys' offense, took few
snaps with the first unit in practice the past three weeks partly
because of bursitis in his shoulder and partly because the Cowboys
were focused on getting Aikman ready.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham also downplayed the significance of the sprained
right thumb he suffered against the Eagles. Cunningham, who was
squeezing putty between his fingers in the locker room Monday to
strengthen the thumb, said there was little swelling on his thumb
and that it wouldn't limit him in practice or the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham also promised that he wouldn't limit his play as he
did at times against Eagles. With Aikman out and no other
quarterback on the roster, Cunningham said he played cautiously
because the team couldn't afford to lose him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave everything I had, but I had to be smart,'' Cunningham
said. ``I made sure I didn't hold on to the ball too long or take
too many hits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have already made the decision to promote rookie
free agent Clint Stoerner from the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones and coach Dave Campo said Stoerner
would replace the injured Joey Galloway on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys already have a fourth quarterback in the fold.
Second-year player Anthony Wright, who played with the Pittsburgh
Steelers last year, was signed to the practice squad last week. He
will practice with the team for the first time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said James McKnight is the leading candidate to replace
Galloway at receiver, although Wane McGarity will also be
considered.
Front seven blamed for run woes
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campo blamed the team's inability to stop the run on poor
technique used by the defensive line and linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the defensive lineman not getting off blocks; it was
linebackers not filling where they were supposed to fill,'' Campo
said. ``We are a better front seven than we showed. We've got to
get back to the basics.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said what was most disappointing is that the mistakes were
made by two units he had the most confidence in coming into the
season. However, he promised that the run woes will be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise you that we will get back to the basics,'' Campo
said. ``As far as those young corners are concerned, I don't know
what's going to happen. But we are going to stop the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said the team might go back to its old philosophy up
front, where the defensive lineman's first responsibility is to
hold up the offensive lineman to allow the linebackers to run and
make plays. Because the Cowboys were so confident in the ability of
their defensive line to dominate in 2000, they allowed them to be
more aggressive and charge across the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   That aggression led to 201 yards rushing for Eagles running back
Duce Staley.
Williams holdout hurt line Though tackle Erik Williams wasn't
primarily responsible for many of the offensive line breakdowns
against the Eagles, Dave Campo said that Williams' 28-day holdout
played a factor in their poor play.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offensive line was together for only one preseason
game. Guard Solomon Page, who had trouble with Eagles rookie tackle
Corey Simon, played tackle for the first four weeks of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something to be said about the fact that you like to
have all your people in training camp,'' Campo said.
``Communication is important up front. There were some
communication problems in the game. You can trace it to that. You
lose some communication when you move guys from spot to spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will also lose some in the wallet; he will be fined by
the league and the team after being ejected in fourth quarter for
punching an Eagles player in the kidney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him as soon as he came off the field,'' Campo
said. ``We will handle that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
