r s BC-FBN-U.S.OPENMEN-TEX     09-05 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-U.S. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 OPEN MEN-TEX 
SAMPRAS SURVIVES TEST FROM QUALIFIER (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ Andre Agassi, the No. 1 seed at the U.S.
Open, lost in the second round. No. 2 Gustavo Kuerten went out in
the first.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Et tu'', Pete Sampras?
</P>
<P>
   The tournament's fourth seed _ and only player left in the draw
that's widely recognized by casual fans _ faced triple-break point
in the sixth game of his fourth-round match Monday against unknown
opponent Hyung-Taik Lee.
</P>
<P>
   How unknown? The Korean native has been playing challenger
events all summer and had to win a qualifier just to get into the
Open. He's ranked No. 182 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a good idea to hide sharp objects from CBS
executives when he had the multiple break chances. Without Sampras,
they no doubt were envisioning a Sunday final that just might get
better ratings than a re-run of ``This Old House.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, though, didn't fold under the pressure of being the
savior of the men's draw. He held serve and went on to a 7-6 (4),
6-2, 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always difficult playing someone I've never seen play,''
Sampras said. ``It's like a batter facing a pitcher he's never
seen. It takes you awhile to feel it out. He came out playing well.
He wasn't overwhelmed by the situation. But after winning the first
set I settled down and started playing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has played well all tournament. He's the only man not to
lose a set, although he has gone to four tiebreakers.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for anyone who wants to see a big-name player
in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Upsets have claimed Agassi, Kuerten, No. 5 seed Yevgeny
Kafelnikov, No. 8 Alex Corretja and No. 10 Cedric Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Moya beat Corretja in straight sets Sunday. Pioline lost
in straight sets against Todd Martin on Monday, although his
conqueror probably qualifies as a big name. The veteran American
played Agassi in the final last year.
</P>
<P>
   With so many seeds out, the Open has become a coming-out party
for talented but little-known players such as Marat Safin, Juan
Carlos Ferrero and Lleyton Hewitt, who played Thomas Enqvist in a
late match.
</P>
<P>
   While the Russian, Spaniard and Australian players might be the
future of the game, in the present they don't have the name
recognition of Sampras. Not to mention the resume of the career
leader in Grand Slam singles titles.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a long way to go before the TV people and the
ticket holders for the final can breathe easy. Next up for Sampras
is the big-serving Richard Krajicek, who advanced with a
straight-set victory against Dominik Hrbaty, 7-6 (11), 6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with my serve-and-volley game,'' Krajicek said.
``It's tough to break me. And my return game is good enough to keep
the ball in play and have a chance to break my opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek has beaten Sampras six times in nine meetings, although
Sampras won in Cincinnati a couple of weeks before the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a match that's going to come down to a couple of
points,'' Sampras said. ``He's a great player, and when he's on
he's tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a matchup of two of the biggest servers in the game.
Krajicek set an Open record with 49 aces in losing to Kafelnikov in
the quarterfinals last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to come down to the return of serve, who puts more
pressure on the second serve,'' Sampras said. ``It's not an easy
match. The court's playing quick, and it'll be tough to break. It
won't be an easy match.''
</P>
<P>
   Time to hide the sharp objects again.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
