r s BC-FBN-REEVES-TEX     09-05 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO SAY GOODBYE: AIKMAN'S LIFE NOT WORTH RISK FROM CONCUSSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
IRVING _ Two thoughts for you, Troy Aikman, as your headaches
gradually grow lighter and the nausea slowly recedes this week; two
word pictures to keep in mind as you consider your future.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think about Eric Lindros, flopping on the ice like a fish in
last year's Stanley Cup playoffs. Think about how that made you
feel, how sickening it was to see him like that.
</P>
<P>
   And consider old friend Steve Young, still puking his guts out
months after he'd decided to quit football. Still fighting the
headaches, the dizziness, the nausea.
</P>
<P>
   Don't go there. Please.
</P>
<P>
   You heard me say it last year, when you had back-to-back
concussions at Indianapolis and Minnesota, and you're still here,
but I'll say it again anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Quit.
</P>
<P>
   Walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Give it up.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it's the hardest thing you'll ever do, it also will be
the best thing you'll ever do, because you'll be doing it for all
the right reasons.
</P>
<P>
   For your new bride.
</P>
<P>
   For the children you someday hope to have.
</P>
<P>
   For yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about the fans, or the media or even the Cowboys and
owner Jerry Jones. This is just about you, and no one is
presumptuous enough to think that it isn't totally your decision.
</P>
<P>
   But from this seat, the risk you'll be taking by continuing to
play just isn't worth it any more.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about courage or being macho. Anyone who has seen you
play has no question about your bravery or manhood. This is about
common sense. Leave, while you still have some.
</P>
<P>
   We sat there at Valley Ranch yesterday _ you'd already come and
gone _ and heard Jones tell us that ``Troy is day-to-day.'' He
talked about how mild this concussion is compared to the severity
of last year's injuries (which were initially terribly understated)
and how tests at the hospital left open the possibility that you
might play Sunday in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Then he also admitted he hadn't even bothered to ask you, when
the two of you spoke yesterday, how you were feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Who's kidding who, here?
</P>
<P>
   Don't do it. Don't even think about playing Sunday. For once,
it's time to ignore what that big heart of yours tells you to do
and be reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would personally share the logic,'' Jones said, ``that if
one week off is the thing to do, as opposed to any risk of him
being out knocked out for four or five games, then I would be the
first to not want him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Four or five games? What about the rest of your life, Troy?
That's what could be at stake here, and don't let Jones or anyone
else convince you otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think I'm sitting here pushing him on behalf of winning
a ballgame to get back out there, the answer is no,'' Jones
insisted. ``One of the really comforting things is that over the
last year Troy went to different experts, if you will, on
concussions, people who have not only treated and advised, but have
studied concussions, and he was assured, based upon anything he'd
had happen in the past, he'd had no long-term effects from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very comforting thing for him and for someone in my
shoes as well. But let me be clear about one thing: I'm not
interested in jeopardizing his long-term wellbeing or quality of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   That's reassuring, but the one thing you've learned, Troy, in
educating yourself about concussions, is that when doctors start
finding bad things in their tests, the damage has already been done
and cannot be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   That's what your friends are worried about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad thing about concussions is, it's not like looking at
an X-ray and saying, `Oh, it's broke. You can't play.' As it has
been explained to him, if something shows up on the MRI, that means
you already have dead \Rbrain\S tissue,'' deep-snapper Dale
Hellestrae said. ``You should have retired the concussion before.''
</P>
<P>
   Helly says you've often talked about quitting before that
happens. Now's the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, you're worried about the individual,'' Hellestrae said.
``You want him to be all right and you want his quality of life to
be good for the rest of his life. He's got a lot of years left and
hopefully kids, a new wife and all that, and you want him to be
able to enjoy that. That's your No. 1 concern. Football is
secondary when it comes to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, he's 33 years old and he knows that. He's
consulted with a bunch of specialists and he knows the risks, so
it's not like he's going into it naive. He's probably as educated
as you can be, and even then, there's some unknown, which is the
scary part. That's what makes this such a sticky situation.''
</P>
<P>
   So do you sit out one game? Two? Five? How many is enough? By
now you should know that there's no answer to that. There's never
enough. You've had three concussions in your past 10 games, at
least nine, and probably some that weren't counted, in your
football career.
</P>
<P>
   Which one is the one that turns a man into a vegetable? Fifteen?
Twenty?
</P>
<P>
   Ten?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he sits out five weeks and goes back,'' Hellestrae pointed
out, ``he can still get another concussion if he gets hit the right
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately,''the right way'' is obviously getting a lot
easier for tacklers. Take a look at Sunday's game film, if you have
the stomach for it. There were the four Eagles' sacks, of course,
but you were belted even when you got the pass off.
</P>
<P>
   Was it the last hit that did the damage? Or did it happen
earlier?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when it happened,'' center Mark Stepnoski said.
``Up until he left the game, he was no different in the huddle than
he always is.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Troy, none of the hits looked particularly devastating;
none of the collisions were of the helmet-to-helmet variety that
causes us to wince and wonder if you're going to get up again.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, you've developed a ``glass'' head like a fighter who
has taken too many punches develops a glass jaw. He becomes easier
and easier to knock out. So have you.
</P>
<P>
   The message is all too clear: The brain just can't take it any
more.
</P>
<P>
   You've never been just about football, as much as people have
tried to paint you that way. You have a lot to offer the world away
from the football field.
</P>
<P>
   Take some time. Think this through. Talk to your family and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for all the right reasons, walk away. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
