<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PIRATES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRATES END DODGERS WINNING STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just in case the Dodgers were starting to think
wild September thoughts, along came Jimmy Anderson and the
Pittsburgh Pirates to humble them.
</P>
<P>
   Those would be the same Pirates who entered the game tied for
the worst record in baseball. The same Anderson, who in his past
six starts, couldn't get out Robert Daly.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Pirates made like they were still family and
Anderson like a hot prospect, as they pushed the Dodgers around for
a 12-1 victory before a Dodger Stadium crowd of 31,418 to snap
their six-game home winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dreifort, who had won his last six decisions, struck out
19 in the 13 innings of his past two starts and hadn't lost since
June 29, was both ineffective and unlucky.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers offense was both scattered and poorly timed.
</P>
<P>
   Put them together, and a team that had won 11 of their past 14
games, was just another club for the 57-79 Pirates to punish Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything kind of went the wrong way tonight,'' Dodgers
catcher Todd Hundley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates scored their 12 runs on 13 hits, seven being charged
to Dreifort (10-8) over his 5 innings of work. That included two
home runs, including a second-inning grand slam to left-handed
Brian Giles _ a slicing drive that landed one row up the
right-field seats, about 335 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Giles was going to beat me, I was going to make it the
other way, and he did,'' Dreifort said.
</P>
<P>
   The third slam of Giles' career left the Pirates up 5-0,
although the Dodgers looked like a team just waiting to explode
against the left-handed Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   They left still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was 0-3 with a 6.12 ERA in his past five starts. Of
course, the last team he'd beaten was the Dodgers _ blanking them
in eight innings Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers did manage to score a run against Anderson (5-8) in
the bottom of the second, but even that was a labored effort. They
had runners thrown out at third and home, needing four singles _
including Hundley's RBI hit to scratch together their run.
</P>
<P>
   In 23 innings in three outings against Anderson this season,
that accounts for their lone run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had six hits in the first two innings, and just one run to
show for it,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   It was still a 5-1 game in the sixth when the Pirates started
embarrassing the Dodgers, scoring seven times against Dreifort,
Onan Masaoka and Matt Herges.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates batted around for the second time, after Dreifort
started the trouble by giving up a walk and a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreifort just didn't have real good command tonight,'' Johnson
said. ``He kept getting behind, threw a lot of pitches (112), and
then our bullpen didn't give him any help.''
</P>
<P>
   Masaoka didn't get any of his four batters out, walking two and
giving up two hits. Herges gave up two more hits and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama said there'd be days like this,'' Hundley said.
</P>
<P>
   About the only bright spot for the Dodgers was the major-league
debut of Luke Prokopec, the right-hander who was scheduled to join
the Australian Olympic team until called up by the Dodgers last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Prokopec threw three scoreless innings, allowing a pair of hits
and striking out two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
