<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-R-PODESTA-BROTHERS-AR     09-05 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PODESTA-BROTHERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR POWERFUL BROTHERS, POLITICS CAN BE THICKER THAN BLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeats to add art advisory.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 25 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT PEAR and JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Politics can sometimes turn brother against
brother.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Podesta, chief of staff at the White House, is trying to
enhance President Clinton's legacy by adding prescription drug
benefits to Medicare and by persuading Congress to enact a bill of
rights for patients.
</P>
<P>
   His older brother, Anthony T. Podesta, represents the
Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America, lobbying
against the president's Medicare plan. In fact, Clinton complained
the other day, ``the pharmaceutical industry has unleashed a
shameless, scorched-earth campaign'' to block his plan.
</P>
<P>
   One of Tony Podesta's partners in his lobbying firm, which he
calls podesta.com, Jeffrey Ricchetti, represents the Blue Cross and
Blue Shield Association in the insurance industry's effort to kill
patients' rights legislation. But John Podesta has his own ally in
pushing the bill: his White House deputy, Steven J. Ricchetti,
Jeff's older brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Medicis controlled everything,'' Tony Podesta said in an
interview, referring to the merchant family that ruled Renaissance
Florence. ``We have it split into two families.''
</P>
<P>
   John and Tony Podesta are two of the most influential people in
Washington, playing opposite sides of the fence that is supposed to
separate policy-making from special pleading. But their
relationship _ brothers, former business partners, spokesmen for
people who hold a large share of the power and money in America _
can be seen as emblematic of the way Washington works in the age of
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying is serious business, but the best of the breed do not
take it too seriously because they know that today's enemies may be
allies on another issue tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, 51, has served as staff secretary, scandal handler
and chief of staff in the Clinton White House. He is needle-thin,
intense, moody at times, but with a wicked sense of humor. He is an
aficionado of roller coasters, working in a White House that often
resembles one.
</P>
<P>
   When he was staff secretary, responsible for the flow of paper
to the Oval Office, Podesta was particularly annoyed by
intelligence bureaucrats who dressed up routine memorandums with
``top secret'' designations to get the president's attention. When
the CIA or the National Security Council submitted a classified
report that Podesta had already seen on CNN, he stamped it
``EMBARRASSING'' in big green letters before sending it to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Podesta, 56, a big, barrel-chested man, is more flamboyant
than his brother. He collects funky contemporary art and wears a
tie only when he has to. Like his brother, he is full of kinetic
energy. ``They're cranked up all the time,'' said their 82-year-old
mother, Mary K. Podesta, who lives here.
</P>
<P>
   The company now known as podesta.com was founded by the Podesta
brothers in 1988. For the first few years, the lobbyists were all
Democrats, but since 1991, the company has become more bipartisan.
Of the 30 professional employees, a third are now Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyists include people who have worked for Democrats like
Sens. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts and Christopher Dodd of
Connecticut; for Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the House
Democratic whip; and for the AFL-CIO and the United Mine Workers.
</P>
<P>
   But the lobbying corps at podesta.com also includes people who
have worked for Republicans like Newt Gingrich, the former speaker;
Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader; Rep. J.C.
Watts Jr. of Oklahoma, the chairman of the House Republican
Conference; and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Another podesta.com associate is Heather Barbour, daughter of
the former chairman of the Republican Party and adviser to Gov.
George W. Bush, Haley Barbour.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Podesta insists he never calls his brother or Steve
Ricchetti to obtain favors for clients, which include biotechnology
companies and drug companies like Eli Lilly and Novartis, as well
as Dow Chemical, Viacom, CBS, General Electric, Time Warner and the
Motion Picture Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   But his clients say he has opened doors for them elsewhere in
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Podesta is a facilitator, a broker, a translator, who helps
businesses understand the ways of Washington. As a liberal
Democrat, he intuitively understands how Clinton administration
officials are thinking. Clients say they value his insights and use
him to send messages to the White House and Democrats in Congress.
Podesta said his company had billings of $8.5 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Berman, executive director of the Center for Democracy and
Technology, a civil liberties group, said: ``Tony is a political
operator, a political networker, with tremendous reach. There are
many connections between the White House and his firm, that's
clear. They know how to keep those lines separated, but it's a
high-wire act.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although clients or potential clients might hope that Tony
Podesta offers entree to the White House, the Podestas say they
never talk policy. It would be wrong ethically and suicidal
politically, they say. ``He doesn't lobby me, I don't lobby him,''
John Podesta says.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime client called Tony Podesta not too long ago and asked
him to contact his brother on a policy matter of concern to his
employer, a big media company.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said no,'' the client said, insisting he not be identified
for fear of alienating one of the Podesta brothers. ``I said, `Come
on, call him.' He said no. I said, `Tony, no one's been with you
longer than me _ call him.' He said no; he just wouldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilary B. Rosen, president of the Recording Industry Association
of America and a podesta.com client, said she had never known Tony
Podesta to lean on his brother on behalf of a client. ``It would be
stupid, and Tony's not stupid,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, other lobbyists, competitors of Tony Podesta's company,
said the relationship had helped generate business and had given
Tony Podesta added clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, when you're an assistant secretary of something
and you have a bunch of phone calls after lunch and one has
Podesta's name on it, that slip gets to the top of the stack pretty
quick,'' said one competitor, a prominent Republican lobbyist.
``You know it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Ricchetti, 43, has spun through the revolving door several
times. He headed the political department of the Blue Cross and
Blue Shield Association from 1987 to 1989 and led the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee from 1990 to 1992. He worked in the
Clinton White House as the top Senate lobbyist from 1993 to 1996
and returned to the private sector to lobby for corporate clients
before going back to the White House in September 1998. Steve
Ricchetti's chief assignment in late 1998 was to keep Congressional
Democrats from voting to impeach or convict the president. In
January 1999, he became deputy chief of staff, with many additional
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Following in his brother's footsteps, Jeff Ricchetti worked at
Blue Cross and Blue Shield, as director of Congressional relations
from 1993 to 1996. The Ricchetti brothers, who grew up in
Cleveland, created a lobbying firm here in 1998. They sold it to
podesta.com early last year, after Steve went back to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ricchetti, 40, said he provided ``the full gamut of
lobbying on behalf of Blue Cross and Blue Shield.'' As a senior
strategist at podesta.com, he follows every twitch of activity on
legislation to define patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   William A. Pierce, a spokesman for Blue Cross and Blue Shield,
said: ``In the patients' bill of rights debate, we do not support
passage of any federal legislation. We oppose all the legislation
in front of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans, which provide managed health
care for 53 million people, are particularly opposed to giving
patients any new right to sue their health plans. Clinton says that
right is essential. But Pierce said it would be ``bad for consumers
because it would increase costs without solving the patients'
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Podesta.com boasts of its ability to build coalitions uniting
Republicans and Democrats, corporations and consumer groups, and
competing companies in the same industry.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Podesta has enhanced his lobbying power by raising money
for politicians including Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, Tom Daschle of
South Dakota, the Senate Democratic leader, and Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Podesta refers to his fund-raising operation, built around
fine meals at his northwest Washington home, as the ``Pesto PAC.''
His mother, Mary Podesta, cooks Italian food for guests at these
political dinners. ``I'm the pesto lady,'' Podesta said in an
interview. ``The funny part is, I'm Greek.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
