   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (Moved in ``i'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-SERVICE (Washington) _ A potentially double-edged
problem is gnawing at the State Department: Talented officials are
quitting for more challenging jobs elsewhere, and graduates are
turning their backs on diplomatic careers in favor of more
lucrative jobs at dot.com startups and on Wall Street. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT 24)
</P>
<P>
   ARCTIC-ICE (Nuuk, Greenland) _ During World War II, when Henry
Larsen took a Royal Canadian Mounted Police ship, the St. Roch,
into the fabled Northwest Passage, his boat was frozen in Arctic
ice through two winters, only emerging at the eastern end after 27
months. On Sunday, the St. Roch II completed a voyage over the same
route in one month, including leisurely overnight stops at
communities visited by the namesake boat half a century ago. After
leaving Tuktoyaktuk, near Canada's border with Alaska, the boat
traversed all of Canada's Arctic without encountering pack ice. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT 13, 14 and map)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-INMATES (Yellow Pine, Idaho) _ Back in Utah, they are
inmates at Bluffdale State Prison, but out here in the fire zone,
they strut proudly in black T-shirts proclaiming themselves members
of the Flame 'N' Go Hotshots. Convicts make up a surprising portion
of the armies of men battling wildfires across the West this
summer. One in six of the firefighting teams now deployed across
the region in this devastating fire season is drawn from a state
prison, with convicts from places like California and Nevada paid
just $1 an hour. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (With map)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DEBATE (Undated) _ Gov. George W. Bush's attempt to
impose his own schedule of debates was dealt a serious setback, as
two major TV networks that were left out of the plan declared that
they had no intention of carrying presidential debates sponsored by
rival networks. The Bush proposal, announced Sunday after intense
negotiations with officials of six cable and broadcast networks,
has thrown into turmoil the work of the Commission on Presidential
Debates. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS-RELIGION (Denver) _ Voters can scarcely miss the overt
expressions of religious faith by candidates in this presidential
campaign. But interviews with more than three dozen voters around
the country found that they had little interest in weighing the
religious convictions of candidates when choosing the next
president. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RETURN (Washington) _ Aware that what they do in the
next few weeks may help determine who controls the federal
government next year, members of Congress return from recess this
week for a final session compressed by the election campaigns and
dominated by tax cuts, education, health care and government
spending. By Steven A. Holmes and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   PODESTA-BROTHERS (Washington) _ John and Tony Podesta are two of
the most influential people in Washington, playing opposite sides
of the fence that is supposed to separate policy-making from
special pleading. But their relationship _ brothers, former
business partners, spokesmen for people who hold a large share of
the power and money in America _ can be seen as emblematic of the
way Washington works in the age of influence. By Robert Pear and
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT 25.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLIGHT-DELAYS (Undated) _ Labor Day marked the end of the second
consecutive summer of chronic flight delays and cancellations
across the United States. Yet despite the expenditure of billions
there is still no relief in sight for frustrated flyers. Most
experts now believe that delays will get worse, not better. The FAA
predicts that by 2010 the number of airline passengers will rise 59
percent, to 1 billion, and about 70 percent of that increase will
occur at the country's 28 largest airports. By Laurence Zuckerman
and Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT18, 19 and three graphics)
</P>
<P>
   SCULLEY-BROTHERS (Undated) _ John Sculley, the former Apple
Computer chief executive, is making a quiet comeback. For the last
five years, he has run a small venture capital firm with his two
brothers. It is his way of fulfilling a desire to work with his
family _ and to help proselytize about the virtues of the Internet
without suffering the corporate intrigue that overwhelmed him at
both Apple and Spectrum Information Technologies. By Hilary
Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT20 and two graphics)
</P>
<P>
   MCDONALDS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Although its brand is
quintessentially American, its business, increasingly, is not. So
McDonald's is turning these days to international promotional
opportunities _ like the Summer Olympic Games, coming soon to a
television set near you _ and to nearly everybody else's on the
planet, too. By Bernard Stamler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CAVE-VISITORS (Benson, Ariz.) - Take a sopping wet
underground cavern in a remote corner of Arizona. Add a man-made
entrance with heavy steel doors to keep out the hot desert air, a
misting system to keep the cavern damp and lights to show off a
wonderland of spires, flowstone, soda straws and other
phantasmagorical cave formations. Then add a human being who, in a
one-hour visit, sloughs off some 60,000 skin fragments, 160 million
dust particles, 20,000 clothing-lint particles, 25 quarts of carbon
dioxide gas and 170 watts of body heat. Multiply this by 183,000
visitors to the cave each year. The result is an ad hoc experiment
now under way at Kartchner Caverns near Benson, Ariz., to learn if
it is possible to bring thousands of people into the fragile
environment of a pristine cave without destroying the cave in the
process. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT 22, 23 and graphic)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ULTIMATE-LAPTOP (Undated) _ In a paper in the current issue
of Nature, an MIT researcher describes the ultimate laptop _ a
computer as powerful as the laws of physics would allow. So
energetic is this imaginary machine that using it would be like
harnessing a thermonuclear reaction. In the most extreme version of
this computer supreme, so much computational circuitry would be
packed into so small a space that the whole thing would collapse
from its own gravity forming a tiny black hole, an object so dense
that not even light can escape its gravity. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-DRUGS (Undated) _ In the 13 years since they were
introduced in the United States, the cholesterol-lowering drugs
known as statins have revolutionized the treatment of heart
disease. Repeated studies have shown they prevent heart attacks and
prolong life, with very few side effects. They have rapidly become
the best-selling prescription drugs in this country. Now, the
latest research indicates that even more people should be on
statins. By Sandeep Jauhar.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALBATROSS (Undated) _ Researchers in France and Germany have
tracked several wandering albatrosses, and their findings are
surprising. As the researchers report in the journal Nature, the
birds do not wander aimlessly during what amounts to a sabbatical
following a year in which they hatch and raise a single chick.
Rather, the albatrosses go to a specific section of the ocean and
stay there. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RACE-RECOGNITION (Undated) _ After a decade of mapping
brains in tasks like recalling numbers, perceiving facial
expressions and using verbs, neuroscientists have recently honed in
on a much more controversial subject: The act of categorizing other
human beings. In recently published papers, two separate teams of
brain scanners joined by social psychologists describe how one
particular part of the brain becomes more active when people look
at members of a different race. By David Berreby.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on coated
seeds that might be used to help farmers overlap winter wheat and
soybeans in the same field; the prospect of genetically modifying
plants to grow coffee without the caffeine; on a die-off of tiger
salamanders at a lake in North Dakota. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE (Undated) _ For many menopausal women, the
question of whether to take hormones is one of the most crucial
health decisions of their middle years _ and one of the most
confusing. Hormone use relieves the hot flashes and night sweats
that plague many women during menopause, and protects against
brittle bones. But does it help prevent heart disease, as
researchers have long believed _ or could it actually increase the
risk, as at least one new piece of data seems to suggest? In a
package of six stories, women discuss the ways they approach the
therapy and their frustrations with unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   These six, approximately 375-400 words each, may be combined to
form a single coherent story:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-QUINTANA
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-DUMONT
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-GOLDMAN
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-HILL
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-LANG
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MENOPAUSE-LAND
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ In recent months, researchers have pointed to possible signals
of Alzheimer's disease that could allow doctors to detect the
ailment before symptoms start. They have spoken of small areas of
the brain that appear to shrink, and psychological tests that yield
subtle clues. Now scientists think they may have found another
clue: smell.
</P>
<P>
   _ With the rate of Caesarean sections on the rise, a leading
group of obstetricians has issued guidelines that may reduce the
number of operations.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who want to start exercise programs but feel they don't
have enough time or energy to begin should think again. A new study
suggests that physical activity that lasts just 15 minutes, if done
often enough, may be as beneficial as longer workouts. The report
appeared last week in Circulation: Journal of the American Heart
Association.
</P>
<P>
   _ Feeling sick to one's stomach may have more to do with the
brain the stomach. Researchers at Ohio State University say they
may have uncovered the reason that, often, people feel nauseated,
even though what ails them has nothing to do with their digestive
tracks. The culprit may be a brain chemical called tumor necrosis
factor, or TNF, which the immune system releases at the first sign
that the body is coming under attack.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study finds that tough guys seem to have tougher immune
systems, the body's natural defense for fighting off infections,
viruses and the like.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column:
Problems of ``polypharmacy'' or dangerous cocktails of drugs are
increasing, as more and more people live into their 70s and beyond.
By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: How do
scientists determine that a rock on Earth came from Mars rather
than someplace else? By C. Claiborne Ray.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ The sinking of the Russian submarine
Kursk was a tragic but incredibly illuminating example of the
transition the world, and Russia, are now going through from the
Cold War system to the globalization system. Unfortunately, there's
always some guy down the line who hasn't gotten the word yet. In
this case, it was Russia's president, Vladimir Putin. By Thomas L.
Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Cincinnati) _ We waited a long time for the
public to get interested in this election, but now in southern Ohio
you can see the signs. Literally. The lawns are full of ads for
candidates who want to be the next congressman or state
representative. This must be what they mean when they talk about
grass-roots politics. By Gail Collins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   READER-AUTHOR-TOURS (Undated) _ The list of writers who are
turning tours into reading vacations is dominated by self-help
authors with a spiritual bent like Neale Donald Walsch, the author
of ``Conversations With God,'' who in June took readers on an
eight-day tour of Peru timed to coincide with the summer solstice
sunrise over Machu Picchu. But there are also published historians
and even a poet who are leading people on tours ripped from their
chapters, whether it be a stroll down Shankill Road in Belfast or a
trip to Colonial Williamsburg in Virginia. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   DESERT-ARTS-PILGRIMS (Black Rock Desert, Nev.) _ The Burning Man
festival has become a yearly pilgrimage for thousands of performers
and artists, as well as Internet techies, adventurous yuppies and
other counterculture aficionados, many of whom trek hundreds or
even thousands of miles to attend this alternative-arts fair that
showcases art of the obscure, the outrageous and the just plain
odd. Flags from Sweden, Israel, Italy and Ireland billowed over
camps this year, as did rainbow banners and pirate skulls. By Jesse
McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BARD-MUSIC (Moscow) _ Every summer, thousands of Russians
make the journey to the Grushinsky Festival, which celebrates bard
music, a genre identified with the Soviet cultural thaw of the
1960s and the subsequent growth and popularity of allegorical songs
as a creative and spiritual outlet. Today conditions are different,
but the songs of contemporary bard musicians seem to serve a
similar comforting purpose. By Sophia Kishkovsky.
</P>
<P>
   PROUST-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In his tedious new study of
Proust, ``Marcel Proust: A Life,'' Jean-Yves Tadie whines that the
adult Proust never revealed his inner life in his correspondence
and makes the odd complaint that George Painter _ the author of the
best-known biography of the writer to date _ succumbed ``without
any qualms'' to the temptation ``to draw from the novel in order to
explain, or understand, the life.'' Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
