<HEADER>
A0932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-DOKIC-NYT &LR;      09-05 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-DOKIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOKIC'S FORTRESS CANNOT WITHSTAND SERENA WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jelena Dokic built a fortress these past six days,
shutting out her unruly father's ejection from the U.S. Open and
then dealing with its lonely consequences by striking the ball
without forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old Dokic seemed to gather strength in solitude
while her father and coach, Damir, stayed at his Manhattan hotel.
He was still there Monday when she ran smack into the strongest
player in the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   Under the broiling sun in Arthur Ashe Stadium, Dokic matched
Serena Williams' blistering power with her own in their
fourth-round tug-of-war. And then, in one tantalizing and telling
moment, having come back to take a 6-5 lead in the first-set tie
breaker against the defending U.S. Open champion, Dokic struck a
crosscourt backhand down the line.
</P>
<P>
   The ball, which on television replays appeared to have caught
the outside of the line, was called out. Dokic mildly protested,
but she would never be the same, her stone resolve crumbling. She
had one more set point, at 7-6, yet Williams fought that third one
off as well to win the tie breaker, 9-7, and then ripped through
Dokic's shell in the second set for a 7-6 (7), 6-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's what turned the whole set around, the whole
match,'' Dokic said later about the point at 6-5. That point,
though, was just the first pull.
</P>
<P>
   When she lost the first set, that unraveled her for the rest of
the match, as she started the second set completely dispirited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's always hard to come out, especially after you
lost the first set,'' Dokic said. ``Maybe you feel like it's
slipping away a little bit when you did have a chance. If I was in
the situation again, maybe I would have won the set, would have
been a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, her turbulent and enigmatic story ends, for now, at the
fourth round of the Open, an understandable exit for a player
ranked No. 43 against the world's sixth-ranked player.
</P>
<P>
   Dokic reached the semifinals at Wimbledon by turning aside yet
another embarrassing public incident from her father, who was
escorted off the grounds for a day when he crushed a reporter's
cell phone and started yelling about the queen.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Australian Open, Damir Dokic got into a scuffle with
an Australian television crew off the grounds, and in the summer of
1999 he was ejected from a tournament in England for drunken and
disorderly behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Tennis Association Tour is investigating Damir
Dokic's pattern of verbal abuse, and could elect next week to ban
him from the tour as his daughter's coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the decision is, I'm just going to have to deal with
it when it comes to that,'' Jelena Dokic said, and then repeated
another familiar refrain she has used since last Wednesday, when
her father sparked an ugly confrontation over a $12.50 piece of
salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to block things out,'' Dokic said. ``You've got to
go out on the court. You know, you've got to be able to just play
the game whether something's happening or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Williams' father and coach, Richard, watched the match
from the players' box in the stadium, Dokic was without any visible
support. Against players ranked below her, she could support
herself well enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whether anybody is around or not, I played well in the
two previous matches,'' she said. ``You know, it's different
playing Serena. You've got to lift your level up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, her biceps and quadriceps bulging from her black and
lilac frock, struck 10 of her personal-best 14 aces in the first
set. But her power was also inconsistent; she had 24 unforced
errors in the first set, nerves gripping her. ``I did not move up
to the ball,'' Williams said. ``I was playing too cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   That was until she realized she was about to lose the set. She
raced to a 4-1 lead in the tie breaker and seemed to relax as Dokic
ripped five straight points to give herself two set points;
Williams was not ready to concede anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a real fighter,'' Williams said. ``At that point when I
was down, 6-4, in the tie break, I was thinking, `Well, all I have
to do is get the ball back in play and make her play.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ahead by 6-5, Dokic was locked in her strategy of attacking
Williams, going for every shot, when the lines official called her
backhand out. Dokic approached the chair umpire on the changeover,
but the umpire let the call stand.
</P>
<P>
   But after Williams tied the score, Dokic hit a forehand that was
called in, and this time, Williams did not agree. ``You win some,
you lose some,'' Williams said. ``That's just how it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if she would have lost that tie breaker, Williams said
she would not have been as deflated as her opponent. ``I would have
come out even stronger in the second set because I tend to play a
little better when I'm down,'' she said. Williams has not lost a
set yet this tournament and is 13-1 in her three years at the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it could have been a tougher match,'' Dokic admitted.
``That's where experience comes into play. The more you play, the
more experienced you are. Maybe that set would have been the other
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
