<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 08:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-CO     09-05 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The Olympics: a moment, just a moment
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, Sept. 6, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not widely known, but Andy Warhol amended his famous '60s
prediction that in the future everyone will be famous for 15
minutes. In 1979, saying he was bored with the old line, Warhol
modified it to read: ``In 15 minutes, everybody will be famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it won't really happen in 15 minutes. More like a week or
so.
</P>
<P>
   As we edge closer to the Sydney Olympics _ curtain up on Sept.
15 _ untold unfamous people will become famous. Today they are just
vague names splashed across a sports page. Three weeks from now,
they will be household names _ people who, bundling Warhol's two
assertions, will be famous in 15 minutes, for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, a headline running across the bottom of a
sports page caught my eye. It said that Greene and Jones sparkled
in sprints in preparation for Sydney. I wondered: Do I know that
Greene and that Jones?
</P>
<P>
   I didn't. But I will. Soon.
</P>
<P>
   And, another story informed me, Lindland will replace Sieracki
on the U.S. Greco-Roman squad. This bothered me because I never got
to know who Sieracki was before he was gone _ and ordered gone by a
federal judge, no less!
</P>
<P>
   I guess I could delve into the reason the issue was before a
federal judge and not a coach, but there's little time to waste on
that. There are too many people about to be famous, why spend time
on those who won't?
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics are a fascinating spectacle. There's hardly a one
of us who has followed something as remote as luge competition
(yes, I know, it's a winter sport), yet every four years we sit
transfixed watching one or two foolhardy types on sleds _ on their
backs, crotch forward! _ plunging down a shaft of ice at God-knows
how many miles an hour. Who was that guy? Hackl of Germany. Oh.
</P>
<P>
   For just a few days, we marvel at a Japanese gymnast, his ankle
broken, twirling on what are called rings. We even get to know his
unpronounceable name, for just a while. And we are led to believe
we know something about ``rings.'' Enough, I daresay, to
second-guess the judges.
</P>
<P>
   (By the way, whatever happened to those contemptuous, plump
judges from the old East Germany who always gave Western athletes
low scores? Were they tried and convicted of something? I hope so.)
</P>
<P>
   Soon, we not only will be admiring svelte young people in skin
tight swimsuits, alien-looking goggles and abhorrent latex head
caps, but we will be wondering what it is, after years and years of
rigid training, makes a person one one-hundredth of a second
swifter than another after 100 meters of swimming.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, we will start to understand the difference between
meters and yards _ but forget it after 15 minutes!
</P>
<P>
   We will admire the continuing growth of female athletes as they
race around the track at seemingly phenomenal speeds. We don't know
them now, but we will know their names then. To most of us, their
names will disappear unless one is so phenomenal that her visage
and name adorn a Wheaties box for a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is meant to imply that the Olympics is minimal, or
that the athletes who appear in them are anything less than
physically superior to our alarmingly obese society.
</P>
<P>
   What puzzles me is not them, but us. We never heard of them
before, loved them for their symbolic 15 minutes, and _ with the
closing ceremonies _ returned to what we were doing never so much
as recalling who they were when they were.
</P>
<P>
   How often does a Jesse Owens come along, a Jim Thorpe, a
Florence Griffith-Joyner? For just a relative few, a gold medal
will have made it well worth their short-lived metamorphosis from
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0990 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     09-05 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS WON'T BE HOLDING THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Sale Isaia may not be the answer but he's
the solution for now.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, the oft-injured Isaia may not be what it takes
or have what it takes to fix the problems along the Patriots'
offensive line, but for this week at least he's the only solution
they've got, so expect to see him at guard most of the game Monday
night against the Jets when the Patriots face a far less formidable
defensive front than the one from Tampa that dismembered them
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Isaia is a four-year veteran who started out under Bill
Belichick when both were in Cleveland, but he's spent half his NFL
career on injured reserve and was one of the last cuts of the
Oakland Raiders a week ago, neither of which is an overwhelming
resume item. But at least the latter explains why he wasn't used
more Sunday after the Tampa game began to resemble a jail break
every time Drew Bledsoe dropped back to pass.
</P>
<P>
   He had been in Foxborough for less than 10 days and didn't have
down all the pass protection schemes and other mental requirements
of the job, so Belichick used him sparingly, alternating him with
versatile Jason Andersen after Max Lane was undressed by Warren
Sapp on three straight series.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick was not willing to reveal what he is going to do about
his offensive line against the Jets except to say he had yet to
settle on five guys, which means (A) he will continue to rotate
players at least some of the time, especially from the shotgun,
when Andersen goes to center and Damien Woody to guard; and (B) he
doesn't have five guys he knows he can rely on for very long. At
least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get the best people you can put out there,''
Belichick said. ``As soon as you know, you make the moves. Once you
know, it's easy to do it and be strong with it and go forward. But
you don't want to make a hard decision and then in a short time
make another hard decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation? I've got more problems than I've got solid starting
linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, too many of those problems Sunday came not from the new
faces in front of Bledsoe but from the old ones like Lane and
tackle Bruce Armstrong, who struggled in his first real test of the
knee he tore apart last season playing eight weeks in silence with
a torn ACL.
</P>
<P>
   Twice Armstrong and a running back seemed to be confused over
whom to block. Both times Armstrong ended up blocking the safety
while the back ended up whiffing on a defensive lineman. It is
unlikely many pass protection schemes are designed to match a
tackle on a safety and a back on a defensive end. Belichick would
not single out Armstrong, but a source inside the organization
conceded, ``It was our veterans who gave us the most problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest Belichick would come to singling out anyone was when
he spoke of mental errors in pass protection, alluding to the
Armstrong/running back mixups that resulted in Bledsoe getting
pounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times we knew what to do and then didn't do it,''
Belichick said. ``Twice in the game people came loose from the back
side (of Bledsoe, his left) and hit him in the back. Those weren't
physical problems. They have good, physical players up front, but
we created problems for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Those problems have to be solved, and a six-time Pro Bowl tackle
will surely not repeat his, but pointing out the problems is far
easier for critics than solving them will be for Belichick. Isaia
may help, but he is but one guard on a line that at the moment
seems solid only at center when Woody is in there.
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle Grant Williams actually played well against a
difficult pass rusher in Chidi Ahanotu, left guard Derrick Fletcher
played like what he is _ an inexperienced big man _ and Andersen
played better than what he is, a seventh-round draft choice from
1998. That's why Andersen played so often and why when the Patriots
go to the shotgun he moves in at center and Woody shifts to guard.
Of course, if Woody weren't wilder than Steve Blass when asked to
make the shotgun snap, that shift wouldn't be in vogue, so don't
make more of that than it is.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone looking for a big personnel shakeup Monday night in
front of Bledsoe or a shift to playing the same five offensive
linemen from opening whistle to final gun can forget it. For now,
the solution to six sacks and 14 knockdowns is Sale Isaia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
