<HEADLINE>
CITY ZIP HITS A TRIPLE AT SARATOGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In horse racing, a tie counts as a win. That's an important
distinction that allowed City Zip's name to be inscribed on a very
important page in the Saratoga record book.
</P>
<P>
   When City Zip rallied to gain a dead heat with Yonaguska in the
$200,000 Hopeful Stakes at Saratoga Saturday, he joined Regret
(1914), Campfire (1916), and Dehere (1993) as the only horses to
sweep all three of the major 2-year-old stakes at The Spa (the
Sanford, the Saratoga Special, and the Hopeful). Regret went on to
become the first filly to win the Kentucky Derby, while Dehere was
2-year-old champion.
</P>
<P>
   Because both of his front knees had been operated on for
ligament problems, City Zip cost only $9,000 when purchased as a
yearling by owner Carl Bowling. His sire, Carson City, was strictly
a sprinter, but City Zip is making hay while the races are short,
and he has now won 5 of 8 starts (8-5-2-1) for trainer Linda Rice,
who enjoys an excellent reputation for her handling of juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Both Yonaguska, who cost nearly $2 million as a yearling and is
trained by D. Wayne Lukas for owner Michael Tabor, and City Zip had
excuses to lose the 7-furlong Hopeful, but each overcame trouble to
hit the wire together, ahead of nine rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the Hopeful, a thunderstorm was threatening Saratoga,
so the horses went directly to the gate without a post parade and
were sent off three minutes ahead of the scheduled 5:22 p.m. post.
City Zip stalked Yonaguska through the early running, but suddenly
dropped back nearing the far turn. His rider, Jose Santos, said
City Zip had been frightened by lightning around the area before
and during the race. But City Zip, the 7-5 choice, got back in gear
and made a rippling, five-wide run to catch 7-2 shot Yonaguska, who
had opened up a 1 1/2-length lead past the eighth-pole, right on
the line in the time of 1:24 2/5 over a track that was still fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He overcame a lot to win this,'' said Santos. ``We started
making our run around the turn, and there was no room on the
inside. But he came with a huge run down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey insisted that Yonaguska, a son of Cherokee Run, would
have won had the saddle not slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the backstretch, the saddle started to ride up on his
neck, and I lost a lot of leverage,'' he said. ``My plan was to
angle him out once we got to the stretch, but I had to keep him on
the rail becaue I didn't want to move with him. I don't think he
was on the best part of the track, and he still ran a great race.
He'll only get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Macho Uno, who finished third at 9-1, closed between horses and
was beaten only a neck. He also had an eventful trip, and the son
of Holy Bull, who was making only his second start after breaking
his maiden in his debut, may have a bright future.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the gate, he reared his head up and hit me in the nose,''
said Edgar Prado, who rode Macho Uno for owner Frank Stronach and
trainer Joe Orseno. ``He gave me a bloody nose, but I was fine. At
the top of the stretch, he started ducking in and was goofing
around. He started picking it up again when City Zip came on the
outside. He ran a big race.''
</P>
<P>
   City Zip took the Sanford July 27 by better than 3 lengths, and
the Saratoga Special by better than 2 Aug. 16. In the Sanford, he
handed Yonaguska (4-3-1-0), who did not contest the Saratoga
Special, his only defeat. Yonaguska had beaten City Zip in the
Flash Stakes at Belmont June 9, so their head-to-head rivalry
stands at one win each, with a tie. It will be interesting to
follow these two colts as they head toward the $1 million Breeders'
Cup Juvenile at Churchill Downs Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Juvenile is run at a mile and one-16th, and at that
distance, it may turn out that Macho Uno is the one to watch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Surf' is up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surfside, a top 3-year-old filly who was considered a Kentucky
Derby candidate before being injured, zipped 5 furlongs over the
Oklahoma training track at Saratoga Saturday in 1:01 under Pat Day,
as she continues her comeback bid under the eye of Lukas. A
daughter of Seattle Slew, Surfside, who had won four Grade I races,
chipped both front ankles, and has not raced since finishing fifth
in the Santa Anita Derby April 8. ``We're still debating about
where we should send her after Saratoga,'' said Lukas. ``I'd like
to get her one start before the Breeders' Cup.'' . . . Also on the
comeback trail is Mighty, a late-runner who has not competed since
injuring his right front knee while running seventh in the Blue
Grass at Keeneland April 15. Mighty, who won the Louisiana Derby,
went a half-mile in :49 1/5 over the Oklahoma surface Saturday.
``He's really coming back to himself,'' said James Jones, assistant
to trainer Frank Brothers. ``He's getting fitter and stronger.''
Mighty's connections hope he can make the Jerome Handicap at
Belmont Sept. 23 . . . A reminder that, for this week only,
Rockingham Park will be dark to live racing Wednesday but run a
live card Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was
used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
