<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE: DO IT YOURSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe every business needs a hook, but that doesn't mean every
business plan must be unique.
</P>
<P>
   For entrepreneurs who freeze up at the keyboard, a California
company has begun selling a $100 software package to help aspiring
capitalists generate business plans quickly using a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Nova Development Corp.'s ``Business Plan Writer Deluxe,''
package mostly consists of suggested charts and graphics to use to
impress lenders with goals like turning a pretax profit or
acquiring a certain number of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``describe your business'' section, containing
a slew of ``professionally-written text examples,'' or business
plans to crib from. According to the company's packaging, the
examples ``can often be used without modification.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the plan for a ``Used Car Business'' outlines a
marketing and sales strategy, a paragraph of suggested financial
considerations, and suggestions for management-team
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   One example: ``The number-one responsibility of our management
team is to create a friendly atmosphere where our customers come
first. They will always be courteously acknowledged with a friendly
smile and a handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't there something unseemly in admitting a business plans
could rely on so much boilerplate?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people starting businesses just don't write well, or
might need some assistance'' said Nova spokeswoman Teri Bruno.
Closely-held Nova, of Calabasas, Calif. bought competitor PlanWrite
last February for an undisclosed amount. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Web watcher &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adero Inc. has announced an alliance with with Inktomi Corp. and
America Online Inc. called ``Content Bridge,'' designed to enable
companies to track exactly who's viewing their Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Adero, of Charlestown, Mass., says its software deployed as part
of the alliance will make it easier for Web-site operators to
figure out exactly which users are accessing their content _ and
bill them.
</P>
<P>
   Currently much content is distributed off the Internet backbone
systems operated of Internet service provider comapnies like AOL
and PSINet. But as Adero chief executive Jonathan Crane points out,
the relationship means there can be ``no real economic
collaboration between the content provider and the cache,'' or the
distributor.
</P>
<P>
   With the software, content providers can pay a fee, or be paid,
when their content is called up, thus making it easier to structure
advertising deals, Crane said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded two years ago, Adero now has about 250 employees and
counts Fidelity Investments as a chief backer. It recently received
a $72 million investment from Intel, Microsoft, and Mitsubishi. The
company sees itself as a competitor to Akamai Technologies of
Cambridge, and plans to move to a new headquarters in Waltham
soon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Learning investment &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WebCT of Peabody, Mass. plans to announce that Thomson Corp. is
taking a majority stake in its online educational site,
www.webct.com. Last month the two companies had announced an
alliance whereby WebCT's coursework-administration package could be
used by teachers to assign material from Thomson's Course
Technology unit. Thomson's latest funding will bring the total
amount invested in WebCT (the CT stands for Course Tools) to $110
million.
</P>
<P>
   WebCT, which employs 173 people in Peabody, describes itself as
the ``leading provider of Web-based course tools, community,
content, and commerce to the higher education marketplace.'' Its
offerings don't always seem so serious, however; users with
RealPlayer software can download videos of a chemistry teacher
known for burning candy Gummi Bears on ``The Late Show with David
Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Learning, in Stamford, Conn., a unit of Thomson Corp.,
distributes educational material to students both in high school
and colleges, and for adult-education courses. Materials related to
oceanography, psychology, and engineering will be among the first
Thomson offerings on the site.
</P>
<P>
   WebCT's largest investor is CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass. The
company licenses out its content to students and faculty at rates
of up to $12,000 a year. The company originated with a 1995 grant
by the Univeristy of British Columbia to develop course-related
tools for the Web. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ross Kerber is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at kerber(at)globe.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
