<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0995 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-LEARNINGBRANDS-2     09-05 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LEARNINGBRANDS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 WESTWOOD, Mass.: ... be different.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seppy Basili is hunched over his desk on a Tuesday morning,
inside a modest office with no door. His is the first cubby one
finds upon entering LearningBrands.com through the wrong, unsigned
door _ the lunchroom door, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   He comes out with a smile, still a little bewildered at the
cavernous new space that puts a good 20 feet between him and the
employees he used to rub elbows with.
</P>
<P>
   He raises his arms wide and looks across the 10,000 square feet
of the new Norwood facility. This office is quiet. You can't hear
voices over the muted whir of a ventilation system. Employees are
still working at the same butcherblock desks, but they've got ample
space now.
</P>
<P>
   The color scheme is similar to the old office, cheerful red,
yellow, and blue walls. The floor is cinderblock, with carpet only
under clusters of desks. Several thick, black coils hang from the
ceiling, with electrical outlet boxes suspended several inches from
the floor _ an inexpensive alternative to rewiring the whole place.
</P>
<P>
   Basili points about 40 feet away, to the row of offices where
Henderson and Nick Vennaro, the chief operating officer and
technology guru, sit. They decided not to put all the top
executives' offices on the same wall, he says, to avoid creating a
traditional ``corridor of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the company's mantra, he says, ``We don't believe in a
hierarchy of ideas.'' But, he concedes, ``In reality, there is a
hierarchy of management.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Basili and Henderson walk across the room many times a day
to talk. They can't shout to each other. ``At first it was weird,''
Henderson says. ``I'd find myself calling him on the phone. Then
I'd think, `What am I doing?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Meetings are more deliberate now, Basili says. People don't just
stop by and constantly interrupt him or Henderson. On the other
hand, their offices have no doors, to preserve a sense of openness.
</P>
<P>
   They wonder how soon they'll have to hire a human resources
director. They consider that the death knell, the sign they've gone
corporate.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of the bigger space, the founders say, is a bit more
privacy. It was literally impossible to have a private meeting in
Westwood. ``You had to take a walk in the parking lot,'' Henderson
says.
</P>
<P>
   And it's much easier to get writing done now, both founders say.
``Before, I either had to write before seven in the morning or
after 10 at night,'' Henderson says.
</P>
<P>
   There is a receptionist's desk now but no one to fill the job
yet. There is even a game corner, in keeping with the start-up
culture. The air hockey table is assembled and there's a
mini-basketball net on the wall. Still no foosball. For one thing,
it's expensive. For another, it's a cliche.
</P>
<P>
   The blue plastic blue couch, plus two matching chairs, is still
the only common furniture in the place. Some boxes in the
conference room offer a glimpse of things to come: new filing
cabinets. And leopardskin pillows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to spend money on people, on growing the business, not
on our space,'' Henderson says. ``We'll earn the luxuries a little
bit at a time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0996 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-LEARNINGBRANDS-2     09-05 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LEARNINGBRANDS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PENNY-PINCHING LEARNINGBRANDS FINDS ROOM TO BREATHE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Mass. _ The mirrored office building seems surreal,
plunked at the end of a dusty suburban industrial park. A blinding
July sun gleams off its 1960s facade. Two middle-aged workers smoke
cigarettes on the curb.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   The lobby is empty. There's no exposed brick, no funky dot-com
signage, no trace of hip Web marketing gurus. Except for an
inflatable blue couch.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, that's the conference room ``annex'' for
LearningBrands.com, which has used up every last inch of its space
in this Westwood office. Some 50 employees are crammed,
elbow-to-elbow, into desks fashioned from long butcherblock slabs.
The walls are bright red, the ceiling high. The room buzzes with
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere in January, our board said, `Go. Go fast,' '' says
Ted Henderson, 33, chief executive and cofounder of LearningBrands.
So the company lurched into high gear, building Web systems, hiring
designers, and wooing clients.
</P>
<P>
   They went slowly in one thing only _ spending money _ to avoid
the cash burn that's derailed many start-ups in recent months. That
may seem elementary, but the LearningBrands experience offers a
glimpse into the daunting process of growing a real company. It's a
process that goes beyond whiz-bang technology and forces
entrepreneurs to mull matters of culture and physical work space.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, a former advertising executive turned ``e-learning''
zealot, sits at a plain brown table, in spitting distance of his
partner and head of content, Seppy Basili, and just a few feet from
the rest of the troops. There are no offices or doors, not even a
cubicle. The space is too crowded for foosball; a dismantled air
hockey table leans on its end, against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't spend a lot of money,'' Henderson says. ``Fifteen
dollars a square foot.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't want to shell out the $60 a square foot landlords are
fetching for chic Cambridge digs. Henderson instead rented a tiny
room in the back of the mirrored building, where he and his
partners set up shop for their first month, with a couple of cheap
folding tables and cable spools for chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were taking it one step at a time,'' says Terry Conroy,
the building's owner and a childhood friend of Henderson's.
</P>
<P>
   He contrasts LearningBrands' penny-pinching ways to the
frivolous approach of another tenant that flamed out of business in
six months. ``The prior start-up took 40,000 square feet, bought
expensive furniture and had only 10 employees,'' Conroy says. ``He
was so confident that his new concept would be viable.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy never got his rent from that entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the market shakeout in April, start-ups and the
venture capitalists who back them have become more sober about
spending. Even in free-wheeling Silicon Valley, where rents are
sky-high, companies are moving to less glamorous addresses, more
suited to a young, profitless state.
</P>
<P>
   Bursting at the seams in this 3,000-square-foot space,
LearningBrands is now planning to move to a site triple the size.
And Henderson's nervous about it, mainly for cultural reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to lose the energy we have here. We've really
thought a lot about what happens when you put people in offices,''
he says. ``We don't believe in a hierarchy of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   LearningBrands made it for seven months on its first $1.5
million, raised from Megunticook Management in Boston last October.
Henderson had approached the firm in the summer, with little more
than his prep school pedigree, a Harvard MBA's chutzpah, and the
germ of an idea: ``Brands should teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Matlack of Megunticook told him to go back and write up a
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was definitely something there,'' Matlack says. ``When
they got rolling, thre was no one talking about (that sector). I
think they were well ahead of the curve.''
</P>
<P>
   By August, Henderson delivered the specifics, and within weeks
he had the venture capital to pursue his decidedly capitalist form
of online instruction. ``If you don't teach your customers,''
Henderson argues, ``your competitors will.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is not peddling online corporate training courses, nor
brush-up sessions on James Joyce _ both viable but separate niches.
His is an advertising and marketing model that aims to help
companies attract customers and sell more product, whether they're
dealing in bicycles, stereos, or mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $85 billion spent annually on advertising, Henderson
says: ``You should be spending some portion of your marketing
budget actively teaching your customers.''
</P>
<P>
   He speaks earnestly of e-learning, one of those unfortunate
monikers of the new economy that seems destined to fade as the
Internet becomes second nature.
</P>
<P>
   But his concept is logical. You've got seven to 12 minutes to
impress the average Internet consumer with your Web site, he says.
If that person learns something during the visit _ say a potential
boat buyer gets a quick sea kayaking course on the L.L. Bean site _
he or she is more likely to make the purchase and become a loyal
customer, he explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of getting somebody to buy something,'' says
Cushing Anderson, an analyst with IDC, a Framingham research firm.
That's a different niche, he notes, than offering customers
training after they've bought a product.
</P>
<P>
   Basili, LearningBrands' executive vice president, is the
curriculum expert and resident teacher. He holds a law degree and a
master's in education from Berkeley, where he studied how to keep
adults engaged in learning. He shows sites the firm has built for
clients, such as Cook's Illustrated in Brookline and Liberty mutual
funds in Boston, with the quiet confidence of a tenured professor.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, he said, is to connect content and commerce.
``You just have to be elegant about it and smart about it,'' Basili
says.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Cook's U,'' LearningBrands has helped the magazine
publisher run courses, such as making classic tomato sauce or
roasting the perfect turkey. Some courses are two to four weeks
long. Instructors respond to student e-mails and students can
interact on message boards. More than 3,000 people signed up in the
first six weeks, Basili said.
</P>
<P>
   The online learning field is so new, analysts say, it's up for
grabs to an array of players, including notHarvard.com of Austin,
Texas, and DigitalThink Inc. of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Rival notHarvard.com has raised $34 million since July 1999,
with backers including barnesandnoble.com. LearningBrands has
raised a total of just $5.5 million, enough to last through the
year, Henderson says. He wants to raise another $8 million to $10
million this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The company's last $4 million was secured in April from
Megunticook, from Seattle's Staenberg Venture Capital, and from
private investors, including Matthew Barzun, chief strategy officer
at CNET Networks Inc., the San Francisco-based Internet network
that produces TV and radio programs.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barzun and Jonathan Staenburg, the venture capitalist and
former Microsoft executive, sit on LearningBrands' advisory board.
The rest of the lineup is high-octane too, including Fortune
magazine president Jolene Sykes; Coby O'Brien, chief of advertising
giant Saatchi and Saatchi's interactive arm; and personalization
expert Bruce Kasanoff.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts applaud LearningBrands for a ``not-com'' attitude.
``They have this advertising agency orientation,'' says Trace
Urdan, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco.
``They're talking to the right people in the right language. I
think that's going to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson still bristles at being called an ad guy.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a respected Boston venture capitalist, Greylock
Management Corp.'s Robert Henderson, his first job after Dartmouth
College was with the Chicago agency Leo Burnett. Then he leaped
into the education field, working most recently as a senior manager
at Kaplan Educational Centers (where he and Basili met), the
trainers for college and grad-school entrance tests. He also
founded the Boston Learning Society, a Needham-based adult
education center.
</P>
<P>
   He's about to learn some new lessons of his own, as he and his
colleagues prepare to move out of their start-up space. Henderson
is excited. But he's also anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried,'' he admits. ``It will really be different.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
