<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MOORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGA PRESIDENT FACES BIGGEST GAME OF HIS CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ Is Peter Moore A glutton for punishment?
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain his last two jobs _ vice president of
marketing at Reebok International Ltd., and now president of Sega
of America?
</P>
<P>
   At Reebok, Moore and his Canton, Mass. shoe company were stomped
by Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Today at Sega, Moore is gazing up at the looming heel of Sony,
the Godzilla of the game console industry. On Oct. 26, Sony is
launching its highly anticipated PlayStation 2 video-game console
in America. This gives Moore roughly two months to outmaneuver
Sony, or at least get out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who came to the United States from Britain in 1981 to
play soccer for the Cleveland Cobras, is hustling to do just that.
This week, Sega is slashing the price of its Dreamcast console 25
percent, to $149. It's also launching its online gaming network,
SegaNet. And it is discounting its top-selling ``all star'' games,
including Sega Bass Fishing, Sonic Adventure, and NFL 2K.
</P>
<P>
   Will the hat trick work?
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly have to do something,'' said P.J. McNealy, a
technology analyst with Gartner Group in San Jose. ``Sega's biggest
advantage is that they are the first company to do online console
gaming. If they can do it well and Sony can't, that's a huge window
of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is placing a huge bet on SegaNet, in the same way Reebok
wagered millions on its Shaquille O'Neal endorsement. Set to launch
Thursday, SegaNet promises to let people play video games over the
Net using their Dreamcasts. While gamers have played online for
years on PCs, SegaNet will be the first to let people play online
through a console. For those without a Net connection, Sega will
provide dial-up access for $21.95 a month, the same fee charged by
America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   It is a high-wire gambit. To break even, Sega will have to sign
up 200,000 paying SegaNet users by March 2001, said McNealy. The
SegaNet launch this week would also have to be glitch-free. To do
that, Sega would have to solve a technical quirk recently unearthed
by testers _ many reported difficulty logging into SegaNet when
they used an Internet access provider other than Sega's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sega has an opportunity to set the stage for people's
expectations of online gaming,'' said McNealy. ``A lot rides on
what happens next week.''
</P>
<P>
   For Moore, this is a familiar refrain. He heard similar
critiques when he was at Reebok in the 1990s when Reebok went up
against Nike _ and lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent more time trying to out-Nike Nike rather than being
true to ourselves,'' said Moore, 45. ``This made us schizophrenic
in our brand positioning. You could say we lost our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok, with decent success, has in recent years returned to its
core business _ fitness and cross-training shoes with an emphasis
on comfort. Sega likewise made blunders in the 1990s with its
overly ambitious Saturn console. Its market share sank below 1
percent in June 1999. Last year, Sega refocused, introduced the
Dreamcast in the fall, and reclaimed a 15 percent market share as
of August.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is working hard to defend Sega's hard-won ground. Knowing
that consumers buy consoles only when there are good games to be
played, he recently criss-crossed the country to personally meet
with 18 game developers over five weeks to urge them to continue to
make games for the Dreamcast. He's also throwing $130 million this
fiscal year into a marketing blitz. And he's stuffed Sega's
pipeline with dozens of new games.
</P>
<P>
   All this has not silenced Sega's naysayers, but that doesn't
bother Moore. A chipper bloke, Moore grew up in a pub his parents
owned in Liverpool. Moore moved to the United States in 1981 to
play and coach soccer. Two years later, he became a salesman for
Patrick USA, a subsidiary of a French athletic shoe company. Five
years later, he became the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Reebok beckoned Moore to develop its worldwide soccer
business. When Reebok retrenched two years ago, Moore ``became a
bit of a dinosaur.'' He left Reebok in 1998 as the senior vice
president of marketing to become head of marketing for Sega of
America. He became Sega's president in April 1998, at the company's
nadir. Perhaps that's why all this talk of gloom and doom doesn't
seem to annoy Moore; he's seen worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything said about us is always skeptical,'' said Moore.
``We're always having to prove everybody wrong. And we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
