<HEADLINE>
HAVING FUN, FUN, FUN AT THE AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some things in life you can count on. Here, from Ed's Joke List
on the Web (www.eds-jokelist.com) are a few of the things bound to
happen on flights:
</P>
<P>
   --No flight ever leaves on time unless you are running late and
need the delay to catch the plane.
</P>
<P>
   --Flights never leave from Gate Number 1 at any terminal in the
world. And the later you are, the farther away your gate is.
</P>
<P>
   --If you have to work on a flight, you will experience
turbulence as soon as you begin to write. (Or start to drink your
coffee.)
</P>
<P>
   --If you are assigned a middle seat, you can determine who has
the seats on the aisle and the window while you're still in the
boarding area. Just find the two largest passengers.
</P>
<P>
   --Only passengers in window seats ever have to get up to go to
the lavatory.
</P>
<P>
   --The crying baby on board is always seated next to you.
</P>
<P>
   (We thank faithful contributor and Web whiz Mike Schuster of
Foxborough for locating these tongue-in-cheek truisms.)
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: On what island is Tokyo? (Answer at end of
column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
What's in a word? In the United States, you ``pass'' a car. In
Great Britain and Australia, you ``overtake'' it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Museum of the month: Eighteenth- and 19th-century Concord clocks
were works of art. See for yourself at the Concord Museum, where
more than 30 of the finest examples of these treasured timepieces
will be on display Sept. 8-Jan. 21. During that time, there will
also be a variety of programs related to the exhibit, including
programs for children and families. For more information on
``Keeping Time: Clockmaking in Concord, 1790-1835,'' call
978-369-9763, e-mail cm1(at)concordmuseum.org, or visit
www.concordmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``The longing for paradise is paradise itself'' _
Khalil Gibran. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Spring city: Reykjavik, Iceland, is the only capital on the planet
heated entirely by underground springs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Restless on the road: Nearly half of all travelers suffer from
sleeplessness, says a survey by Hilton Hotels and the National
Sleep Foundation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Amazing travel question: visitor to a shop in Bar Harbor, Maine,
asked: ``At what age is a deer fully matured and considered a
moose?'' (With thanks to Ken Stalberg of Belmont.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Honshu. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIDBITS MAILBAG &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In response to a Travel Trivia answer that said Big Ben is the
nickname for St. Stephen's Tower in London, Paul Mason of
Brookline, Mass. writes that this is a common misconception. ``Big
Ben is actually the name of the bell itself _ and only the one that
strikes the hours. St. Stephen's Tower (in which the bell is
housed) does not have a nickname.'' Chiming in with similar
comments were Joseph Schmuch of Reading, Harry Gennis of Concord,
and Rose Johnson of Augusta, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hounsome of Ottawa, in responding to a reader's comment
that ``America'' should refer to more than just the United States,
writes: ``All the people in North and South America are Americans,
yet it's only the US of A that uses that term to describe its
citizens, which is just a bit irritating to us non-US Americans.
May I suggest `Usanians'? Better yet, start a contest to rename
your country and give it a name which isn't just the equivalent of
a bunch of political entities which banded together as part of this
continent. You've got a great country, get a great name. I suggest
`Bob.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our mention that Calais, Maine, and Calais, France, were
pronounced differently (CAL-is vs. Cal-AY) brought this response
from Fred Cohen of Newton, Mass.: ``You don't have to go to France
to get pronunciation variants. How about Des Moines, Iowa
(de-MOIN), and Des Plains, Ill. (Des PLAINS).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Pike of Natick, Mass. continues to protest our use of
``loopy laws,'' saying we have failed ``to verify the truth of the
bizarre things you write.'' He calls our sources inadequate and
cites a law we mentioned earlier, saying it cannot be found on the
books.
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but not all the laws or ordinances are as worded in
our source books. Some stem from incidents where existing laws
(public nuisance, care of animals, driving to endanger, public
nudity, etc.) are applied in court or elsewhere to so-called
bizarre behavior in the city or state mentioned in the loopy law.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate: Stuart Cohen of Marblehead, Mass. notes that in
Sandwich, Mass., near the pond by the old grist mill, a sign says,
``Abandoning of ducks or geese shall be punished by a fine of not
more than $500. Violators will be prosecuted to the fullest extent
of the law. (Massachusetts General Laws) 272 Sec. 77.'' That
section of the law, however, says nothing about ducks or geese but
a lot about animal cruelty. Thus a loopy law might read: ``You are
forbidden to dump your ducks in Sandwich.'' (Not that there's
anything loopy about proper treatment of animals.)
</P>
<P>
   Pike responds, ``You make very good points . . . although I do
not consider a court decision to be the same as a law.'' That,
likewise, is a very good point.
</P>
</TEXT>
