<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1002 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-GREEN-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      09-05 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GREEN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREENING OF SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SYDNEY _ They are 400,000 strong, these gutsy competitors
gathered in an Olympic village the size of a gold medal podium.
They are the worms of the 27th Olympiad, a writhing mass of
spineless participants in what Olympic organizers promise will be
the most environmentally friendly Games in history.
</P>
<P>
   Housed in a large bin in the basement of the Sydney organizing
committee's headquarters, the tiger and red worms eat, process, and
turn into compost an estimated 165 pounds of organic waste daily
from a staff cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   The worm farm is among scores of ``Green Games'' projects _ from
a solar-powered athletes' village to roads pitched so that they
channel storm water for recycling _ designed to minimize waste and
resource consumption by the 500,000 people expected to converge
here each day from Sept. 15 to Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the efforts represent an unprecedented bid to
expand the Olympic credo of ``faster, higher, stronger,'' to
include the environmental mantra: ``reduce, reuse, recycle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Care for the environment has been integrated into all the
planning, design and construction of the Games,'' said Michael
Bland, a former Greenpeace official who is environmental spokesman
for the Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games. ``It's
not some kind of public relations campaign that was slapped on at
the last minute with a can of green paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Protecting the environment is surprisingly difficult at the
Olympics, which create, in essence, overnight cities with all the
sewage, waste and air pollution of major urban areas. Making
matters worse, most ``residents'' are tourists who are living on
the run and giving little thought to Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   But environmental concern has increasingly been part of Olympic
planning since the 1994 winter games in Lillehammer, Norway. There,
organizers recycled many of the buildings themselves once the Games
were over, even hauling the 500-room athletes' quarters most of the
way to the North Pole to house tourists and students. Sydney won
the 2000 Olympics in part because of planners' ambitious
environmental agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmental groups have complained that Sydney Olympic
organizers could have done more and failed to achieve all the goals
they set for themselves. But even most of the harshest critics
acknowledge that Sydney has done something remarkable, going far
beyond the achievements of previous Olympic hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is far and away the best Olympic Games from an
environmental standpoint,'' said Rupert Posner, an Olympics
campaign worker with Greenpeace Australia. The Greenpeace flagship,
the Rainbow Warrior, sailed into Sydney Harbor last week to pay
tribute to Olympic organizers' green achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the International Olympic
Committee, has gone so far as to declare that, in light of Sydney's
efforts, protecting the environment will be the ``third dimension''
of the Olympic movement, along with sport and culture.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Sydney seemed the least likely city to become a
role model for Olympic environmentalism, if only because of the
industrial wasteland where it decided to stage the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the competition and ceremonies will take place at the
Sydney Olympic Park at Homebush Bay, a 1,900-acre site with a
two-century history of environmental abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Ten miles from downtown, its first industrial use began in the
early 1800s, as a saltworks, and later as a naval armaments depot.
In 1907, part of the site was set aside for a state abattoir that
eventually became the largest in the Southern Hemisphere, employing
1,600 people who slaughtered more than 20,000 animals daily.
</P>
<P>
   Futher degrading the site, part of Homebush Bay was home to a
brickworks for much of the 20th century, creating a landscape so
barren and ugly it was chosen as a location for the
post-apocalyptic movie ``Mad Max III: Beyond Thunderdome.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s and 70s, as Sydney grew up around it, Homebush Bay
became an enormous dump. Domestic, commercial and industrial waste
was strewn throughout one-quarter of the site, with enough refuse
to cover a football field with a mile-high trash mound.
</P>
<P>
   Wetlands had been filled, creeks had been converted to concrete
channels, and waterways were badly contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Although reclamation work began in the 1980s, it wasn't until
1993, when Sydney was awarded the 2000 Summer Olympics, that the
cleanup moved into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Integrated into Sydney's proposal to the IOC was a detailed plan
to restore Homebush Bay's natural beauty at the same time sports
facilities were being built. The sweeping efforts fell into five
main categories: energy conservation; water conservation; waste
avoidance; pollution avoidance; and protection of significant
natural and cultural environments.
</P>
<P>
   From the first shovel of dirt to the eventual choice of
packaging used at the ubiquitous McDonald's restaurants at Homebush
Bay, environmental considerations frequently trumped commercial
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Among the results:
</P>
<P>
   -- The 110,000-seat Olympic Stadium was designed to save energy
with a sophisticated natural ventilation system that draws in cool
air while allowing warm air to escape. Similarly, the Aquatic
Center was designed to cool only the air surrounding the spectators
_ not around the pool _ which saves both on cooling the stands and
heating the pool. The Aquatic Center also was designed to
significantly reduce the use of toxic chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   -- Existing wastes were consolidated into four containment areas
on the site _ large mounds essentially _ each of which was capped
with clay, topsoil and landscaping at a cost of $90 million.
Contaminated runoff from the mounds is collected in drains, pumped
into tankers, and taken to a nearby waste treatment plant.
Meanwhile, formerly damaged wetlands are being restored to a more
natural creek system.
</P>
<P>
   -- The design of the Olympic Village _ through methods including
shading, cross-ventilation, and energy-efficient appliances _
reduces energy demand by 50 percent compared to conventional
construction. Most of that demand is met by solar power, making it
the world's largest solar-powered suburb. After housing 15,000
athletes during the Games, the village will become a private
neighborhood _ prices start around $200,000. Solar power is also
used in numerous other places in the Olympic Park, including 19
huge solar towers that line, and light, the main thoroughfare,
Olympic Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   -- A dual water system was developed to provide drinking water
through one set of pipes and non-drinkable water _ recycled from
storm water and sewage effluent _ through a second set. The
non-drinkable water is used for irrigation and toilet flushing.
Streets and buildings were designed to catch and channel as much
storm water as possible to a complex filtration system.
</P>
<P>
   -- Plans to build the Olympic Tennis Center at the former
brickworks were changed when it was discovered that, despite its
polluted past, the site was home to the rare green and golden bell
frog. Special tunnels were built to allow the frogs to move through
the site without the risk of being squished. In a stroke of
particularly good luck for the frog, its green and gold coloring
matches Australia's sporting colors, instantly turning the
amphibian into an unofficial national mascot.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Sydney Games will be the first car-free Olympics, with
nearly all spectators using public transportation to Homebush Bay.
New train lines that can handle 50,000 people an hour were built at
a cost of $54 million to reduce pollution and increase access and
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   -- To offset greenhouse gases, Olympic organizers have
undertaken the planting of 2 million trees, not just at Homebush
Bay but across Australia.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Olympic Torch was designed to be both energy-efficient
and non-polluting; ``solar buggies'' will move athletes around the
site; and building materials throughout Homebush Bay were chosen
for environmental friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic organizers say there is no way to calculate the added
costs of the environmental efforts. ``They were integral to
everything, so it's not like we added them separately and asked,
how much could we save by not doing this,'' Bland said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the few items with environmental price tags are the
initial waste cleanup, which cost about $90 million, and the water
recycling plant, $10 million. The total cost of transforming
Homebush Bay and building the sports venues was about $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The results have generally won praise, but some skeptics have
wondered whether the environmental efforts have been overplayed by
a public relations machine eager to polish Olympic rings tarnished
by bribery scandals and various smaller missteps.
</P>
<P>
   Take the worms as an example.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
