<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SUNAPEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT SUNAPEE, IT'S ALL ABOUT LAKE, MOUNTAIN, TRANQUILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNAPEE, N.H. _ ``There have been two important times in
Sunapee's history,'' declares Capt. Bob Henry as he heads the
excursion boat M/V Mount Sunapee II out into Lake Sunapee. ``One
was 100 years ago, and the other is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, more than a dozen grand resort hotels were built
in the Lake Sunapee area and a fleet of steamers launched to carry
visitors, most of whom came for long stays from Boston or New York
by train, to resorts and summer homes around the 9-mile-long lake.
The passenger trains, steamers and vast old wooden hotels are long
gone, victims of changing times.
</P>
<P>
   However, the things that attracted visitors in the first place,
the large, crystal-clear lake (there are also a number of smaller
lakes and ponds in the area) and Mount Sunapee _ the 2,743
foot-high mountain that towers over it _ are still here. And
they're both being rediscovered and appreciated by a new generation
of city dwellers looking for easy-to-get-to natural beauty and
tranquility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a backwater,'' says innkeeper Ted Harriman happily.
``There are no shopping malls, bowling alleys or fast-food
franchises. All those things are not too far away if you need them,
but they're just not here.'' Harriman owns the 16-room Inn at
Sunapee (603-763-4444/www.innatsunappee.com), a former 1870s dairy
farm typical of the pleasant but modestly sized (and priced) inns
and B&AMP;Bs that have replaced the resort palaces of the Gilded Age.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mount Sunapee II cruises down the lake, Capt. Henry
points out the sights: a lighthouse, one of three on the lake; the
sites of several once-famous resort hotels; and the yacht club with
the country's largest flotilla of Star Class racing sailboats.
Also, some landmark old homes and cottages. ``That one has been in
the same family for five generations,'' he says of a sturdy-looking
lakeside cottage.
</P>
<P>
   Given Lake Sunapee's long history as the focal point of a resort
area, there is still a surprising amount of undeveloped land along
the shoreline, including forested sections belonging to the John
Hay National Wildlife Refuge and Mount Sunapee State Park. The
state park's long, sandy beach is Lake Sunapee's only public beach,
but there are a number of places where boats can be launched.
</P>
<P>
   There's also quite a bit of construction around the lake.
Calling attention to a large mansion being built on a beautiful
point of land jutting into the lake, Henry shakes his head in
wonderment. ``They say that place will cost about $10 million when
it's finished,'' he says, ``Sunapee is changing!''
</P>
<P>
   Another visible example of the area's renaissance is Sunapee
Harbor, home port for the vessels of Sunapee Cruises
(603-763-4030/www.sunapeecruises.com), the Mt. Sunapee II and its
sister vessel M/V Kearsage, which carries passengers on nightly
dinner cruises around the lake. The center of resort activity at
the turn of the 20th century, Sunapee Harbor fell on hard times
with the completion of Interstate 89, which made the area _ now
only a 90-minute drive from Boston _ more a day trip than a
vacation destination for southern New England.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, most of the buildings in Sunapee Harbor were
boarded up. Today, largely because of the efforts of the
improvement-minded Sunapee Harbor Riverway Corporation, the harbor
is a lively and attractive place once more. Beds of flowers
brighten a waterfront park, and a large bandstand _ which stands on
the site of the Ben Mere, last of the local grand hotels _ is the
scene of frequent concerts and performances.
</P>
<P>
   There are several interesting gift shops and boutiques in
Sunapee Harbor, including the Wild Goose and the Woodbine Shoppe as
well as The Anchorage (603-763-3334), an informal restaurant with a
lakeside deck that's a popular place to be just about anytime on a
sunny day. The Sunapee Historical Society operates a small seasonal
museum, housed in a former livery stable across from the excursion
boat dock, filled with photos of the old hotels and memorabilia of
the steamboat era, including the pilot house of one steamer.
</P>
<P>
   Sunapee Harbor is the area's summer recreation focal point,but
the year-round hub is New London, a few miles to the east on Route
11. An elegant old town with a gracious Main Street, New London is
the home of Colby-Sawyer College, a liberal arts college founded in
1837. Another local cultural institution is the highly regarded New
London Barn Playhouse (603-526-6710) one of the oldest summer stock
theaters in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Another important fixture in town is the venerable New London
Inn (603-526-2791/800-526-2791) on Main Street, founded in 1792,
and still dispensing food, drink and hospitality. Peter Christian's
Tavern (603-526-4042), a nearby restaurant, gets high marks from
locals, and there is usually a line waiting to get in.
</P>
<P>
   Maple Hill Farm (800-231-8637/www.maplehillfarm.com) a 175-
year-old, 10-guest-room farmhouse just off the I-89 exit for New
London, is a cozy and comfortable B&AMP;B with an authentic country
feel to it. (There are sheep in a back pasture, and the eggs served
at breakfast come from the farm's hens.)
</P>
<P>
   Also pretty traditional is Twin Lake Village (603-526-6460), a
200-acre resort on Little Lake Sunapee in New London. Owned by the
Kidder family since the 1890s, this really is rather like a
village: Guests stay in 18 two-story mansard-roofed ``cottages''
scattered around the grounds. One of the amenities is a nine-hole
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Because until the 1920s most visitors to Lake Sunapee arrived in
the area by train and got around the lake by boat, no road was
built around the shoreline. So, it's almost impossible to get good
lake views from a car. To see Lake Sunapee up close, you have to
get out on the water. For the best overview, however, the place to
be is the summit of Mount Sunapee.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain is also enjoying something of a renaissance. Mount
Sunapee is part of the state park, but two years ago the formerly
state-run ski area was leased to the Okemo Mountain Co. of Vermont,
which has expanded thefacilities and operating season. Mount
Sunapee Resort (1-877-687-8627/603-763-2356/www.mtsunapee.com) now
has an active summer program that includes mountain biking,
skateboarding, and special events, among them one of the largest
craft shows in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest attraction of all, however, is the chairlift that
carries hikers (the state park has a network of hiking trails) and
rubberneckers to the summit lodge. The 360-degree, panoramic view
from the top is impressive anytime but spectacular in foliage
season. And, directly below _ seeming so close you could almost
dive in _ stretches the gleaming expanse of Lake Sunapee.
</P>
<P>
   Lake and mountain. That, after all, is what the area is about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
