<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1006 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-05 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP THE RHETORIC, SAVE THE CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women's rights groups ought to take a deep breath in the legal
drama unfolding around cult member Rebecca Corneau and the
impending birth of her baby. If they don't, they're at risk of
harming their own worthy cause.
</P>
<P>
   Far more important than any murky precedent that may or may not
be established by placing Corneau in state custody, far more
significant than the ongoing intellectual parrying in the courts
and news media, is one simple, indelible fact: This case is about
life and death.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of weeks, a child will be born to Rebecca Corneau, a
child who, from the very second he or she enters this world,
deserves the full rights and protections inherent as a citizen of
the United States. That child didn't ask to be born to a member of
an extremist cult, and that child shouldn't be put at risk because
of the mother's noxious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Some facts: Two children of this Attleboro, Mass. cult are
missing and presumed dead _ a 10-month-old who authorities have
good reason to believe was starved to death over the course of
three agonizing months as part of ``God's will,'' and an infant
(Corneau's most recent child) who died at birth, probably for lack
of proper medical care.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-member cult regards science and medicine as blasphemy and
refuses to acknowledge the existence of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Members apparently buried the tiny bodies in makeshift coffins,
perhaps somewhere in the wilderness of Baxter State Park in Maine.
No one really knows because the cult members won't say. Rather than
speak to authorities, eight of them have been placed in jail for
contempt of court. Cult leader Jacques Robidoux went so far as to
tell a judge that authorities have no right to search for his
missing son, Samuel, because the boy was a sovereign individual and
not a citizen of the United States. Good one.
</P>
<P>
   So officials have taken a series of uncommonly sensible steps.
First, a judge ruled that the members of the cult _ including
Corneau _ were unfit parents, and so their 13 children were removed
and placed in the custody of the state Department of Social
Services.
</P>
<P>
   Then District Attorney Paul Walsh asked a judge to place
Corneau, who is believed to be about 8 1/2 months pregnant, in
state custody to assure that she will take proper steps in
delivering a healthy baby. After Corneau refused to be examined by
a court-appointed nurse, Attleboro Juvenile Court Judge Kenneth
Nasif granted the order, and last week, she was taken from the
courthouse to a state prison hospital in an unmarked cruiser by a
pair of state troopers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is that as soon as the baby is delivered, Corneau will
be free to go; the child will be turned over to the DSS.
</P>
<P>
   Enter an assortment of women's advocates and civil rights
groups, many of whom have begun sounding as shrill as the National
Rifle Association when it fights proposed bans on deadly submachine
guns by saying that such measures will erode the rights of hunters.
</P>
<P>
   In a vacuum, their arguments have some merit. It is not without
alarm that the government detains a healthy woman for the purpose
of imposing the medical will of a prosecutor and judge. There are
civil rights, religious rights, that create the foundation of our
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be clear: The body count from this cult already stands
at two _ two boys named Samuel and Jeremiah. A criminal
investigation forges onward, the detectives trying to penetrate the
wall of silence.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be equally clear: This is not about religious freedom. No
acceptable religion allows a child in its immediate care to starve
to death. No acceptable religion hides corpses from authorities who
don't just have a right but a responsibility to recover and analyze
them.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, this is not about abortion rights, of which I'm
entirely, unequivocally in favor. In this one instance, it is about
the care of just one child _ a newborn who will be endangered by a
group of fanatics the second he or she enters the world.
</P>
<P>
   One commentator recently said authorities were only ``guessing''
at the danger involved. With two dead, whether by intent or
neglect, it's a pretty educated guess.
</P>
<P>
   Women's groups would do well to acknowledge that Corneau's
newborn baby has the right to be protected against a cult in which
children tend to die. These women's advocates don't want to appear
extreme, which is precisely how they look right now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
