<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-AMICHAI-BOS &LR;      09-05 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-AMICHAI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE WALKS HOLY CITY'S LITTLE CORNERS OF HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Yehuda Amichai pulls back the window curtain on the
soft light at the end of the day and looks over the climbing pink
bougainvillea and onto the Old City's gray ramparts at Jaffa Gate.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's 75-year-old poet laureate, the man who has put words to
the soul of Jerusalem, watches people traverse the paths that lead
through dry scrub pines and up into the fortress-side revetments of
the Ottoman-era gate _ Orthodox Jews in black hats, Palestinian
children pushing vendor carts, tourists with their camera bags.
</P>
<P>
   They are Jerusalem, and they are all his muse. From his home in
the Yemin Moshe neighborhood, a hillside of stone bungalows with
red-tiled roofs and long windows facing the Old City, Amichai just
watches and says nothing.
</P>
<P>
   With the future of Jerusalem in the hands of Israeli and
Palestinian leaders, and so many political analysts and ideologues
with opinions on sovereignty and sacred space, it seemed time to go
to Amichai for the poet's view on the city that is holy to three
faiths and a national symbol to two peoples.
</P>
<P>
   His passion as a writer _ mostly of poems but also of novels and
short stories _ has always been for the people whom these decisions
will affect the most _ the ones who live here.
</P>
<P>
   Amichai dwells in ``the small corners,'' as he puts it, of
Jerusalem, the human moments, the contact _ and the lack of it _
between people. How will they fare after all the negotiating is
done _ or undone _ and the city has to go on?
</P>
<P>
   So is Amichai hopeful?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopeful means nothing. Hopeful is too big a word. I have cut
it down to little hopes. One peaceful day with a breeze,'' says
Amichai. ``I don't look high, I look down. On a dish in a
restaurant. Buying vegetables from a woman in the Old City. At this
bougainvillea plant. My hopes are not like big stones, but little
stones ground up and made of cement that will support a whole
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked every little corner of Jerusalem,'' says Amichai,
slowly shuffling in from a terrace to sit in a bamboo chair. Two
fans are cooling him on a scorching hot day. ``I walked every
little corner of hope. And somewhere in there, that's where peace
will come from.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Amichai speak is to hear him form a poem, thoughts and
words carefully chosen and then arranged and presented in a slow,
raspy voice. But, put to the page, these words are more than
collections of poems; they have become part of the daily language
of modern Hebrew. They are woven into life here. He is Israel's
Robert Frost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amichai is somebody who has managed to tap into the deepest
currents in this society, the greatest hopes and the deepest
sorrows, in a way that is simultaneously high literature and an
expression of the common soul,'' says Noga Tarnopolsky, an Israeli
writer and reviewer of literature and poetry who has just returned
from a fellowship at Amherst College.
</P>
<P>
   Lines from his poems have become proverbs voiced by people every
day. And he is alone among Israeli writers in having made a
contribution to modern Hebrew, a language that was re-created only
within the last 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Phrases such as, ``It's sad to be the mayor of Jerusalem,'' can
be heard just about any day, on any street corner or city bus. The
phrase conveys a resignation to the craziness of life in Jerusalem,
and is taken from one of his best-known poems, titled ``Mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Other lines uttered among lovers and former lovers have been
etched into the collective consciousness, such as, ``A pity. We
were such a good invention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is loved. He is truly loved,'' says Ariel Hirschfeld, a
professor of literature at Hebrew University. ``It's probably hard
to understand how much outside of Israel. But it is an appreciation
across all of the generations of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``His poems are our slang, they are our popular wisdom,'' adds
Hirschfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Amichai was born in Wurzburg, Germany, in 1924, and his family
immigrated to what was then Palestine in 1936, when it was under
the rule of the British Mandate of the League of Nations after
World War I. The family landed at the port of Haifa, and Amichai's
life has been woven into the history of this land ever since. He
has been part of Israel's struggle to exist, then to survive, and
now, as he puts it, to overcome the past and ``just live'' in the
``complicated mess'' that is Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He fought with the Jewish Brigade of the British Army in World
War II, and after discharge in 1946 he joined the Palmach, an elite
fighting unit of the emerging Jewish state. He fought in Israel's
1948 War of Independence on the southern front, in the Negev
region.
</P>
<P>
   Following the war, he attended Hebrew University and studied
biblical texts and Hebrew literature. He held a series of teaching
positions, and through it all he sat down every day at an old
wooden desk, one he still has in his office, and wrote poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now and in Other Days,'' his first volume of poetry, was
published in 1955 to very good reviews, and he has been a prominent
figure on Israel's literary landscape ever since. He is now
published in 37 languages and has been awarded the prestigious
Israel Prize. His most recent collection of poems, ``Open Closed
Open,'' was recently published in English.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other poets who are successful in their own time,
Amichai has his share of critics. Some have been known to scoff at
his poetry as facile, and too approachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a good poet for critics,'' says Tarnopolsky, who is
an admirer. ``He is so direct and so heartfelt that he touches
people, and doesn't give much work for critics who want to
deconstruct and explain. Amichai's poetry doesn't need them.''
</P>
<P>
   Amichai has written beautifully about Jerusalem, about love, but
also about war, especially the loss and the fear that come with
war. One poem, titled ``I Want to Die in My Own Bed,'' was seen by
some Israelis as a kind of betrayal of the Zionist cause.
</P>
<P>
   He is among the founders of Peace Now, the Israeli peace
movement that has pushed for justice and reconciliation among
Israelis and Palestinians, and in many ways he has sought to pave a
path toward the long, drawn-out negotiations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a soldier in his soul. But he was always proud of
his service. He felt it a duty,'' says his wife, Hanna, who sat by
his side through an interview and cared for him through two years
of cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is in remission from lymphoma, but the deep lines
etched on his face tell of a long battle with illness. He still has
a proud profile, with the bent nose of a boxer. His skin has a warm
tone, like worn leather.
</P>
<P>
   He has a son and a daughter in their 20s, and an older son from
a previous marriage has given him his first grandchild. On
Saturday, the Sabbath, he gathers with his family.
</P>
<P>
   He is a staunch Zionist but not religious, he says, at least not
since he was a boy. Still, he has a stone on his desk with the
Hebrew word ``Amen'' etched into it. It is a 1,000-year-old
fragment from a Jewish cemetery in his hometown in Germany. It is
his talisman, a sandstone triangle that he unconsciously holds in
his hand, as if he were gauging its weight while he talks.
</P>
<P>
   His father was an Orthodox Jew, and Amichai's poetry seems drawn
to the mystery of faith, and to prayer. Asked about his father, he
smiles and says, ``We had such love.'' But Amichai struggles with
the religion of his father, warming his hands by its fire but
pulling away and yelling in lyrical verse when it burns.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Amichai's poetry is Jerusalem. He is a scribe in the
Holy City with an ability to see life from many perspectives, and
in that sense he has opened Israel up to the possibilities of peace
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Amichai has, on occasion, done readings with the Palestinian
poet laureate Mahmud Darwish. But he does not see two poets getting
together for a select group of academic elites as true peace. That,
he says, has to come from the people, from the streets, and from
those ``small corners of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his most enduring poems is titled simply ``Jerusalem.''
At the end of a long, hot day, he reads it aloud:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a roof in the Old City
</P>
<P>
   Laundry hanging in the late afternoon sunlight:
</P>
<P>
   The white sheet of a woman who is my enemy,
</P>
<P>
   The towel of a man who is my enemy,
</P>
<P>
   To wipe off the sweat on his brow.
</P>
<P>
   In the sky of the Old City
</P>
<P>
   A kite.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the string,
</P>
<P>
   A child.
</P>
<P>
   I can't see
</P>
<P>
   Because of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   We have put up many flags,
</P>
<P>
   They have put up many flags.
</P>
<P>
   To make us think they're happy,
</P>
<P>
   To make them think that we're happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
