<HEADLINE>
IN NEW ECONOMY, MORE IS DEMANDED OF ANALYSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The job of a stock analyst used to entail, well, analyzing
stocks. But there's more to it than that in the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   With venture capitalists pumping money into a host of ambitious
technology start-ups, analysts for investment bankers increasingly
must have a handle on promising companies before they go public.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jim Kedersha. He recently left SG Cowen's Boston-based
research group to start a communications technology group for local
rival Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill. Adams wants him and his new recruits
to be gurus of the hot telecom sector, with perspectives that can
reach from the big, established companies to the emerging companies
Adams, Harkness takes public and follows for its investment
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a view on the new players in the industry,
which are often private,'' Kedersha says. ``The opportunity for
someone to come out of left field with a disruptive technology is
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites successes such as Sycamore Networks Inc. and Juniper
Networks as telecom companies that took the market by storm.
</P>
<P>
   Kedersha just lured one of his Cowen colleagues, Blaine Carroll,
a wireless expert, to join him at Adams, Harkness. His focus is on
convergence, where voice, data, and video meet and are transmitted
through wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll says clients have a range of investments, and they often
want to know not just the outlook for a particular stock, but what
buyouts of private firms mean for bigger companies, such as Cisco,
Nortel, and Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably one of the funnest parts of this business _
going out and meeting the privates,'' Carroll says.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, Harkness has gone fishing for talent at Cowen before. A
few years ago, the firm hired three biotech analysts from Cowen to
build its expertise in what is again a high-profile business,
particularly since the human genome project.
</P>
<P>
   Research is a route to greater credibility in the market, even
for regional brokers, and, with any luck, to more investment
banking business. Boston-based Tucker Anthony Sutro last week
announced it had recruited two new analysts to beef up its Internet
investment banking resources.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, Harkness now has 18 analysts, up from 14 a year ago. The
firm has been enjoying a higher profile in recent years as a
technology and health-care investment banker. And the firm's tech
conferences are drawing huge crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lead with research and follow with banking,'' says Matt
Patsky, research chief at Adams, Harkness. With the new telecom
group, he notes: ``We will be very active in the banking space. It
will be very much dictated by the research analysts'
(contributions).''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it is the job of investment bankers to find and woo
companies that are preparing to sell shares to the public. But
there are so many young companies in the Boston area market now _
particularly in telecom and Internet-related businesses _ that
analysts can be an important source of deal flow, too.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting companies and meeting with their executives,
Kedersha explains: ``If we think highly of them, that's when we try
to see if there's any role for us that fits in on the investment
banking side.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has been struggling to hold on to analysts, as
research talent is in high demand among venture capitalists,
consultants, and a new cottage industry of consulting analysts that
has sprung up around the Internet. Start-ups now regularly plan
visits to pay their respects at firms such as IDC, Forrester
Research, and Gartner Group, much as they make the rounds on Wall
Street, before going public.
</P>
<P>
   Cowen's research chief did not return a call seeking comment
about the recent departures.
</P>
<P>
   Kedersha and Carroll said they left because Cowen, since its
acquisition by French banking giant Societe Generale, is doing
bigger investment banking deals. The analysts are more interested
in emerging companies, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The added draw, Kedersha said: ``It's a smaller shop, more
focused. We have the opportunity to build something from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OneLiberty Ventures of Cambridge, Mass. has raised a new $200
million fund, which will invest mainly in early-stage information
technology companies. About one-quarter of the money will go toward
medical technology firms.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 0942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
