<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOMAKERS MAKE THEIR PLAY ON NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ You're not supposed to laugh at this, but
big car makers including General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler-Daimler
are thinking they could be the next big Internet companies of the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that as traffic and the mobile lifestyle make many
of us spend ever more time in our cars, the automobile will join
the office, home, and wireless phone as a place where we want _ and
demand _ access to the convenience, information, and entertainment
of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ford, for example, already offer services to luxury car
owners providing emergency roadside assistance and directions with
so-called telematics devices. IBM, Microsoft, Motorola, and
old-line car accessory makers such as Delphi are pouring millions
of dollars into joint ventures to roll out new car-Web services,
such as e-mail and Net access.
</P>
<P>
   But especially compared to Europe and Japan, the US market has
only begun to develop. GM's OnStar service, for example, counted
only 200,000 customers earlier this year, and Ford has yet to
launch its Wingcast venture with Qualcomm. Most systems out there
are limited to what small slices of the Web, or special in-house
services, your carmaker has arranged to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   A Belgian company called SmartMove earlier this year opened a US
subsidiary in Kendall Square that aims to become a key player in
the field by creating a unified platform for bringing a vast array
of information sources into your car.
</P>
<P>
   SmartMove envisions cars outfitted with a miniature touch-screen
device that is connected to everything from FM radio to wireless
phones to satellites to special short-range communications services
you might use at a gas station to download a movie for the kids'
back-seat TV set.
</P>
<P>
   But it would not necessarily make these devices or produce the
content delivered to cars.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, SmartMove hopes to become a king of the hill with its
plans for equipping so-called communication and control centers
that companies such as Ford and GM, or maybe America Online or
AT&AMP;T, would use to bring together a vast array of services to
deliver to your car through five or 10 communications modes. The
system would also handle connecting and billing you for them.
</P>
<P>
   By incorporating the Java computer code, which simplifies
writing programs to run on numerous devices and systems, SmartMove
hopes to create the common operating system that pretty much all
carmakers and vendors say they want but remain far from coming to
terms on.
</P>
<P>
   Today you might have an on-board navigation system running off
compact disks stored in the trunk, plus a global positioning
satellite receiver, not to mention a car phone and a radio and
maybe a port for your wireless Palm Pilot (or a passenger seat for
your wirelessly connected laptop computer).
</P>
<P>
   SmartMove hopes to make the system that enables you to put all
of those functions in a single box in your dashboard _ with
speech-recognition technology included so you can use your voice
and ears to get much of the information and keep your hands on the
wheel and eyes on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot have 100 hardware modules in my car,'' says
SmartMove's Luc De Brouckere. Likewise, there are many services you
would rather have delivered from satellites or special FM radio
channels rather than from expensive cell-phone airtime. ``You want
to have a car that can have an interface on several levels,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   One of SmartMove's innovative system features is software
allowing people to subscribe to services when they want them. For
example, instead of spending $30 every month to be connected to a
Web-based navigational aid showing where you are on a computer
screen map, you might only turn it on for $2 a pop when you are
driving someplace unfamiliar.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, instead of paying GM $35 every month for OnStar
monitoring that instantly alerts operators whenever your air bags
are deployed _ and uses GPS to help them tell an ambulance exactly
where you are _ you might be happier to spend $5 calling 911 only
when you really need 911.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond what can be sent to the car, industry officials also
think there could be a market for data sent from cars: real-time
reports from actual vehicles about how fast they are driving on
highways for traffic reports, or data on where people are using
their windshield wipers _ and at what setting _ to help forecasting
companies develop super-precise weather readings.
</P>
<P>
   A new report issued last month by UBS Warburg LLC estimated that
automotive telematics revenues will explode over the next 10 years
in the United States, from $280 million in subscriber revenues this
year to $21.7 billion in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, automotive industry leaders are convinced there is a
potential gold mine in going beyond selling people $20,000 cars
every five years to also selling them $25 Internet-access packages
every month, or $5 movie and music rentals for long trips. The idea
is not just to sell you a car you live in two hours a day, but to
make money off the time they have you captive.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have been selling steel and rubber for 100 years,''
says SmartMove marketing executive Bart Stevens. ``Now they want to
move on to bits and bytes, and the sky is the limit to come up with
new services.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at howe(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
