<HEADLINE>
YOU, TOO, CAN BE A `SPACE COWBOY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are 55 or older and dreamed of being a space cowboy, it's
time to stop fantasizing and join the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys,'' the hit movie about older astronauts
returning to space can be a near reality for just about any older
person who's ready to pull up to five ``Gs,'' fly an Advanced
Flight Simulator, or direct a lunar rover mission. And it's all
held in _ you won't believe this _ Togo, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   And, you don't have to follow the yellow brick road to find
this, just call Elderhostel and sign up for the Astronaut Training
Program held at the Smithsonian affiliate Kansas Cosmosphere and
Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   The program is based on one that has been offered to middle
school students for 16 years, and as a senior astronaut you'll
perform stress tests in the Centrifuge, a G-force trainer that
pulls up to five Gs, work in teams in the Cosmosphere's Mission
Control, fly the Advanced Flight simulator housed in an actual
F-101 cockpit, and direct a lunar rover mission much like the Mars
Pathfinder. The week ends with a pace shuttle mission aboard a
motion-based shuttle simulator, the Falcon.
</P>
<P>
   Currently 33 people ages 57 to 89 from 13 states are on the
mission of their life. The program's cost is quite reasonable. If
you live nearby, it's just $290 a person; from out of town, it's
$440 and that includes a room, meals, and transportation to and
from Cosmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmosphere is located in the prairie town of Hutchinson, about
50 miles northwest of Wichita, and houses the largest space
artifact collection outside the Smithsonian Institution's National
Air and Space Museum. The center tells the story of the Space Race
between the United States and the former Soviet Union from early
rocketry to the present and examines the future of space
exploration. Among exhibits are the largest collection of Russian
space artifacts in the Western world, a full set of Mercury,
Gemini, and Apollo spacecraft and German V-1 and V-2 rockets.
</P>
<P>
   There are four Elderhostel programs a year, with three still
upcoming. For information, call Elderhostel director Helen Unruh at
800-397-0330, ext. 319, or visit www.cosmo.org/elderhostel.htm.
</P>
<P>
   For information on other activities or programs, call
800-397-0330 or 316-662-2305 or visit www.
</P>
<P>
   cosmo.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-----
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parents who dream of someday sending their child to the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology will want to check out the
Smart Family Package at The Hotel (at)MIT, the Cambridge,
Mass.-Dot-com lifestyle hotel. The hotel is on the grounds of MIT
and features whimsical inventions and original works of modern art
in its lobby, futuristic style elevators and guest rooms with
natural light, ergonomically designed furniture, original art from
the MIT collection, modem connections, even Sony Playstations.
Packages begin at $199 weekdays, $149 weekends and are available
through Dec. 30. For information, call 617-577-0200 or 800-222-8733
or visit www.
</P>
<P>
   univparkhotel.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
White Mountains origin
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in learning how the White Mountains of New
Hampshire came to be, join the geology workshop planned for Sept.
23-24 atop Mount Washington. The workshop ($45) is designed for
those with little or no prior training in geology and will include
field trips. For information, call 800-706-0432 or visit www.
</P>
<P>
   mountwashington.org.
</P>
