<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-HAUGHEY-BOS &LR;      09-05 1581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-HAUGHEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURE, YOU'RE TALKING ABOUT THE SAME MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ There was a pause during the recent questioning of
Charles J. Haughey at Dublin Castle, where he is being asked to
explain how he managed to solicit at least $12 million from
businessmen during the three terms he served as Ireland's prime
minister, and Haughey's eyes drifted skyward.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to briefly regard the imposing chandeliers that hang
from the ceiling at Georges Hall where the tribunal investigating
widespread corruption in Ireland is sitting, and one could not help
thinking those chandeliers and the chiaroscuro paintings that adorn
the green walls were the very sort of things that Charlie Haughey
once had handed to him by wealthy businessmen currying his favor.
</P>
<P>
   Watching him on the witness stand, it was striking to note the
parallels between Haughey, the most charismatic, controversial
Irish politician of the 20th century, and James Michael Curley, the
most charismatic, controversial Irish-American politician of the
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Curley, the son of Irish immigrants, was elected governor of
Massachusetts once and mayor of Boston four times, the last time
while he was under indictment on corruption charges. He served a
term in Congress, and a term in prison for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey served three terms as Ireland's prime minister, or
taoiseach, during the 1980s and 1990s, despite having been indicted
on, and controversially acquitted of, charges that he ran guns to
the IRA in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey was, like Curley, a rogue, a man who used his public
position for private gain. But, like Irish-Americans, the native
Irish love a rogue, especially when he's one of their own. Curley's
cheeky, subversive campaign slogan, ``Vote often and early for
Curley,'' played on that sympathy for rogues. It also sounded like
something that could have been dreamed up in the members bar at
Leinster House, home to the Dail, Ireland's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Curley grew up poor but studied well. He was smart, erudite, and
one of the greatest orators in American politics. Still, the best
thing you can say about a Boston pol is that he never forgot where
he came from, and Curley never forgot where he came from. His
compassion for the poor was genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Curley first got into trouble in public life when he got caught
impersonating an Irish immigrant at a civil service examination.
The Protestant Brahmin establishment was horrified by Curley's
audacity. But to the first- and second-generation immigrants living
in the tenements of South Boston, Charlestown and Roxbury, where
Curley grew up, his fraud was an act of compassion, the work of a
politician who cared deeply about the plight of those struggling to
get a foothold in the New World.
</P>
<P>
   Having been born into poverty, Curley never lost his empathy for
the poor. As mayor, he built Boston City Hospital, vowing that no
one would be denied medical care, regardless of their ability to
pay. That Curley shamelessly extorted money from the
Brahmin-controlled banks and property developers to underwrite his
philanthropy never seemed to bother most Bostonians. Nor did the
fact that Curley, like Haughey, enriched himself in the process. If
anything, Curley's storied shakedowns of bankers and developers
enhanced his reputation among the immigrants who by the 1930s had
assimilated and formed the biggest voting bloc in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When, 60 years apart, Curley's and Haughey's coat holders found
their heroes facing charges of corruption, they defended them by
noting how much each had done for the poor and elderly. Along with
their defenders, both Curley and Haughey seemed to share a healthy
sense of entitlement, believing that their help of the poor and
their positions of enormous responsibility somehow excused their
acceptance of enormous sums of money from rich businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Both Haughey and Curley exploited the inherent bias against rich
people in their own constituencies. Some years ago, when I told my
mother that there was overwhelming evidence that Curley had used
his position to extort millions of dollars from banks and property
developers, her response was telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good for James Michael Curley,'' said my mother, the daughter
of immigrants from Galway. ``What did the banks ever do for the
poor people?''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in Dublin, I heard variations of the same theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your man Charlie's all right,'' a man in O'Reilly's pub in
Sandymount told me. ``Sure, they were all stealing. He's no worse
than the rest of them.''
</P>
<P>
   As Fintan O'Toole recently pointed out in The Irish Times,
Haughey was the product of a Fianna Fail party whose members relish
their revolutionary past, who see themselves as rebels even though
they have, more than any other party, run the Republic of Ireland
since 26 of Ireland's 32 counties won independence from Britain in
1922. It is a delusion, rooted deeply in folk myth.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Curley was portraying the Boston Irish as exploited
victims of the Protestant Brahmin establishment long after the
Irish had pushed the Yankees aside to assume political control of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   It is true the Irish were treated shabbily when they first
arrived in Boston in large numbers, after the potato blight in
Ireland that began in 1845. But the Irish worked hard, and through
sheer numbers and political savvy were able to make Boston their
own. Hugh O'Brien and Patrick Collins, the first immigrants to
break the Brahmin hold on City Hall, and the only Irish-born mayors
of Boston, were conciliatory toward their former oppressors,
seeking a partnership that would mutually benefit the Yankee
establishment and the mostly poor but industrious immigrant
community.
</P>
<P>
   But, by the 1930s, when Curley had become the most charismatic
and powerful mayor the city had ever seen, he continued to appeal
to the worst instincts of the Irish, playing them off against other
ethnic groups and telling them that only his continued hold on the
reins of power would ensure that they got their fair share from the
Brahmins.
</P>
<P>
   Second- and third-generation immigrants, especially the Irish,
kept Curley in power, even while the establishment railed that he
was corrupt. He played their vulnerability, their fondness for
rogues, like a virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey did the same in Ireland, winking and nodding and getting
rich while presiding over a country that in the 1980s was among the
poorest in Europe, with an unemployment rate of 20 percent. While
the Irish were putting their children on boats and planes so they
could find work in London, Boston, New York, and just about every
major city in the world, Haughey was lining his $200 million
mansion on 300 acres north of Dublin with priceless works of art,
much of it handed to him by businessmen whom he claims sought no
favors.
</P>
<P>
   Like Haughey, Curley loved the finer things in life: good food,
fine art, exotic travel. And like Curley, who was forever telling
people of his spartan lifestyle, Haughey didn't seem to think his
lifestyle was extravagant at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a lavish lifestyle,'' Haughey told a lawyer for
the tribunal. ``My work was my lifestyle and when I was in office I
worked every day, all day. There was no room for any sort of an
extravagant lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Curley justified his luxury ocean cruises and trips to Europe
with similar sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if all politics is local, all corruption is relative.
Like Curley, Haughey did good, too. Haughey was a creative finance
minister between 1966-70, introducing free travel, cheap fuel, and
free electricity for the elderly and tax breaks for artists.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Haughey did many good things for Ireland,
just as there is no doubt that Curley helped many Bostonians. But
both men were swamped by a change of tide in public opinion. By the
1950s, as Americans became more educated and affluent than ever,
petty corruption by public officials became widely frowned upon. In
his ``Last Hurrah'' campaign for a fifth term as Boston mayor,
Curley was defeated at the polls by John B. Hynes in a
138,000-126,000 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government put him in jail and he came out a broke
and broken man. He died virtually penniless, though his wake was an
impressive tribute. Bob Lawler, the Boston undertaker who became
Curley's surrogate son after his own father died when he was 11,
remembers how thousands of people lined up to view Curley's body at
the Statehouse rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had tears in their eyes,'' Lawler recalled. ``They were
saying, `We love you Jim.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Curley had nine children. All but one of them died young, before
he did. He had no grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful that Haughey's demise will be as sad as Curley's.
But just as Bostonians tired of their politicians lining their
pockets, so, too, does it seem the Irish people have said enough is
enough, that the days of furtive exchanges of cash in parking lots
is over.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if Haughey will follow Curley's footsteps
into prison. Curley emerged from prison unrepentant, and went on to
write his autobiography, which he called, ``I'd Do It Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Haughey may not go to jail, but if he ever writes his
autobiography, he'd be hard-pressed to come up with a better title.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kevin Cullen, The Boston Globe London Bureau chief and European
correspondent, was the Globe's Dublin bureau chief in 1997 and
1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
