<HEADER>
A1014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-GREEN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     09-05 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GREEN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 SYDNEY: ... as an example.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are four worm farms, including two at the main press
center and one at the Novotel Hotel at Homebush Bay, a javelin
throw from the Olympic Stadium. Their combined effect on waste
reduction, when compared to the 10,000 tons of waste anticipated at
the Olympic venues, will be something like removing a fraction of a
grain of salt from a super-sized Big Mac meal.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials, however, say the worms are only a tiny part
of the effort, despite their appeal to journalists looking for a
story. Organizers say they hope to recycle or compost fully 80
percent of the waste generated at the Games using more traditional
means.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite its general praise for the work at Homebush Bay,
Greenpeace Australia last month gave Games organizers an overall
grade of ``C'' for environmental performance _ one activist called
it a ``bronze medal.'' The grade was based on goals Olympic
organizers had set for themselves with Greenpeace's participation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace grades for individual elements of the Olympic effort
ranged from an A-plus for the athletes' village to Fs for
abandoning plans for a solar power station, and placing a
volleyball stadium in the middle of Sydney's Bondi Beach, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they've crossed the line in terms of delivering
Green Games, but they haven't delivered on everything they promised
to the world,'' said Posner, the Greenpeace official.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace's biggest complaint was aimed at the presence of air
conditioning and refrigeration units that contain chemicals that
deplete the ozone layer and contribute to the buildup of greenhouse
gases. ``That's a real disappointment,'' Posner said. ``None of the
air conditioning on site will comply with their own guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Bland, the Olympic environmental spokesman, acknowledged that
was ``the biggest downfall in terms of construction and
development.'' But he said the blame should be shifted onto
Australia's air conditioning and refrigeration industry, which he
said failed to make cleaner equipment available.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, officials of Olympic sponsor Coca-Cola _ the
largest user of refrigeration units at the site _ promised to phase
out greenhouse gases called HFCs in all its new cold drink
equipment in time for the Athens Olympic Games in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace also faulted organizers for failing to move more
quickly to clean up what it described as ``hundreds of tons'' of
dioxin still contaminating the land and mud around Homebush Bay. In
1997, Greenpeace discovered 69 barrels of highly toxic materials
abandoned on a peninsula adjacent to Homebush Bay, and Greenpeace
officials said they remain there, untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Bland said cleanup work has been planned, and the government of
New South Wales, the Australian state where Sydney is located, has
committed $14 million for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Bland said Greenpeace ``has a legitimate position because they
were there at the beginning of the process and now they're there at
the end.'' However, he dismissed the group's overall conclusions as
``a bit of a whinge,'' an Australian term for whine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fairly cheap publicity ploy,'' Bland said. ``At the
end of this process, I think it's pretty clear we've set a new
benchmark, not just for the Olympics, but for any major new
development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
