<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-05 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT PERSONAL? BELICHICK COOLING HIS JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Football, lies, and videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Brace yourself for the very best of them.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a short week of what went wrong in the Tampa Bay game
and a long week of Bill Belichick's return to the Meadowlands to
face the team he scorned last January to take the head job in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a softball for Dennis Miller, the ``Monday Night
Football'' comedian, who will have lots of ammunition for next
week's Jets-Patriots game, starting with the ugly divorce between
Belichick and Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Included are two chapters of Parcells's new book, ``The Final
Season,'' in which he depicts Belichick in a bad light after
Parcells handed him the torch as the Jets' next head coach, only to
have Belichick reject it in a bizarre final press conference in
which he resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Miller will have fodder in Belichick and his relationship with
Jets players, plus Belichick and New York coach Al Groh, who worked
together for years, and the Jets' brokering of a deal to free
Belichick for a No. 1 draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   There's also ``The Video'' acquired by the Lawrence Eagle
Tribune's Bill Burt, which shows a disoriented Parcells in the late
moments of last year's season-opening loss to the Patriots. The
tape shows Parcells, now the Jets' director of player personnel,
apparently unaware of the score and questioning why the Patriots
were trying to set up for a field goal. The Patriots were trailing
by a point, but Parcells apparently thought they were up a point.
It may all be moot by now, but the video has received much
attention in the media, including Channel 7's ``Sports Xtra,''
which showed it Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Just another game?
</P>
<P>
   Not when Parcells writes in his book, ``In retrospect, I think
something happened with Belichick or with his agent on Monday
afternoon that made Belichick reconsider his position with Jets (on
Tuesday). I can't prove it, and I really don't care now that he has
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   On Belichick's performance at the press conference, Parcells
wrote, ``He was just too emotional to handle the situation. And he
said some things about me that weren't true. He also said some
things that were said in private conversations between coaches,
which coaches know are not to be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Parcells writes, ``His excuse about things changing with
the death of Mr. (Leon) Hess was weak. Mr. Hess had been dead for
seven months. The potential buyers of the Jets were all told by
Goldman Sachs that Belichick, by contract, would automatically be
the next coach as soon as I stepped down.''
</P>
<P>
   And this baby: ``Bill did a good job for me. But I did a good
job for him. Honestly, I still can't figure out why he didn't take
this job instead of going to New England. If the Patriots never
came forward, I think he would have been happy to be the head coach
of the New York Jets.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the book, which hit stores this weekend,
Belichick took the high road, as he did when asked about the
videotape, which he appears on.
</P>
<P>
   While answering questions about his sorry offensive line Monday,
Belichick also began to get Jets questions from the New York media.
</P>
<P>
   One reporter asked whether there will be extra emotions about
facing the Jets for the first time. Belichick's official response
was, ``No. That's really not the issue. The main issue for me is
that it's a divisional game. Every team needs to win its division
games. It's a division game on the road, and that's what's really
important. They're not going to have everyone's personal record in
the standings on Monday; it's going to be what the Patriots are,
and that's why we're here. It's about what this football team does
collectively. It's not about individuals. It's not about my record
and your record and somebody else's record.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that Tampa Bay wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson, the
former Jet, said he would be rooting for Belichick Monday, the
coach quipped, ``If that translates into points on the board, I'll
take them. I doubt that it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said, ``It's not like you're out on the field playing.
You're just trying to get your team prepared to play. I feel I put
as much into this Tampa Bay game as I'll do the New York game and
the Minnesota game.''
</P>
<P>
   He did say that, because of the familiarity between the teams,
``It'll be like an intrasquad scrimmage. Each side can probably
call every play. There are a lot of storylines.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots defensive back Otis Smith, another former Jet, also
joined the parade of ``it's just another game'' commentary. ``Our
sole purpose is to go down in New York and try to win,'' said
Smith. ``Hopefully, we will get that done. It's no bigger than any
other game. I played there. I know what the guys are like over
there, and they know what I'm like. It's like the first time I left
there and came here to play and went back. It's the same feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``As players, we don't know what's going on with coaches and the
front office. That stuff is out of our control. To link me with
what's going with Bill and the Jets I don't think is the right
thing to do. That situation is done with. We're here now and we're
trying to win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ty Law, who loves Monday night football anyway,
expects a highly emotional night, especially with old friends like
Curtis Martin and Vincent Brisby on the other sideline. ``That's
going to be a fun game,'' said Law. ``Curtis is over there, and
he's a guy we have to stop to stop the Jets' offense. And Briz,
he's going to pick up where he left off a couple of years ago here.
He's a good receiver. He had those hamstring problems, and a
receiver can't be expected to go out there and run around with
those. He was a great asset for our team. He opened things up for
other guys. I think he can go over there and fill Keyshawn's shoes
and they probably won't miss a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said he does believe Belichick will have a personal agenda
in this one. ``He has total control of this team,'' said Law,
``which he wouldn't have had up there. So I think he's going to
have a little personal side to this.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Law added, ``You can't pick that up because it's not
talked about. As the week goes on, you'll get the sense of it if
it's going to be personal or not. He has a good way of keeping the
same tone of voice, so it will be hard to pick it up with him. All
you have to do is go talk to (offensive coordinator) Charlie
(Weis). He'd probably let it all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Weis, of course, was the coordinator in New York who was
stripped of his play-calling duties by Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick brought other personnel with him to New England,
including defensive backs coach Eric Mangini, assistant personnel
director Scott Pioli (Parcells's son-in-law), and national scout
Lionel Vital. Former Patriots defensive line coach Ray Hamilton is
the Jets' line coach.
</P>
<P>
   What the story is missing is Keyshawn firing the first shot.
Someone will have to do that between now and Monday. Rest assured,
it won't be Belichick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
