<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TALK0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `529' plans popular for college
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Suppose you could stash away money for your kids'
college years, invest it and skip paying taxes on your earnings for
years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that opportunity has been available for several years.
It comes in several dozen state-sponsored college savings plans
that offer savings not just on income tax, but also on estate and
gift taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Now the plans _ named 529 plans after the section of tax law
that authorizes them _ are catching on.
</P>
<P>
   What made the difference? The answer is classic capitalism: More
salesmen will sell more stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first were Fidelity _ pushing a plan sponsored by New
Hampshire but available all over the United States _ and TIAA-CREF
in Connecticut and New York. Now Merrill Lynch, Salomon Smith
Barney, Vanguard and others have joined the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have stashed $1.7 billion into 529 plans, and the
numbers are growing. Assets in Fidelity's New Hampshire plan
tripled in one year. Maine, a partner with Merrill Lynch, picked up
$264 million in its first year.
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons for the accelerating growth.
</P>
<P>
   It's a no-brainer. Once you pick your plan, all you do is write
a check and leave the investment management to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia and South Dakota are the only states that do not offer a
529. But at least 21 other states will open accounts for residents
of Georgia or any other state.
</P>
<P>
   Tax benefits are the most attractive advantage, says certified
financial planner Kyle H. Flynn. Your earnings grow tax-free until
you withdraw money to pay college expenses. Then the money is taxed
at the student's tax rate, presumably lower than his or her
parents' rate.
</P>
<P>
   You can put a lot of money into a 529 account. The limit for any
one child is over $100,000 in most states.
</P>
<P>
   You might try to top that by opening accounts in more than one
state. ``But I think the IRS is going to try to prevent that,''
said Joseph F. Hurley, author of a book on 529 plans and founder of
www.savingforcollege.com. ``You're asking for trouble, because
you're abusing the program.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no income caps. Other tax incentives are phased out
for high-income taxpayers but not 529 plans.
</P>
<P>
   The donor keeps control of the money. ``If Johnny doesn't go to
college, it's not Johnny's money,'' said Abram Claude, Fidelity's
vice president for college planning. ``You can change
beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom and Dad also have the power to decide when to make
withdrawals. They can even take the money back, though they would
pay both income taxes and a penalty on earnings, usually 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Grandparents can rejoice: Contributions to a 529 plan are
removed from the donor's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions qualify for the $10,000 annual gift exclusion.
What's more, a donor can contribute as much as $50,000 into an
account at one time and spread the tax benefit over five years.
</P>
<P>
   There are drawbacks, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not able to control the investments,'' said Flynn, a
member of the Financial Planning Association. ``You need to be
comfortable with how the sponsor invests the money for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, you lose the income tax benefit if the money doesn't go
for college expenses. In general that includes tuition, fees, books
and room and board. If college plans collapse, you can leave the
money in the account indefinitely, transfer it to another family
member or withdraw it and pay a penalty on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The complex part is shopping for the plan that best meets your
needs.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is the place to start. Hurley's
www.savingforcollege.com offers details on every plan and links to
related Web sites. Click on ``5-Cap Ratings'' to get started.
</P>
<P>
   You will want to know who manages the money in the accounts. If
you are already comfortable with managers at Fidelity or TIAA-CREF,
for example, that will help narrow your list.
</P>
<P>
   Asset allocations are important, too. In most plans, your money
will be split between stock and bond mutual funds, and the portion
in bonds will increase as your child approaches college age.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative investors can check out the Iowa plan, which starts
children under 5 in the Vanguard LifeStrategy Growth Portfolio. It
keeps 57 percent of assets in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Maine is more adventurous. One option is an age-based portfolio,
which starts very young children with 90 percent stocks and 10
percent bonds. Other options include a 100 percent equity portfolio
and one that is 75 percent equities. You can mix and match, but
once you make a contribution to a particular portfolio, that money
has to stay in that portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Expenses are an important consideration. The more you pay for
management, the less you get to reinvest. The difference can be
significant, especially if you start when your children are very
young.
</P>
<P>
   Utah uses low-cost Vanguard funds, and its expenses are capped
at $25 plus 0.35 percent of assets.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, Merrill Lynch's plan costs 1.36% to 1.58%, according
to www
</P>
<P>
   .savingforcollege.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
