<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1039 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0906-CO     09-05 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breaking even in the game of life
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. ``Life's a crapshoot. Ya' lose a little of
this and you gain a little of that. The best ya' can hope for is to
break even.'' This from the wiseguy peering over my shoulder as I'm
weighing myself on the old penny scales
</P>
<P>
   in the pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez!'' I mutter, looking only half-way back at him. ``Gimme a
break here. Can't a girl even weigh herself in private any more?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This here ain't private, Lizzie,'' the voice says and adds
with a chuckle, ``and you ain't no girl.'' I swivel for a better
look at my tormentor and discover it's just one of my smart-mouth
coffee buddies. I fish in my pocket for a coin, hold it out, and
dare him to take my place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' he says by way of refusal. ``I only weigh nekkid.'' I
tell him to go ahead and he says he would but worries that the
excitement of catching a glimpse of him in his altogether might be
just too much for the lady behind the
</P>
<P>
   counter. I agree with him, but not for the reason he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Then I try to make a deal, suggesting we could each subtract 15
pounds for clothes and shoes. He turns me down and shuffles off to
the prescription counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get your Viagra over the Internet, you know,'' I shout
after him in an effort to get even. He just shakes his head and
keeps on going.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking it must be time to buy my own scales so I can weigh
at home _ stripped, before breakfast, and with a modicum of privacy
to avoid situations like this. The kind with really big numbers
would be ideal so that way I won't have to subtract five or six
pounds for my glasses _ depending on whether I'm wearing the new
lightweights or my old horn-rims.
</P>
<P>
   But my geezer friend has set me to thinking about losses and
gains, and wondering if in the long run, life really does break
even. One can only hope.
</P>
<P>
   It's a definite loss when the eyesight dims. The flip side is,
we begin to look better to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, we lose speed, but we gain awareness _ kind of a
``stopping to smell the flowers'' thing.
</P>
<P>
   And so what if a little bit of the memory goes? Do as one of my
friends suggests _ invent a new reality, one that makes you happy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest benefits of joining the ``slightly over the
hill bunch'' is the serenity that comes with the realization that,
unlike what our mothers taught us, it really doesn't matter what
other folks think. If we choose to
</P>
<P>
   stop in the middle of digging up lilies or spading in manure, to
walk uptown for a bite of lunch, who cares if we look a fright?
It's not going to affect our standing in the community one bit.
Besides, by this age we know who we are
</P>
<P>
   and that conformity counts for nothing. Can't please everybody
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   My geezer buddy is right. Life really is a crapshoot, and since
we have no idea where it's going to dump us from one day to the
next, the best we can hope for is a journey smoothed by family and
friends who love us _ AND a sense of
</P>
<P>
   humor to help us enjoy the gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
