<P>
   QUAKE-WINERIES (Napa, Calif.) _ The 5.2 earthquake last weekend
couldn't have shaken Northern California's famed Wine Country at a
more hectic, vulnerable time. Crowded with Labor Day tourists and
migrant farm workers, its restaurants and spas booked and
fermenting tanks filling up with the spoils of harvest, the
wine-saturated Napa Valley landscape was ripe for chaos. By JENNY
STRASBURG and ANASTASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   SUVS-POLLUTION (San Francisco) _ The Sierra Club is launching a
nationwide campaign to showcase what it sees as the dark side of
SUVs _ the brown haze of air pollution, weather disasters linked to
global warming, and oil derricks chugging away to fill gas tanks.
In a snappy six-page brochure released Sunday, the 108-year-old
national environmental group is depicting gas-guzzling,
carbon-dioxide-spewing SUVs as hazardous, not hip. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   KILLER-OTTER (Moss Landing, Calif.) _ The placid waters of
Elkhorn Slough are host to the things that make Monterey Bay a
natural treasure: gliding pelicans, twittering sandpipers, lounging
sea lions and frolicking harbor seals. But all is not well here: a
serial killer may be at work. The suspect: an adolescent male sea
otter. By VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   SF-ASIAN-CENSUS (San Francisco) _ Sometime this year, according
to trends projected in a survey by the U.S. Census Bureau, San
Francisco will join Honolulu as the nation's only major cities
where Asians outnumber whites. By ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STUDIO-APARTMENTS (Undated) _ A studio apartment can be a gem if
you put a little thought and creativity into it. With a bit of
ingenuity, you can make living areas from seemingly nonexistent
space. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   COACH-HORN (Undated) _ The melodic coach horn was the precursor
of the modern, blasting car horn. Road coaches served as public
transportation and for delivering supplies and mail. Each of the
authentic calls, still used by pleasure coaches, carries a message:
we have arrived, we're thirsty, we need lodging, get ready and
let's go. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-DEATH (Undated) _ How do we about dying? Investigative
reporter Bill Moyers and his wife, Judith Davidson Moyers, spent
the past two years in hospitals, hospices and most importantly the
homes of terminally ill people. Their efforts resulted in a
four-part, six-hour documentary for PBS that examines, as one dying
subject puts it, ``living in the light of death.'' By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY-BIOGRAPHY (Undated) _ Cornelius ``Sonny'' Vanderbilt
Whitney was born with a silver spoon in his mouth and grew up to be
one of the world's wealthiest tycoons and the stuff legends are
made of. Jeffrey L. Rodengen's new biography, ``The Legend of
Cornelius Vanderbilt Whitney,'' provides an in-depth journey into
the privileged life of a gentleman. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MORMON-WRITER (New York) _ Despite the gallery of rogues
who lie and cheat in his films, Neil LaBute had escaped the
attention of his Mormon Church elders for a long time. Then LaBute
got personal. He introduced Mormon characters. Homicidal Mormon
characters. In ``Bash: Latter-Day Plays,'' a filmed version of
which aired on Showtime last week, pretty people of the faith
confess ugly crimes. That made the phone ring. It was the church
asking LaBute to portray Mormons in a positive way. By RON DICKER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' CATEGORY)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For people who can never catch
a big fish, a new grow-your-own phenomenon is creating a shock
among fishermen across America _ starting with a world-record
5-pound bluegill grown and caught in a private pond. This
world-record bluegill is 15 inches long, 12 inches tall and 3 1/2
inches thick, and according to the fellow who grew it in his pond,
there's plenty more where that one came from. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Last week I celebrated my 15th
anniversary at The San Francisco Examiner. Well, ``celebrated'' is
the wrong word, for obvious reasons. There won't be any 16th
anniversary at The Examiner. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Think your personal papers are
safe in the bank? Think again. In June, when Mrs. O'G learned that
her cancer had returned and metastasized, she figured she might not
have a whole lot of time to get her affairs in order. One big item
of business: A 30-year-old safe deposit box that rested in a branch
of Bank of America a few blocks from Mrs. O'G's home. She was
surprised to learn that the bank had sent the contents to the state
Controller's Office as ``unclaimed property'' in 1997. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD-OLD-BOY (San Francisco) _ Bill Clinton, our first Bubba
president, is commonly known in the South as a Good Ol' Boy, which
actually means a bad boy, or at least a naughty one, a fact made
clear during his effective but morally tarnished administration.
The problem with Al Gore is that too many people think that he is
cut from Clintonian cloth. He's not. Al Gore is not a Good Ol' Boy,
and try as he might, he never will be. He is, instead, a Good Boy.
By JAN MILLSAPPS.
</P>
