<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-GIRL-LIFEBEAT-ART-650-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLIE KATE EISENBERG: PRINCESS OF POP
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 (ART ADV: Photo of Hallie Kate Eisenberg is available on Newscom or
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By JESSICA BROWN 
 c.2000 Child magazine. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At age 8, Hallie Kate Eisenberg has a career that would make
most actresses jealous: She worked with Al Pacino and Russell Crowe
in last year's Oscar-nominated ``The Insider'' and plays Minnie
Driver's daughter in ``Beautiful.'' Then there are the Pepsi ads
that catapulted her to fame, in which she channels the voices of
such legends as Aretha Franklin and Marlon Brando. Not bad for
someone too young to stay up for her six guest spots on ``The
Tonight Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her high profile, Hallie seems like a typical kid. She
arrives after a full day as a second-grader at her New Jersey
hometown's public school, chatting about the usual little-girl
loves: dancing (she's taken tap, ballet and jazz classes), glitter
nail polish, in-line skating and her three pets (a dog, a cat and a
bird). It isn't until she mentions that it was Hollywood hunk
Russell Crowe who bought her the skates that you remember she
really isn't your typical 8-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   So how does her family cope with Hallie's sudden fame?
Surprisingly, her mom, Amy, reports that the Eisenberg household
isn't as crazed as you'd think. ``We all view this as a lot of
fun,'' she says. In fact, the lifestyle isn't so new to them, since
the family is chock-full of performers: Son Jesse, 16, has acted on
TV and on stage, and Amy herself worked as a clown for 15 years.
Only Hallie's father, Barry, a healthcare consultant, stays behind
the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Hallie had her first brush with fame when she was only a day
old. ``I gave birth to Hallie during National Breastfeeding Month,
and the hospital put her on the cover of their newsletter, wearing
a bib that said 'I Eat at Mom's,''' remembers Amy. But it was at
age 3, during a meeting with Jesse's agents, that Hallie got
noticed. ``The agents asked if they could send her out on
auditions, too,'' Amy recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Hallie's first gig was a ``Blue's Clues'' commercial, in which
she was supposed to react enthusiastically as she watched the show
with a group of kids. ``But I had never seen it before. Everyone
else was yelling out the clues, and I just sat there like this,''
Hallie explains, demonstrating a transfixed stare.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, much larger and more successful jobs followed,
namely, the Pepsi ads. But Hallie almost missed her chance to be
Hollywood's soda songstress. Though her agents assured Pepsi that
they had the perfect girl for the part, the Eisenbergs were out of
the country for most of the audition period.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we finally got an appointment for her to try out in New
York City, we were given the wrong address. We ended up stuck in
rush-hour traffic, desperately trying to get across town to make
the meeting,'' Amy says. But in the end, there was no need to worry
_ on their way home from the audition, Amy got a call on her cell
phone from Pepsi, telling her that Hallie had gotten the part.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her glamorous job, Hallie appears unaffected. ``It's not
like we have to work at maintaining our values,'' says Amy. ``She's
not spoiled at all. She makes her bed, sets the table and cleans up
her messes. Acting is just fun to her.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an attitude Amy wants her to keep. ``I see kids at
auditions who simply aren't into it, and I wonder why they're
there. But Hallie has shot scenes in the pouring rain and been the
happiest person on the set.'' Amy is also very conscious of
protecting her daughter from any pressure. ``At one point, she had
just filmed 'The Insider' and a TV movie at the same time, and I
said to her, 'You know, after this maybe you'll just go back to
first grade and be a regular girl.' But Hallie burst into tears,
asking 'What did I do?' I wanted to give her an out,'' Amy says.
``But she didn't want it. She loves having a lot to do. You could
wake her up in the middle of the night and she would still be ready
for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
