<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! ``Psycho Beach Party'' Norman Bates meets Gidget in this
cleverly cheesy send-up of surfer and slasher drive-in movies.
Charles Busch, who wrote the play on which it's based, plays a very
butch cop and Lauren Ambrose is a tomboy with multiple
personalities, as indeed the film has in its fun and games with
oceanside mayhem. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) !!! 1/2 ``The Tic Code'' In its soft, muted, heartfelt way,
this film about a single mom, her young son with Tourette Syndrome,
and a sympathetic saxophonist is the antithesis of Hollywood gloss.
Polly Draper, who wrote the screenplay based on the experiences of
her jazz musician husband, is a standout. So are Christopher George
Marquette as her unhappy prodigy son and Gregory Hines as the
musician. New York's jazz world is portrayed with an insider's
authority, too. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Titanic Town'' The Troubles, circa 1972, in West Belfast,
rendered with jolting immediacy and riding the fiery performance of
Julie Walters as a wife and mother of four. Radicalized into peace
activism by a determination to see her children survive into
adulthood, she doesn't care that Catholic and Protestant factions
each see her as the other side's pawn. (Unrated) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
