<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1360 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-NOWHERE-BOS &LR;      09-05 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOWHERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID LOVE AND LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
NOWHERE ELSE ON EARTH 
By Josephine Humphreys. Viking. 341 pp. $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Josephine Humphreys is a shrewd Southern writer whose fiction
has long embraced the contradictions of the region. She knows that
evil can take up residence on the most ordinary street corner, that
humor can conceal and sometimes appease a world of pain. As a
native South Carolinian, she understands the land's allure and
treachery both: understands that, to a Southerner, the strands of
place and love and obligation can get as tangled as kudzu.
Humphreys's earlier novels _ ``Dreams of Sleep,'' ``Rich in Love,''
``The Fireman's Fair'' _ relied on emotional insight and depth of
character to explore these themes, drawing their rich sense of
story from a New South steeped in old and intractable ways.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Nowhere Else on Earth,'' she has eschewed this contemporary
palette for a historical novel set in North Carolina during the
final months of the Civil War. Certainly all the makings for high
drama are in place here in Scuffletown, on the banks of the Lumbee
River: violence, betrayal, familial ties assaulted by hunger and
heartbreak as well as slavery and war. But Humphreys has focused
her sights upon a particular segment of the rural, war-weary South:
the insular settlement of Lumbee Indians in Scuffletown, under
siege by a roving home guard that is intent on saving its own white
sons by drafting Indian boys first. The resulting saga has both the
familiar ring of old Civil War themes (broken homes and loyalties,
huge losses and unlikely heroics) as well as the more remarkable
story of a community ostracized from within. As with other recent
Civil War efforts by contemporary writers (Charles Frazier's ``Cold
Mountain,'' Russell Banks's ``Cloudsplitter''), ``Nowhere Else on
Earth'' seeks to deliver individual agonies on a war-torn stage _ a
character study wrung out from history's bloody garb.
</P>
<P>
   The novel opens as a retrospective memoir, written in 1890 by a
41-year-old woman named Rhoda Strong. The only daughter of a Lumbee
Indian mother and a Scot father, Rhoda is 15 in the last year of
the war, subsisting on potatoes and cornmeal and day-dreaming about
a better life. Her quick mind nurtured by a doting father, Rhoda
has left home once, to be tutored by a white woman, but the girl's
love for her family and strong ties to Scuffletown brought her
back. The town is more fishnet or cobweb than real town, Rhoda
tells us: ``two hundred houses spread through miles of swampy
woods, threaded together by footpaths and narrow oxcart lanes of
sand.'' Most of its residents make their living from pine resin:
Robeson County is home to 80 turpentine stilleries, worked by
slaves and Lumbees and, more often than not, owned by whites.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the South by that point in the war, the folks in
Scuffletown are simply trying to outlive the Union's final victory:
``What we wanted,'' Rhoda tells us, ``was the life before us. To do
the work, to fall in love, survive the sorrows, stay put.'' An even
greater threat than Sherman at this point is an evil man named
Brant Harris, whose home guard has turned from a ragtag local army
into a marauding gang with personal vendettas. The Strongs spend
too many days hiding from Harris in their one-room house,
protecting Rhoda's brothers, Boss and Andrew, but their best hope
lies in Scuffletown's prodigal son. At 19, Henry Berry Lowrie is
already a young legend, feeding the hungry and outrunning the enemy
and hiding the good town boys in the woods. His brothers have made
him the leader of the band who can stand up to Harris; even Rhoda's
mother, Cee, wary of all that charisma, knows that the community's
future is riding on him.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda loves the legend even before she's laid eyes on the man,
of course, and Henry, when he appears, takes to this outspoken girl
who wants to shield her brother from harm. And so the love story
between Rhoda and Henry unfolds with an elusive if predictable
persistence, enough to provide the obligatory romantic thread in a
story rife with blood and doom. But it's the dark transformation of
its characters that offers the real ballast of the novel: Henry's
moral tests, too often bigger than he is; Rhoda's surrender of
desire, or transient happiness, for the greater potential of a
long-term investment. There are piercing subplots that sustain this
ominous milieu, from the martyrdom of the retarded brother of one
of Harris's henchmen to Rhoda's creepily poignant tending of a
dying Yankee soldier. The fates of the innocent are what we fear
most: Playing Little John to Henry's Robin Hood, Boss Strong is so
young and serious you know he'll have to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere Else on Earth'' feels young and serious, too. It's
meticulously researched, and Humphreys's narrative attention to
specific scenes (usually the horrific ones) can be riveting. But
too often this novel seems less than the sum of its considerable
(and desultory) parts. In constructing a story possessing some of
the great themes of all wars, and this war in particular, Humphreys
has sacrificed many of the finer elements of resonant fiction. We
care far more for a character's interior struggles than, say, the
racist specifics of 19th-century anthropology, but the characters
in ``Nowhere Else on Earth'' don't have much room to thrive or
develop _ they're up against too much history. In the face of so
much backdrop _ the rumble of Sherman's march, the internecine
violence of Scuffletown, the familiar losses endured by an entire
society _ it's hard to focus on anything much beyond the
well-traveled territory of Civil War fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Writers turn to history for a variety of reasons; they may be
drawn to a moment in time, or they may simply want to flee the one
they're in. A rash of Civil War novels in the past five years
suggests to me the latter. In this present-tense world of so much
ironic distance, careless ennui, and blurry, untraceable sorrow,
maybe the Civil War _ with all its well-delineated horrors and
classical tragedy _ looks pretty good. But the genre can't help
doing the same thing historical fiction has always done: provide a
setting of so much unarguable fact that it precludes any real
creative flight. And instead of imaginative possibility, what you
get is paint-by-numbers fiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
