<HEADER>
A1363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-DELAYING-BOS &LR;      09-05 1586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-DELAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE STUDENTS DETOUR FROM TRADITIONAL PATH TO COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMONT, Mass. _ The night he made the big decision, Mike Crotty
drove alone through the streets of his hometown, hoping that the
familiar geography of his life would inspire him.
</P>
<P>
   His dream, a basketball scholarship, had come true. St.
Michael's College had offered $100,000 in tuition and fees, and the
chance to play for the same school that his childhood idol had
attended, a fellow point guard who had helped Crotty become Belmont
High's shooting star.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chance, too, that his parents never had. A young man
who grew up in public housing developments, Crotty would be
fulfilling their dreams as well.
</P>
<P>
   But he was torn. After taking the SAT over and over, until he
had a 1200, hadn't he earned a spot at a top college? St. Michael's
was a safe bet. But his education was so crucial, he kept thinking,
that the stakes seemed worth raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``A true point guard is someone who gets the best shot,'' he
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   His parents were up when he came in that night in the spring of
1999. I've decided, he said. He would risk the scholarship, even if
it meant going into debt, and wait for his best shot.
</P>
<P>
   With a record 15.1 million Americans enrolling on campuses this
fall, Crotty's story stands out among the many that admissions
officers hear. He said no to St. Michael's and spent the last year
shoring up his academic and athletic records in an unusual way.
This week, he's heading to college, hoping his choice will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, more families are wrestling with where to send their
children, how to pay, and what kind of education is right for them.
Specialists say the strong economy and increasingly abundant
options after high school are encouraging students to work,
volunteer, or study in nontraditional settings, before beginning
the college experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say that there's a traditional course of study or
one clear path to college anymore,'' said Mark Cannon, deputy
executive director of the National Association for College
Admission Counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Crotty's decision to reject a scholarship was unusual, as he is
a ``first generation'' student _ one whose parents didn't go to
college. Some educators see these freshmen at some risk, since
parents who went to college may be more equipped to show their
children the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Crotty wagered his scholarship on the hope of
something greater _ an unusual choice for a young man who dreams of
playing professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big thing, my education. And I had to think about
the next 10 years more than the next four,'' Crotty said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Crottys, it was a long journey _ not only over the last
year, as they waited to see if a thick acceptance letter from an
elite school would arrive, but for the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had any money, and we're never going to have any
money,'' said Michael Crotty, Mike's father, sitting in a living
room filled with high-school pictures of Mike and his older sister,
Tarsha. ``The only thing important to us is to make sure the kids
get their education.''
</P>
<P>
   Crotty grew up dunking baskets in a mini-hoop set that he would
break, and his father would fix, again and again. He was a little
guy in a tall man's sport. And if he didn't have flash, there was a
scrappy style that began to gel in pickup games with other children
in his old subsidized housing complex. Playing for his dad's youth
basketball team pushed him as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we wouldn't dive on the floor for the ball, my dad
would say, `What is this, a Belmont thing? You don't want to get
dirty?' '' Crotty said.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet confidence surrounds Crotty, who is as comfortable
passing the ball to others as driving to the hoop himself. He is
much like his father, from the hooded eyes and long eyelashes, to
the lead foot on the gas pedal. The elder Crotty's work ethic seems
to have also rubbed off. His son recalled watching his dad go to
work during the weeks he was also undergoing radiation for
Hodgkin's disease.
</P>
<P>
   In high school Crotty earned As and Bs while becoming an
all-star on the court. He imagined playing Division II basketball
at his sister's college, St. Michael's, which also had recruited a
Belmont point guard who guided Crotty into high-school play by
making him a ballboy in the fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   St. Michael's moved quickly with the scholarship offer. ``I had
St. Michael's folders, St. Michael's binders,'' he said. But he
felt as if he was grasping for reasons to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``My deal was to get the best school with good basketball,'' he
said, ``but to get that best school first.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Joe O'Donnell. The head of Boston Concessions Group Inc.
and a family friend, O'Donnell urged Crotty to consider a Plan B: a
fifth year of high school, at Phillips Exeter Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I did,'' O'Donnell said. ``I thought he had great
ability, mentally and physically, and that the year could help him
trade up on any college he could go to.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of watching his buddies go off to college, while he
went back to high school, seemed ridiculous to Crotty at first. But
the chance to grow intellectually, while also growing a couple more
inches, would help him in the long run, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   Exeter made the offer _ nudged, in part, by a couple of calls by
O'Donnell _ and offered a need-based aid package that left the
Crottys with a $5,000 bill. By then, the parents were sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really wanted to have a basketball scholarship and didn't
want us to pay for his college,'' said his father, who is a
technician for Polaroid. ``But once he was past that, he could see
the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Post graduate'' programs like Exeter's are one of several
popular options for students who want shore up their academic or
athletics skills, or who don't feel quite ready for college,
according to Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   New England has a wealth of schools with such programs _ several
with reputations for admitting players to beef up teams. While many
of these students play sports at Exeter, they are admitted on their
academic record, school officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes they're young men and women who aren't ready for
college yet,'' said Susan Herney, Exeter's associate director of
admissions. ``They bring a freshness and vitality.''
</P>
<P>
   And in return came opportunities: classes of 12 students around
the legendary wood seminar tables, where debates among classmates
take precedence over lectures by teachers. Crotty started on the
basketball squad, and was elected a captain.
</P>
<P>
   He lived in a 12-man house on campus, the first time away from
home. He introduced one of his housemates to basketball, and the
two ended up working on computers together. Shooting pool one day
in the house, Crotty watched two students fiddling with the
lighting in the room, and then filming the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that the light is so unbelievable, and I'd just be
playing pool,'' Crotty said, comparing the moment to watching a
basketball play unfold with someone who had never dribbled.
</P>
<P>
   Crotty said his richest learning came out of the classroom.
``Everyone has something that makes them go,'' he said. ``But
there, everyone has something that makes them go that's different,
and everyone accepts that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Crotty settled in did his thoughts return to
college.
</P>
<P>
   The close-knit atmosphere and classes on Exeter's campus were
deeply appealing. Like other prospective first-generation college
students, he'd had limited exposure to higher education, which made
the Exeter experience that much more influential. He liked how
students spoke up, spoke out.
</P>
<P>
   Size was also crucial, and he thought small: Brown University,
Amherst, Williams, or maybe Bowdoin College.
</P>
<P>
   An Exeter guidance counselor told him to consider some safety
schools as well, not to become too entranced with those he saw
first. But the warning faded once he reached Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball coach, Harry Sheehy, invited Crotty and his
parents out for Halloween weekend, to see the campus and a football
game, and talk over the basketball program. Williams has a strong
Division III team, but no athletic scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy's low-key sales job and the enthusiasm of students stood
ou to Crotty. But what won him over in particular was the
description he heard, several times, of many undergraduates there:
``Student-athletes.'' That sounded just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was walking in the middle of town with my parents, not
saying anything. And they said, do you like it? And I said, this
might be the place,'' Crotty recalled. His parents tried to hide
their excitement: ``My dad's like, yeah, maybe. And I was like, I
think it is. And they're both like, Oh, we LOVE it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeks grinded by with no word on his application. But the day he
was heading home for winter break, a single letter was slipped into
his mailbox at school. ``I read the whole thing by myself,'' he
said, ``and it just felt like, bingo.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Crotty will head for Williams. Meanwhile, he will
pack clothes and pictures and a computer, what with 600 songs on
it. He will meet his roommate, Adam. He will play basketball, he
hopes, and put more energy into a part of life he hasn't explored:
falling in love.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, he will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope everything continues to go well. But I'm working
hard. I'm working at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
