<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-PRICELINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE AIRFARE SITES READY TO CHALLENGE PRICELINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Amazon, AOL, and eBay before it, Priceline.com made an
almost immediate jump into the public consciousness three years
ago. And like its fellow trailblazers, Priceline quickly attracted
a swarm of imitators.
</P>
<P>
   The Priceline name, though, has remained synonymous with
name-your-own-price airfare over the years despite facing a gaggle
of look-alike sites. Only now, in fact, is Priceline about to face
truly threatening competition.
</P>
<P>
   That's because at least half a dozen Web sites have just taken
off _ or are taxiing into final position _ with the promise to save
fliers money using unique ``alternative pricing mechanisms.''
</P>
<P>
   As Priceline shook up the travel world with its innovative way
of selling tickets in 1997, a couple of these sites could shake
things up in 2000:
</P>
<P>
   --www.Hotwire.com is a joint venture of six major airlines, and
it is aimed squarely at Priceline's market. Also, from a consumer's
standpoint, it's a darned good idea.
</P>
<P>
   American, America West, Continental, Northwest, United, and US
Airways teamed up, essentially, to win back the ``distressed
inventory'' market from Priceline. These are the seats that go
empty on scheduled flights.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than get nothing for the unoccupied seats, airlines try
to lure last-minute, budget-minded travelers to them with low fares
not listed in industry-wide reservation systems. Airlines make the
unpublished fares available through their own Web sites, discount
travel agencies, and, increasingly, Priceline.
</P>
<P>
   Hotwire differs from Priceline in that you don't have to name
your own price. You plug in the parameters you want and see what
kind of discounts Hotwire can dig up for you.
</P>
<P>
   After you do a search, you have half an hour to buy a ticket for
one of the itineraries offered. If you pass, you can't search the
same route for 72 hours _ though your spouse, child, or Internet
alter-ego can.
</P>
<P>
   The site is technically scheduled to launch later this month,
but the ``beta version'' is online and open for business now.
</P>
<P>
   --www.Orbitz.com is the most controversial of the new sites,
even though it isn't scheduled to take off for a couple of weeks.
Both low-tech and high-tech travel agents have complained loudly
and bitterly about Orbitz since it was unveiled last spring, and
the Justice Department is reportedly conducting an antitrust
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   With all that fuss, you have to assume there must be something
interesting going on. And there is.
</P>
<P>
   American, Continental, Delta, Northwest, and United combined
forces to found the site, which has a $100 million war chest of
start-up financing. The idea is for this single site to use an
MIT-created search engine to plow through both the published
industry fares and the unpublished discount fares available from
the major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that really scares travel agents is that Orbitz plans
to offer the same discount services for hotel rooms, rental cars,
cruises, and full-service travel packages. They fear Orbitz will
offer low-ball prices until it essentially puts the competition out
of business, then will raise them again.
</P>
<P>
   While the travel agents fret and the feds investigate, you can
take a sneak peek at a stripped down version of Orbitz's system at
www.itasoftware.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.iDerive.com began selling consumer electronics Friday and
will launch its car-buying service Sept. 15, but won't make hotels
and plane tickets available through the site until November.
</P>
<P>
   When it does, iDerive will offer a list of discounted tickets
for the route in which you're interested. If one looks good, you
accept it and then wait _ to see if iDerive accepts you. If the
airline later opts not to give you seats at the quoted price, your
credit card doesn't get charged and, for your trouble, you get a
check for the full amount of the would-be tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Mark Nordlicht says the airlines have such sophisticated
revenue-management software these days that iDerive customers will
get the tickets they sign up for 95 times out of 100. In the other
five cases, they'll get a nice little check but will be left
scrambling for another ticket five days before they want to travel.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting concept, but probably one that works better
for cars and consumer electronics than for airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   --www.Savvio.com is a good, old-fashioned reverse auction site
that happens to specialize in airline and cruise-ship tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines can get rid of distressed inventory through Savvio by
offering the tickets at a discounted price, usually 10 percent to
40 percent below the going rate. As the flight dates approach,
prices will fall for any unsold tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are supposed to keep heading south until they're sold out
or the auction ends _ in the case of travel tickets, the auctions
have limited time frames, for obvious reasons. Travelers can jump
in at any time during the auction to scoop up tickets that have
fallen to prices they're willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The site started taking orders Friday, even though its official
launch date is Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   --www.Revelex.com promises to offer a ``continuous double
auction'' format along the lines of the Nasdaq Stock Market. It has
circled Sept. 20 on the calendar as its launch date in the 25
biggest markets.
</P>
<P>
   In English, a ``continuous double auction'' is one in which
buyers and sellers submit bids and offers on a rolling basis that
are visible to everyone involved. There is no beginning or end to
the auction, but shares (or plane tickets) change hands whenever a
buyer and seller match prices.
</P>
<P>
   On Revelex, travelers submit bids that are listed for all to see
and are ranked from highest to lowest. At the same time, airlines
and ticket consolidators submit offers that are also displayed for
all to see, but listed from lowest to highest.
</P>
<P>
   Any time a high bid and a low offer overlap, a deal is
consummated. To ensure adequate sellers on the site, Revelex has
partnered with the International Air Transport Association, which
counts the major US airlines as members.
</P>
<P>
   --www.FairAir.com hopes to split the difference between the two
groups of traditional travelers: corporate road warriors who aren't
concerned with price, and price-conscious vacationers who are
perfectly willing to stop in Pittsburgh and Minneapolis on their
way to Denver if they can save $150 per ticket.
</P>
<P>
   FairAir's big breakthrough is to acknowledge that some business
fliers want cheap tickets, too, but not with the limitations that
usually make them non-transferable and non-refundable for the
vacation set.
</P>
<P>
   The details are sketchy at this point, but FairAir says it is
creating an industry-sanctioned electronic exchange where travelers
can buy, sell, or trade tickets they bought on the site. That would
allow frequent fliers to buy discounted tickets, then unload them
if something changes later.
</P>
<P>
   FairAir.com is scheduled to debut in November, but you can leave
your e-mail address now if you want to get updates as things
progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
