<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1369 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COMICS-KIDS-BOS &LR;      09-05 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMICS-KIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARVEL GAMBLES ON `ULTIMATE' READERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUIS PORTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the whirlwind of American teen culture, the flashy
superheroes and soap-operatic stories of comic books seem like a
beacon of stability, or at least longevity. Spider-Man, the
Fantastic Four, and the X-Men have been around for decades, but the
stability is an illusion.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than having a safe, if immature, spot in the world of
publishing, the spandex-wearing superheroes face a threat much
scarier than the arch-villain Green Goblin _ a precipitous drop in
sales over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Marvel Comics, the largest independent comics company (DC, its
main rival, is owned by Time Warner), is trying to reverse the
trend of declining readership. Starting this week, the company will
release a new line of comic books, optimistically titled the
``Ultimate'' series, as a way to get kids reading _ and buying _
comics again.
</P>
<P>
   The largest publishing initiative in Marvel's history will
reintroduce some of its most popular characters _ Spider-Man on
Thursday, the X-Men early next year _ in new story lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing absolutely the most obvious thing possible,''
says Bill Jemas, Marvel president of publishing and new media.
</P>
<P>
   For years, he explains, the industry neglected young readers who
buy comics in drugstores, newsstands, and shoe shops, to write and
sell almost exclusively through specialty comic book outlets.
Consequently the industry has been losing 7 to 10 percent of its
sales a year since the speculative comic boom of the mid-1990s.
(Yes _ there was a speculative boom in comics just like those in
21st-century Internet stocks and 17th-century tulip bulbs.) Marvel
has suffered along with the rest of the pack _ the company sells
about 36 million issues a year now, down from the 150 million it
produced at the speculation peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a madness going on, as happens every so often,''
says John Miller, a comics fan and editor of Comics Retailer and
Comics Buyer's Guide, a publication based in Iola, Wis. A friend of
Miller's bought 5,000 copies of the 1991 issue in which Marvel
relaunched the X-Men, believing he would eventually make money on
their resale as collectibles. Unfortunately for Miller's friend,
Marvel printed more than 7 million copies of the book, making them
almost worthless today.
</P>
<P>
   Along with takeovers, consolidations, and confusion among the
distributors and the boom-and-bust speculation cycles, there were
fewer and fewer outlets for comics. Mom-and-pop drugstores and
newsstands stopped carrying the heroes' adventures. Consequently
there is now a generation who never spent time under the covers
with a flashlight getting hooked on heroes spouting one-liners and
fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   But probably the biggest reason for the decline in sales is the
complexity of the stories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The continuity problem &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvel is finding itself trapped by their very strength _
their continuity,'' says Matt Lehman, the owner of Comicopia, a
comics bookstore in Boston's Back Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Marvel's innovation was that if Peter Parker (Spider-Man's nerdy
alter ego), or any of Marvel's characters, got married or killed in
one issue, they stayed that way in future ones, Lehman explained.
This strict continuity was lacking in the comic books of other
companies, including DC, which predated Marvel.
</P>
<P>
   The continuity ``was really interesting and exciting,'' says
Lehman, who started reading comics as a teenager growing up on Long
Island in the 1970s. But over the decades the complex, cohesive
story line meant that getting a new reader was like asking a
pre-teen to jump into the middle of ``War and Peace.'' As Jemas
says, it is almost impossible for a 12-year-old to pick up an
``Uncanny X-Men'' book and follow the story. Or a 40-year-old, for
that matter.
</P>
<P>
   So along comes the ``Ultimate'' experiment's attempt to vanquish
comics' availability and accessibility woes with one dynamic,
web-swinging entrance by Spider-Man. Taking a page from comic book
history, the company will sell the books in a wide variety of
places, shipping about 75,000 monthly issues to comic shops (making
``Ultimate Spider-Man'' one of the top 15 comic titles), and
200,000 copies to newsstands. The first comic in the ``Ultimate
Spider-Man'' series will retail for $2.99; following issues will
cost $2.25, the price of most comic books. In addition, Marvel will
produce 3 million free, one-time promo copies of ``Spider-Man''
that will be distributed by Buster Brown Shoes and game company
Activision.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's popular ``X-Men'' feature film and next summer's
``Spider-Man'' movie will also help Marvel with its promotional
campaign. The company hopes the films will introduce the
superheroes to new readers, preparing them for Ultimate's new story
lines.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to modernize the stories and reshape them from
the beginning. For instance, Peter Parker will no longer be a
freelance photographer for the 1960s Daily Bugle, but instead will
be a Web designer for the newspaper's online edition. And since the
comic will start, well, at the beginning of Parker's story, Marvel
hopes a new batch of teens will start reading the books,
unencumbered by almost 40 jam-packed years of back story.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the Ultimate series will be able
to climb the Empire State Building (we won't say leap it in a
single bound _ Superman works for DC). Comic companies have tried
to entice kids back to reading comics before, and had little
success because of the quality of the comics, according to Jemas.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, those books for kids have been some of the worst
(stuff) in comics, and maybe in publishing,'' says Jemas, who left
Marvel in 1996. When he rejoined the company last February after
managing the sports division of Madison Square Garden, he
immediately focused on the Ultimate project. He knew that the
writers and artists working on the new books had to be the best,
which, he says, was not the case with previous kid-directed books.
</P>
<P>
   So Marvel signed Brian Michael Bendis, a freelancer who has
built a large following by drawing his own, independent comics, to
write the Ultimate Spider-Man books. Bendis will not significantly
alter the characters or dumb down the comics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comics have always been written on a pretty adult level. My
job is merely to write the best story possible,'' Bendis says,
adding, ``Stan Lee (the `grandfather' of Marvel who created
Spider-Man and the X-Men) is such a great writer that you don't
have to fall far from his ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how good the comics, there is no guarantee of success.
Marvel has to win back a mass audience that it hasn't reached in
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we have lost a generation of older-brother
influence,'' Jemas says. But he adds that he is sure the venture
will succeed, at least in producing good comics. ``On a content
level, we are not going to fail with this creative team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
