A1370 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-STUDIO-APARTMENTS-HNS     09-05 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIO-APARTMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDIOS: SMALL CAN BE BEAUTIFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A studio apartment can be a gem unto itself if
you put a little thought and creativity into it.
</P>
<P>
   With a bit of ingenuity, you can make living areas from
seemingly nonexistent space.
</P>
<P>
   An ordinary closet can become a kitchen, and room dividers made
from a pair of antique doors or wrought iron gates define open
space as functional and personalized living areas.
</P>
<P>
   Before you start, get rid of any unnecessary items _ from
furnishings to clothing. If you can't part with some things, put
them in storage.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to think about unifying the space with
monochromatic tones and materials that appear weightless, suggests
James Grayson Trulove and Il Kim in their book, ``Studio
Apartments: Big Ideas for Small Spaces'' (William Morrow $30).
</P>
<P>
   Trulove is a publisher, editor and author in the fields of
landscape, architecture, art, graphic design and architecture. Kim
is an architect and co-author of ``The New American Cottage.''
</P>
<P>
   Photos and floor plans in their book illustrate how more than 20
architects and interior designers extract maximum style and usage
from small, urban dwellings. The result is a compilation of ideas
spanning styles from traditional to casual modern and cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Parsons + Fernandez-Casteleiro designed a studio
with five separate parts _ library, study/dining room, living room,
entrance and kitchen _ with each part crossing over to another, but
unified by a sinuous wall. One section of wall conceals a Murphy
bed that opens into the living area at night. In the main area of
the studio, a large built-in shelf hides a bed.
</P>
<P>
   When the bed is down, a rolling translucent panel divides an
open living/dining space into two distinct areas: a guest bedroom
and a breakfast room, where the owners can eat without disturbing
their sleeping guests.
</P>
<P>
   Interior designer Diana Vinoly, of Diana Vinoly Interiors in New
York City, told the authors she was inspired by yacht architecture,
which requires many functions in a restricted space.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a small space, you can always be adventuresome without much
cost,'' said interior designer Nancy Smith, owner of Saratoga
Signature Interiors in Saratoga Springs and Albany. ``It's easy to
experiment with paint, and the color you choose has a lot to do
with the personality of who lives there.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith says dark colors paired up with white woodwork are
especially effective in small areas, particularly bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Trulove and Kim suggest painting the trim, ceiling and walls in
deep, strong colors that can blur the edges of a room, making it
appear larger.
</P>
<P>
   Lighting is also critical to making small projects provocative,
according to the authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In small spaces, it's nice to be dramatic,'' explained Smith.
``You can accomplish this in a few ways by using lighting coming up
from the floor to wash a wall or highlight a plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how you direct it, recessed lighting in the ceiling
can also wash a wall to illuminate artwork, sculpture or plants.
Table lamps (if you have space for tables) add warmth to a room.
</P>
<P>
   Mirrors can also do wonders for a small area. In addition to
reflecting light, they create the illusion of space.
</P>
<P>
   A photo in ``Studio Apartments,'' shows a room by New York City
designer James Brehm, who hung a drapery divider near a
floor-to-ceiling mirror. The effect makes the drapery look twice as
wide. It also was hung in front of a wall to create the illusion of
space beyond it.
</P>
<P>
   Placing a mirror on a wall across from a window will give the
appearance of two windows. A floor-to-ceiling mirror can create the
illusion of another room.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture should be multifunctional, such as a storage trunk
coffee table or a desk that's built into a freestanding wall of
bookcases with a walk-around on one or both sides. The back of the
bookcase can serve as a wall for the head of your bed. A daybed
doubles as a sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Curved walls create irregular movement within the space. Walls
can be a simple as framed panels covered with a neutral colored
burlap or sturdier framing and Sheetrock covered with paint or
wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Add another dimension to the wall by constructing shelving,
cubicles or drawers or build the wall around a buffet or antique
chest of drawers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Built-ins are not only functional, but add architectural
appeal as well,'' added Smith. ``They also help to free the space
from too much clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Studio apartment dwellers need to be creative with storage and
closet space. IKEA (http://www.ikea.com or 800-434-IKEA) offers a
large selection of reasonably priced beds, such as a twin daybed
that has a roll-out spare bed underneath for $60.
</P>
<P>
   The company also features a wide selection of wardrobes for
between $676 and $834 that feature shelves, drawers and hanging
space enclosed with frosted tempered safety glass doors.
</P>
<P>
   Their wardrobes, which also have solid or mirrored doors, can be
customized to fit your space and storage needs. These freestanding
units make great room dividers. Hanging framed pictures and works
of art on the back creates a dining or breakfast space.
</P>
<P>
   If the ceilings are high enough in your studio, you might
consider the addition of a loft, which can be used for sleeping, a
library or guest area. The area beneath can be used as a living
room or dining area.
</P>
</TEXT>
