<HEADER>
A1373 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MICHEAUX-BOS &LR;      09-05 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MICHEAUX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIONEER OF AFRICAN-AMERICAN FILMMAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WRITING HIMSELF INTO HISTORY 
Oscar Micheaux, His Silent Films, and His Audience 
By Pearl Bowser and Louise Spence 
Rutgers University Press, 288 pp., illustrated, $52 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's probably not a coincidence that Oscar Micheaux made his
first film just a few years after D.W. Griffith's ``Birth of a
Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith's 1915 racist masterpiece presented such a virulent
depiction of blacks that it was blamed for riots, lynchings, and
the resurgence of the Ku Klux Klan, which it glorified. Four years
later, Micheaux made ``The Homesteader,'' with the promise that
``aside from the general public, who themselves have never seen a
picture in which the Negro race and a Negro hero is so portrayed,
12 million Negro people will have their first opportunity to see
their race in (a) stellar role.''
</P>
<P>
   As astute as he was ambitious, Micheaux saw the ill effects of
Griffith's film, and understood the ability of film to help shape
public perceptions about his community. So for 30 years, Micheaux
made his pioneering ``race films,'' each boasting ``an all-star
colored cast,'' which sought to counterbalance Hollywood's
then-common portrayals of blacks as buffoons and brutes.
</P>
<P>
   Given his importance as one of the seminal figures in American
film, ``Writing Himself into History,'' Pearl Bowser and Louise
Spence's scholarly examination of Micheaux serves a dual purpose.
Through six essays, they analyze Micheaux's work, how it was
received by both blacks and whites, and how his films encouraged
fresh discussions about race. But Bowser and Spence's book also
rescues the filmmaker's accomplishments from decades of obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1884 on a farm on the Ohio River, Micheaux declared
early in his life that he would become, in his words, ``a personage
of much importance.'' He was the son of a slave, but he had no love
of field work, preferring to spend his days reading and writing. By
his 20s, he was submitting autobiographical stories to the Chicago
Defender, a black weekly, about his experiences as a homesteader in
South Dakota. He self-published his first novel, ``The Conquest,''
in 1913, and would write six more books.
</P>
<P>
   Micheaux saw himself as a man without limits. He thought himself
capable of anything he set his mind to, and that included writing
and directing a film based on his novel, ``The Homesteader.'' That
Micheaux knew nothing about making a film was irrelevant; he
budgeted the film at $15,000, and produced an eight-reeler that he
declared was ``destined to mark a new epoch in the achievements of
the Darker Races.''
</P>
<P>
   The film was a hit, and Micheaux was committed to representing
black life as he knew it. And by ``addressing such contemporary
social issues as rape concubinage, miscegenation, peonage, and
lynching,'' the authors write, ``he created a textured and
expressive response to the social crises that circumscribed Negro
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Micheaux's films gave the white establishment
all kinds of fits. Sheriffs and theater owners believed the films
would inflame racial tensions and send black folks rioting in the
streets. Micheaux was quick to point out that the only film of the
time that violently agitated black filmgoers was Griffith's ``Birth
of a Nation.'' To the contrary, his films became known as race
pictures, which ``identified them as products generated by and for
the community,'' and blacks saw them as a source of pride.
</P>
<P>
   Well, some blacks anyway. There were complaints that Micheaux's
scripts tended to focus on the foibles of the black middle class,
ignoring their counterparts in the inner city. Though all of his
actors were black, their light complexions and straight hair also
seemed to promote a European ideal of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the films themselves. Technically, they were
a mess. The lighting and editing were sloppy, and Micheaux's
scripts were at times poorly plotted. Of course, it's doubtful his
actors noticed, since most were amateurs, and their skills ran the
gamut from wobbly to woeful. By 1925, even black critics were
denouncing Micheaux's films. In the Amsterdam News, a black weekly
in New York, Romeo L. Dougherty criticized Micheaux's films as
``passe'' compared with Hollywood films, which were beginning to
open slightly to black performers. Wrote another critic in The
Afro-American, ``The day is gone when people will pay to see a
colored picture simply because it is a colored picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their faults, the films of Micheaux paved the way for
others by and about African-Americans, proving there was a market
and an interest in films about his community. Just this summer,
three films starring or directed by African Americans _ ``Scary
Movie,'' ``The Nutty Professor 2,'' and ``Big Momma's House'' _
have surpassed the magic $100 million mark. Micheaux would be proud
_ but not surprised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
