<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FESTIVALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL FILM FEST OFFERS NEEDED ALTERNATIVE TO HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Momentarily, the season's new films will be upon us,
ushered in via a stream of festivals _ Telluride, Toronto, Boston,
New York. But first, as always, the season's new crop surfaces in
Montreal, fittingly enough for a city perched on North America's
birth canal, the St. Lawrence River. At a time when the film
community, like the rest of the world, is run by a handful of
multinationals, ``festival'' has come to mean an alternative to
Hollywood. Most of the more than 300 films that were screened here
through Labor Day won't be seen at your local multiplex. Festivals
are a reminder that there's more to film than what the studios
aptly call ``product.''
</P>
<P>
   Two international figures bringing new films were China's Gong
Li and India's Om Puri. Each is the equal in stature to any
Hollywood star. Yet, it's a tossup whether ``Breaking the
Silence,'' in which Gong plays the struggling single mother of a
deaf boy, or ``My Little Devil,'' in which Puri plays a cook who
befriends a boy in a Catholic boarding school, will be seen on many
screens in the United States. Gong's quiet heroism shines from
beneath the everyday textures of ``Breaking the Silence.'' So does
that of her unruly young son (Gao Xin) in a film where the big
question is how she can scrape enough money together to replace his
hearing aid, broken by school bullies.
</P>
<P>
   There's no sense of victimization or playing for sympathy in Sun
Zhou's ``Breaking the Silence,'' just a bravery whose
matter-of-factness is reinforced by the film's muted neorealistic
style. Om Puri also takes a chance playing opposite a charismatic
child, in this case Rushabh Patni, the protagonist of ``My Little
Devil.'' The title is affectionately bestowed. Patni's spry orphan
gets into trouble, but most of it stems from his kindheartedness in
stealing food to feed the hungry family of an African-Indian
friend. As the avuncular cook who does what he can to help, Puri
plays only a supporting role, but he manages to stand for the
humane impulses of an entire culture in this film directed by his
``My Son the Fanatic'' costar, Gopi Desai.
</P>
<P>
   As you would expect in French-speaking Quebec, most of the films
are from Canada and France. Opening-night films can be political
triumphs but artistic disasters. Happily, this wasn't so for Agnes
Jaoui's ``Le Gout des Autres'' (``The Taste of Others''). It's a
richly rewarding ensemble piece that doesn't rely on dramatic
thunderbolts, but rather makes you feel steadily more invested in
the lives of its characters, who without exception grow on you as
they always did in the hands of Jaoui's obvious model _ and it's a
great one _ Jean Renoir.
</P>
<P>
   There's much humor, including a lot of the rueful kind. But it's
humane comedy as well as human comedy, set in motion by characters
imparting meaning to the title by imposing their tastes _ in
paintings, plays, decor, morals _ on others. In general, the
control freaks don't emerge happily, but Jaoui has given the actors
fresh, unexpected, and complex roles, and they respond brilliantly
and affectingly. First among equals is Jean-Pierre Bacri, as a
factory owner who is by no means the philistine he initially may
seem. He's so moved by a play that he falls in love with its
leading actress _ and deeply, not superficially. His two bodyguards
provide a few surprises, too. So does Jaoui as a waitress who sells
drugs on the side. But so do they all in this film, one of the
year's very best, that unerringly finds the telling behavioral
detail.
</P>
<P>
   As for films from the United States, the big event was David
Mamet's screwball comedy and Hollywood showbiz satire, ``State and
Main.'' It should once and for all lay to rest any doubts about
whether Mamet can write funny. ``State and Main,'' set in motion
when a Hollywood film shoot invades a small Vermont town, isn't
quite all it could have been, but it throbs with gleeful
outrageousness and comic inventiveness. Imagine Mephistopheles with
a cell phone, invading Eden, and you'll have an idea just how
amusingly William H. Macy's director and David Paymer's producer
work the place over, with the aid of Alec Baldwin's star who seeks
out underage girls with the destructive intent of a heat-seeking
missile. Philip Seymour Hoffman, as the writer whose soul is the
film's moral battleground, is, as always, a big plus, and so is
Rebecca Pidgeon in what I can't help thinking of as the Jean Arthur
role. More later on ``State and Main,'' when it begins what I hope
will be its long run.
</P>
<P>
   The promise in the casting of Gene Hackman and Morgan Freeman in
``Under Suspicion'' was thuddingly unfulfilled by that film. One
had hoped for a meaty routine thriller, but it was not to be. The
only fresh things in this otherwise inert remake of Claude Miller's
``Garde a vue'' were a few views of San Juan, Puerto Rico, and
Monica Bellucci as the sleekly beautiful young wife of a big-shot
tax attorney played by Hackman. He's suspected by Freeman's
homicide detective of serially raping and murdering preadolescent
girls. The lawyer is diverted from a charity gala to a grilling in
police headquarters across the plaza. But if the idea was to turn
up the claustrophobic pressure, it backfires badly. Once confined
to the interrogation room, the film goes nowhere fast, losing
energy and purpose and reminding us that even pros the caliber of
Hackman and Freeman are in the end only actors, not magicians.
</P>
<P>
   A much livelier and more original twist on violence comes in an
offbeat feminist action thriller from Finland, Auli Mantila's
``Pelon Maantiede'' (``Geography of Fear''). In it, a squad of
abused women turned ninja avengers go after male sexist abusers.
Caught in the middle is a forensic dentist who, as a woman, shares
their views, but has trouble accepting their embrace of
criminality.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the name of the late Krzysztof Kieslowski on its
screenplay drew audiences to a Polish film, ``The Big Animal.''
It's an elegant, wistful parable in artful black and white,
directed by Jerzy Stuhr, who completed Kieslowski's unfinished
script. He also stars as a provincial bank clerk who awakens one
day to find that a camel has wandered into his yard. Flecked with
the wonder of incongruity, the film alternates Magritte-like
vignettes with prototypical Central European absurdity and
sociopolitical resonances as it plays out the fate of the exotic
arrival in an environment too base to know how to appreciate it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1376 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-SHEEDY-BOS &LR;      09-05 1636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SHEEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLY SHEEDY'S REALITY CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So what happened to Ally Sheedy? Back in the
mid-1980s, when she was in her early 20s, Sheedy seemed like a
sure-fire star in the churning _ from the girl-next-door ideal in
``WarGames'' to the foxily frumpy screwball in ``The Breakfast
Club'' to the only appealing character in the Brat-Packed ``St.
Elmo's Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, she vanished into a decade-long vortex of drab
roles in dreary comedies and finally just about went pphhht!
altogether, until two years ago, when, out of the blue, she took a
colossal leap to play a heroin-snorting lesbian photographer in a
small indie film called ``High Art.'' She won enormous acclaim for
her performance _ including three top critics' prizes for best
actress _ only then to return to obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she stopped working. Her latest film, ``Autumn Heart''
_ which was shot in and around Boston a month after ``High Art''
was wrapped _ opens Friday. She's done some episodes of ``Oz'' for
HBO. She plays the title role in ``The Warden,'' a TNT pilot that
airs in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the big agents, the big producers, the big networks haven't
been calling, and the big question is, Why not? Why isn't this
woman's phone ringing off the hook?
</P>
<P>
   The answer may have as much to do with modern Hollywood as with
her.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a coffee bar not far from her apartment on
Manhattan's Upper West Side, Sheedy recalls the epiphany of her
professional life. It took place 11 years ago, just after she had
starred in two successive bombs. Her career seemed in danger of
tanking, and her agent of the time told her _ though she quotes his
remarks in more vivid terms _ that her problem was, nobody in the
moviegoing audience would want to go to bed with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling was,'' Sheedy goes on, lighting up another in a
nonstop series of cigarettes (American Eagles: no additives, no
preservatives), ``that there was this emergency, that I had to turn
myself into something people would want to buy. The idea was I'd
have to become a sexpot. I needed to change my hair, my body. None
of it had anything to do with any work I wanted to do.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Immersed in feminism &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The whole incident threw Sheedy into particular shock because,
while she was growing up, her mother, the literary agent Charlotte
Sheedy, was one of Manhattan's most active feminists; she'd turned
their Central Park West apartment into a lively salon. In 1971,
when Ally was 9, Charlotte divorced her ad-executive husband and, a
few years later, came out as a lesbian. For as long as she can
remember, then, Ally Sheedy wasn't merely immersed in the women's
liberation movement; she was practically present at its creation.
</P>
<P>
   So, to be told, while still in her 20s, that she would have to
go sexy to make it in Hollywood _ ``well,'' she says, still
seething a little, ``it would be like a writer being brought up in
a left-wing family and having an editor say, `The only thing you
can do is write a book that's a glowing portrait of Bill Gates.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just my agent who told me this,'' she adds. ``I
heard the same thing, in lots of different translations, from
everybody. The only person who told me otherwise was Jane Fonda.
She took time to talk to me. She told me, `What you are is a
character actress. You need a variety of roles. Work really hard to
get them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was the studios weren't offering many such roles for
actresses. The independent-film scene didn't yet exist. So, Sheedy
says, ``I just felt I had to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Around this time, Sheedy was in a relationship with Richie
Sambora, the guitarist in Bon Jovi, and became addicted to the
sleeping drug Halcion while traveling with the band on tour. After
the intervention of a few friends _ including Fonda _ she checked
into a clinic in Minnesota, cleaned up, went to Chicago to audition
for a play at the experimental Steppenwolf Theater (she got the
part), then moved back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that being a movie star is not what I wanted to do
_ not once I realized what it entailed,'' she says. ``I wanted to
be an actress. I got out of New York originally because I'd grown
up there, I wanted to be independent. I'd done commercials here. I
wanted to see if I could get into movies, see if I could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   She did get into the movies, almost from the moment she arrived
on the coast at age 18. But after the hits came the duds, and that
was it. ``They really have these lists,'' she says. ``One day I was
on the A list, then suddenly I was way down in the alphabet _ I was
on something like an E list. When that happens, especially if
you're a woman, you just don't get many shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Abramowitz, author of ``Is That a Gun in Your Pocket?,''
a chronicle of women and power in Hollywood, says Sheedy's story is
far from unusual. ``A female head-of-production at a major studio
told me that actresses are `a disposable commodity,' '' Abramowitz
recalls. ``All these beautiful young women come out here, have one
or two minutes in the spotlight, then it's on to the next one. It's
very hard for actresses, after they turn 35, to move to another
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one actress, Julia Roberts, can all but guarantee the
success of a movie these days. Several men can. So, Abramowitz
says, the studios ``build a movie around a male star, build him up,
and basically gut the female part. You see this constantly _
constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, even a genius like Meryl Streep has a hard
time. A cannily appealing actress like Renee Russo keeps her career
going by playing mature wives or girlfriends to Kevin Costner or
Mel Gibson. Other talented actresses who don't quite fit that bill
_ Isabella Rosselini, Elizabeth Perkins, Diane Lane _ start
dropping off the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sheedy, who is 38, Abramowitz says, ``She really shocked
the town when she came back with `High Art.' But she seems a
too-complicated presence just to be somebody's girlfriend. She has
this spiky intelligence. The studios don't know what to do with
it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A resonant line &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a line in ``High Art'' when Sheedy's character explains
why she left the high-glamour world of photography: ``I loved the
attention, but I couldn't handle the impact _ I sort of felt
pigeonholed.'' ``When I read that monologue,'' she remembers, ``I
thought, `I know this part, I know this like the back of my hand.'
''
</P>
<P>
   It was by pure accident that Sheedy even found out about that
role. In the summer of 1997, she was fired by the William Morris
Agency, whose executives calculated that her acting income was too
meager to justify their continued services. Suddenly, she was an
actress without an agent, which is like being a canoeist without a
paddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so depressed,'' she says, ``I didn't know what I was
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Sheedy's sister-in-law, a secretary in a smaller
agency, had just been promoted to agent. Her agency had the script
for ``High Art.'' She read it and passed it along to Sheedy, who
jumped on the chance, called the director herself, and pleaded for
an audition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roles like this are so hard to find _ complicated characters
with a dark side,'' she says. ``The actresses I've always admired _
Judy Davis, Helen Mirren, Genevieve Bujold _ they're complicated,
they get angry, they're real people, they have all sorts of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to be nice anymore,'' Sheedy sums up. ``I'm
not interested in nice characters anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly she's not nice in ``Autumn Heart,'' a film about three
sisters and their rocky reunion with their father and brother, who
ran out on them and their mother when the girls were small. Sheedy
plays the most bitter, profane, and unforgiving of the sisters. She
speaks in a convincing Boston accent (which she learned from her
sister's Boston-bred husband _ ``I had him sit down and read my
part'') and works herself into fits of anger so stormy and real you
can feel the steam blowing out of her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I have a lot of anger inside,'' she says. ``It's fun to
get a character who's such a raging _ I wouldn't say `lunatic,' but
someone just about to go over the edge. There's something
liberating about that. It's not cathartic, because I still have it.
I think it's important not to lose it. It's important to keep it
all in reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheedy hasn't hit stardom, but by most actors' standards, she's
doing very well. That is to say, she manages to support herself and
her family _ her husband, fellow actor David Lansbury, whom she met
on a stage set in 1992 shortly after she returned to New York, and
their 6-year-old daughter, Rebecca _ on her earnings..
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant juggling act,'' she says. ``Indies don't
pay.You get scale or less. I got paid less than scale for `High
Art' and `Autumn Heart.' The TV stuff'' _ the movies she's made for
various cable channels _ ``is where I make money. I try to find
something that's not totally dreck _ most of the time. I have to do
something at least once a year to pay the bills. The rest of the
time, I get basically nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Her success in ``High Art'' improved her situation _ a little.
``I was in the desert for a while _ which is not to say it's an
oasis now,'' she says with a laugh. ``I'm seeing a lot of material
that I wouldn't have been offered before. Stuff like `The Warden' _
I don't think they would have considered me a viable option for
that.'' But the basic reality is the same: ``If `The Warden'
results in a series, fine. If it doesn't go, I'm looking for
another job to pay the bills. This is one thing about being an
actress _ you're always waiting for the project to come along and
find you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
