<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1377 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SECRET-BOS &LR;      09-05 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SECRET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RON ROSENBAUM: TEARING THROUGH THE KNOTTIEST MAZES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SECRET PARTS OF FORTUNE 
Three Decades of Intense Investigations and Edgy Enthusiasms 
By Ron Rosenbaum. Random House,. 799 pp. $29.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not the smallest delight of living where I do is the Wednesday
ritual of going to the newsstand, picking up the weekly New York
Observer, and riffling through its back pages to read the column
called ``The Edgy Enthusiast'' by Ron Rosenbaum. There is nothing
like these columns anywhere else: impassioned, obsessive probings
of whatever puzzles or pleasures happen to be crossing the author's
mind _ the broader significance of Yale's secret societies, the
true meaning of Keats's ``Ode to Autumn,'' the zen wisdom of Bill
Murray, the mystical silence of Salinger and Pynchon _ all imbued
with a feel, at once funny and melancholy, for humanity's uneasy
place in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   There's an enormous chutzpah to this sort of venture, and in
most hands it would turn arrogant or plain silly, but Rosenbaum
tears through the knottiest mazes and hieroglyphs _ whether of
metaphysics, poetics, or politics _ with an infectious zest, a
rock-solid meticulousness, and a conspiratorial intimacy, as if he
were inviting you to join him on a secret treasure hunt.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his essays, on the blind Argentine fantasist-novelist
Jorge Luis Borges, he writes, ``It's a seductive and dangerous
taste, Borges. Once you've allowed yourself to be enticed into his
garden of forking paths, you can't be sure you'll emerge the same,
you can't be sure you'll emerge at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Rosenbaum's own twisty labyrinths.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum's approach to life and letters stems from two great
influences: Hardy Boys mysteries, which he devoured in his drab
suburban boyhood; and ``close reading,'' the technique of finding
literature's meaning by scrutinizing its text, which he learned
from Harold Bloom and the other ``New Critics'' in the English lit
department at Yale (Class of '68).
</P>
<P>
   ``Close reading,'' Rosenbaum writes in this book's introduction,
``was more than a way . . . of unlocking the secret parts of
literature. It was also, later, to become my chief asset as an
investigative reporter,'' as he realized he could apply the art to
such texts as ``trial transcripts, autopsy reports,
congressional-hearing records, Mob wiretap pickups'' _ in short,
the clues of real-life mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   He is drawn most avidly to ultimate mysteries, the enigmas whose
decoding might illuminate something fundamental in the nature of
things. ``The search for the hidden hand, the hidden springs, the
hidden handshake behind history,'' he writes, ``attracts a certain
kind of glory seeker, Ancient Mariner, mad scholar, Wandering
Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum is not quite one of those seekers; he has, as he puts
it, too much of ``what Keats called negative capability _ the
ability to abide uncertainties, mysteries, and doubts without
succumbing to the temptation of premature certainty.'' Yet his best
essays are about the succumbers _ the mad-driven scholars of the
Dead Sea Scrolls, the conspiracy buffs who glom on to the Kennedy
assassination, and their myriad kin ``who risk disintegration,
destabilization, in the single-minded, even self-destructive
devotion to the decipherment of such enigmas. . . . There's
something thrilling,'' he observes, ``about the passion, even the
madness of scholars when ultimate truths are at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Parts of Fortune'' compiles 53 of Rosenbaum's
essays over the past 30 years, taken from a variety of
publications, some of which were collected in two earlier, long
out-of-print books (``Travels with Dr. Death'' and ``Manhattan
Lunches''). The thread running through nearly all of them is this
obsession with obsessives, a pursuit of pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum is the opposite of didactic on this theme; he sneaks
up on you with it, then delivers a shiver. Take his piece on Henry
Lee Lucas, who confessed to murdering hundreds of random victims
and then said he'd made it all up. The tale is a well-told mystery
in its own right _ the tense uncertainty over which of Lucas's lies
are true, the fascinating ease with which he convinced the Texas
Rangers of the most glaring improbabilities. But what pushes the
piece over the top, what transforms it into something beyond
journalism, is the capper, Rosenbaum's final musing on serial
killers as a ``consoling myth'' _ based on a common ``longing to
ascribe all the inexplicable violence and tragedy in contemporary
life to inhuman alien monsters, cold-blooded killing machines,
rather than the warm-blooded people we live and work with.''
</P>
<P>
   To Rosenbaum, this longing is the human comedy and he finds it
explored most riotously in the novels of Charles Portis _ and here,
I should digress to touch on another of Rosenbaum's roles: literary
crusader. His main purpose in writing this particular piece, for
Esquire, was to urge some publisher to reissue Portis's
out-of-print masterpieces, ``Dogs of the South'' and ``Masters of
Atlantis''; and so passionate and persuasive was his plea that
Overlook Press did just that. For that alone, Rosenbaum deserves
enormous plaudits.
</P>
<P>
   But back to our theme. As Rosenbaum puts it, Portis's novels are
all ``about the longing for Hidden Secrets, the seductions of
secret societies . . . the profound, wistful desperation in the
American collective unconscious, to believe that somehow things do
make some kind of sense, that life is not all chaotic horror and
random acts of cruelty by fate, that there is an Answer, even if
it's locked in a trunk somewhere and we've lost the keys.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum touched on this desperation in ``Explaining Hitler,''
his brilliant bestseller of two years ago that sifted through the
various theories that scholars and theologians have devised to
explain _ ``to make some kind of sense'' of _ how the epicenter of
Western civilization could produce the most monstrous mass murderer
of all time.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of essays in ``The Secret Parts of Fortune''
are, in their own fashion, no less provocative and engaging.
Rosenbaum makes reading _ even reading about reading _ an
adventure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
