<HEADER>
A1381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-VANDROSS-BOS &LR;      09-05 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VANDROSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANDROSS: NEW LIFE WITH A NEW LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlos Santana got the Clive Davis treatment and ended up
winning eight Grammy awards this year. Whitney Houston, Sarah
McLachlan, and TLC didn't do too badly, either, with Davis guiding
their careers at Arista Records, where he was label president for
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always admired Clive's commitment to his artists. I can't
wait to be on his wagon,'' said Luther Vandross, the first major
artist joining a new label that Davis has formed since he was
squeezed out of Arista. _ thanks to a corporate power play that no
one quite understands _ soon after Santana's Grammy triumphs. The
new company, J Records, will be a subsidiary of BMG Records, which
owns Arista.
</P>
<P>
   Vandross, who headlines FleetBoston Pavilion  &UR; tomorrow &LR;  (some
tickets are still available), made the finest, most personal record
of his career two years ago in ``I Know,'' but it only went gold
(500,000 sales). He then parted ways with the label that released
it, Virgin Records.
</P>
<P>
   Vandross recently went to dinner with Davis, and the two hatched
plans for a comeback that may mirror what was done for Santana _
that is, a number of guest artists and producers are hired who give
Vandross fresh credibility and get him back on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clive wants to get started immediately, and I can't wait to
work with him,'' Vandross said.
</P>
<P>
   Vandross's renewed enthusiasm extends to other areas of his
life. He is feeling great from doing step aerobics five days a week
and following a diet that has seen him shed 124 pounds and 20
inches of his waistline (from 54 inches to 34 inches). ``It's a
high-protein, low-carbohydrate diet _ no bread or pasta, rice or
cereal. It's based on the Atkins diet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've changed my attitude toward food. I always used food
to cope with sadness and even extreme happiness. If you win a
Grammy, you eat to celebrate. If you lose a Grammy, you eat to
drown your sorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   His weight loss also has helped his singing, he says. ``You get
more power, because you have more ability to breathe. Your
respiratory system is better, so you can hold a note much longer,''
Vandross said.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side, however, is that his dramatic weight loss sparked
rumors that he was sick. One rumor this summer even said that he
had died. ``It was started by some bored (expletive),''Vandross
said. ``It was horrible. I was only glad that I got to my mother
first before she heard it. I have three siblings and they all died
in the last three to four years, so my mother didn't need any more
bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm officially telling everyone that I'm fine,'' said
Vandross, who has been on a well-received tour with Boyz II Men as
his opening act.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent suggested touring with Boyz II Men and I immediately
said `yes.' I felt it would be a treat for the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Several reviewers have talked about how relaxed Vandross appears
on stage this time, and he's pleased to hear it. And another reason
that he's eager to work with Davis is that he won't have to work so
hard to produce his own music, which drained his energy, but will
have outside producers helping out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a variety of people on the record so I don't have to be
bouncing cello and viola tracks together at 4 a.m. like I have
done,'' Vandross said. ``I want to sing and then put on my coat and
go out with friends and go see things like `The Scary Movie,' which
is my recent favorite. And I want to go out with my nieces and
nephews. In this business, you can get sequestered in limousines
and the like, but I've gotten to the point where I rebel against
security. I want to go out and be with the public and breathe the
same air that they breathe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
