<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PRINCE-BOS &LR;      09-05 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PRINCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL GORE, GRASPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE PRINCE OF TENNESSEE 
The Rise of Al Gore 
By David Maraniss and Ellen Nakashima. Simon and &AMP; Schuster. 298
pp. $22. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The subtitle of this campaign biography could be: The Riddle of
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Why does a disciplined, earnest, intelligent man with high
morals have, as the authors describe it, ``an occasional propensity
to enhance his role in events''? To believe that as a 20-year-old
he contributed to Hubert H. Humphrey's acceptance speech at the
1968 Democratic convention. To claim that he was ``shot at'' in
Vietnam when he never faced enemy fire. To expand his job
description at The New York Times from copy boy to ``newspaper
trainee.'' And, most famously, to pose as father of the Internet
and role model for the protagonist of ``Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   David Maraniss and Ellen Nakashima provide some answers in their
study of Gore's life, tracing the Democratic presidential nominee
from his unusual childhood and formal relationship with his father,
the late former senator Albert Gore of Tennessee, through Harvard
and the Vietnam War years to his decision to go into politics
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had a need to live up to expectations, first those
of his parents, then those of the larger world,'' the authors
write. ``He had a competitive instinct that made him want to be
able to show that he could do anything and know everything. In a
broader sense, manipulating reality is an inherent aspect of
politics. Some politicians are deft at it, Gore seems especially
clumsy. His exaggerations are clunkers and he is a bad liar,
without the nuance or fluidity of Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Maraniss won a Pulitzer Prize for his work for
The Washington Post probing Clinton's background in Arkansas, an
assignment he turned into the best of the biographies of the
president, ``First in His Class.'' This year, Maraniss and
Nakashima, his colleague at the Post, produced an excellent series
on Gore that led to ``The Prince of Tennessee.'' (The publisher
says that roughly half the material is new and did not appear in
the newspaper.)
</P>
<P>
   The book is grounded in strong reporting and honest perception.
While many candidate biographies are rushed and rely on newspaper
clippings, ``The Prince of Tennessee'' sparkles with vignettes
drawn from hundreds of interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The authors' portrait of Gore is that of a good family man with
a fine intellect and work ethic, though saddled with a few curious
flaws, an overachiever who always seemed older than his years.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to admire about Al Gore. Raised in the rarefied
air of a residential hotel off Dupont Circle in Washington and
educated at prep school, Gore managed to preserve his ties to the
earthier world of his ancestors in middle Tennessee. Deeply
conscious of the racial divide, he specifically requested a black
roommate at Harvard. When others, including Joe Lieberman and both
members of this year's Republican ticket, found ways to avoid
Vietnam, Gore felt an obligation even though he opposed the war.
</P>
<P>
   The courthouse square in Carthage, Tenn., near the Gore family
home, contains a memorial to the fallen men of Smith County: 138
dead from the Civil War, 24 from World War I, another 54 from World
War II, and eight from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cambridge, reassured by the prevailing sense that the war
was evil and had to be stopped and that any means of avoiding it
was acceptable, Gore allowed himself to consider other options,''
the authors write. ``But it was impossible, he said later, for him
to think of Carthage and not come back to the conclusion that he
had to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors located sources who said that Gore was given a safe
position in Vietnam. ``It was like being on a college campus,''
said one. Gore obtained an early release after less than five
months in the country. But he served.
</P>
<P>
   Like others of his generation, Al Gore smoked dope. The account
of his attempt to escape this bit of personal history is quite
comic. As is the time Gore, a cub reporter on the Nashville
Tennessean, took a phony obit for a Swedish gynecologist named
Trebla Erog. His own name spelled backward.
</P>
<P>
   There are suggestions that Gore's character has been shaped by
strains of his Southern Protestant faith. ``He comes from that
brand of religion that is informed by John Calvin,'' says
theologian Walter Harrelson, who taught Gore during his brief brush
with divinity school. ``Calvin has this deep, deep sense of how
human beings, none of them, can fully be trusted, precisely because
we're not God.''
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, Barbara Howar, remembers young Al as ``an
egregious little tattletale'' at the Fairfax Hotel. As a reporter,
he went beyond the bounds of traditional journalism to testify
before Congress and to collaborate with Tennessee authorities in a
bribery investigation. He wrote every word of his best-selling
environmental scold, ``Earth in the Balance,'' and remains proud of
its preachy, provocative passages.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore was clearly influenced by his father, three women
have played enormous roles in his life: his mother, Pauline, a wise
guide throughout his life; his wife, Tipper, whose quiet work among
the homeless is almost Christlike in its virtue; and his sister,
Nancy, who had all the joie de vivre Al didn't. The chapter
concerning Nancy's death is more heartbreaking than Gore's personal
description, delivered at the 1996 Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   The book effectively ends as Gore becomes vice president. There
is nothing of his demolition of Ross Perot in the NAFTA debate and
little of his fund-raising caper at the Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   But there is plenty in ``The Prince of Tennessee'' to round out
a picture of a complicated man. The authors find intimations of the
courage it took to ask an Orthodox Jew to be his running mate, as
well as the fear of failure in a political leader who once blurted
to an aide: ``Don't you know how insecure I am?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
