<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1386 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-GORE-COLUMN-NY     09-05 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-GORE-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HAD THE KISS, NOW IT'S TIME FOR THE DISS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, Sept. 5, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 NOTE: Word in 6th graf, which may be offensive to some readers, has
been rendered a--hole. Please make any changes to that word you see
fit.  
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Al Gore doesn't move fast, he's going to lose all the
momentum he's built up in the weeks since the DNC-17 Convention,
when he smooched Tipper with a kiss worthy of an episode of ``Red
Shoe Diaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kiss was great for Gore. The Kiss inspired dozens of
late-night monologue jokes, a hundred op-ed pieces and countless
political cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it was greeted with raised eyebrows by the cynics, the
Kiss at least raised the possibility that the Tin Man has a heart.
</P>
<P>
   The Kiss even put a temporary halt to all those lame and
ill-informed digs at Gore for supposedly saying he'd invented the
Internet, was the inspiration for the character of Oliver in ``Love
Story'' and had a childhood friend named Harry Potter who had a
mysterious, thunderbolt scar on his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's time for Gore to leave behind the Kiss in favor the
Diss.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's talking about the Kiss any more. All anyone wants to
talk about is the offhand remark George W. Bush made in Naperville
on Labor Day, on one of approximately 150 campaign stops the
Republican candidate made during a 36-hour stretch during which he
went without sleep, food, water or executing a prisoner on Death
Row in Texas _ all new records for ``W.''
</P>
<P>
   As you've no doubt heard by now, Bush put his Cole-Haan foot in
his mouth when he took to the stage at a rally, spotted a reporter
he considers to be particularly tough and said to Dick Cheney,
``There's Adam Clymer, major league a--hole from The New York
Times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, he is, big time,'' chimed in Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, so THIS is what Bush meant when he said ``It's time to get
some plain-spoken folks in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   (By the way, in the interest of accuracy, I checked with the
Times, and the aforementioned comment is NOT Clymer's official job
description. Their official stylebook indicates a preference for
the term ``correspondent.'')
</P>
<P>
   No doubt political candidates say stuff like that all the time
when the ties have been unbuttoned and the phones have been muted
and the room service trays are stacked outside the door _ but the
Bush-Cheney exchange took place in public and was caught by a live
microphone, thus giving a snoozing Labor Day press corps a spicy
little story worthy of a 24- or even a 48-hour news cycle.
</P>
<P>
   It was a positively Clintonian moment for the candidate, and I
mean that in a good way. People like to hear these guys
occasionally talking like real human beings as opposed to
programmed cyber-candidates on automatic pilot. (Bush had another
Clintonian moment years ago when a reporter asked him what he and
his pop talked about when they weren't talking politics, and the
frisky W. replied, ``Women.'' Only he didn't say ``women.'')
</P>
<P>
   With depressing self-righteousness, the Gore campaign pounced on
the remark with a load of horse hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold virtually all members of the Fourth Estate in the
highest regard and we believe they should be part of the democratic
process day in and day out,'' said Gore spokeswoman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, and you're all for campaign finance reform, and the check
is in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Clarification from the GOP and finger-wagging from the Dems
aside, the comment was a win-win for everyone involved. Clymer said
he was disappointed with Bush's language, but as a hard-hitting but
fair-minded reporter, he can't be too upset that the Republican
nominee has been rattled by his stellar work. (One of the more
satisfying moments in my career was when Michael Jordan told the
press a column of mine was ``all B.S., trying to sell newspapers.''
It proved I wasn't one of those creampuff media cronies of Jordan's
who spent most of the 1990s with their lips Super-Glued to his
posterior.)
</P>
<P>
   The jibe won't hurt W. either, as many voters would use that
same term to describe many of the perceived ``liberal media'' who
cover politics.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Gore has got to find a way to go from the Kiss to
the Diss. Beat W. at his own game!
</P>
<P>
   _ Get into a shoving match with a scribe from the Wall Street
Journal on Air Force Two.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do a Mick Jagger and point to an adversarial reporter from the
stage and proclaim, ``People, why are we fighting? Look if that guy
doesn't stop it right now, we're leaving!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Challenge Sam Donaldson to a duel.
</P>
<P>
   With the Kiss and the Diss, we've finally got a little campaign
momentum going here, boys. Don't go back to the script now.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper and the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
