<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1388 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MINORITY-ORIENTATION-     09-05 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-ORIENTATION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MINORITY ORIENTATIONS ON CAMPUSES DEFENDED, RAPPED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Lucas Orwig arrived at Brown University last
fall as nervous and excited as any freshman, eager to make new
friends with people from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   His roommate, who is Chinese, was already done looking for
friends by the time Orwig arrived, however. ``I thought it was
weird that all of his friends were Chinese,'' said Orwig, who grew
up in Houston. ``He had this group of friends, and I didn't get to
join them.''
</P>
<P>
   His roommate had been on campus four days early to attend the
Third World Transition Program, a pre-orientation conference for
minorities only. No whites were invited.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the program has become troubling to some people on
this Ivy League campus that prides itself on embracing diversity.
Critics say the program, designed to help minority students adjust
to the social and academic pressures of an elite school, is
divisive and indirectly promotes a segregated campus.
</P>
<P>
   Orwig, who describes himself as mixed-race, declined an
invitation to the program, known as TWTP. ``I don't feel like I
have issues with my race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other top colleges, including Yale, Tufts, Williams, Mount
Holyoke, and Wesleyan, have long held similar orientation programs.
Most, if not all of them, grew out of pro-diversity activism in the
1960s and 1970s. Brown's program started in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   But some students and observers say minority orientations,
instead of encouraging integration and a more unified campus,
actually harm university race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Amherst College ended its minority orientation three years ago,
concluding that it sent the wrong message. And Brown's TWTP has
long been condemned by critics _ whites and non-whites alike _ as
fueling self-segregation on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   On a broader level, debates over the merits of minority-only
orientations are another illustration of how complex and tense the
topic of race continues to be.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, a ``Visiting Committee on Diversity'' at Brown,
made up mostly of scholars from other institutions, said in a
report that it ``strongly suggests'' that TWTP ``be integrated into
orientation activities organized for all entering students.''
</P>
<P>
   One member of that committee, Harvard Professor of Education
Pedro A. Noguera, said he was shocked to find that ``nothing had
changed in 20 years,'' since he was a Brown undergraduate.
</P>
<P>
   TWTP ``is such a cozy experience. You meet all these nice folks,
and you don't feel the need to meet a lot of other people,'' said
Noguera, who attended TWTP. ``The administration has got to find
ways to serve students without isolating and separating them.''
</P>
<P>
   At Amherst, qualms about the school's minority orientation were
serious enough that trustees canceled it in 1997. ``Amherst risks a
serious misunderstanding of our principles by asking students to
arrive on campus in the first instance on the basis of differences
among them,'' President Tom Gerety said in a statement at the time.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown decides to follow the Visiting Committee's
recommendations _ after holding campus forums on them this fall _
it will face fierce and vocal opposition from many partisans of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Shin, now a senior, has found Brown's racial climate at
times inhospitable. One of the most startling affronts, said the
21-year-old Asian-American, came at the beginning of her freshman
year. A white student stood up at a class meeting and proclaimed,
as Shin remembers it, that racism doesn't exist, and that students
of color are paranoid if they think otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   It was a comment Shin took personally. Thankfully, she said, she
was able to draw strength from her experience at TWTP.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't gone to TWTP, I would have completely cracked when
he said that,'' said Shin, who coordinates the program. ``Survival
for us (minorities) is a lot harder.''
</P>
<P>
   In exit interviews on the eve of graduation, minority students
repeatedly name TWTP as the best, most vital part of their Brown
education, said Armando Bengochea, associate dean of the college,
who added that ``self-segregation'' would happen even without TWTP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have TWTP because the students who participate in it tell
us they want it, they need it,'' said Bengochea.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have only anecdotal evidence, administrators
believe TWTP _ along with other services such as ``minority peer
counselors,'' who live with freshmen, helps retain minority
students who might otherwise drop out, said Karen McLaurin-Chesson,
director of the Third World Center at Brown and an associate dean
of the college.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at TWTP, which mixes barbecues and dances with
workshops on topics like racism, sexism, and homophobia, usually
hovers around 50 percent of eligible students. This year, of about
400 minority freshmen (29 percent of the class) 171 attended the
Third World Transition Program.
</P>
<P>
   The Visiting Committee on Diversity also recommended omitting
the term ``Third World.'' For decades, it has been embraced at
Brown as a term of empowerment, less pejorative than the word
``minority,'' McLaurin-Chesson said. Yet countless outraged parents
call the admissions office each year, asking how their
African-American daughter or Japanese-American son can possibly be
labeled ``Third World,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Semantics aside, TWTP is controversial only because of the
discomfort and suspicion that surround race, said Bengochea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical response (from white students) is `How come not
me, too?' And I don't recognize that as a legitimate, thoughtful
retort,'' said Bengochea. ``There are no such complaints about
international orientation or athletic training,'' both of which
draw freshmen to campus early.
</P>
<P>
   TWTP is designed to offer a forum for discussion of sensitive
issues and introduce students to a network of administrators,
professor and peers whom they can rely on later as they enter a
mostly white environment.
</P>
<P>
   Some participants come from mostly white schools and
communities, and delight in their first opportunity to be in the
majority. Others have never before faced a largely white
environment, like freshman Michael Lucero, from a predominantly
Mexican-American town of Raymondville, in south Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what it would feel like to be faced by all these
white people,'' said Lucero. ``This lessens the blow. It's not
going to be a cold shower. It's going to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of this year's TWTP participants say it's important to them
that the program is for minorities only. To explain, Shekinah
Elmore, an African-American from Denver, offered her opinion that,
of the many TWTP workshops on various social ills, the sexism
discussion with men and women in the same room was the most
strained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder to be open when someone else comes from a
perspective of more societal power,'' said Elmore.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even some mostly satisfied participants see problems with
TWTP. Thai Vargas, a junior, said she enjoyed TWTP, but still feels
that it can coddle students who make friends quickly with members
of their own race, and don't expand their horizons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freshman year I stayed mostly with the TWTP `clique,' so to
speak, and only last year did I start to branch out,'' said Vargas.
``As you grow, you have to move and see different kinds of people.
You can't just segregate yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
