<P>
   FRANCE-NEW-NOVELS (Paris) _ The long vacation is over and the
French are once again being bombarded with books. Not school books,
but no fewer than 557 new novels, all published within a two- or
three-week period, all timed to coincide with ``la rentree'' _
``the return'' _ to work, to school, to the theater, to restaurants
_ that takes place en masse across France in early September. By
Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   ARMSTRONG-CEE-DEES (Undated) _ Louis Armstrong has gotten the
treatment he deserves in his centennial year: a thorough sonic
overhaul and repackaging of most of his major work. By Ben Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   TURN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Turn It Up,'' which has been
touted in advance as the hip-hop answer to ``Purple Rain,'' the
rappers Prakazriel Michel (better known as Pras) and Ja Rule (who
is making his movie debut) hold the screen with a brash, swaggering
arrogance. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ALMONDS (Huron, Calif) _ Eat marzipan in Germany or
almonds salted in the shell in India or China, and odds are high
that the nuts came from California. In California's Central Valley,
almonds are big business. The state's 6,000 growers produce more
than 600 million pounds a year, more than 70 percent of the world's
supply. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `l' category)
</P>
<P>
   DASTARDLY-DINERS (London) _ Behaving badly while eating well is
traditional in England, and would be just another minority pastime,
like trainspotting or cricket, if London's restaurant boom hadn't
provided an arena for a new generation of oafs. It has become so
bad that the president of the Restaurant Association here recently
declared British diners the worst behaved in the world. By Sam
Willetts.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `l' category)
</P>
