<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE NEEDS TO AMASS MORE SAVINGS FOR EARLY RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We have no children, but are planning to start a family
within a year or two. At that time, my wife will stay at home with
the children and we will live on my salary. Our goals are to save
for college education, save enough to meet emergencies, move up
from our current home to a single-family home in the $275,000
range, and retire at age 50. We have some lofty goals, but feel
confident enough that through careful planning they can be
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   B.S., Beverly, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, you certainly have set yourself some aggressive
targets, with the final one _ retirement at age 50 _ being the
toughest.
</P>
<P>
   Before I go into details, I have to say something is missing:
savings. As you outline your income and expenses, and after making
a 28 percent estimate of taxes, I come up with a monthly surplus of
a little more than $2,000, and that's not counting your rental
income. Since you list no savings beyond the two 401(k) accounts, I
am wondering where that money has been going.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that the two of you have sat down and decided to
turn over a new leaf, financially speaking. But that's a lot easier
to do on paper than it is in fact. My guess is that your outlay of
$1,292 a month for all expenses beyond your mortgage is based on an
idea of what you should spend rather than on an historical view of
what you have been spending.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, projecting 10 percent average annual returns from your
joint 401(k) accounts and ongoing contributions at current levels
would take you to $57,810 after two years. Then, with contributions
from you but not from your wife, the pool would grow to $923,681
during the next 19 years, following the same assumptions. Let's
consider that after the effects of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   If you are indeed spending $2,599 a month, you would need $5,338
a month to maintain the same lifestyle in retirement, provided
inflation averages 3.5 percent during those 21 years. Your
accumulated savings would have to produce a 6.93 percent yield to
meet that requirement, and if you simply withdrew what you needed,
you probably would not be reinvesting enough to protect you against
the inflation of the late years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   So it would probably be wise to build a supplemental retirement
savings plan. If you wanted to build a sufficient supplementary
savings pool to support your lifestyle without touching the 401(k)
funds until age 59 1/2, you would need a total of $391,881 at age
50, and to build such a pool you would have to save a further $460
a month, starting now. And you would have to draw upon other funds
to deal with the tax liabilities that this savings program would
generate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with $2,000 to $2,600 surplus monthly income at this
point, that sounds realistic, but when your wife's paycheck
disappears in a couple of years, your after-tax income would be
sufficient only to cover expenses and those savings _ with very
little beyond your rental income left to cover the costs of the
growing family, working on your emergency savings, and trading up
to a single-family home.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is not all that black. All of these assumptions
have been based on savings at the current level. Presumably, your
income will rise and your savings level will rise with it. Also,
the estimate of the effects of inflation includes your mortgage
expense, which probably would go up if you bought a new home, but
otherwise would not be subject to inflation. Still, you will have
to be awfully frugal to get where you want to go. I suggest you
think in terms of retiring sometime in your 50s, rather than
pinning your hopes on giving your boss your regrets on your 50th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   A few other points: as you build emergency savings, I suggest
that you put the first $10,000 into a mutual fund money market
account, with additions beyond that going into an investment such
as a good GNMA fund. If you anticipate buying a new home within
five years, savings toward that goal also should be in a money
market mutual fund _ not one of those low-yielding money market
funds offered by many banks. If you think it will more likely take
longer to move up to a single-family home, you could save toward
that goal in a balanced mutual fund. As for supplemental retirement
savings and money put aside for college costs, both accounts could
be in a mutual fund managed to track the results of the Standard
and Poor's 500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My father is selling his home and moving into a retirement
apartment and I am helping him set up his finances. He is risk
averse and would never invest in mutual funds. I'm proposing
investing all of the $236,000 in Vanguard GNMA fund, which pays
monthly dividends. He will need to use some principal each month,
so I am proposing the GNMA dividends be reinvested and that he then
write checks as needed. I calculate that his money will last him
well beyond age 100. I'm interested in your opinion.
</P>
<P>
   G.B., Acton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. One of the cardinal rules for advising on investments is not
to push people into something that makes them uncomfortable. While
Vanguard GNMA is an excellent fund, like other bond funds its value
will rise and fall as interest rates move, and it is indeed
possible _ and in fact even likely about two years out of every
decade _ for it to lose money in a given year. It is not for
somebody who is resolutely risk averse, any more than for somebody
who would never invest in mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, GNMA funds aren't particularly attractive right now,
given that long-term CD rates provide a more attractive yield. For
a risk-averse person, the rates on a five-year jumbo CD _ as high
as 7.81 percent entering last week _ are simply unbeatable. I
suggest you shop around and open two jumbo $100,000 CD accounts and
one regular account for $36,000. No muss, no fuss, and everything
federally insured.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, I don't see how you calculate that your father
will have to dip into capital. I tally that he will need $1,087
monthly in addition to his pension to meet his expenses. Even with
your assumption of a 6.5 percent yield from the fund, he would have
sufficient yield to reinvest a bit every month. If he went with the
highest CD rates, he would have quite a bit _ $444 a month _ to add
to his savings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our only investment is Fidelity Equity Income fund, which we
hold for emergency purposes. It has been doing very poorly. Would
you recommend switching to another fund? We've had this investment
for about 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   R.G., Ipswich, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The woes of Fidelity Equity Income fund are not isolated _
you'll see almost all funds that take a value-oriented approach to
investing have had the same lackluster results over the last six
years, during which the market has been almost universally growth
oriented.
</P>
<P>
   But with a 20-year perspective, you should be able to take a
longer view. While a value fund will not deliver the stellar spurts
that sometimes come with growth stocks, it provides a steady and
less risky ride. Over the last decade, Fidelity Equity Income fund
has delivered average annual returns of 15.21 percent, the kind of
thing that didn't look bad before the rabid pace of recent growth
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Equity Income has stuck to its knitting, maintaining a
low price-to-earnings ratio, currently 22, a modest price-to-book
level, currently 4.6, and a low turnover level of 26. Its 1.52
percent yield is modest but not in comparison to that of
growth-oriented funds.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think this is the time to quit on value investments. The
markets traditionally move from one sector to another and the value
stocks eventually will return to favor, and the funds such as
Fidelity Equity Income that have stuck by their guns through the
growth markets once again will shine.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the fund has a portfolio that should prove relatively
resilient if a serious market downturn develops. Its investments
are concentrated in energy, financial, industrial and utility
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I don't think a stock fund is a particularly
good place to hold emergency money. My suggestion is that you
decide how much you would likely need in an emergency _ say $5,000
or $10,000 _ and move that money to a more conservative investment
such as Fidelity Mortgage Securities, leaving the balance in
Fidelity Equity Income with the assumption that it will deliver
long-term growth to protect you against future inflation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
