<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1437 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-DEATH-HNS &LR;      09-05 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PBS TO AIR EYE-OPENING SERIES ON DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are not a nation of quitters, especially when it comes to
death.
</P>
<P>
   As a society, we follow the philosophy of a Welshman, Dylan
Thomas, who told us to not go gently into that good night. Of
course, he never got to rage against the dying of the light: The
poet died suddenly at age 39.
</P>
<P>
   But how much rage is enough? When does the ``good fight'' mean a
bad death? When is a desperate grab for a cure worse than the
disease?
</P>
<P>
   In virtually all cases, we can't determine what will kill us.
For the most part, we can't determine when we'll go. God, nature,
fate pick one takes all that out of our hands.
</P>
<P>
   But what about how we choose going about dying? Investigative
reporter Bill Moyers and his wife, Judith Davidson Moyers, spent
the past two years in hospitals, hospices and most importantly the
homes of terminally ill people (note: not always ``patients'').
Their efforts resulted in a four-part, six-hour documentary for PBS
that examines, as one dying subject puts it, ``living in the light
of death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On Our Terms: Moyers on Dying'' airs Sept. 10-13 (9 to 10:30
p.m. Eastern, check local listings). This is advocacy television
that attacks a basic Western precept: Death is the enemy, and we
must never surrender until our last bullet is fired. The
counter-argument suggests that, sometimes, a waning life is best
lived preparing for death.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-20th century, death came quickly and early. Before
World War II and the advent of penicillin, death came at a median
age of 52 and the end usually came fast. Now people live to a
median age of 76, and death is often a drawn-out process, the
result of lingering disease.
</P>
<P>
   This medical-cultural shift and other factors such as the aging
of the baby-boom generation, the rise of a mobile society which
scatters families, and the global toll of the AIDs epidemic has
lent urgency to discussion about the quality of life's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the face of that slow and tortuous death, most of us have
realized we want to die ... with peaceful closure,'' Moyers told
members of the Television Critics Association in July. ``We want to
be free of pain; we want some control over the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   We rarely get it. Four out of five of us want to die at home
surrounded by loved ones, but that same number will die in a
hospital or some other institution. ``Too many of us today are
dying deaths we deplore in places we despise,'' Moyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting if not embracing death contradicts the professional
ethos of most doctors, who believe in heroic measures backed by
modern medical technology. Saving lives is always the noble goal,
while prolonging life regardless of its quality is most often a
viable fallback position.
</P>
<P>
   The third option is palliative care, which places the emphasis
on comfort rather than cure. The concept does not sit well with
some in the medical community. The thinking is death is failure,
not the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Diane E. Meier, director of Mount Sinai Medical Center's
Palliative Care Institute, joined Moyers, and offered a telling
detail about the medical community's priorities: Through medical
school, residency and a fellowship nine years in all Meier never
heard a single lecture on pain management.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been this sort of infatuation and love affair with
the ability of modern medicine to cure sometimes and to prolong
life,'' Meier said, ``and we get so caught up in the excitement of
that and the rewards of that that we forget our core mission as a
healing profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The PBS miniseries focuses on different topics in each of its
four nightly segments. On Sunday, ``Living with Dying'' focuses on
the choices faced by the terminally ill and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ``A Different Kind of Care'' looks at Meier's
department at Mount Sinai in New York City, where the focus is
making death as comfortable a transition as possible. On Tuesday,
``A Death of One's Own'' looks at the agonizing steps people take
in the decision of when to suspend debilitating treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's final segment, ``A Time to Change,'' calls for
hospice, home and palliative care. Like many things in America,
access to this kind of care is a question of money.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people featured in the program is Dr. William
Bartholome, a noted pediatrician and medical ethicist who
contracted cancer of the esophagus. Bartholome underwent surgery
but, recognizing that his war against the disease is futile, chose
against chemotherapy or radiation treatments. Bartholome was
shocked by the insensitivity of the hospital hierarchy: If a full
medical school professor is treated that way, he told the PBS
program, what happens to the average person?
</P>
<P>
   Bartholome checked himself out of the hospital. ``I knew I
wouldn't be free until I got out of there,'' Bartholome said.
</P>
<P>
   Could Bartholome have extended his life? Maybe, by weeks or
months. But at what cost?
</P>
<P>
   ``We shifted the fight,'' said Pam Roffol Dobies, Bartholome's
widow (they married after his terminal diagnosis). ``Instead of a
fight for medical care ... our fight shifted to quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not giving away the ending to tell you that Dr. Bartholome
died, in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The story is how he got there and how we will, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
