<HEADLINE>
$ADV07 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Sept. 7, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard.  
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're one of those people who find today's pop culture
frightening, you'd better stay away from your TV tonight at 8.
That's when Shawn and Marlon Wayans of ``Scary Movie'' co-host
``The 2000 MTV Video Music Awards.'' The two outrageous comedians
are likely to be on their worst behavior, as will many of the
artists at the cheerfully raucous annual event, broadcast live this
year from Radio City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Sisqo (``Thong Song'') and Christina Aguilera are the most
recent additions to a list of performers that also includes 'N
Sync, Eminem, Rage Against the Machine, the Red Hot Chili Peppers
and Britney Spears. The pairing of hard core rock and rap artists
with teen-age bubblegum hotties ought to produce some amusing
ad-libs _ this could be a bleep-intensive production. Presenters
range from Robert DeNiro to Chris Rock to ``Survivor'' winner
Richard Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees for Video of the Year are Blink 182 (``All the Small
Things''), D'Angelo (``Untitled 'How Does It Feel'''), Eminem
(``The Real Slim Shady''), 'N Sync (``Bye Bye Bye'') and the Chili
Peppers (``Californication'').
</P>
<P>
   While this is one of TV's most entertaining awards
extravaganzas, we've yet to be convinced that the music video is a
form of art, and not advertising. Still, we can hardly wait to see
what Lil' Kim is wearing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: Nothing at the MTV event, not even
Lil' Kim's outfit, will be as depraved as this manipulative
``reality'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends,'' NBC at 8: Katherine's father (Bruce Willis)
threatens to get Ross fired. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Smackdown,'' UPN at 8: Even pro wrestling is looking good
compared to ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead Presidents,'' Fox at 8: Larenz Tate stars in this 1995
film about a young Vietnam veteran who turns to crime. It's a
thriller with a message from directors Allen and Albert Hughes.
Rated R.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC at 8:30: Two episodes air back to back. In
the first, Will's old boyfriend returns to the scene. In the
second, Joan Collins guests as Grace's competition for a design
job. Reruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 9: Regis Philbin
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia: Beyond the Fatal Shore,'' PBS at 9: This is the
final two hours of writer Robert Hughes' investigation of his
native land and its culture _ the best warm-up for the Sydney
Olympics starting on Sept. 15. Racism against the Aborigines is one
focus tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just Shoot Me,'' NBC at 9:30: An elaborately conceived episode
that plays as an A&AMP;E ``Biography'' episode on demented model Nina
Van Horn. A&AMP;E helped out, and sure enough, Harry Smith hosts. A
funny rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER,'' NBC at 10: It's Julianna Margulies' last episode as
Hathaway, and there's a surprise at the end. Or there would be if
this wasn't a rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parent Trap,'' Disney Channel at 7: Lindsay Lohan plays
the double role of twins trying to reunite their divorced parents
in this 1998 update of the 1961 Hayley Mills comedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open Tennis, USA at 7:30: Live from Flushing, N.Y. CBS airs
a wrap-up show at 12:35 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Splendor in the Grass,'' American Movie Classics at 8: Natalie
Wood and Warren Beatty star as young lovers tragically driven apart
in repressive 1920s Kansas. Elia Kazan directed this emotional 1961
drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard, Fast and Beautiful,'' Turner Classic Movies at 8: This
little-seen 1951 drama stars Claire Trevor as a mother who pushes
her daughter toward success in pro tennis. Ida Lupino directed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Jesse Ventura
and Spinal Tap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Hillary Clinton's
N.Y. Senate race opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, and music by Joan
Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05 a.m.:
Actor Adrian Paul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 1:05: Kevin
Nealon. Note time after tennis update.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Actor Ryan
Phillippe.
</P>
