$ADV08 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, Sept. 8, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard.  
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy's animated series ``The PJs'' appears on the WB
tonight, debuting at 8:30 before moving to its regular night and
time on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It surprised many that the show wasn't more of a hit last season
on Fox, given its distinctive stop-motion animation and voices by
creator Murphy, who's enjoying a career resurgence in the movies.
And the PJs' setting in the urban projects hasn't been explored on
TV much since ``Good Times'' back in the 1970s. Nowadays the barbs
are more pointed and knowing.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy stars as the voice of cantankerous building super
Thurgood Stubbs, who's forever put upon by his tenants and the
larger world, and never shy about voicing his complaints. In
tonight's episode, ``The Last Affirmative Action Hero,'' Thurgood
gets involved when a Jackie Chan movie films in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   If you were a fan of the show on Fox, by the way, all of this
fall's episodes are reruns to you; new episodes won't appear until
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: The nadir of the reality-show trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence,'' NBC at 8: Syd (Melina Kanakaredes) has a
near-death experience. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Blues,'' WB at 8: Zoe won't stop crying. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jag,'' CBS at 9: Excavation of a wrecked sub from 1941 could
provide evidence of a new twist concerning Pearl Harbor. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popular,'' WB at 9: It's a backward twist on ``The Parent
Trap,'' as Brooke and Sam try to break up their parents for good.
Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making the Band,'' ABC at 9:30: The boys in the bubblegum band
O-Town reach the pinnacle of their genre _ an appearance on ``TRL''
with Carson Daly. (The previous episode reruns at 9.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit,'' NBC at 10: Andrew
McCarthy guests as a wealthy lawyer who may be connected to murder
and sexual abuse. Broadway sensation Audra McDonald also appears.
Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Other Me,'' Disney Channel at 7: Andrew Lawrence stars as
a boy who accidentally clones himself while working on a science
project. But what if his clone's more popular than he is? A nice
little back-to-school comedy. Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``VH1 Confidential,'' VH1 at 8: A look at the deaths of
father-and-son singers Tim and Jeff Buckley, and the ever-popular
story of Sid Vicious and Nancy Spungen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window,'' AMC at 8: The 1954 Alfred Hitchcock classic
about voyeurism stars James Stewart and Grace Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Full Monty,'' FX at 8: Popular 1997 comedy about some
unemployed Brits who become male strippers. It's not clear how much
of the Full Monty we'll see on FX, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maximum Performance: The Science Behind Olympic Competition,''
Discovery Channel at 9: A look at the high-tech equipment that
gives the world's greatest athletes an additional edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``E! True Hollywood Story,'' E! at 9: Two hours on Janis Joplin,
featuring interviews with Bob Weir, B.B. King and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the Dollhouse,'' Bravo at 9: Heather Matarazzo
gives a brave performance as a junior-high wallflower in this dark
Todd Solondz drama from 1995. Rated R.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iron Chef,'' Food Network at 10: It's a banana battle!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Greg Kinnear
of ``Nurse Betty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Garry Shandling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05 a.m.:
Bishop Earl Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 1:05: Jenna from
``Survivor.'' (Note time after CBS ``U.S. Open Tennis Report'' at
12:35.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Hot actor Donal
Logue.
</P>
