<SLUG> BC-GOOD-OLD-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AL GORE IS NO GOOD OL' BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAN MILLSAPPS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bill Clinton, our first Bubba president, is
commonly known in the South as a Good Ol' Boy, which actually means
a bad boy, or at least a naughty one, a fact made clear during his
effective but morally tarnished administration.
</P>
<P>
   Good Ol' Boys work hard. They may run the local feed-and-seed
store or neighborhood branch bank or the whole United States, but
they all know how to stop working long enough to kick back and have
a rousing good time.
</P>
<P>
   Come Sunday morning, they go down to the Southern Baptist Church
to repent for all the naughty things they have done that week and
then hurry away to sin some more so they can come back to church
next Sunday and repent all over again.
</P>
<P>
   But this piece is not about Clinton. It is about that other
Southern Democrat who would be president, Al Gore, who has stood so
long in Clinton's shadow that sometimes he seems permanently gray.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Gore is that too many people think that he is
cut from Clintonian cloth. He's not. Gore is not a Good Ol' Boy,
and try as he might, he never will be. He is, instead, a Good Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Differences between Good Ol' Boys and Good Boys are major. The
outcome of November's election may depend on our understanding the
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   If Billy the Bad has spent his life being naughty and then being
sorry for it, Gore has spent his life actually being good.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore the Good went to Sunday school, and later to divinity
school, he paid attention. When the preacher read from the Good
Book, ``Go and sin no more,'' that's exactly what Gore did.
</P>
<P>
   His wholesome Saturday nights on the family farm, boring perhaps
in contrast to Billy the Bad's carousing, have provided him a less
than exciting public persona.
</P>
<P>
   Good Boys ARE dull; Good Ol' Boys excite simply by swaggering
into a room _ such as the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Good Boys are perfect public servants, however, because they
spend all their time trying to do what's right. Early on, they
learn to please their parents and then their schoolteachers and
then pretty much everybody they run into after that.
</P>
<P>
   Because he obeyed his parents and listened to his school
teachers and probably had perfect attendance to boot, Gore the Good
Boy is well-schooled with the intelligence to figure out the
answers to all the really tough problems, and he has the good
manners to not strut or gloat when he does.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore says he wants to work for you, this is not empty
rhetoric. He'll figure out how to get whatever it is you want _ a
good job, Medicare prescription medicine coverage, a clean
environment _ then, by God, he'll get to work and make it happen.
If someone else hadn't invented the Internet and we still needed
one, Gore would do this, too.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally Gore tries too hard to please. When his campaign
advisers, who do understand the differences between Good Boys and
Good Ol' Boys, told him they wanted him to be more exciting, Gore
tried his best, leaping into a crowd to glad hand, looking
absolutely foolish in the process.
</P>
<P>
   When they say ``jump,'' Gore jumps, sometimes to his own
detriment.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, by the time he had to write and deliver his
acceptance speech at the Democratic National Convention (``I stand
here tonight as my own man''), he had reclaimed his less mobile but
more sincere self.
</P>
<P>
   Good Boys can be good boyfriends or good husbands because they
try so hard to please. But, wouldn't you know it, for Southern
girls, the grass is always greener.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Tipper Gore may sometimes wish she had a Good Ol'
Boy, while Hillary Rodham Clinton no doubt wishes her man would
just lose the Ol' part and behave himself for a change.
</P>
<P>
   So you can call Gore stiff, you can call him formal and boring,
but don't call him Bubba. He is more a Southern gentleman than a
Southern scoundrel.
</P>
<P>
   Think Ashley Wilkes instead of Rhett Butler. And if the American
voters understand the difference, we may even be able to call him
President.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, I might add, is neither Good nor Good Ol', but
something else again. Down home, we call his type a Rascal. You
figure that one out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jan Millsapps, a professor of cinema at San Francisco State
University, grew up in the South.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
