<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-WHITNEY-BIOGRAPHY-HNS     09-05 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-BIOGRAPHY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOOK CHRONICLES LIFE OF INTRIGUING MILLIONAIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cornelius ``Sonny'' Vanderbilt Whitney was born with a silver
spoon in his mouth and grew up to be one of the world's wealthiest
tycoons and the stuff legends are made of.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey L. Rodengen's new biography, ``The Legend of Cornelius
Vanderbilt Whitney'' (Write Stuff Enterprises, $39.95), chronicles
the story of this multimillionaire before the age of dot-coms.
Rodengen has penned 29 other books, 22 of them in the series ``The
Legend of ...''
</P>
<P>
   Laid out in coffeetable format chock-a-block with photos, the
book provides an in-depth journey into the privileged life of a
gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   One of the twists of the history of C.V. Whitney's life is the
fact that the man who married his widow would commission this
biography.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after Whitney died in 1992 at the age of 93, John
Hendrickson married Marylou Whitney in a small ceremony in Alaska.
Their main residence remains Cady Hill House in Saratoga Springs,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was a remarkable man who accomplished things most
people only dream of,'' said Hendrickson, who also paid $250,000 to
bring the book to fruition. ``I've learned so much about this
compelling man and I wanted to produce a comprehensive book of his
life story.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Whitney kept a journal, which later helped
him and Marylou write five books about his adventures, including
``First Flight,'' about his days as a cadet in the Signal Corps in
World War I.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of Whitney's parents, Gertrude Vanderbilt and Harry
Payne Whitney, joined two of America's wealthiest families.
Whitney's mother, Gertrude, a sculptor, founded the Whitney Museum
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   C.V. Whitney, the only son of Gertrude and Harry Payne, was
named for his great-great-grandfather, steamship and railroad
tycoon Commodore Cornelius Van Derbilt, builder of Grand Central
Terminal in Manhattan. When the commodore died in 1877, he left a
fortune of approximately $100 million to the eldest of his 13
children.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 26 years old, C.V. Whitney turned a land deal around
that netted him his first half-million dollars. With that money, he
co-founded Pan American Airways. The following year, by selling
some stock in Pan Am, he founded the Hudson Bay Mining &AMP; Smelting
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Not one to be idle, Whitney went on to establish the world's
first public oceanarium, Marineland in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Already a millionaire in his own right, at age 35, Whitney
inherited $20 million from his father's estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money was to him simply a way to be involved in greater
challenges, not a cushion upon which to recline and live the
lagabout, ne'er-do-well existence his father seemed to fear,''
wrote Rodengen.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney's accomplishments also included producing ``Gone With
The Wind,'' ``A Star is Born,'' ``The Searchers'' and ``Missouri
Traveler.'' The last starred Mary Schroeder, who would become
Marylou Whitney, the fourth Mrs. Cornelius Vanderbilt Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   C.V. Whitney was an avid sportsman and polo player, and excelled
in the competitive thoroughbred racing industry, breeding 141
stakes winners in 54 years.
</P>
<P>
   In Saratoga Springs, which Whitney listed as his legal voting
address, he co-founded the National Museum of Racing and Hall of
Fame and established the National Museum of Dance.
</P>
<P>
   When not engaged in business deals, Whitney would relax by
hiking or fishing, especially in the Adirondacks of upstate New
York, where his family had owned more than 83,000 acres since the
1800s.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what his accomplishments and travels around the world,
Whitney was always most proud of being an American and flew the
American flag at each of his homes.
</P>
<P>
   Although he enjoyed his privacy, Whitney was always charming and
entertaining, whether sharing candid stories of his personal life,
reciting poetry, a limerick or telling a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``A success in spite of his money,'' proclaimed Sports
Illustrated in 1961, calling Whitney a ``thoroughbred purist'' and
a ``far cry from the popular tintype of the rich American sportsman
and socialite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
