<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1498 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ZELLEWEGER-FEATURE-LA     09-05 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZELLEWEGER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURE `BETTY'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RBOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raised right in a semi-rural Houston suburb by conservative
European parents, Renee Zellweger turned out smart, sweet,
hard-working and well- mannered. She is to the cliched stereotype
of the high-strung, high-living movie star what water is to fire.
You'll be hard-pressed to find a less affected, better adjusted
person in all of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   How she ever went so bad is just one of those mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding there. But considering some of the things
Zellweger's been getting up to in the past year, it's
understandable if some people are starting to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   These guys she's been hanging out with _ nasty, nasty filmmakers
like Neil LaBute and the Farrelly brothers, that unpredictable
boyfriend of hers, Jim Carrey _ they're so, well, kind of
dangerous. And then she upset those nice English people (they're
all very polite over there, you know), which we'll get into in a
little bit.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the French like her (make of that what you
will). Zellweger's latest film, the LaBute-directed ``Nurse
Betty,'' was a hit at the Cannes Film Festival in May. And it was
something of a surprise, considering how highly her performance was
regarded by festgoers, when Zellweger just missed taking Cannes'
best actress honors as well.
</P>
<P>
   An unexpectedly charming black comedy in which Zellweger's
Kansas waitress loses her mind, pursues her dream and for the
longest time manages to elude a pair of hitmen, the film lives or
dies on Zellweger's ability to make Betty's madness believable and
her plight sympathetic. When she sees her no-good husband murdered
over a drug deal gone wrong, Betty retreats into her favorite
fantasy _ a daytime soap opera she watches religiously _ and takes
off for California in search of her ``true love,'' one of the
show's fictional characters.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Kinnear is the somewhat befuddled actor who is nonetheless
charmed by Betty's earnest interest in his work on the show. Morgan
Freeman and Chris Rock play the bad guys on her tail. And while the
comedy certainly has its dark hues, many will find it a cheerier
exercise than LaBute's aggressively misanthropic previous films,
``In the Company of Men'' and ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   But like the proper person she is, Zellweger is not about to let
anyone get away with dissing a friend that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil's not a misogynist; he's a nice, kind man,'' the
31-year-old actress says in her warm, whispery Southern accent.
``His films can be dark, but it's commentary. It's not him. It may
be his sense of humor; he's very witty and wry, but not ugly or
malicious.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the basic Zellweger take on, oh, just about everybody.
The Farrellys, for whom she appeared in last summer's
much-criticized grossout comedy ``Me, Myself and Irene,'' are
perhaps misunderstood but ``talented filmmakers whose humor really
appeals to me, as terrible as that is to admit. It's rude and
disgusting and borderline offensive, but I absolutely love it.''
And her ``Irene'' co-star Carrey, whom she realized she was in love
with months after having had a wonderful time making the film with
him last year, naturally receives gushing praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a vast range of ability that he has,'' she says.
``I have tremendous respect for that, and it's funny: what he does
isn't typically recognized as great acting, but I would say that
that's the most difficult kind of acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And of course, all these false reports that we were dating
came after the shoot. But after some months of telling people how
wonderful Jim was while denying that we were an item, I started
missing him and gave him a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrey, who had apparently been smitten at first sight, needed
little encouragement. The outlandish and outlandishly successful
comedian had been suffering romantic traumas for years before,
evidently, he met the right person.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's too special; she's a gem, she's a gem,'' Carrey
says,deliriously, of Zellweger, then gets a bit more specific.
``And she's a very straightforward person. What you see is how she
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinnear, who had already made ``Nurse Betty'' with Zellweger
before she made ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' calls them ``pretty grounded
people. I've met Jim a few times. He's a funny guy, and she's
funny. She's such a warm person.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest you get the impression that Zellweger might be suffering
her own, dangerously Pollyannish delusions at this point,
understand that a sharp, analytical mind is constantly at the
controls of the sunny disposition. Take, for example, her shrewd
view of the role that many are calling her best work since she
first came to critics' attention in the smart popular hit ``Jerry
Maguire'' and the spunky arthouse character study ``The Whole Wide
World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty Sizemore is kind and generous to a fault,'' Zellweger
observes. ``Everything is at her expense. But she's content, goes
to her waitressing job, stays married to her mean husband and
watches her soap opera doctor every day. She dreams of a better
life but doesn't have the ambition to go out and get it. But
interestingly, the way she learns to live her dreams is by kind of
falling into her subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tricky thing to play, but also very technical,''
Zellweger adds. ``(Betty's) is a very specific condition that
happens after someone experiences a really traumatic blow that
makes it impossible for them to cope. The mind creates this altered
state in order for the person to go on. For me, it was about
understanding the parameters of the condition, and then making
creative choices about her and how far to take it within those
limits. It was fun to do the research and talk to the therapists
who've studied it, but it also left me a lot of creative leeway as
she evolves through this.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the power of the mind ... pretty scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. As Zellweger learned earlier this year, people's
preconceived notions can be powerful things, especially when
they're challenged. The actress has been in England since February,
preparing for and playing the title role in the movie version of
the bestselling novel ``Bridget Jones's Diary.'' The award-winning
book's heroine, an unmarried thirtysomething publishing worker in
constant anxiety over her weight, social standing and romantic
prospects, was considered by many to be the fictional spokesperson
for a generation of British women.
</P>
<P>
   When Zellweger was cast to play Jones over such homegrown
possibilities as Kate Winslet and Emily Watson, outcries ensued.
The sensationalist tabloids went ape over the perceived Yankee
invasion (never mind the fact that British actors have played far
more American characters in films than vice versa). Helen Fielding,
the book's author, even severed relations with the production.
</P>
<P>
   But with typical, industrious dedication, Zellweger threw
herself into mastering a British accent, familiarizing herself with
Bridget's world and even (remember what we said about her not being
your stereotypical Hollywood actress) bulking up to fighting
weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't felt any hostility, personally, over there, just
what I read,'' notes Zellweger, who as part of her research clipped
and compiled articles decrying her casting for the publishing house
that distributed Fielding's book. ``And that stuff could be
unnecessarily hostile in certain respects, to the point where it
felt like they were trying to hurt your feelings. But, of course, I
realized that they were just trying to make a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what can you do about it? I just tried to work as hard as
I could. The accent work has been fun, and I tried very hard to get
it right. I guess we'll know how well I succeeded if I'm lynched or
not next spring when the film comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the eating requirements, Zellweger brought her natural
good humor to that part of the job, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I have been enjoying the London cuisine,'' she says,
laughing. ``That's a fun thing for an actress to do ... for about
two weeks. Then the novelty wears off and you've got three
obligatory chocolate bars to get down a day. That becomes not as
exciting as you might have anticipated. After all the fettucine
Alfredo and pizza lunches you could ever imagine overindulging in,
it gets to the point where you just want some spinach.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she confessed to massive homesickness and missing her
dog, Zellweger typically faced her long sojourn in London as
cheerfully as she possibly could. Maybe there is something of a
Pollyanna syndrome at work here _ but if so, it seems pretty
beneficial, and has certainly helped her live out her dreams as
effectively as Nurse Betty's psychosis helped her.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, being so nice can be a little embarrassing sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an incredible adventure I've had, gol-lee,'' Zellweger
chirps, then stops short. ``Oh, no! `Golly' _ that sounds so geeky.
But it's instead of saying the other g-word that your mom doesn't
want you to say. Still, I hate reading myself saying that in print
_ 'I don't say that' _ but I guess you just caught me doing it.
It's very Gomer Pyle, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wire services contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
