<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-MORMON-WRITER-HN     09-05 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MORMON-WRITER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MORMON TESTS CHURCH AND FAITH ON SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RON DICKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite the gallery of rogues who lie and cheat in
his films, Neil LaBute had escaped the attention of his Mormon
Church elders for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Then LaBute got personal. He introduced Mormon characters.
Homicidal Mormon characters.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bash: Latter-Day Plays,'' a filmed version of which aired
on Showtime last week, pretty people of the faith confess ugly
crimes. That made the phone ring. It was the church asking LaBute
to portray Mormons in a positive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``From their point of view, art is something used to enlighten
and promote a kind of goodness,'' LaBute said in New York recently.
``And they don't really care for the idea of using bad to exemplify
good. So now it's up to me to say I'm going to follow that or I
will continue writing as I see fit.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute already has made up his mind _ he'll keep following his
own vision _ so it is just coincidence that he made a departure
into comedy by directing ``Nurse Betty,'' which opens Friday. Renee
Zellweger plays a waitress who is so traumatized by seeing hitmen
kill her husband that she becomes delusional. She believes her
favorite soap star (Greg Kinnear) is a real doctor, and pursues him
cross-country with the killers (Chris Rock and Morgan Freeman) on
her trail.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute would never have touched such zaniness as a writer. So
why lighten up as a director?
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was any calculation,'' LaBute said, ``it was that
people will respect this. It wasn't that this has a much better
chance of making people happy.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute has never been about spreading joy. He insists his
upbringing in the Midwest was essentially normal and that he is a
regular guy. But the mantel of provocateur he once cloaked himself
in now fits so well, there's no use trying to stake out gentler
ground.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview in an Upper East Side hotel suite, LaBute,
37, looks like a video-arcade refugee from the '70s. He sports a
Greg Brady Afro, glasses and a checked button-down shirt over a
striped T-shirt. His bearing is pleasant, and he speaks quietly, in
measured tones, making no apologies for his cynical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Back when he attended New York University, LaBute wrote a play
called ``Deaf People are Funny.'' Then he penned another in which a
character railed against homosexuals, prompting the audience to
scream its disapproval. LaBute knew he was on to something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the challenge of taking an audience to task,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute has known upstanding citizens, including his wife, Lisa,
and his parents. Lisa LaBute is of the same mind as the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, that art should mirror beauty.
LaBute says he thinks of her as he writes, yet what springs from
his imagination would make church founder Brigham Young cringe.
</P>
<P>
   Consider his feature films so far: In ``In the Company of Men''
(1997), an office Lothario bets an associate that he can make a
deaf worker fall in love with him before he dumps her.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' (1998), bored Manhattanites
slither around their spouses and best buddies to get a little on
the side.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute likes to think of his works as how-not-to manuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful people who we tend to emulate and want to be friends
with have as much trouble being nice and making good choices as
anybody,'' LaBute said. ``It's interesting to dissect. As long as
that interests me, I can't imagine not wanting to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute's latest project stars Gwyneth Paltrow in a screen
adaptation of A.J. Byatt's novel, ``Possession,'' about a pair of
modern academics who discover an unlikely love affair between two
Victorian poets.
</P>
<P>
   What could be creepy about that?
</P>
<P>
   LaBute smiled. ``That was part of what I was worried about,'' he
said, ``so I had to give it as much dysfunction as I saw fit.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute sounds like a wholesome guy. Really. He helps his two
children, ages 9 and 12, get ready for school. He likes to putter
around the house and munch on potato chips _ anything to avoid a
blinking cursor and a blank page. And he is devoted to his religion
and the Midwest. LaBute recently moved his family from Fort Wayne,
Ind., to a Chicago suburb to have access to O'Hare Airport.
</P>
<P>
   He takes meetings in Los Angeles, but feels far less creative
there. ``I'm suspicious of blue skies,'' he said. ``I'm more
comfortable around frequent and furious change.''
</P>
<P>
   There is turbulence in ``Nurse Betty,'' but it comes in the
confection of Zellweger, whose goodness beams through even as her
Betty breaks from reality.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute knew he had to find the genuine article or the movie
would collapse under the weight of a wacky premise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renee has a lot of good will with the audience and you can't
manufacture that with a person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute expects that ``Nurse Betty'' will illuminate his hopeful
side, but as long as his dark side is lurking, the Mormon Church
will be watching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
