<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING OFFICIAL ACCUSES TAIWAN'S PRESIDENT OF SEPARATISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A Chinese spokesman on Tuesday attacked Taiwan's
president for remarks suggesting that the island's unification with
China is not inevitable, calling them ``very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman also indicated at a press conference that China's
patience with the president, Chen Shui-bian, who took office in
May, is beginning to wear thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewing his first 100 days, we think he is not moving toward
accepting the one-China principle and is instead moving in the
direction of Taiwan separatism,'' said Zhang Mingqing, spokesman
for the Taiwan Affairs Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhang did not indicate that Beijing was taking any new steps
to threaten Taiwan, which it considers a part of China that was
separated by civil war and must some day return.
</P>
<P>
   China was deeply concerned about Chen's election because his
Democratic Progressive Party has long advocated Taiwan's formal
independence. But before and after his election, Chen eased
tensions by making it clear that he would not declare independence
unless China attacked Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office, Chen has sought to differentiate his
position as national leader from that of his party and, in a
gesture of friendship toward China, has offered to discuss closer
economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government continues to shun discussions with Chen's
party, and on Tuesday the spokesman in Beijing said, ``We will not
have any contact with the DPP until it revises its pro-independence
platform.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Chen said a majority of Taiwan's 23
million people do not support unification under the ``one country,
two systems'' formula for autonomy that China has offered. He also
rejected the policy of the long-ruling Nationalist Party that the
unity of Taiwan and the mainland was ``the only possible conclusion
for Taiwan's future.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman in Beijing said Tuesday that the remarks were
``very dangerous and cannot but incite alarm among all Chinese
people, including Taiwan compatriots.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taiwan's official spokesperson, Chung Chin, dismissed the
warnings by saying that ``the situation is definitely not as
disappointing'' as Beijing had described.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's government hopes to coax China into talks on economic and
other issues without agreeing first on the overall goal of
unification, and the two sides still appear to be warily testing
each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
