<P>
   CALIF-ALMONDS (Huron, Calif) _ Eat marzipan in Germany or
almonds salted in the shell in India or China, and odds are high
that the nuts came from California. In California's Central Valley,
almonds are big business. The state's 6,000 growers produce more
than 600 million pounds a year, more than 70 percent of the world's
supply. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   DASTARDLY-DINERS (London) _ They do it harmlessly in Wodehouse,
and horribly in Waugh. Behaving badly while eating well is
traditional in England, where undergraduate hellfire clubs still
play at being Regency bucks by getting expensively sick over
shattered crockery. It would be just another minority pastime, like
trainspotting or cricket, if London's restaurant boom hadn't
provided an arena for a new generation of oafs. It's become so bad
that the president of the Restaurant Association here recently
declared British diners the worst behaved in the world. By Sam
Willetts.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NETWORK (Undated) _ how far the Food Network has evolved
from trying to teach anybody to cook. After a financial struggle
that cost the cable startup an estimated $88 million in the seven
years since its creation, media analysts predict the network will
finally break even this year. It is thriving by replacing the shows
with cooks standing behind counters _ the sorts of programs that
dominated the airwaves during the first four decades of
television's existence _ with shows that are purely about
entertainment. By Michelle Slatalla.
</P>
