<P>
   SANTAFE-OPERA (Undated) _ A curtain is descending, slowly and
gracefully, on a long stretch of the Santa Fe Opera's history. On
Sept. 30, just as the new concert season gets under way in the
world's arts centers, John Crosby will step down as the general
director of this adventurous company, which he founded in 1957 and
has run since. By Alan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-NEW-NOVELS (Paris) _ The long vacation is over and the
French are once again being bombarded with books. Not school books,
but no fewer than 557 new novels, all published within a two- or
three-week period, all timed to coincide with ``la rentree'' _
``the return'' _ to work, to school, to the theater, to restaurants
_ that takes place en masse across France in early September. By
Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on television. By Bill
Carter and Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ARMSTRONG-CEE-DEES (Undated) _ Louis Armstrong has gotten the
treatment he deserves in his centennial year: a thorough sonic
overhaul and repackaging of most of his major work. By Ben Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   BACKSTAGE-FILM-REVIEW (Undted) _ ``Backstage'': Chris Fiore,
director. Performers Jay-Z, DMX, Method Man, Redman, Ja Rule,
Bennie Sigel, Busta Rhymes, Chuck D, Magic Johnson. Rewiewed by
Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BULL-FILM-REVIE (Undated) _ ``The Bulls' Night Out'': Lindley
Farley, director; with Jack Marnell. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   TURN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Turn It Up,'' which has been
touted in advance as the hip-hop answer to ``Purple Rain,'' the
rappers Prakazriel Michel (better known as Pras) and Ja Rule (who
is making his movie debut) hold the screen with a brash, swaggering
arrogance. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   DARK-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Dark Horses and Black Beauties,''
by Melissa Holbrook Pierson (Norton). Reviewed by Richard
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HIPHOP-REVIEW (Undated) _ On ABC's ``Nightline,'' a
three-night special on hip hop. Reviewed by Julie Salamon.
</P>
