<SLUG> BC-U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON EVE OF U.N. SUMMIT MEETING, ANNAN SPEAKS OF HOPE FOR MIDEAST
PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Tuesday that
Israel and the Palestinians were closer to achieving a peace
agreement than ever before, and expressed hope that further
progress would be made at the next round of talks scheduled by
President Clinton for later this week in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the two parties have ever been closer than they
are today,'' said Annan, who earlier this week talked with Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and the Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat. He described both leaders as wanting more progress. ``But
of course we need to have a package on the table that both sides
find mutually acceptable,'' the secretary-general said.
</P>
<P>
   The last round of talks at Camp David, Md., ended in July when
the two sides could not agree on the future status of Jerusalem.
But Annan said, ``I think Camp David made major strides, and I
would hope we would be able to capitalize on that progress and
reach an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general made his remarks at a news conference on
Tuesday in advance of the three-day Millennium Summit meeting,
which its U.N. organizers are calling the largest gathering of
political leaders in history.
</P>
<P>
   Annan used the news conference to emphasize that the United
Nations could not be expected to do everything alone. And he warned
that the world's problems, from poverty to AIDS and economic
inequality, would never be solved without the active cooperation of
every country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is everyone's responsibility,'' Annan said. ``We will play
a catalytic role,'' but ``everyone has to do their bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting will bring together more than 150 heads of
state here on Wednesday. It will conclude on Friday with a joint
declaration, a draft of which began circulating on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The draft declaration commits signers to ``spare no effort to
free our peoples from the scourge of war'' and to promote
democracy, expand respect for human rights and ensure every
country's right to economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Other resolutions call for ridding the world of poverty,
promoting education and reversing the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no illusion that a single summit in itself can change
the world,'' Annan told journalists. ``But I believe this meeting
provides a unique opportunity for leaders to renew our mission and
our purpose.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Annan acknowledged that the goals that were set out were
ambitious. But he expressed hope that everyone at the summit
meeting would go home and take action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems seem huge,'' the secretary-general said, ``but in
today's world, given the technology and the resources involved, we
have the means to tackle them.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the proposed expansion of the 15-member Security
Council sought by many countries, Annan said that he believed an
expansion was possible, though he doubted that it could be achieved
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, one of the council's five permanent members, on Monday
suggested an expansion of the council. Last spring, the U.S. chief
representative, Richard C. Holbrooke, spoke of increasing its
membership beyond 20 or 21 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western countries have argued that adding too many members
would dilute the council's effectiveness. But Annan expressed
sympathy with many developing countries that contend that the
council should be made more democratic and representative of the
diversity of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject the idea that the expansion will necessarily lead to
a confused, ineffective Security Council which fudges all issues,''
the secretary-general said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
