<HEADER>
A1623 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-PR     09-05 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-PROVENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARADISE THAT'S PROVENCE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material, the sixth destination
column from the MICHELIN ON TRAVEL feature from The New York Times
Syndicate, is for use by MICHELIN clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: A photo and a map of Provence are available on Newscom or
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By JUDY FAYARD 
 c.2000 Michelin 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The small road from Malaucene to Suzette winds through
deep-green wooded hills and rounded valleys terraced with rows and
rows of vineyards _ horizontal, vertical, diagonal _ a lush and
leafy basket weave of vines.
</P>
<P>
   The hills are not very high but the air is almost alpine, and
the landscape so rich, so carefully cultivated that it seems a
vision of earthly paradise. Then, suddenly, the road bends and
there, in the center of a circular green dell, two jagged white
rocks jut skyward like the razorback spines of a dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the Romans called these hills ``mons mirabilis,'' the
marvelous mountains. Today, they're called the Dentelles de
Montmirail. And they are at the center of one of the most
historically curious regions of France, the splatter-shaped Comtat
Venaissin, a ``county'' which for some 500 years did not belong to
France at all but to the Pope.
</P>
<P>
   A good launching point for the Dentelles is the Comtat's old
capital, Carpentras, whose Friday morning market is one of the
biggest and best in Provence, filling the streets of town all the
way to the 15th-century St. Siffren cathedral and the 14th-century
synagogue, the oldest in France.
</P>
<P>
   Just north of Carpentras, the road divides. It doesn't matter
whether you take the right fork or the left _ both routes lead
around the Dentelles to Vaison-la-Romaine and, on the way, to some
of the most delightful villages in Provence. Most are medieval
towns built on old Roman foundations and most are engaged in wine
making.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful chateau-fortress of Le Barroux pops up out of
nowhere, silhouetted against the sharp, blue sky, and on some days
the mistral wind literally howls as it whips past the crenelated
walls. Gigondas is surprisingly small, given the renown of its
wine, but it has an instant charm that befits its old Roman name of
``Jocundatis,'' the jolly one.
</P>
<P>
   Sablet forms an almost perfect circle in the vineyards, its
twisted streets and covered passages squeezed within its rampart
walls. Seguret is strung around the base of its dome-shaped hill
like a ruff, with its ruined castle perched all alone at the top.
This might be the prettiest town of all, with its sinuous streets
of stone houses cascading with flowers, and its artisans _ weavers,
potters, and makers of religious figurines called ``santons'' _ at
work behind amiably open doors. It also has a cozy little vineyard
hotel, the Domaine de Cabasse, and an excellent restaurant, La
Table du Comtat, with a superb view of the Dentelles.
</P>
<P>
   Crowning the circle of the Dentelles, Vaison-la-Romaine is, in
fact, not just one town but three: the ruined Gallo-Roman colony of
Vaslo Vocontiorum on the southern bank of the Ouveze river, the
fortified medieval village perched on the opposite hill, and the
lively modern Provencal city built squarely on top of the Roman
one.
</P>
<P>
   Vaison's sprawling archaeological site covers 37 acres,
including the ruins of vast, private villas larger than any found
at Pompeii. Divided into two principal sites, Puymin and Villasse,
the ruins lie a few feet below the current street level. The ``rue
des boutiques'' in the Villasse quarter was once arcaded and lined
with shops. Early in the morning, when the ruined street with its
broken columns is still empty of visitors, you can almost hear the
sounds of shutters being thrown open as shopkeepers prepared to
start the day.
</P>
<P>
   In the Puymin quarter, there's a large 1st-century theater and a
museum housing other treasures found on the site, including statues
of the emperor Hadrian and his empress, Sabine.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive Roman monument in Vaison is not a ruin at
all but the single-arch stone bridge across the Ouveze. In
September 1992, a flash flood devastated the city, sweeping away
everything in its path except the 2000-year-old bridge, still the
principal link to the medieval city on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the citizens of medieval Vaison moved across the
river to their citadel, however, they used foundations of a
Gallo-Roman temple to build their 11th-century Notre Dame de
Nazareth cathedral _ one of the most beautiful Romanesque churches
in Provence. The capitals of its thick-walled cloister are carved
with mythical figures and its galleries are filled with ancient,
marble fragments, like pieces of a puzzle that still won't fit.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the citadel, the cobbled streets climb past vine-covered
16th- and 17th-century houses with painted shutters. Tucked among
them is the delightful Hostellerie Le Beffroi, a small hotel near
the medieval belfry tower. At the top, the ruins of the
12th-century chateau offer a wonderful view of Mount Ventoux, the
big, bald, white rock that is Provence's tallest mountain.
</P>
<P>
   If you have time for side trips, take the road from Malaucene to
the windy summit of Mount Ventoux (the snow-capped peak is
sometimes closed in winter), or follow route D40 along the valley
beneath Ventoux's spectacular northern flank to the perched hamlet
of Brantes. There, you'll find a 12th-century chapel, a tiny
terrace for a cold glass of wine and an omelette and the small
workshop of Le Faience de Brantes, where Martine Gilles and Jaap
Weimar have been making some of Provence's loveliest ceramics for
more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
