<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1642 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-CAMPAIGN-VEEPS-NNS &LR;      09-05 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-VEEPS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN SERVES AS FOIL FOR GORE; BUSH, CHENEY FOLLOW TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Sept. 5, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By ROBERT COHEN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Joe Lieberman prepared to speak at a recent rally in downtown
St. Louis, he chuckled, tapped Democratic presidential candidate Al
Gore on the shoulder and pointed to a campaign placard that caught
his eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that sign, I love it: `Batman, Superman,
LIEBER-MAN,''' said the bemused senator from Connecticut as he drew
laughs from the crowd and then launched into his stump speech
promoting Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In the four weeks since he was named as Gore's running mate,
Lieberman has added a touch of humor and a lot more to what had
been an often sluggish presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore staffers believe Lieberman has helped put the Democratic
presidential nominee at ease, conveyed positive aspects of his
character and biography, promoted a message of ethics and values,
and managed to carry out effectively the traditional role of vice
presidential attack dog.
</P>
<P>
   The chemistry and result have been so good, say campaign
officials, that Lieberman is likely to have frequent double dates
with Gore rather than simply following the standard vice
presidential script of campaigning alone in secondary markets and
attending fund-raising dinners. The pair's 27-hour Labor Day
weekend campaign sprint through several states tested the double
date theory to the satisfaction of advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see Lieberman on his own, but you will probably see
the two campaign together along with their spouses more than has
been the case in past elections,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane has
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are good personal friends; they enjoy being together and
campaigning together. A central part of the campaign's focus and
message is how as a team they will work together to continue our
prosperity,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic between Texas Gov. George W. Bush and his GOP
running mate, Dick Cheney, is different. While the two have
appeared together and get along quite well, it is likely they will
follow the historic pattern of campaigning separately most of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Being together on the campaign trail can have drawbacks,
however. Sometimes Lieberman's visibility has prompted questions
about his past differences with Gore on key issues such as school
vouchers, affirmative action and Social Security privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman also campaigned together last week on the
West Coast, where Lieberman was deployed to denounce a new
Republican National Committee television commercial. That ad
attacks Gore's character and mocks his appearance at a fund-raising
event at a Buddhist temple four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than focusing on the serious issues before our country,
our opponents have hit the airwaves with paid political negative
personal attack ads, and that's wrong,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore was asked about the ad, he declined comment, saying
Lieberman ``addressed that on behalf of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials say the tag-team affair not only has given
Gore a warm-up partner, but has allowed him to take the high road
and to be seen as the leader instead of the understudy he has been
for eight years as Bill Clinton's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the message is that Gore is a strong leader -- a gap
he made up at the Democratic convention and with the bold and
historic selection of Lieberman,'' said Democratic pollster Mark
Mellman, referring to the fact that Lieberman is the first Jewish
candidate ever selected for a major party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having Lieberman with him reinforces the notion of Gore as No.
1 and as a leader,'' Mellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans believe that Cheney brings experience to the ticket
as a White House chief of staff, a congressman and a defense
secretary -- acting as a kind of wise man for Bush, whose political
experience has been as a governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are working closely together on important decisions and
will continue to do so,'' said Bush spokesman Ken Kisaius.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney is also dour and serious, offering little humor or
animation on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   It is Bush, in fact, who is more colorful and has an easygoing
</P>
<P>
   speaking style. If campaign audiences are going to get a laugh
or two at a rally, it will come on a line from Bush and not from
his running mate. Cheney, a native of Wyoming, admits as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of in keeping with my quiet, low-key demeanor,''
Cheney said last week after brief remarks to a Christian athletic
group. ``I come from the West, a man of few words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Cheney adding a lot as a campaigner,'' said George
Edwards, director of the Center for Presidential Studies at Texas
A&AMP;M University. ``There is not the same kind of synergy as Gore and
Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically when Bush and Cheney are together, Cheney offers brief
remarks that include a vow to restore ``dignity and honor'' to the
White House -- a reference to the scandals of the Clinton
administration. Bush, in turn, describes Cheney as an able leader
who will be ready to help govern.
</P>
<P>
   When he has campaigned alone, Cheney has tended to avoid
questions from the press. He has appeared at smaller events and
followed a standard and often brief script, talking about weighty
defense issues and moral values, among other topics.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, in contrast, draws laughs and chants of support from
his crowds when he is alone or with Gore, and has given numerous
interviews. He talks about his own background as the son of a
bakery truck driver and his days as a civil rights worker in the
1960s, a tack Cheney does not follow.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also repeatedly talks of Gore as ``a man of courage''
who served in Vietnam, and a family man and individual of ``moral
values.'' He sprinkles his speeches with biblical references. These
comments have drawn criticism from the Anti-Defamation League,
while Cheney has been dogged by questions about his
multimillion-dollar retirement buyout from the oil services firm he
headed.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The decision to campaign often with Lieberman rests solely with
Gore, who in 1992 had to fight Clinton staffers to remain on the
post-convention bus tour. He has told friends he should have been
there more often.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane, Gore's spokesman, said the Democratic nominee is not
worried that the campaign will limit its ability to reach a wider
audience that might otherwise come from splitting up the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this media age where there is a constant flow of
information, new cable networks and satellites, radio and the
Internet, campaigning together doesn't diminish our ability to hit
different markets,'' Lehane said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
