<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARDON, BUT DID YOU JUST HEAR A BURP IN THE RAIN FOREST? 

</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood may want to hold onto footage of President Clinton's
quick spin through Colombia last week. It could come in handy for a
movie someday.
</P>
<P>
   I envision a film _ let's give it a blockbuster title,
``Fungus!'' _ set in the Amazonian jungle. As the opening credits
appear, Clinton is shown defending his $1.3 billion aid package to
Colombia. ``This is not Vietnam,'' he thunders, ``neither is it
Yankee imperialism.'' Meanwhile, in the background, growing louder,
is the sound of munching.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the fungus and star of our show, Fusarium
oxysporum, a relatively unknown actor with a voracious appetite for
marijuana, cocaine, heroin and _ according to some critics _ just
about anything else that's leafy, green and unable to pull up roots
and flee.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, you may recall, Florida officials briefly pondered
testing this soil-borne fungus to combat the state's thriving
marijuana trade. Promoters touted it as a lean, mean weed-eating
machine, but skeptics pointed out _ accurately _ that precious
little is known about what else it may devour.
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics include David Struhs, director of the state
Department of Environmental Protection. He joined a chorus of
opponents, including a predictably off-key contingent of potheads,
in denouncing the plan. He said the fungus is ``capable of evolving
rapidly'' and may be ``difficult, if not impossible, to control.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the fungus could live for decades in the steamy soil of
Florida. We've seen other species of greenery, meek and agreeable
in their home climates, become mean and gluttonous down South.
Think kudzu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally do not like the idea of messing with Mother
Nature,'' Bill Graves, a biologist at the University of Florida
Research Center, told The New York Times last summer, shortly
before state officials shelved the idea. ``I believe that if this
fungus is unleashed for this kind of problem, it's going to create
its own problems. If it isn't executed effectively, it's going to
target and kill rare and endangered plants.''
</P>
<P>
   But the aid package delivered to Colombia last week includes _
surprise! _ $3 million to test the effectiveness of Fusarium
oxysporum on Andean coca bushes. U.S. drug czar Barry McCaffrey
hopes to demonstrate that the fungus is safe, then put it to work
wiping out Colombia's estimated 300,000 acres of coca.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Colombian officials are thrilled by the gift. ``This is
a living organism that will transform itself in order to survive,''
an unidentified Colombian government biologist told The Los Angeles
Times last week. ``Field tests are a risk for Colombia and the
entire Amazon region.''
</P>
<P>
   Others echo those fears. ``If it's bad for Florida, why is it
good for us?'' Colombian Sen. Rafael Orduz asked the Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   In its May issue, Mother Jones magazine pointed out that the
fungus wiped out a large crop of coca plants in Peru in the early
1990s but also killed banana and other food crops. Writers Sharon
Stevenson and Jeremy Bigwood raised alarms about the U.S.
government's supposedly reassuring claims that the fungus will
attack only plants in the genus Erythroxylum _ a genus that
includes more than 200 plants besides coca.
</P>
<P>
   Drug czar McCaffrey says more than 100 species of plants have
been tested with the fungus and none has been affected. But that's
only a tiny fraction of species contained in the Amazon jungle, the
second most biodiverse region in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics point to studies indicating that the fungus can be
toxic to humans under some circumstances. McCaffrey's office
contends that the toxins would affect only ``immune-suppressed
cancer patients whose defense levels were very low, making them
vulnerable to almost any microbe.'' Those folks, according to the
drug czar, could be kept out of the way during spraying.
</P>
<P>
   The cheering squad for the tests includes Rep. Bill McCollum, a
Florida Republican running for the U.S. Senate. He says the fungus
could be ``the silver bullet'' in the drug war.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's right, and Fusarium oxysporum will be a rare instance
in the history of government when the law of unintended
consequences is temporarily suspended. Maybe we really are looking
at a major turning point in the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, we ought to bring plenty of extra popcorn to the
show. The fungus may well appear on our doorsteps in mid-viewing _
with a bad case of the munchies.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
