<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Time was, encounters with snakes
were no big deal
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Chris Myott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strange how things that petrify me now, like snakes, were
natural occurrences when I was a child during the early 1940s in
rural North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   I remember how happy mama was when daddy decided we would move
to Mr. Daniel Keen's newly acquired farmland adjacent to Black
Creek in Johnston County.
</P>
<P>
   It had a brand new four-room bungalow with a well beside the
front porch and a giant sycamore tree for shade in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Keen was a gentleman farmer and owned a lot of land. He
would give us kids a nickel each when he came to visit.
</P>
<P>
   As the landlord, he furnished the seed and fertilizer for the
crops. We, as tenant farmers, supplied the work and received half
the money from the cash crops of tobacco and cotton. The food crops
and animals were ours.
</P>
<P>
   The black water of the creek, from which it got its name, was
good for fishing, especially catfish, and enriched the adjoining
farmland. But it was also a natural habitat for snakes.
</P>
<P>
   My first encounter with a snake was in the summer when we had
the windows up and the doors open.
</P>
<P>
   The windows had screens, but there were no screen doors on our
house.
</P>
<P>
   It was customary for us to take a nap for an hour or so after
the big noon meal.
</P>
<P>
   Mama would spread an old quilt on top of the clean bedspread and
whoever wanted to could lie crosswise on the bed to rest.
</P>
<P>
   I remember coming into the room one day and seeing a snake
coiled on the floor underneath my mother's legs that were dangling
over the side of the bed.
</P>
<P>
   All I remember after that was that someone killed the snake and
my mother was not bitten.
</P>
<P>
   The snake was hung on a tree limb so it would rain.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Sunday afternoon when all of us were lounging
under the giant sycamore tree on the platform where we prepared
tobacco during the week for the curing barn.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody looked up in the branches and saw a huge snake curled
around a limb directly over us.
</P>
<P>
   Guess he was looking for a cool spot, too.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy nonchalantly walked into the house, came out with his
double-barrel shotgun and unloaded the first barrel into the tree.
</P>
<P>
   It took a second barrel to bring the snake tumbling to the
platform.
</P>
<P>
   He was pretty shredded, but we hung what was left of him on a
tree limb so it would rain.
</P>
<P>
   My final encounter with a snake at the Black Creek house was a
day when I was looking for something to snack on.
</P>
<P>
   I knew mama kept leftovers like biscuits, fried meat and gravy,
and the syrup pot in the pie safe on the shelf above her clean
dishes. I undid the latch and flung open both doors at once.
</P>
<P>
   There, lying in Mama's dishes, stretched from one side of the
safe to the other, was the biggest black snake I had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   That was one time I knew fear! I still don't remember who killed
the snake.
</P>
<P>
   I was too young to worry about things then, but many times over
the years I have wondered how a snake that big could have gotten in
the pie safe.
</P>
<P>
   He met his fate just like the others, and we hung him on a limb
so it would rain.
</P>
<P>
   Just thinking about these experiences scares me more now than it
did when they actually happened.
</P>
<P>
   I remember running barefoot and barelegged in the fields and
woods, wading up and down the branch that ran into the creek, even
wading in the creek water when it overflowed its banks and flooded
the road.
</P>
<P>
   No one in my family was ever snake-bitten, nor showed the
slightest caution about walking barefoot outside at night.
</P>
<P>
   Seems like in those days that country folks thought no more of
snakes than they did about leaving their doors unlocked.
</P>
<P>
   Those were dream times.
</P>
<P>
   (Chris Myott lives in Eden, N.C.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
