<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1699 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SUVS-POLLUTION-HNS &LR;      09-05 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUVS-POLLUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SIERRA CLUB WANTS TO PUT BRAKES ON SUV CRAZE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a snappy six-page brochure, the Sierra Club
is taking aim at sport utility vehicles, depicting them as
gas-guzzling, carbon-dioxide-spewing vehicles that are hazardous,
not hip.
</P>
<P>
   Switching from driving an average new car to a
13-mile-per-gallon SUV for a year, the 108-year-old environmental
group says, would waste more energy than leaving a refrigerator
door open for six years, a bathroom light burning for 30 years, or
a color television turned on for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other disturbing factoids in the brochure, based on industry and
independent research, assert the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ SUVs emit 43 percent more global-warming pollutants _ 28
pounds of carbon dioxide per gallon of gas consumed _ and 47
percent more air pollution than the average car.
</P>
<P>
   _ Raising the fuel-economy standards for SUVs and other light
trucks to equal that of cars would save 1 million barrels of oil
per day.
</P>
<P>
   _ An SUV or a pickup is more than twice as likely as a car to
kill the driver of the other vehicle in a collision, and an SUV is
four times as likely to roll over in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the things we know how to do to reduce global warming,
the biggest single step we can take is making vehicles go farther
on a gallon of gas,'' said Daniel Becker, director of the Sierra
Club's $200,000-a-year Global Warming and Energy Program in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He said improving the standards would be a greater benefit than
reducing power plant emissions by switching to cleaner fuels and
renewable energy or by cutting energy demand with efficient
lighting, appliances, and heating and cooling systems in houses,
offices and factories.
</P>
<P>
   Although not all scientists agree that pollutants alone are
causing the Earth's temperature to warm, many researchers say auto
and factory emissions are largely to blame. Pollutant gases such as
carbon dioxide emissions trap heat, they say ultimately raising
temperatures that could have devastating effects on the polar ice
caps and lead to flooding in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Bergquist, a spokeswoman for the Alliance of Auto
Manufacturers, which represents Ford, General Motors,
DaimlerChrysler, and other automotive manufacturers, said the
industry is improving SUVs for all the people who want them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make SUVs cleaner and more fuel efficient. We
believe that competition is going to drive more progress,''
Bergquist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``SUVs meet the demands of a lot of farmers, ranchers,
tradespeople, families and small business owners. While some SUV
drivers might not use their vehicles to their full capability, they
like knowing they could have the passenger room, cargo room, towing
ability and performance when they wanted,'' Bergquist said.
</P>
<P>
   According to calculations in the Sierra Club brochure, the Ford
Excursion, at 13 mph, emits 134 tons of carbon dioxide over the
124,000-mile life of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with 96 tons from a Jeep Grand Cherokee at 18 mpg,
74 tons from a Ford Taurus at 23 mpg, 48 tons from a Honda Civic HX
at 36 mpg, and 27 tons from a Honda Insight at 65 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the barrage of statistics is the Sierra Club's political
message: SUVs are getting a free ride. Classified as light trucks
instead of cars, they do not have to meet the federal fuel-economy
standards of 27.5 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, when the standards were first adopted, light trucks,
mainly pickups, made up about 20 percent of the vehicle market.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 48 percent of the 16.9 million vehicles sold were
light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of working vehicles, the Sierra Club says, today's SUVs
are ``far more likely to haul lattes home from Starbucks than
lumber from the yard. Even though Detroit has technology that could
make them both cleaner and safer, SUVs and other light trucks are
still held to low environmental standards, roll over more than cars
and pose greater danger to other vehicles than cars do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
