<HEADER>
A1719 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-05 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRACISCO BAY AREA HAS CHANGED BY A FACTOR OF FIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last week I celebrated my 15th anniversary at
the San Francisco Examiner. Well, ``celebrated'' is the wrong word,
for obvious reasons. There won't be any 16th anniversary at the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   I just popped a can of Bud in my 1,100-square-foot shack that's
now worth almost a million bucks on paper, and thought about how
much the Bay Area has changed.
</P>
<P>
   It's changed by a factor of five.
</P>
<P>
   That's rent times five, rudeness times five, politically correct
idiocy times five, and traffic times five. And there are five
parking spaces left somewhere in San Francisco and 500,000 drivers
looking for them.
</P>
<P>
   But I bought in when homes were ridiculously overpriced at
$200,000, and I've got a parking space, which I'm opening to bids
on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago was the 21st anniversary of the publication of my
first story at the old Palo Alto paper, and the 23rd anniversary of
my arrival in the Bay Area as a slacker of a grad student at
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Palo Alto was a sleepy college town with a couple of beer joints
that pumped out pitchers of old-fashioned macrobrews served up with
peanuts instead of goat-cheese pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Now Palo Alto is the exact geographic center of the universe, a
gold hole that sucks BMWs, Mercedes-Benzes and oversize homes and
egos into it.
</P>
<P>
   That first newspaper story of mine in 1979 was about the first
Gilroy Garlic Festival, which drew a few hundred people, many of
whom thought that eating garlic was very daring.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays having a steak is daring.
</P>
<P>
   Man, has the Bay Area distorted my mind, wallet and palate.
</P>
<P>
   When I was in San Diego two weeks ago, I went to Black Angus
steak house (because I love the ads). I felt like an anthropologist
studying an exotic tribe that enjoys foodstuffs with earthy names
like ``ranch'' and ``mud pie,'' and shamelessly enjoys sides of
recently slaughtered salad or cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Dining in the Bay Area must seem like an episode of ``Survivor''
to those Southern California suburbanites. We enter restaurants
that aren't even tried and tested chains, and we don't even blink
when we order braised skate, free-range beef cheeks and cuisine
made by hot and cold fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Well, we enter restaurants if they'll let us in. The real game
of ``Survivor'' in the Bay Area is trying to get a table for two at
a highly rated restaurant before the chef goes to another place.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful job is not mayor, but reservationist, a person
who speaks the dread words, ``We can get you in at 5:30 or 9:45.''
That's on a Tuesday, three months after the chef has moved on.
</P>
<P>
   We're so twisted we like restaurants that refuse to feed us. I
don't know why people practice bulimia when all they have to do is
try to get a reservation at the French Laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Think of how the language has changed in the Bay Area. Of
course, there are more of the world's natural languages spoken here
as the population has changed, but the artificial and vernacular
languages have changed even more.
</P>
<P>
   We don't recoil in disgust at people talking loudly in public
about downloading, inputting, hacking and spam. We put ``e-`` in
front of everything the way hippies once started everything with
``Man.'' Companies end with ``dot-com'' as predictably as a night
in a bar once ended with ``My place or yours?''
</P>
<P>
   Sex has gotten weird. It hardly exists, at least as far as I
know, and the sex that exists is safe.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area is where people once came to be free. Now they come
here to be free of sex talk in the workplace, free of smoke and
alcohol, free to obsessively exercise, free to tell strangers not
to eat meat or wear fur and free to flip people off in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   All this freedom is getting pretty tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   How did we ever live without cell phones or personal computers?
Somehow most of us did 15 or 20 years ago, and we lived pretty
well.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny, but it seems the more we communicate, the less
community we have. A stranger speaks behind you, and you turn to
talk but find he's talking to someone else on a cell phone. Were
you crazy, thinking a stranger in the Bay Area would strike up a
conversation?
</P>
<P>
   We need Nokias and modems as go-betweens.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area has changed immensely as people have moved here
from Asia and Latin America, and money has moved here from
everywhere. But there have been some less welcome changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were people ever polite here?'' asks a young friend who moved
here not long ago from a famously rude city back East.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't believe it when I said they were. No car horns?
Unbelievable. No middle-finger salutes? Couldn't be. People who
treat others with respect unless those others were Dodger fans? No
way.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way it was, and you even could get a table at
Chez Panisse.
</P>
<P>
   We've always been lucky to live here. Now we're lucky if we can
survive here. Let's pop a cold one to luck and next month's
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
