<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-MOTORCADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOTORCADE MEMORY
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies KENNEDY-RESEARCHER)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Although Mary Ferrell was not in Dealey Plaza when
President Kennedy was slain, her car was.
</P>
<P>
   In a minor footnote to history, she explains that, at the time,
her husband, Buck, worked for Eagle Lincoln-Mercury, the auto
dealer that furnished cars for the presidential motorcade. In
October 1963, her husband had bought her a new 1964 station wagon,
a Mercury Colony Park. On Nov. 22, 1963, the car was in the shop
for a 2,000-mile checkup.
</P>
<P>
   Buck called her at the lawyer's office where she worked and,
says Ferrell, there was this exchange:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother, could I loan your car to this motorcade? They've
stripped us. We don't have anything else we can loan them. ... It's
out of the shop and it's in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to drive it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. Probably the DPS.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When will I get it back?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, when they're through with the motorcade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they going to put gas back in it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, hell. Forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope, go ahead, you can have it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' she adds, referring to film shot that day, ``the station
wagon you see with the doors open and the men jumping out of it and
running up the grassy knoll? That's my car!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Cochran
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
