   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MEDICARE (Allentown, Pa.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush
unveils a health care plan, including a requirement that
Medicare-funded insurance plans include prescription drug coverage.
By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-HEALTH (Washington) _ The Democratic National
Committee trots out new television advertisements bashing Texas
Gov. George W. Bush on health care, using as a club provided by a
recent federal court order to improve care for poor children's care
in Texas. By MICHAEL HEDGES.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House and Senate return this week to
tackle spending legislation in a four- or five-week session more
akin to rugby than lawmaking as Republicans and Democrats scrum for
position in the November elections. Among the issues that may be
dealt with this week: An effort to override President Clinton's
veto of the estate tax repeal. By KAREN MASTERSON.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HIGH-TECH (Washington) _ With a month left before
Congress adjourns, high-tech industry leaders urge lawmakers to
move quickly on trade, tax and immigration legislation before
adjourning for the final campaign push. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   UN-SUMMIT (Washington) _ As President Clinton departs for the
summit of United Nations leaders in New York, White House officials
are saying this is a crucial week in make progress toward a Middle
East peace deal. President Clinton plans meetings with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in hopes
of spurring negotiations. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ NASA prepares for a
scheduled launch Friday of the Atlantis on a mission to the
international space station. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Some political scientists are
predicting Al Gore will win the presidential race on the basis of
mathematical formulas alone. What a hoot. Politics is not a
science, but if it were, it would be an inexact one determined not
by numbers-crunching but by the vagaries of human nature. Who could
predict, for instance, that George W. Bush would be caught making a
crude remark, and who knows how the public will react to that? By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
