<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SF-ASIAN-CENSUS-HNS &LR;      09-05 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-ASIAN-CENSUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     S.F. TO BECOME SECOND U.S. CITY WHERE ASIANS OUTNUMBER WHITES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIN McCORMICK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sometime this year, according to trends
projected in a survey by the U.S. Census Bureau, San Francisco will
join Honolulu as the nation's only major cities where Asians
outnumber whites.
</P>
<P>
   While census estimates released this week indicate that
so-called ``minorities'' have now become the majority in
California, San Francisco is way ahead of the trend.
</P>
<P>
   The city's white population dropped below the 50 percent mark in
the early 1990s, and starting this year, the survey indicates,
whites will no longer even make up the largest racial group in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The census study, which questioned one of every 33 San Francisco
households, found that, as of 1999, Asians and whites each made up
36 percent of the city's population. And the Asian population is
growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become the mainstream,'' said Rose Pak, who heads the
San Francisco Chinese Chamber of Commerce. ``We have suspected this
was happening for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while Asians are set to be the largest racial group in San
Francisco, they lag far behind when it comes to political clout,
according to Pak and other community leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The census survey estimated that people who considered
themselves ``white only'' accounted for only a little more than a
third of the city's population in 1999, but they still make up
about 72 percent of the voters, according to David Lee of the
nonprofit Chinese-American Voter Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who has done polls and surveys of the election rolls to
find out who is voting in San Francisco, calculates that about only
18 percent of voters are Asian although the census survey found
that their population was equal to _ and on its way to surpassing _
that of whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of population, (San Francisco) has a majority of
minorities,'' he said. ``But in terms of voters, it's
overwhelmingly white.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco State University political scientist Rich DeLeon
said citizenship issues and cultural barriers might keep San
Francisco's Asian community from being able to fully exercise its
political voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the sleeping giant has awakened,'' he said. ``That
may be true, but it's not out of bed yet. Translating those big
(population) numbers into political clout can be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The census bureau's 1999 American Community Survey provides a
preview of the 2000 census, which won't be tabulated until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   It was tested last year in 21 places around the United States,
including San Francisco, as an annual study that could eventually
replace the census long form.
</P>
<P>
   The survey estimated that in 1999 the number of people in San
Francisco who considered themselves to be either fully or partly
Asian was virtually equal to those who considered themselves to be
``white only'' _ without Hispanic or mixed-race backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   And the Asian population in San Francisco has been growing
steadily every year, with an influx of new immigrants and a large
number of births. Meanwhile, the white population shrank in the
1990s and now is believed to be stable.
</P>
<P>
   So Asians are on track to quickly outnumber whites for the first
time, demographers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian population is growing rapidly,'' said DeLeon, who
noted that if Pacific Islanders are counted, people with Asian
heritage already composed the largest group in San Francisco. ``As
we speak, the Asian-Pacific Islander population has outnumbered the
white population in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco schools have been noticing this trend for a
long time. Asian and Pacific Islanders make up 42 percent of the
district's student enrollment, while whites constitute only 12
percent, according to data from the California Department of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   Asians in San Francisco are also having more children. Last
year, there were 2,800 children born to Asian-Pacific Islander
families in San Francisco and 2,600 born to whites, according to
state records.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, the Chinese population has become the middle class
of San Francisco,'' said Lee, a Chinese American raised in San
Francisco. ``They're the ones having children. They're getting
together to buy houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lee and other community leaders lament Asians' relative lack
of political power. Lee said some new immigrants cannot vote
because they are not U.S. citizens, but many qualified voters in
the Asian community simply choose not to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many, there is a cultural barrier to voter
participation,'' he said. ``In some countries, like China, citizens
were actively discouraged from voting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
