<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1800 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ANTHEM-BOS &LR;      09-05 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ANTHEM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTHEM LEAVES RUSSIAN ATHLETES AT A LOSS FOR WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Oh, say, can't you sing the Russian national anthem?
</P>
<P>
   That question could come to mind at the sight of tight-lipped
Russian athletes on the winner's pedestal at the upcoming Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Russian athletes hope to win more than 30 golds in Sydney. But,
as they are painfully aware, they cannot sing along to Mikhail
Glinka's ``Patriotic Song,'' because there are no words.
</P>
<P>
   And not because no one has tried to write them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nothing quite so eloquently captures post-Communist
Russia's struggle to find an identity as the inability to find
words to go with Glinka's 1833 composition, which former president
Boris N. Yeltsin decreed the national anthem after the collapse of
the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, composers, poets, blue-ribbon commissions, and even
a soccer coach have submitted a total of 500 proposed texts, but no
one has been able to agree on a final version. Glinka's music has
been criticized by specialists who say it is impossible to
remember, hard to write words for, and possibly not Glinka at all,
but a rip-off of a 17th-century Polish Catholic hymn. Kremlin
musicologists are investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament, which until recently was dominated by Communists,
has refused to approve even Glinka's music, just as it rejected the
other Czarist-era symbols Yeltsin chose for the new Russia _ the
white, blue, and red tricolor as Russia's flag and the
double-headed golden eagle to replace the Soviet hammer and sickle
as the state symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Parliament has given preliminary approval for the
Soviet hymn commissioned by Josef Stalin in 1943, popularly known
by its opening phrase, ``Indivisible Union'' _ with new words, of
course, that someone would have to write.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Russia's Olympic athletes with the same wordless
anthem for the Sydney games that the winners of 26 gold medals had
to hum in Atlanta. This is only marginally better than standing on
the pedestal listening tight-lipped to Beethoven, which gold
medalists from former Soviet countries did in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're up there on the pedestal, you're full of
emotion,'' said runner Natalya Nazarova, a member of Russia's
four-by-400 relay team, which has gold-medal ambitions. ``If we had
words to sing, that would be good.''
</P>
<P>
   To speed the process up, players of the Spartak soccer club,
some of whom also play on Russia's national team, in July sent
President Vladimir Putin a letter asking him to give them something
inspiring to sing before international matches. The team told Putin
their coach had suggested words for the work.
</P>
<P>
   But the request went unanswered, partly because this country has
so many more important things to do, but also because responsibilty
for writing words to the anthem seems to have been lost in the
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   The State Duma, the lower house of parliament, is now dominated
by a pro-Putin party, one of whose leaders is wrestler Alexander
Karelin, who is a favorite to win gold in Sydney, and who
presumably would like to have something to sing when he does. But
an aide said Karelin was too busy training to worry about anthems
now. Another Duma spokesman said it was the government's business
to propose words.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Rozhkov, chairman of Russia's state committee on sports,
said it was a matter for the Culture Ministry. A Culture Ministry
spokesman passed the buck on to Putin's administration. And there,
no one can find the person who is responsible for anthem-writing.
</P>
<P>
   Various unconfirmed press reports, meanwhile, have indicated
that Putin also prefers giving new words to the old, Soviet
national anthem. Rozhkov thinks that would be a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all remember the Soviet anthem of course,'' he told
reporters last week. ``We remember the feeling, and we miss it. If
some words were apprvoed we would all be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   But who can find the proper words, if neither Yevgeny
Yevtushenko, one of Russia's best-known poets, nor a commission
that includes the author of ``Indivisible Union,'' have been able
to?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that question misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   The words to national anthems, as Americans know, are not
necessarily written by a culture's greatest poets. Nor do they need
to convey only universal ideals shared by all a nation's citizens
at all times _ surely, not everyone in France is always thinking
about ways to fill the furrows of our fields with the impure blood
of invaders.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have to somehow encapsule some event, some feeling,
some sense of nationhood, something patriots can rally around for
generations to come. And that has been missing in Russia the past
nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that could become such an event has been overshadowed
by something worse. Take the August, 1991 coup attempt by Soviet
hardliners, which ended in a victory for Yeltsin, who had made a
brave stand in the Russian parliament building. Down came the red
banner of the Soviet Union, up went the Russian tricolor, as the
symbol of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, Yeltsin sent tanks to the same parliament
building to blast away at legislators who were resisting his
(unconstitutional) order to disband. What could anyone write about
that?
</P>
<P>
   Any progress towards turning the old Soviet system into a sleak,
new market has been overshadowed by the fact that most of the
country is poorer, and the few people who have become really rich
have preferred offshore havens to investing at home.
</P>
<P>
   And while the perceived success of last year's offensive against
separatists in Chechnya seemed to many Russians a turning point,
that enthusiasm has dimmed as the second campaign against the
rebels has turned into the same costly quagmire that the 1994-1996
war was.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials say, why even bother, when times are so hard? And
anyway, what is so important about words?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not easy to come up with the words of the national
anthem,'' said Georgy Vilinbakh, chairman of Russia's State Herald
Council, said in an interview published here last week. ``The main
thing is not the words, but the music. . . . There's nothing
terrible about a government with no words in its national anthem.''
</P>
<P>
   How true. Take Spain, a perfectly stable, Western democracy,
whose national anthem has no words.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only Russia could decide about the authenticity of that
Glinka.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1804 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     09-05 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING STOCK OF MOUNT CARMEL, SEVEN YEARS AFTER THE TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM JONES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a recent visit to Waco, I decided to drive by Mount
Carmel, the place where David Koresh and about 80 of his Branch
Davidian followers died in their flaming compound seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The catastrophe that unfolded before our eyes on television
intruded on our minds again this summer when special counsel John
C. Danforth issued a preliminary report of an investigation saying
that the Davidians themselves, not the federal government, set the
fire that destroyed the sprawling makeshift religious complex.
</P>
<P>
   Assigning blame for the fire, of course, does not reduce the
magnitude of the tragedy in which innocent children perished,
supposedly in the name of religion. Now the 77 acres, which
surviving Branch Davidians still see as holy ground, are a place of
curiosity. And also a shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it remains a battleground of sorts. Three different groups
of Davidians are vying for the rights to the property.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty granite markers with names of all known to have died in
the fire are near the property's center. Each one is marked by a
flowering crape myrtle. One of the markers reads ``David Koresh _
April 19, 1993 _ Age 33.''
</P>
<P>
   A handsome new Branch Davidian church built by volunteers and
opened in April now stands near the memorials to the dead. A
granite plaque in front of the church thanks ``benefactors who have
faithfully answered the quiet call to rebuild upon the ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   An eerie stagnant lake on the land symbolized to me the dark
tragedy that unfolded there. Also, there are two burnt-out buses,
one of Koresh's scorched motorcycles and a green Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   Near the church is a granite stone memorializing four federal
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms officers who were killed as they
tried to arrest Koresh at the Branch Davidian compound on Feb. 28,
1993. Six Davidians also died that day.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived on the Branch Davidian Sabbath, and a church service
led by those who still see Koresh as an earthly messiah was going
on in a mobile home near the entrance. About five cars were parked
outside. I didn't intrude.
</P>
<P>
   That group is led by Clive Doyle, a survivor of the fire, his
mother, Edna Doyle, and Sheila Martin.
</P>
<P>
   A rival Davidian, Amo Bishop Roden, welcomed visitors to the
property from a spot near the entrance as she has done for years.
Roden claims the right to the property because she was married, by
contract she says, to the late George Roden, whose parents, Lois
and Ben Roden, followed teachings of V.T. Houteff and created the
group known as Branch Davidians in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   She heartily disagrees with those who believe Koresh was a
prophet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still see David Koresh as a holy man of God,'' she said.
``If they are sincere, I think they are misguided. I thought he was
a very bad man.''
</P>
<P>
   Another group claiming the right to the property is led by
Charlie Pace, who also is not a follower of Koresh, but who is an
outspoken opponent to Amo Bishop Roden's assertions.
</P>
<P>
   Pace, a construction worker, lives in a mobile home on the east
end of Mount Carmel. He was a part of the Branch Davidians during
the Roden era. But his loyalty extends to Lois and Ben Roden, the
early leaders of the Branch Davidians. He claims that their son,
George Roden, deserted the movement.
</P>
<P>
   All three groups consider the property hallowed ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is holy ground, made even holier by what happened here,''
said Pace.
</P>
<P>
   Pace said he believes Koresh was a false prophet. But he
believes he had an important role in Bible prophecy and that his
life and death were predicted by Scriptures. He says Koresh and his
followers' violent end is referred to in Ezekiel 9:1-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Scripture declares: ``Cause them that have charge over the
city to draw near, even every man with a destroying weapon in his
hand. And, behold, six men came from the way of the higher gate,
which lieth toward the north, and every man with a slaughter weapon
in his hand. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Pace had held his own separate Sabbath Day worship
service at Mount Carmel. His group has its own church in a concrete
block building marked with a sign, ``The Branch. Congregation of
the Lord (YHVH) Our Righteousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Pace, Amo Roden, the Doyles, Sheila Martin and other Branch
Davidians around the world disagree on many things. But all have
complicated end-of-the-world theology. All believe that God will
someday return and establish the kingdom of heaven on earth.
</P>
<P>
   And many believe that a peaceful prairie in the heart of Central
Texas _ the holy ground of Mount Carmel _ will be the center of
that heavenly kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
