<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMSTRONG-BOXEDCDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIS THE FIRST: BOXED SET REMINDS JAZZ FANS WHY ARMSTRONG WAS
KING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louis Armstrong is defined in the memories of many by two songs
that really don't represent his talents all that well.
</P>
<P>
   Born 100 years ago this past July 4 (or so the story goes; his
birthday has also been listed as Aug. 4, 1901), Armstrong always
will be linked in the public consciousness to two novelty songs,
``What a Wonderful World'' and ``Hello Dolly,'' done when he was
far past his prime.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to such sentimental numbers, Armstrong was widely _ and
somewhat accurately _ seen in his later years as a gravel-voiced
relic of a previous age, his signature New Orleans swing/Dixieland
sound long before supplanted by everyone from Charlie Parker to
Miles Davis to John Coltrane. His mugging and smiling were almost
embarrassing, maybe even a bit Uncle Tomish, to youngbloods who had
embraced the cool _ almost cold _ elegance personified by Davis
turning his back on his audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was simply the old man with the hanky and the big
smile and the quaint sound. Dixieland? Who the heck still listened
to Dixieland?
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine years after his death, the world does. The music of
Louis Armstrong is providing one of the best boxed sets of the
year, and one of the very best ever for fans of jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The four-CD, 89-cut ``The Complete Hot Five and Hot Seven
Recordings'' (Sony//Columbia, $54.97) brings together all of the
seminal recordings Armstrong and his bands cut between 1925 and
1929 in a well-annotated package that includes a wealth of
information and vintage photos.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because everything old becomes new again. Maybe it's
because we've been primed for this set by fellow New Orleans native
Wynton Marsalis, who's championed older forms of jazz. Whatever the
case, this music sounds as fun, sweet-natured and marvelous now as
it did back in the day when Armstrong and his band were _ along
with Duke Ellington _ defining jazz in its first great era.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans always has been a great melting pot of sounds and
cultures, and thus right from the start Armstrong's music was an
inventive stew of the Dixieland and blues that were often heard in
the city's many rough-and-tumble dance halls.
</P>
<P>
   And Armstrong was highly adept at transferring the feel of a
live performance to wax. He'd call out to different musicians
before their solos, do give-and-take vocals with band members,
throw in asides such as ``Aw, hear me talkin' to ya!,'' and mix
funny song-stories such as ``Sugar Foot Strut'' or sentimental
ballads alongside instrumental showcases such as ``West End
Blues.'' He was, first and foremost, an entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, like Ellington, Armstrong understood (and this is
surprisingly rare) that a bandleader/lead singer can only look
better when he surrounds himself with truly great players. And you
just don't get any better than those who would earn their
reputations in his band, among them trombonist Kid Ory and
clarinetist Johnny Dodds.
</P>
<P>
   His band would, at different times, include pianist Earl
``Fatha'' Hines, banjoist Johnny St. Cyr,
arranger/multi-instrumentalist/songwriter Don Redman, drummer
Warren ``Baby'' Dodds, trombonist Jack Teagarden and guitarists
Eddie Lang and Lonnie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   A finer collection of American musicians in the 1920s is
impossible to imagine _ and that includes Ellington's band, which
boasted players such as Cootie Williams and Johnny Hodges.
</P>
<P>
   Taken altogether, then, Armstrong's work of this period was as
influential as Duke's, as anybody's. Armstrong's vocal style easily
can be heard in the recordings of both blueswoman supreme Bessie
Smith (with whom he recorded) and jazz legend Ella Fitzgerald, and
his inventive trumpet solos are a virtual textbook of unexpected
triplets, economy and liveliness.
</P>
<P>
   Here we had the complete package: A man of astonishing
instrumental finesse _ check his introduction to ``West End Blues''
_ who could make music both ribald and achingly sentimental, all in
the same breath. His blues, as heard on ``St. James Infirmary,''
had depth. His ballads, such as ``I Can't Give You Anything But
Love,'' are lovely. His funny, or novelty, songs were sometimes a
bit ribald but never dirty, and his band's instrumental attack was
second to none.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his strengths, Armstrong was not particularly adept
at change. His music remained resolutely stuck in the '20s, and in
his later years would suffer for it. He kept busy to the end,
recording with big bands and smaller groups, but essentially he was
recycling. ``Dolly'' and ``World'' were of a piece with the vocal
numbers he'd done way back when, except not as good.
</P>
<P>
   Do yourself a favor. Forget that stuff. Go back to his golden
days, when he and his bands were defining jazz in its formative
stages. What you'll find is a treasure trove. Armstrong was dubbed
``King Louis'' because he was an absolute titan of his era. As this
box set shows, he might still hold the title now.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
