<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL SURVIVOR CHALLENGES AREN'T TAPED FOR TV
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I watched only one episode of ``Survivor,'' the much-ballyhooed
television series about a bunch a people stranded on a desert
island for a month, or however long they were there. I really don't
even care enough to look it up.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I felt compelled to watch the final episode when I
stopped to get my morning cup of coffee at the local convenience
store. That's when I noticed that the program had managed to make
the headlines of the three daily newspapers on the stand by the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Gosh, I thought, this is really big stuff. I guess I need to
tune in and see what all the hoopla is about.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, I understood the basic objective.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows I had seen enough commercials, previews and
articles about it. But the idea of taking a bunch of yuppies to an
island and following them around with cameras while they
back-stabbed each other with piercing words just didn't appeal to
me. I have better stories than that in my diary.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been different if they had mounted a bunch of
cameras in the trees and actually just left the people there until
they surrendered to the elements, one by one, begging to be
rescued.
</P>
<P>
   However, while I found the final episode quite entertaining, it
was hardly a contest to determine the survival of the fittest mind
and body. The craftiest mind? Perhaps. Darwinism in the jungle?
Definitely not.
</P>
<P>
   So in the ensuing week, I have been trying to think of a contest
that would really and truly test the contestants' personal
preservation skills. How about this:
</P>
<P>
   Let's find a young boy in elementary school, say the fourth or
fifth grade. Why don't we give him an unwed mother, three younger
siblings and an unknown father? Have him live in the inner city,
surrounded by gangs and drugs. Send him to a school where he has to
share textbooks because there aren't enough to go around. Even more
challenging, what if there aren't enough teachers, so the
classrooms are crowded? Let's put up a nice government-funded
recreation center in the neighborhood, even though walking down the
street in this community is as safe as walking in a mine field.
</P>
<P>
   The objective for our young contestant is to become an
investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   First, he has to graduate from high school without becoming a
member of a gang or getting killed by a stray bullet. As he grows,
he also has to control his raging hormones so he doesn't become a
teen-aged parent like so many of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides going to school, he has to work to help his mother
support the family because her minimum wage job covers only half of
their bills. The temptation to deal drugs for easy money is strong,
but our young contestant has to resist because if he succumbs, he
loses the game.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, against insurmountable odds and with few, if any, role
models, this little boy has to get accepted into college and earn a
degree while working a full-time job. You know his grants or
scholarship won't cover all his expenses, and he's still got his
mother and siblings to think about.
</P>
<P>
   Now that, my friend, is a true test for a survivor. But who
would want to watch such a difficult struggle on prime-time
television? No, I dare say that this program would be canceled
early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this scenario is being continuously played out on stages
across America whether we're watching or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' was entertainment: part comedy, part drama and part
mystery. The lives of this boy and so many like him are a tragedy.
The chances of anyone not surviving on that island were extremely
slim.
</P>
<P>
   As slim as the chances of this boy becoming an investment
banker, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a dentist, TV talk-show host and
author in Arlington, Texas. Her latest book, ``Mom, Are We There
Yet?,'' is a collection of her favorite columns. Contact her online
at www.moeanderson.com, or call (817) 548-5564. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
