<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WINE COUNTRY MAKES QUICK RECOVERY AFTER QUAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNY STRASBURG and ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ The earthquake that struck Northern California's
famed Wine Country last weekend could not have happened at a more
hectic, vulnerable time.
</P>
<P>
   Crowded with Labor Day tourists and migrant farm workers, its
restaurants and spas booked and fermenting tanks filling up with
the spoils of harvest, the wine-saturated Napa Valley landscape was
ripe for chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Still, tourists seemed to stick to their plans, despite initial
fears from Sunday's earthquake and the threat of aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
   For the region's celebrated vintners, the damage could have been
much worse: Some awoke to the early-morning tremors and imagined
broken glass, shattered oak barrels and millions of dollars of wine
soaking their cellar and tasting-room floors.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they arrived at their wineries to find a few broken
glasses here, a toppled bottle of Sauvignon there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost a total of $36. I'm very lucky. Very lucky,'' said Andy
Gridley, sales manager at the Napa Wine Co., where 65 Napa wineries
make their wine.
</P>
<P>
   Gridley lives on Howell Mountain, about 10 miles north of the
winery, and slept through the quake. When he heard about it in the
morning, he immediately pictured his tasting room and its 2,700
racked bottles as a mess of broken glass and wasted liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Only two bottles of wine broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-six bucks,'' Gridley sighed. ``I envisioned it could be
thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frank-Rombauer Larkmead Cellars in Calistoga, which in June
lost an estimated 85,000 cases of wine in a devastating fire,
suffered no earthquake damage, said Alan Cannon, a retail salesman.
Neither did the company's other sites in St. Helena and Napa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it woke a few of us up; that was it,'' Cannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar relief settled upon Domaine Chandon Winery, south of
Yountville and much closer to the epicenter of the 5.2-magnitude
quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in harvest. All our tanks are full with fermenting wine,
and nothing broke,'' Susan Azevedo, an exhausted but relieved wine
educator, marveled Sunday afternoon as visitors crowded the Domaine
Chandon tasting room, creating just the kind of scene expected on
Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists pour about $650 million into the Napa Valley every
year, according to the Napa Valley Conference and Visitors Bureau.
Labor Day weekend is one of the busiest of the year, when the
aromas of harvest attract thousands of visitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
