<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CALIF-ALMONDS-2TAKES-     09-05 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ALMONDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENDING THE MARZIPAN TREES 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: recipes at end of article) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HURON, Calif. _ They are among the oldest cultivated foods on
earth, the stuff of Greek myths, a prized ingredient of the
pharaohs' breads, a staple of Biblical feasts. They are believed to
have originated in China and Central Asia, and their pinkish white
blossoms and graceful branches call to mind the cherry trees whose
botanical family they share. Transported to the Mediterranean by
the traders of the Silk Road, they have been an important commodity
since the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the flat, hot, rich farmlands of California's
Central Valley, almonds are nothing so much as big business. The
state's 6,000 growers produce more than 600 million pounds a year,
more than 70 percent of the world's supply and virtually 100
percent of domestic production. Almonds far outpace wine, oranges,
apples and raisins as the United States' top horticultural export,
worth close to $800 million annually. Eat marzipan in Germany or
almonds salted in the shell like ballpark peanuts in India or
China, and odds are high the nuts came from California.
</P>
<P>
   These late summer weeks are crunch time in the long endless
groves. The fruit has ripened, its outer gray-greenish hull has
cracked open to reveal a pale, crackly perforated inner shell,
inside which a jewel is nestled: the moistly crunchy, brown-skinned
nut itself. The harvest, from early August to Halloween, is a
7-day-a-week, 24-hour-a-day affair, as growers rush to get their
crop hulled and shelled, packed and shipped before the fall rains
come and make the groves a soggy mess.
</P>
<P>
   The groves are vast, more like factories than farms, stretching
up the spine of the state for 400 miles. Though the landscape is
broken by the occasional cottonwood tree, it is not a place of
roadside stands. Here the tomatoes lie in great heaps waiting to be
processed into paste, and cotton grows in endless seas. There are
no mom-and-pop shops with bags of almonds, the way one finds paper
sacks of boiled peanuts in Georgia. Even a family farm, like Chris
Woolf's, is an industrial sort of operation. The tidy farm
lunchroom, a small building with whitewashed walls, Mexican tile
floors and Fiestaware plates, does not feature almonds on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Time was, workers walked the groves tapping trees with tall
poles to shake the fruit to the ground. Now an armada of
diesel-powered mechanical shaking machines (one leading model is
the ``Shock Wave Shaker'') grip trees with rubber-coated hydraulic
pincers, creating custom-made mini-earthquakes of trembling trunks
and branches and hailstorms of falling nuts up and down the orchard
rows.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you compare that to?'' asked Stacey Kollmeyer, the
communications manager of the Almond Board of California and a
third-generation almond hand. The ground rumbled and a tornado of
dust rose from a shaking Sonora almond tree on the Woolfs' farm
here the other day. ``It's like the tree's being electrocuted.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolf, 38, is the very model of a modern major almond grower,
producing something on the order of 6 million pounds of nut meat a
year on a couple of thousand acres of family owned and leased land
about an hour southwest of Fresno, just off Interstate 5. His
family has been farming almonds (and cotton, tomatoes, pistachios,
garlic, onions and oranges) since 1973, and now has a full,
vertically integrated operation, starting with an almond nursery of
some 300,000 seedlings and ending with a processing plant (owned in
partnership with the Harris cattle ranching family) that hulls,
shells and ships about 20 million pounds a year, most of it for
direct overseas export.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so important not to have a breakdown at this time of
year,'' Woolf said as he checked in with Jose Jimenez, a worker
operating a new $95,000 shaker, one of six in the Woolf family
fleet, from inside its compact, air-conditioned cab.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the University of California at Berkeley, with a
degree in history, Woolf also has an M.B.A. in agribusiness from
the University of Santa Clara, and is what's known in the trade as
a handler, one of about 100 growers officially responsible for
recording the weight and quality of growers' almonds, collecting
assessments for the Almond Board; his farm also serves as a site
where the U.S. Department of Agriculture inspectors assess the
crop. He is also in the middle of a one-year term as chairman of
the Almond Board, created in 1950 to help market almonds.
</P>
<P>
   As such, Woolf is squarely astride what has amounted to an
explosion in the California almond crop. Almonds were first brought
to the state in the 18th century, by the Franciscan padres who
founded the chain of coastal missions, but the trees suffered in
the misty, moist conditions near the Pacific, and only a hundred
later were successfully planted inland.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Valley has been prime almond terrain for most of the
20th century, but the crop has quadrupled over the last 30 years as
efficient production, ideal growing conditions, economies of scale
and growing demand for almonds in everything from breakfast cereal
to specialty oils have given the state a virtual corner on the
world market, with countries like Spain, Italy and Greece together
producing not even a third of California's yield.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Gingrass, the chef at Hawthorne Lane in San Francisco, uses
almonds year-round, and in ways that are not always obvious. In a
risotto with dried red chilies and goat cheese, she chops up
almonds and cooks them with the rice so they attain a similar
texture as the grains and, she added, they round out the flavor and
heat of the chilies. She also uses them to thicken chicken soup,
pureeing the almonds with the broth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hazelnuts are so strong, pine nuts are unpredictable _ you
don't know if you're going to get a bad one, and they're really
fatty,'' she said. ``Almonds are subtle.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almonds, long touted in culinary lore as a hedge against
intoxication if eaten with wine, have also benefited from a recent
wave of nutritional and dietary revisionism. Like all nuts, they
are high in fat, but mostly in mono-unsaturated fat, the kind that
predominates in canola and olive oils and avocados, and is
celebrated for its ability to lower harmful cholesterol. Several
current diets, like the Zone, by Barry Sears, celebrate almonds for
their satiating qualities and their ability to help satisfy
cravings for less healthy fats.
</P>
<P>
   Almonds contain beneficial calcium, potassium and magnesium, all
protections against high blood pressure, and are also potent
sources of anti-oxidants, intended to keep their fats from turning
rancid but a source of vitamin E for humans. An ounce of almonds,
about 24 whole nuts, has 164 calories.
</P>
<P>
   An almond tree in commercial production today begins with a
hardy root stock grown from a peach pit (another botanical
relative), onto which a more delicate almond cutting is grafted.
Trees can begin producing nuts in about five years (two or three
years shorter than pistachios) and reach peak productivity at about
10 years, tapering off to almost nothing by about age 25. The
annual production cycle _ and forecast of the year's yield _ begins
romantically around Valentine's Day with the bloom, when orchards
are transformed into spectacular oceans of pale pink blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   Because almonds are not self-pollinating, different varieties
are planted in alternating rows and more than 1 million beehives
are brought by commercial beekeepers into the state each winter to
pollinate trees. It is a fraught time, and a whole year's crop
depends on the vagaries of wind and weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bees won't fly if it rains,'' Woolf said, talking of this
year's spotty bloom, which is expected to produce a crop about 25
percent below last year's record yield. ``They won't fly if it's
under 54 degrees. We knew we'd have a lower crop.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the nuts have been shaken to the ground, another set of
machines, a bit like street sweepers, blow and rake them into neat
rows between the trees, and still others with whirling
rubber-toothed paddles come and pick them up into a wagon. They are
taken to the Harris-Woolf processing plant nearby and piled in like
batches, covered with plastic sheeting and fumigated.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the hulling and shelling, which is the province of
Dean Nelson, a former banker from Arizona who used to handle the
Woolf family account and decided a few years ago to return to his
roots as a Utah farm boy by coming to run the almond plant. It's a
spiffy operation, worthy of Rube Goldberg, in which the almonds
move along a series of elevators and conveyors, under rollers and
over shaking perforated trays with a series of successively finer
holes. Nothing (except dust) gets wasted. First the hulls are
cracked off completely and piled in giant mounds to be hauled off
as a feed supplement for dairy cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Then the brittle, almost papery inner shells are cracked and
separated, in part using air blasts and suction. They become
livestock bedding. Finally, the brown nuts fall through a series of
slots to be sized, graded, weighed and, ultimately, packed for
shipment in 2,000-pound wood containers or 50-pound cardboard
boxes. The plant's annual electric bill is about $130,000, most of
it racked up in the hundred days of harvest.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem, as Nelson puts it: ``Every time you move an
almond, you take a chance of chipping it up.'' The chipped ones
fetch less at market, and go for products from candy bars to
blanched almonds for baking and cooking. The unscarred nuts are
reserved for snacking and fancy use, with the most popular variety
_ _ the nonpareil, the fat, perfectly shaped nut in a can of smoked
almonds or atop a fine pastry _ accounting for nearly 40 percent of
California's total production.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nuts hulled at Harris-Woolf are bound for shipment
to Blue Diamond, the giant cooperative that handles about 35
percent of all the state's production and is the single largest
processor. Most are sent directly to brokers for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The big growth market at the moment is China, which now accounts
of 25 percent of U.S. export sales. In the 1998-99 crop year, China
accounted for just 8.2 million pounds and now buys more than 25
million pounds a year. So the almond growers are thrilled at the
prospect of lower tariffs once China enters the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Woolf may sell globally, but he still grows locally, something
he made clear as he walked a row of ripening trees the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not rocket science,'' he said, ``but a lot of farming is
just checking. The best sign of management is seeing the owner's
footprints in the dirt.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALMOND PLUM TARTS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``New Food Fast,'' by Donna Hay (Whitecap Books,
1999) &QL; 
Time: 35 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup blanched whole almonds
</P>
<P>
   4 small plums or apricots
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces (1 stick) butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   { cup superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Lightly sweetened whipped cream, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Using a food processor, chop
almonds until finely ground; do not allow to become a paste.
Transfer to a bowl and set aside. Cut a small cross into stem end
of each plum and remove pit; set plums aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In bowl of food processor, combine butter and sugar. Process
until smooth. Add eggs, vanilla, flour and ground almonds. Process
until just combined.
</P>
<P>
   3. Divide almond mixture among four 1-cup pudding or souffle
dishes. Press a plum, cut side up, into center of batter; a portion
of the plum will remain above the batter.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake until filling is puffed and golden, 15-20 minutes.
Garnish each tart with a dollop of whipped cream. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ALMOND-AND-HAZELNUT-CHIP MACAROONS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Desserts: Mediterranean Flavors, California
Style,'' &QL; 
by Cindy Mushet (Scribner, 2000)  &QL; 
Time: 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup whole hazelnuts, shelled
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole natural almonds, shelled
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons apricot jam
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced lemon zest.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Spread hazelnuts across baking
sheet and bake until skins are lightly browned, about 5 minutes; do
not turn off oven. Roll nuts in a clean kitchen towel. Pressing
lightly on towel, roll back and forth to loosen skins of nuts.
Transfer skinned nuts to a food processor. Chop until nuts are the
size of chocolate chips. Transfer to a bowl and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Spread almonds cross a baking sheet and bake until lightly
browned, about 5 minutes; remove from heat. Reduce oven to 350
degrees. Allow nuts to cool, and place in bowl of a food processor.
Add sugar, and process until almonds are very finely ground, 30 to
40 seconds. Add 2 egg whites, jam and lemon zest. Pulse until
blended; mixture should be thick and tacky when pressed with a
fingertip. If dry, add a teaspoon of remaining egg white, and
pulse; repeat if necessary to reach desired consistency.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer mixture to a large bowl. Add hazelnuts, and knead by
hand until blended. Lightly wet hands to prevent sticking. Divide
dough in half, then divide each half into eight pieces, for a total
of 16 pieces. Shape pieces into balls and place eight balls on each
of two parchment-lined baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   4. Position oven racks in top and center thirds of oven. Bake
macaroons until golden brown, 18 to 22 minutes, reversing baking
sheets from front to back and top to bottom halfway through cooking
time. Store for up to one week in an airtight container, or freeze
for up to one month.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: Sixteen 3-inch macaroons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
