<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1846 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-UN-0906-COX     09-05 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN-0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIDEAST PEACE TOPS CLINTON'S AGENDA AT GATHERING OF WORLD
LEADERS
 &HT;    EDs: Lede must be updated later to show Clinton's expected
arrival in New York after 10 p.m. ET.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Taking his quest for Middle East peace before the
largest gathering of world leaders in history, President Clinton
was to arrive here late Tuesday, using a United Nations summit to
try to break the latest stalemate in Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming his role as senior statesman one last time at the U.N.
podium, Clinton is scheduled to give a keynote address Wednesday
morning opening the body's Millennium Summit, expected to draw more
than 160 heads of state from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   After a luncheon hosted by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
Clinton was slated to hold back-to-back closed-door talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and, separately, with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the talks, Clinton's national security adviser,
Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger, told reporters that the president still
believes an Israeli-Palestinian peace accord is within reach,
though the odds for attaining it are long and growing longer as
next week's deadline for the end of the 1993 Oslo peace process
looms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very, very, very difficult, and I don't know whether
we can do this,'' Berger said, speaking to reporters at the White
House before leaving for the summit. ``But I think conceptually,
the ideas exist for progress if there is the political will to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meetings with Arafat and Barak form the cornerstone
of a day of almost frenzied U.N. diplomacy for Clinton. He is also
scheduled to meet Wednesday with Russian President Vladimir Putin,
for wide-ranging talks touching on regional issues such as the
Balkans, the Korean Peninsula and the Middle East, and on the
prospects for future reductions in nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Clinton is to meet with King Abdullah of Jordan
and Crown Prince Abdallah of Saudi Arabia, for separate talks
centered on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's bilateral meetings would be Clinton's first
get-togethers with Arafat and Barak since he hosted them for two
weeks of peace talks at the presidential retreat at Camp David in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations collapsed after Arafat rejected Barak's offer
of partial sovereignty over disputed portions of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes to bring the two leaders together to close a peace
deal, but only if Barak and Arafat are prepared to reach further
than they did in July toward a compromise over the future of the
holy city.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who traveled to Cairo last week to seek Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak's assistance in the matter, said in July
that Arafat had further to go than Barak in the quest for
compromise, a view Berger reiterated on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Minister Barak obviously is deeply committed to making
this process work if he can find an honorable, principled
compromise,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed Chairman Arafat is also interested in an
agreement,'' he added, ``but there are some very hard decisions
that need to be made, and he has to make them in a way . . . he can
accept as a matter of principle and he can sell as matters of
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The best Clinton could hope for in Wednesday's meetings is an
agreement by both leaders to participate in another summit, Berger
said, but ``only if both sides are prepared to give some, to make
principled compromises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Barak) needs to have a meeting of the minds with Chairman
Arafat,'' Berger said. ``I don't see that happening this week. What
I hope will happen . . . is that we see a distinct way forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has been the chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, or PLO, since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Barak and Arafat are working against a series of
deadlines, some flexible, others far less so.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, of course, leaves office in January and becomes an
official lame duck after the Nov. 7 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Barak faces a number of political challenges at home and a
possible parliamentary call for a new government, and his ouster as
early as the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Even more urgently, Arafat has threatened to unilaterally
declare an independent state of Palestine on Sept. 13 unless he and
Barak can settle on solutions to the disputes near the heart of 52
years of Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   He is to meet Saturday with elected Palestinian representatives
in Gaza to discuss whether to carry out that threat or to continue
moving forward with the U.S.-brokered peace process.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, there were conciliatory words from the speaker of
the Palestinian Legislative Council, Ahmed Korei, and from the
speaker of Israel's Knesset, Avraham Burg.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is good is that there is a spirit of continuing
negotiations,'' Korei told reporters in Strasbourg, France, after
speaking to the European Parliament. ``If the success of the
process needs more time, we are ready to give it more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Korei also said Palestinians would accept placing Jerusalem
under some sort of international jurisdiction, an idea Israel has
so far rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the same forum, Burg, signaled flexibility on the
part of Israel over the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Burg quoted the late King Hussein of Jordan, who once suggested
that sovereignty over Jerusalem be given back to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy that this concept has not yet been rejected by
either side,'' Burg said. ``Let's explore it.''
</P>
<P>
   With multiple impending deadlines, Berger said Wednesday's talks
would be pivotal in determining whether to expect a Mideast peace
accord on Clinton's ebbing watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we see a decisive way forward from this week,'' Berger
said, ``I think it becomes increasingly difficult to imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli troops captured heavily-Arab East Jerusalem in the 1967
Israeli-Arab war.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli sovereignty over that territory has never been endorsed
by the international community. After the collapse of the Camp
David talks, however, Clinton said he would decide by December
whether to move the U.S. Embassy in Israel from its present
location in Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, a move that would grant tacit
recognition of Israel's sovereignty over all of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans's E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
