<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRY MUSCADET, THE OYSTERS FOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hard to imagine a better meal on arriving in
Paris than a plate of oysters and a carafe of Muscadet, the house
white of many cafes. The wine's dry, almost saline quality seems to
come directly from the sea. In fact, the vineyards, at the western
end of the Loire around Nantes, are close to where the river
empties into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   It galls me that so few shellfish restaurants in New York offer
a decent Muscadet. The most likely reason is that it has a plebeian
reputation, and many people assume that a luxury item like oysters
requires a wine of equal status. But if you try both a Muscadet and
an expensive California chardonnay with a dozen on the half shell,
the wisdom in saving a few bucks becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
   Muscadet is one of those rare French wines named for a grape
rather than for a region. Confusingly, the muscadet grape is also
known as the melon de Bourgogne, reflecting its origins in
Burgundy. The best Muscadets come from three appellations: The
largest is Muscadet de Sevre-et-Maine, followed by Muscadet Cotes
de Grand Lieu and the Muscadet des Coteaux de la Loire.
</P>
<P>
   The best Muscadets are also made sur lie, meaning the newly
fermented wine is left in contact with the lees, or sediment of
fermentation, which can include dead yeast cells and grape
fragments. This contributes carbon dioxide, which accounts for the
pleasant sparkle in many bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.
</P>
<P>
   SERGE BATARD, DOMAINE LES HAUTES NOELLES, &QL; 
MUSCADET COTES DE GRAND LIEU SUR LIE 1998 $10  &QL; 
Bright lemon and melon aromas, with a lively taste of the sea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GILBERT CHON ET FILS, DOMAINE DE LA JOUSSELINIERE, &QL; 
MUSCADET DE SEVRE-ET-MAINE SUR LIE 1999 $8  &QL; 
Aroma of lemons and limes, dry with depth and length. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHATEAU DE LA CHESNAIE, MUSCADET DE SEVRE-ET -MAINE SUR LIE 1999
$8  &QL; 
Lemon and salt aromas, bright, brisk and sparkly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GUITTENY-PAUVERT, DOMAINE DE LA BORNE, &QL; 
MUSCADET DE SEVRE-ET-MAINE SUR LIE 1999 $10  &QL; 
Aromas of lemon, melon and herbs, tart and dry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PIERRE LUNEAU-PAPIN, CLOS DU POYET,  &QL; 
MUSCADET DE SEVRE-ET-MAINE SUR LIE 1998 $9.50  &QL; 
Floral and saline aromas, light and briny.
</P>
<P>
   MARC OLLIVIER, DOMAINE DE LA PEPIERE, &QL; 
MUSCADET DE SEVRE-ET-MAINE SUR LIE 1998 $9  &QL; 
Yeasty, briny aroma, fresh and clean with a long finish. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
