<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-DOG-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS FROM A CERTAIN ISLAND VINEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: A 250-word recipe from the book appears at end of
review.) 
 By MATT LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a T-shirt concession replaces the cloakroom in your
favorite restaurant, it may be time to find a new hangout.
Institution status, for even the best-run brasserie, can be lethal
to the spirit of the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Black Dog Tavern Summer on the Vineyard Cookbook,'' by
Joseph Hall and Elaine Johnson (Little, Brown; $25.95), appears at
first be just another extension of a successful brand, like the
restaurant's famed T-shirts with canine motif. Its busy,
magazine-style design, smiling photo subjects and breathless prose
make it read like a resort brochure for Martha's Vineyard or an
Orvis catalog. Recipes are printed in a rustic ``Olde Yankee''
typeface that might have been chiseled from Plymouth Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the slick exterior beats the heart of a genuine
cookbook. The 100-plus recipes, a collaborative effort of past and
present employees, are categorized by breakfast, lunch, dinner and
dessert, followed by an exceptionally detailed index.
</P>
<P>
   Historical notes, sequences on how to flip an omelet and how to
clean squid, and profiles of the restaurant's suppliers (like ``the
chicken lady'') are interspersed throughout. It is all written with
the restaurant's easygoing style: folksy, and playful as a kitchen
full of college kids on summer break.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Dog was founded in 1971 as one of the first year-round
restaurants on Martha's Vineyard serving three meals a day, seven
days a week. Like many restaurants of its generation _ identifiable
by their blackboards and espresso machines _ it was the first to
bring ingredients like couscous and fresh ginger to the area.
Keeping an island restaurant in top form, staffed and supplied with
fresh ingredients (and ideas) year-round is a supreme challenge,
and in many ways the book reflects the hard-won wisdom and
flexibility required to weather 30 years in such an environment.
</P>
<P>
   The book emphasizes basic techniques like grilling and making
fish stock and marinades, and widely encourages sensible
substitutions. A recipe for linguine with pesto, for example, also
suggests using the pesto sauce to prepare a simple pizza, topping
it with slices of fresh beefsteak tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   For all the sturdy New England cod, bluefish and potatoes in the
table of contents, there are plenty of Asian, Mexican, Italian and
Middle Eastern influences that the restaurant has embraced as its
rotating chefs brought new flavors to the island. Littleneck clams
with spicy black bean sauce is a tasty variation on a Vineyard
staple; hot and sour soup, with kimchi, tamari and dried lily buds,
has more than a ring of authenticity to it.
</P>
<P>
   Most recipes contain a delicious twist. A roasted eggplant and
tomato soup seasoned with fresh herbs calls for a garnish of
ricotta and roasted garlic puree that adds richness to each
spoonful. Summer ingredients in particular are well represented,
and fresh herbs are positively worshiped: a simple red wine
marinade calls for no fewer than four _ parsley, thyme, savory and
chives.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, the book's shortcomings flow from its origins.
A few recipes presume the cook has a restaurant's access to
ingredients and labor. While all the recipes are written with a
brisk efficiency that suits the style of the cooking, they can
sometimes skirt important details, like how big a vegetable should
be. All onions, after all, are not created equal.
</P>
<P>
   Some good general tips on subjects like slicing and curling
scallions, preparing lobsters and cleaning quohogs do make this a
very serviceable all-purpose cookbook, even if its sunny photos of
the good life don't inspire you to hop the next ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED EGGPLANT SOUP WITH GARLIC RICOTTA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Black Dog Summer on the Vineyard Cookbook''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Little, Brown, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   2 whole eggplants
</P>
<P>
   { cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium or 1 large head garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds fresh plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 red pepper, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 green pepper, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1} quarts vegetable or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 cups ricotta
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Cut eggplants in half. Brush
each cut face with \ cup olive oil. Place on baking sheet with
garlic and tomatoes. Roast 35 minutes or until soft.
</P>
<P>
   2. When eggplant and tomatoes are cool enough to handle, remove
stems and skins. Coarsely chop, reserving any liquid in a bowl.
Remove pulp from garlic by slicing off stem end and gently
squeezing skin. Set aside in separate bowl.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat remaining olive oil in a large saucepan, and saute onion
and peppers until onion is transparent. Add stock, herbs and
chopped eggplant-tomato mixture. Reduce to a simmer and continue
cooking over a low flame for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. While soup is cooking, blend garlic and ricotta in a food
processor. Add salt and pepper and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. Taste soup and adjust seasoning with salt and pepper. Serve
in bowls with a dollop of the garlic-ricotta mixture on top.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
