<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, the mercury fell to 27 degrees at Saranac Lake in
upstate New York as a cold high-pressure system settled south from
Canada. At daybreak Wednesday, scattered frost will coat many of
the sheltered valleys of the interior Northeast before
scintillating sunshine boosts readings close to seasonal levels by
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, a stiff wind from the northeast circulating
around a New England high-pressure system will direct chilly air
into the southern Middle Atlantic and Southeastern States. Beneath
a thick canopy of clouds and patchy rain, daytime highs will stay
below 70 degrees in much of the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary heat that has stricken the southern Plains and
Texas will ease as slightly cooler air arrives from the east.
Nevertheless, daytime highs will approach 100 in spots.
</P>
<P>
   A surge of sultry air reaching the northern Plains will ignite
strong thunderstorms Wednesday afternoon.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TORRID TEXAS &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Extreme heat of historic proportions has stifled much of eastern
Texas the past several days, with records dating from the early
part of the last century shattered in many places. On Monday, the
temperature reached 109 at the Houston airport, the hottest ever
recorded there. Records were also broken at Corpus Christi, Austin
and Galveston. One-hundred-degree heat is uncommon along the Texas
Coast, since prevailing onshore winds usually temper the extreme
heat often found farther inland. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
