<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1857 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-PIED-PIPERS-NNS &LR;      09-05 2398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIED-PIPERS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILANTHROPIC LEADERS ENCOURAGE MORE GENEROUS GIVING BY AMERICA'S
NEW WEALTHY 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Sept. 5, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With two photos, of Claude Rosenberg Jr. (NNS1) and
Mario Morino (NNS2) For information about purchasing these photos
call 202-383-7824  
 (Editors: Claude Rosenberg's data, which may be used to compile a
chart on giving and potential giving in your state and where that
ranks nationally, is at
www.newtithing.org/content/state.table.html)  
 By MARK O'KEEFE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) From his office perch on the 37th floor of Four
Embarcadero Center, 73-year-old Claude Rosenberg Jr. views the
splendor of the San Francisco Bay and envisions the wealthy writing
bigger checks for charity.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite coast, at a Virginia hotel just outside the
byteway of the nation's capital, 57-year-old Mario Morino works a
crowd of young ``netpreneurs.'' Offering a smile here and a touch
on the shoulder there, Morino realizes that many will exceed his
$200 million in net worth, and lays plans to tap that worth for
society's greater good.
</P>
<P>
   Retired mega-money manager Rosenberg and technological tycoon
Morino have never met. But they are philanthropic pied pipers of
the upper classes, motivating the rich and super-rich to share, not
just to accumulate, wealth.
</P>
<P>
   One has established a new standard of giving that draws upon
previously sacrosanct investment assets; the other is trying to
create a culture of generosity that recognizes the entrepreneurial
spirit of the ``new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the concentration of wealth in this country,
because there's so much of it, and because it's growing so rapidly,
a very slight shift in giving of a point or two among the affluent
would transform the face of nonprofit activity in America,'' said
Karen Maru File, associate professor of marketing at the University
of Connecticut and co-author of ``High Net-Worth Psychology,''
published in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 9 million American households with a net
worth of more than $1 million, and these are the targets of
optimists like Rosenberg and Morino. The new millionaires, the pair
hopes, will rise to the challenge if given gentle guidance, time to
mature and the freedom to become charitable in their own way.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg's crusade began with an unsent letter.
</P>
<P>
   As the former manager of billions of dollars in investment
portfolios at RCM Capital Management, the firm he founded and sold,
Rosenberg knew the fortunes that many people on the West Coast had
built up, sometimes with his advice. Yet as he encouraged giving a
portion of that wealth to charity, too many refused, hanging on to
stocks and bonds as if they were off-limits security blankets.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated and more than a little angry, Rosenberg sat down at
his computer and fired off a public letter, hoping The San
Francisco Chronicle would print it.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenberg -- who was known for his thorough research of
stocks -- read his diatribe and realized that before he spouted
off, he'd better have his facts straight. Over several weeks, he
culled data from the Internal Revenue Service, analyzed statistics
such as the previous year's average stock market return, performed
some algebraic equations, and figured out what the wealthy could
``comfortably'' give.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flabbergasted to learn how little the highest level
persons were giving when compared not only to their income, but
their investment assets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg wrote a book, ``Wealthy and Wise,'' first published in
1994, explaining his findings. He formed a nonprofit organization,
NewTithing Group.
</P>
<P>
   His intent is not to replace the biblical notion of ``tithing''
-- giving 10 percent of annual income to charity -- but to provide
a modern guide on what people can give based not only on income,
but on the market value (after debt) of investment assets,
excluding housing and retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   In analyzing the data, Rosenberg considered what the stock
market has done over the last 50 years, not just during the recent
bull market. He defines ``comfortable'' as what one can give while
keeping asset wealth steady, even if the market returns to less
sensational performance. If the market continues as it has
recently, the wealthy can increase giving and still become much
wealthier.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I mean by comfortable giving is they can do it without
any real sacrifice, without stretching at all,'' said Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   This month, NewTithing will unveil a personal calculator linked
to its Web site (www.newtithing.org) enabling individuals to
determine what they can give based on their own comfort levels.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Rosenberg has also done state-by-state rankings,
comparing what people on average actually give to what they could
afford to give. Utah givers rank first, contributing 68 percent of
what Rosenberg thinks they could afford, and Delaware givers rank
last, donating 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The latest study, released in June, analyzed national giving in
1999, a record year for contributions. It showed that if Americans
considered their earning assets as well as their income, they could
more than double their total giving, with virtually all the
increase coming from the highest tax brackets. Those earning less
than $75,000 are already giving at appropriate levels, according to
Rosenberg's estimates.
</P>
<P>
   What about the super-wealthy, the nearly 150,000 households from
the highest tax bracket, with adjusted gross income exceeding $1
million annually? By Rosenberg's measure, if they considered their
investments, which average more than $19 million, the average they
gave to charity would increase nearly tenfold, from $129,000 to
$1.2 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people with a lot of investment assets to give simply from
their income and their income alone is shortsighted, outdated,
outmoded and basically unfair,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg said he has donated 50 percent of his income and 3
percent of his investment assets to charity in the last two tax
years, a total over and above what he gave to the Louise and Claude
Rosenberg Jr. Family Foundation. He declined to provide specific
total figures.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg knows he hits a nerve when he talks about giving from
investments that some consider untouchable. In preaching the
NewTithing gospel, he tells the fictitious story of a man in New
York City who thinks he has spotted his cousin dressed as a lady of
the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The man crosses the street, taps the woman on her shoulder, and
is shocked to discover it is, indeed, his cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cousin Bertha,'' he says, ``how could you possibly do such a
thing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cousin George,'' she replies, ``I think you will understand.
It was either this, or dip into capital.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Challenged by Rosenberg's data, a Minneapolis group has formed
with the purpose of dipping into capital for charity. They call
themselves the One Percent Club, with members promising to
contribute 1 percent of net worth annually. After two years, more
than 300 have signed pledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's working,'' said Joe Selvaggio, the club's executive
director. ``It's just a lot slower than I thought it would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to one guy yesterday who is wealthy and young. He
said his net worth fluctuates in his high-tech business. I said we
can make it easy for him to join by just looking at the low end of
his business. He ultimately joined. But some don't.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, the Community Foundation Silicon Valley has
condensed Rosenberg's book into a 32-page, $1 booklet. More than
32,000 copies have been mailed.
</P>
<P>
   If the heart of the new national economy is California's wealthy
high-tech valley, a 1998 survey by the foundation gives a peek into
the region's soul. While the news wasn't all bad (83 percent of
area households gave to charity, versus 69 percent nationwide), the
survey identified what some might consider the wealthy
cyber-stingy.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five percent of those with net worth exceeding $1 million,
not including their homes, gave less than $1,000 a year to charity.
Of those earning more than $100,000 annually, 7 percent gave
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Another finding: About one-third of high-net-worth people in the
valley were compensated with an employer's stock, but only 7
percent gave any of that away to charity, despite potentially
significant tax advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who have made money haven't even figured out
what to do with their lives, much less what to do with their
money,'' said Peter deCourcy Hero, president of the Community
Foundation Silicon Valley. ``John Rockefeller didn't give the
enormous amount of money he gave away the moment he made it, and I
think it's unrealistic to expect these new philanthropists to
immediately start pouring out these enormous sums when they haven't
had time to research it and figure it all out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say be a little bit patient.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's Fairfax County, with more than 2,000 high-tech firms
and a median household income of $90,937, is the most affluent
county in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hilton Hotel on a morning in midsummer, Morino worked a
crowd of about 300, many of them 30-somethings in bluejeans and
golf shirts, as he hosted another session of coffee and
``dough-nets.'' Most guests were there to gain business connections
and perhaps to glean some wisdom from Morino, founder of
Netpreneur, an acclaimed organization for digital start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Morino is glad to help, and has been dubbed ``St. Mario'' for
his willingness. But what these young business owners with dollar
signs in their eyes don't know is that Morino's ``primary
motivation'' is to cultivate them for future philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a master strategy for this, I'm serious,'' Morino
said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to introduce the subject of giving this fall by
recognizing someone who has been an agent for social change in his
or her community. The idea is to celebrate philanthropy quietly,
without applying the hard sell or guilt trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can predict when it happens,'' Morino said
of the decision by the e-wealthy to give generously. ``What you
want to do is be on their radar screen when it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're doing here, earning the trust of a lot of
young entrepreneurs. At some point later in their careers, they're
likely to turn to us for advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Morino sees -- and has experienced -- four stages in becoming a
philanthropist:
</P>
<P>
   First, after making your fortune, you decide to do some good.
Next, you encounter frustration and disillusionment as you are
overwhelmed with requests to give to good causes. Third, you slow
down, reflect and ``think through what the hell you want to do.''
Finally, you step out with a philanthropic strategy of your own.
</P>
<P>
   Morino ``retired'' eight years ago and founded the nonprofit
Morino Institute, which uses business and technology ``for the
social, educational and economic benefit of communities.'' His
personal philanthropy plan for this year alone is to give 5 percent
of his net worth to charity.
</P>
<P>
   His investments continue to grow. In 1992, he was worth $100
million, he said, while today he's worth double that, meaning he
has more money than he can spend on himself and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question then becomes, what do I want to do with it?''
Morino said. ``Do I buy yachts or sports teams, or do I put it to
something that does some real good?''
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   File, the marketing professor, said these questions typically
occur when wealthy people are in their 50s. That may explain why
much of the new economy's new money hasn't yet been given away.
</P>
<P>
   File said it's already evident that high-tech money often
bypasses traditional charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many types of wealth, but when we're talking
e-wealth it's a forward-looking community,'' she said. ``Their
technology has enabled them to peer around the corner and see the
world that's emerging. They believe they're on the new frontier, on
the edge of space, building the next new thing. It wouldn't make
sense for them to be part of something traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ``What's it all about, Alfie?'' questions emerged for
Art and Kathy Bushkin, who are now in their 50s, they met with
Morino as well as with other friends to try to sort it out. The
Bushkins had profited handsomely from stock in America Online, as
well as from successful careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest question wasn't where to give money, but what do I
want to do, how do I want to spend my time?'' said Art Bushkin, a
former Bell Atlantic executive.
</P>
<P>
   With a $3 million gift, the couple formed The Stargazer
Foundation, which, among other things, awards $100,000 ``genius''
grants to ``encourage the creative spirit.'' Art Bushkin runs
Stargazer, which also has started investment funds in which profits
are funneled directly into charities, part of a movement called
``venture philanthropy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bushkin said he considers his wife and himself to be ``wealth
custodians,'' a new category of people ``who have accumulated
wealth and have discretionary income that exceeds the amount of
municipalities and, in some cases, countries.''
</P>
<P>
   These custodians, he said, could replace governments as the
primary agents of social change. But first they must decide to
donate their money, develop their own plan, and just do it. That
takes time.
</P>
<P>
   Morino predicts that the next 10 to 15 years ``will be
staggering for philanthropy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have moved mountains in their lifetimes and they
want to continue to do that,'' he said. ``There's going to be a big
difference between the old money and the new money and if the new
money isn't more effective in its philanthropy, we have failed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
