<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARK-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DARK HORSES AND BLACK BEAUTIES':   WOMEN ARE FROM VENUS,   HORSES
ARE FROM HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There comes a time in almost every girl's life when she falls in
love with horses. This phenomenon, this quality of nature, is
easily observable, but Melissa Holbrook Pierson more than observes
it; she muses on it to deep and lyrical effect in ``Dark Horses and
Black Beauties,'' her new collection of slender and delicate essays
on horses and women. Pierson loves horses, and they are a major
subject here, but a deeper concern is for the human animal, its
need for love, its propensity for cruelty, its habit of imposing
ardently wishful meanings on brute or tender nature.
</P>
<P>
   Along her somewhat meandering path Pierson does provide a few
hard and interesting facts about the special relationship between
girls (and women) and horses. ``Facts?'' she writes. ``Of the
United States Pony Club's 14,000 members, four-fifths are girls.
... A survey taken a few years ago by the British magazine Gallop!
found that three-quarters of women who own horses would as soon
give up their husbands as their horses; 90 percent would rather
have a new horse than a new baby. ... Only 22 percent of Canadian
horse owners are male.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that is less persuasive than Pierson makes it out to be;
after all there is a difference between what 90 percent of female
horse owners might want and what 90 percent of women want. There's
no point in arguing the general proposition that many women love
horses.
</P>
<P>
   This sentiment is behind a vast literature, thousands of novels,
and Pierson cites a few of them to give a bit of the spirit of the
woman-horse love affair and the trembling fantasies that it
creates. She covers historical issues like the fierce 19th-century
debate over whether women should ride astride or sidesaddle. She
makes telling observations on what might be seen as the connections
among aristocratic thinness, money, social snobbery and horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping a horse in Manhattan is the epitome of expansive
wealth,'' she writes in one passage, ``and of the weird perversions
that money can buy, as if money were of such little concern that
you might consider installing a half-acre of grass lawn with a
stream and a waterfall somewhere on East 58th Street.''
</P>
<P>
   She describes a woman she knows who cannot stand not to see her
horse, which she keeps at the Claremont Stables in Manhattan, every
day. ``She is investigating the possibility of having fresh alfalfa
flown in from the West, because it is the finest in the land,''
Pierson writes, maintaining a sympathetic distance from what has
turned love into narcissism.
</P>
<P>
   Horses, in other words, are elements in the great vain comedy of
human affairs, and Pierson has a good eye for foibles. But her
essays mostly have an autobiographical edge to them, she being a
woman who loved horses as a little girl and has fallen in love with
them as an adult. Her writing has a austere quality to it, a formal
restraint that, given the subject, makes one think of dressage, of
riding crops, leather boots, of subtle motions in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Several themes are evoked, among them ruminations on the
character of horses and on the reasons girls become so smitten.
``We are attracted to horses, in particular, because they echo our
own tentative whispers but do so in a bold, ringing call; they
speak with certainty of exactly those things we are most unsure of
in ourselves. For the qualities that most define the equine species
are the ones most suppressed currently in the human: raw sexuality,
fear, open vulnerability and need, uncomplicated drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that the explanation? Certainly it is an interesting
hypothesis, the horse as a kind of echo of the deeper female
qualities. But Pierson offers it only as a thought, a possibility,
and that is characteristic of this writer whose intellectual
delicacy seems inconsistent with aggressive opinions. ``I myself
have become almost addicted to the taste of the unknowable, and
sometimes gorge on it in the middle of the night, straight out of
the container and with no sauce,'' she writes. ``With this
revelation, I hereby give up all pretense of offering some final
explanation of why girls love horses with the abiding passion they
do. Instead, I invite you to the feast of uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   In her autobiographical mode Pierson recounts her efforts to
learn to ride and to listen to horses. She is not an
anthropomorphist, being wise enough to understand that humans do
not generally know what is going on in a horse's mind. She does,
however, verge on the sentimental at times, or at least on the
mystical, as when she wants to believe that horses are more
intelligent than we are, or that they can read our minds.
</P>
<P>
   Her most impassioned remarks have to do with cruelty to animals,
and she brings us, with her usual poise, into the very abbatoir,
the dog food factories where most horses end their lives. ``We
decide who lives and who dies,'' she writes, with a resigned sort
of acceptance of human supremacy. ``The worthless die.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is sentimentality in this, Pierson puts up a spirited
defense of it. Anyway you don't have to be persuaded by everything
she says to appreciate the play of her mind, which is subtle and
quick; coltish, one wants to say, and one would be right.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `DARK HORSES AND BLACK BEAUTIES: Animals, Woman, a Passion'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Melissa Holbrook Pierson  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 254 pages. W.W. Norton. $22.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
