<HEADER>
A1864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MAGIC-FASHION-NYT &LR;      09-05 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGIC-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGAS CHEESE, OR JUST A SPREAD? 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUY TREBAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS, Nev. _ ``A little bit of eye candy'' is how the
singer Kevin Aviance modestly characterized himself as he paraded
around the pool of the Hard Rock Hotel on a sultry desert night
wearing patent leather thigh-highs, a buttocks-baring leopard-print
jump suit and a glittery fedora rakishly cocked on his shaved
skull.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all about sparkle,'' he added. ``Out of the box and over
the top. That's why I love D&AMP;G.''
</P>
<P>
   D&AMP;G, of course, is the Italian label run by Domenico Dolce and
Stefano Gabbana, whose idea of making their debut at the colossal
apparel convention known as Magic was to bypass so prosaic a sales
tool as a booth. Instead, they gambled on making their presence
felt with a poolside fashion show and a live performance by the
singer Mary J. Blige before an invited crowd of 3,500. Although
short on the Hollywood celebrities who attend their Milan runway
shows, the evening did feature a posse of drag queens to lend some
old-style Las Vegas glitter and oomph.
</P>
<P>
   It was needed. Las Vegas has been cleaned up, as everyone knows,
the raw frontier town of neon and naked ladies, of mobsters in
sharkskin suits and saurian pensioners yanking the slots rendered
family-friendly. But a certain conviction is missing from the
city's latest incarnation, with its fake Paris, its fake Monte
Carlo and its crude miniature fake New York. The root of the
problem also afflicts the twice-a-year Magic trade show and, for
that matter, American fashion itself. Someone mislaid the franchise
on Americanness.
</P>
<P>
   With 3,200 companies, 5,500 brands, 21,000 product lines and
96,000 attendees from 110 countries at the latest show, from Aug.
28 to 31, a visitor would expect an energetic surge, or, at the
very least, the appearance of a direction. But Magic _ ground zero
for mass market apparel, especially men's wear _ felt aimless and
mired.
</P>
<P>
   There were entire aisles of Hawaiian shirts. There was a section
given over to board sports, with skateboarders flying about
``catching air.'' There were the industrial majors _ Ralph Lauren,
Levi's, Tommy Hilfiger _ showing clothes guaranteed not to
surprise. There were thousands of variants on the T-shirt, still
the essential American contribution to world fashion. And there was
a larger-than-ever representation of hip-hop-inspired urban wear,
the clothes that have driven a revitalized apparel industry in
recent years, with brands like Fubu, Phat Farm and Sean John, and
now look as renegade as a button-down shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist, one of the few manufacturers supplying some
certifiable cool at the latest Magic was Ben Sherman, a 37-year-old
British firm that introduced American-style poplin button-downs to
England in the '60s and was, for a while, shirt maker to the
Beatles and the Rolling Stones. ``Kids are into these shirts their
fathers wore,'' said Steve Collins, a sales representative for
Acupuncture, a trendy British shoemaker whose current ad campaign
features a man masturbating with a shoe. ``Ben Sherman is burning
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Very little else here is, unless you factor in the halfhearted
effort some manufacturers are making to revive the '80s, an era
you'd have to develop amnesia to lament. In fashion terms, the '80s
are a John Hughes film, a Cyndi Lauper video. Think of shiny
fabrics, moussed hair and skinny ties hanging loose from a shirt
with an oversize pointed collar.
</P>
<P>
   As stylistic detours go, this revival is a singularly perverse
one _ although possibly on the money. Vegas, too, is in the grip of
an unfathomable '80s revival, with casino headline acts like Sheena
Easton, Eddie Money and Andrew Dice Clay. Even T was spotted, on
opening night of Magic, strutting through the Mandalay Bay hotel
lobby and boasting, ``I kicked Rocky Balboa's behind!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all coming back, all together,'' said Bruno Derval,
president of California Sunshine Activewear, a licensee of Playboy
Enterprises. At Derval's booth in the immense Las Vegas Convention
Center, the main exhibition hall, buyers lined up to see denim wear
sporting Playboy bunny logos as centerfold models served Krispy
Kreme doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   The tone associated with the nattier days of Sinatra and the Rat
Pack, or even Playboy, reflected a town where high rollers were
expected to dress for play. Las Vegas is not that place anymore.
Maybe nowhere is, in the aftermath of casual Fridays. Heavy hitters
in Vegas are now mostly segregated in private betting suites, while
the lobbies of most casinos are given over almost entirely to the
slots that generate over 50 percent of gambling revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The dress code there is set by the ``worms,'' as the slots
players used to be known. Any visitor who expects glamorously
bejeweled women worn as armpieces by guys in Brioni is in for a
letdown. Even in VIP lines to casino restaurants and lounge shows,
customers turn up in tube socks and short shorts. ``Never in 100
years would you guess that these people have money,'' said a sales
representative at the Bellagio hotel's luxury mall, Via Bellagio
(Chanel, Gucci, Vuitton, Prada). Looking as if you'd hit the
jackpot now seems somehow beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't for Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, which is not only attuned to the
mythical cheesiness of this most American city, but enthusiastic
about American archetypes. In the D&AMP;G scheme of things, consumption
is axiomatically conspicuous, flash is good and the borders between
retail categories _ urban wear, sports, formal _ are permeable, to
say the least. The United States market currently accounts for just
16 percent of Dolce &AMP; Gabbana's overall business, but the company's
showing at Magic bids to change that by exposing D&AMP;G to a wide
range of retailers. The beneficiary of the coolly democratic vision
put forth by this Milanese and Neapolitan couple might be American
men's wear over all.
</P>
<P>
   Why, D&AMP;G seemed to suggest, segregate style into hip-hop or
preppy ghettos? As demonstrated at the runway show, staged on a
catwalk cantilevered over the Hard Rock pool, Perry Como cardigans
can look great with graffitied denim. Glitter isn't dead. Even a
mullet can be cool if you bleach it and add some post-Twisted
Sister attitude. And there's life beyond a Tommy Hilfiger logo in
Old Glory, now reworked as hip-huggers and worn with a denim work
shirt with artificial ``dirt'' stitched into the elbows, the whole
thing topped by a plaid fedora for some Vegas-y pizazz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
