<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-KENFINKLEMAN-1200(     09-05 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KENFINKLEMAN-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S ENIGMATIC, HE'S INFLUENTIAL _ SO WHY HAVEN'T YOU HEARD OF
HIM?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canadian actress Cynthia Dale, attempting to research a part, is
shadowing George Findlay, a self-absorbed Toronto television news
director. Findlay, an ethically challenged chap who has already hit
on Dale, has a knack for speaking before he thinks _ as when he
tells Dale: ``I know you've never cracked the American market. But
you're as big as it gets here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Dale is real. George Findlay, however, is fictional _ at
least, he seems to be. Findlay is the creation of 54-year-old
actor-writer-director Ken Finkleman, a Winnipeg native who has
played the character in five TV series and counting. And when
Findlay offers Dale those words of, er, comfort during an episode
of the sitcom ``The Newsroom,'' Finkleman could be talking to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guy who has been called Canada's best satirist, and its
highest-thinking auteur. He has been compared with adventurous film
directors such as Robert Altman and Federico Fellini. He is
mentioned in the same breath as such iconoclastic writers as Dennis
Potter and Raymond Carver.
</P>
<P>
   But while he's a major star in his own country, he's barely
known anywhere else. He's a prophet with honor in his own country,
but not much honor anywhere else _ especially in the United States.
Even though PBS picked up ``The Newsroom,'' which compares
favorably to ABC's recently canceled ``Sports Night'' and HBO's
``The Larry Sanders Show,'' the sitcom never found much of a
foothold south of the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   But Finkleman isn't losing sleep over his inability to cross
over. He's simply trying to please his own creative muse.
</P>
<P>
   Making it in the U.S. market ``may matter to different people;
it doesn't matter to me,'' Finkleman says during a phone interview.
``It's not that I don't care about the audience. The audience is an
abstract, and if you write for the audience _ which you always do
in Los Angeles _ executives try to imagine what the demographic is,
who their audience is. When they look at scripts and ask, `Does
this work or doesn't it work?' that doesn't mean `Do they like it
or don't they like it?,' it means `Will the audience like it?' And
it's this guess at this abstract. It's a stupid game because you
can't figure out who this `audience' is.''
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't sound like anything a typical sitcom
writer/producer would say. It certainly doesn't sound like anything
George Findlay would say. Yet to know Finkleman, you have to know
Findlay. Finkleman's repetition of the character is a tactic
unusual even for a maverick.
</P>
<P>
   Findlay first came to being in ``Married Life,'' a 1995 series
that earned an airing on Comedy Central. But he came to full
fruition on ``The Newsroom,'' an acclaimed 1996 series that was so
unconventional that Canadian celebrities like Dale and film
director David Cronenberg clamored to make appearances as
themselves. On the series, Finkleman brought Findlay to the heights
of self-obsession: Findlay is the type of guy who's so covetous of
a primo office parking spot that he feigns interest in a
heart-attack victim, in hopes that he'll get the man's spot in
return for his sympathy when the guy kicks off. The 1997 series
``More Tears'' gets its title from a scene in which Findlay, now a
documentary filmmaker, asks for a second take of an interview with
the mother of a murder victim _ and asks if the poor woman could
cry more tears this time.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists who cover Canadian TV not only say that it's hard to
tell where Finkleman ends and Findlay begins, they also often
transpose the names in conversation _ saying Ken when they mean
George, and vice versa. You wouldn't think that Finkleman would
want to be identified so closely with someone as morally challenged
as Findlay, a guy who hires an attractive ski bunny as an assistant
even though she's less qualified than a lesbian feminist candidate,
and whose misguided flirtation with a young children's-show
producer lands him in sexual-harassment hot water. But it's enigmas
such as these that have made Finkleman a very big deal in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the appeal is really the mystery of whether it's
Finkleman or Findlay,'' says John Doyle, a TV critic for the
Toronto Globe and Mail, which named Finkleman one of the 40 most
influential people in Canadian television in 1999. ``Ken Finkleman
is very clever in offering this character who resembles himself
very much in physical presence, but the real Ken Finkleman can be
harder to pin down. He's an absolute chameleon; he can be utterly
different from George Findlay, and then he can be exactly the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonia Zerbisias, the TV columnist at the Toronto Star, is a
little more direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a character that's not really him,'' she says. ``I think
that Ken would like to put out the impression that he's a
lady-killer, but he's really quite dedicated to the woman he's been
with for several years. (The character) is just the worst of Ken
brought up to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, at one point, Zerbisias describes Finkleman as a
giant egotist and refers to him with a seven-letter synonym for
``jerk,'' but then she goes on to say, ``The guy's an enormous
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkleman's series, which skewer the media, corporate politics,
modern notions of romance and whatever else catches their creator's
attention, reflect not only his chameleonic tendencies, but his
spongelike traits as well. He seems to soak up all that's around
him, especially the foreign films that he loves. He followed ``More
Tears'' with ``Foolish Heart,'' a dramatic anthology series that
looks at the darker side of love and offers a huge shift in tone
from his satires. The first two episodes _ one of which is largely
in French and Armenian with subtitles _ evoke images from works by
Altman, Potter, Carver, Michelangelo Antonioni, Francois Truffaut
and Jean-Luc Godard.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
