u a BC-OLYMPICS-BUSINESS-NNS     09-05 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-BUSINESS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COMPANIES REACH FOR OLYMPIC GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Sept. 5, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By ANDY DWORKIN  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) No one can buy an Olympic victory.
</P>
<P>
   But dozens of corporations are trying to buy the aura of pride,
hope, patriotism and success that surrounds the Olympic Games. They
will wear it like a gold medal, flashing their Olympic connection
at consumers to suggest their products are tops.
</P>
<P>
   The best doesn't come cheap. The Olympics rely on corporate
sponsors to fund quadrennial orgies of construction and
entertainment. The 2000 Games, which start Sept. 15 in Sydney,
Australia, will cost $2.28 billion -- 63 percent more than the $1.4
billion budget for the 1996 Atlanta Games. Nations, teams and
athletes sell sponsorships, too.
</P>
<P>
   American companies such as Nike and Adidas America each will
spend millions of dollars on marketing the Games and making
products for Olympic personalities. Nike alone will spend more than
$50 million on the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Top sponsors in Sydney paid far more than $100 million apiece.
That cost has more than doubled during the past two Olympics, said
Jens Bang, a sports marketing expert with Cone Communications in
Boston. And companies must pay lots of costs beyond the sponsorship
price for expenses such as advertising, TV time and sending
executives and guests to the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Such huge investments in the Sydney Games look risky for several
reasons. There are fears that many people, especially Americans,
will pay relatively little attention to these Games. But companies
and sports marketers alike say they have faith that the Games are
always widely watched and loved. They offer an unmatched chance to
associate your product with excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every product, if it's going to position itself well, has got
to be able to say it's the best something, even if it's the best
cheap beer,'' said Rick Burton, director of Warsaw Sports Marketing
Center at the University of Oregon. ``What the Olympics does is
deliver bestness.''
</P>
<P>
   Several spoilers could dim the luster of Sydney's games for
marketers. The Olympics have been tainted by scandals recently,
including allegations of bribery in the 2002 Winter Olympics in
Salt Lake City and a ticketing scheme in Sydney that siphoned the
best seats off to powerful companies. Australia is a relatively
small sporting goods market, its more than 18 million residents
about equal to the population of New York state. That means fewer
sales chances for sponsors in the Games' host market. Although most
Olympics draw lots of interest, U.S. residents won't see live TV
from Sydney because of the time difference. That could cut the
number of people who watch the Olympics -- and the related ads.
</P>
<P>
   It will be hard to measure how much benefit companies extract
from their pricey sponsorships, Bang said. Only extensive
before-and-after surveys can tell how many more consumers know a
brand, and that can be difficult to value. Meanwhile, competing
companies can get similar boosts on the cheap by skipping official
sponsorships and running less costly ads featuring sports themes or
a few athlete endorsers.
</P>
<P>
   But marketers and corporate executives brush aside such fears,
relying on a combination of past experience with Olympic marketing
and gut-level faith that the Games have qualities that are unique
and contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these Sydney games are going to be incredibly
well-celebrated,'' Burton said. ``The world is largely at peace,
and Sydney is a spectacular place.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Columbia Sportswear Co., based in Portland, Ore.,
hope to tap that spirit with an unusual marketing deal. The company
has paid an undisclosed amount to outfit the NBC broadcast crew for
this and the next Games. The company will send about 15,000 items
to Sydney. Officials say they get lots of TV time in exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exposure that the Olympics generate for the brand ...
really puts it close to the top of brand-building efforts we have
planned in the next several years,'' said Dan Hanson, the company's
marketing communications director.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Big, global sportswear companies such as Nike and Adidas see the
Olympics as an important venue, marketers said. Some sports events,
such as the World Cup, are more closely followed than the Olympics
in certain nations. But Burton said no sports event is more broadly
followed around the world than the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cuts across different countries and sports,'' said Kathryn
Reith, a spokeswoman for Nike, based in Beaverton, Ore. ``As a
result, it really pulls in a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   By clothing athletes and teams from dozens of nations, and
tailoring their marketing campaigns to specific countries, Nike and
Adidas use the Olympics to pitch themselves as a local brand in
nations throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   In Australia, Nike is hanging a 187-foot-high billboard on a
building overlooking Sydney's harbor. The ad for Nike, which has
paid to sponsor and outfit all the Australian teams, shows three of
the nation's athletes who are also Nike endorsers. Outside
Australia, Nike will run distinct ads tailored to other nations,
featuring local athletes. The company's Olympics-related Web site
will run in eight languages and feature athletes from the same
nation as the computer users accessing the site.
</P>
<P>
   Adidas is running a global ad campaign, stressing that it makes
products for 26 of the 28 Olympic sports. Like Nike, the German
company is tailoring other ads to specific nations. Within the
United States, for instance, Adidas America, also based in
Beaverton, plans ads and Web sites featuring U.S. athletes
discussing training.
</P>
<P>
   More important than the marketing, Nike and Adidas officials
say, is the Olympic opportunity to make and show flashy new
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really gives our designers a chance to stretch their
imagination and not worry about, `What is this going to cost?'''
Nike's Reith said. ``The work that went into choosing fabrics and
figuring out what's going to work was huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Nike and Adidas spend years working on their Olympic
designs. They spend months making piles of products. Nike will send
about 120,000 pieces of clothing and several thousand pairs of
shoes to Australia for the 2,000 athletes with which it's working.
Adidas works with 4,000 of the Games' 10,000 athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The Games' wide range of events forces the companies to work on
some weird products. Nike had to make team handball shoes and
supply equestrian products. Adidas developed a Kevlar-laced
weightlifting suit to help strongmen roll weight bars up their
thighs and asymmetric fencing shoes -- one for the foot you lunge
with, one for the foot you drag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't necessarily reap a lot of financial reward for that
product,'' Adidas America spokeswoman Nicole Vollebregt said.
</P>
<P>
   Sports companies will make sales on other products, though --
either on goods inspired by Olympic apparel or on souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the styles worn in competition go directly into stores
for sale. Nike will introduce a whole new line of track-and-field
shoes this holiday taken from its Olympic designs. The companies
also sell less-expensive versions of Olympic designs, or items that
incorporate some new Olympic features. Adidas will sell shoes
featuring a new Z-shaped track spike that debuts at the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Such goodies provide a nice sales boost for the sports
companies, although just how nice is hard to say. The Summer
Olympics impact is mixed in with gains from the back-to-school
buying season, the sports industry's top sales time.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ivester, Nike's global brand director for the Olympics,
said the company always sees its sales rise after the Olympics, but
she doesn't know by how much. She said the Olympics definitely
gives Nike its money's worth as a marketing investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at where the opportunity is to make a statement
about which is the brand for athletes, and a brand that pushes'' to
the cutting edge, she said, ``the Olympics is definitely the
biggest marketing opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
