<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRANCE-NEW-NOVELS-2TA     09-05 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-NEW-NOVELS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHERS   OVERWHELM   THE FRENCH   WITH BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ So the long vacation is over, classes have resumed, and
the French are once again being bombarded with books. Not
schoolbooks, please note, but no fewer than 557 new novels, all
published within a two- or three-week period, all timed to coincide
with ``la rentree'' _ the return _ to work, to school, to the
theater, to restaurants _ that takes place en masse across France
in early September.
</P>
<P>
   True, publishers everywhere know the seasons that are best for
business, yet ``la rentree litteraire,'' or literary return, seems
peculiarly French because it is not good for business. Editors,
book sellers and critics agree that the market cannot absorb the
flood of new books, that many are doomed to sink even before they
appear. But the tradition goes on: since 1991, the wave of fiction
has grown by 50 percent, with a new record being set this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uneconomical,'' said Pierre-Louis Rozynes, the news
editor of Livres Hebdo, a French weekly devoted to the publishing
industry. ``It's simply illogical to bring out so many books at a
moment when the French have no money left after the vacations, when
they're busy readjusting to school and work. But it's like the
fashion shows: all the publishers want to parade their authors,
always hopeful that one will catch the public's eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it is hard for the annual phenomenon to go unnoticed
by the reading public. As in previous years, since late August
weekly magazines and daily newspapers have been proclaiming its
arrival with special supplements and lengthy articles in which the
books of a lucky few novelists have been singled out for praise. No
less typically, articles have also been lamenting what Le Monde
last week called the ``permanent inflation'' of new books every
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Press coverage is itself one good reason to publish at this
time. A book is more likely to be reviewed and an author more
likely to be profiled now than at any other time in the year,
although Rozynes, for one, believes this does more for egos than
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press, book critics and authors belong to the same world
that is basically talking to itself,'' he said. ``But the
relationship between articles published and books sold is quite
disproportionate.''
</P>
<P>
   These articles nonetheless serve to draw up an initial list of
20 or 30 French novels _ this year's crop comprises 347 French and
210 translated novels, plus 460 nonfiction books _ considered
worthy contenders for the literary prizes awarded here every
November. Because these prizes, notably the Goncourt, Femina and
Renaudot, virtually guarantee sales of 200,000 or more copies of
winning novels, they too stimulate the onslaught. In reality at
least half the time the top prizes go to novels from one of the
three main ``literary'' publishers, Gallimard, Grasset and Le
Seuil, yet this does not prevent smaller or more commercial houses
from joining the race in the hope of a surprise. The ``literary''
three, though, frequently select and promote their novels for this
season with the prizes specifically in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is the choice of the publishers,'' said Antoine
Audouard, whose new novel, ``Adieu, Mon Unique,'' or ``Goodbye, My
Only One,'' has just been published by Editions Gallimard, ``and
what they have in mind _ and what I have in mind if I want to be
honest _ is one of the prizes.''
</P>
<P>
   Audouard is in an unusual situation, however, in that barely a
year ago he was on the other side as director general of Editions
Robert Laffont/Fixot. As an author, he admitted, he was delighted
that his book was one of Gallimard's 15 ``rentree'' novels. But
when he was a publisher, he recalled, he felt that the seasonal
tradition verged on the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term trend is smaller print runs and more new
titles,'' he explained, ``so it becomes like gambling. If you have
more chips your chance of having one that makes money is higher.
But it doesn't help the trade, the quality, the critics or the
readers. It's just a panic. If you talk to any publisher, they'll
say it's wrong. They think that in principle it's right to produce
less _ but that's for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivier Nora, who recently took over as president and publisher
of Editions Grasset, said there was an overproduction of novels
throughout the year, although the ``inflation'' was coming less
from established houses than from new publishing ventures, which
see the seasonal push as an opportunity to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   But many authors contribute to the autumnal glut by insisting
that their books be released then. ``That puts you in a delicate
position because you can lose them if you refuse,'' Nora said.
</P>
<P>
   For publishers, then, the scramble is to have their books
noticed, first by the press, then by booksellers. As a result books
are being printed earlier each year so they can be sent out, in
final form, by late June to give critics and booksellers time to
read them. ``Since it's costly to print just a few,'' Nora noted,
``you print all your fall books in the spring. That means you order
your print run before you know the views of your sales people.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, because bookshops have limited display and shelf
space, many books timed for the season are now distributed in
mid-August in the hope that they will beat others for good display
places. Struggling to manage the flood of new novels, booksellers
frequently complain that the situation is out of hand, and that it
is increasingly difficult to separate the good from the bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``From June, we go to meetings organized by publishers, often
with authors present, to discuss `la rentree litteraire,''' said
Pierrette Berthaume, the fiction buyer for a Left Bank shop that is
owned by Gallimard but also sells books by other houses. ``We know
some authors have a following. Some salesmen may have a good track
record. I also took about 40 books home to read over the summer. We
order at least one copy of every new novel. But inevitably there
are good books that we miss.''
</P>
<P>
   With serious fiction, though, it is apparent that bookshops play
an important promotional role, less through eye-catching displays
common in, say, American book chains than through recommendations
to regular clients. Berthaume, for instance, said that she and her
colleagues gave a special push to books they admire in much the
same way that independent bookshops do in the United States.
``Booksellers have growing influence,'' Nora said. ``In the past
they'd call journalists for tips. Now journalists call them to ask
what is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the sales strategies, there is no disguising that ever
more books are chasing a fairly static number of readers. Further,
polls show that the number of ``big readers'' _ of more than 20
books a year _ is falling, while the number of ``small readers'' _
1 to 5 books a year _ is growing, figures that suggest that serious
fiction sold in bookshops is losing out to paperback potboilers
sold in supermarkets. Rozynes estimated that 60 percent of the new
novels (there are 76 first novels among this year's French crop)
would sell fewer than 5,000 copies each.
</P>
<P>
   Much as France's protected and subsidized movie industry
produces more films than the local market can handle, the abundance
of books also reflects rules designed to help French publishing.
Convinced that independent bookshops are good for society, the
government not only supports them with subsidies but also blocks
the emergence of discount chains by requiring that books be sold at
their cover price.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The government also believes it is helping authors by banning
book advertising on television, the theory being that television
advertising would encourage the phenomenon of best sellers to the
detriment of scores of other less-publicized books. The power of
television is nonetheless demonstrated by book programs that invite
authors to discuss their work, with competition particularly
intense to appear on Bernard Pivot's weekly ``Bouillon de
Culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a cutthroat business culture in French publishing
is no less evident in the way editors and writers deal directly
with each other rather than through literary agents. A handful of
agents sell foreign books for publication in translation, but the
idea of a literary agent hawking a book to various publishers in
search of a mega-advance is still unheard of here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to book fairs some of my foreign colleagues ask me
what I have bought,'' Nora said. ``My job is not to buy a book from
an agent. It is to convince an author to write a book. The right
question is, what have I commissioned?''
</P>
<P>
   For all the singularity of the way French publishing operates,
it does have the effect of defending French culture. Just as the
French can see more locally made movies than other Europeans,
French authors are featured more prominently on national
best-seller lists than their fellow writers in, say, Germany, Italy
or Spain. If ``la rentree litteraire'' is true to form, this will
be even more the case between now and Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1889 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-KENFINKLEMAN-2ndTa     09-05 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KENFINKLEMAN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 UNDATED: Jean-Luc Godard. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's funny to be called derivative,'' Finkleman says. ``Take
other successful shows on television _ `West Wing' or `Roseanne' or
any big show _ they don't say that they're derivative when they are
actually all derivative. But being derivative is an interesting
idea. Because you get things from the culture. This is part of the
culture. Those films are part of the culture. So yeah, I do it
shamelessly.'' So shamelessly that an episode of ``Foolish Heart''
not only makes a verbal reference to Godard's counterculture '60s
film ``Masculine-Feminine,'' it also shows a clip from the movie
and shoplifts from Godard's unconventional filmmaking techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The Findlay character appears briefly in the first episode of
``Foolish Heart,'' with Findlay pretending to be a director named
Peter. The opening shots reveal a huge soundstage as the director
blathers on to an unseen interviewer. An actress goes through a
prop door, and suddenly everything has changed _ we've gone into
something that resembles a TV soap opera, and the story of a
star-crossed affair begins. By the sixth episode, Peter/George/Ken
has become part of the soap opera, as the director has an affair
with a writer who has been shadowing him on the set.
</P>
<P>
   It's house-of-mirrors television, and it doesn't aim at the
lowest common denominator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say that the only person in the audience is me,''
Finkleman says. ``That's my only standard. And I bet that to a
certain extent that I'm not a complete freak. I'm sure that to a
certain extent I have similar taste to a large number of people out
there. But why apply any other standard? It's senseless. What it
does is it seems to transform the material into something that is
similar to other material, rather than a sort of idiosyncratic
feeling and attitude. I tend to think that people actually like to
see something that's different.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkleman knows what he's rebelling against, and in part, it's
his previous self: As a Los Angeles-based writer, he foisted the
legendary flop ``Grease 2'' onto an unsuspecting public. His first
feature directing credit was ``Airplane II: The Sequel,'' a
watered-down follow-up to the zany 1980 hit. His most high-profile
U.S. credit is probably the 1986 Judge Reinhold comedy ``Head
Office,'' a movie that actually has earned a small cult of
admirers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That work in LA has as much influence on what I'm doing here
as when I was a parking-lot attendant during the summer going to
school,'' Finkleman says dismissively. ``They're the equivalent of
how much they influence what I'm doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkleman retreated to his native Canada, where he began working
on his string of series for Canadian Broadcasting Corp., a
public-broadcasting service. It was there, observers say, that he
got the freedom that he couldn't find in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work is done for a public broadcaster that does not really
care about offending anyone,'' Zerbisias says. ``So it can be out
there in a way that it can't on American television.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it can _ it just seems to be taking the wrong route.
PBS may have picked up ``The Newsroom,'' but few affiliates gambled
on it, and many that did pulled it after as few as three episodes.
PBS has picked up some of Finkleman's other series, but their
airing is even more doubtful. That's unfortunate because the effect
of Finkleman's series is cumulative; one TV writer theorized that
critics love his shows more than viewers because critics can watch
whole series uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Zerbisias _ who dismisses PBS as ``the Mobil-funded network'' _
believes that Finkleman's work belongs on a pay-cable outlet such
as HBO. Right now, the easiest place to find ``The Newsroom'' is on
video _ it's available through Amazon.com _ though none of
Finkleman's other series has made it to tape.
</P>
<P>
   Finkleman's latest series, ``Foreign Objects,'' wrapped
production in late August and is expected to air on the CBC in
early 2001. It's another dramatic anthology series that promises to
indulge his obsessions even more than ``Foolish Hearts.'' Findlay
is back to documentary filmmaking this time, examining _ according
to a CBC Web site _ such subjects as God, evil, the body and
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very odd,'' Finkleman says. ``You couldn't tell from the
scripts what the show was about, because the scripts were simply
the first part of the process and the second part was the
directing. It was like having half a jigsaw puzzle put together.
You couldn't see it till it was directed.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the jigsaw puzzle of Finkleman and Findlay, even
Finkleman doesn't seem to have figured that one out. Some people
say he's exactly like Findlay; other say he's the nicest, sincerest
guy in the world. Finkleman waves off the question by saying that
it's irrelevant _ and then makes an attempt to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Findlay changes from series to series, but at one point
during ``The Newsroom,'' I said, `Well, he's just sort of my darker
side _ he's my unedited id,''' he says. ``We all have thoughts that
we don't necessarily act upon because we're social people and we do
have a moral compass and an ethical compass, and no matter what
thoughts or ideas or impulses go through or heads, we tend to have
this other system which controls our behavior. So there's a little
bit of (my) id in George, I admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film and pop culture critic for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
