<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1895 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0906-COX     09-05 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH'S PRESCRIPTION DRUG PLAN UNVEILED
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calling Medicare ``too vital to be neglected,'' George W. Bush
announced a $158 billion plan Tuesday to help seniors pay for
prescription drugs and to improve benefits and shore up finances of
the health program that ensures millions of elderly Americans. His
proposal, made in Allentown, Pa., would pay at least one-fourth of
the cost of prescription drug coverage, whether seniors choose a
new Medicare benefit or a private plan. The elderly poor would get
drug plans for free. And under the proposal, health plans that
participate in Medicare would be required to provide a prescription
drug benefit. Medicare currently offers no prescription coverage.
Al Gore, who wants a more expansive prescription plan added to
Medicare, said Bush's plan wouldn't do enough for millions of
middle-class seniors.
</P>
<P>
   GORE RETURNS TO INTERNET FOCUS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore urged massive new investments in technology education
Tuesday. He went to Resource Marketing Inc., a Web site development
company in Columbus, Ohio, to make his pitch to move the nation
into ``the new economy'' based heavily on information technology.
He said the cutting-edge focus on computers should make sure that
low-income residents are brought along. ``I'd like to see
storefront computing centers in neighborhoods where computers are
not readily available,'' he said. Gore often casts himself as an
advocate of emerging technologies, but after being stung by
criticism of his claims concerning creation of the Internet, he has
been relatively quiet on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   GORE BUDGET DETAILS COMING UP
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore plans to offer a new wave of budget details today. In
the meantime, his senior economic aides are laying out a detailed
critique of George W. Bush's tax cut and spending proposals, which
they claim would lead to huge budget deficits. In their analysis,
Gore aides assign numbers to various Bush proposals and the latest
projections of the nation's budget surplus to claim the Texas
governor's approach would create a trillion-dollar deficit problem
over 10 years. Bush aides challenged Gore's assumptions and
conclusions, saying his predictions aren't to be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN FINDS PLACE FOR SCHOOL PRAYER
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman said today that religion should be part of public
life, and that politicians have an obligation to make America's
``moral future better by the tone we set.'' He acknowledged that
some of his comments about faith have been misconstrued, including
his use of a quote from George Washington's farewell address: ``I
never felt that he meant that religion was the only source of
morality, but in an open society he was saying religion is one good
source of good values,'' Lieberman said on ABC's ``Good Morning
America.'' He voiced support for parents who launch independent,
public prayers from the stands before high school football games,
saying ``God bless them,'' but backed the Supreme Court's ban on
school prayer as ``an official authority, a government, saying you
must pray in this particular way.''
</P>
<P>
   NADER TAKES ON HEMP RESTRICTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader joined people who want to grow and market industrial
hemp in criticizing federal agencies for making it difficult for
farmers to grow the crop. The Green Party presidential candidate,
in Washington, also spoke out against a recent raid on a South
Dakota Indian reservation in which federal agents seized at least
2,000 plants described as industrial-grade hemp plants by the
crop's owner. Hemp cannot be grown commercially in the U.S. because
it belongs to the same family as marijuana, although Nader pointed
out that the levels of hallucinogenic THC are far lower in hemp
than in marijuana. ``It is analogous to consuming poppy seed bagels
or nonalcoholic beer,'' he said. ``Although these foods both have a
small psychoactive component, people do not abuse them.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDS OF EARTH A FRIEND OF GORE
</P>
<P>
   The national environmental group Friends of the Earth endorsed
Al Gore Tuesday after agonizing over whether to support Ralph
Nader. The group, which has been critical of Gore and the Clinton
administration, ultimately sided with the Democrats after deciding
that endorsing Nader would only help elect Republican George W.
Bush, said Brent Blackwelder, head of the organization. ``There is
a Grand Canyon of difference'' between Gore and Bush, Blackwelder
said. But, ``while Nader has a platform with which we are largely
in agreement, the fact is that third parties don't win presidential
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN TALKS UP TARGETED TAX CUTS
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman sat at at a table at a coffee house in Peoria,
Ill., Tuesday, talking with families about challenges they face:
how to pay for long-term care for an elderly parent, how to afford
college expenses, what to do about child care costs. He sought to
reassure middle-class taxpayers that Al Gore's plans for targeted
tax relief would help them more than an across-the-board tax cut
proposed by George W. Bush. ``We've come a long way in the last
eight years, so we've got a lot to be grateful for, but now the
question is now how do we use the prosperity we have?'' Lieberman
said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ADS HIT BUSH HEALTH CARE RECORD
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee plans TV spots bashing George
W. Bush on health care this week, pointing to a federal court order
to improve poor children's care in Texas and insisting: ``Bush's
record: It's becoming an issue.'' The ad will begin airing Thursday
in nine key states, but Democrats unveiled it Tuesday as Bush was
announcing a plan to provide prescription drug coverage for
seniors. ``George Bush says he has a plan to improve children's
health care,'' an announcer says in the 30-second spot. ``But why
hasn't he done it in Texas?'' Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett countered
that Texas has enrolled a record number of children in the
state-federal Medicaid program under the governor's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS DOMINATE SUMMER AD WAR
</P>
<P>
   More than $1 million in TV ads poured into Detroit in August,
wooing voters in one of the presidential contest's most crucial
states. It was a lopsided spending spree: 69 percent of the ads
boosted Al Gore or criticized his rival, George W. Bush. It was the
same story in every corner of the country, helping explain how Gore
turned a solid lead by Bush into a deadheat race by Labor Day. The
Democrats spent $35 million over the summer compared to about $25
million by the Republicans. ``You just can't let the other side
spend that many more dollars than you,'' said Kenneth Goldstein of
the University of Wisconsin, who is analyzing the ad spending of
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-DEMOCRATIC TIES CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission apparently has concluded that
close ties between organized labor and the Democratic National
Committee during the 1996 election campaign were not illegal. USA
Today reported today that FEC general counsel Lawrence Noble
concluded the level of coordination between labor spending and
party officials would have been illegal if not for a federal court
ruling last year that imposed a stricter standard for determining
illegal coordination. Republicans complained that the AFL-CIO spent
as much as $35 million to help Democrats in the 1996 elections,
much of it on TV ads, and that the level of coordination between
labor and party officials made the spending illegal.
</P>
<P>
   MIXING IN WITH POLKA AND KIELBASA
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney danced the polka with a Polish beauty queen, spoke a
little Polish and dished out a few plates of kielbasa and stuffed
cabbage in Chicago on Labor Day. Cheney, whose campaign style has
sometimes been described as aloof in recent weeks, shed his
motorcade and rode the El to the Taste of Polonia festival. At the
festival, he greeted the crowd in Polish. ``Sto lat,'' Cheney said,
or, ``May you live 100 years.'' Then he spoke about his role as the
secretary of defense under President Bush. ``We were proud to work
with all of you to help bring down the wall and free the peoples of
Eastern Europe,'' he said, to applause.
</P>
<P>
   STEPPING OFF IN DIFFERENT PATHS
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates for the Senate from New York could not have
found two more disparate neighborhoods to mark Labor Day, what is
traditionally viewed as the first day of the general election
campaign. Rick Lazio was in Clarence Center, a Republican dot of a
town 20 miles outside Buffalo, stepping briskly down narrow streets
lined with trees and single-family homes in a firefighters' parade
to waves of applause and shouts of support. At the other end of the
state, Hillary Clinton marched in a West Indian parade through one
of the most solidly Democratic parts of New York, the Crown Heights
section of Brooklyn. She crisscrossed the street reaching for hands
amid the cacophony of shouts of support and calypso music blaring
from floats.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARIES IN FLORIDA AND NEVADA
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas faced nine candidates in a bid for
a second term today after months of tumult over the Elian Gonzalez
case. But primary elections featuring open Senate seats in Florida
and Nevada promised little suspense as favored candidates in both
parties faced lesser-known opponents or none at all. In Florida,
Rep. Bill McCollum should have an easy time in the Republican
primary to fill retiring Republican Sen. Connie Mack's seat. On the
Democratic side, Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson also is
expected to breeze to victory. In Nevada, Republican John Ensign, a
former House member, is the overwhelming favorite against two
little-known opponents in a GOP primary for the Senate seat being
vacated by retiring Democrat Richard Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
