<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts and travel articles this week for release
Sunday, Sept. 10, 2000. If you have questions about stories, call
888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (moving in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NEW-SEASON (New York) _ Ben Brantley surveys the
upcoming Broadway season, which includes the return of Edward
Albee, one of the handful of working American playwrights to whom
the word ``great'' adheres easily and a dramatist who rarely fails
to exasperate and never fails to intrigue, as well as the return of
Alan Bates in ``The Unexpected Man.''
</P>
<P>
   SEUSSICAL-THEATER (New York) _ Broadway is becoming more
preoccupied with the needs of an age group that in the past it
rarely catered to _ children _ while holding on for dear life to
the adult audience that has sustained it. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SEASON (Undated) _ Elvis Mitchell surveys the upcoming film
season, which he says will be a season of radical departures, with
an astonishing number of musicals from directors new to the genre
and an action film from a director who made his name with finely
tuned pictures based in the comedy of manners.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LEAN-SEASON (Undated) _ The film industry's autumnal hopes
seem to be pinned, for the moment, on a live-action adaptation,
``Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas'' and an updating of
the '70s television show ``Charlie's Angels,'' which not even those
of us who decorated our bedrooms with pictures of its
crime-fighting stars ever considered a work of art. And there are
further signs that cinematic seriousness has fallen on hard times.
By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ZELLWEGER (Los Angeles) _ Renee Zellweger has all the
trappings of a rising Hollywood starlet: the blond hair, the thin
frame, the bee-stung lips, the homespun childhood in Texas, no
formal acting training and a boyfriend who gets $20 million per
picture. But Zellweger, though best known for playing Tom Cruise's
girlfriend in her breakthrough role in ``Jerry Maguire'' in 1996
and, more recently, Jim Carrey's girlfriend in this summer's ``Me,
Myself and Irene,'' is not simply another actress who has succeeded
by perfecting the art of playing herself. By Dana Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   AFFLECK-FILM (Hollywood) _ Since wafting into the public
consciousness three years ago in ``Good Will Hunting'' _ a film for
which he shared a screenwriting Oscar with his co-star and Little
League teammate, Matt Damon _ Ben Affleck has emerged as one of
Hollywood's major heart flutters. When his new romantic drama,
``Bounce,'' is released on Oct. 13, cardiologists across the
country will be on call. By Franz Lidz.
</P>
<P>
   BLAIRWITCH-FILM (Los Angeles) _ No matter who does it, making a
sequel to a hit film is one thing; making a sequel to a phenomenon
is another. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   DEVIL-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Lately, and almost unnoticed the
Devil has been getting his due on the silver screen. For the new
season, ``Bedazzled'' stars Brendan Fraser as a nerdy young man who
surrenders his soul to a very seductive Devil played by Elizabeth
Hurley. ``Little Nicky'' stars Adam Sandler as Satan's good son,
Harvey Keitel as Satan and Rodney Dangerfield as Satan's father. In
``Lost Souls,'' a thriller, Winona Ryder plays a devout
schoolteacher who becomes aware of a Satanic conspiracy. And the
granddaddy of them all, ``The Exorcist,'' will be rereleased with
additional material never shown before. By Jamie Malanowski.
</P>
<P>
   VAMPIRE-FILM (Undated) _ When E. Elias Merhige's ``Shadow of the
Vampire,'' with its attention-snagging stars John Malkovich and
Willem Dafoe, opens Dec. 29, it will mark at least the fourth time
that filmmakers have resuscitated this particular version of the
vampire: Nosferatu, that disturbingly peculiar and apparently
iconic figure created by an odd little group of Germans 79 years
ago. By Jim Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   CROWE-FILM (Santa Monica, Calif.) _ For Cameron Crowe, it has
always been about rock 'n' roll. That has been the story of his
life and work, starting with his precocious stint as a teenage
journalist with Rolling Stone magazine in the '70s, right on
through his current filmmaking career as a writer and director. In
all his films _ from ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' which
details the normal adolescence he never had, to ``Almost Famous''
(his newest and most autobiographical film), which describes the
extraordinary adolescence he truly had _ rock helps people come of
age. By Bill Desowitz.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS-FILM (Undated) _ Presumably, with the blurring of
once-rigid boundaries between male and female roles, the action
heroine is no longer the anomaly who has to be softened, made
acceptable, by precisely those ``feminizing'' qualities that
undermine her plausibility, threaten to turn her into a harmless
joke. ``Charlie's Angels,'' the movie, will no doubt give us the
real thing: powerful, enterprising women who haven't got time to
look perfect, whose fingernails crack and whose roots grow out, who
give their Bosley (Bill Murray) not girlish giggles but power-grrrl
guff. By Molly Haskell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SEASON (Undated) _ The cleft dividing the composers of the
19th century from those of the 20th is arguably the most prominent
geographical feature of our musical landscape. Two attitudes _ on
how music should sound, how it should feel and what its purpose
should be _ have split audiences, musicians and commentators so
decisively that in still a third century, the 21st, the gap is only
marginally narrower than it was 100 years ago. On consecutive days,
March 2, 3 and 4, 2001, at Carnegie Hall, the sides face each other
in a format of rare concentration and potency. The Vienna
Philharmonic plays; Pierre Boulez conducts. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   SERKIN-MUSIC (New York) _ Peter Serkin has never been an
ordinary virtuoso. His deep concern with the music of living
composers has brought him to work more than most solo pianists in
collaborative contexts and encouraged him to be unconventional in
his programming. So he has all the qualities Judith Arron, the
executive and artistic director of Carnegie Hall until her death in
1998, was looking for when she set about inviting a few musicians
to imagine coherent sequences of concerts that they and others
would give at the hall around the time of the new millennium. By
Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   POP-MUSIC (Undated) _ The paradox of pop is that intentions
rarely correspond to results. The most carefully thought out,
elaborately realized musical opus may well be ignored or
repudiated, while a casually tossed off ditty can turn out to be
timeless. Listeners, not musicians, will make the final decisions
about what's worth saving. And in the meantime, fleeting pleasures
will do just fine. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   JOAN-OSBORNE-MUSIC (New York) _ The music business has a long
tradition of making over its female artists, whether it's the
Supremes in finishing school or just the latest battery of stylists
dispatched to a video shoot. What's odd about Joan Osborne's
situation is that she seems to have forced this transformation upon
herself. By Karen Schoemer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEW-SEASON (Undated) _ In a television season whose big names
include Bette Midler, Geena Davis and Gabriel Byrne, all starring
in sitcoms, the most promising series belong to Andre Braugher,
David E. Kelley and some guy who looks like David Letterman. Their
shows are not entirely original; let's be realistic, that is not
what most television series do. Yet they accomplish something
equally good, breathing fresh life into traditional genres. By
Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-TV (Undated) _ Two gentle, unobtrusive voices unite the
many seemingly disparate threads that are woven into Bill Moyers'
magisterial documentary on death, ``On Our Own Terms,'' which
begins September 10 on PBS. The first is the voice of Moyers
himself, the temperate sound of a compassionate understanding that
never treads roughshod on the boundaries of another's sorrow. The
other voice is one unheard and yet heard constantly, the more
powerful for being soundless, the more insistent for not needing
words. By Sherwin B. Nuland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PIERRE-GILLES-ART (Paris) _ When Claudia Schiffer posed for
them, she became ``Venus,'' framed by sparkling plastic flowers,
two lovely tears running down her porcelain cheeks. The pop singer
Nina Hagen metamorphosed, improbably, into a beatific Virgin Mary
and, in another image, into a bondage victim, dressed in latex and
roped to a kitchen chair. Catherine Deneuve turned into the ``White
Queen,'' floating among clouds in a gown and tiara. This is the
pop-culture paradise of the French artists Pierre and Gilles, who
use fashion, religion and the star system to create an idealized
universe of their own. Over the next year, that universe is coming
to the United States. By Amy Serafin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-DANCE (New York) _ Diversity, thy name is individuality.
That may well be the message of ``France Moves,'' a major festival
of French contemporary dance that will spread some 10 experimental
troupes in New York from April 24 to May 6. By Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELATIONAL-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ The time has come to speak
of ``relational'' design _ buildings that interact with their
surroundings in full dimension instead of dumbly mimicking the
scale and form of their next-door neighbors. In the coming months,
there will be many opportunities to enrich the vocabulary for
talking about architecture in relational terms. Perhaps the most
spirited of these projects is the continuing development of
SPARCity _ Eric Owen Moss' name for the discontinuous loop of urban
development he has been designing for Culver City, Calif. By
Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-SEASON (New York) _ In the year ahead there will be an
amazing variety of private art collections starring in exhibitions
at museums across the country. Three in New York illustrate why
private art collections are formed, why museums exhibit them _ and
in some cases acquire them _ and why museumgoers find them
irresistible. One such show, ``The Embodied Image: Chinese
Calligraphy From the John B. Elliott Collection,'' opens September
15 at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS, PAPERBACKS and BESTSELLERS-CHILDREN have all moved.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Coded `t') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MISSISSIPPI (Undated) _ The French settled on the great
river as trappers and traders, and their sturdy colonial homes can
still be seen on both banks some 60 miles south of St. Louis. By
Shirley Christian.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FRANCE (Undated) _ In Normandy's heartland in mellow
autumn, a traveler fills up with the hearty food and spirit of a
robust area. By Frederick Turner.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SKI-ENVIRON (Undated) _ Ski resorts pledge to protect
natural areas. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: A casbah by the casinos,
the opening of Desert Passage by the Aladdin resort in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Lead item: A King Arthur tour of England.
By Eric P. Nash.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Let the buyer beware: A boom
market in travel scams. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Click for a safari in Africa or
spelunking in Arizona. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
