<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NETWORK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD NETWORK OFFERS FOOD GARNISHED WITH A GENEROUS PORTION OF
ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: 2nd take contains brief descriptions of six new shows on
the Food Network.) 
 By   MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My biggest disappointment while previewing the Food Network's
new fall lineup last week was that the ``Naked Chef'' was dressed.
If I dedicate a full half-hour of my life to a scrupulous
inspection of a new Generation Z (yes, he looks that young) kitchen
whiz from England, I expect more in return than a winning smile and
a recipe for vodka-soused watermelon.
</P>
<P>
   But I had to concede that Jamie Oliver still managed to hold my
attention, even after he explained that ``naked'' referred to the
food: ``We're stripping down a recipe.'' At least I think that's
what he said; Oliver, who catapulted to BBC stardom after a
producer spotted him cooking in a British restaurant, has a heavy
accent.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters. I wasn't watching the new shows to revel in
the wisdom of such cooking tips as Oliver's advice to ``just bash
the hell out of it.'' What captivated me was how far the Food
Network has evolved from trying to teach people to cook.
</P>
<P>
   While the glitz and silliness of shows like ``Iron Chef'' and
``The Two Fat Ladies'' may have alienated serious cooks, they have
been enormously successful for the network. After a financial
struggle that cost the cable startup an estimated $88 million in
the seven years since its creation, media analysts predict the
network finally will break even this year.
</P>
<P>
   It is thriving by replacing the shows with cooks standing behind
counters _ the sorts of programs that dominated the airwaves during
the first four decades of television _ with shows that are purely
entertainment. This fall's lineup will feature even more of the
escapades, exotic locales and celebrity chefs that have seized
control of the network's prime time schedule in the last couple of
years.
</P>
<P>
   With instructional programs relegated to daytime hours, the Food
Network has reserved the coveted prime time slots for ``very sexy
programs that satisfy viewers' cravings for entertainment over
education,'' said Eileen Opatut, the network's senior vice
president of programming.
</P>
<P>
   That means lots of moody, jerky footage of the Naked Chef
wandering around rain-slicked streets buying cheese; think MTV
meets ``The Blair Witch Project'' over appetizers. On another new
show, ``Ming's Quest,'' the celebrity chef Ming Tsai travels around
the country in hot pursuit of the live ingredients he will later
cook on location. Along the way, he dresses in waterproof orange
slicks to haul in lobster traps or a wet suit to dive for abalone
off the California cost. On ``B. Smith With Style,'' the host,
Barbara Smith, barely talks about food at all. Sure, she can
squeeze in a quick segment with Bobby Flay, but count on the
program to focus more on such issues as container gardening and how
to braid hair (``Let's talk about extensions'').
</P>
<P>
   By sacrificing the serious to embrace the ludicrous (no, you did
not dream it, the ``Three Dog Bakery'' show did feature chefs who
cooked for pets), the Food Network has developed from a rinky-dink
channel with six hours of programming recycled four times in each
24-hour cycle into an infotainment colossus whose popularity
reaches far beyond the 50 million American households who subscribe
to its schedule of 31 television shows. Celebrity chefs now parade
around the country _ you can get the New Orleans chef Emeril
Lagasse's autograph if you happen to be in Las Vegas on Sept. 17.
The network's Web site, Foodtv.com, attracts 1.7 million visitors a
month and has a collection of every recipe on every program.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the television network is our core business and will
stay the core business,'' said Judy Girard, the network's general
manager, ``we are in the process of reviewing almost every
department to allow us to develop the brand beyond the actual
network.''
</P>
<P>
   The network bears little resemblance to the cable channel that
its creator, CNN's first president, Reese Schoenfeld, started in
late 1992 with two hours of programming and a jaunty motto: ``A
network for people who eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest programs included ``Getting Healthy,'' a program on
nutrition, ``Food News and Views'' with the co-anchors Donna
Hanover and David Rosengarten delivering updates on the drawbacks
of drinking too much liquor, and ``Eating Lite,'' which featured
low-fat ethnic recipes. The only recognizable celebrity ancestor
was Robin Leach's explorations of the food fetishes of the rich and
famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what I intended when we started, when it was less
entertainment-oriented than it was instructional, but they've done
a terrific job of broadening the audience,'' said Schoenfeld, who
is writing a book about the history of CNN called ``Me and Ted
Against the World.'' ``In prime time, they have more people under
55 watching them than CNN does.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the popularity?
</P>
<P>
   ``The network has managed to take food and turn it into in a
glamorous hobby,'' said Robert Thompson, the director the Center
for the Study of Popular Television at Syracuse University. ``It
has the same effect as rock 'n' roll on a whole generation of
viewers. We've gotten to a point in our culture where you're hip if
you've discovered the latest hot program on the Food Network.''
</P>
<P>
   The channel's popularity is an indication that its programs
satisfy Americans with a voracious, if contradictory, interest in
food. On one hand, the number of restaurants in the United States
nearly doubled from the early 1970s to the mid 1990s, up to 815,000
from 492,000. On the other? Americans are cooking less. Almost half
of all weekday meals are prepared in a half hour or less, according
to the NPD Group, which studies consumer trends.
</P>
<P>
   But the real success of the Food Network is that despite its
current scarcity of instructional content, ``people kid themselves
into thinking that watching it is an educational experience,'' said
Garth Jowett, who directs the University of Houston's School of
Communication and is writing a book about the social history of
television. ``So while most people see the experience of watching
TV as a guilty pleasure, they feel justified watching these
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the network's current approach emerged in the
mid-1990s, when the network decided to revamp the image of Lagasse.
His ``Essence of Emeril'' had been among the most popular early
Food Network offerings. With ``Emeril Live,'' the network added a
band, a studio audience and celebrity guests to Lagasse's routine
and created the network's first superstar chef; an onslaught of
50,000 callers clamoring for tickets disrupted service at a New
Hampshire call center in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson was obvious. ``During prime time, people want
entertainment and you're not going to get a significant number of
viewers with a chef behind the counter,'' said Eric Ober, who was
the network's president from 1998 until early this year and is now
the chief executive of the Internet career services company
Vault.com. ``My feeling was, let's get out of the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we made the decision to do that during prime time, food
would be fun, action, adventure and excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   The gamble paid off. Overall, last year the network had a 0.2
rating, which means that 84,000 people were watching on any given
day, according to Derek Baine, a senior analyst at Paul Kagan
Associates. Before 1999, the network wasn't rated, which is not
uncommon for small operations. That rating doesn't put the Food
Network at the top of the heap _ the largest cable networks, like
USA or TNT, generate a 1 rating. The Food Network is solidly in the
second tier, with a rating more comparable to ESPN2 or Headline
News.
</P>
<P>
   But it is growing. In the last two years, the network has been
picked up by cable operators across the country, and the number of
homes where it is available has nearly doubled, up from 28 million
to 50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impressive that they've been able to sign on that many
subscribers in their short life, especially when you consider that
there are only 100 million TV households in the United States,''
Baine said. ``They're in half of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Which makes me wonder: what are all those households eating for
dinner tonight? Not the vodka watermelon, I hope. &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Food Network is unveiling six new shows this season. Two
were not available for preview: a dessert show called ``Sweet
Dreams,'' scheduled for next month, and one yet unnamed starring
Wolfgang Puck, to premiere in January. I watched episodes of the
other four. All times are Eastern Standard Time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``B. SMITH WITH STYLE''
</P>
<P>
   Weekdays at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Smith, the lifestyle guru and owner of B. Smith's
restaurant in the Theater District, is the host of a show on
entertaining, lifestyle and cooking. Watch if you want to know
whether dry shampoos are an option for braided hair that comes
loose in water. Don't watch if you want to grill a chicken; in a
guest appearance, Bobby Flay promised it would take only 14 minutes
to cook. Mine was pink after 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``MELTING POT''
</P>
<P>
   Weekdays at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A rotating group of five sets of chefs explore various ethnic
cuisines. I watched two Manhattan chefs, Aaron Sanchez, the chef at
Isla, and Alex Garcia, the chef at Calle Ocho, prepare a Latino
cocktail party. The menu included white anchovy salad,
habanero-marinated shrimp and yucca fritters. Garcia confided, ``I
love to be a guest at my own party.'' Maybe that explains all the
dancing in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``MING'S QUEST''
</P>
<P>
   Thursdays at 10 p.m. and 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ming Tsai, the star of ``East Meets West With Ming Tsai,''
demonstrates his athleticism as well as his chopping skills as he
farms ostriches in Texas or dives for lobster in Massachussetts,
then cooks his catch. The lobster, for example, was grilled with
garlic and black pepper, with the sea in the background and the
wind ruffling his bangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``NAKED CHEF''
</P>
<P>
   Previews Oct. 29 at 10 p.m.; premieres Nov. 4 at 9:30 p.m.; and
will then be shown on Saturday at 9:30 p.m. &AMP; 12:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The winsome Jamie Oliver is the latest cooking sensation from
the BBC. We see him shop for clothes, and for food. His parties are
casual, and so are his cooking techniques: for instance, to avoid a
spatter of lime juice and garlic from a monster-size mortar and
pestle, he grabs a plastic grocery bag and drapes it over the top
of the bowl. At the end of the show, he serves his guests on paper
plates. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
