<HEADLINE>
`TURN IT UP': THE KILLER AS SUFFERING ARTIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If your music is so important to you, why do you keep up this
Batman and Robin s--- with Gage every night?''
</P>
<P>
   The question is posed to our hero, aspiring rap artist and
part-time drug courier Diamond, or D for short (played by former
Fugees member turned solo rap star Pras), by his eternally
forgiving girlfriend Kia (Tamala Jones).
</P>
<P>
   You've seen it before in dozens of films: the childhood street
buddies turned adult best friends who hit the crisis point when one
of them, in this case D, wants to go straight and the other,
hot-headed Gage (rapper Ja Rule), aspires to become the baddest
gangsta on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe the warmed-over and contradictory cliches about
loyalty and responsibility served up in ``Turn It Up,'' a hip-hop
crime thriller about a guy torn between dreams of music stardom and
the .32-caliber muscle of blazing handguns. The real answer to
Kia's question is that for all D's lip service to leaving the life,
and for all the film's superficial moral lessons, he is a
cool-headed, criminally sharp gangster at heart. He just doesn't
know it, and the film is too embarrassed to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   D's absent father (Vondie Curtis-Hall), a musician who abandoned
his family to follow his music, comes back into his son's life to
hand out paternal advice just as Kia reveals to D that she is
(surprise!) pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't guarantee I'll be there for you,'' tortured, torn
artist D lamely sputters to Kia before heading back out for a night
of music and gunplay, coming to life with two-fisted ferocity as he
coolly empties clip after clip into rival gangs. (By the end of the
film, he has over a dozen kills to his credit without fear of
retribution or arrest, let alone any moral pangs.)
</P>
<P>
   Director/screenwriter Robert Adetuyi consciously apes John Woo
in flashy but half-hearted action scenes without ever getting it
right, and he never worries about reconciling them with the
wan-suffering-artist pose D strikes through the rest of the film.
Pras is too withdrawn to make that pose convincing. Looking more
sleepy than introspective, he's a burned-out match next to
firecracker Ja Rule, who plays the loose-cannon bad boy with
pent-up anger and a bullying sneer.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a trace of irony as this glib, sense-numbing action
fantasy has it both ways: violence without personal consequences
and decisions without repercussions. It's a rather irresponsible
position for a film ostensibly about responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   TURN IT UP
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/WRITER: Robert Adetuyi
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Pras, Ja Rule, Vondie Curtis-Hall, Jason Statham, Tamala
Jones
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 83 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R for strong drug references, violence and language
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
