A1912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-05 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE CAMPAIGN AS A MATHEMATICAL EXERCISE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The California earthquake on Sunday surprised
professional seismologists. In all their years of studying and
searching for possible tremblers they had missed the fault line
along which this one occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Well, well. The experts were fooled by Mother Nature _ just as
other so-called experts can be fooled by Human Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Politics, too, is an inexact science. In fact, it is not a
science at all but a grand, erratic democratic experiment in the
conduct of ambitious but fallible humans under pressure as they
pursue legislative or executive power.
</P>
<P>
   This reality has not deterred seven political scientists from
creating mathematical formulas on which they base their ultimate
presidential year prediction. They conclude that the winner will be
Vice President Al Gore, based primarily on the current economic
prosperity, President Clinton's continuing high job approval
ratings and the candidates' standings on Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   What a hoot. If these scholars are right, nothing Gore or Texas
Gov. George W. Bush does or says in the next two months will matter
to voters at all. So why are both men spending millions to smear
each other in advertisements, arguing intensely over debate formats
and wearing themselves to a frazzle running all over the country?
</P>
<P>
   Silly candidates. Where have they gone wrong?
</P>
<P>
   The numbers-crunching was presented in official scholarly papers
at a recent annual meeting of the American Political Science
Association. The theory behind this unrealistic exercise is that
numerical precision can be applied to the conditions that shape
public electoral decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush themselves have been trying to take some of the
mystery out of their tense contest by holding focus groups and
taking all kinds of polls to tell them what works with voters and
what doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   But these sneaky efforts to figure out which potentially
unpopular positions to bland out and which likely winning stances
to highlight do not tell the whole campaign story.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes candidates get it right. Sometimes they don't. Tongues
get tangled. Messages get distorted. And voters are fickle. What
they want today may not be what they want tomorrow after mulling
over competing campaign claims.
</P>
<P>
   The personality quirks of the candidates, the quality of the
advice they get and the habitual intrusion of unexpected events are
not measurable quantities. The seven experts who predicted the
election outcome could not have anticipated, for instance, that
Bush would be accidentally overheard using an expletive to describe
a reporter he does not like.
</P>
<P>
   He called Adam Clymer, a respected veteran New York Times
correspondent, a term only a few media outlets had the courage to
repeat. Some delicately referred to Bush's aside as ``ass. . .e''
or ``...hole.'' Some said it was an unspecified ``obscenity,'' and
one called it a ``vulgar euphemism for a rectal aperture.'' This
columnist prefers to use the relatively classy ``donkey's bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   A presidential candidate who uses language considered too
scatological for the modesty of television viewers and newspaper
readers suddenly tosses a new, unpredictable factor into the White
House race. It may not matter, it may humanize Bush or it may
disgust voters demanding dignity in the presidency. But it was
clearly an unscripted incident that does not fit neatly into any
pre-determined mathematical formula.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial constructs by scholars cannot anticipate the dynamics
of a fast-moving campaign without precedent in past races. This
includes around-the-clock media sound bites and new Internet
venues, constantly changing interracial issues driven by increasing
immigration, uncontrolled, secretly financed spending on so-called
independent commercials, and new clandestine tricks by hidden
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can statistical models evaluate luck, personal weaknesses
and strengths, candidates' health, sudden scandals or unlikely
policy stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   The past may repeat itself, but it never repeats itself exactly.
</P>
<P>
   So why go through this academic exercise at all? The political
scientists claim that their statistical models came up with the
final result in every election since 1952 _ except those that were
very close. In 1996, their predictions were even more accurate than
the Election Day polls.
</P>
<P>
   So what? Anybody who didn't know well in advance that
pre-Monica-Lewinsky, sunny Bill Clinton was sure to beat grumpy
old-timer Bob Dole in 1996 wasn't living in this galaxy. And, gosh,
don't we have a close election on our hands this fall? Send the
professors back to their ivory towers and get on with the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT     09-05 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDEAUX THAT REQUIRES NO BODYGUARD 
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are one of those pessimists who react with fear and
trembling to even the slightest sign that the economy is cooling,
take some comfort from Bordeaux wine. Prices are just as high as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a personal selection of Bordeaux wines, all of
them good and all of them selling for $30 or less. I won't call
them bargains; for many people $30 is a lot of money to pay for a
bottle of wine. It's only in comparison with top of the line
Bordeaux that this gathering of bottles will begin to look good.
The first growths continue to exist on another planet: the 1998
Lafite-Rothschild is around $175, and the 1998 Haut-Brion around
$275. Both the Petrus and the Chateau Le Pin 1998's hover around
$1,000 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The down-to-earth wines recommended here are mostly from the
1997 vintage, a very good year in Bordeaux if not a memorable one.
The classic Bordeaux ploy _ figure out what the market can bear,
and add 20 percent _ applied to 1997. The wines were overpriced.
But there are some moderately priced ones and, for the most part,
they are ready to drink now. After the movies and most restaurants,
isn't it pleasant not to have to wait for something?
</P>
<P>
   For good Bordeaux at reasonable prices, it's usually prudent to
look first to the lesser appellations like Fronsac and
Canon-Fronsac. But good wines can be found in more prestigious
places, too. In the Margaux appellation, for example, Chateaux
d'Angludet, du Tertre and d'Issan are all priced at $30 or less.
All offer the warmth, soft tannins, medium body and good fruit
characteristic of this vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Prieure-Lichine, in Cantenac, which is part of the Margaux
appellation, gained a reputation for good, occasionally outstanding
wines under the late Alexis Lichine. The 1997 is light, pleasant
and ... well, inconsequential. Better, perhaps, to opt for the
appealing and more substantial 1997 Chateau Giscours at about the
same price _ $27 _ and wait for the 1998 Prieure, which I'm told is
a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   From Moulis, one of the towns just west of Margaux, I like
Malmaison, a property rejuvenated by the late Edmond de Rothschild
as a companion piece to his Chateau Clarke. Poujeaux, long a worthy
competitor for wines far better known, is my favorite here for its
intensity. But for the price, around $20, the more rounded
Malmaison provides some very pleasant drinking. The Poujeaux is
selling for around $27.
</P>
<P>
   A third Moulis property worth mentioning is Chateau
Chasse-Spleen, whose 1997 is a bit more tannic than the two above
and a trifle leaner. Many people like that in a Bordeaux. It's
about $20.
</P>
<P>
   Among the famous communes of the Medoc, St.-Julien has always
been noted for its rounder, more approachable wines. Much in that
image is the 1997 Les Fiefs de Lagrange, the second wine of Chateau
Lagrange. Lagrange itself is a full, elegant wine with firm but not
harsh tannins. Les Fiefs has the same charm but is softer and more
one-dimensional. A most attractive wine at about $22.
</P>
<P>
   From Pauillac, I liked the Carruades de Lafite, at just $30.
This is the second wine of Chateau Lafite-Rothschild and, as
expected, it offers Lafite finesse if not the Lafite depth or
length in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the scale is an interesting little
Pauillac property called Chateau Bernadotte. In 1997, May-Elaine de
Lencquesaing, the owner of Chateau Pichon-Lalande, bought
Bernadotte and set about reviving the house and vineyards. The wine
is getting better, and it's about $15.
</P>
<P>
   The Medoc road turns inland just after it passes Lafite, and the
vineyards of St.-Estephe, specifically Cos d'Estournel, come up on
the left. Cos is beyond reach here, but St.-Estephe is not without
its $30-and-under charms. Chateaux Meyney, Les-Ormes-de-Pez and
Phelan-Segur range from about $25 to about $30.
</P>
<P>
   Meyney at times can be rough and tannic. Not so this wine. Like
many St.-Estephes, it has a rough edge, but it is mostly supple and
rounded, with plenty of body and fruit and a long finish.
Les-Ormes-de-Pez is owned by Jean-Michel Cazes and his family, and
its wines regularly display qualities of their Lynch-Bages.
</P>
<P>
   As for Phelan-Segur, I liked it before the Gardinier family
bought it from the Delons in 1986, and I've watch it improve
steadily. The 1997 is solid, well made, with a lovely bouquet. It
is less concentrated than it might be and shows a bit of typical
St.-Estephe muscle, but it's worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Having mentioned Fronsac and Canon-Fronsac, I'm obliged to
suggest a wine from there. I particularly liked Chateau Canon
Moueix, a minor star in the Moueix family's collection of chateaus.
The wine displays the familiar 1997 softness, but there is richness
and some succulent fruit as well. It's about $20.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been much of a fan of half-bottles, but if you like
the idea, there are plenty around. Certainly, they're a way to move
up in quality. Among the 1997 Bordeaux in half-bottles hovering
around $25 are Grand-Puy-Lacoste, Leoville-Barton and
Leoville-Poyferre. Calon-Segur is about $15, Brainaire-Ducru $20
and Lafon-Rochet $15.
</P>
<P>
   Should you choose to go right to the top, in half-bottles, of
course, Haut-Brion and Lafite are both around $72; Chateau Margaux
is $110 and Mouton-Rothschild $129.
</P>
<P>
   They say good things come in small packages. OK, but I'd prefer
a Lynch-Bages at around $50 to any of these pint-size heavy
hitters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
