<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICKMENU-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Elegant Dinner Is Easier Than It Looks  &HT;       
 By Tara Duggan 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Hosting a dinner party is not by nature a
quick-and-easy prospect, but you can make even an elegant,
four-course, sit-down dinner a lot easier on yourself if you do as
much as possible ahead of time.
<P>
   At the risk of sounding like a self-help book, the first thing
to do is know your limits. How much time will you need on the day
of the dinner to not only cook but clean the house, wash dishes and
figure out what you're going to wear? How much do you want to
actually be cooking when your guests arrive?
</P>
<P>
   To avoid party-day stress, shop two nights ahead, then set aside
the evening before the dinner to complete the bulk of the prep
work. As notes on top of each recipe indicate, this menu was
designed to be done mostly in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Do yourself a favor and take as many shortcuts as you can. For
the appetizer, Toasted Cumin Pita Crisps with Hummus, I suggest you
buy a good ready-made hummus at a Mediterranean deli or supermarket
(although I include a recipe for die-hards). Then just bake the
pita crisps at the last minute so they come out of the oven hot,
crisp and smelling of toasted spices just as your guests arrive at
the door.
</P>
<P>
   The first course, Shrimp and Artichoke Skewers with Lemon
Tarragon Mayonnaise, uses skewers and is great for a crowd because
they're so easy to serve at the last minute. Look for packages of
shelled, deveined, uncooked jumbo shrimp in the freezer aisle to
avoid the messy task of cleaning them. Everything in this recipe
except the actual cooking _ which takes all of six minutes _ can be
done ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The main course, Roast Pork with Pomegranate Sauce &AMP; Wild
Mushroom Barley Timbales, is full of deep, woodsy flavors that are
the essence of fall. It also looks elegant when it's plated, with
slices of pork on top of a bed of greens. Set them alongside the
timbales, which are miniature drum shapes formed by packing the
cooked barley into ramekins and then baking them.
</P>
<P>
   Start roasting the pork when you serve the first course so you
won't have to wait between courses. When you're ready to serve,
prepare the sauce, dress the greens and reheat the timbales.
Appoint someone to help you rush the carefully composed plates to
the table.
</P>
<P>
   Figs in Rosemary Port Reduction With Vanilla Ice Cream might
sound complicated, but it's really easy. The port is infused with
rosemary and vanilla bean and thickened into a sauce, and then the
figs are gently poached. When you're ready to serve, just reheat
them and ladle them out over dainty scoops of ice cream. A rosemary
sprig garnish imparts a fresh, herbal scent that plays beautifully
against the dessert's rich, decadent flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
QUICK AND EASY DINNER WINES
</P>
<P>
   Keep this theme light and simple with wine as well as food. Here
are some nice wines that you can keep around the house for quick
dinners, and still pay the rent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Toasted Cumin Pita Crisps and Hummus.  &LR; The starter has thick
textures and savory flavors so lighten up with a bright sparkler.
Try Chandon Brut Fresco ($11), a fruity sparkling wine from
Argentina, and MezzaCorona Brut, dry and citrusy from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Shrimp &AMP; Artichoke Skewers with Lemon-Tarragon Mayonnaise. &LR; 
With the shrimp you can continue with the sparkling wine, or switch
to a light Chardonnay such as Callaway Chardonnay 1998 or 1999
($10). The crisp acidity will be a refreshing foil to the shrimp,
and the lemon-citrus varietal flavors will work beautifully with
the lemon dipping sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Roast Pork with Pomegranate Sauce &AMP; Wild Mushroom Barley &LR; 
 &UR; Timbales.  &LR; This calls for a lively, flavorful red wine like Syrah.
It has rich, sensuous dry berry flavors, a hint of black pepper,
nuance of forest aromas and softly manageable tannins. One of
America's best, Geyser Peak Sonoma Shiraz 1998 ($17), is an
excellent value.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Figs in Rosemary Port Reduction &AMP; Ice Cream.  &LR; A dessert like
this would be great with an inexpensive port. Although the sauce is
made with Ruby Port, the finished dessert would be better with a
Tawny Port. The figs, with a burnt sugar undertone, and the
luscious flavors and textures of the cream makes the Tawny Port
flavors more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Fonseca makes Tawnies that are creamy and nutty, with hints of
caramel and coffee. For only $12, you can get the regular Fonseca
Tawny Port; for a little more, lose your heart to the seductive
Fonseca 10 Year Old Tawny Port ($24).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Diane Teitelbaum &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TOASTED CUMIN PITA CRISPS WITH HUMMUS
</P>
<P>
   For ease in preparation, purchase prepared hummus, then all
you'll have to do at the last minute is make the crisps. Serve with
radishes and/or baby carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   10 pita breads, cut into quarters
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pint hummus, prepared or homemade (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle of extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the salt, cumin, pepper and cayenne in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pita quarters in a large bowl. Drizzle with enough
canola oil to coat the quarters evenly, then toss with the spice
mixture until evenly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Place the breads in a single layer on a large baking sheet and
bake for about 10 minutes, or until golden and crisp on one side.
Flip the breads over and bake 5 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately alongside a bowl of hummus drizzled with olive
oil.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 445 calories, &LR;   &LR; 15 g protein, 72 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 12 g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 1,120 mg
sodium, 3 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HUMMUS
</P>
<P>
   If you opt for making the hummus yourself, it may be prepared up
to 2 days in advance. Store in a covered container in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 (151/2-ounce) can chickpeas, drained and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tahini
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the chickpeas, lemon juice, tahini, olive oil, parsley,
garlic, salt and cayenne in a food processor and puree until
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Taste for salt and check for smoothness. If the mixture is still
chunky, add 1 to 2 tablespoons water, puree and check again. You
might need to add an additional 1 to 2 tablespoons water to get a
thin consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 150 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 15 g carbohydrate,
9 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 94 mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SHRIMP &AMP; ARTICHOKE SKEWERS WITH LEMON TARRAGON MAYONNAISE
</P>
<P>
   The lemon-tarragon mayonnaise may be prepared 1 day in advance.
Store it in a covered container in the refrigerator. The shrimp and
artichoke skewers may be assembled and marinated for up to 1 hour
before cooking them.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Zest and juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper + pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   12 jumbo shrimp or 18 large shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   2 (6-ounce) packages frozen artichoke hearts, defrosted
</P>
<P>
   12 wooden skewers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Finely mince the lemon zest. You should have about 2 teaspoons.
Set the juice aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the mayonnaise, lemon zest, 2 tablespoons of the
tarragon and a grinding of fresh pepper in a serving bowl. Cover
and refrigerate until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Thread the shrimp and artichoke hearts on skewers, alternating
with the cherry tomatoes. Place in a shallow baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the olive oil, 1/2 teaspoon pepper, the salt,
cayenne, the remaining 1 tablespoon tarragon and the lemon juice.
Pour the mixture over the skewers and turn to coat. Let marinate
for at least 30 minutes, but no more than 1 hour. Turn the skewers
occasionally while they marinate.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Place the skewers on a broiler pan and broil for about 3
minutes, or until the shrimp turn pink. Turn the skewers and broil
for 3 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with the seasoned mayonnaise as a dipping sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 360 calories, &LR;   &LR; 17 g protein, 8 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 30 g fat (5 g saturated), 152 mg cholesterol, 390 mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades vary &LR; 
 &LR; and are difficult to estimate. Variables include the type of &LR; 
 &LR; food, marinating time and amount of surface area. Therefore, &LR;   &LR; the
marinade is not included in this analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ROAST PORK WITH POMEGRANATE SAUCE &AMP; WILD MUSHROOM BARLEY TIMBALES
</P>
<P>
   The timbales and ragout may be made 1 day ahead (cover and
refrigerate), and reheated just before serving. If you don't have
ramekins, use teacups to form the timbales. For ease in
preparation, purchase packaged cleaned arugula so you don't have to
fuss with washing all those little leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Timbales
</P>
<P>
   1/2-ounce dried shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound button mushrooms, halved and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound fresh shiitake mushrooms, stemmed, halved and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pearl barley
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   The Pork
</P>
<P>
   11/2-pound piece pork tenderloin, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   The Salad
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch arugula, about 1/4 pound, trimmed  &LR; _ &LR; 1 teaspoon extra
virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pomegranate vinegar (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   The Sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pomegranate vinegar
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the timbales: &LR;  Soak the dried shiitakes in 4 cups
boiling water for about 20 minutes. Strain the mushrooms, reserving
the soaking water, then squeeze dry and chop.
</P>
<P>
   Butter 6 ramekins. Melt the remaining butter in a Dutch oven
over medium heat. Add the onion and thyme and saute for 10 minutes.
Add the button mushrooms and fresh shiitakes and saute for 5
minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Add the barley and stir for about 1 minute. Add the
mushroom-soaking water, the dried mushrooms, salt and pepper. Bring
to a boil, then reduce heat, cover and simmer until the barley is
tender but al dente and moist, about 35 minutes. Adjust seasonings,
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately pack the barley mixture into the buttered ramekins.
Let cool to room temperature, then cover and refrigerate until
ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the pork:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Season the pork well on all sides with salt and pepper to taste.
Place in a heavy roasting pan that can be used on the stovetop.
Fold under the thin end of the tenderloin so the pork is uniform in
thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Roast for 30 minutes, or until the meat reaches at least 137
degrees (medium/medium-rare) on an instant-read thermometer
inserted into the thickest part of the meat. Let rest for 20
minutes before carving.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, reheat the timbales in the oven (350 degrees) for 15
to 20 minutes, and dress the arugula with a little olive oil, the
pomegranate vinegar and a sprinkle of salt and pepper. Arrange on
dinner plates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sauce:  &LR; Discard the excess fat in the roasting pan,
then place the pan over high heat and deglaze with the pomegranate
vinegar and chicken broth. Bring to a boil, scraping up the brown
bits in the pan, then reduce the heat and simmer for about 10
minutes, or until the liquid has reduced a bit. Season to taste
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Carve the pork into 1-inch-thick slices and place on
the greens. Use a small knife to loosen the timbales, then unmold
next to the pork. Drizzle the sauce over the meat and timbales.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Pomegranate vinegar is available at farmers' markets in
the fall, and at specialty supermarkets. If you can't find it,
substitute balsamic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 330 calories, &LR;   &LR; 29 g protein, 33 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 8 g fat (4 g saturated), 84 mg cholesterol, 629 mg
sodium, 7 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FIGS IN ROSEMARY PORT REDUCTION WITH ICE CREAM
</P>
<P>
   The port reduction may be made 1 day in advance and the figs may
be poached a few hours before the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 (750-ml) bottle Ruby Port (about 31/3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   3 rosemary sprigs
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, or 1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   15 ripe fresh figs (Mission or Calimyrna or a combination),
halved
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pour the port into a medium saucepan; add 1 of the rosemary
sprigs. If you're using a vanilla bean, split it and scrape the
seeds into the pan, then drop in the vanilla pod. Bring to a
simmer, then maintain a steady simmer for about 1 hour, or until
the mixture has reduced to about 1/2 cup and has thickened.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the liquid and return it to the pan. If you're using
vanilla extract, add it now.
</P>
<P>
   Place the figs cut-sides down into the pan. They should be
crowded and partly immersed. Simmer for a few minutes until the
figs begin to soften, then turn the figs and poach for 5 to 10
minutes, basting with the pan juices from time to time, until the
figs are very soft but still hold their shape.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, reheat the figs, if necessary, over low heat (the
sauce will be thick, so watch carefully). Scoop ice cream into
dessert bowls, top with figs and drizzle with the reduced juices.
Break the remaining 2 rosemary sprigs into 2-inch pieces and
garnish each serving with a tiny spray.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 385 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 50 g carbohydrate,
5 &LR;   &LR; g fat (3 g saturated), 20 mg cholesterol, 53 mg sodium, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
