 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: Cooking Sprays Differ Mostly in Their Cost   By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Many cooks replace cooking oil with nonstick
cooking spray to save fat, calories and time so today's panel
tasted nine of them to find the best. We were surprised by the
results.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The panel first tasted the sprays on their own, then sampled
boneless skinless chicken breasts sauteed in a nonstick skillet
with the spray. They noticed big differences in the flavor of the
sprays themselves, but little to no difference when they were used
in cooking.
</P>
<P>
   There was also no difference in the actual effectiveness of
cooking or in the clean up of the pans.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, prices varied dramatically, from $1.69 to
$4.09 for a 6-ounce can. The panel's reaction to that? Might as
well buy the cheapest.
</P>
<P>
   We did not include any flavored sprays or olive oil sprays in
this testing.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the results, but keep in mind that in the end, the
panel thinks these could all be used interchangeably. The ones
panelists liked best were the ones with the most neutral flavor.
</P>
<P>
   First place went to  &UR; Albertson's &LR;  (6 ounces, $2.69 at
Albertsons). Panelists described it as tasting ``neutral'' and
``bland.'' One thought it was probably the best for baking or
cooking because it had no flavor, even though another detected a
peppery aftertaste. Two would buy it, two might buy it and one
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pam &LR;  (6 ounces, $3.69-$4.09 at many supermarkets) came in
second. Three panelists described the flavor as sweet, with two of
them also noticing a particularly strong alcohol flavor on the
finish. One thought the flavor was especially mild. Two would buy
it; three might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to  &UR; Spectrum &LR;  (6 ounces, $3.49 at Whole Foods).
Panelists liked the neutral flavor and the emulsified look. One
panelist said this would be his choice if he was replacing cooking
oil with a spray. Three would buy it, one might buy it and one
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mazola &LR;  (5 ounces, $2.69 at Safeway) came in fourth. Most of
the panelists thought the flavor was fairly neutral, even though
one noticed a peppery aftertaste. Three might buy it; two would
not.
</P>
<P>
   The least expensive brand,  &UR; Trader Joe's &LR;  (6 ounces, $1.69 at
Trader Joe's), came in fifth. One panelist described it as
``ordinary and plain'' but others thought it left a particularly
greasy mouthfeel. One would buy it, two might buy it and two would
not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Canola Harvest, Naturally, Mazola Pro Chef
and Safeway, but they scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Flo Braker, cookbook author and Chronicle food
columnist; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San
Francisco; Roland Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and
Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe
Kati, San Francisco. A perfect score for any prduct would be 100.
All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
