<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: A Modest Stash of Wines Will Fit Almost Any 
 Occasion   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  A few years ago, a trend forecaster with the
trendy name of Faith Popcorn coined the term ``cocooning.'' She
meant that after a day on the fast track of modern commerce, folks
were retreating into the quiet and safety of their homes for meals
and entertainment. With today's hot economy and more disposable
income to go around, the cocoon may be unraveling a little, but
people still like to entertain at home.
<TEXT>
<P>
   An organized host or hostess will not only have a well-stocked
pantry, but a collection of wines to fit most every occasion. A
proper cellar with hundreds of bottles of all types of wines would
be nice, but the reality is that most people don't have the time,
money or storage space to build and maintain a large wine
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. With some basic guidelines, a modest collection
will handle the wine demands of most home entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Start by defining your personal style of entertaining. Casual
affairs work well with quick-and-easy wines, while more elaborate
dinners call for more serious wines, ones that are compatible with
specific dishes or entrees.
</P>
<P>
   Every home entertaining plan needs an all-purpose wine like
Champagne or sparkling wine. The range of styles, from ultra-dry
(Natural) to sweet (Doux) fits most food demands. Besides,
sparkling wines have a festive feeling; while the bubbles
contribute to the complexity and texture of the wine, a flute of
Champagne also sends a merry message.
</P>
<P>
   For inexpensive bubbly, try Freixenet Cordon Negro or Seaview
Australian Brut. California sparkling wines with class include Mumm
Napa Valley, Domaine Chandon, Gloria Ferrer, Domaine Carneros and
J. In general, Champagne is a bit more expensive, but try the
non-vintage bruts from Mumm, Moet &AMP; Chandon, Piper Heidsieck,
Taittinger, Pomerey and others.
</P>
<P>
   For casual dining or get-togethers, keep the wine light and
refreshing. Pinot Gris and its French soul mate, Viognier, share
similar flavors and both are good casual wines. Old standbys
include Riesling, Gewurztraminer and Chenin Blanc. More substantial
choices are lightly oaked Chardonnays and crisp citrusy Sauvignon
Blancs.
</P>
<P>
   California Pinot Gris tends to be lighter, more along the
Italian Pinot Grigio style. From California, try Callaway Pinot
Gris or Ivan Tamas Pinot Grigio.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon Pinot Gris, like Rex Hill, are more mid-range in terms of
flavor density and texture, while French Alsatian Pinot Gris
(Hugel, Trimbach) are fuller-bodied whites.
</P>
<P>
   The rising interest in Viognier has spread the wine's style
spectrum all over the board, but generally there are the more
fleshy-tropical fruit styles from California, Australia and
Washington, and the drier, more mineral styles from France.
California's Concannon and McDowell and Washington's Hogue Cellars
make very good Viognier. Oxford Landing Australia Viognier is one
of the best values on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Chenin Blancs from Chappellet and Pine Ridge are good choices,
or try a French Vouvray (Chenin Blanc) from Chateau Moncontour.
</P>
<P>
   Rieslings and Gewurztraminers are fresh and juicy from cool
growing areas like Anderson Valley. I like those produced by
Navarro, Husch and Greenwood Ridge. Also, try Trefethen Riesling
from Napa Valley and Fetzer's luscious Gewurztraminer.
</P>
<P>
   Any New Zealand Sauvignon Blanc (Villa Maria, Brancott) or
lightly grassy California Sauvignon, like Raymond, St. Supery,
Navarro, Geyser Peak, Lambert Bridge, fit nicely into any casual
food event.
</P>
<P>
   Chardonnays on the light side include Lockwood, Belvedere,
Fetzer Sundial, Callaway.
</P>
<P>
   Light casual reds usually include easy-drinking wines such as
California Gamays, French Beaujolais (Georges Dubeouf, Chateau de
la Chaize), Pinot Noir and some California Sangiovese. Lighter
Carneros Pinot Noirs like Saintsbury Garnet and Carneros Creek
Fleur de Carneros are great quaffers.
</P>
<P>
   More complex Pinots are available from both those wineries, plus
ones from Schug, Acacia, Etude, Edna Valley Vineyard, Sanford and
Keegan. A good alternative, especially with grilled meats is
California Sangiovese, like those from Swanson, Chappellet, Venezia
and Shenandoah Vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   Elaborate meals with multiple courses usually call for more
thought and planning _ and a more substantial wine budget. The
lineup of vintage Champagne, aged Chardonnay, Cabernet
Sauvignon/Bordeaux, Pinot Noir/Burgundy, Red Rhone/Shiraz/Syrah and
Italian reds from Piedmont and Tuscany often share the table with
finer meals.
</P>
<P>
   The process for selecting these wines, though, is the same. For
instance, if Viognier is your white wine of choice, you might want
to move up to a Northern Rhone Viognier from Condrieu (Guigal or
Chateau du Rozay), or even blow the wine budget on a bottle of
Chateau Grillet. German Rieslings and Gewurztraminers, or the drier
ones from the Alsace region of France, are about as good as it gets
from these two noble grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Although New World Chardonnays, especially from California and
Australia, are among the world's best, the ultimate Chardonnay
experience still comes from the Burgundy region of France. The list
of outstanding Burgundy producers, for red and white, is long, but
for value and reliability it's hard to top larger producers such as
Joseph Drouhin, Louis Jadot, Bochard P &LR; e &LR; re &AMP; Fils, Louis Latour
and Jaffelin.
</P>
<P>
   California's top Cabernet Sauvignon and Meritage reds are great
main-course wines. Look for Joseph Phelps Insignia, Beaulieu
Private Reserve Cabernet Sauvignon, St. Supery Meritage and a host
of others.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeaux choices include a long string of top-rated chateaux
such as Pichon-Lalande, Palmer, Margaux, Cos d'Estournel, Cheval
Blanc and Ausone. If these are too expensive but you still want the
Bordeaux experience, drop back to the so-called petit chateaux of
Fronsac, Castillon, Bourg and Blaye.
</P>
<P>
   However you fill your collection, consult your local wine
merchant for help in selecting the best bottles to fit your budget.
And, your merchant likely will have a few suggestions for other
wines not mentioned here.
</P>
<P>
   Now, kick back, raise your glass and let the entertainment
begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
