<SLUG> BC-ROVINGFEAST-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Roving Feast is a bi-weekly column by food writer
and cookbook author, Marlena Spieler. She will lead us through her
special world of food locally and abroad. &HT;     
 The Roving Feast: Racing to Summer's Sweet End   By Marlena Spieler  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; LONDON _  &LR; Summer evenings in Britain are long _ very long. At the
height of summer, the days will stretch until about 11 p.m., when
darkness finally falls. If it's not raining, it's simply delightful
to go to the races and sit outside sipping, nibbling, watching the
horses whizz by.
<P>
   Now in London it's heading toward fall, but in Northern
California the real summer is just beginning. In California, I grew
up going to the races at CalExpo and Golden Gate Fields. There is
something about the sound of the horses as they round the track,
the thrill of choosing your horse, oh, and what do they sell to
eat?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, though, I went to Ladies' Day at Royal Ascot. I got
lost in the endless crowds, rained on and sunburned, drank too much
Champagne, got muddy feet, and didn't win a penny. True, I saw The
Queen and her party in their carriage trotting to the races. Still,
I thought I'd give this year's Ascot a little break. So when one
day a London cab driver said to me, out of the blue, ``Have you
been to the Windsor Racetrack? Its small and lots of fun,'' I was
mildly interested. And when a second taxi driver asked me the same
thing a few days later I thought, ``OK, let's go to the races!''
</P>
<P>
   To get there, we rode a little train that chugs right into the
tiny town of Windsor and Eton, then grabbed a cab near Windsor
Palace and went into the countryside to the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor Racetrack, is, in a word, enchanting. It harks back to a
different, genteel era. There are no huge crowds even though the
place has a certain excitement. The grounds are green and
manicured, small enough not to get lost and, like a movie about
Olde Englande, swarming with characters from Central Casting. There
are men in bowler hats with umbrellas, women in summery frocks,
horsey folks, serious-looking jockeys and well as dodgy-looking
fellows munching on cockles and winkles and pouring over the Racing
Post.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MARLENA (59636 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In between the people you find the horses, with proud owners
brushing them, leading them around, and all admiring them. Everyone
had a moment for us, a few words, advice about a horse, a jockey, a
hot tip, a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the grassy knoll between the track and the winner's
circle is the important part of the place _ the food and drink.
</P>
<P>
   We spied a Champagne garden with wooden tables and benches set
on the grass. One of us wandered over to the winkles and cockles
stand and came back with jellied eels. There were fish and chips,
of course. Why do they always smell (and taste) so good? Another
stand sold sausages and ``beefburgers'' _ we gave that one a miss
(ask me sometime about British burgers).
</P>
<P>
   And there was a stand selling the most refreshing summer drink _
Pimms, bought by the glass or in great pitchers, served up with
handfuls of mint and cucumber and slices of orange, so refreshing
you don't know what hits you when it does.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I had a Pimms cocktail had been at a garden
reception at the British Embassy in Athens. The weather had been
hot and we had drunk heartily of the refreshing mixture to quench
our thirst. I think I have to accept the fact that I disgraced
myself, although I maintain that dancing on the tables and
imitating Janis Joplin is a friendly rather than disgraceful thing
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Pimms is such a convivial drink, especially sitting in the cool
shade of the warm evening at the races. Chunks of fruit, thin
slices of cucumber and leaves of fresh mint bobbed at the surface,
beckoning innocently. We drank, we placed our bets. I used the
method that works for me _ the cuteness of the name.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering my old favorite from the Grand National rodeo a few
years back, Benny The Dip (who rewarded me generously), I went for
Mon Dieu! Fantastic Light! Sweet Girl! We won first in the first
race, we lost in the second and placed in the third _ a more
profitable evening than any of us had had at work all day. I
decided to give up the day job and just bet on the races, a
decision I've since, sensibly, given up. And I decided that next
warm evening it was definitely going to be Pimms Cup.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MARLENA (59636 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Marlena Spieler, a food writer who divides her time between the
Bay Area and London, has been a frequent contributor to The
Chronicle's Food Section for nearly 12 years. She's the author of
more than 30 cookbooks, writes for magazines in Europe and the
United States and is a regular contributor to BBC Radio. You can
e-mail her at  &LR; food &LR; sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of MARLENA (59636 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; recipe  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; PIMMS CUP
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; note  &LR; Pimms cup is slightly bitter, quite alcoholic, and the basis
for Britain's quintessential summer refreshment. Nothing says
summer in Great Britain more than a Pimms. Being a freewheeling
drink, this is as close to a recipe as it gets. Serve on a hot
afternoon or evening. If you have access to borage flowers, with
their pretty blue color and cucumber-y flavor, freeze them in ice
cubes and float them in your Pimms. You can make as much of this as
you like _ say, in a big punch bowl, and as you need more, just add
to the bowl as the party progresses. It is that sort of drink. I
like the salad-in-a-glass quality, too _ so refreshing on a summer
evening.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ingred  &LR;  &QL; 
INGREDIENTS:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; _ &LR; 2 parts Pimms (this you buy in a bottle)
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 1 part gin
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 5 parts chilled ginger ale or 7Up-type drink
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Lots of ice
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Juice of 1/2 to 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; English hothouse cucumber, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Mint sprigs
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Oranges, diced or sliced, some slices with their peel left
on, reserved to perch on glasses as garnish
</P>
<P>
   &LR; instruct  &LR; INSTRUCTIONS:  &LR; Combine the Pimms, gin, ginger ale,
ice, lime juice, cucumber, mint and orange. Garnish each glass with
an orange slice.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; stats  &LR; Due to its general nature, this recipe contains no &LR; 
 &LR; analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; recipe  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; MINI-CHICKEN TIKKA CANAPES
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; note  &LR; This is modern British food with echoes of The Raj.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ingred  &LR;  &QL; 
INGREDIENTS:
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR; 3 chicken breast halves, boned
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 2 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 1 teaspoon chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Tandoori or tikka paste (Patak makes a delicious though
strikingly red one), as needed
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 4 tablespoons plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; 1 tablespoon butter, melted, or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; About 3 tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Dash of ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Chopped cilantro, to taste
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Chopped mint, to taste
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Whole-wheat bread, cut into bite-size pieces, or pita
triangles
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Thinly sliced cucumber
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ &LR; Handful of lettuce-y greens
</P>
<P>
   &LR; instruct  &LR; INSTRUCTIONS:  &LR; Cut the chicken into bite-size chunks
then rub with most of the garlic (saving a little bit for the
dressing) and 1 tablespoon of the lemon juice, the ginger, as much
of the tandoori paste as you need, and 1 tablespoon of the yogurt.
Set aside to marinate for at least 30 minutes. If you plan to
marinate it longer, cover and refrigerate for up to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Blot the chicken dry, then brush with the melted butter. Place
on a broiler pan and broil for about 2 minutes, turning once, or
until the chicken is done.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; st  &LR;   &UR; To make the sauce/dressing:  &LR; Mix together the remaining 3
tablespoons yogurt, the remaining garlic, the mayonnaise, cumin,
cilantro and mint.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Spread a bit of the dressing on the bread, then top
with a slice of cucumber, a chunk of chicken and a tuft of greens.
</P>
<P>
   Eat right away. Then have another glass of Pimms.
</P>
<P>
   Serves about 6 as nibbles, though you can make these into big
sandwiches and serve 3 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; stats  &LR;   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 200 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 14 g fat (4 g saturated), 56 mg cholesterol, 106 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 0 fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades vary &LR; 
 &LR; and are difficult to estimate. Variables include the type of &LR; 
 &LR; food, marinating time and amount of surface area. Therefore, &LR;   &LR; the
marinade is not included in this analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
