<SLUG> BC-SECRET-BREAD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 Secrets Of Success: Brix's Sticks Make Snappy Party Bread   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Brix is a beautiful restaurant in St. Helena
serving delicious, innovative East-West food. Unfortunately, I
always fill up on the breadsticks _ I even ask for seconds and then
pick at them the rest of the meal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The breadsticks from former chef Tod Michael Kawachi are thin,
crisp and salty, with an almost nutty flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The 100-seat dining room, broken up by partitions, is given an
expansive feel with a peaked wood ceiling and airy yellow and green
color scheme. Ironwork shaped like branches and leaves form the
backs of chairs, which are surprisingly comfortable. A large open
kitchen featuring a wood-fired oven stretches along two walls at
the back.
</P>
<P>
   It all works to create a visual package that fits the casual
sophistication of the valley.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Brix, 7377 St. Helena Hwy., St. Helena; (707) 944-2749. &LR; 
 &LR; Lunch and dinner daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The seasoning. &LR;  Freshly grated Parmesan cheese, salt, pepper
and cayenne are sprinkled on the dough, which is then folded and
rolled, trapping the seasoned cheese in the middle. This adds
flavor and prevents the cheese from burning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Two kinds of pepper. &LR;  Cayenne and black pepper give the thin
breadsticks a double whammy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CRISPY BREADSTICKS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup lukewarm water (about 100)
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   21/4 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve the yeast in the water in a large bowl. Let stand for
about 5 minutes, until the mixture is foamy.
</P>
<P>
   Add the flour, olive oil and 11/2 teaspoons of the salt; mix by
hand using a rubber spatula until a smooth dough forms. Cover the
bowl with plastic wrap and let stand in a warm, draft-free place
until doubled in size, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cheese, black pepper, cayenne and the remaining 3/4
teaspoon salt in a small bowl. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Line a large baking sheet with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the dough into 4 pieces and roll each piece on a lightly
floured surface into a rectangle about 1/4 inch thick and 14 to 16
inches long. Sprinkle the dough with the cheese mixture and fold in
half.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out the dough again to its previous size. Cut the dough
into very thin, long strips measuring 1/8 inch wide by about 16
inches long.
</P>
<P>
   Place the strips on the prepared baking sheet and bake for 10 to
12 minutes, or until golden.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the breadsticks to racks to cool. Serve at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 48 breadsticks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER BREADSTICK: &LR;   &LR; 30 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 5 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 1 g fat (0 saturated), 0 cholesterol, 108 mg
sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
