<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1981 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-HARVESTMENU-SFCHRON &LR;      09-05 1869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVESTMENU-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Alfresco Menu Celebrates Autumn  &HT;       
 By Joanne Weir  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; This time of year always makes me nervous. The
summer fog has cleared from the bay and the winds have subsided
somewhat. But will autumn bring its usual perfect weather? How many
more lunches can I expect to enjoy outside?
<P>
   This is the time I try to take advantage of the weather and
seasonal ingredients, and spend as much time as possible at the
table _ not just eating, but talking and enjoying the company.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, I try to get as much done ahead as possible, and
that's how I've created this al fresco menu. The first course _
Endive with Gorgonzola, Caramelized Onions and Fig Jam _ can be
made ahead and passed while guests are standing and talking and
makes a terrific entree to the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Recently in France, I saw tartine salads on just about every
menu. A tartine is simply an open-faced sandwich topped with
anything from smoked salmon, grilled tuna with aioli, roasted
peppers or grilled fresh sardines, to this one made with roasted
tomato tapenade and creamy goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   All summer long, when I find good Roma tomatoes, I oven-dry or
roast them and store them in sealable plastic bags in the freezer
to use year-round. For this dish, make the roasted tomato tapenade
up to a couple days in advance. A few hours before serving, wash
the greens and make the vinaigrette. Minutes before, toast the
bread, top with goat cheese and the tapenade and toss the salad.
Simple!
</P>
<P>
   During late summer with early hints of autumn, I start to cook
dishes that are a bit more substantial. Veal Chops with Olives,
Capers and Crisp Sage fill the bill. This is a dish that should be
done at the last minute, but don't let that scare you. It's easy
and the results are impressive. Serve the veal chops with roasted
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, the polenta custard cake is a breeze. The polenta,
flavored with sugar and orange zest, is creamy and delicious and
can be made a day in advance, as can the pears.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it _ a simple menu that will impress your guests
without spending hours in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ALFRESCO DINNER WINES
</P>
<P>
   Although casual in style, this Mediterranean menu is chock full
of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Endive with Gorgonzola, Caramelized Onions &AMP; Fig Jam.  &LR; The
topping on the endive leaves is dense, salty and sweet. Your best
bet is a fresh wine with crisp acidity to stand up to the cheese
and yet enough fruit concentration to balance and marry the sweet
and savory flavors, like Cakebread Napa Valley Sauvignon Blanc 1999
($21). It's classic in style but abundant in flavor and texture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Tartine Salad with Goat Cheese &AMP; Roasted Tomato Tapenade. &LR; 
Goat cheese and tomatoes are classic companions for Sauvignon
Blanc. The like acidities balance each other on the palate to
produce a delicious marriage of food and wine. You could continue
with the Cakebread Sauvignon Blanc through this course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Veal Chops with Olives, Capers &AMP; Sage.  &LR; An aggressive white
wine such as a white Chateauneuf-du-Pape will best show off this
dish. The Vieux Telegraphe Chateauneuf-du-Pape Blanc ($33) from the
Rhone Valley is dry, full-bodied and flinty, with earthy mineral
flavors, and satin textures that beautifully complement the
caper-olive sauce and the veal.
</P>
<P>
   If you insist on red wine with meat, try Marc Bredif Chinon
1997. This Loire Valley wine is made of Cabernet Franc grapes,
which give a touch of herb and pepper to the dry red fruit flavor.
The tannins are low enough to meld with the sauce for a delightful
match.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Polenta Custard Cake with Cinnamon Poached Pears.  &LR; Try Delas
Muscat Beaumes de Venise ($23, 500 ml) from France. Lusciously rich
fruit flavors complement the pear and cake with orange rind, while
matching the spicy cinnamon-clove flavors of the poaching liquid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Diane Teitelbaum &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ENDIVE WITH GORGONZOLA, CARAMELIZED ONIONS &AMP; FIG JAM
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 yellow onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 large heads of Belgian endive
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces Gorgonzola cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fig jam
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Warm the olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the
onions, sugar and thyme; season with salt and pepper. Cook,
stirring occasionally, for 30 to 40 minutes, or until the onions
turn a caramel color and are very soft. This mixture may be made 1
day in advance. Store in a covered container in the refrigerator.
Rewarm before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Cut 1/2 inch off the bottom of each head of endive. Discard the
outer leaves. Separate the remaining leaves (except the inner tiny
leaves, which may be discarded) and place them in a single layer
under damp towels. This may be done up to 4 hours ahead of time.
You should have approximately 36 leaves.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, fill the base of each endive leaf with warm
caramelized onions. Top with 1/2 teaspoon Gorgonzola and a dollop
of fig jam. Arrange on a platter and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 36.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER LEAF: &LR;   &LR; 40 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fat (1 g saturated), 4 mg cholesterol, 87 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TARTINE SALAD WITH GOAT CHEESE &AMP; ROASTED TOMATO TAPENADE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Tomato Tapenade
</P>
<P>
   3 anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cured black olives, such as nicoise or kalamata, pitted
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons capers, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon herbes de Provence
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup oven-roasted tomatoes, finely chopped (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   The Toasts
</P>
<P>
   6 large slices rustic coarse-textured bread
</P>
<P>
   1 whole garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh goat cheese at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   The Salad
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 cups young tender salad greens
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; To make the tapenade:  &LR; Soak the anchovies in cold water for
10 minutes. Pat dry and mash. Place the anchovies, olives, garlic,
capers, lemon zest and herbes de Provence in a food processor.
Pulse a few times until the mixture becomes a rough paste. Add
pepper, the lemon juice and tomatoes. Pulse 2 times. Season with
salt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the toasts:  &LR; Toast or grill the bread. Rub one side of
each toast with the garlic clove. Cut each toast in half
diagonally. Spread the toasts with goat cheese, then top with
tomato tapenade, spreading it evenly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the salad:  &LR; Whisk together the vinegar and oil in a
small bowl. Season with salt and pepper. Toss the greens with the
vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Place 2 pieces of toast on each serving plate,
overlapping them slightly, then pile the salad on the toasts.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 410 calories, &LR;   &LR; 12 g protein, 25 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 29 g fat (8 g saturated), 20 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 2,885
mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; OVEN-ROASTED TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds plum tomatoes, cored, cut in half lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the tomatoes cut-sides up on a baking sheet and sprinkle
with salt. Let stand at room temperature for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 200 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place the tomatoes in the oven and bake for 4 to 5 hours, or
until they are almost dry, yet still slightly soft and plump.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER RECIPE: &LR;   &LR; 120 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 27 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 1 g fat (0 saturated), 0 cholesterol, 4,314 mg sodium, 9 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; VEAL CHOPS WITH OLIVES, CAPERS &AMP; CRISP SAGE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   20 large sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 rib-eye veal chops, about 8 to 10 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cured black or green olives, pitted, very coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup capers
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Warm about 1/4 inch of olive oil in a skillet over medium-high
heat. When the oil is hot, add the sage leaves and fry for 30 to 60
seconds, or until crisp. Remove from the pan and drain on paper
towels. Reserve for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon of the extra virgin olive oil in a large
skillet over medium heat. Add the veal chops and saute for 5 to 6
minutes, or until golden. Turn the chops, season with salt and
pepper and saute for 5 to 6 minutes, or until golden and
medium-rare. Transfer to a warmed platter, cover with foil and keep
warm.
</P>
<P>
   Increase the heat under the skillet to medium-high. Add the
remaining 1 tablespoon olive oil and the garlic and cook for about
15 seconds, or until the garlic is soft. Add the wine and simmer
for 3 to 5 minutes, or until it has almost evaporated. Add the
chicken broth and cook for 3 to 5 minutes, or until reduced by
half. Stir in the olives, capers and chopped sage. Add the lemon
juice, then season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, divide chops among plates and spoon the sauce, olives
and capers over the top and around the sides. Garnish with crispy
sage leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 575 calories, &LR;   &LR; 47 g protein, 2 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 39 g fat (6 g saturated), 189 mg cholesterol, 3,527 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 0
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; POLENTA CUSTARD CAKE WITH CINNAMON-POACHED PEARS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Pears
</P>
<P>
   2 cups port
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   6 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   12 whole cloves, tied together in cheesecloth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 Bosc pears, peeled, quartered and cored
</P>
<P>
   The Cake
</P>
<P>
   4 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup + 1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup polenta
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   4 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Grated rind of 1 large orange
</P>
<P>
   Powdered sugar for dusting
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Combine the port, water, cinnamon, cloves and sugar in a
saucepan over medium heat and bring to a boil. Add the pears and
simmer for 20 to 30 minutes, or until they are tender and can be
easily pierced with a fork. Discard the cloves and reserve the
pears and syrup separately. Boil the poaching liquid over high heat
until reduced by half.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the cake:  &LR; Place the milk and sugar in a saucepan and
bring to a boil over medium-high heat. Gradually add the polenta,
whisking constantly. Simmer until it is very thick, about 25
minutes. Let cool to lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 375 degrees. Butter a 9-inch cake pan.
</P>
<P>
   Stir the whole egg, egg yolks, butter and orange rind into the
polenta. Spread the batter into the prepared pan and bake for 30 to
35 minutes, or until the cake just begins to turn golden and is
firm to the touch in the center. Unmold onto a cooling rack and let
cool for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, cut the cake into wedges and place on individual
plates. Spoon the pears, cinnamon sticks and reduced poaching
liquid around the cake, dust with powdered sugar and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 535 &LR;   &LR; calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 82 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 14 g fat (7 g saturated), 164 mg cholesterol, 80 mg
sodium, 5 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
