<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HIGH-TECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HIGH-TECH INDUSTRY PUSHES CONGRESS TO PASS LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a month left before Congress is set to
adjourn, the high-tech industry urged lawmakers Tuesday to move
quickly on immigration, trade and tax measures before leaving for
their final campaign push.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the election season now upon us time is running short, so
speedy action is paramount,'' said William T. Archey, president of
the American Electronics Association, a Washington-based trade
group representing more than 3,000 high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Archey said that for his group the most important pending
legislation is a bill that would boost the number of so-called H-1B
visas that allow college-educated foreigners to work in the United
States for up to six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortages of high-tech workers continue to shortchange the
American economy by limiting the capacity of high-tech firms to
grow and innovate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the law limits the number of H-1B visas to 115,000.
It would fall to 107,500 in 2001 and 65,000 in 2002. The proposed
legislation would increase the H-1B visa cap to 200,000 a year for
2001, 2002 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``With unemployment at record lows, high-tech companies are
literally putting projects on hold as they wait for more workers,''
Archey said.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of high-tech visas initially had bipartisan
support in both the House and Senate. But consensus broke down when
some House Democrats sought to link the issue to the granting of
amnesty to some 2 million undocumented immigrants from some Latin
American countries _ a move opposed by many Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Archey said the high-tech industry also wants to the Senate to
pass a bill granting China permanent trading privileges with the
United States, which most other countries enjoy, without annual
review.
</P>
<P>
   ``America simply can't turn its back on legislation that will
open up the world's largest market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which the House passed, 237 to 197, in May after
heated debate, is expected to reach the Senate floor for a vote
next week. Although the measure is opposed by organized labor, it
is a top priority of President Clinton and Senate Majority Trent
Lott and is expected to pass. However, the vote on it could be
slowed by debate over a controversial companion measure by Sens.
Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., that would
urge the White House to impose sanctions if China continues to give
weapons of mass destruction to rogue nations.The high-tech leaders
also asked Congress to pass bills that would extend for five years
the current moratorium on new Internet taxes and expand a tax
credit for technology companies that engage in research and
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the survival for brick-and-mortar retailers is clearly
important to the nation's economy and entrepreneurial spirit, we
shouldn't be too hasty in implementing taxes on the Internet that
would otherwise have a far more drastic effect on the growth of our
thriving economy,'' Archey said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
