<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DEMS _ WASHINGTON _ As the Senate reconvenes, President
Clinton and Democratic leaders on Tuesday outline their
end-of-session priorities at the White House. GOP senators expected
to respond on Capitol Hill. (Mollison, Cox News Service). 12
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush on Tuesday
announced a $158 billion plan to help seniors pay for prescription
drugs, improve benefits and shore up finances of the health program
that ensures millions of elderly Americans. The governor's proposal
would pay at least one-fourth of the cost of prescription drug
coverage, whether seniors choose a new Medicare benefit or a
private plan. The elderly poor would get drug plans for free. Under
Bush's proposal, health plans that participate in Medicare would be
required to provide a prescription drug benefit. Medicare currently
offers no prescription coverage. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ Al Gore starts a two day trot through Ohio in Columbus
Tuesday, and details economic plans: to wipe out national debt by
2012, protect social security and medicare by putting them in
``lock boxes,'' and spellingout his savings plus Social Security
plan, that would allow for private investment in addition to social
security. (Hershsey, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BOYSCOUT _ School board to discuss Wednesday night whether Boy
Scout troops can used schools for meetings if the group won't let
gays be in their troops or act as a leader. (Flannery, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-UN _ NEW YORK _ President Clinton arrives here today to
do far more than give his last big speech before a major gathering
of his peers, he also hopes to make progress on Mideast peace and
heal some wounds with Russia and China. Developing. (Deans, Cox
News Service) WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, Religion;
Subcategory, Other.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by 5 p.m. EST on the NYT Wire in both
International and Washington categories
</P>
<P>
   GA-SENATE-MATTINGLY _ GOP Senate hopeful Mack Mattingly hung out
with some high-profile Republicans last week _ Dick Cheney in
Atlanta on Wednesday and Nathan Deal in the 9th District on
Thursday. He's hoping for some coattail momentum to help boost his
name recognition after having not been on the ballot for 14 years.
But wonks say he'll need more than that _ namely lots of TV
advertising to become more familiar with voters. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-HOMES WASHINGTON _ Government investigators, industry
leaders and independent analysts discuss why one in every 10
nursing homes in the nation has gone bankrupt at a Senate Aging
committee hearing at 2:15 EDT Tuesday. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, Science/Medicine, Medicine
</P>
<P>
   PRESCRIPTION-DRUGS _ WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
announces details of his plan to provide prescription drug coverage
for the elderly. How it compares with Al Gore's plan, and reaction
from elderly groups, the insurance industry, Democrats and others.
(Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, National, Politics
</P>
<P>
