<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2021 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LILEKS-DEBATES-COLUMN     09-05 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-DEBATES-COLUMN-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NOBODY SHOULD EXPECT TO LEARN MUCH FROM DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Sept. 5, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(AT)nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This campaign needs fewer debates, not more. It certainly
doesn't need a debate about the debates, but we can't avoid those,
either. How many? Where? What subjects? Larry King as moderator?
Peter Jennings? Regis Philbin? Lifeline calls permitted for foreign
policy questions? Lovely parting gifts for the loser?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has weighed in: ``What's needed,'' Gore said, ``is to
respect the right of the American people to see these debates on
all the networks in prime time the way it has been done since
1988.'' Of course, we must respect these ancient, time-honored
traditions, particularly those that stretch back to the
mist-shrouded era of 1988. But do the American people really have a
right to see the debates on all the networks in prime time?
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution is remarkably silent on the matter. One could
extrapolate from the ban on ``cruel and unusual punishment'' that
the Founders would be opposed to the debates taking place at all.
Certainly putting them on all three channels is cruel to the poor,
who cannot afford cable and thus are stuck, like the protagonist of
``A Clockwork Orange,'' staring in horror as one rhetorical
atrocity after another streams from the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs them? Who needs a stilted debate to make up their
mind? People who are undecided haven't been paying attention, or
they don't care. Please, no balderdash about how folks are too busy
to pay attention to the issues. Anyone who wants to know what Gore
or Bush is all about is perfectly capable of doing so. Put down the
People magazine, pick up a political journal. Put down the remote,
read a newspaper. Or point the remote to a channel that doesn't
consist entirely of greased men hitting each other in the head with
folding chairs. It's amazing what you learn when you forswear
sports and sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll learn little from the debates. The formats are so
dull, so strict, that nothing really gets said. Every exchange can
be boiled down to this:
</P>
<P>
   Larry King: Vice President Gore, tell us about your drug plan to
help working families.
</P>
<P>
   Gore: My drug plan is good for working families.
</P>
<P>
   Larry King: Very well, then. Gov. Bush, tell us why your drug
plan won't kill every American over the age of 12, as some are
saying.
</P>
<P>
   Bush: Larry, my drug plan is good for America.
</P>
<P>
   Larry: Mr. Gore, a response?
</P>
<P>
   Gore: Larry, he's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there might be a ``spirited exchange,'' in which someone
gets a little peppery and lands a feather-light quip. But what we
really want is this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Drug plan? Bush, your idea of a drug plan used to be telling
your dealer when and where you'd meet him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Mr. Vice Lackey, given that lip-chewing sex maniac you
work for, I'd rather have a white nose than a brown one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the ties come off and it's out to the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   No, it wouldn't be the level of Lincoln-Douglas, but those days
are gone for good. We'll never get people to sit in the hot sun
slapping horseflies while two men discuss weighty ideas in barely
audible unamplified voices. Besides, that was all there was to do
back then. People had fewer entertainment options in those days. No
TV. No radio. No movies. On Saturday night Pappy made
shadow-pictures of rabbits on the wall with candlelight. And if
Pappy lost both his hands in a farming accident, well, then it was
The Adventures of Log and Stump again, and quitcher complainin'.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we don't have issues like they had back then. The issue
of slavery has been settled. We lost; it's just a question of
whether we work for the government until May 17 or July 9.
</P>
<P>
   This is where you really need the third-party candidates. They
should all be part of the debate _ Ichabod Nader, Pat Buchanan,
Harry Browne and his Goblet of Flaming Libertarianism, and all the
rest. Third-party candidates have nothing to lose; they throw bombs
and poke their cutlasses in the fatty shanks of the mainstream
candidates. The events might devolve into a free-for-all, but who'd
complain? The debates are little more than pro wrestling for
political junkies. Just as scripted. Just as thrilling. And just as
real.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
