<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING DESERVES BETTER OF HIS FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether he really did say it first, or whether he borrowed it,
Wilt Chamberlain certainly had it right.
</P>
<P>
   For it is to Wilt we attribute the phrase, ``Nobody loves
Goliath.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger they are, the more we resent them. At least, that's
the way we regard our basketball players. Being tall in other
sports is actually viewed as a handicap. Randy Johnson, for
example, is one of the few very tall pitchers of note in the
history of baseball. 'Tis said the mechanics of a windup get too
complicated when a man is much bigger than, say, 6 feet 4 inches,
which also happens to be plenty tall enough for either a football
or a hockey player. But being tall in basketball is the ultimate
unteachable asset.
</P>
<P>
   But being tall also brings expectations, and fans very often
refuse to acknowledge that not all big guys are inherently created
equal. Being tall helps, but being tall without the accompanying
benefit of being athletic makes for a very perilous basketball
existence. There can be few lonelier existences on this earth than
that of the klutzy, lumbering big man. It's hard enough just
getting through the day as the Brobdingnagian in the world of the
Lilliputians without being subjected to the verbal abuse of angry
fans when you are outplayed on the basketball floor by someone half
a foot smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Big men are seldom accorded the benefit of the doubt. When
things go sour, the first targets are the big men. People can't
relate to them, on any level. They think that what these people do
must be easy, and, of course, it isn't. On a personal basis, they
just can't, well, relate to them the way they can to medium-sized
players or small players.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up and big men just aren't inherently lovable. The
one conspicuous exception may be Shaquille O'Neal, whose distinct
personality has caught on with young people. But almost every other
big man has either been mysterious or actively disliked.
</P>
<P>
   Would that Patrick Ewing were merely ``actively disliked.'' The
feelings pouring out of fans and press during the ill-fated attempt
his team made to trade him a couple of weeks back were just plain
venomous. How could a man who plays hard all the time, competes
when injured, is never in trouble with the law, and has
accomplished so much become such a reviled figure?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Ewing has always needed a good personal publicist, but
he is hardly the inept and evil figure he was made out to be by
segments of the New York press and fandom. The New York Post, a
paper without boundaries, actually managed to out-Post itself with
the back page headline ``GOOD RIDDANCE.'' Ewing may not have been
able to deliver an NBA championship to New York, but one may quite
legitimately argue that he is the best player in the history of the
franchise. Isn't such a bitter sendoff just a teeny bit over the
top?
</P>
<P>
   It was written that he was poisoned by John Thompson. It was
written that he made too many foolish ``guarantees'' he was unable
to back up. It was written that he had become an impediment to a
quicker, younger Knicks team and was unwilling to alter his game to
suit the changing situation. It was written that he had demanded
the ball too often and missed too many big shots. It was written
that he was arrogant and aloof and that he had never tried hard
enough to make himself accessible to the media and, therefore,
understandable to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   There is some truth in all of this, but only some. The further
truth is that the team's record with him, even in the past two
years when he was supposed to be such a drag, was far superior to
its record without him. The further truth is that he is an
old-fashioned low post center who scores, rebounds, and clogs the
middle, even at age 38. The truth is that his exemplary work habits
make him a model for all young players.
</P>
<P>
   It is regrettable that he did not do a better job of selling
himself. Friends say he is warm and witty, and he would never show
that side to either the press or the fans. Much was made from an
incident last season when he refused to sign an autograph, saying
he never signed on game day, when he wasn't even activated at the
time. If it happened, it was a dumb thing to say and there is no
defense. But should that foolish action outweigh 15 years of
valiant service to his team?
</P>
<P>
   Just because a man is not a saint does not necessarily mean he
must be a villain. You never would have thought Ewing had scored
more than 20 points a game for 13 consecutive seasons or become the
all-time team leader in scoring, rebounding, and shot-blocking, or
been an original Dream Teamer or been voted as one of the 50
greatest players. Vilifying such a man is ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so bad in New York that last week support eventually
materialized in a very curious place. In an editorial headlined ``A
Sour Fadeout for the Ewing Era,'' The New York Times (known in
these here parts as ``Daddy'') came passionately to Ewing's
defense. ``The failure to win,'' it said, ``is attributable less to
Ewing than to the coaches who misused him and to the executives who
failed to provide him with a credible supporting cast until too
late in his career . . . As a star with the big paycheck, Ewing has
been a convenient target for these failures. His stoic style, which
strikes many people as surly, also left him exposed. But the blame
for the missing championship lies elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing is one of the great big men of all-time. This is
beyond dispute. Rather than bemoan his shortcomings, the fans
should ponder how bad basketball life in New York would have been
this past decade and a half without him. Were he a guard or a
forward, he would be revered. But Patrick Ewing is 7 feet tall, an
unloved Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
