<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WorldCom buying Intermedia to get Web-hosting Digex
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WorldCom has agreed to a $6 billion deal to buy Intermedia,
mostly as a way of gaining control of Digex, a hot firm
specializing in Web hosting.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will give WorldCom the lead in a still-nascent
market that is expected to explode along with the Internet, said
John Stupka, president of ventures and alliances for the
Mississippi-based company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow WorldCom to have a first-mover advantage, to
let WorldCom become a category leader,'' he said. ``The name Digex
in managed Web hosting is a `wow.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Digex deal is the first since WorldCom's purchase of Sprint
was blocked by federal and European regulators in July.
</P>
<P>
   While falling far short of that gargantuan merger _ which would
have been worth well over $100 billion _ Digex shines a light on
WorldCom's plan to extend its reach into business use of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The market remains modest. Digex has annual revenue of less than
$200 million. However, Forrester Research predicts managed Web and
application hosting will account for $17 billion in spending by
2004. Gartner Research consultants are even more bullish,
predicting the market will be $22 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Few companies with a Web presence manage the infrastructure used
in their own sites. Instead, control of the high-speed lines and
powerful servers needed is farmed out to others. WorldCom's UUNet
subsidiary is already a leader in providing high-speed access.
</P>
<P>
   Possession of Digex will let WorldCom handle more of a
customer's needs, Stupka said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for WorldCom to pay $39 a share for Intermedia
stock and to take on $2.4 billion in company debt.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom will wind up owning 55 percent of Digex stock but with
94 percent of the company's voting interest.
</P>
<P>
   The companies expect to complete the transaction early next
year. All three boards have approved the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Digex, based in Maryland, was purchased in 1997 by Intermedia
for $150 million. A portion of Digex shares was sold publicly last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa-based Intermedia is one of dozens of competitive local
exchange companies, or CLECs, that offer businesses
telecommunications services, often as a rival to incumbent firms
like BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Because WorldCom in many places offers some of those same
services, some units or operations will be shed, Stupka said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is one of the markets in which offerings of the two
companies overlap.
</P>
<P>
   Like some other CLECs, Intermedia has of late run into financial
trouble and has projected a decline in sales this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company reportedly entertained _ and rejected _ a
$22-a-share acquisition bid from Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   An offer from Exodus Communications to buy just Digex also was
spurned, according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Intermedia stock jumped briefly in June after reports of a rumor
that it was in talks to be bought by Broadwing.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom stock dipped $3.13 a share Tuesday to close at $33.81 _
close to its 52-week low and down from a high of more than $61 last
fall. A.G. Edwards upgraded WorldCom to a buy recommendation from
maintain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
