<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGHAM CORNERED ON PATRIOTS OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Tampa Bay was back on its own 10-yard line,
doing nothing but going backward early in Sunday's game. The Bucs
had a first down, and Antonio Langham, the Patriots' cornerback,
was in his zone coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing in that coverage is that if we see the ball thrown,''
said Langham, ``we break on it. ``(Jacquez Green) ran his route and
I saw him go, and I was coming in, and the ball sort of went
through his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The pass from Tampa Bay quarterback Shaun King, not one of the
most accurate passers in the National Football League, was off
line, perhaps a step or two ahead of his receiver at about the
20-yard line. As Langham jumped inside the slant route, King's pass
``hit me in the chest a little bit,'' said Langham. ``I almost had
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game might have turned on that play, or as New England coach
Bill Belichick put it, on one of ``30 other plays.'' Langham might
have been able to return the interception for a TD, the Patriots
could have been up, 10-0, and Tampa Bay would not have been able to
bounce fullback Mike Alstott off tackle all afternoon long.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, Langham's week, if not his season, might have turned
if he had made the interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been sweet music,'' said Langham. ``The pass
was tipped and it went through Jacquez's hands and it hit me right
in the chest. And I thought I still had a chance for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Langham has been battered and bruised the last few seasons,
battered and bruised in his ego and his confidence. If a receiver
went by him, he'd quickly go into a shell ``and I'd be wondering
what's going to be happening next.'' He had played very poorly,
most notably in San Francisco, but Belichick gave him another
chance here in New England. A last chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, as far as training camp went, as far as the
exhibition season went, my confidence is back,'' said Langham.
``And it was back (Sunday). I was out on the field saying, `Hey,
don't worry about this stuff no more. You all right. Just keep
playing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And an interception only five minutes into his return from the
deepest of depths would have been proof of that. But Langham did
not hold onto King's pass, Langham did not make the interception,
Langham did not dance into the end zone with the football. The ball
bounced off his chest.
</P>
<P>
   And . . .
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, when the Bucs had a third-and-9 from their
11-yard line, Green again went downfield and Langham again was on
the coverage. The Patriots put heavy pressure on King, and a stop
by the defense in this situation, against a young quarterback and
with the home crowd in a full uproar, was almost expected. Again
King threw to Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, that was just a good pass, a good throw and
catch,'' Langham said of the back-breaking 33-yard completion that
took the Bucs out of the shadow of their goalposts. ``He put it
right where I couldn't get it. Still, that's one of the two plays I
wish I could take back because I was so close. It'd be different if
I was playing the coverages and I was out of position and they
burned me deep. But it was good coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Langham was right; he was not badly beaten on the play. Yet the
pass was completed. Just as so many passes have been completed
again him the last few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   `` `They get theirs,' '' Langham recalled thinking, `` `and next
time it'll be my turn.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The game played on. Just before the half, Langham was on Green
and once again came close to making a drive-stopping play. King
threw a short pass to Green from Patriots' 41, Langham went for the
ball but did not tip it, and Green caught it. The receiver then
spun free of Langham's tackle and went 33 yards down the sideline.
The next play was the fake spike play by King and the Bucs had a
TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a situation where we were playing man and we were
trying to be aggressive,'' said Langham. ``He tried to run a slant
on me and I had him _ I had good coverage _ and I went for the
ball, to break the ball up. But he caught it and I tried to lock
him with my outside hand, but he spun out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, close to a making a good play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, yeah,'' Langham muttered with disgust. ``There's a slim
margin of error in this business. It can go either way, something
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Every offensive coordinator the Patriots face this season would
be foolish not to test Langham. Is Langham the efficient and
aggressive cornerback who played for Belichick in Cleveland five
years ago or is Langham the shell of an NFL corner that he was the
last few years?
</P>
<P>
   Langham knows this. Langham expects it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there'll be times when they'll be coming at me,''
said Langham. ``Like (Sunday), later on in the game, they started
to come at me again to see, well, see if he is the same person. Is
he the same type of person who'll go into a shell or not?''
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, there was no shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started to come at me and I started to come, too,'' said
Langham. ``I'm a different person, I'm in a different place, and
I'm in a place where I'm a whole lot more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   And which person is now in New England? The Antonio Langham of
the Cleveland Browns from the mid 1990s or the Langham who could do
nothing in San Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the Antonio who first came with the Browns,'' said
Langham. ``And I said, `Maybe a couple of plays went against me,
but the Antonio of the last couple of years, even though I had good
coverage, would have gone into a shell.' But now it's just a matter
of, `Hey, you were there; you just have to make the play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Patriots can ever find a semblance of a professional
offensive line is now the question of the moment for the team. But
a much more personal question is whether Antonio Langham once again
can find himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're going to keep coming at me,'' said Langham.
``There were times when they tried to come at me and I made some
plays. And that's what I've got to do _ just keep working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
