u e BC-SANTAFE-OPERA-ART-2TA     09-05 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTAFE-OPERA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR OF SANTA FE OPERA LOOKS BACK ON 43 YEARS OF INNOVATION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ The costumes, props and scenery used in the
Santa Fe Opera's five summer productions are being packed for
storage, and the singers and choristers who held the spotlight are
en route to their next engagements. But as the company's backstage
staff wraps up the loose ends, a more figurative curtain is
descending, slowly and gracefully, on a long stretch of the
company's history. On Sept. 30, just as the new concert season gets
under way in the world's arts centers, John Crosby will step down
as the general director of this adventurous company, which he
founded in 1957 and has run since.
</P>
<P>
   Having built an opera house in the middle of the Southwestern
desert then quickly establishing it as an important stop on the
summer festival circuit, Crosby, 74, will turn over the reins to
Richard Gaddes. As the associate general director for the last five
years, Gaddes has been Crosby's right-hand man; and as the founder
of a similar venture in St. Louis, he knows about running an opera
company. He has invited Crosby to return to conduct Strauss operas,
his specialty, next summer and in 2002. Otherwise Crosby is to
exert no influence on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you stop, you stop,'' Crosby said, speaking
barely above a whisper throughout an interview in his office on the
company's grounds here. ``I think it's very important that you
recognize that you can't manage in the background. You can't be
breathing down somebody's neck.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that relinquishing the company will be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think I haven't thought about anything else for 45
years,'' he said. ``I fall asleep worrying about it and wake up
worrying about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A visitor to the company's comfortable, technologically
up-to-date theater might not fully appreciate how daring was
Crosby's notion of establishing a company here when he began
contemplating it in the early 1950s. The wide highway that connects
Albuquerque, the closest major airport, to Santa Fe was then a
rustic two-lane road, and the drive that now takes 50 minutes took
two and a half hours. More to the point, Santa Fe itself was not
clamoring for an opera company. But Crosby said it had the kind of
audience that would support one.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, and very important, Santa Fe had a long history
of what I like to call hospitality to the arts,'' said Crosby, who
was born in New York but began visiting Santa Fe as a child because
its dry climate was good for his asthma. ``It was a community that
had a flourishing art colony, if you will: painters, poets,
writers, sculptors. And strangely, from that galaxy of the arts,
music was rather missing. So it seemed to me that the community
would receive this missing link warmly.''
</P>
<P>
   He assembled a company of 65 performers for his first season,
which opened with ``Madama Butterfly'' on July 3, 1957, just a few
days short of his 31st birthday. The budget that summer was
$110,000, about $60,000 of which he had raised in donations, with
the rest covered largely by ticket sales. For the season just ended
the company had a payroll of 550 and a budget of $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   Its home has expanded as well. Its first house was a 480-seat
open air theater, which burned down in 1967. A theater seating
1,890 served the company for 30 years and was replaced in 1998 by a
new 2,130-seat house designed by James Stewart Polshek and Partners
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The company's real attraction, though, is its programming.
Although it by no means neglected the standard repertory,
contemporary and rarely staged works _ from Handel to Henze _ have
won it an international audience. An early coup of Crosby's was
persuading Igor Stravinsky to oversee the production of his
``Rake's Progress'' during the company's first season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that it would not make sense to try to run a museum of
opera in a small mountain town like Santa Fe,'' Crosby said. ``You
can have all the `Bohemes' and `Carmens' you want in New York all
winter, with brilliant international casts, and you don't have to
come here to see them.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   All told, the company offered nearly 50 world and American
premieres during Crosby's tenure, including works by Hindemith,
Hans-Werner Henze (his ``Venus and Adonis'' this year was his sixth
work to be given its United States premiere by the company),
Gian-Carlo Menotti, Krzysztof Penderecki, Martin David Levy,
Carlisle Floyd, Peter Lieberson, David Lang, Judith Weir and Tobias
Picker.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg's ``Jakobsleiter'' and ``Von Heute auf Morgen,''
Shostakovich's ``Nose'' and several rarely heard Strauss operas
also had their first American performances here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Fe has been a huge influence on the American opera
scene, the way Glyndebourne influences opera in England, and
Aix-en-Provence influences opera in France,'' said Matthew Epstein,
the artistic director of the Lyric Opera of Chicago and for the
last 20 years a consultant in Santa Fe as well.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense of confidence here about the company's future.
For one thing, there is not much mystery about Gaddes. He began
working here as an artistic administrator in 1969 but left to found
the Opera Theater of St. Louis in 1976. There are many similarities
between the Santa Fe and St. Louis companies; both perform in the
summer and present a similar repertory mixture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not a coincidence,'' Gaddes said. ``I always say that
John Crosby sired the Opera Theater of St. Louis. The whole concept
was modeled on Santa Fe, and part of the idea was that the
apprentices here would feed into St. Louis. Which they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaddes returned to Santa Fe in 1988, first as a consultant, then
as associate general director, a title that Crosby said was meant
to give him authority but not necessarily to make him his chosen
successor. That decision, he said, was the board's.
</P>
<P>
   Gaddes seems intent on maintaining many of the traditions that
Crosby has established. Among the works he has announced for next
season are Berg's ``Wozzeck,'' Strauss' ``Egyptian Helen'' and a
Mozart rarity, ``Mitridate.'' He has commissioned new works from
Aaron Jay Kernis, Bright Sheng and Kaija Saariaho and is bringing
in the director Peter Sellars.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby is keeping his own plans to himself. He has given up the
New York residence he maintained for many years, and will split his
time between Santa Fe and Palm Springs, Calif. And he is thinking
about writing what he calls ``a journal'' about the company.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the only activity he said was on his agenda was
driving around in the silver Rolls-Royce convertible he bought last
year. A visitor noted that a convertible seemed an odd choice for
someone living in a climate where a half-hour's drive is likely to
take one through four short rainstorms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that's true,'' he said. ``But I so much enjoy pulling the
top down that I do it too frequently. It's an old one, a 1985, and
I had to do a lot of work on it. But it will outlive me; that's all
I care about. And you see that's something I can do: I can spend my
time washing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
