<SLUG> BC-FBC-SIMMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMMS VS. APPLEWHITE ON EVERY TEXAN'S MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He can't run from it. He can't ignore it. Go out
to eat, people ask him about it. Walk around campus, people want to
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the gas station the other day,'' says Chris Simms
with a smile that can light up a room. ``And when I went to pay,
the guy says to me, ``Hey, you're that Simms kid. Are you going to
beat out Applewhite?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In some places in this capital city that bleeds orange during
the football season, the power conversations speculate on whether
Texas Gov. George W. Bush can make the quantum leap to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   But with another college football season upon us, even in the
backrooms of Texas politics the question du jour seems to be, who
will be the starting quarterback for the University of Texas
Longhorns? Chris Simms, the precocious, highly touted sophomore? Or
Major Applewhite, the talented, experienced veteran and 1999 Big 12
Offensive Player of the Year who holds 37 school records but is
coming off a knee injury that sidelined him all spring?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mack Brown says he won't announce the starter until
Saturday's opener against Louisiana-Lafayette, but insists it
doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got two starters,'' says Brown. ``And one will walk out
there before the other. And if that one's struggling, the other
will come in and try and give us a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people think the ultimate choice will be ``that Simms
kid,'' who also happens to be Simms's kid. As in Phil Simms, the
former New York Giants quarterback and current CBS NFL analyst who
has a pair of Super Bowl rings and a Super Bowl MVP award on his
resume.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You look at Chris Simms, you talk to Chris Simms, and you see
and hear Phil. The blond hair, the wide smile, the easygoing
personality that hides a toughness necessary to survive in the
business world of college and professional football.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids would duck the comparisons. Chris Simms does not. In
fact, he embraces them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if people try to compare me to my dad,'' he says.
``If they do, it's great. I love him. That's just part of the
situation and how I grew up and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Simms was a small-town kid from Kentucky who made it in New
York, which means he could make it anywhere. Early in his NFL
career, he had to deal with a situation like the one Chris is
dealing with now.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, the coach of the Giants, was waffling on his
starting quarterback. The choice was Simms, who had been plagued by
injuries early in his career, or Scott Brunner, a low draft pick
from Delaware who had shown some promise filling in.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells chose Brunner, whose tenure as starter turned out to be
temporary. Chris Simms, though he was not born at the time, is
still angry over the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Parcells's first year,'' says Chris. ``And he chickened
out. I tell you, I'm still bitter about it to this day. I'm also
bitter about the Hostetler one (Jeff Hostetler won another
coin-flip choice by Parcells to be starting QB). If someone wants
to make me angry and get my blood hot, all they have to do is bring
that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil never talked publicly about his anger or disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad doesn't have a mean bone in his body,'' says Chris. ``I
have more respect for him for biting his lip and not saying things
when most QBs would have come out and laid into you. I don't know
how he does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that cool detachment is evident in Chris as he endures
the speculation and questions about the Texas starter. It's even
tougher in some ways for Chris, since he knows that if he had kept
his original commitment to Tennessee, there probably would be
little question about his starting status.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about it, Simms laughs and shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the choice I made,'' he says. ``And I'll live with it.
I am happy here beyond belief. We've got good fans. It's a great
city.''
</P>
<P>
   But Simms also shows his competitive side in his next breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could come here and cause some ruffles my freshman
year,'' he says. ``It didn't happen. But I didn't plan on coming
here and sitting on the bench for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Miello remembers the first time he saw Chris Simms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in sixth or seventh grade,'' said Miello, who is the
football coach and athletic director at Ramapo (N.J.) High School.
``He was just bigger and more mature than everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what blew me away was when I saw a game he played in
seventh grade. He came up to the line of scrimmage and he was
checking plays off and calling audibles. It was unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris took it for granted. He had been around pro football since
he could walk and he felt comfortable with who he was and who his
dad was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of kids would have tried to break away,'' said Miello.
``But Chris never did. He took advantage of what his dad had. He
thrived in that environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Simms is reticent in talking about his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a less intrusive parent,'' said Miello, ``and,
Lord knows, he has more of a right than most people to say things.
In fact, I go to him and say, `Phil, what do you think about this?'
And he'll just say, `Coach, you know what you're doing,' and leave
it at that. But let's face it, Chris has had the best quarterback
coach in the world for a lot of years and it shows.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed in the summer before Chris's freshman year of high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three other quarterbacks, all more experienced,'' said
Miello. ``But Chris just blew them away. He started his first game
as a freshman and never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time Chris did look back was when it came time to pick
a college from the hundreds that had recruited him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mannings were all over him about going to Tennessee,''
said Miello. ``And the media barrage was constant. He liked it
there, but a couple of weeks after he made the decision, when
things had quieted, I got a call to go over to his house. He had
changed his mind. He said Texas felt like a family to him and he
wanted to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The battle has been waged in the media throughout the spring and
on the field through training camp. The consensus seems to be that
the emerging leader is Simms.
</P>
<P>
   Going by the preseason scrimmages, there was little to choose
between. In one of the final tuneups last week, Simms completed 5
of 8 passes for 144 yards and two touchdowns, while Applewhite was
10 of 13 for 171 yards, two touchdowns and an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that you're going to see a huge separation
between them,'' said Texas offensive coordinator Greg Davis.
``We've said all along we've got two good ones. Two No. 1s.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite says the knee he injured at the end of last season is
fine, but he also knows that it may be the ostensible reason given
if he is not the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been taught it's not how you start but how you
finish,'' says Applewhite. ``If Chris and I had our way, we'd want
to be the starting QB and starting every game and win every game.
But the reality of it is that there hasn't been a QB here to start
the season and finish the season since 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms says he understands the two-QB concept; he has seen it
tried at places such as Michigan and Penn State and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see it staying that way through the season,'' he says.
``I don't think it could work. It's too much turmoil for a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms has adjusted well, taking the normal grief that every
freshman must take _ particularly a Yankee freshman and especially
one with the fanfare that accompanied him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they adjusted to me,'' he says with a laugh. ``I came
in and they made fun of every word I said. I was like, `I'm
speaking English here. What are we fixing to do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Simms is fixing to be the starting quarterback at Texas, and
despite the heated competition _ which will only increase as the
season unfolds _ he sees a unity on the team no matter who plays
QB.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no `Chris camp,' '' he says. ``I would never let that
happen. The team is first. I don't go out and try to win guys over.
I just try and go out and have fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about this team is that everyone wants to win,
and if you go out on the field and do it, they are going to be
happy with you.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Chris Simms, every bit his father's son, went out
into the Austin night, very much secure in who he is and where he
is going.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
