</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal comes a week after he began running ads
criticizing the Clinton-Gore record on Medicare and promised to
offer his own detailed plan.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, the federal health-care program for 40 million elderly
and disabled Americans, is expected to go bankrupt in 2025. In
1993, when Clinton and Gore took office, it was scheduled to go
bankrupt in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   As he has on a series of issues, including education and
military readiness, Bush criticized the Clinton-Gore record while
offering his own solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president said he's been involved with every decision
for the past eight years, and after eight years of his active
involvement, 8 million more Americans are left without health
insurance than in 1993, a 20 percent increase ... 2.4 million more
children have no health insurance, and, of course, nothing's been
done to reform Medicare or provide prescription drug coverage,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush offered a two-part proposal that he said would provide
immediate assistance to the elderly most in need through state
governments, and a long-range reform of the entire Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan would give states $48 billion over four
years to help cover prescription drugs for low-income seniors. The
grants also would cover out-of-pocket drug costs in excess of
$6,000 per year. Currently, 20 states offer such a program
according to the Health Insurance Association of America (HIAA).
</P>
<P>
   The second part of Bush's plan would use $110 billion of the
projected budget surplus over 10 years to reform the Medicare
program and subsidize the cost of premiums for low-income elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, following a proposal offered by Clinton last year, has
proposed spending an additional $253 billion over the next 10 years
to cover 50 percent of prescription drug costs up to $2,000 in 2002
and up to $5,000 when fully implemented in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The key difference between the Bush and Gore plans is how they
would be administered. Bush relies on private insurance companies
to offer a variety of benefit plans at various costs. Gore would
offer a new, voluntary Medicare benefit in addition to the current
program.
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, legislative and policy director for the AARP, the
nation's largest senior group, said that because Bush's proposal
relies on plans offered by private insurers it would be impossible
to tell his members how much they would pay for coverage and what
benefits they would receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've finally gotten to the point where both parties are
talking about a prescription drug benefit in Medicare, but there
are real differences in how those benefits would be delivered, when
they would be effective and how much money out of the federal
surplus would be used to support it,'' Rother said. ``(But) I'm not
sure we will be able to make a direct apples-to-apples comparison
before the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Coorsh, spokesman for the HIAA, called Bush's plan ``a
serious proposal. It will help the seniors who need it the most pay
for their drugs faster than any proposal that has been offered so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Coorsh said Bush's plan ``would not run the risk of bringing
about the prospect of price controls which could potentially
inhibit the development of life-saving drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott told reporters Tuesday that he
liked Bush's plan but has asked Finance Committee Chairman William
Roth to draft a prescription drug bill that can be considered by
Congress this fall.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the web:
</P>
<P>
   www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   www.algore2000.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
