<SLUG> BC-COKE0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Optimistic words from Coke send shares up 3%
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Shares of Coca-Cola jumped 5.7 percent Tuesday
afternoon, right after the company tried to soothe investor
concerns about its earnings and case sales.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola shares ended the day at $56, up $1.75, or 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, the Atlanta-based beverage giant saw
its stock decline as much as 12.7 percent, primarily because
analysts have been reporting that North American case sales have
been weaker than expected.
</P>
<P>
   While the company said Tuesday that its North American sales
``have been soft,'' it also announced that many other markets
``reflect improving economic conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Coca-Cola said it is comfortable with analysts'
estimates of its third-quarter earnings and added that its own
outlook for full year 2000 and 2001 profit is unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it ``remains comfortable with the
previously established objective of growing worldwide unit case
volume in the range of 5 to 6 percent for the full year 2000 and 6
to 7 percent for the full year 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts predict that Coca-Cola's earnings per share
will increase 13 percent this year to $1.45. They also predict an
increase of 21 percent next year to $1.75.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Bill Pecoriello of Sanford Bernstein said markets in
Brazil, China, Mexico, Japan and Eastern Europe are offsetting
weaker sales in North America, where supermarket prices have been
rising.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Dunn, Coca-Cola's deputy group president of North America,
said the company will employ ``innovative marketing activities'' to
try to turn around the situation. That includes a ``significant
advertising and promotional presence during the Summer Olympic
Games'' for Coke Classic, PowerAde, Dasani and Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   In the four-week period ending Aug. 13, Coca-Cola's U.S. case
sales in the important food, drug and mass merchandising segment
declined 7.7 percent, said analyst Marc Cohen of Goldman Sachs.
That was largely because prices were up 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After the market closed Tuesday, Coca-Cola's largest bottler,
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises, said it expects North American
case sales to decline about 2 percent in the third quarter,
compared with the same period last year. For all of 2000, CCE's
case sales are expected to approach those of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, meanwhile, CCE predicted case sales would drop 2
percent to 3 percent in the third quarter. The decline is related
to the substantial increase in volume the company had in the fall
of last year when it replenished retail shelves following a massive
product recall in Belgium and France.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 2000, CCE's European case sales are expected to
increase 4 percent to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
