A2066 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-05 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HAVING BIG FISH IN A LITTLE POND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For people who can never catch a big fish, a new
grow-your-own phenomenon is creating a shock among fishermen across
America _ starting with a world-record 5-pound bluegill grown and
caught in a private pond.
</P>
<P>
   This world-record bluegill is 15 inches long, 12 inches tall and
3 1/2 inches thick, and according to the fellow who grew it in his
pond, there's plenty more where that one came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go out and catch 500 of them in an afternoon, all 2, 3
pounds and up,'' said Ken Holyoak, 63, who is selling fingerlings
from the progeny of that bluegill for 25 cents apiece for people
who want to try to grow their own world records.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor that Holyoak had successfully created a strain of giant
bluegill, or bream (pronounced ``brim'') as they are called in the
South, started circulating a year ago. But the idea of a 5-pound
bluegill seemed as credible as a 10-pound hamster, especially for a
fish that averages about 4 to 5 inches in most lakes.
</P>
<P>
   But then these two pictures arrived in the mail, proof of the
giant fish, sent to a few outdoors writers across America. Holyoak
was then tracked down at his small fish farm in Alapaha, Ga. In one
mudhole of a pond, just 30 feet wide and 75 feet long, every
bluegill was 2 pounds or bigger. At other ponds at the fish
hatchery were fingerlings from this ``continuous bloodline'' of
giant bluegill, as Holyoak termed it, which are sold and shipped
out across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody told me I couldn't do it,'' Holyoak said. ``All the
fish people, biologists, all the people who know more than I do,
said it was impossible. It took me 10 years before I pulled it off.
I almost gave up, and right then, the first really big ones started
showing up.''
</P>
<P>
   What Holyoak did at his warm-water fish hatchery was to cull
only the biggest fish to pass on their genetic traits, then keep
them in warm water and feed them heavily. So not only would the
bluegill have the bloodlines of big fish, but would have the
conditions (warm water) and food to grow year-round.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of culling, this strain of bluegill can reach 12
inches and weigh a pound in only one year. Holyoak calls them
``Georgia giants.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked him about his education, training and science
background, in other words, the guidance he had received in the
process of this experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' he answered in his deep Southern drawl, referring
to any formal training in science and biology. ``I was just born
this way.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then added, ``I've been doing this, working with
fish, for 37 years now. I started working on a strain of giant
bream (bluegill) about 10 years ago. Just kind of kept at. I can't
help it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I've done it, I can make more of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire affair started as a private experiment in his own
pond, many years before genetic engineering became a hot button
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a half-acre to three-quarters acre pond is big
enough to grow 3- to 5-pound bluegill, and that many warm-water
lakes also provide excellent habitat conditions to provide similar
results.
</P>
<P>
   For information, phone 912-532-6135, or write Ken's Fish Farm,
U.S. Highway 129 North, P.O. Box 449, Alapaha, GA 31622-0449.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
