A2067 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BOYS-MURDER-BOS &LR;      09-05 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CONVICTED IN BOY'S MURDER SEEKS RETRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One of two men convicted of killing 10-year-old Jeffrey
Curley in 1997 will ask for a new trial, arguing that the judge at
his murder trial gave faulty jury instructions and improperly
excluded the public and the media during the jury selection
process.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Ruth Greenberg, who is handling Charles Jaynes' appeal
of his 1998 second-degree murder conviction, said closing the
courtroom during jury selection was a grave error by then-Middlesex
Superior Court Judge Judith Cowin, now a justice of the state
Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constitutional guarantees to a public trial are very
important guarantees,'' Greenberg said Tuesday. ``They are so
important that denial of a public trial requires reversal, even in
the absence of prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg is also expected to argue before Superior Court Judge
Regina L. Quinlan that Cowin improperly instructed the jury on one
key point and failed to tell them about another.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg alleges that Cowin should have told the jury that _ as
a matter of law _ it had to find beyond a reasonable doubt that the
crime happened in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Although prosecutors insisted that the murder occurred in
Massachusetts, Jaynes and his co-defendant, Salvatore Sicari, also
reportedly traveled to New Hampshire and Maine, where the boy's
body was dumped in a river.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Greenberg said she will argue that Cowin gave a faulty
manslaughter instruction that effectively prevented Jaynes from
being found guilty of the lesser charge.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Kimberly Diaz Peterson, however, has
said in court papers that Jaynes waived his right to a fully open
trial by not objecting at the time, and that the judge could
properly close jury selection to the media and public in certain
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz Peterson has also filed court papers insisting that the
evidence overwhelmingly showed that Curley, who lived in East
Cambridge, was killed in Massachusetts and that Greenberg is
``misquoting'' the judge's actual manslaughter instruction in her
arguments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0214 </DOCNO>
