r e BC-SONGWRITERS-LADN &LR;      09-05 4293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONGWRITERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE VOICE
</HEADLINE>
  Singer-songwriters create a sound that's pure, personal and
provocative 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAILY NEWS STAFF 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tired of the jingle-jangle of the current music scene? Boy
groups, boy-toy groups, heavy metal, heavy pop, heavy sighs from
everything sounding (BEGIN ITAL)sooo(END ITAL) packaged.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're plugged in or willing to spend hours on the
Internet listening to samples of songs or reading gossip, you're
likely to miss a lot of talented singer-songwriters whose work
falls through the cracks of radio's rigid formats.
</P>
<P>
   So our staff got together and came up with a listing of our
favorite singer-songwriters. This is not to be construed as a
definitive list, and we apologize to all those terrific ones we
missed _ and there are a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   What these artists have in common is a willingness to go their
own way. Many of them put out their own albums, hawking them over
the Internet or at their concerts. Some are on smaller labels (and
are still hawked at concerts). It may not make them rich, but it
gives them the freedom to follow their own muse rather than some
record company's formula for riches. And maybe freedom is another
common denominator.
</P>
<P>
   Some, unfortunately, are no longer with us, but their music
lives on.
</P>
<P>
   So take a look at our suggestions (you may even want to keep
this around for reference). Finding some of the music may be tricky
at some record stores; so we've included some Web sites. You can
always try sites like amazon.com, musicblvd.com or some of the
label sites. Hopefully, you'll give a listen to some of these
artists, many who we regard as old friends. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
---NICK DRAKE: &QL; 
(Timeless quality) If you've watched television lately, you've
probably heard Drake's music. There's a visually intriguing
commercial for a Volkswagen Cabrio in which four friends are
driving at night to a party and then decide to keep going. The
music accompanying it is the spare, ethereal Drake song ``Pink
Moon,'' also the name of one of his albums. Drake's music has also
appeared almost constantly, it seems, on the WB's teen series
``Young Americans.'' Both the ad and the show exude hipness that
says today _ so you'd probably be surprised to learn that Drake
died from a possible overdose of anti-depressants at 26 in 1974,
two years after ``Pink Moon'' was released.
</P>
<P>
   A recluse throughout much of his life, Drake's three albums met
with poor sales. His isolation, however, must have contributed to
the uniqueness of his music. Anyone who plays the guitar will tell
you it's nearly impossible to play his music like he did. He used
his own tunings, and even his vocals _ because of their timing _
are hard to duplicate. Yet everything fits together seamlessly in a
sound that is both familiar and exotic at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Drake has become a cult figure with fans all
over the world, and his albums have continued to sell.
Hannibal/Rykodisc Records is releasing remastered versions of
Drake's three albums _ ``Five Leaves Left,'' ``Bryter Layter'' and
``Pink Moon'' later this month. On Sept. 11, a documentary on
Drake's life, ``A Skin Too Few,'' will premiere in Amsterdam. &QL; 
-Rob Lowman &QL; 
---RICHARD FARINE: &QL; 
(Stuff of legends) In 1966, at the age of 30, depending on which
bio you read, Richard Farina died in a motorcycle accident, going
off a cliff after attending a party for the publication of his
novel, ``Been Down So Long It Looks Like Up to Me.'' The tale of a
youth in search of himself has been reissued over the years and now
sports a wonderful introduction from no less than novelist Thomas
Pynchon, an old friend from Farina's Cornell University days.
</P>
<P>
   Before his college days, though, the half-Cuban, half-Irish
Farina ran guns as a teen for the Irish Republican Army before
being deported by the British. Along the way, he developed an
interest in the burgeoning folk music scene of the early '60s in
Greenwich Village. He then married the youngest of the Baez
sisters, Mimi. The pair recorded two albums _ ``Celebrations for a
Grey Day'' and ``Reflections in a Crystal Wind,'' most of which can
be found on ``Pack Up Your Sorrows: Best of the Vanguard Years''
(Vanguard _ www.vanguardrecords.com).
</P>
<P>
   The music often has a neo-Appalachian-bluesy flavor (Richard
played the dulcimer), reflecting a social conscience as well as a
lyrical beauty. Farina could be sweet (``Pack Up Your Sorrows''),
funny (``Hard Loving Loser''), and cutting and rocking (``House
Un-American Blues Activity Dream''), and those who know of him
wonder what else this poet-novelist-songwriter could have been. &QL; 
_ Rob Lowman &QL; 
---ERIC ANDERSEN: &QL; 
(Unsung in his own country) It's interesting that Eric Andersen's
new album is titled ``Can't Relive the Past.'' Andersen arrived on
the folk scene in the early '60s and for more than 30 years has
been turning out his unique songs. It's hard to figure out why
Andersen isn't better-known (he is more likely to be cited by other
artists as being influential rather than by critics). Perhaps his
personal songs didn't translate into record sales. One of his
record companies even lost one of his best albums, ``Stages,'' in
the early '70s, and it was 20 years before it was found and
released. Along the way, Andersen, who now splits his time between
the United States and Norway, hasn't been reliving the past but
turning out wonderful albums. Vanguard has a compilation album of
his early work called ``Violets of Dawn,'' but don't overlook his
classic album ``Blue River,'' remastered and released on Sony last
year. Also check out his more recent works.
(www.ericandersen.com). &QL; 
_ Rob Lowman &QL; 
---JANE SIBERRY: &QL; 
(Unbounded) You know that anybody who can write a song called
``Everything Reminds Me of My Dog'' has an offbeat view of life,
and Jane Siberry's music reflects that. You may have heard her
gorgeous ``Calling All Angels,'' on which she duets with k.d. lang,
but that is only the surface of Siberry's eclectic spin on life.
Though she has a song and album called ``Bound by the Beauty,'' she
seems to have no limits in her music. Her early works on Reprise
Records, such as ``When I Was a Boy'' and ``Maria,'' sparkle with
inventiveness. The idiosyncratic chanteuse now releases albums from
her own label (www.sheeba.com) and has a new disc, ``Hush,'' coming
out Sept. 26. &QL; 
_ Rob Lowman &QL; 
---PETER CASE: &QL; 
(Hooks to roots) In the early '80s, Peter Case led the rock band
called the Plimsouls and had a hit with ``A Million Miles Away.''
But Case, who has a great talent for catchy hooks, wasn't
satisfied. Having started as a street musician, Case returned to
his roots and American musical roots in his self-titled ``Peter
Case,'' a terrific combination of both his pop sensibility and his
sense of tradition. Case has continued to turn wry, fun songs ever
since. His latest, ``Flying Saucer Blues'' (released this year on
Vanguard _ www.vanguardrecords.com) is no exception. &QL; 
_ Rob Lowman &QL; 
---DAVID WILCOX: &QL; 
(Poetic vision) About six years ago, I heard a live cut on KCRW
(89.9-FM) from their ``Rare on Air Vol. 1'' (Mammoth) of a David
Wilcox's ``Chet Baker's Unsung Swan Song'' that just takes your
breath away. It's a hauntingly beautiful piece about the death of
the legendary trumpet player. On his latest CD, ``What You
Whispered'' (Vanguard _ www.vanguardrecords.com), Wilcox does a
funky little number called ``This Tattoo'' that could be construed
as his philosophy: ``Make your clear and solemn vow before the age
of compromise ... this tattoo will hold your vision, always looking
back at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Through eight albums Wilcox has kept his vision, turning out
songs that have been poetic and philosophical with clever turns of
phrase and catchy, memorable melodies. &QL; 
_ Rob Lowman &QL; 
---RICHARD SHINDELL: &QL; 
(Goodbye anonymity) The cover of his latest album, the hauntingly
beautiful ``Somewhere Near Paterson'' on Signature Sounds Records,
features a photo of Richard Shindell looking away into the shrouded
distance, his back to the camera. Shindell ascribes the cover's
anonymity to a profound dislike of having his picture taken, but
we'd prefer to find the deeper meaning. The man The New York Times
describes as America's best singer-songwriter would rather let his
extraordinary songs do the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paterson'' is Shindell's fourth solo album. He, along with Dar
Williams and Lucy Kaplansky, also belonged to Cry Cry Cry, a folk
supergroup that lived up to its name in terms of quality and ticket
sales. But even after cracking Pollstar's Top 50 concert tours in
1998, the group decided to disband in order to focus on their own
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Good move. ``Paterson'' is Shindell's most accomplished work to
date, his bittersweet tenor and complex narratives revealing
modern-day emotional bankruptcy and distress. Tormented
stockbrokers, road warriors in minivans and transcendent nuns
changing flats on the New Jersey turnpike are just a few of the
memorable characters, their lives told with telling and empathetic
detail. This is the voice of a master. (www.richardshindall.com) &QL; 
_ Glenn Whipp &QL; 
---RAY WYLIE: &QL; 
(Don't call him a redneck) Ray Wylie accidentally made a name for
himself as a young pup by writing ``Up Against the Wall, Redneck
Mother.'' The song poked fun at hard-drinking, barely thinking good
ol' boys, but, of course, was misread and became a party anthem for
that very same crowd. Never mind, Wylie himself was too busy
tipping Lone Stars and snorting cocaine to notice.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Wylie got clean and sober in 1987 _ he was 41 at
the time _ that he began to take his craft seriously, and everyone
(especially Ray) is the better for it. No longer a joker (although
he can still write a beautifully ridiculous tune, check out
``Conversation With the Devil'' on his excellent last album,
``Crusades of the Restless Knights'' on Rounder Records), Wylie has
transformed himself into one of Texas' great singer-songwriters by
blending the profane with the profound. It's a potent mix from a
survivor who, today, has a lot to live for. (www.raywylie.com.) &QL; 
_ Glenn Whipp &QL; 
---JOHN GORKA: &QL; 
(Voice of experience) You start with the voice, which is supposed
to be beside the point when it comes to songwriters, but try
telling that to anyone who has seen James Taylor a dozen times in
concert. Gorka's soulful baritone envelops you like a warm bath and
invites you into his humorous and heart-rending (sometimes in the
same song) sketches of ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
   Gorka became a husband in 1996 and a father a year later. (His
son's name is Bocephus Mahatma Sinatra Gorka, which tells you a lot
about the man.) Some say bliss has dulled Gorka's craft. We beg to
differ, believing it has only deepened his sense of life's
preciousness. (Check out ``Cypress Trees'' and the title track on
his 1998 tour de force ``After Yesterday'' on Red House Records.)
Besides, while pop music revels in songs glorifying familial
violence and discord, Gorka's musings about how his little boy
``looks like Charles Bronson when he cries'' impresses us as a
beautiful thing. (Go to www.flemtam.com for more information.) &QL; 
_ Glenn Whipp &QL; 
---GREG BROWN &QL; 
(A quarter century of excellence) Greg Brown has been writing
contemplative, sharply observed songs for more than a quarter of a
century, and listening to the lead track from his latest album,
``Covenant'' on Red House Records, it's abundantly clear he hasn't
lost his touch. ``Half the people you see these days are talking on
cell phones / Driving off the road and bumping into doors,'' he
sings wearily. ``I guess nobody's lonely anymore / 'cept you and me
babe.''
</P>
<P>
   In his prolific career, Brown has appeared on ``A Prairie Home
Companion,'' recorded an album of children's music (``Bathtub
Blues'') and set William Blake's poetry to music (``Songs of
Innocence and Experience''). Along the way, he's picked up two
Grammy nominations and a legion of loyal fans that thrill to the
bluesy folk-country that Brown ably delivers with a charismatic
growl. You can't go wrong buying any of this man's albums _ they're
all gems. &QL; 
_ Glenn Whipp &QL; 
---SLAID CLEAVES: &QL; 
(Pro-depression troubadour) Like Bruce Springsteen without the
bombast, melodious Maine-born, Ireland-educated and Austin-based
folkie Cleaves has a straightforward yet haunting knack for
detailing everyday people's personal struggles. On ``No Angel
Knows'' and ``Broke Down,'' his two striking, Gurf Morlix-produced
Philo albums, Slaid swings his clean, empathetic tenor from the
most intimate (``Dance Around the Fire's'' love-leached marriage)
to mythic (the Canadian logjam saga ``Breakfast in Hell'')
narratives with consistent sensitivity and authority. But his
greatest strength is his loving embrace of fatalism; the guy
unerringly pinpoints any strength or beauty to be found in the most
devastating circumstances. And he plays McCabe's in Santa Monica on
Sept. 23. (www.rounder.com) &QL; 
_ Bob Strauss &QL; 
---TOM RUSSELL: &QL; 
(Six-string John Ford) For years, Topanga, Calif.-reared Russell
has shared top contempo cowboy honors with Canada's Ian Tyson. But
along with such intricately told western stories as ``Hallie
Lonnigan,'' ``The Sky Above, the Mud Below'' and ``The Banks of the
Musselshell,'' Russell has also actively accessed Mexican music and
his Celtic and Scandinavian roots for thematic variety and stirring
sonic flourishes. This approach reached its apex on his last album,
``The Man From God Knows Where,'' a collection of original and
classic songs that traces his forbearers' progress from Ireland and
Norway to the frontier plains and on to our elusive Eden, where the
promise of the West either plays out or dies. (www.tomrussel.com) &QL; 
_ Bob Strauss &QL; 
---NEKO CASE: &QL; 
(Heaven sent honky-tonk hellcat and self-immolating torchbearer of
the awful truth) Whether it's the notion that love is an acid bath
or that religion is the opiate of those who can't accept the former
premise, Case loves the sound of her own claws scratching out the
blackboard lessons of traditional country idioms. With her echoing,
girly/grrl vocals _ she sounds like a latter-day Brenda Lee after
her heart's been ripped out and dragged down a few miles of bad
road _ and training as a punk band drummer, Case is prone to
writing songs with titles like ``High on Cruel'' and ``Mood to Burn
Bridges.'' But dang, there's a born entertainer inside that angry
wailer, too, one who's not averse to falsettoing, yodeling,
hiccuping and naming her act Neko Case &AMP; Her Boyfriends for fun.
``The Virginian'' and ``Furnace Room Lullaby,'' her two raucous
albums on Chicago's irreverent but musically serious Bloodshot
label, define the Insurgent Country movement in a nutshell ...
emphasis on the nut. (www.bloodshotrecords.com.) &QL; 
_ Bob Strauss &QL; 
---TRENT SUMNAR: &QL; 
(Mick &AMP; Keith's hillbilly bastard son) With his high-octane band
the New Row Mob, Sumnar injects wild-haired rock energy into
traditional honky tonk idioms. Redneck pride comes first in most of
the compositions on his group's recently released, self-titled
album (``I'm Country'' being the signature anthem), but wit and
wordplay don't lag far behind. His voice is all coiled snarl, but
can be sweet and sensitive when necessary for appreciative love
songs like ``Starletta.'' Overall, this guy matches funny with
ferocious like nobody's business, while always keeping true to the
spirit of assorted Hanks and the ``Country Honk'' era Stones.
(www.trentsumnar.com.) &QL; 
_ Bob Strauss &QL; 
---IRIA DEment: &QL; 
(Folkie with heart) With a distinctive voice that seems to sum up
the history of American folk music and a talent for storytelling
that can move you to tears, DeMent delivers her story-songs with a
down-home twang that never sounds forced. Influenced by Kitty Wells
and Joni Mitchell, DeMent has some high-profile fans, including
Emmylou Harris and Nanci Griffith. John Prine wrote the liner notes
to her 1992 debut album, and Merle Haggard co-wrote a song for her
third disc. DeMent, the youngest of eight children born in Arkansas
and raised in California in a strict Pentecostal family, never
imagined being a songwriter until her late 20s. Best album: 1994's
``My Life,'' a sad and moving collection of autobiographical and
fictional sketches. (www.irisdement.com.) &QL; 
_ Fred Shuster &QL; 
---CHANTAL KREVIAZUK: &QL; 
(Soul-searching piano prodigy) A fast learner on piano who started
playing at age 5 after watching her older brothers practice,
Kreviazuk began writing commercial jingles as a teen at home in
Canada. A horrible car crash while visiting Italy in 1994 left her
with a new enthusiasm for music, and she cut a demo of personal new
songs. Her first album, 1997's ``Under These Rocks and Stones''
(Sony) with its standout track, ``Surrounded,'' dealing with a
boyfriend's suicide, became a favorite of Sarah McLachlan and the
Lilith Fair set. Her latest, ``Color Moving and Still'' has brought
raves and critical awards in her native Canada.
(www.chantalKreviazuk.com.) &QL; 
_ Fred Shuster &QL; 
---ALEX CHILTON: &QL; 
(On a soulful self-destruction derby) It's often said nobody has
more completely betrayed his talent than Chilton, with the possible
exception of Rod Stewart. After the demise of the almost totally
ignored but supremely wonderful '70s power-pop band Big Star,
Chilton set out to ignore his talent for bittersweet r&AMP;b-informed
pop and blue-eyed soul by cutting drunken covers of songs like
``Volare'' and jazz standards on must-avoid albums such as the
aptly titled ``Like Flies on Sherbet.'' But if you check out
compilations like the recently issued ``The Best of the Box Tops''
(a teen Chilton's Memphis soul band _ hits included the late-'60s
classics ``The Letter'' and ``Cry Like a Baby''), anything by Big
Star or the fine 1991 anthology ``19 Years: A Collection,'' you'll
find a great talent that sparks up in surprising places.
(www.barnone.com) &QL; 
_ Fred Shuster &QL; 
---MICHAEL HEAD &QL; 
(Best of British) Unless you're a Britpop obscurist or a dedicated
follower of UK fashion, you've probably never heard of Head or his
heartbreakingly good pop band, Shack. Head, who grew up in a tough
Liverpool housing project, formed his first band, the Pale
Fountains, in 1981, mixing pastoral psychedelia and bossa nova. It
was a good indication of where he would go with the far-superior
Shack, which issued its wonderful fourth album, ``H.M.S. Fable,''
last summer and then promptly refused to tour behind it in the U.S.
His folk-tinged Merseybeat on such genuinely touching songs as
``Streets of Kenny,'' ``Comedy'' and ``Captain's Table,'' sung and
played in Shack with his brother, John, should have been a shoo-in
for radio play. No such luck. A live album with Shack backing its
biggest influence, Love's Arthur Lee, was recently issued in
Britain. (www.shack.org.uk/pacific.) &QL; 
_ Fred Shuster &QL; 
---BRUCE COCKBURN: &QL; 
(Vaguely Christian lefty folk-popster) The Canadian Cockburn
(pronounced Coe-burn) has recorded more than two dozen finely
wrought albums of thoughtful, often achingly beautiful, sometimes
fiercely political music, and has won Canada's equivalent of the
Grammy, the Juno, numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   But Cockburn has never been able to get much attention south of
the 45th Parallel, other than a teensy bit of notice for
``Wondering Where the Lions Are'' in 1978 and ``If I Had a Rocket
Launcher'' in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his problem is the unusual artistic journey he's
followed. His Christian faith was more explicitly spelled out in
many of the songs of his first decade in the business, but he
de-emphasized that strain in his work in the 1980s in reaction to
the extremes of the Religious Right.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, his world traveling had brought him to places such
as Central America, and to the leftist politics of songs such as
``Rocket Launcher.'' More recently, his concerns have become more
environmental in nature, and a gentle romantic side, always evident
in his music, has become more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   He creates lovely tone poems backed by snazzy guitar and smart
instrumentation. Unlike a lot of artists easing into their fourth
decade in the business (his first album was released in 1970),
Cockburn remains vital and interesting, continuing to put out
challenging and thoughtful pop. (www.rykodisc.com.) &QL; 
-David Bloom &QL; 
---DAVID GRAY: &QL; 
(English-Welsh Internet-fueled eight-year overnight discovery) Gray
was born in England, finished his upbringing in Wales and is huge
in Ireland, where his most recent album, ``White Ladder,'' has gone
10 times platinum. Yes, that's only 150,000 albums, but that's
still something like one copy of the record for every third Irish
household. He's also gone to No. 2 on the quirky UK music charts,
and double platinum in England, which is another 150,000 records.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be a secret much longer in this country either, as
``White Ladder'' has won several increasing levels of notice in an
Internet success story.
</P>
<P>
   Gray had recorded three albums in the 1990s for various labels
that met with indifferent success, eventually costing him any deal
with a major U.S. record company. He tried to shop another disc
around with no luck, then shelved it and began work on ``White
Ladder'' with his drummer, who helped him build his gorgeously
crafted introspective songs about relationships on a series of drum
machine beats that work surprisingly well with his otherwise spare
sound.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting work got a deal in Ireland, and Gray also made the
record available on his own Web site, www.davidgray.com, where he
soon was selling enough records that he also made it available
through Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Airplay on eclectically programmed public radio stations, such
as KCRW-FM in Los Angeles, helped fuel interest enough that he got
a deal this spring with ATO Records, the label partly owned by
musician Dave Matthews, a Gray fan. In the past couple of weeks,
RCA (for whom Matthews records) has partnered with ATO to begin
pushing the record stateside, and he's leaping up the charts in the
small but influential AAA radio format.
</P>
<P>
   You could go see his second L.A. show in three months at the
Palace on Sept. 8, but it sold out two weeks ahead of time. A
shame; he's an engaging performer live, and his songs are tough to
beat. &QL; 
_ David Bloom &QL; 
---VICTORIA WILLIAMS: &QL; 
(Cool Louisianan) Williams writes great songs that other musicians
love. She sings them in a squeaky-cool voice that grows on you. She
has multiple sclerosis, which led to a celebrated 1993 all-star
tribute album (with artists such as Lou Reed and Soul Asylum
singing her songs) that was a bigger success than anything she had
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   The album did so well, in fact, that it not only paid for her
medical bills but led to the creation of the Sweet Relief Fund, a
still-functioning charity (they took part in an event at the
Knitting Factory Hollywood just two weeks ago) that benefits other
musicians facing medical challenges.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Louisiana in 1959, played in a jug band with
Case, busked on Venice Beach and just put out her best album yet,
``Water to Drink'' on Atlantic. What else do you need to know?
(www.victoriawilliams.com.) &QL; 
_ David Bloom &QL; 
---BEN HARPER: &QL; 
(The funky folk rocker whose day has finally come) He's just as at
home playing the Delta blues as he is riffing Hendrix-style on the
Weissenborn lap slide guitar. But Inland Empire-born and -bred
Harper resists characterization. He is simply a musician that
weaves American folk, the militancy of Bob Marley and shredding
guitar into a sound so earthy its roots can only come from the
down-home blues of greats like Son House. This has been the base
for all four Harper recordings, including his latest, ``Burn to
Shine'' on Virgin. This album finds Harper contemplating alienation
(``Less''), love (``The Woman in You'') and spirituality (``Two
Hands of a Prayer'') over a range of sounds created by his unusual
choice of instrumentation. But it's the playful Harper (``Steal My
Kisses''), a side the tarnished singer doesn't always show
musically, that has earned him attention from a mainstream that had
shunned his music for so long. And they ain't even seen nothing
yet. (BenHarper.com.) &QL; 
_ Sandra Berrera &QL; 
---beth orton: &QL; 
(A voice of the 21st century) Her earlier collaborations with
Madonna's Ray of Light producer William Orbit and the Chemical
Brothers got her dubbed a techno-folkie. She was the human voice
kids in Clubland could take listen to on their way down from a
hangover _ that is, until Orton became a solo artist. She has since
flexed her singing muscles over strummy songs that bookmark her
endearing emotional songwriting about longing (``Galaxy of
Empitness'' off her ``Trailer Park'' debut album), loss (``Pass'')
and romantic breakups (``So Much More'' off her latest album
``Central Reservation'' on Arista). These bittersweet portraits are
contrasted by Orton's plaintive voice, an achy and husky tone that
has been compared to the likes of English folkie Sandy Denny and
American country singer Bobbie Gentry. (www.arista.com) &QL; 
_ Sandra Berrera &QL; 
---PATTY LARKIN: &QL; 
(A far-out folkie) Some performers are good at doing everything,
and Larkin happens to be one of them. She's a prolific lyricist and
accomplished musician who straddles the genres of folk and rock,
though her latest album, ``Regrooving the Dream'' on Vanguard,
finds the singer-songwriter steeped in a melting pot of sounds from
Celtic to jazz and bossa nova to r&AMP;b. This musical stew she's
cooked up is made all the more interesting by her frequent use of
electronic looping and sampling of her own instruments and voice.
Larkin even tempers her own voice in a way that befits the mood of
each song, be it the airy samba of ``Only'' or her parched
``Rivers.'' She makes music an art, again. (pattylarkin.com.) &QL; 
_ Sandra Berrera
</P>
</TEXT>
