<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-2TAKE     09-05 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-2TAKES-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOPES TO NUDGE ISRAELIS AND PALESTINIANS ON LONG TREK TO
PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ None of the three parties engaged in the
long-suffering Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations are
optimistic that President Clinton can nudge the leaders closer to a
deal when he meets with them, individually, in New York on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He will certainly try to impress upon them, particularly on
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, a sense of urgency. But as
they did at the close of the Camp David summit meeting in July, the
two sides remain both closer to and further than ever from a
permanent peace agreement, frozen at a decisive moment that
represents a test of their political strength and their will.
</P>
<P>
   Before them on the negotiating table still lies Jerusalem,
waiting to be carved up. Only an unexpected shift in either side's
position on the holy city's future status will allow them to
progress to another summit meeting at the close of the United
Nation's gathering of world leaders, U.S. officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several Israeli and U.S. proposals for sharing
sovereignty, Arafat has remained immovable from his longtime demand
for full sovereignty over what is known in Arabic as Haram
al-Sharif _ the sacred, bitterly contested nerve center of
Jerusalem's walled Old City that Jews call the Temple Mount. And
Barak is unwilling and too weak politically to go that far, to
concede what is considered the holiest Jewish site.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, the parties had all forecast a gloom-and-doom
scenario for September if this standoff continued. But the Israelis
and the Palestinians are not, as predicted, at the precipice of
bloody conflict. After failing to win international backing for his
stance, Arafat appears prepared to postpone the unilateral
declaration of statehood from his pledged deadline of Sept. 13.
That eliminates the prospect of an imminent collapse of the peace
effort and a spasm of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a matter of at most a few months before another
moment of reckoning is upon the leaders. The Palestinian Central
Council will meet this weekend to debate whether the statehood
deadline should be pushed back to Nov. 15 or year's end. Clinton's
presidency is drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   And Barak, his government in tatters, is starting to give up on
reaching an agreement, close associates say. Publicly, he puts his
chances at 50-50. ``But I feel him shifting focus,'' said a close
associate. ``Not that he's lost interest. Obviously peace has been
his obsessive priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``But his political situation is desperate, and he has to be
realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Israeli officials say that they are having trouble
reading Arafat right now. Is he engaging in brinkmanship, or is he
genuinely unwilling to be budged from his longtime core positions?
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, however, say that Arafat's feelings seem quite
clear. ``I think he's developing some negative attitudes toward
your American president,'' said Ghassan Khatib, a Palestinian
political analyst. ``And if he's going to give the honor of a peace
agreement, he'll give it to someone else at a later time.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's public statements, Palestinians say, represent a
genuinely unwavering stance on East Jerusalem _ ``the heart of
Palestine, the heart of Arabs, the heart of believers,'' as he told
the Arab foreign ministers in Cairo last weekend. His speech in
Cairo emphasized that he would not be rushed into a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinian experts say that Arafat thinks it less risky to
protract the conflict than to seal a deal that would be perceived
as selling out not just Palestinian, but also Arab and Muslim,
rights. Many in the Arab world still believe that the Palestinians
have the right to all of the former Palestine, not only the West
Bank and Gaza Strip but what is internationally recognized as
Israel, too. Arafat, the experts say, has been putting forth the
compromise position of U.N. resolutions that call for Israeli
withdrawal from all territory occupied in the 1967 war _ which
includes all of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been fighting the extremists by the argument you have
to abide by international legality _ not more,'' Khatib said. ``How
can he tell them to live with less?''
</P>
<P>
   Experts also say that Arafat is calculating that he can
out-bluff Barak and outlive him politically. At the helm of a
minority government, Barak is holding on to office by a thread _
one legislative vote _ until parliament reconvenes at the end of
October.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are portraying Barak, who is willing to
reconfigure Jerusalem along ethnic lines, as Arafat's dream peace
partner. But the Palestinians are not as appreciative of his
concessions as the Americans and the Israelis would like them to
be, and they contend that the U.S. and Israeli positions have
become indistinguishable _ and allied against them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Having offered to guarantee unlimited access to the Western
Wall, the Palestinians do not see why the Israelis cannot concede
to them legal sovereignty over the Temple Mount, which they already
control in practical terms. They dismiss as ideologically
unacceptable and impractical the proposals on the table, which
include declaring ``divine sovereignty'' over the Temple Mount _
that is, both sides would agree that God owns the site in all its
layered history.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is reportedly under serious consideration, although
many Israelis, too, scoff at it. ``Would God then pick up the
garbage?'' an Israeli columnist asked this week. ``Whose God?''
another asked.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, some Palestinian experts say, Arafat does not
necessarily fear a right-wing Israeli government. Under the
rightist government of the former Israeli prime minister, Benjamin
Netanyahu, the Palestinians enjoyed the embrace of ever fuller
international support for their claims. Barak, on the other hand,
has courted world opinion and regained Western world backing for
Israel, successfully portraying himself as a peacemaker willing to
risk his hold on power to secure peace.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But world opinion cannot keep Barak in power, and his domestic
problems are severe _ so severe that it is unclear whether any
agreement he achieved could stand the test of time. This is
something else that the Palestinians know, robbing the moment of
its urgency for them.
</P>
<P>
   Barak remains confident that he can win the Israeli public's
backing for a far-reaching agreement that includes the
reconfiguration of Jerusalem. Getting parliament's support,
however, would be difficult _ if not impossible. So Barak would
probably call for new elections, using an agreement as a platform,
political experts say. Then, in order to get a more supportive
parliament elected, he would have to campaign not only for himself
but for a center-left coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Without an agreement, Barak is on unsteady ground. He has
indicated that he may put aside his peacemaking efforts and shift
to his domestic agenda, undertaking the so-called ``civic
revolution'' he proposed two weeks ago that would challenge many of
the powers and privileges of traditional religious parties. He
would seek to accomplish this by forging a unity government with
the rightist Likud Party and others, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is problematic. ``It is almost impossible to shelve the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict, for starters, and then the Likud has
said that it is not interested,'' said Joseph Alpher, an expert on
Israeli diplomacy who served as Barak's adviser during Camp David.
Still, Ariel Sharon, the former general who heads the Likud, might
be tempted into a transitional alliance if he is assured that no
territorial concessions to the Palestinians would be made in the
near future, Alpher said.
</P>
<P>
   These complexities are sobering for peace advocates who believe
that Camp David was a breakthrough, engaging the Israelis and the
Palestinians in their most substantive discussions to date of the
thorniest issues.
</P>
<P>
   While some with a long lens think those discussions broke ground
that will eventually bear fruit, others say they cannot help but be
downbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even veterans of the peace process who didn't lose hope during
the Netanyahu years have been talking about the need to save the
peace process from total collapse,'' Aluf Benn wrote in the Israeli
newspaper Haaretz on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And a senior diplomat here said glumly, ``I've always tended to
be optimistic, but I'm not very at this moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
