<P>
   ANDERSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: Here's a real survivor scenario: Let's find a young boy
in elementary school, say the fourth or fifth grade. Why don't we
give him an unwed mother, three younger siblings and an unknown
father? Have him live in the inner city, surrounded by gangs and
drugs. Send him to a school where he has to share textbooks because
there aren't enough to go around. Even more challenging, what if
there aren't enough teachers, so the classrooms are crowded? Let's
put up a nice government-funded recreation center in the
neighborhood, even though walking down the street in this community
is as safe as walking in a mine field. The objective for our young
contestant is to become an investment banker. By MONICA FRAZIER
ANDERSON. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ During a recent visit to Waco, I decided to drive by
Mount Carmel, the place where David Koresh and about 80 of his
Branch Davidian followers died in their flaming compound seven
years ago. The catastrophe that unfolded before our eyes on
television intruded on our minds again this summer when special
counsel John C. Danforth issued a preliminary report of an
investigation saying that the Davidians themselves, not the federal
government, set the fire that destroyed the sprawling makeshift
religious complex. By JIM JONES. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARMSTRONG-BOXED CDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Louis Armstrong may be remembered best for his later
work _ ``Hello Dolly'' and ``What a Wonderful World'' _ but it was
his groundbreaking work in the 1920s that earned him his legend and
gave the world some of the best jazz ever heard. Now all the songs
he cut with his Hot Five and Hot Seven bands has been collected in
a four-CD boxed set. By DAVE FERMAN. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-KEN FINKLEMAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Ken Finkleman has been called his country's best
satirist and its brightest ``auteur.'' Unfortunately, that country
is Canada, and his five TV series have had a tough time catching a
break in the United States. He plays the same ethically challenged
character, George Findlay, in each _ and Canadians are fascinated
by the mystery of where Findlay ends and Finkleman begins. By
ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
