A2097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-HIPHOP-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-05 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HIPHOP-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NIGHTLINE': NIGHTLINE EXPLORE'S HIP-HOP IN SAUNTERING 3-PART
REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Krulwich, a ``Nightline'' correspondent, shows a group of
teen-agers a snapshot of Al Gore and draws from them a collective
blank. Then he pulls out a photograph of Russell Simmons, a
corporate executive. Instant recognition all around!
</P>
<P>
   If you do know who Al Gore is, you may not know that Simmons was
one of the founders of Def Jam Records, the rap music label. He is
also chairman of Rush Communications, whose holdings include Phat
Farm. With these overlapping music and fashion franchises, you
could call Simmons the CEO of hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   In his three-part impressionistic series on hip-hop for
``Nightline,'' Krulwich almost immediately establishes himself as a
Gore-recognizing fogy. He begins his wry report with the image of
the rapper LL Cool J grinning from his limousine at his
enthusiastic fans in New York, who include a fawning policeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``LL Cool J has been famous for 15 years, or that is what I'm
told, because frankly I am not a rap fan and I am a little old,''
declares Krulwich. Later he says with puzzlement, ``If you're over
40, this world's a mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   But the music that came shouting defiantly out of the ghetto 25
years ago has become a huge international business, and economics
is one of Krulwich's reportorial specialties. So he plunges in _ or
rather, saunters in, approaching his subject in the deliberately
confounded style of Peter Falk as the eccentric detective on
``Columbo.'' (That series went off the air in 1977, just as rap was
taking hold.)
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night's episode, ``Hip-Hop Grows Up,'' using
Simmons and his Phat Farm as the centerpiece, Krulwich slyly
demonstrates how roaring capitalist success has harnessed this
revolutionary form of gangster-celebrating music (or co-opted it,
depending on your point of view).
</P>
<P>
   Simmons began his career 20 years ago as a young man promoting
raucous parties in the Bronx. Now, at 42, he has become a
caricature of a nouveau riche mogul. He has a much younger _ and,
of course, fabulous-looking _ wife, the 23-year-old fashion model
and television hostess Kimora Lee. He shops with The Robb Report,
which specializes in brands like Boucheron and Cartier
(``ridiculously lavish'' brands, to use Krulwich's description). He
denies his own fallibility, as rich people tend to.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean my body's going to change shape?'' he
responds defiantly when Krulwich asks him if, as a trendsetter for
people ages 15 to 25, he's worried about growing older and wider.
Luckily, Phat Farm's baggy hip-hop fashions give middle-aged men
plenty of deniability in the love-handles arena.
</P>
<P>
   Krulwich captures the supreme self-confidence and accessibility
that has helped Simmons acquire a net worth of $200 million. As
supremely self-confident people do, he has a trademark outfit _ a
baseball cap and sparkling Adidas, even when he's otherwise dressed
in more-or-less conventional evening clothes. Yet when young
recording star hopefuls greet him at the elevator in his sleek
corporate office building, he listens politely to their rap and
takes their demo tapes. He met Kevin Leong, the 23-year-old former
graffiti artist who is now Phat Farm's chief clothing designer, on
the elevator. ( Leong is featured in the third episode.)
</P>
<P>
   On camera, as Krulwich follows him through his workday, Simmons
is breezily arrogant, as if he had been bred in Hollywood instead
of in Hollis, N.Y., in Queens County, by middle-class teachers.
Asked why a white 50-year-old banker in Des Moines isn't hip-hop,
Simmons replies dismissively _ and quickly because he's about to
pick up the phone (again): ``You are going to buy at Old Navy,
you're going to be corny, you ain't got no flavor, you don't know
what's new and hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Krulwich, whose fashion preference is the rumpled look, gives
Simmons' emphasis on clothes and on what's ``new and hot'' a
friendly sociological spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hip-hop culture was born in poor neighborhoods where people
dream of owning things that instantly confer status _ the right
clothes, hot logos, brand names,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   But he does seem to wince when a clothing designer describes the
Simmonses' personal extravagance as an important marketing tool for
Phat Farm. Becoming what you buy, the designer explains, is ``the
American dream.'' The correspondent says dubiously, ``Well, it's an
American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing how enmeshed rap has become in the culture, the issue of
rap-related violence doesn't emerge until Part 2, to be shown
Thursday night. Listening to the lyrics of a Jay-Z song about rough
sex with a prostitute and murder, Krulwich says, ``I find this
music offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the cagey reporter, stating an opinion is just another
way of opening an inquiry. Lyor Cohen, Simmons' partner in Def Jam
Records and the son of Israeli parents, says that Krulwich should
find the music offensive because destroying the establishment is a
time-honored tradition in music.
</P>
<P>
   That acknowledged, Krulwich still distinguishes rap from other
once-revolutionary forms of music like rock 'n' roll, jazz and
ragtime. He questions the merits of rap lyrics that are often dirty
and graphically violent. ``How could this have any lasting value?''
he asks. (You'll have to watch the program to learn the answer. The
second half of Part 2 wasn't available for screening.)
</P>
<P>
   This is an amicable investigation, however, so in Friday's
episode Krulwich also manages to find a quiet, poignant figure in
the highly charged, materialistic hip-hop world. Joseph Sadler,
known as Grand Master Flash, was the man who found his calling in
the breaks between the grooves in records. For three years in the
1970s he sat in his room spinning records, composing riffs that
could be tucked inside the beat. He developed ``scratching,'' an
improvisational style that became intrinsic to hip-hop music. There
was no money in it then, just an idea about music. Imagine that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
