<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    IF THE GORE AND BUSH THINK IT'S HOT NOW
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 9/6-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's gotta be the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Only the double-plus-killer-degree temperature possibly can
explain, not just all the political silliness of the Labor Day
weekend, but the public's reaction to all of it.
</P>
<P>
   So, there actually have been pleasant, at least quite bearable,
temperatures in much of the country, and maybe it's just the
inclination of so many Americans to empathize with Texans that
explains a lot of the screwy doings.
</P>
<P>
   How else to account for so much that's occurred with not even a
noticeable public shrug in reaction?
</P>
<P>
   It just has to be the heat that kept Bill Clinton from being
laughed out of the presidency with his veto of a bill repealing the
federal estate tax because, he said, it was fiscally irresponsible
and unfair to the 98 percent of Americans who would be left out.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me? A bill that ends the practice of taxing, in the views
of Democrats Clinton and Al Gore, 2 percent of the public isn't
fair to the 98 percent who don't pay the tax? If it's not the heat,
what in the occasional thunderstorm is it?
</P>
<P>
   Was the temp in Washington actually bearable, the air
conditioning in the White House working when Clinton, in what The
New York Times called an echo of Gore's repeated charges at his
Republican presidential opponent, George W. Bush, vetoed the repeal
of the estate tax?
</P>
<P>
   According to the Houston Chronicle, the hottest it got in
Washington that veto-day was 81 degrees, and there was no
indication his publicly sponsored air conditioning was out of whack
when Clinton vetoed the bill and warned its passage would prevent
the federal government from paying down the debt and investing in
education, health care, the environment and other priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, it was the heat of some kind, somewhere that kept most
Americans from scratching their heads in great alarm that paying
for all those things is dependent on 2 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while it indeed seems it was the heat that kept America
quiet about this bill, one round of errands in the 107-degree heat
of Houston that veto-day found the veto was being discussed.
Certainly, it was far behind the weather in most conversations, but
if your errands take you to family-owned businesses, bring up the
topic the next time you're out and about.
</P>
<P>
   As for other effects of the heat on Labor Day politics:
</P>
<P>
   Bush may have been in a pretty cool Chicago suburb when he stuck
his proverbial foot in his political mouth by insulting _ over an
open microphone _ a New York Times reporter. What's to say? That he
was not long gone from the horrid heat of Texas when he, aided and
abetted by his running mate Dick Cheney, pointed out, ``a
major-league anatomical expletive'' from the Times?
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows where Al Gore spokesman Chris Lehane was when he
was quick to comment on Bush not knowing how far to be from a mike
to ensure you're safe. But he sure should count himself lucky he
wasn't struck by lightening when he had the nerve to say, with,
presumably, a straight face: ``We hold virtually all members of the
Fourth Estate in the highest regard, and we believe they should be
part of the democratic process day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   This had to have been the heat. Geez, the whole careless
coarseness and evaluation of it had to have been the products of
heat-struck brains.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there was Gore and his Labor Day gimmick of a
28-hour political tour, flying about the countryside in an awfully
comfortable government plane to tell folk how he's for the people
while his GOP opponent is for the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, he staged this marathon excursion to demonstrate he
can work long hours.
</P>
<P>
   Just one more example of how the heat surely had to be a
contributor to Labor Day politics. That's the one about the
presidential debates. The temptation is to say Bush blazed a bit
ahead when he offered to do three debates with Gore, but with only
one to be run by the Presidential Debate Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who really has, as Bush contended, gone just about
everywhere, challenging and begging and bugging Bush to debate him,
turned down Bush's offer. Seems Bush now has to do the three
debates proposed by the commission or Gore, who's coming way up in
the polls, doesn't want to play.
</P>
<P>
   So both sides had an awful lot of Labor Day silliness. What both
sides need to understand now is: It may still be as hot as the
plain old hell, but it's getting on toward too late to keep all
this up.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, guys, if you all don't cool down and start acting like
adults, Lord knows how hot the voters will be by Election Day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
