<SLUG> BC-UN-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE DOWNPLAYS CLINTON USING UN SUMMIT TO REVIVE PEACE
TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As more than 150 world leaders gathered in New York
for a summit on global problems, the White House downplayed the
likelihood that President Clinton can use the event to revive
Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in New York for the United Nations Millennium Summit,
plans to meet separately with Israeli and Palestinian leaders
Wednesday in his bid to rejuvenate talks that collapsed at Camp
David earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But national security adviser Sandy Berger said Tuesday there is
little chance that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian Chairman Yasser Arafat will have a ``meeting of the
minds'' before their Sept. 13 deadline for reaching agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is a make or break week,'' Berger said
during a White House briefing on the president's trip. He added,
however, that unless there is some progress in New York, ``it
becomes increasingly difficult to imagine'' a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hope will happen this week is that we see a distinct
way forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that trilateral talks were not expected this weekend.
Arafat is to leave New York in time to attend a meeting with the
Central Council of the Palestine Liberation Organization in Gaza
City on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, Clinton addresses the largest-ever gathering
of kings, presidents and prime ministers at the United Nations,
kicking off a whirlwind three-day schedule in which he will shuttle
between the United Nations and the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel to meet
with leaders from Russia, China, Korea, the Middle East and Africa,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the president and his Middle East envoy, Dennis
Ross, have spent the past few weeks assessing the situation and
urging both sides in the 52-year-old conflict to avoid unilateral
moves that might jeopardize the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a week in which the president can take stock of where
we are in this process, whether there is the possibility here for
progress beyond where we were in Camp David,'' he said. ``I think
that we're all quite conscious of the fact that there is not an
enormous amount of time left for the parties to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. mediators have downplayed the urgency of completing
an agreement in the next seven days, Arafat has threatened to
declare an independent Palestinian state if the Sept. 13 deadline
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who has come under fire at home for concessions he
offered Arafat this summer, has said it is now up to the
Palestinians to compromise. Israel's Foreign Ministry said Monday
that the prime minister was not planning to present new ideas to
Clinton this week.
</P>
<P>
   The major sticking point is over the future of Jerusalem, which
both Israelis and Palestinians claim as their capital. Disagreement
on that crucial point caused the Camp David peace talks to fizzle
after 15 days of negotiations at Clinton's retreat in Maryland's
Catoctin Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The eastern part of Jerusalem has been held by Israel since
Jordanian troops were expelled in the Six-Day War in 1967. Barak
had tentatively agreed to give up major portions of east Jerusalem
and made other concessions, but he was not willing to meet Arafat's
demand that the old walled city be placed under Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
   Since those talks ended, Clinton has been in contact with other
regional players. Last week, he made an impromptu stop in Cairo for
a 90-minute meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. After
the meeting, both said they were committed to helping Barak and
Arafat find a solution, but they cautioned that the two sides did
not appear to be nearing a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the time is short for resolving this,'' Clinton said
then. ``...We're going to work together and see if we can find a
way to help the parties get over this next big hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said Clinton and Mubarak were ``keeping in very close
touch'' to share information on the peace process. The envoy has
spent the past week drafting a paper summarizing points of
``near-agreement'' at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that, based on discussions we've had at Camp David,
that it is possible to reach an agreement,'' Ross said in Cairo.
``The real question is how do you translate that possibility into a
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton had earlier praised Barak, saying he had made
deeper concessions than Arafat, Ross said there's ``no question''
that a genuine effort is being made by both Barak and Arafat to
reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we can do that, I can't yet say,'' he said. ``That we
think it's possible, I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York Tuesday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan also
expressed optimism. ``I don't think the two parties have ever been
closer than they are today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan urged all leaders arriving for the summit to use the
unprecedented meeting to end poverty and make peace.
</P>
<P>
   But some heads of state are expected to use the event to push
their own agendas, including some United States-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro, who arrived in New York Tuesday,
is expected to rail against American dominance of the United
Nations in his speech Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea denounced the United States as a ``rogue state''
Tuesday. And Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin and Chinese
President Jiang Zemin are expected to use the gathering to rally
support against U.S. national missile defense plans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
