<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following business
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Sept. 6, and thereafter. For more information, contact
William Toren at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-PROFITS (Los Angeles) _ The long, hot summer of 2000 set
more than dry forest land on fire, as the stocks of two companies
in the business of reliable power provision have skyrocketed since
the beginning of summer. That's when Capstone Turbine and Power-One
split 3-for-2. By Robert Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   CALSTATE-COMPUTERS (Los Angeles) _ Southern California computer
companies are behind one of California State University,
Northridge's newest majors, the bachelor's of science in computer
engineering. The hybrid between computer science and electrical
engineering teaches both the software and hardware sides of the
technology, servicing a growing need in L.A.'s tech corridor. By
Robert Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   MOM-FRIENDLY (Los Angeles) _ Universal Studios is among
America's 100 best employers for helping women balance careers and
motherhood, according to a ranking by Working Mother magazine. By
Jesse Hiestand.
</P>
</TEXT>
