<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-05 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BUSH'S INEXPLICABLE LATE-SUMMER SLUMP
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the race for the Republican presidential nomination quickened
last fall, George W. Bush said: ``I still have time to screw this
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps over the last three weeks, as Bush's lead in polls
vanished and Al Gore gained a clear upper hand in the national
race, the Texas governor recalled that observation, which he made
to the Washington Post's David Broder.
</P>
<P>
   There is almost always some ebb and flow in a presidential race
without an incumbent, but Bush's at least momentary fade in the
wake of the Democratic National Convention has been startling.
</P>
<P>
   As we wait for the rest of the post-Labor Day polling to reveal
the kind of fix Bush really is in, let's examine the governor's
slump.
</P>
<P>
   Bush chief strategist Karl Rove legitimately can point out that
he was firmly on the record predicting that the race would likely
narrow and that Bush could slip behind. But if that's the case, why
were Bush and his campaign seemingly so unprepared to respond to
what were hardly surprise Gore turns to populist bombast and to the
reliably Democratic issue of health care, specifically a
prescription drug benefit through Medicare?
</P>
<P>
   Republican insiders say that the Austin high command was stunned
by the strongly positive response to Gore's selection of Joe
Lieberman as his vice-presidential running mate. Rove's publicly
expressed view that there was nothing Gore could do to shake up the
race was proved wrong. Bush leaders watched in virtual silence as
the Gore campaign whipped up attention to Lieberman as the first
Jew on a national ticket _ instead of focusing on Lieberman as a
fanny-covering device that Gore needed to deflect the Clinton
scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush, Rove &AMP; Co. breathed easier as public polling during
the first three nights of the Democratic convention, including
President Clinton's self-indulgent performance, produced little, if
any, movement to Gore. But that changed dramatically with Gore's
acceptance speech, which played much better with the general public
than with many delegates and commentators (including me).
</P>
<P>
   Gore hasn't looked back. What was Bush thinking? Did he believe
the Democrats would pack it in for a couple of weeks? Politics
abhors a vacuum, and Gore and his campaign filled it, both
nationally and in some states where Bush should have been breathing
easily by now.
</P>
<P>
   Most alarming for Republicans is Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's prescription drug message, which Bush only got around to
answering Tuesday, has been aimed directly at Florida's plethora of
older, persuadable &QL; 
voters.
</P>
<P>
   On the national front, there was a panicky look to the Bush
campaign's handling of the first Republican National Committee
attack ad against Gore. The governor ultimately canned the spot,
but not until it had been beamed out to television stations.
Perhaps that's what made Bush defensive about the second RNC ad, a
medium-sharp send-up of Gore and, among other things, the Buddhist
fund-raising fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may have a number of things of late to be modest about, but
running an ad with Gore at the Hsi Lai Temple shaking down the
faithful is not among them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lapses on the trail have been more than verbal gaffes.
He's missed some easy pitches, including an odd reluctance to
endorse Alan Greenspan for another term as Federal Reserve chairman
_ even though his latest term has only begun and the seat won't be
up again until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. If Bush were at the top of his game he might have
recalled that there are two Fed vacancies likely to be there in
January and proposed cloning Greenspan for both spots.
</P>
<P>
   For some Bush partisans, the lackluster response from Austin in
late August was reminiscent of the all but non-existent effort to
counter John McCain's build-up in New Hampshire which began about a
year ago and climaxed with his drubbing of Bush in the Granite
State primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin operatives don't have much time to decide how to
respond now. For there is something else Bush told Broder last fall
that the governor and his campaign might want to keep in mind:
``This is going to be over before a lot of people realize &QL; 
it's begun.''
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
