<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2114 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECHOPTICS0906-COX     09-05 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHOPTICS0906-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Optics a hot topic among venture capitalists
</P>
<P>
   By Kathy Brister
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Ask a venture capitalist what his eye is on these
days, and he's likely to say optics.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of optic technology is that it can make fiber now
being buried at a furious pace by telecommunications and cable
companies efficient enough to handle bandwidth-hungry applications
for years.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is if these companies can do more with the fiber
they've already got in the ground, it'll be a long time before they
must undertake the costly task of burying more.
</P>
<P>
   That's why some of the same venture capitalists and Wall Street
pundits who last year touted business-to-business Internet firms as
sure things now are singing the praises of optics. The market has
switched from being interested in what people will do with the
Internet to the plumbing of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Internet infrastructure) does feel much more viable than
content or applications,'' said Alan Taetle, a venture capitalist
at Noro-Moseley Partners of Atlanta. ``It's tangible. You can
identify the customer base. You can clearly see coming revenues''
based on an ``insatiable demand for bandwidth.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining with the monied chorus are companies positioning to
profit from selling optic technology. They make the hardware _
transmitters, amplifiers, receivers _ needed to push light-based
data streams down a fiber strand.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta has gone on an investing spree to ramp up its
optics expertise, putting about $31 million in the past few months
into three firms on the leading edge of the technology.
Scientific-Atlanta now touts its optical amplifier as one of the
most powerful on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Through the investments, the Norcross company gained more than
tech know-how. It also capitalized on Wall Street's fondness for
optics. Scientific-Atlanta's $13 million investment in U.K.-based
Bookham Technology, made in mid-1999, now is worth more than $300
million based on a soaring valuation of the optical-component
maker, said Paul Connolly, vice president of network architectures
for Scientific-Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value to us is not the gain on investment. We really
wanted to keep a close eye on (Bookham's) technology,'' Connolly
said.
</P>
<P>
   Duluth-based Antec Corp. has tapped into the optics marketplace,
selling equipment that boost light-based transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Stanzione, Antec's chief executive officer, contends
Internet site Napster _ which lets user exchange digital music
files _ is all the proof he needs to see bandwidth demand has the
potential to outpace fiber capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Napster, the cat's out of the bag. (Napster's) given
people an idea what it's like to easily share files,'' and
ultimately those files will include bandwidth-draining video, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is convinced that fiber going into the ground
today will need the efficiencies of optic technology soon. The idea
that burgeoning applications _ video-on-demand, in-home video
conferencing, houses wired for remote control by out-of-town owners
_ will suck up the capacity of available fiber is a myth, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly no possibility of fiber exhaustion,'' said Tom
Nolle, president of New Jersey-based telecommunications consulting
firm CIMI Corp. Nolle _ who bases his research on Federal
Communications Commission and Securities and Exchange Commission
filings by large telecom companies and on industry interviews _
contends just 13 percent of fiber in the ground is being used.
</P>
<P>
   Nolle said it would take years for burgeoning bandwidth-heavy
applications to use up available fiber capacity. Investors and
industry players are creating an irrational frenzy around the idea
that fiber will run out, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that seems to be a minority view and the development of the
new technology continues rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest optic technologies is wavelength division
multiplexing, which uses laser technology invented in the 1950s but
largely shelved until the 1980s. In WDM, lasers push light through
prisms. The resulting rainbow then is separated into color-coded
channels, or wavelengths. Each of these colors _ numbering from a
dozen to hundreds _ carries a stream of information with a single
purpose or destination.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a shade of blue can carry all the voice traffic
leaving an office tower. A red channel can carry all the data
heading out of the building. Or, a yellow stream of light can carry
all the voice and data traffic traveling from that building to a
satellite office.
</P>
<P>
   Wavelength division multiplexing has at its core another
fiber-enhancing technology _ time division multiplexing. TDM has
been in use via copper lines since the mid-1970s and via
fiber-optic cables since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It uses pulses of light generated by a laser to transmit data.
</P>
<P>
   While wave division multiplexing increases the number of
channels simultaneously running across a fiber, time division
multiplexing increases the speed at which each bit of information
travels over that fiber.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't manufacture enough (fiber) to keep up with demand,''
said Kathy Szelag, vice president of marketing for Lucent
Technologies' optical networking group. That's why Lucent is
looking beyond simply producing more fiber _ as 3,600 of the
company's employees do at its fiber-production plant in Norcross _
to making the fiber that customers have do more.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's New Jersey-based optical group creates equipment for
building optical networks. A single strand of Lucent's
highest-grade fiber combined with its state-of-the-art optics
transmission equipment can carry all telephone voice traffic in the
United States, Szelag said.
</P>
<P>
   Antec's Stanzione contends the number of Internet users sending
truly heavy-duty information across today's networks is
``minuscule.'' But that will change once cable and
telecommunications companies deliver the high-speed Internet
connections people want, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antec's customers (cable companies) aren't having trouble
selling these services, they're having trouble keeping up with
demand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies who will foot the bill for optic technology
aren't rushing to deploy it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Time Warner Cable and Atlanta-based Cox Communications
predict it'll be a while before they'll need wavelength division
multiplexing to expand the capacity of their fiber. And even then,
it'll only be used in high-use homes or businesses within high-use
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner has included optical equipment in 95 percent of its
upgraded cable markets, but the company doesn't expect to use wave
division multiplexing soon, said Paul Gemme, vice president of
plant engineering for Time Warner Cable.
</P>
<P>
   For Cox, ``it'll be three to five years before we have enough
subscribers and enough high-powered applications to need to look at
more efficient fiber use,'' said Alex Best, Cox's executive vice
president of engineering. Cox Communications is majority owned by
the same company that owns the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   CIMI's Nolle predicts it'll take even longer and that the wait
will cool growth in optics-based firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation in the industry is not for a gradual change,
it's for an immediate change,'' he said. ``But vendors who are
entering the market in optics today are not going to find the
buyers they expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
