<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA BEGINS COUNTDOWN FOR ATLANTIS MISSION TO SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ NASA on Tuesday began the countdown for
the launching of the shuttle Atlantis on a mission to prepare the
international space station for the arrival of its first resident
astronauts and cosmonauts late this year.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle is scheduled to lift off from NASA's Kennedy Space
Center on Friday at 7:45 a.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters offered a 60 percent chance of favorable weather,
warning that showers or cloudy skies could thwart efforts to begin
the 11-day flight.
</P>
<P>
   Once they dock with the station, the seven-member Atlantis crew
will unload 5,000 pounds of cargo from the shuttle and from an
unmanned Russian Progress cargo capsule that has been parked at the
orbital outpost since early August.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo includes mechanical devices to generate and recycle
air aboard the space station, a toilet, exercise equipment and
other gear future residents of the station will require.
</P>
<P>
   During a lengthy spacewalk, two of the fliers are prepared to
install an external guidance device called a magnetometer as well
as to connect communications cables between two of the station's
three modules.
</P>
<P>
   The activities are intended to prepare the slowly developing
station for the arrival of American commander Bill Shepherd and
cosmonauts Yuri Gidzenko and Sergei Krikalev in early November. The
three men are prepared for a four-month stay, kicking off at least
a decade of permanent occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   The milestone was made possible in July with the long-delayed
launching of the Russian-built Zvezda crew module, a 43-foot-long
compartment that equipped the station with its first living and
working quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Russian economic problems slowed development of the Zvezda
module by more than two years. The difficulties brought all major
construction of the station to a halt after the first major
components were joined in orbit in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis mission marks the first in a wave of nine supply
and construction flights planned by NASA this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all excited. There are an awful lot of launches coming
up in the next year, and the space station will really begin to
take shape,'' said Atlantis astronaut Ed Lu as the shuttle crew
arrived at Kennedy late Sunday for the countdown. ``We're all
looking forward to getting this off on the right foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis commander Terry Wilcutt's crew includes pilot Scott
Altman, flight engineer Rick Mastracchio, mission specialist Dan
Burbank, Russian cosmonaut Boris Morukov, Lu and his spacewalking
colleague Yuri Malenchenko, also a Russian cosmonaut.
</P>
<P>
   The seven men will fly NASA training aircraft, attend mission
briefings, undergo medical exams and rest during the countdown.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, space agency officials reported near trouble-free
launch preparations. Over the weekend, lightning damaged a runway
navigational aid that furnishes shuttle crews with distance and
directional measurements during the landing phase of their flight.
The ground system was repaired Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
