<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Sept. 6 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DRUGS (Allentown, Pa.) _ Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday
proposed a fundamental overhaul of Medicare, giving elderly people
the option to purchase a prescription drug benefit and offering
subsidies for lower income people to buy private health insurance.
Bush unveiled his Medicare plan after weeks of pressure from Vice
President Al Gore who considers health care one of his strongest
issues and who has been hammering his rival for avoiding specifics.
In doing so Bush took a sharply different approach from Gore who
would dedicate more money to the current Medicare system and then
add a new government prescription drug benefit on top of it. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,4.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DRUGS-COMPARE (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush's proposal
to redesign Medicare and offer drug benefits to the elderly puts
him squarely in line with his party's drive to change the course of
the program by reducing the role of government, increasing the role
of insurance companies and giving elderly people more choices. By
Robert Pear and Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-COSTS (Undated) _ Health insurance premiums are increasing
anywhere from 10 percent to 30 percent across the country, the
steepest increase since the early 1990s, according to employers,
insurers, and regional business groups. The increase is driven in
large part by a rapid increase in drug costs, analysts and
employers said. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-ITHACA (Ithaca, N.Y.) _ In rampage killing cases around
the country, people who knew the killers often said they alerted
police about strange behavior beforehand, but were told by police
that their hands were tied. Ithaca, in a system that policing
experts say is unmatched in the country, has tried to deal with
this problem. When police here receive a report that someone is
behaving bizarrely, making threats or talking suicide, a police
officer and a mental health clinic supervisor are sent together to
assess the situation. They can intervene when the case is
potentially dangerous, such as when someone is threatening murder,
but also in cases that seem less serious, as when a woman recently
reported seeing Martians. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT (United Nations) _ Ledeall on the summit
at the United Nations. By Dean E. Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT6,21.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS NOTE: The early version of the U.N. summit story, by
Christopher Wren, has moved; it will be updated with a complete
writethru later tonight. The press conference with the
secretary-general covered in the early version will be refiled
later as U.N.-ANNAN.)
</P>
