<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COX-AOL-MERGER-06     09-05 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-AOL-MERGER-06 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIME WARNER AND AOL FACE REGULATORY PRESSURES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - As regulators in the United States and Europe
increase scrutiny of the proposed merger of Time Warner Inc. and
America Online Inc., consumer advocates may be getting closer to
winning the safeguards they want on the deal
</P>
<P>
   ``Regulators on both sides of the Atlantic are alarmed about
this merger and its consequences to competition,'' said Jeffrey
Chester, executive director of the Center for Media Education, a
non-profit group pushing for government-imposed restraints on the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   Today and Thursday, European regulators will be holding
closed-door hearings to grill AOL and Time Warner executives about
their plans to create a global interactive media giant. A
confidential report, issued by the European Commission and leaked
to the U.S. media, suggests the hearings will be less than
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The report says the European Commission, which sets anti-trust
policy for 15 countries, has reached the ``preliminary view'' that
``competition would be significantly impeded'' if the merger were
to proceed as proposed.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, both the Federal Trade Commission (FTC)
and Federal Communications Commission (FCC) are stepping up their
investigations, and the House subcommittee on telecommunications
plans to hold a hearing on the merger later this month. The date
has not yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   Chester said that if AOL, the world's No. 1 Internet company,
and Time Warner, one of the world's biggest cable and media
companies, were to join forces, the combined company could force
captive cable customers to take AOL Time Warner's services and
content.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent that, Chester said regulators must insist AOL Time
Warner offer its cable customers an unlimited number choices among
Internet service providers. It also must offer a full array of
content, without bias for its own material, and end all joint
ventures with AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest cable operator, to
ensure tough competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deal was announced Jan. 10, executives of AOL and Time
Warner have repeatedly said they would offer their content and
services via digital subscriber lines and satellite, as well as
cable, to give customers plenty of choices.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cooper, research director of the Consumer Federation of
America, said even that assurance rings hollow without a consent
decree, enforceable in court. AOL and Time Warner executives
``obviously have not convinced anyone'' they will keep their word,
he said. As a result, consumer advocates are gaining ground with
the regulators. ``We're getting there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Washington Post reported that unnamed sources
said the FTC may ask AOL to sell its $1.5 billion stake in General
Motors Corp.'s Hughes Electronics unit, a maker of satellites. And
the Wall Street Journal reported that regulators might restrict AOL
Time Warner's relationship with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   An FTC spokesman refused to comment on the reports.
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory reviews may be rattling some investors. Shares of
Time Warner fell $2.88, or 3 percent, to close at $81.50 on the New
York Stock Exchange, where shares of AOL were unchanged at $57.50.
</P>
<P>
   Scott B. Davis, a Wall Street analyst with First Union
Securities, said he believes that while some consumer safeguards
may be imposed, the merger is in no danger of being killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at what issues have been raised, I don't see
anything...that would be anywhere close to a deal breaker,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Time Warner executives ``are going to have to provide strong
assurances that they will do what they have said'' about giving
consumers many choices, he said. ``But at the end of the day, the
merger will close on schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for AOL and Time Warner say the reviews do not
threaten the deal, which is ``on track to close this fall.''
Shareholders of both companies already have approved it
overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Trade Commission site at http://www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Federal Communications Commission site: http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   AOL site: http://www.corp.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner site: http://www.timewarner.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
