<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV10-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three Discounters Open New Air Routes
</P>
<P>
   Three discount airlines are establishing new routes this autumn
_ AirTran Airways is adding service to Toledo, Ohio, from its hub
in Atlanta; JetBlue Airways is expanding its service between
Kennedy International Airport and Florida; and the Las Vegas-based
National Airlines will begin flying to Ronald Reagan National
Airport in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran, (800) 247-8726 or www.airtran.com on the Web, is
introducing service between Atlanta and Toledo on Oct. 3 with three
daily nonstops using DC-9 jets. A one-way ticket starts at $79 if
purchased 14 days in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Oct. 18, JetBlue, (800) 538-2583 or www.jetblue.com,
will offer daily flights from Kennedy Airport to West Palm Beach,
Fla., aboard Airbus A320s. On Nov. 18, that service will increase
to twice a day, and a daily flight to Fort Myers, Fla., will begin.
A one-way ticket for either destination starts at $79 14 days in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   National Airlines, (888) 757-5387 or www.nationalairlines.com on
the Web, will begin offering daily nonstop flights on Boeing 757's
to Ronald Reagan National Airport in Washington from Las Vegas on
Oct. 26. The 14-day advance round-trip fare starts at $328.
</P>
<P>
   London Museum Addresses Digital Age
</P>
<P>
   London's Science Museum has recently opened a
107,640-square-foot addition that explores such topics as genetics,
digital technology and artificial intelligence. Designed by
MacCormac Jamieson Prichard, the four floors of the new Wellcome
Wing contain six exhibition areas and a 450-seat Imax theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A first-floor exhibition called Antenna presents the latest
developments in science. It covers drugs in sports, among other
subjects, and looks at how engineers study sea life such as sharks
and seahorses with robotic submarines. Pattern Pod, an area for
children 8 and younger, allows participants to explore patterns
that occur in nature, like those in a butterfly's wings, through
hands-on games and interactive wall and floor panels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who Am I, on the second floor, presents the latest developments
in biomedical research. Visitors will see equipment used for the
Human Genome Project and will be able to find out how DNA was used
in identifying living relatives of the Bleadon Man, a
2,000-year-old Iron Age man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A highlight of the new wing is the computer that Tim Berners-Lee
used to design the World Wide Web at the CERN physics laboratory
near Geneva, writing the first software for it in 1990 and 1991; it
can be seen at Digitopolis on the third floor. In Future, on the
fourth floor, allows visitors to use interactive games to explore
how science and technology can affect the future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Science Museum, Exhibition Road, South Kensington, London
SW7 2DD; (44-207) 942 4455, www.sciencemuseum.org.uk. Open daily 10
a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission $10.40, free for children under 16.
</P>
<P>
   Nob Hill Landmark Unveils Renovations
</P>
<P>
   The Mark Hopkins Inter-Continental Hotel in San Francisco is
scheduled to complete a yearlong renovation by the end of this
month. Although the 19-story hotel, a Nob Hill fixture for more
than 75 years, has remained open during the project, up to 75
percent of its rooms were closed at a time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Improvements include expanded bathrooms, a renovated lobby, new
decor and the installation of high-speed Internet access and
high-tech lighting and temperature controls in each room. To
accommodate 10 new suites, the number of rooms has dropped from 389
to 380. Other than a cleaning, the renovations did not involve the
hotel's landmark facade, which was restored about 18 years ago.
Also untouched was its well-known Top of the Mark lounge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Built in French chateau and Spanish Renaissance styles, the
hotel opened in 1926 on the site of the former mansion of Mark
Hopkins, one of four magnates who founded what eventually became
the Southern Pacific Railroad.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mark Hopkins Inter-Continental is at 1 Nob Hill, (800)
662-4455; on the Web at www.markhopkins.net. Doubles run $320 to
$410, with suites $510 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Authors Offer Advice On the Web, for a Fee
</P>
<P>
   A new Web site allows travelers to consult with guidebook
authors to plan their trips and make reservations with specialists
on particular destinations. The site, 12degrees.com, which went
online in June without fanfare, is not a search engine for
discounts but rather is a way to plan customized travel.
</P>
<P>
   The site lists more than 30 writers who are available for
consultation in planning a trip. These freelance authors have had a
name-brand guidebook published _ by Fodor's, Lonely Planet or
Frommer's, among other series _ in the last three years, according
to Steve Bisset, the chief executive officer. These consultations,
generally by phone or e-mail, cost $75 to $125 an hour, with an
estimate given before the consultation. The authors also provide
the site with suggested itineraries, which are available free to
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the site lists 60 travel specialists, wholesale
companies of 2 to 10 people, who plan and book travel to areas they
know intimately. Pallavi Shah, for example, who specializes in
India and Italy, operates Our Personal Guest, a custom travel
agency in Manhattan. She grew up in India and has returned more
than 80 times, and has been planning trips to Italy for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   There is no extra charge for the service of the specialists, who
work on a typical commission basis with hotels, airlines and other
providers, according to Mark Campbell, 12degrees' marketing
director.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, go to www.12degrees.com or call (888)
390-1919.
</P>
<P>
   French Towns Compete With (and for) Flowers
</P>
<P>
   There's a fairly common road sign in France that guidebooks and
maps aren't much help with. Wherever a major roadway enters a city,
town or village, there is a sign stating the name of the community
in bold black and white _ easy to understand. But right under the
name of about 1,600 communities, you will also see one to four
cartoonish flower symbols, five-lobed daisies of the sort that used
to adorn VW Beetles 30 years ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   If you are lucky, your map might tell you that the symbol means
``award-winning floral environment,'' an indication that in the
town ahead, you should plan on stopping to smell the roses ... and
the cannas, petunias and other flowers. The town has won a
nationwide competition for horticultural excellence called Villes
et Villages Fleuris, which has been under way for more than 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   This year 185 towns in France have proudly hung new signs _ in
bold red and yellow. Recent winners are Bandol, on the Cote d'Azur,
and Houlgate, in Normandy, both of which won a one-flower sign last
year. The highest rank is four-flower Grand Prix, which means a
second sign, in white and green, is added. Last year Colmar in
Alsace won such a rating.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a town enters the competition, the citizens, businesses and
government agree to cooperate in planting flowers and gardens in
all sorts of places visible to the public, including front yards,
traffic circles and residential windowboxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 11,000 communities compete each year. Last year, 129
cities and villages were awarded the four-flower sign (the number
changes each year).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A free booklet (in French and updated annually) describes the
four-flower villages. ``Ballades: 129 Villes et Villages Fleuris''
is distributed by the French Government Tourist Office, 444 Madison
Ave., 16th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10022.
</P>
<P>
   By the Casinos, a Casbah (Las Vegas Style)
</P>
<P>
   The word ``bizarre'' has been applied to Las Vegas more than
once. Now ``bazaar'' has entered the local lexicon, too, with the
opening last month of Desert Passage, a shopping mall with a Middle
Eastern theme.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a ``shopping adventure,'' rather than a
``shopping mall,'' if one is to believe the promoters of the
500,000-square-foot retail center, which is connected to the
Aladdin Resort and Casino, across Las Vegas Boulevard from
Bellagio. How adventuresome most shoppers will feel as they walk by
such mall regulars as Ann Taylor, Clinique and Hugo Boss is
anybody's guess. Then again, there's probably a limited market for
figs, dates and exotic spices in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Passage, much like the Forum Shops at Caesars Palace, is
designed to apply the theme-park touch to spending and getting. The
130 stores and 14 restaurants are set amid Moorish archways,
authentic antiques and other Moroccan decor, all of it aimed at
making shoppers think they are strolling in the markets of Tangier,
Fez and Marrakesh. A 115-foot freighter is ``docked'' inside the
building, and there is an eight-story re-creation of a hillside
village.
</P>
<P>
   The stores are open daily from 10 a.m. to midnight, although the
restaurants and nightclubs will operate later. Even when all the
businesses are closed, Desert Passage will remain open for visitors
to walk through.
</P>
<P>
   As with any good casbah, the pace barely slows at night. The
restaurants in Desert Passage will include branches of Commander's
Palace, the New Orleans restaurant; Bice, from Milan; and Anasazi,
from Santa Fe. The Blue Note Jazz Club, a haunt of Manhattan jazz
aficionados, also has a branch there.
</P>
<P>
   But even though there is a rug merchant, Desert Passage will
never pass for an authentic souk for at least one reason: No
tourist touts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
