<SLUG> BC-MA-ADL-LEIKIND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT DIRECTOR TO LEAD NEW ENGLAND ADL EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nine months after the death of its revered regional
director, the Anti-Defamation League Tuesday chose the longtime
director of its Connecticut office to replace Leonard Zakim as the
civil rights organization's top official in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Leikind, a former Essex County assistant district
attorney and a graduate of Boston College Law School, will begin
work Wednesday as executive director of the organization's New
England region, based in Boston. The Anti-Defamation League is a
Jewish community organization that fights anti-Semitism with a
variety of programs aimed at preventing and responding to prejudice
and bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Zakim had directed the ADL's New England region for 15 years
before his death of cancer last December at the age of 46. Zakim
was well regarded by a variety of community and religious leaders
for his efforts to battle prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously difficult whenever you have someone as
charismatic and as important to an organization who you lose, but
Rob is going to be a terrific executive director,'' said Carl E.
Axelrod, regional chairman of the ADL. ``He knew Lenny, and that
will help, but Rob will be his own person and Rob will be
different. He will have his strengths as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Leikind, a 47-year-old native of Great Neck, N.Y., has been the
director of the Connecticut office for 11 years. In that capacity,
he has been an advocate of laws against hate crimes, an opponent of
school vouchers, and has worked with Jewish insitutions on security
concerns after a rash of bomb threats last year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Leikind said that although numerous people have
suggested to him that following Zakim will be difficult, he views
succeeding such a visible leader as a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenny was an extraordinarly gifted and heroic leader who had a
creative mind and a passion that was second to none,'' Leikind
said. ``He instilled a vision in people, and that gives me an
advantage and a leg up that few professionals have.''
</P>
<P>
   Leikind takes over the Boston office at a time when it is
strong, having enjoyed fundraising and programming successes over
the last year. He declined to offer any specific proposals for
Boston, saying he would spend the next months familiarizing himself
with the office and the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to understand the programs that are already running and
existing, but a big part of my job will be to sustain the momentum
and the excitement that surrounds the work of the ADL,'' Leikind
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, Leikind spent his energy working on diversity
training programs for adults and children, including using
theatrical programs to discuss prejudice. He also attempted to help
local communities to create anti-bias coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   Leikind was active in pushing the Connecticut legislature on a
variety of proposals to stiffen punishment for bias crimes and to
promote freedom of religious expression.
</P>
<P>
   As a resident of New Haven and an active member of Connecticut's
Jewish community, Leikind is friendly with Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
who is the Democratic nominee for vice president. Asked whether he
supported the ADL's decision last week to take Lieberman to task
for some of his comments about religion in public life, Leikind
said he thought the ADL had ``raised an important issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as our religious values and faith are a very important
avenue for hope and healing in our society, historically religious
differences have become forces of divisiveness, and that means
public leaders, who exercise enormous power, need to operate with
care,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2151 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RAMPAGE-ITHACA-ART-2T     09-05 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMPAGE-ITHACA-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A UNIQUE PAIRING TRIES TO GET TO THE DISTURBED BEFORE THEY BECOME
DANGEROUS
</HEADLINE>
   (Special Report) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITHACA, N.Y. _ It was nearly four years ago when the police
climbed the creaky stairs to Deborah Stagg's apartment in response
to calls from neighbors who had heard her screaming and raving
alone in there. Stagg was known around town as a woman so disturbed
she had once delivered her own baby by cutting her womb open with a
penknife.
</P>
<P>
   This time, a steak knife in hand, Stagg bolted from her
barricaded bathroom and stabbed Inspector Michael A. Padula in the
neck, a fatal wound. The police opened fire, killing Stagg. The
double deaths were a pivotal trauma in Ithaca, where Padula was the
first police officer killed in the line of duty. In the grim
aftermath, the police blamed the mental health department, and
mental health advocates blamed the police.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the mourning and finger-pointing, a policeman
and a mental health clinic supervisor who were distant
acquaintances got together over beer to talk about whether they
could prevent such occurrences, jotting down ideas on bar napkins.
Out of it grew a collaboration between the Ithaca police and mental
health departments that some policing experts say is unmatched
anywhere in the country because of its focus on pre-empting
problems in addition to responding to crises.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when the police department receives a call that someone is
behaving bizarrely, making threats or talking of suicide, it is
usually the two men who brainstormed in the bar _ Lt. John Beau
Saul of the police department and Terry Garahan, the mental health
clinic supervisor _ who drive to the scene together in a worn
police van to assess the situation. They have paved the way for
other police officers or county sheriffs and mental health workers
to regularly go out on calls together.
</P>
<P>
   They intervene when the case is potentially dangerous, as when a
young man threatened to kill the staff at a temporary employment
agency and then kill himself. But they also intervene when the case
might appear frivolous, as when a woman called to report Martians
invading through her ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go out and find these people and try to get them to get the
help they need,'' said Saul, steering the van down a leafy street
to visit an elderly man who had called the police to report a jar
of peanut butter stolen from his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to other places,'' Saul said, ``people like this are
avoided like the plague. We actually go out of our way to find
these people and engage them.''
</P>
<P>
   Garahan said, ``The theory is, you solve problems even when
they're not problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely team, one a clean-cut cop, the other a long-haired
social worker, uses a carrot-and-stick approach, sometimes cajoling
a person into getting mental health treatment or contacting other
social services, and sometimes, where criminal behavior is
involved, using the threat of arrest or imprisonment. The result is
that even Ithaca police officers who were initially cynical about
the approach now say they have seen a steep decline in the number
of chronic phone callers tying up police lines and time, and fewer
untreated mentally ill people out on the streets. In several cases,
they succeeded in defusing emotionally disturbed people who were
armed and threatening violence, prodding them into psychiatric care
rather than prison.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of ``Rampage Killers'' conducted earlier this year by
The New York Times, family, friends, and neighbors of killers
repeatedly said in interviews afterward that they had observed the
killers behaving strangely or making threats before the crime, and
had tried to alert the police or mental health officials, to no
avail. The police often say their hands are tied, and they can
intervene only after the person has demonstrated a danger to
himself or others. Mental health services and hospitals in most
places are stretched so thin that they too are unequipped to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Ithaca has dared to move beyond this ``hands are
tied'' response. A maverick university town in upstate New York at
the southern tip of Cayuga Lake, Ithaca has committed the resources
of its police and mental health departments to respond even when
there is no immediate crisis. It allows the sharing of information
between the departments about past criminal and mental health
histories, treading close to a line that could raise the hackles of
civil libertarians and advocates for mental health patients.
</P>
<P>
   The approach in Ithaca goes beyond that of other cities in which
police departments have begun policing programs for dealing with
the mentally ill. The model most commonly copied is from Memphis,
Tenn., where a specially trained police unit responds to crisis
calls about emotionally disturbed people, referred to by the police
as EDP's). Other cities, like Los Angeles and Birmingham, Ala.,
have paired social workers with police officers who respond to
crises involving the mentally ill, said several experts who study
policing.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual in Ithaca is the emphasis on prevention, and the
decision to devote police resources to following up on people with
chronic problems who do not always want to accept help. Over the
course of the summer, they revisited several cases, including those
of a mentally ill crack addict who is resisting drug treatment, an
angry schizophrenic who had threatened his ex-wife and was making
harassing phone calls to public officials at their homes, and a
paranoid factory worker who wanted the police to investigate ``mind
intrusion machines'' he insisted were planted in his home and
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   By Labor Day, Saul and Garahan had succeeded in steering two of
them into treatment and were still making weekly visits to persuade
the crack-addicted man to enter a drug detoxification program.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty unique. I haven't heard of that type of
follow-up before,'' said Melissa M. Reuland, a research associate
at the Police Executive Research Forum, a nonprofit group in
Washington whose members include chiefs from the nation's larger
police departments. ``This really is problem-solving in action,
identifying hot spots and partnering with service providers in your
community who have expertise where you don't. If we could subject
this to a really critical legal and ethical analysis, I think it's
got some promise.''
</P>
<P>
   But such aggressive police involvement has a risk, said Henry J.
Steadman, the president of Policy Research Associates, who studies
mental disorders and the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a potential invasiveness there for individuals who
would feel coerced into mental health services because the police
are still checking up on them in the role of police officers,''
Steadman said. ``If the person is simply seen as in need of
treatment, then why should the police be hanging around forcing the
person into treatment?''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Honberg, director of legal affairs at the National Alliance
for the Mentally Ill, said, ``I think it's great that Ithaca cares
enough to do something creative. I just worry that if it's done the
wrong way it conjures up images of Big Brother at its worst.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The police are often on the front lines of mental health care in
this country, like it or not. For instance, the Ithaca police
department was called on Aug. 26, 1999, when the managers at
Stafkings, a temporary employment agency, arrived at work to hear
two chilling messages on their answering machine from an unemployed
man who said he was frustrated that he had not been offered a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll kill all y'all up in there. I ain't playing, man,'' he
said, spitting out his words in the recorded message. ``The day
that I kill all you I'll probably kill myself because I'm upset
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In many smaller police departments that have not been trained in
threat assessment, the routine response would be to document the
complaint, and leave it at that. In Ithaca, the police department
contacted Garahan, who, as supervisor of the county outpatient
mental health clinic, knew the man who had left the message. Jason
James, who is 21, suffered from psychotic episodes and had received
a diagnosis of schizoaffective disorder at the clinic, but had quit
treatment. The phone threats indicated he had reached a critical
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Found at his house, James was charged with aggravated harassment
but was told he could avoid jail by committing to a program of
counseling and psychiatric medication. James, accompanied by
Garahan, appeared in court before Judge Judith A. Rossiter, who
often works closely with Garahan and Saul to devise alternatives to
prison for emotionally disturbed people. Rossiter discontinued the
charge on the condition that James resumed treatment.
</P>
<P>
   One day last month, James rode his bicycle to Ithaca's mental
health clinic to receive his daily medication. Soft-spoken and
serious, James said that now that the voices have faded, he knows
he needs the treatment. He said he still struggles, however, to
explain his illness to his family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just wave their hands and say, `He's sick,' `He's crazy.'
I want people to see that I am getting treatment, that I am living
a better life,'' he said, before riding off to a job interview.
</P>
<P>
   Often, however, people are far less compliant, even when facing
arrest. All summer, Garahan and Saul worked on the case of Nicholas
Celia, a 44-year-old man with a record of arrests on charges of
assaults on civilians and police officers, and a history of alcohol
and drug abuse as well as psychiatric problems and hospitalizations
_ the three factors that experts say indicate a potential for
future violence. Recent studies have found that the mentally ill
are no more violent than other people, except when they are off
their medications or have been abusing drugs or alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like a pirate in a blue bandanna and hoop earring, Celia
wandered the Ithaca Commons, the city's open-air street mall,
sometimes mellow and bumming cigarettes, sometimes screaming and
menacing. He was repeatedly arrested on charges of harassment and
assault, once on Garahan, who got an order of protection against
Celia and began to carry pepper spray. Even some of Celia's friends
at the regular Wednesday night dinner of the local mental health
advocacy group said in interviews that Celia was starting to scare
them, and needed help.
</P>
<P>
   Garahan and Saul decided to use the newest, most aggressive tool
they had to compel Celia into treatment: Kendra's Law, named for
Kendra Webdale, who died after being pushed in front of a New York
City subway train by a mentally ill man. They filed a petition
asking a judge to order Celia into outpatient drug treatment and
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   At his hearing, Celia interrupted a psychiatrist testifying that
he had examined Celia and diagnosed bipolar disorder, or
manic-depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just like to say, Your Honor, I am getting a little
upset hearing these lies and innuendo, and this is what happens
when I am under stress and this is a farce to me,'' Celia said,
speaking loud and fast.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered Celia to report to the outpatient clinic for
injections of Haldol.
</P>
<P>
   In his police car after the hearing, Saul volunteered that he
was uneasy at the idea of forcing psychiatric drugs on someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a miniature soul-search about it, but then maybe if
Deborah Stagg had been forced to take medication, Mike would still
be alive,'' said Saul, who wears a small pin on his uniform in
honor of Michael Padula, the dead policeman.
</P>
<P>
   Celia's response was to flee. He went to New York City, checked
in to Bellevue Hospital's psychiatric ward, returned to Ithaca, was
arrested, hospitalized again and released, returned to New York
City, was arrested and sent again to Bellevue before being
transferred to a county hospital for long-term treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Bellevue in August, Celia, now
more subdued, insisted he needed no treatment, saying, ``What's
happening to me is an injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in this politically liberal college town, however, it is
hard to find a civil libertarian or mental health consumer who
objects to the work of Garahan and Saul. Some do oppose the law
stemming from the Kendra Webdale killing, but all said in
interviews that they were glad there were officials with mental
health experience to call in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Much of Garahan and Saul's work boils down to protecting
emotionally disturbed people from hurting themselves, or from being
victimized by others. After months in which they tried to convince
the woman obsessed with Martians to seek treatment, she set a fire
in her apartment to exorcise the extraterrestrials. She walked to
the police station and was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   And when Garahan and Saul responded to the elderly man who had
reported a jar of peanut butter missing, they found him living in a
basement apartment swarming with flies, with feces tracked across
the floor and a bare light bulb that had burned through a
lampshade. They called building inspectors, who condemned the
place. They called an ambulance for the man, in keeping with their
approach that ``medicalizing'' a mental illness is less threatening
for the person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it doesn't look like compassion, but it is for his
best, and for the neighborhood's best,'' Saul said to neighbors
curious about the ambulance. The landlord has since renovated the
apartment, Garahan said.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether they have ever stopped a rampage killer, Garahan
said: ``You do this stuff and you don't know whether you prevented
something or not. But I do know that the ability of the two
disciplines, police and mental health, to work together has a
tremendous effect on a lot of people's lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
