<HEADLINE>
UMASS TO BEGIN COSTLY PREPARATION FOR UNCERTAIN DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The costs of preparing for a presidential debate are
mounting for Massachusetts taxpayers, even though it is
increasingly uncertain whether the event will take place.
</P>
<P>
   University of Massachusetts officials say they are about to sign
a contract for electrical work that will cost between $120,000 and
$165,000, on the assumption that a debate will be held on the
school's Dorchester campus.
</P>
<P>
   And unless the Commission on Presidential Debates pulls the plug
_ which it said Tuesday it does not want to do _ the university
will soon face an even costlier decision: In two weeks, it is
scheduled to sign a contract to complete the production work needed
to accommodate the press and nationally televise a debate. The
labor and materials for that final phase of construction would cost
between $250,000 and $400,000, according to school officials.
</P>
<P>
   They expressed hope that Governor George W. Bush, who has
proposed a debate schedule that doesn't include Boston, will either
change his mind or that the commission sponsoring the event will
scrap its plans before UMass enters into that last financial
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective spending would come on top of $250,000 the
university has already laid out for infrastructure improvements and
other preparations for a planned matchup between Bush and Vice
President Al Gore on Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money is expected to come out of $900,000 that the
state Legislature appropriated for this purpose after the
bipartisan Commision on Presidential Debates chose UMass-Boston as
one of three sites for presidential debates. Any additional funding
presumbably would have to be made up by the school itself, since it
would be contractually obligated to return the $1.6 million it has
raised from corporate sponsors if the debate doesn't take place.
</P>
<P>
   Annemarie Lewis-Kerwin, the UMass spokeswoman, said Tuesday that
the university is contractually bound to continue preparations
until the commission decides to call them off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to stop,'' said Lewis-Kerwin. ``We're going to
keep going until someone tells us to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has accepted an invitation to participate in the Boston
event, as well as the commission's proposals for debates in
Winston-Salem, N.C., and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Sunday announced he would attend only that last debate.
In lieu of the others, he proposed that he and Gore appear next
week on a prime-time edition of NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' and on
CNN's ``Larry King Live'' Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   All the major television networks have agreed to air the three
events run by the commission, as well as one it proposed for the
two vice presidential contenders. But CBS and ABC said Tuesday they
would not broadcast debates that would effectively shine a
prime-time spotlight on their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's offer not only raises questions about this year's
presidential debates _ and threatens to cost Massachusetts hundreds
of thousands of dollars _ but appears to undercut the commission's
authority for the future as well. Most analysts believe the
Democratic and Republican candidates will reach some compromise,
but that might not include a stop at UMass-Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On campus Tuesday, national and local media were given a tour of
the facilities they would use if a debate is held. But many of
those who took the tour grumbled that they were wasting their time
because the prospect appeared to be dimming.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference at UMass yesteray, the debate commission's
executive director, Janet Brown, said Gore had accepted a
commission invitation to discuss the debate schedule in Washington.
She said Bush had not yet replied.
</P>
<P>
   Brown stressed that the commission is amenable to any sort of
suggestion about format to accommodate the candidates' concerns.
And she expressed optimism that, ultimately, Bush's would be met
and the debate at UMass-Boston will take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be here if we thought we were wasting people's
time or resources,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's work has always been financed primarily by
corporate contributions. Ralph Nader, the Green Party presidential
candidate, contends that is illegal, but a federal judge in Boston
last Friday refused a request by Nader and his supporters to
prohibit such contributions.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Patti B. Saris upheld the legality of
regulations adopted by the Federal Election Commission some 20
years ago that allow corporations and labor unions to make
unlimited donations to the commission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Shelley Murphy of The Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
