<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By ERIC P. NASH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quest for the Grail
</P>
<P>
   Q. For my sister's 30th birthday, I would like to take her on a
King Arthur tour of England, since this is one of her interests. Do
any tour companies, American or English, offer such a program? _
Amy Hoddick, Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. A number of companies will squire you around southwest
England in search of King Arthur, with prices ranging from the
princely to the pedestrian. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gothic Image Tours are led by Arthurian scholars. Highlights of
the 10-day tour include Arthur's legendary birthplace, Tintagel
Castle, on a rocky cliff above the Atlantic; the desolate Dozmary
Pool, one of several spots where Arthur is believed to have thrown
his sword, Excalibur, to be received by the Lady of the Lake;
Stonehenge, said to have been transported by the wizard Merlin from
Ireland; the Glastonbury Tor, where legend has it that King Melwas
held Queen Guinevere captive until Arthur rescued her; and what is
generally agreed to be King Arthur's grave, in Glastonbury. The
cost of the trip, which includes transportation by minicoach and
lodging in three-star hotels featuring traditional British fare, is
$2,150 a person, double occupancy. Call (44-1458) 831281.
</P>
<P>
   Britannia Tours and Travel offers a three-night package, which
includes a stay in the 15th-century George &AMP; Pilgrims Inn in
Glastonbury (built for pilgrims to Glastonbury Abbey), English
breakfasts and all admissions. The cost of the guided tour with a
private car and driver is $995, or $399 for a self-drive car, per
person, double occupancy. Highlights include the wind-swept
earthworks of Old Sarum in Salisbury, where King Arthur supposedly
fought his last battle against the traitorous Mordred, and the
Round Table in the Great Hall of Winchester Castle. Information:
Britannia Tours and Travel, (800) 220-0658.
</P>
<P>
   Camelot International will take you on a customized seven-day
tour of the counties of Cornwall, Devon, Somerset, Dorset and
Wiltshire in pursuit of Arthurian lore for $1,114 a person. The
company provides a private car and driver, and lodging and dining
in three- and four-star hotels, culminating with a stay at the
Camelot Castle hotel in Cornwall. Information: (734) 930-9921 or
(800) 201-1598.
</P>
<P>
   You can follow your own grail with British Footpaths' booklets
and workshops. The publishing and workshop company is run by the
author Richard Hayward, whose booklet ``Cornwall Coast Path Guide:
Land's End to Lizard Point'' ($8.95 plus $1.50 shipping) will guide
you through Britain's westernmost point, past one of the 15 or so
``slumber legend'' sites, where Arthur and his knights are said to
sleep until their return. Topics covered in the workshops _ offered
in February and April in Seattle, Bellevue and Bellingham, Wash.,
for under $50 _ include B&AMP;B's, pubs, food, living on $35 a day and
packing light. Information: www.britishfootpaths.com, or contact
British Footpaths, 914 Mason St., Bellingham, Wash. 98225; (360)
671-1217.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas in Vienna
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 7 years old. I would like to know what my family and I
can do in Vienna during Christmas vacation. Are there any puppet
shows or concerts for children? _ Emma Hitchcock, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Vienna is a wonderland for children at Christmastime.
Beginning Nov. 18, the traditional Christmas market will open in
front of the Rathaus, or City Hall, featuring more than 140 booths
with presents, games, sweets and pony rides, with a magic lantern
show of woodland creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Events for children will include a Christmas Workshop to be held
in the Volkshalle of City Hall, where kids can make their own
Christmas presents and bake gingerbread cookies. There will also be
a games tent, featuring characters from Austrian children's books
and television.
</P>
<P>
   On the four Sundays before Christmas, choirs from all over the
world will sing carols from their homelands under a lighted tree at
City Hall. There will also be a life-size Nativity scene, and eight
creches from the southern province of Styria. Another highlight is
the mechanical dolls of Vienna Waltz World, an exhibit in City Hall
Park, which are based on historical models.
</P>
<P>
   Trees in City Hall Park will be lighted and trimmed with
fantastical decorations, including an all-Santa tree. The Christmas
market is a 700-year-old tradition, where candied fruits and hot
roasted chestnuts (called maroni in Vienna) are served in small
wooden stalls.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic of Advent 2000, including the market and City Hall
events, will be open daily Nov. 18 to Dec. 23, 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.,
and until 5 p.m. on Dec. 24. For information, and a brochure, call
the Austrian National Tourist Office at (212) 944-6880, or visit
www.christkindlmarkt.at.
</P>
<P>
   Health Coverage Abroad
</P>
<P>
   Q. I understand Medicare does not cover injuries or illnesses
that are treated outside the United States. What are the insurance
choices for someone who travels outside the United States three or
four times a year for a month or so at a time? How do tourists in
countries with socialized medicine pay for illnesses that occur and
are treated there? _ Rita H. Irons, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The original Medicare plan, with a few exceptions, does not
cover medical care outside the United States. The exceptions are if
the condition occurs within the United States, and the most
accessible hospital is across the border with Mexico or Canada, or
if you are in direct transit to the continental United States from
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare HMOs do cover emergency procedures abroad, but not
routine care. Eight of the ten Medigap policies that are available
provide 80 percent of the cost of emergency care during the first
two months of a trip outside the country. The deductible is $250,
and the coverage is up to $50,000 in a lifetime. The cost of
additional premiums varies from carrier to carrier and state by
state. In New York State, monthly premium prices for Medigap plans
that cover foreign travel can range from $101.15 to $296, depending
on other features of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call the consumer group, the Medicare Rights
Center, (800) 333-4114, or go to its Web site,
www.medicarerights.org. You can also call the New York State
Insurance Department at (800) 342-3736 for information about
insurance companies and premium prices.
</P>
<P>
   Countries with socialized medicine, such as those of the United
Kingdom, will treat you free in case of an accident or emergency,
but will charge for after-care and convalescence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
