<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDSCHOOL-RACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES LOSING OUT ON SENIOR POSTS AT MED SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minority faculty members are less likely to be promoted to
senior professorships at US medical schools than their white
counterparts, even among junior faculty who have won prestigious
research awards, according to a study in the Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's incredible,'' said Ernest Moy, director of
research at the Association of American Medical Colleges and one of
the study's authors. ``These are the best people in the country in
research, and they're not being promoted at the same rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Moy said the study proves that the ``glass ceiling'' in academic
medicine cannot be blamed on a notion that minority professors are
less productive than others.
</P>
<P>
   The study comes at a time when medical schools are struggling to
hold on to recent gains in minority admissions, in the face of
affirmative action cutbacks in California and Texas. Medical school
applications declined 6 percent overall this year, falling 6.8
percent among the groups medical schools designate
``underrepresented minorities'': African-Americans, Mexican
Americans, Puerto Ricans and Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Another study in the current JAMA found that minority
representation on medical admissions committees, while up from the
last major study in 1972, is still small. Dr. Douglas G. Kando of
the Menninger Clinic in Topeka, Kan., reported that 51 percent of
schools have zero or one committee member from an underrepresented
minority group.
</P>
<P>
   The issues are intertwined, according to Moy and Boston-area
medical faculty. Deans want _ and local communities demand _
minority representation on every committee, said Dr. Alvin
Poussaint, a psychiatrist and associate dean of Harvard Medical
School. So the handful of minority professors ``are asked to do
more than their share of administrative duties. . . . That pulls
them away from their department and research and other things that
will get them promotions.'' They also spend a disproportionate
amount of time mentoring minority students, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Moy said, minority students who see that minority
faculty members are ``not rewarded'' for their work may be more
likely to seek careers outside academic medicine.
</P>
<P>
   A commentary accompanying the articles said that while the
problem reflects broader societal issues, that is no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``As members of a profession dedicated to caring, listening and
sensitivity, physicians may rightfully ask whether it is
professionally appropriate to fail to intervene in such systematic
disadvantages for certain individuals,'' wrote Dr. Stanley S.
Bergen Jr., of the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New
Jersey, in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Moy's study looked at 50,145 full-time U.S. medical school
faculty who became associate or assistant professors between 1980
and 1989. By 1997, 46 percent of white assistant professors had
been promoted, compared to 37 percent of Asians and 30 percent of
underrepresented minorities, with similar numbers for associate
professors.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, this year's first-year class of 167 medical students
has 48 underrepresented minorities, up from 30 last year. And in
1995, the medical school strengthened programs to support minority
faculty, said Dr. Joan Reede, associate dean of faculty development
and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, minority representation is lowest at the senior levels.
Among senior faculty, there are five blacks (0.8 percent), no
Native Americans, five Hispanics (0.8 percent) and 22 Asians. Among
assistant professors 20 are black (1.3 percent), one is Native
American, 19 are Hispanic (1.3 percent) and 160 are Asian (11.4
percent).
</P>
<P>
   Poussaint, who came to Harvard in 1969 to help recruit minority
students, said that in the ultra-competitive world of medical
schools, it is easier for white faculty to embrace increasing
minority student ranks than to actively recruit minority
professors, who are ``peer competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a bit of cronyism that goes on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Facing heavy competition for minority faculty, the University of
Massachusetts Medical School decided to ``grow our own,'' said
associate vice chancellor Deborah Harmon-Heins. She runs the
Worcester Pipeline Collaborative, which works with 6,000 children
from kindergarten through high school to get poor and minority
children prepared for careers in the health sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Underrepresented minority students entering U.S. medical schools
increased 27 percent between 1991 and 1994, according to the
Association of American Medical Colleges.
</P>
<P>
   But the organization now worries those gains will be eroded with
affirmative action under attack and the smartest students being
lured into other professions _ a problem magnified by studies that
show minority physicians are more likely to work in medically
underserved communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
