<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LYCOS-OLYMPICS-BOS &LR;      09-05 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-OLYMPICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS HOPES OLYMPICS DEAL WILL BOOST IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos Inc. hopes a global deal with the sponsors of the 2000
Summer Olympic Games will provide a major boost to the company's
worldwide visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos has been selected to run more than 200 Internet community
sites related to the Olympic games, which will take place in Sydney
later this month. The Waltham, Mass. company will operate 199
sites, one for each of the countries represented in the games, as
well as 35 sites devoted to particular sports, such as gymnastics
and soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics are probably the most well-known sporting event
in the world,'' said Lycos chief executive Bob Davis, adding that
the popularity of the games should help his firm cement its image
as a worldwide Internet power. Growing its non-US audience has long
been a major priority for Lycos, which already offers Web portal
services in 30 countries and is in the process of being acquired by
Spanish Internet firm Terra Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Lycos Olympic communities will be based on the online
community system already used at the Lycos Web portal. Visitors can
create their own communities devoted to particular interests, such
as politics, movies, or sports. Anthony Antonuccio, director of
Lycos Communities, said the service currently hosts about 200,000
such user-created communities.
</P>
<P>
   But the Olympics communities will be created by Lycos and
overseen by about 50 moderators, who will screen incoming messages.
Most of this screening will involve the sites' photo albums, where
visitors will be able to publish favorite pictures. Antonuccio said
all pictures will be checked by the moderators to ensure no
inappropriate or offensive images appear on the sites.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the sites will also need a basic knowledge of
English, because Lycos has not translated the home pages of each
community site into the various national languages. ``It takes
great time and expense to do it properly,'' said Antonuccio, ``and
we only had two weeks.'' Basic navigation links on each site will
be written in English, but users of the site's chat room or message
board will be able to write in his or her own language.
</P>
<P>
   The Lycos Olympics community sites will be advertiser-supported,
with ads provided by various companies sponsoring the games.
Antonuccio predicted advertising at the site would provide more
than enough revenue to cover the costs of running the communities.
The main Sydney Olympics Web site, at www.olympics.com, is expected
to receive 1.4 billion page views during the games, he said, and
Lycos will have a prominent link to its communities on the Olympics
home page. Vistors also will be able to get to the Lycos Olympics
communities by going to clubs.lycos.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
