A2161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GA-SENATE-MATTINGLY06     09-05 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SENATE-MATTINGLY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coverdell's widow helping Mattingly
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nearly seven weeks after her husband died, Nancy
Coverdell is taking an active role in the race to select his
successor in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign mailing over the holiday weekend, Coverdell
encourages voters to support Mack Mattingly, a former U.S. senator
and longtime family friend, to carry on her late husband Paul
Coverdell's conservative philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   And she could become more of a presence as the campaign goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever I think might be a need for me, I will offer my
services,'' she said Tuesday. ``I would prefer a conservative
Republican filling my husband's seat. It seems to me Mack Mattingly
is closer in philosophy to Paul than Zell Miller could ever be.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the popular two-term Georgia governor, was appointed to
the seat by Gov. Roy Barnes, a fellow Democrat, until a Nov. 7
special election to fill the remaining four years in the Senate
term. Coverdell died July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's involvement in the race is welcome news to
Mattingly, who has been working the state, trying to bolster
familiarity with a name that hasn't been on the ballot since his
unsuccessful Senate re-election bid in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   And he's hoping endorsements from well-known Republicans will
provide a powerful reintroduction and the built-in politician
organization he will need during the short, intense campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Mattingly introduced Republican vice presidential
nominee Dick Cheney to a group of high-dollar Republican donors in
Atlanta, remaining onstage with Cheney during his brief address.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Mattingly accompanied Republican U.S. Rep. Nathan
Deal on several campaign appearances through North Georgia's 9th
Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Mattingly has campaigned in the home districts of four
of Georgia's eight congressional Republicans. He's expecting visits
from several Republican U.S. senators, including Majority Leader
Trent Lott (R-Miss.).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big plus,'' Mattingly said of the GOP notables. ``The
way I look at it, I've got eight (congressmen) and Zell's got
three. They help bring people to the polls _ along with the
presidential candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   But political scientists say Mattingly must reach beyond the GOP
base and connect with millions of Georgians to win the nonpartisan
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's too big to shake every hand,'' said Charles
Bullock, a University of Georgia political scientist. ``He's also
got to get on TV if he's going to cut into the percentage of the
public who don't know who he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly has hired a media firm, but he declined to discuss TV
or radio ads.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he doesn't need TV ads to secure the support of voters
like Paul Stringer, one of about 25 Lumpkin County residents who
turned out to hear Mattingly speak Thursday. ``National-level
politics is what's going to fuel this race,'' Stringer said. ``With
the direction of the Democratic Party, people are looking at
changing and moving Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
