<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILENES-GERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUSTED CHIEF OF FILENE'S BASEMENT SUES NEW OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ohio)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a lawsuit filed last week with in Massachusetts,
former Filene's Basement chief executive Samuel J. Gerson says he
is owed at least $1.5 million in bonus and severance benefits after
his termination by the chain's new owner.
</P>
<P>
   Alleging breach of contract and fraud, the suit claims the new
owner, Value City Department Stores Inc. of Ohio, repeatedly misled
Gerson into believing that he would continue to run Filene's
Basement after the sale.
</P>
<P>
   A Value City spokesman said the company would have no comment
Tuesday on Gerson's lawsuit, filed in Middlesex Superior Court on
Aug 28.
</P>
<P>
   When it was announced in June that Gerson was leaving Filene's
Basement after 16 years at the top job, it seemed to be a mutual
decision.
</P>
<P>
   But in the lawsuit, Gerson said he was ``terminated without
cause'' after about three months of working for a new boss; based
on the employment agreement he said he had reached with Value City,
Gerson claimed the Ohio retailer owes him ``in excess of $1.5
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing fierce competition, Filene's Basement Corp. of Wellesley
filed for bankruptcy protection a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, in consultation with the chain's board
of directors and its creditors, Gerson concluded that the only way
to save the legendary retailer was to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   In February it was announced that a Value City subsidiary would
buy some of Filene's Basement's assets for about $15 million in
cash and stock and also assume about $74 million of Filene's
Basement debt. The deal was completed in March.
</P>
<P>
   At the time when the proposed sale was made public, Gerson said
that he expected he would continue to run Filene's Basement, only
now as a separate division of the Ohio retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Between the sale's announcement in February and his departure in
June, Gerson said he closed several Filene's Basement stores and
cut staff in an effort to improve the chain's productivity.
</P>
<P>
   During this period Gerson also said he had entered negotiations
with Value City over an employment contract that would pay him a
base annual salary of $500,000 and entitle him to performance
bonuses equal to a year's pay as well as severance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But in June, despite improvements at surviving Filene's Basement
stores, Value City terminated Gerson and replaced him with Alan R.
Schlesinger, Gerson said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to pay him, Value City breached the employment
agreement it had reached with him, Gerson said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during bankruptcy proceedings, Gerson noted that
Filene's Basement owed him at least $4.3 million in severance
benefits. The lawsuit filed last week against Value City is a
separate claim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
