<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2171 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HAEMONITCS-TCC-BOS &LR;      09-05 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAEMONITCS-TCC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAEMONETICS BUYING TRANSFUSION TECHNOLOGIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Haemonetics Corp., a developer of equipment to automate red
blood cell collection from volunteer blood donors, has agreed to
acquire privately held Transfusion Technologies Corp. of Natick,
Mass. in a cash deal.
</P>
<P>
   Final terms of the deal were not divulged although Haemonetics
said the purchase will be completed by Sept. 29, subject to
regulatory approval. Last November, Haemonetics spent $15 million
for a 19.8 percent equity stake in Transfusion, a seven-year-old
developer of portable blood separation systems used in orthopedic
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Lopez, a Haemonetics vice president, stressed Tuesday than
in acquiring the remaining 80.2 percent of Transfusion, ``the price
for the purchase is at a valuation substantially below what we
intitially paid last year.'' She declined to comment further on the
financial details.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine A. Martinelli, a vice president at Merrill Lynch
Global Securities, said: ``This deal makes sense for Haemonetics
because they get a complementary technology that gives them new
flexibility in mobile blood collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Transfusion's decision to sell was based largely on an offer
earlier this summer by Haemonetics. Transfusion was looking to
raise additional cash before launching an initial public offering,
according to Terrance J. Bieker, Transfusion president for the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply ran out of time,'' said Bieker, noting the company
had revenues last year of $1 million. ``In this business cash is
everything, and we needed to raise $10 million to $15 million more
before we could go for an (initial public offering). We were in the
process of talking with various blood bank partners for the
additional funds when Haemonetics approached us with their offer.
So our board of directors agreed that it was better to take a bird
in the hand now rather than wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Bieker acknowledged that the announcement was bittersweet, since
Transfusion was formed by former Haemonetics employees. Their goal
was to develop new blood separation equipment that would compete
against their former employer's products.
</P>
<P>
   Haemonetics officials said Transfusion's forthcoming products
will help it leverage its global presence in the $300 million
automated red blood cell collection market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of Haemonetics's resources and Transfusion
Technologies's propietary technology and product development
capabilities will enable us to accelerate delivery of systems which
are smaller, lighter and more user-friendly, allowing our customers
to reach donors through the use of transportable blood collection
equipment,'' said James L. Peterson, Haemonetics president and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how many of the nearly 60 employees will join Haemonetics,
Lopez said offers were made to nine Transfusion employees. She said
a dozen were asked to work during the six- month transition period
that will shut down the Natick operation and transfer everything to
Haemonitcs' Braintree headquarters, and 23 will be asked to
consider applying for unfilled Haemonetics jobs. She said the goal
is to help find jobs for all Transfusion employees.
</P>
<P>
   Haemonetics employs 1,300 people, including 700 in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Bieker said the company's founders have accepted jobs at
Haemonetics, including Transfusion chairman Thomas D. Headley, who
will now be an executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Haemonetics shares closed at $24.75, down 50 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
