   444-8286.
</P>
<P>
   LALO (Undated) - For more than 60 years, Lalo Guerrero has sang
songs in English and Spanish rooted in the deep love for his
Mexican-American heritage. Known as the father of Chicano music,
Guerrero has been honored by three Presidents and called a national
treasure by the Smithsonian institute. On a recent day, a reporter
accompanied Papa Lalo, as he is affectionately known, through a
tour of the Barrio Viejo in Tucson, where Guerrero was born in 1916
to Mexican immigrant parents. In front of one house, Lalo became
emotional as he recalled standing outside the window of his first
love, where he and two friends used to serenade her with Spanish
love songs. As a child, Guerrero endured ridicule from neighborhood
kids who made fun of the pock marks left behind by a bad bout with
small pox. But Lalo was inspired to become someone by the affection
shown him by his first love. On Sept. 6, the Phoenix-based
organization, Valle del Sol, will honor Lalo during a luncheon at
the Arizona Biltmore recognizing the contributions of several
Latinos in Arizona. Lalo will be inducted into the organization's
Hall of Fame. By DAVID GONZALEZ. Story will move in the ``A''
category.
</P>
<P>
   CAVERNS (Phoenix) - Despite elaborate precautions to protect it
from outside air, Kartchner Caverns appear to be drying out and the
Arizona parks department has been ignoring the problem, say the men
who discovered the caverns. By KATHLEEN INGLEY. Story will move in
the ``A'' category.
</P>
