u w BC-FBI-SHOOTER-HNS &LR;      09-05 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-SHOOTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI TO RELEASE `SCHOOL SHOOTER' THREAT ASSESSMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL HEDGES 
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to prevent future Columbine-type
massacres, the FBI has created a ``school shooter'' threat
assessment that it said will help teachers spot potential killers
among their students.
</P>
<P>
   But some child advocates and teacher representatives are
expressing concerns that the guidelines are too vague and could
label a normal adolescent a budding psychopath.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI Wednesday planned to issue a two-year study called,
``The School Shooter: A Threat Assessment Perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   The 36-page report said there are personality traits common
among school shooters, as well as family dynamics and even school
characteristics that can be looked for when deciding whether a
threat of violence by a student should be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The assessment, by the FBI's National Center for the Analysis of
Violent Crime, said it does not create a ``profile'' of the
teen-ager likely to gun down his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   But the study does say it can help schools, ``assess a threat
and a threatener, evaluate the risk, and respond appropriately and
effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the 28 behaviors listed in the report that may signal a
potential for violence were low tolerance for frustration, a lack
of resiliency, a failed love relationship, narcissism, an attitude
of superiority, intolerance and an unusual interest in sensational
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Other warning signs include anger management problems, a change
of behavior, use of inappropriate humor, or having negative role
models like ``Hitler, Satan or others associated with violence and
destruction,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The study also listed ``family dynamics'' that can contribute to
a child becoming violent in school. Those included an acceptance of
a child's pathological behavior by parents, access to weapons, a
lack of intimacy and even no limitations on television and internet
use.
</P>
<P>
   And schools also could contribute to a potential violent episode
by tolerating disrespect, having an ``inflexible culture'' or
unfair discipline habits, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   The study said those characteristics were common among cases
like the Columbine High School massacre in Littleton, Colo., in
April 1999. But the report was actually begun a year earlier, in
May 1998, and studied 18 school shootings that occurred before
Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine case created, ``a new urgency'' with Attorney
General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis Freeh to complete
research into identifying common traits of school shooters, and
giving schools guidelines on how to react to that threat, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Fallon, president of the Houston Federation of Teachers,
said she believed the report would be of limited use to local
educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those categories are so broad you could apply them to a number
of adolescents,'' she said. ``The average 13-year-old loves blood
and gore, the more the better. It is very easy for me to see a lot
of normal adolescent behavior in that list.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Schiraldi, a children's advocate with the Justice Policy
Institute in Washington, worried that the report would be used to
prejudge normal kids as potential killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this opens the door for a tremendous amount of false
positives,'' Schiraldi said. ``The ramifications for the kids being
misidentified as dangerous would be huge. Frankly, I see no role
for the FBI in America's schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno acknowledged that ``the risk of unfairly labeling and
stigmatizing children is great.'' But she said, ``If we use this
threat assessment model judiciously ... we will be able to fight
and win the war on two fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the assessment would allow schools to get help for
troubled children while protecting innocent ones.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Leone, a University of Maryland professor who is the
director of the National Center for Education, Disabilities and
Juvenile Justice, said, ``I think a thing like this has a great
potential to become part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the behaviors listed are normal developmental stages
for adolescents. To me, this is saying if we can pinpoint the right
kids we can solve the problem, and that is simplistic,'' Leone
said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI threat assessment provides guidelines for determining if
troubling statements by a high school student should be taken as a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   A low level threat is one that is vague and indirect. An act
that could be carried out, though it may not appear realistic, is
called a medium level of threat in the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   A high level threat is one that is direct, specific and
plausible. An example cited in the study: ``At 8 am tomorrow
morning I intend to shoot the principal. That's when he is in the
office by himself. I have a 9mm. Believe me, I know what I am
doing. I am sick and tired of the way he runs this school.''
</P>
<P>
   That type of threat must be responded to quickly by school
officials, the FBI warned. It recommended calling local police and
activating an emergency response plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lesser threats should be dealt with by a team formed of teachers
and mental health workers, the report said. ``A school cannot
ignore any threat of violence. Plausible or not, every threat must
be taken seriously, investigated, responded to,'' said the report.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon said Houston schools have a zero tolerance policy for
weapons on school grounds and also for direct threats of violence.
``We can get a child out (of the school) who displays a weapon or
makes terroristic threats,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the less direct categories of threat, it becomes tougher,
she said. ``I'd be reluctant to ask our teachers to make those
assessments,'' said Fallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is tremendous potential damage to the child. I'd be
upset if you made those allegations about my child.'' Fallon and
others said to designate a child as a ``school shooter'' before he
or she had committed an overt act would invite a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon said only one student had been killed at a Houston area
school in her memory, and that killing was gang-related, not the
actions of a disturbed adolescent shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Schiraldi, the children's advocate in Washington, said the
report is an overreaction to a relatively small number of school
violence incidents. ``About one student in two million is involved
with a shooting in school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 80 people killed by lightning last year, and 26 in
school violence related deaths,'' said Schiraldi. ``This is an
effort to protect us from lightning. That can't be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
