<HEADER>
A2188 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     09-05 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOOM MARKET IN TRAVEL SCAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vacation swindle business is booming, according to law
enforcement agencies, consumer advocates and travel industry
organizations. The bait for unsuspecting victims ranges from
nonexistent trips to identification cards offering anyone the kind
of discounts only travel agents can get legitimately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we go out there looking, we find there are people
running travel scams,'' said Mitchell Katz, a spokesman for the
Federal Trade Commission, which last month announced its third
round of enforcement actions against deceptive travel industry
practices since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The commission and 19 state agencies filed 85 actions against
travel promoters, who were accused of actions ranging from falsely
telling people they had won a free trip to concealing costs to
refusing to make refunds.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the commission reached an agreement under which
American International Travel Services Inc., of Deerfield Beach,
Fla., paid $1 million to the FTC for refunds to people who say they
were improperly charged for what they thought were free trips to
Florida. The firm did not admit wrongdoing in the settlement, which
was approved by a federal judge in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Travel schemes consistently rank among the top 10 complaints to
the FTC, Katz said. This year, faxed offers of free trips have
prompted a surge of complaints from consumers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Davis, 28, of Dubuque, Iowa, was one of those who
complained about deceptive practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I filled out this card at the Dubuque County Fair in 1999 and
then I was notified that I had won a free trip,'' Davis said. She
paid $598 to ``reserve'' her trip for four to Florida. She said the
vendor, Epic Travel, of King of Prussia, Pa., one of the firms the
commission has filed charges against, never returned her calls
until she wrote that she had retained a lawyer; then, she said, the
firm called only to say that it had no record of her calls and that
it was too late to get a refund.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far I haven't gotten anything back and I never got a trip
anywhere,'' she said. ``But I did learn to never again fill out a
slip for a free trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Semegen, general counsel for Epic Resorts, said Davis'
remarks were ``not anywhere close to factual.'' He said that the
company issues refunds if requested within 30 days, and that it
sells time-share packages and does not promise free trips.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the fraud techniques currently in vogue and
some tips on how to spot them.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has provided a lucrative new venue for a variety of
travel swindles. Travel scams are the ninth most common swindles
reported to Internet Fraud Watch at the Web site www.fraud.org,
said Philip McKee, assistant director of the project, a service of
the National Consumers League, a nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should ignore ads on Internet auction sites from
people who say they have frequent-flier miles expiring or a ticket
in their own name, said Kristina Rundquist, a spokeswoman for the
American Society of Travel Agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot transfer frequent-flier miles for money and you
cannot use a ticket made out to someone else.'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stan Bosco, the society's assistant director for
consumer affairs, one common scheme is to offer a trip that, if
paid for immediately, can be taken any time in the next 18 months.
The extended time period, as well as any efforts to stall the
making of reservations, are signs that the promoters intend to
close the business and flee with the money before any trips are
taken.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Travel Agents said it has been receiving
a growing number of complaints about phony travel-agent
identification swindles, which it calls ``card mill scams.''
Consumers are told they can buy credentials that make it possible
to pose as a travel agent and obtain the deep discounts on air
fares, hotel rooms and other services that are available to travel
agents on trips that are meant to familiarize them with a
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents do get such discounts. But Bosco said that as this
swindle has spread, at a time when demand has pushed up rates, both
airlines and hotels have begun to tighten up on the availability of
such discounts for legitimate travel agents while training their
employees to weed out fake travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   Another dubious deal offers free travel as an inducement to take
out a credit card. William J. McGee, editor of Consumer Reports
Travel Letter, published by the same company that puts out the
magazine, said one such offer it investigated required customers to
join a travel club with a membership fee so high that it offset any
potential travel benefit.
</P>
<P>
   McGee also advises consumers not to deal with any travel company
that will not allow them to pay by credit card or will not conduct
business through the mail. Sales made by credit card can be
contested. Refusal to send through the mail can be a sign of fraud
by people trying to avoid mail-fraud statutes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trips on chartered aircraft are one area that can easily be
checked out. Federal consumer protection rules require charter
companies to specify the airline whose planes are being chartered
in all advertisements and promotional materials.
</P>
<P>
   To check out charter operators, call the Department of
Transportation at (202) 366-1037 and give the name of the tour
operator and travel dates; the department will tell you whether the
company has posted a P.C. number as a public charter operator,
meaning it has met minimum financial-stability requirements. Even
if the operator volunteers its P.C. number, check with the
government, McGee said.
</P>
<P>
   Tour operators can cancel up to 10 days before a trip if they
refund all money. Customers have the right to cancel if the tour
operator changes the departure or destination, raises prices more
than 10 percent or moves departure and return times by more than 48
hours.
</P>
<P>
   When you are already at your destination and ready to return
home, tour operators have the right to delay you by up to two days.
And if you refuse the delayed return, all the charter operator owes
you is the return air fare at the charter rate, which typically is
a fraction of the cost of buying a one-way ticket home or two extra
nights in most resorts, assuming you can even get a room.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC has two advisories for travelers on its Web site, at
www.ftc.gov, one about telemarketing fraud and the other about
travel scams in general (click first on ``consumer protection'' and
then on ``telemarketing'').
</P>
<P>
   There is one simple rule that, if followed, pretty much
eliminates the risk of being taken by even the slickest travel con
artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that nothing comes free,'' McGee said.
</P>
<P>
   Bosco of the American Society of Travel Agents echoed his
sentiments. ``An offer of a week at a beachfront hotel in Hawaii
for $299 is likely to leave nothing but memories of money spent for
a trip that was never made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
