<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CARMEL-PROGRESS-ART-T     09-05 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARMEL-PROGRESS-ART-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL TOWN DEBATES WHETHER TO GIVE UP A CHERISHED ECCENTRICITY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL-BY-THE-SEA, Calif. _ This is a town that cultivates
eccentricity like a rare organic tomato. Ever since it was
discovered by artists, writers and assorted free spirits nearly a
hundred years ago, people have been drawn to this
precious-as-a-poodle community beside the Pacific Ocean for the
touches of modernity it does not have: street lights, illuminated
signs, parking meters, neighborhood sidewalks, street addresses and
door-to-door mail delivery.
</P>
<P>
   As long as there has been a Carmel-by-the-Sea (not to be
confused with Carmel, the broader area surrounding this
1-square-mile ``urban forest'' that tourists flock to see),
residents have, by choice, picked up their mail at the post office,
opting for the routine of bumping into one another among the oaken
post boxes and avoiding the confusion of carriers delivering mail
to houses without addresses. Houses here, many of them elfin
cottages with thatchlike roofs in the Late Troll style, have always
been identified either by name _ like Tide Pool or Tinkerbell _ or
by folksy descriptions of their location (``second house southwest
of 7th on Camino Real'').
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a significant tempest in a Teapot (the name of another
house here) ensued when, after months of aggressive lobbying by a
determined citizen, the U.S. Postal Service announced at a packed
city hall last month that free home delivery, pending the assigning
of street numbers, would finally be offered in Carmel-by-the-Sea.
</P>
<P>
   To Joe Steinfeld, 71, the choice is clear. Steinfeld has led the
campaign for mail delivery since he moved here last year from
nearby Big Sur, using tactics like visiting Postal Service
headquarters in Washington twice, telephoning members of the
service's board of governors at home and picketing the post office
here with a sign that said ``Choice Not Boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get pizza delivered to my house, but not the mail,''
Steinfeld said. ``They call it a quaint tradition. It's not quaint.
We're paying for something we're not getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinfeld, a retired antiques dealer who ran unsuccessfully for
the City Council on the mail issue, became frustrated about lack of
home delivery after an illness left him bedridden and unable to
pick up his mail.
</P>
<P>
   Among his supporters is Tom Conmy, 66, a packaging broker, who
does not see the charm in threading his car through about 25,000
summertime tourists a week strolling to the 111 art galleries and
eyeballing 15-carat Cartier diamond rings _ all to get to the post
office.
</P>
<P>
   But many in town see Steinfeld's quest as an assault on a
cherished community tradition that has larger reverberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another step towards the homogenization of Carmel,''
said Alice Englander, 54, a computer programmer, who has taken to
calling her town ``Stepford-by-the-Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the difference between McDonald's and a roadside cafe,''
she said. ``Next, the mailmen will need street lights to see the
boxes, then sidewalks for safety, and soon we'll be one of those
places that used to be wonderful but aren't anymore, like La Jolla
or Laguna Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one square mile that's different,'' she added. ``The
people who don't want that can live in the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The post office here looms large. It is ``like the old cracker
barrel of a general store or neighbors talking over a backyard
fence,'' said Steve Bardin, 56, who has occasionally found a
lipstick pucker mark on the window of his box after a spat with a
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Here, Carmelites encounter Dan Tarallo, 64, ``the whistler,''
who improvises tunes from his ``inner radio'' twice a day on the
post office bench, and neighbors like Kathleen and Isabel Blythe,
75-year-old twins who use the excursion as an excuse to ``get out
of the house every day, have lunch and throw out the dumb catalogs
before we go home,'' in Kathleen Blythe's words.
</P>
<P>
   The post office is a public spot in a famously private town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates connections between people,'' said Barbara Bolgard,
66.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's, `I had a dream about you last night _ are you all
right?' Well, the mailman is not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Carmel-by-the-Sea is one of about 4,400 independent post offices
that do not have carrier delivery, said Mark Saunders, a spokesman
for the Postal Service in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Steinfeld has threatened to file a class-action suit on behalf
of Carmel-by-the-Sea's box renters, who he said were entitled to a
97-year refund, which he has calculated as $30 million, for having
paid rental fees for post office boxes throughout the town's
history when mail delivery, he said, is ``supposed to be free.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, box holders in Carmel-by-the-Sea, who pay about $14 a
year, are entitled to a fee refund dating from June 1997, when free
post office box service became available to qualifying
municipalities, Saunders said. (Steinfeld collects his mail at
nearby Pebble Beach because there is a long waiting list for Carmel
boxes.)
</P>
<P>
   Saunders said the postal service was not legally obligated to
provide home delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Among the strongest supporters of street numbering here, which
would be required to deliver the mail, is the city's fire chief,
Bill Hill, a third-generation Carmelite who estimates the price of
idiosyncrasy as ``about a minute longer'' in emergency response
time. The 911 dispatchers are based in Salinas, about 30 miles
away. ``Put yourself in their hands,'' Hill said, when a caller
explains where the emergency is by saying, ``Well, there's a blue
Volvo parked in front.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   David Louie, a veteran United Parcel Service driver, noted that
rookie drivers avoid Carmel-by-the-Sea. ``Sometimes a customer
gives out an address and even they don't know where they live,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of mail is not new in this formerly bohemian
community, once home to Upton Sinclair and Robinson Jeffers and
today better known as the woodsy hideaway of Doris Day, Kim Novak
and the football announcer John Madden. (Former Mayor Clint
Eastwood, whose rugged profile adorns tote bags and mugs here, now
lives up the coast in Pebble Beach.)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout its history, the town has, in effect, legislated
uniqueness, a boon to tourism. Currently on the books, for
instance, is a ``high heels'' ordinance, inspired by the city's
crooked, uneven streets, requiring a permit to wear shoes with
heels more than 2 inches high and with less than ``1 square inch of
bearing surface.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Now Carmelites will have a choice of mail delivery. But the
debate is far from over: This week the City Council will decide
whether to ban street numbers or mailboxes on streets, potentially
challenging the postal service.
</P>
<P>
   The postal service says it will deliver regardless.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation, Steinfeld has put a mailbox up in front of his
house. But others in town, like J.B. Williams, who describes
herself as ``ancient'' and walks slowly to the post office each
weekday with her cane, say they will continue to pick up mail, by
hook or crook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to give up Box 12,'' she said resolutely as if
it were a precious heirloom. ``It belonged to the family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
