<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV10-(     09-05 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV10-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)  
 By BOB TEDESCHI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adventure travelers represent the fastest growing segment of the
$447 billion leisure travel market, according to the nonprofit
Travel Industry Association. It is no surprise, then, that Internet
entrepreneurs have flocked to this category with all the reckless
abandon of the travelers they hope to serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On paper at least, the notion of an adventure travel Web site
for information and bookings is a perfect Internet idea. Relatively
few conventional travel agencies specialize in this type of
business, in part because the trips are very labor intensive to
plan, and therefore offer meager financial returns. But Internet
travel agents can operate much more efficiently than their offline
counterparts, since, in theory, travelers assume most of the burden
of researching and selecting trips and itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the Web contains a multitude of sites that offer
more information on adventure travel destinations than one could
find in an entire bookstore _ where someone might spend $70 on five
books about hiking treks in Montana _ and, often, a way to reserve
a trip.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, information on these sites is typically better, or
at least more extensive, than the offerings of the adventure-travel
publishing world. That's because sites like GORP.com, away.com,
REIadventures.com, Adventureseek.com, iExplore.com and Altrec.com,
frequently establish agreements with travel publishers to use their
information, then bolster that with an abundance of other tips and
features.
</P>
<P>
   Away.com is one example. The site operators say users can find
over 100,000 pages of information about trips, from African safaris
to spelunking in Arizona. But those who want even more information
have several other options. First, they can type in questions for
one of eight experts who specialize in a region, like Latin
America, or a theme, like ecotourism.
</P>
<P>
   The questions and answers are displayed in a forumlike format,
and the postings are archived, just in case you have a question
like one asked before. If you're considering a trip to Madagascar
to see rare lemurs in the Ankarafantsika Reserve, for instance, the
ecotourism section of the site has some suggestions already
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   If you've forgotten how to spell Ankarafantsika and want to lean
on a human being to find more information about the trip, Away also
provides phone support, e-mail support, and online chats with other
travelers or an Away travel consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The last option can be as much fun as building a campfire in the
rain. I recently asked a question on Away.com about hiking in
Kauai, since my wife and I were headed there with our year-old
daughter, and we figured that if this child was to fit in with her
peers, she really needed to toughen up and get with the whole
adventure travel idea.
</P>
<P>
   During the online chat, a service representative ``pushed'' onto
my screen a page about horseback riding in Molokai _ the connection
between that and hiking in Kauai was unclear _ and another page
with general information about traveling to Kauai.
</P>
<P>
   Within two minutes, there were so many pages opened on my screen
that I had to bushwhack my way through the browser to find the
pop-up window where I'd been chatting with the service
representative. Before I found it, I suspended the search to catch
my breath and check e-mail, which was a bad idea, because my
computer flashed a message about a ``connection failure'' and cut
off the chat.
</P>
<P>
   The phone was much better. A friendly Hawaii specialist on
Away.com told me that the company doesn't take reservations for
day-tour companies in Hawaii, because it wouldn't be financially
feasible, but she told me about the Web site of a tour operator who
might help me. The call took three minutes, and I was able to check
my e-mail at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The top-tier adventure sites include many of the same features,
like online chats and phone support, as well as tips from regional
experts and lists of the most popular tours. But they are also
prone to using unedited versions of sales literature sent by their
tour providers _ which sell their products on multiple sites, so
it's not unusual to feel like you're retracing your tracks while
comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best differentiator for these sites is their search
functions, which let you narrow the universe of available options
quickly. Of those I visited, adventureseek.com had the most nimble
and useful search feature. It let me set my price range, the number
of days I wished to travel, and even the tour company. And when I
chose a particular trip, it gave far more online information about
the tour company than other sites, which leave such issues to their
phone representatives.
</P>
<P>
   IExplore.com _ now partly owned by National Geographic _ also
had a decent search engine, and some nice features, including one
that allowed users to e-mail a page to a friend _ a particularly
useful feature for people traveling in groups.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you found the perfect trip on these sites, however, you
would not be able to book it online. Adventure sites typically ask
their prospective customers to call an 800 number to reserve a
trip. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this are both pragmatic and technological. Most
of the companies in the market are small businesses run by people
who are much more in tune with nature than e-commerce. They lack
both the budget and the inclination to spend thousands of dollars
on Internet booking systems.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The adventure travel Web sites that depend on those tour
operators for inventory have, in some cases, begun the long process
of helping build reservation tracking systems for the operators, so
everyone knows when a booking has been made, and how many available
spots there are on a given trip.
</P>
<P>
   But even then, tour operators and their Internet partners prefer
to have some interaction with the customer _ other than a mouse
click that delivers a credit card number. By discussing the
itinerary with a customer, travel agents can steer less-qualified
adventurers toward less-strenuous trips, and make sure that those
who are fit enough to climb a mountain have the right equipment and
expectations for the vacation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Carla Kinney, 31, an acquisitions editor in Sugar Hill, N.H.,
recently tested the waters of online adventure travel planning
while researching a backpacking trip to Montana. Her husband,
Luther, 29, is a whitewater and backpacking enthusiast, and
although Kinney says she is fit, she has not gone on overnight
backpacking trips with him because she is not sure how she'd hold
up with a heavy pack for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan was to try a guided backpacking trip on her own first,
to ease into the experience, so she checked a number of online
search engines to find such a tour. Eventually, Kinney said she
landed on the GORP.com site, where she had a 90-minute online chat
with a travel consultant named Melissa. The chat ended abruptly
when Kinney's computer dropped her Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   But because she had typed in her phone number at the beginning
of the chat session, Melissa called immediately, and they resumed
their conversation. Twenty minutes later, they settled on a
weeklong backpacking and horseback riding trip with nine other
participants and five guides in the Bob Marshall Wilderness in
Montana, for roughly $1,600, not including air fare or gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy,'' Kinney said. ``And it could've been very
difficult because I was so vague about what I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   After the trip, Kinney was impressed. ``The outfitters met me at
the airport, even though I'd never spoken to them,'' she said.
``GORP handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether the trip gave her confidence enough to go solo
the next time, Kinney said: ``Absolutely. Most nights I didn't even
sleep in the tent. It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
