<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2205 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FALL-FOLIAGE-BOS &LR;      09-05 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FOLIAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIPPED OF PR, FALL FOLIAGE STRICTLY NATURE'S WHIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaves go insane. At least that's what new research suggests
about how and why leaves turn those riotous shades of red, yellow
and orange each fall. Facing certain death, leaves appear to
undergo a last crazed metamorphosis to better absorb ultraviolet
rays or protect themselves before becoming mulch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the first wave of foliage forecasters predict that this
could be a big year for fall color, tree experts warn that &UR;  &LR; the
predictions have more to do with bolstering tourism than reality.
Weather during the last two weeks before Columbus Day _ when the
leaves go insane _ will play a big role in determining whether we
get a bumper crop of color, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we get to the middle of September, everything that
happens before then really doesn't affect fall color,'' said Peter
Del Tredici, director of living collections with the Arnold
Arboretum in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to come up with a prediction of how bright it's going
to be is pretty iffy,'' added John O'Keefe, curator of the Fisher
Museum at Harvard Forest in Petersham, Mass. ``I'll wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   But, at this time of year, the science of foliage tends to take
a backseat to commerce as various state tourism offices begin
issuing early predictions to lure peepers and their pocketbooks.
And the tree experts feel pressured to make predictions, too.
</P>
<P>
   This week, out of Connecticut, came New England's first guess,
with that state's director of forestry saying the soggy summer
could be a boon to this fall's foliage season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trees have larger leaves and more of them, and I think
everyone will find the colors this year will be pretty
impressive,'' said Don H. Smith Jr., director of Connecticut's
forestry division.
</P>
<P>
   However, Warren Archey, chief forester for Massachusetts, was
less certain about both the brilliance and arrival of the foliage
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't go out and book a hotel on the basis of a certain
weekend expecting necessarily to see the peak, but I'll go with the
second week of October,'' he said, falling back on the traditional
peak foliage week for Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's O'Keefe wouldn't even make a prediction even though he
is one of the state's leading foliage experts. Tuesday he walked
more than 1 1/2 miles and surveyed about 100 species of trees and
shrubs for their leafy changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched it for 10 years and . . . my sense is that the
foliage is impressive every year,'' he said. ``In many cases, the
predictions may be relatively true, but I think that we don't have
a consistent scale to measure this against.''
</P>
<P>
   If the past is any indication, O'Keefe is right to be reluctant.
Forecasters predicted a dire year during the 1995 drought as leaf
peepers mourned. But according to O'Keefe, it didn't dramatically
reduce the perceived color. Even last year's predictions of a dull
fall fell flat when the colors turned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some horrendous weather in the last five to six
years in which trees lost 20 percent of their foliage, and yet
we've had some spectacular fall color,'' said Del Tredici.
</P>
<P>
   Although summer rainfall is one indicator of the intensity of
fall foliage (healthier trees equals bigger leaves equal more
intense colors), experts agree that it's only one variable. But
they are often pressed by the media and the public to make bold
predictions because of all the interest in fall tourism.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported that the proliferation of
bed-and-breakfasts has made leaf-peeping an $8 billion annual
business in New England, ahead of skiing in several of the states.
In Maine alone, nearly 400,000 people arrive to view the fall
colors, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you knew my grades in plant physiology, the last person you
would call would be me,'' said Massachusetts' Archey.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that the fall foliage season ahead could
be a good one. In June and July alone this year, the region had a
rain surplus of almost six inches above normal, a good indication
of healthy trees, according to the Weather Services Corp. of
Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   To really predict what's going to happen, O'Keefe and Del
Tredici say that one must combine rainfall with cooling
temperatures, a day-length component, and a bunch of other factors
and, maybe, you'll be able to make a prediction.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the confusion, biologists are continuing to learn more
about these simple fall pleasures, including new insights into why
leaves turn red.
</P>
<P>
   Elementary school textbooks teach that the change is a simple
dying off that unmasks reds and yellows as trees slowly go dormant.
But David Lee and Missy Holbrook of Florida International
University, believe trees may purposefully produce the colors when
they sense the end of the growing season.
</P>
<P>
   Under their theory, the colors may protect the leaves, allowing
them to remain on the tree a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really uncharted territory,'' he said. ``It's amazing
there's been so little research on this, especially given the
American academic establishment's headquarters is in the Eastern
US.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Keefe plans to continue his weekly trips into the forest and
plotting the progress of the foliage. And, as for these early
predictions, he sees some positives.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it gets people looking,'' he said. ``And maybe
they'll do a little bit more thinking than they normally would when
they get up one morning and notice that the trees are red and
yellow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
