<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2207 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MEDICARE-HNS &LR;      09-05 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MEDICARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PLAN REQUIRES INSURANCE COMPANIES PROVIDING MEDICARE TO
INCLUDE PRESCRIPTION DRUG OPTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLENTOWN, Pa. _ Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush tried to take the offensive on the prescription drug issue
Tuesday by detailing a $158 billion plan to help pay Medicare
insurance premiums on plans that provide drug benefit options to
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the cruel choices some seniors face: Heat or
medicine. Food or pills. In a wealthy nation, this is a scandal. In
a compassionate nation, it is a call to action,'' Bush said at the
Gross Towers senior citizen home.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's 10-year proposal would shift Medicare away from being a
government-run program to one that involves more competition among
private insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would require all insurance companies providing
Medicare coverage to include a prescription drug option. Medicare
would pay the premiums for the poorest Americans, subsidize the
cost for others and cover catastrophic Medicare costs exceeding
$6,000 a year for all seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also is proposing to spend an additional $40 billion to
restore payments to Medicare providers that were reduced under the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997. That would bring the total value of
Bush's package to $198 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore immediately attacked Bush's proposal, claiming
it would force the elderly poor unwillingly into health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign appearance in Columbus, Ohio, the vice president
also contended that Bush's plan ``would leave millions of seniors
without prescription drug coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with the plan, Gore said, is that Bush
cannot pay for it and still go ahead with his proposed $1.3
trillion tax cut, which Gore has said will eat up most of the
federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed a $150 billion prescription drug benefit that
would have the Medicare program directly subsidize senior citizens'
drug purchases. Under the Gore plan Medicare would subsidize half
the costs of prescription drugs up to a $5,000 annual limit. Poor
seniors would get larger subsidies depending on their incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore plan also provides catastrophic coverage for expensive
drug purchases. Once a beneficiary paid $4,000 a year in
prescription drugs Medicare would pay the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Gore put Bush on the defensive two weeks ago by outlining a $253
billion plan to directly subsidize prescription drug costs for
senior citizens. Gore's plan helped pull the vice president into a
dead heat with Bush in national polls and has been credited with
Gore's new lead in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would pay for all the prescription drugs of the
poorest elderly, individuals earning up to $11,200 a year. More
affluent Americans would have half their drug costs paid for by the
federal government if they took a one-time opportunity to sign up
for a drug plan when they became eligible for Medicare. The
eligibility age is now 65.
</P>
<P>
   In detailing his own plan, Bush sharply criticized Gore as part
of an administration that has failed to reform Medicare. Bush
claimed Gore was more interested in using Medicare for partisan
political advantage than in fixing the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore talks about the `people' vs. the
`powerful.' For eight years he has been the powerful and on health
care he has little to show for it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On health care, my opponent offers the same tired, partisan
ideas that have led our country nowhere,'' Bush said. ``His is the
path of politics, the path of posturing, the path of least
resistance. But it is not the path of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush throughout this year has said he supported the framework of
a plan developed by the National Bipartisan Commission on the
Future of Medicare to have private insurance companies rather than
the government provide prescription drug benefits to seniors, with
a premium subsidy for the poor. But Bush had not previously said
what details he would back.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan proposes spending $110 billion over 10 years to
modernize Medicare by guaranteeing every senior current Medicare
benefits and expanding coverage to include plans with prescription
drug benefits:
</P>
<P>
   Total catastrophic coverage would begin for all seniors when
their medical charges exceeded $6,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   As an emergency measure, Bush also proposed giving $48 billion
directly to states to subsidize prescription drug payments for
seniors locally while the new federal program gets up and running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there is no prescription drug benefit in Medicare, 23
states have now established state drug assistance programs,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas under Bush's tenure as governor is not one of those
states. Bush campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes said such a program
has never been proposed in Texas by either the Legislature or the
governor's office. But she said interim legislative committees are
looking at the issue for the legislative session that begins in
January.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Gore's plan will keep prescription drug benefits as
part of a government-run program, but seniors who sign up will know
that half their prescription costs are paid. Gore's plan also
includes premiums of about $25 a month that will rise to $40 a
month in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would most benefit poor people who now have no
prescription drug benefits. The Congressional Budget Office has
estimated that in 1996 the average Medicare beneficiary paid $673
for drugs. Gore's plan would pay about $337 of that while requiring
about $300 in new premiums, leaving the average beneficiary $37
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan, by relying on private insurers, leaves open
questions about how much the premiums would cost or how much
prescription drug benefit the elderly actually would receive.
However, it has the advantage that the elderly could switch plans
every year and pay additional premiums to get extra coverage for
prescription drugs and other health care.
</P>
<P>
   Bush offered a point-by-point critique of Gore's plan, attacking
first the fact the elderly would only have one chance to sign up
for a prescription program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like the plan the Washington bureaucracy puts you
into, it's too bad. You have no other options,'' Bush said. ``If
you want coverage at age 67 or you change your mind, you're again
out of luck. It's the Gore plan for life or nothing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also noted that Gore's plan does not become fully effective
for eight years, while his own plan has provisions to quickly help
pay for prescriptions for the poor through his state programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Gore's plan also would lead to price controls by
putting the federal government in the position of negotiating major
discounts with pharmaceutical manufacturers. Bush said such price
controls would end drug research.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hostile government takeover of the drug industry would
actually dry up the supply of new miracle drugs,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Gore's plan does nothing to bring about a
fundamental reform of how the Medicare system is run and still
risks the system going bankrupt by 2025 because of a growing
elderly population.
</P>
<P>
   Noting Medicare was created in 1965, Bush compared the system to
an old car that Gore and President Clinton promised to fix in the
1992 and 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have changed the odometer, but it's still not
running. Medicare needs an overhaul,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
