<SLUG> BC-GATES-GRANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES PUTS $28.5M INTO `SMALLER IS BETTER' EDUCATION THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a major investment in the increasingly hot ``smaller
is better'' educational movement, Microsoft chairman Bill Gates
will donate $28.5 million to Massachusetts and Rhode Island groups
working on small schools and other educational innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Citing research that touts the effectiveness of small schools,
the Bill &AMP; Melinda Gates Foundation is granting $8.5 million to two
Massachusetts organizations and showering $20 million on Rhode
Island schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Collaborative Education, which works with the 11
pilot schools in the Boston Public Schools, will use $4.9 million
to create 20 small public schools with fewer than 400 students in
New England and upstate New York. Some will be entirely new; others
will be carved out of larger existing schools.
</P>
<P>
   With its $3.6 million share, the Harvard Graduate School of
Education will develop a ``Change Leadership Group'' to offer
training and support services to schools around the country that
are pursuing innovation and change.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million earmarked for Rhode Island goes to the
Providence and Coventry school districts and the Big Picture
Company, a nonprofit that created two public schools in Providence.
The money is for opening small schools and ``smaller learning
communities'' within schools.
</P>
<P>
   The donations, to be announced Wednesday, are the first outside
of Washington state in the Gates Foundation's $350 million campaign
to improve primary and secondary schools. The foundation is also
pouring $1 billion during the next 20 years into college
scholarships for minority students.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates is putting his wealth behind an educational
philosophy very popular today _ the idea that smaller schools can
do wonders for students in urban and rural settings.
</P>
<P>
   The first step to a good education, said Dan French, executive
director of the Center for Collaborative Education, is providing an
environment where ``each student is known well by at least one
adult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is mounting evidence and research, particularly with
low-income students and students of color, that small schools are
more successful at providing them a quality education,'' French
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gates Foundation and French both point to a recent study in
Chicago, which found that in schools with populations of 350 or
fewer, students were less likely to drop out and more likely to get
better grades. The study, by the Bank Street College of Education
in New York, was published in June.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 report by the Northwest Regional Educational Laboratory
in Oregon also found that small schools have fewer problems with
discipline, violence, theft, substance abuse, and gang
participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small schools have higher retention, college acceptance, and
motivation,'' said Carol Rava, a spokeswoman for the Gates
Foundation. ``We need to step back from the thinking most of us
know from our high school experiences, oriented toward traditional,
large, comprehensive American schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Collaborative Education currently supports the
network of 11 pilot schools in Boston. These schools are part of
the public school system but free from most union and school
committee rules. They include the Boston Arts Academy, Boston
Evening Academy, Young Achievers Math and Science School, and
Fenway High School, which emphasizes critical thinking.
</P>
<P>
   With its grant money, the group hopes to open four small public
schools _ most of them in urban school districts _ each year for
the next five years. The organization will provide them with
professional development and curriculum guidance and will pair each
one with a ``mentor'' school, a preexisting small school, French
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard Graduate School of Education has three goals for its
share, said Tony Wagner, an educational consultant who will be
codirector of the Change Leadership Group. First, they plan to
research the best practices available in educational coaching.
Second, they intend to develop a certification program for school
leaders interested in smaller schools and other reform. Third, they
intend to create a nonprofit consulting business for schools and
school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming more and more clear that schools need help
(implementing change) and that help simply isn't available,''
Wagner said. ``Educational leaders know how to manage the status
quo, but they don't know how to do change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
