<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PELE-ENDORSE-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S OIL COMPANY, IN QUEST OF WORLD STATUS, HIRES PELE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ When Edson Arantes do Nascimento was 18, he
used to run onto the soccer field with a 130-pound sack of coffee
beans on his back. Even then, in the days before Colombia's Juan
Valdez stole the limelight from Brazilian coffee, the young man
known as Pele was already using his fame to promote his country's
products abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Some things never change. In a new role as goodwill ambassador
for the Brazilian oil giant Petroleo Brasileiro, or Petrobras,
Pele, who turns 60 next month, is lending the considerable weight
of his name to another company with international aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Petrobras is a Brazilian company that made good, just like
Pele is a Brazilian who made good,'' Pele said in an interview
here. ``I can help Petrobras project that image abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrobras is one of a growing number of Brazilian companies that
have become competitive enough in recent years to turn their sights
toward the international market. Like most of the others, though,
the oil company is hard pressed to come up with the investment
capital in Brazil needed to finance its efforts. So Petrobras has
sought international investors.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, though, is that Petrobras, the world's
seventh-largest publicly traded oil company, is not well known
outside Brazil. The fact that most of the company's oil is used by
Brazilians has not helped. Nor did the company's 45-year reign as a
state-owned monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Petrobras formally lost its monopoly five years ago, and Brazil
is now in the process of opening the energy market to full
competition. To compete against the likes of Royal Dutch/Shell and
Exxon Mobil, the company is increasingly feeling the pressure to go
global. Indeed, Petrobras has plans to spend $33 billion over the
next five years to double its current production and buy up oil
exploration blocks in the Gulf of Mexico and off the coast of West
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to expand abroad,'' said Henri Philippe Reichstul, the
president of Petrobras, when the advertising contract was
announced. ``Pele, his legend, will be our ambassador.''
</P>
<P>
   But the job will not be easy. In years past, Brazil has gotten
more headlines abroad from its political antics, violence and
environmental damage than its business acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Pele said that in his many years of travel, the most frequent
question he has been asked is how Brazil is going to overcome its
chronic corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sad about the negative propaganda that our politicians
create for Brazil abroad,'' he remarked. ``Unfortunately, the
administration of Brazil has been terrible, and it is just starting
to get better now.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrobras also has its own baggage. The company was responsible
for two extensive oil spills this year that have tainted its
reputation in and outside Brazil. The first spill, in January,
flooded Guanabara Bay in Rio de Janeiro with 325,000 gallons of
oil, blackening some famed beaches and endangering a fragile nature
preserve. After a thorough mea culpa by Reichstul, Petrobras
thought it had put the troubles behind, when another spill, this
time on the Iguacu River in July, sent a million more gallons of
oil into Brazilian waterways.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Pele comes in, with 43 years as an international
icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pele is without a doubt the most well-known Brazilian in the
world,'' said Washington Olivetto, president and creative director
of W/Brasil, a leading advertising agency in Sao Paulo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prominent in his resume are Pele's efforts to help put
Pepsi-Cola behind both the Iron Curtain and the Great Wall of
China. He turned MasterCard International, with which he has a
continuing relationship as spokesman, into something approaching a
household name. And perhaps most challenging, for a short time in
the late 1970s, his efforts on behalf of the North American Soccer
League brought early attention to professional soccer in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint as Brazil's minister of sports from 1995 to 1998,
during which he tried to remake the legislation that governed the
country's soccer teams, Pele has settled into roles as goodwill
ambassador for several U.N. agencies and spokesman in Brazil for
the Finnish cellular phone giant Nokia, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   He is already hard at work for Petrobras. Last month, in his
first ambassadorial mission, he made a personal appearance at the
New York Stock Exchange for the company's newest stock offering.
The government sold about $4.4 billion in shares, or 17 percent of
the company, to domestic and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a Brazilian company to be understood as being Brazilian,
Pele is an extremely efficient spokesman,'' Olivetto said. ``It is
much easier to explain what Petrobras is to foreigners by using
Pele.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the two years of his contract, he will take part in
commercials, publicity campaigns, speeches and personal appearances
for Petrobras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although, running with a barrel of oil on my back,'' Pele
remarked with a grin, ``now that could get a little complicated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
