<P>
   BUSH-MEDICARE (Allentown, Pa.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush
unveils a health care plan, including a requirement that
Medicare-funded insurance plans include prescription drug coverage.
By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-HEALTH (Washington) _ The Democratic National
Committee trots out new television advertisements bashing Texas
Gov. George W. Bush on health care, using as a club provided by a
recent federal court order to improve care for poor children's care
in Texas. By MICHAEL HEDGES.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House and Senate return this week to
tackle spending legislation in a four- or five-week session more
akin to rugby than lawmaking as Republicans and Democrats scrum for
position in the November elections. Among the issues that may be
dealt with this week: An effort to override President Clinton's
veto of the estate tax repeal. By KAREN MASTERSON.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HIGH-TECH (Washington) _ With a month left before
Congress adjourns, high-tech industry leaders urge lawmakers to
move quickly on trade, tax and immigration legislation before
adjourning for the final campaign push. By MARK HELM. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FBI-SHOOTER (Washington) _ In an effort to prevent future
Columbine-type massacres, the FBI has created a ``school shooter''
threat assessment that it says will help teachers spot potential
killers among their students. But some child advocates and teacher
representatives are expressing concerns that the guidelines are too
vague and could label a normal adolescent a budding psychopath. By
MICHAEL HEDGES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   UN-SUMMIT (Washington) _ The White House downplays the
likelihood that President Clinton can use a United Nations summit
to revive the Mideast peace talks. Clinton plans to meet separately
with Israeli and Palestinian leaders Wednesday in his bid to
rejuvenate talks that collapsed at Camp David earlier this summer.
By PATTY REINERT. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ NASA prepares for a
scheduled launch Friday of the Atlantis on a mission to the
international space station. By MARK CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Some political scientists are
predicting Al Gore will win the presidential race on the basis of
mathematical formulas alone. What a hoot. Politics is not a
science, but if it were, it would be an inexact one determined not
by numbers-crunching but by the vagaries of human nature. Who could
predict, for instance, that George W. Bush would be caught making a
crude remark, and who knows how the public will react to that? By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HINES-COLUMN (Washington) _ As the race for the Republican
presidential nomination quickened last fall, George W. Bush said:
``I still have time to screw this up.'' Perhaps over the last three
weeks, as Bush's lead in polls vanished and Vice President Al Gore
gained an upper hand in the national race, the Texas governor
recalled that observation. There is almost always some ebb and flow
in a presidential race without an incumbent, but Bush's recent fade
has been startling. By CRAGG HINES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ELY-COLUMN (Undated) _ It must be the heat. Only the killer
temperature possibly can explain it, not just all the political
silliness of the Labor Day weekend, but the public's reaction to
it. By JANE ELY. (Already filed.)
</P>
