<SLUG> BC-TURN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TURN IT UP': RAPSTERS' ATTITUDE CAN'T SAVE `TURN IT UP'  
 BY STEPHEN HOLDEN  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been called screen presence, star quality and charisma. But
a more apt word for the buzz exuded by the stars of the rickety rap
melodrama ``Turn It Up'' might be attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The projection of attitude _ that's with a capital A _ is a
basic ingredient of hip-hop performance, and it's one reason
rappers seem able to make the transition from music to movies far
more easily than their rock-and-roll forerunners. Long before
appearing in the films, they were already rehearsing their roles.
</P>
<P>
   The typical rap record, after all, is an action-adventure film
(minus the visuals) in which the performer struts a personal
fantasy of urban life. And in ``Turn It Up,'' which has been touted
in advance as the hip-hop answer to ``Purple Rain,'' the rappers
Prakazriel Michel (better known as Pras) and Ja Rule (making his
movie debut) hold the screen with a brash, swaggering arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Pras, a founding member of the Fugees, plays Diamond, an
up-and-coming rapper from Brooklyn, and Ja Rule is Gage, his
thuggish manager and best friend since childhood. As the movie
opens, Diamond has already acquired an underground reputation for
his rap performances in after-hours clubs. He and Gage are
recording a demo with funds made from low-level drug deals arranged
by Mr. B (Jason Staham), a sinister and vicious British drug czar
with ties to the record business. One of Mr. B's closest pals is a
record president known only (and symbolically) as Mr. White (John
Ralston).
</P>
<P>
   Diamond is also trying to hold together a volatile relationship
with his girlfriend, Kia (Tamala Jones), who announces that she's
pregnant and pressures him into making a commitment. One sure sign
of Diamond's ambivalence about the relationship is his refusal to
give her his cell phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Everything explodes at once. Diamond's mother suddenly dies, and
his father, Cliff (Vondie Curtis-Hall), who had vanished years
earlier, appears out of the blue and invites himself to stay with
his still-resentful son. And without consulting Diamond, Gage goes
on the criminal rampage to acquire the big bucks to pay for an
independently produced record.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Adetuyi, who wrote and directed ``Turn It Up,'' has a
sharp ear for streetwise dialogue and an eye for seedy urban
ambience. His screenplay captures the urgency, impatience and
frustrations of impoverished musicians just one recording away from
becoming millionaires. The story takes for granted Diamond's and
Gage's illicit interim self-support system, implying without
judgment that this is the way it's often done in the rap world.
</P>
<P>
   But in the film's more intimate scenes, the dialogue turns
wooden and self-conscious. And as the movie goes along, it loses
track of its subplots. Its minor characters, especially the robotic
Mr. White, who talks like an Eddie Murphy imitation of Richard
Nixon, are implausible. And what are we to make of the prodigal
father, who abandoned his wife and young son to pursue a career as
a jazz pianist, then sank into alcoholism and now exudes a sagelike
authority and wisdom? The complicated father-son relationship,
which could have been a movie in itself, is left unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually ``Turn It Up'' deteriorates into a gory shoot-'em-up
gangster movie with a quick-fix ending that leaves many threads
dangling. It could have been something more. The movie is rated R
(Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian).
</P>
</TEXT>
