<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO OFFER DETAILS ON ECONOMIC GOALS: PAYING DOWN NATIONAL
BUDGET, USE OF SURPLUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Hoping to prove he is more fiscally prudent than his
opponent, Al Gore Wednesday will lay out a detailed budget plan
spelling out how he intends to pay down the national debt and use
the projected federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to be delivered at Cleveland State University, aides
said, Gore will list 10 economic goals that include eliminating the
national debt by 2012, doubling the number of families with savings
in excess of $50,000, and ensuring that Medicare and Social
Security payroll taxes are not used for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to be giving an economic policy speech that is
comprehensive and detailed and chock-full of details,'' Gore said
on Tuesday. ``It will set some clear goals. It will describe how we
can have a balanced budget every year and still set aside enough
money to pay down the debt and completely eliminate the debt by
year 2012.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech will be accompanied by the release of a several
hundred page budget document providing a year-by-year accounting of
how the surplus will be spent and how the debt will be whittled
down.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the details, however, are not new. Gore has spent much
of the campaign season trotting out a series of spending programs
and a $500 billion tax cut, to be funded largely from the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   What is new is the packaging of the proposals. For example, he
had previously announced a tax program to allow people to set up
401(k)-style retirement savings programs. But the budget plan will
use those tax deductions and credits as the means to achieve his
goal to double the number of families with savings in excess of
$50,000. About a third of all families have reached such savings
now, according to Gore aides.
</P>
<P>
   Aides also hope the presentation will put Gore's Republican
opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, on the defensive by contending
that the governor's proposed $1.3 trillion tax cut and spending
proposals will leave the country saddled with a $2.8 trillion debt
in 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials have defended his economic program as
sound. They argue there will be ample money to pay for their tax
cut and spending initiatives. On Tuesday, Bush enriched that
spending package with a $150 billion health care plan for senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett said that under the governor's
plans, the debt would be eliminated by 2016. He dismissed the four
additional years of debt as insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the context of our economy that is minuscule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said the timing of the debt reduction was partially
dependent on how Bush's plan to let some people invest part of
their Social Security taxes in private retirement accounts shapes
up. The transition costs for the retirement plan are estimated to
be as high as a $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett also dismissed the notion that Gore was being more
fiscally conservative, arguing that according to an analysis by the
Bush campaign, Gore's spending program would eat up the surplus
plus another $396 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In another move pounced on by the Bush campaign, Gore aides said
that their budget plan will include the more generous estimates
from the Congressional Budget Office which has pegged the surplus
at $4.5 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Up until recently Gore has stuck to the more conservative
estimate of $4.1 billion surplus estimate by the federal Office of
Management and Budget. And his campaign has criticized Bush for
relying on the larger CBO numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said it was ``hypocritical'' of Gore to criticize Bush
for relying on the larger estimates when he was now willing to use
them to create extra revenue for his budget plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
