<HEADLINE>
THE PUBLICITY ON `JAZZ';   `BIG BROTHER' CASH 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE PUBLICITY ON `JAZZ'
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago Ken Burns, the documentary filmmaker, sat down
with his public relations advisers as well as executives from
General Motors, his corporate sponsor, and PBS to figure out how
best to promote his forthcoming documentary, ``Jazz,'' which is to
begin running on PBS in January.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-part series tracks the history of jazz from its inception
_ during the days of the slave trade _ through current times.
</P>
<P>
   Burn's first two major documentaries, ``The Civil War'' and
``Baseball,'' which ran several hours over several nights, had been
shown before the Internet was a part of everyday life for so many
and before cable was so aggressively programming against the
broadcast networks and PBS.
</P>
<P>
   When ``The Civil War'' made its debut in 1990, and even in 1994
with the debut of ``Baseball,'' it did not take so much promotional
work to convince people to watch a lengthy documentary on public
television, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   For those films, Burns said, ``you could probably put ads in the
paper, get a couple of feature stories and you had a huge
percentage of the audience primed and geared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you have to yell a little bit louder,'' he said. ``Just
to get, maybe, even less.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Burns and his associates came up with what
they are calling an unusually intensive corporate promotional and
marketing campaign for a PBS series, one that is akin to those
undertaken by corporate behemoths like the Walt Disney Co. It was
put together by reaching out to various industries for which the
documentary could be of interest.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, after being approached by General Motors
representatives, Sony Music and Verve Music Group, the major
competing distributors of jazz in the United States, have agreed to
jointly produce 24 separate jazz compilations based on the
documentary. Those compilation CD's will be offered for sale in
record stores starting in November.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks coffee shops, where the documentary will be
advertised, will offer a ``Jazz'' CD for sale in January. Some of
the proceeds from those sales are to go to the United Negro College
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Klores, General Motors' public relations and marketing
specialist, enlisted another one of his clients, the National
Basketball Association, to promote the film with half-time jazz
performances at the nation's basketball arenas throughout the fall.
The NBA will also produce television spots promoting the
documentary.
</P>
<P>
   GM will sponsor jazz concerts and screenings of the documentary
around the country and has signed on as a sponsor of the 2000/2001
season of Jazz at Lincoln Center. It also plans to underwrite a
jazz education program for middle-school pupils around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Knopf is publishing a ``Jazz'' book by Burns and
Geoffrey C. Ward, based on the documentary. It is to go on sale in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Burns and PBS executives said they hoped that all the promotion
would help the documentary reach wide swaths of the television
audience that PBS does not normally draw.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt PBS has much riding on its success.
</P>
<P>
   Burns' documentaries typically double, or even triple, PBS's
average ratings. That kind of draw is more meaningful than ever to
PBS' executives, considering that it now faces new competitors on
cable, like A&AMP;E and the History Channel, which show programs
similar to those that were once the sole purview of PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the importance of ``Jazz'' to PBS, the network was
originally planning to show the documentary in the fall. But it
instead decided to show it in January to move it out from under the
shadows of the Olympics and coverage of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While the promotional campaign goes far, Burns said, it does
have limits. ``We're holding off on the cups and the lunchboxes,''
he said. ``I don't think there's a Happy Meal in our future.''
</P>
<P>
   `BIG BROTHER' CASH
</P>
<P>
   Now, the producers of the CBS reality series ``Big Brother'' are
getting really serious.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to get someone now in the ``Big Brother'' house to
quit the show, the producers intend to increase a cash offer to
contestants to more than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The money will go tonight to the first one who is willing to
quit the camera-filled house in which he or she has been locked for
the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to create an opening so a new contestant, a
22-year-old woman named Beth, can be inserted in the house _ and,
the producers fervently hope _stir things up. But after word that
$10,000 would be offered was reported on Monday, several fans of
the current cast took to displaying signs around the house to tell
the participants the offer was coming and urging them to reject it.
</P>
<P>
   That is the last thing the Big Brother producers want to see
happen. So they plan to up the ante further.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are going to be higher than anyone expects,'' said
Eddie Michaels, a spokesman. Indeed, the number will ``certainly go
higher than $20,000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is intended to light some kind of fire under what is
considered an increasingly sparkless show. At a time when the
show's popularity had been expected to improve because the number
of possible winners was down to six, the ratings are slipping.
</P>
<P>
   How far will the producers go to squeeze someone out of the
house? Michaels would not say. But the show's winner is to get
$500,000, with $100,000 going to the second-place finisher and
$50,000 to the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
