<SLUG> BC-TECH-REGENERATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM SAYS IT RESTORED USE OF LIMBS IN PARALYZED RATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston Life Sciences Inc. says it has produced a near
total recovery of limb function in an experimental rat model of
stroke, advancing hopes for a treatment that could reverse nerve
damage and paralysis in stroke victims.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 days of treatment with the company's nerve growth
factor Inosine, rats that had been paralyzed recovered more than 90
percent of the muscle function in their limbs. The treatment began
two days after the rats had suffered a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Although Inosine still must pass years of rigorous testing in
human clinical trials before being made commercially available, the
company said the drug has the potential to be the first
regenerative therapy for stroke victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``All current stroke therapies, which must be given almost
immediately after stroke to take effect, are based on preventing or
minimizing the original damage,'' said Dr. Marc Lanser, founder and
chief scientific officer. ``Inosine appears to be effective even
when given after the damage has been done and the stroke is
complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Life Sciences contracted Cerebrotec, a neuroscience
research laboratory, to perform the actual experiment. The rats'
limb function was assessed over the 20-day treatment through a
variety of measures, including paw reaching and twisting tests.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Opel, a health-care technology analyst with Boston-based
investment bank H.C. Wainwright &AMP; Co., said that even if all goes
well, it would be another three to five years before Inosine could
reach the market. The company must get approval from the US Food
and Drug Administration before beginning human clinical trials to
test the product's safety and effectiveness. Then, it must get
clearance from the FDA to market the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, I would say that from nothing at all to success in an
animal model is a bigger advance than going from an animal model to
a human model,'' Opel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
