<HEADER>
A2235 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-SKI-ENVIRON-$A     09-05 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-ENVIRON-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKI RESORTS PLEDGE TO PROTECT NATURAL AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the nation's biggest ski resorts, trail maps this season will
be emblazoned with a proclamation of environmental good will.
``Sustainable Slopes,'' the new program, is the product of a ski
industry association campaign to quiet critics and to reassure
visitors that its members are committed to protecting natural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   At least 165 ski resorts around the country, including the 20
largest, will be entitled to display the logo, having signed off in
June on a set of standards drafted by the association with help
from government agencies and some environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the standards are often vague, leading many critics to
complain that they do not go far enough to shield forests, rivers
and other wild areas from the damage that ski areas can cause.
</P>
<P>
   The charter calls for voluntary commitment to follow ``best
practices'' in several areas, including ``to use the natural
surroundings as a means to increase environmental awareness'' and
``to conserve natural resources'' in dealing with water, energy,
waste management, fish and wildlife, forests and wetlands. It also
calls on signatories ``to engage surrounding communities and
interest groups in a dialogue on development plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort has already kindled debate between an industry trying
to show itself as ecologically sensitive and skeptical activists
who have now vowed to develop a rating system of their own in order
to grade ski areas on their environmental conduct. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we feel that this so-called charter is being
used as a public relations ploy rather than a genuine attempt to
improve their environmental performance,'' said Jeff Berman,
executive director of Colorado Wild of Durango, Colo., one of the
organizations trying to develop the report card by the time the ski
season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups and the ski industry have long been at
odds, wrangling in the courts and other arenas over issues like the
development of ski areas in the national forests and the tapping of
mountain streams for snowmaking.
</P>
<P>
   One of the angriest battles, over the proposed expansion at Vail
Mountain in Colorado, was fought through the mid 1990s. After a
federal court upheld the development plan, arsonists destroyed a
mountaintop restaurant and four ski lifts at Vail in October 1998,
causing $12 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was condemned by mainstream environmental groups, but
an organization calling itself the Earth Liberation Front took
responsibility, saying it was protesting destruction of habitat for
the lynx.
</P>
<P>
   In drafting the new charter, the industry group, the National
Ski Areas Association, has not tried to hide its determination to
put forth a greener image.
</P>
<P>
   The resorts that make up the ski industry ``are operated or
owned by individuals who have a strong environmental ethic,''
Geraldine Hughes, the group's director of public policy, said in a
telephone interview from Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the document, issued as a 22-page book on
recycled paper, calls for voluntary commitment to protecting nature
through more efficient use of energy, safer waste disposal and
water conservation. Hughes said the association would issue a
report next spring assessing progress toward meeting those goals.
</P>
<P>
   The signatories include virtually every major ski resort,
including Vail, Aspen, Park City, Jackson Hole and Sugarloaf, with
the total number accounting for about 70 percent of skier visits.
Half the group's 330 members have not yet agreed to the plan, but
Hughes said most of these were small operators with limited
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Among 12 outside organizations that have endorsed the plan as
partners (including the Environmental Protection Agency and the
Forest Service), two were environmental groups: Leave No Trace, of
Boulder, and the Conservation Law Foundation of New England, which
has filed numerous lawsuits against ski resorts in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In a June announcement, Mark Sinclair, vice president of the
Conservation Law Foundation, said he believed that the charter
would ``allow resort owners and environmental groups to work more
closely together to improve the sustainability of the ski
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   But many other environmental groups chose not to endorse the
plan, including Trout Unlimited, which objected to the absence of a
clear commitment to protect fish habitats from increasingly
extensive snowmaking operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I grew up, skiing started at Christmas or, if you were
lucky, at Thanksgiving,'' said Melinda Kassen, a Colorado-based
expert for the organization. ``With snowmaking, ski areas open in
mid- to late October, the low-flow season for the streams and
creeks, and so that means they're sucking water when the fish are
most vulnerable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, the ski industry official, said the resort operators had
been careful not to promise too much. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We do create great recreation opportunities,'' Hughes said.
``But with those opportunities come impacts, and we're not going to
agree to something we cannot do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
