<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BACKSTAGE-FILM-REVIEW     09-05 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKSTAGE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BACKSTAGE': FILM PRESENTS RAPPER'S-EYE VIEW OF CONCERT TOURING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I came to blow it down, and I'm gonna blow it down,'' DMX says
of his turn onstage in the concert documentary ``Backstage,'' which
follows the 1999 ``Hard Knock Life'' tour headed by Jay-Z and
several other rappers, including the likable and funny Beanie
Sigel, Redman, Memphis Bleek and others, along with a cameo by an
effusive Busta Rhymes, who has the cheerfulness of new money.
</P>
<P>
   DMX, who's so prolific _ and sometimes repetitive _ he may get
his own wing at Tower Records, has a remarkable and combative stage
presence. Bombastic and hot-blooded, he holds court in a singular
fashion, exercising sheer force of will to pull the spotlight down
on himself and demanding the crowd's attention: ``That's the need
to be heard,'' he states, offering his view. (``He epitomizes the
have-nots,'' the Def Jam Music producer Irv Gotti says of the lean,
prowling star.)
</P>
<P>
   DMX's portion of the performance is unlike the family vibe that
permeates the shows of the other rappers on the tour. They include
Jay-Z, who rescued his hit ``Hard Knock Life'' from the inanity of
the movie version of ``Annie'' and built a generation's anthem
around the original song's tossed-off chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Jay-Z used his stature to create the tour he wanted. Instead of
being coerced to go out with an rhythm and blues act to make him
more accessible (as is mentioned in the movie), Jay-Z flexed his
3-million-record sales muscle to surround himself with the rappers
he likes.
</P>
<P>
   Like Spike Lee's ``Original Kings of Comedy,'' which shows the
unanimity of purpose among four professional but extremely
competitive comedians, ``Backstage'' provides a glimpse into the
lives of tough and cooperative black entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of DMX, who seems to seal himself off from
his fellow performers _ ``The only part of the tour I like is the
one hour I'm onstage,'' he says, and a handwritten sign warns that
only his beloved pit bull is allowed to visit him before his show _
the rappers spend copious hang time eluding and flirting with
groupies. (Their faces are obscured by dots of various colors and
sizes and with messages, including ``Your Ad Here.'') It's the
standard life of revelry and exhaustion, something that has been a
staple of concert music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backstage'' deals with that as well as the performers'
awareness of the way rappers are perceived. The tour was in Denver
when the Columbine High School shootings occurred, and Jay-Z makes
a point of contributing the profits from the Denver show to the
school. At another point Redman notes that he had seen a mosh pit
while touring with Everclear: ``If that ever happened at a hip-hop
show, they'd shut it down,'' he muses.
</P>
<P>
   Where things get really tense and interesting is in the stances
of the management companies. Damon Dash, head of Roc-A-Fella
Records, is furious because Def Jam upstages Roc-A-Fella's artists
by usurping props like jackets; the Def Jam jackets, by the way, do
the job because they're quite fly. Since Jay-Z is a Roc-A-Fella
artist, and the focal point of the show _ ``I came all the way from
Montana to see Jay-Z,'' a young white fan enthuses _ Dash's anger
seems justified.
</P>
<P>
   The film would have been better served had it given a more
complete picture of the shrewdness that has made Def Jam such a
player, although hard-core fans (and ``Hard Knock'' fans) know of
the rivalries in the rap world. As Ja Rule says, ``As long as
you're black, it's gonna be a hustle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Backstage'' isn't as good as the rap documentaries ``Rhyme and
Reason'' and ``The Show,'' but it still casts a keen, observant eye
(even though video fatigue sets in) on this world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
