r s BC-COWBOYS0906-COX     09-05 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS0906-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Aging Cowboys headed nowhere but down
</P>
<P>
   By Rick Cantu If you believe in omens, the season for the Dallas
Cowboys turned to ashes about the time Philadelphia recovered the
game's opening kickoff Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The season was four seconds old when the red-faced Cowboys
became victims of a sneak attack, a successful onside kick by the
hated Eagles. One play symbolized what has happened lately to the
Cowboys, and where they are headed in 2001, 2002, 2003. ...
</P>
<P>
   The NFL basement is a cold and lonely place.
</P>
<P>
   Why such gloom and doom over the 41-14 loss? There are 15 games
left, for Dave Campo's sake. A marathon season is never over after
the first mile. Isn't 10-6 still possible? What about 9-7?
</P>
<P>
   The prophets have already written on the subway walls. The
script for the next few seasons has already been written. The chief
playmakers in Dallas are old, and the new blood does not consist of
blue-chip material. When Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith play their
final games, there might be nothing left at Texas Stadium but some
old jockstraps and film of glory days gone by.
</P>
<P>
   There comes a time when pessimism and realism become the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are 24-25 since 1997, and Aikman and Smith are
almost as old as Mick Jagger. Joining them in the over-30 club are
Leon Lett, Chad Hennings, Mark Stepnoski, Jackie Harris, Darren
Woodson, Erik Williams, Randall Cunningham, Rocket Ismail, Barron
Wortham and Chris Warren. ``The Golden Girls'' showed more spunk
than these Cowboys did Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clues about this dismal start started this summer in oven-hot
Wichita Falls, where devils go to get a tan.
</P>
<P>
   Players were hurt. Williams skipped four weeks. The first-team
offense rarely played together. Smith never carried the football in
a game. And in the course of an 0-5 preseason, players and coaches
had the same battle cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preseason games mean nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, they do.
</P>
<P>
   Forget 0-5. The first-team offense never clicked in preseason
games. The Aikman-to-Joey Galloway connection never connected. And
now Galloway is gone for the season, victimized by a torn knee
ligament. The team has speed but no cohesiveness.
</P>
<P>
   There was no good news Sunday, and Smith, the wise old man of
the offense, summed up the mood perfectly: ``As individuals and as
a team, we have to look in the mirror and ask ourselves what we can
do to become better players.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame the players cannot get any younger.
</P>
<P>
   Blame most of this on Jerry Jones. The team owner has gambled
with amazing luck during his 12 years in Texas, and his fortune is
bigger than Deion Sanders' ego. He has been a brilliant
businessman, a steely-eyed poker player.
</P>
<P>
   The dice no longer are kind.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have become victims of the NFL's salary cap, which
is $62 million this year. Jones was the driving force who made the
Cowboys the NFL's team of the 1990s. His philosophy of giving huge
contracts to players who could win Super Bowls _ Aikman, Smith,
Sanders, Hennings, Lett, Ismail, Galloway _ faces a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's ninth concussion reminds the Cowboys they don't have a
franchise quarterback if his career is close to ending. Smith's
legs will carry him to the Hall of Fame, but it is unrealistic to
believe he can carry the offense by himself. The offensive line is
supposed to be a strength, but the Eagles were hardly impressed.
The defense yielded 201 yards rushing to Duce Staley, not exactly
the reincarnation of Jim Brown.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the scary part: The Cowboys will spend about $10
million in 2001 on players who no longer are on the team. The
signing bonuses Jones gave his top players will still count against
the salary cap. He mortgaged the future by giving bonuses to
players such as Sanders and retired Cowboys Michael Irvin and Daryl
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the Cowboys traded their 2000 and 2001
first-round draft picks to Seattle in exchange for Galloway. While
the Redskins draft players such as All-Amercans LaVar Arrington and
Chris Samuels, the Cowboys add no one with impressive football
pedigrees.
</P>
<P>
   Before long the Cowboys of the '90s will not be much better than
the New Orleans Saints of any decade.
</P>
<P>
   Who will lead the Cowboys when the well of talent runs dry?
Rookie cornerbacks Dwayne Goodrich and Mario Edwards have shown no
glimpses of greatness. There are no running backs to replace Smith,
no quarterbacks to replace Aikman, no offensive linemen to replace
Williams and Stepnoski.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Jones absorbed the heat Sunday, answering
questions for nearly 30 minutes after the game. ``I don't put this
one on Dave Campo's shoulders,'' he said. ``This one goes on my
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones deserves credit for creating an empire. If he reaches the
playoffs with this group, it will be his biggest accomplishment
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Email: rcantu(at)statesman.com or 445-3953.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
