r s BC-TUBERVILLE00906-COX     09-05 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUBERVILLE00906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unwelcome mat is out at Ole Miss
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ Playing on the road in the SEC is tough enough.
It's pretty much impossible when the opposing town has had two
years to get ready.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Auburn coach Tommy Tuberville faces Saturday night
when he takes the Tigers to Mississippi for a key showdown in the
SEC West.
</P>
<P>
   On the Saturday after Thanksgiving 1998, Tuberville left his job
as Mississippi's coach, which paid about $450,000 a year, for one
at Auburn, which would pay $900,000. Tuberville kept his intentions
quiet until he was introduced at Auburn. Mississippi players, fans,
and administrators felt that he had misled them. Others just said
he lied. Tuberville contended it was the nature of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult situation for everybody involved,''
Tuberville said. ``There is no good way to leave. No matter what
you do, people are going to be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi fans didn't buy that explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they appreciated that Tuberville rebuilt a program that had
been wracked by NCAA probation, losing 26 scholarships. They
appreciated that he led the effort to expand and improve
Vaught-Hemingway Stadium, and that he produced 25 wins and three
bowl teams in four years.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who love Ole Miss put a lot of stock in loyalty,
and Saturday night in Oxford they will express _ loudly _ their
displeasure with Tuberville's perceived lack of it. For Saturday's
opener with Tulane, a sign on a store in the Oxford town square
read: ``Sept. 9 _Tommy Tuberville Appreciation Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Tuberville said. ``I've been called a lot of bad
things in a lot of stadiums before. No matter what happens, we have
to get ready to play again next week.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Mississippi fans bought every ticket they could for
the game at Auburn. The Rebel fans were so worked up they were
doing the ``Hotty Toddy'' cheer during the Auburn alma mater. The
Rebels beat Auburn 24-17 in overtime to spark a wild celebration at
Jordan-Hare Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Now Tuberville returns to the place that gave him his first
chance to be a head coach, to a place where 45,000-plus will wish
him ill, to a place where 19 of the 22 starters on the opposing
team were recruited by him and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed with the way coach Tuberville left,'' said
running back Deuce McAllister, a candidate for the Heisman Trophy.
``But I understand. It's business. We just like to remind him what
he left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
