<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PITBULLS-GANGS-BOS &LR;      09-05 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITBULLS-GANGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANGLED PIT BULL MAY HAVE SETTLED GANGS' SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Animal control officials were horrified last year when
they discovered the story behind the naked carcass of a young dog.
</P>
<P>
   Rival gangs, embroiled in a turf war, had settled the dispute by
putting their prized mascot pit bulls in a ring to fight, officials
discovered after interviewing gang members. The losing dog was
skinned and its pelt kept as a trophy by the victorious gang.
</P>
<P>
   The disturbing incident illuminated the growing popularity of
organized dog fighting _ particularly among urban gangs _ that has
spawned a a demand for pit bulls trained to attack, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   City authorities have seized some 450 dogs in the last four
years _ most of them pit bulls that were considered so dangerous
they had to be put down. At least 20 were seized just last month.
</P>
<P>
   A recent string of pit bull attacks has focused attention on a
breed with an entrenched _ and some say undeserved _ reputation for
viciousness. As a result, the City Council Wednesday will consider
a tough law that could include anything from mandatory insurance
for pit bull owners to an outright ban on the breed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to hold owners of these dogs responsible for vicious
behavior,'' said councilor-at-large Stephen J. Murphy who sponsored
the bill. ``This is a problem that needs to be addressed, one way
or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Gang members, city officials say, are deliberately mistreating
pit bulls to turn dogs that are not innately menacing into violent
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These gangs are settling differences with a dog fight, and
dogs that are trained to do that _ there's not much chance for
them,'' said Stephen Crosby, Boston's director of animal control.
``There are a whole lot of pit bulls in this city that are great
dogs. But those that are trained to fight are starved and abused
and trained to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Pit Bulls _ formally called Staffordshire terriers _ have been a
favorite of gang members since the early 1990s as a symbol of fear
and virility. Their stout stances, boxy heads and massive jaw
muscles _ traits supposedly bred into the dogs specifically for
ring fighting _ make them potentially among the most dangerous
breeds when trained to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Outbreaks of pit bull attacks have been widely publicized, and
cities around the country have considered banning or imposing
strict regulations on pit bulls. Public fear has even spread to
France, where recent attacks in a Paris suburb sparked an angry
uprising from people who denounced the breed as not only dangerous
but an American fad.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston last month an attack by two pit bulls sent three
sisters to the hospital, including a pregnant woman who gave birth
prematurely after the attack. Then, a man stabbed a pit bull to
death as he was being attacked, and a Boston police officer shot
and killed a pit bull near a park after the dog attacked a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Police and animal control officials are investigating whether
the dogs in the first incident may have had links to gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists who work with pit bulls say that despite their
reputation, the dogs are no more likely to attack than other
breeds, unless they are abused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're raised normally, they're very sweet,'' said Karyn
Prestier, an animal caregiver at the MSPCA in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The animal shelter has seen increasing evidence of dogs trained
for fighting, however. ``It's there,'' she said. ``It's
underground, but we know it's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston already has an ordinace requiring dogs with violent
histories to be kept indoor or in pens. But the council's proposed
ordinance would specifically target pit bulls. At the very least,
councilors say fines for owners who don't control their dogs should
be raised from $50 for a first offense to $250.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
