<HEADLINE>
CONCERNS OVER INTEL'S GROWTH HELP SEND NASDAQ LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks fell broadly Tuesday, sending the
Nasdaq composite index lower. Intel led the decline after an
analyst said that its sales growth would be slower than forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in drug stocks, meanwhile, coupled with the slide in
technology shares, dragged down the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index. But the Dow Jones industrial average posted a gain, despite
the weakness in Intel.
</P>
<P>
   The first day after Labor Day is often seen as a time when
America gets back to business. But traders and analysts were
reluctant to attribute much significance to Tuesday's price action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the strong gains Nasdaq recorded in August, when it was
up 11 percent, the index was clearly vulnerable to profit taking,''
said Richard E. Cripps, chief market strategist at Legg Mason in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq fell 91.15 points, or 2.2 percent, to 4,143.18.
Declines in Intel, Cisco Systems and JDS Uniphase accounted for
more than one-third of the Nasdaq price drop.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 index slumped 13.69 points, or 0.9 percent, to
1,507.08.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow industrials rose 21.83 points, or 0.2 percent, to
11,260.61, helped by a bullish forecast from Coca-Cola and gains in
stocks like Home Depot and Proctor &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Intel was the most active stock. The shares fell $4.69, to
$69.25, after Ashok Kumar, an analyst at U.S. Bancorp Piper
Jaffray, cut his ratings on the stock to ``buy'' from ``strong
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The forecast for sluggish Intel sales brought down shares of
other semiconductor manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Xilinx fell $2.81, to $89.06. And Applied Materials fell 38
cents, to $84.44.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were reluctant to write off Intel, despite the
downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolute fortunes have been lost trying to market-time
Intel,'' said Philip S. Dow, a managing director in equity research
at Dain Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis. ``This is a buy-and-hold
stock until you know the world is coming to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom fell $3.19, to $33.75. The company, a long-distance
phone service provider, agreed to buy Intermedia Communications for
about $3 billion in stock and will assume $3 billion in debt to
gain a controlling stake in Digex Inc., which helps to operate Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks fell after an analyst at Banc of America Securities
recommended that investors pare holdings in pharmaceutical
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Merck slipped $1.13, to $68.06; Pfizer fell $2.16, to $41; Eli
Lilly declined $2.94, to $69.75; and Pharmacia closed at $56.44,
down $1.94.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola had its biggest one-day gain since June 22, rising
$1.75, to $56. The company said sales should rise 5 percent to 6
percent this year and as much as 7 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Ciena was another drag on the Nasdaq on Tuesday. The company, a
maker of telephone equipment, said it would take a charge against
fourth-quarter earnings because a British customer, Iaxis Ltd.,
probably would not be able to pay its bills. Ciena closed at
$216.33, down $13.80 on the day.
</P>
<P>
   But Niagara Mohawk Holdings rose $1.88, to $15.75, after the
National Grid Group, which owns a power transmission network in
England and Wales, agreed to buy the utility owner for $8.9
billion, or about $19 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utility stocks traded well,'' said Jonathan Olesky, head of
block trading at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``There is evidence
the economy might be weaker than we thought it was, so people are
looking for a defensive tilt to their portfolios.''
</P>
</TEXT>
