<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2246 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-MISSISSIPPI-2T     09-05 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MISSISSIPPI-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CORNER OF NEW FRANCE, ALONG THE MISSISSIPPI 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By SHIRLEY CHRISTIAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The French roots of St. Louis slip into focus at unexpected
moments. On a hot afternoon in May, as a radio announcer was
warning rush-hour commuters that traffic was snarled on Interstate
270 going through Chouteau Island in the Mississippi River, I was
reminded of a time 200 years ago when the river was filled with
flat-bottomed boats laden with furs and skins to be exchanged at
trading posts operated by the Chouteau family.
</P>
<P>
   An evening visit to gracious Demun Avenue also carried me back
to that era. Jules Demun and A.P. Chouteau, cousins by marriage,
set St. Louis abuzz in 1817 when they returned from a trade mission
to Santa Fe to tell of being held in chains by the Spanish
authorities. It took an act of Congress and a treaty with Mexico to
gain compensation for their merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these reminders of the past, only one structure has
survived from the era of the vibrant society created by the French
families who began building St. Louis in 1764: The elegantly
restored Basilica of Saint Louis, King, known as the Old Cathedral,
near the Gateway Arch. Still used for worship, the church, with its
clean lines, subdued tones and scattered touches of the ornate, is
a worthy example of early 19th-century French taste.
</P>
<P>
   In an alcove on the right just inside the main doors hangs an
oil painting of St. Louis praying on the eve of his coronation as
King Louis IX. It was a gift from Louis XVIII in 1818. The
fleur-de-lis decorates the altar cloths, and the altar is flanked
by statues of Joan of Arc and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cathedral was not consecrated until 1834 _ there
were three earlier churches on the site _ just 60 miles south of
St. Louis, along both sides of the Mississippi, a truly remarkable
collection of earlier French buildings has survived. The
centerpiece is Ste. Genevieve, Mo., founded about 1735 as a river
depot for lead and salt.
</P>
<P>
   A thriving community of more than 4,000, Ste. Genevieve today is
a vast museum of French Colonial structures, with some worthy later
examples of German and early American styles as well. Many are open
as historic sites, with others still being restored by preservation
groups. Private citizens are also restoring _ and living in _ some
of the sturdy remains of these houses built by the French pioneers.
All of them are a pleasant walk from the Inn St. Gemme Beauvais,
where I stayed on a visit in May.
</P>
<P>
   The Bolduc House, an authentically restored French Creole house,
is a gem. Built in 1785 for Louis Bolduc, a Canadian-born fur
trader and lead-mine owner, it includes only a few pieces of Bolduc
family furniture, including an walnut armoire. But the other
furnishings are authentic French Canadian pieces of the era, based
on an inventory left by Louis Bolduc.
</P>
<P>
   The Bolduc House illustrates the construction basics used by the
early French in the area. It's a large, one-story rectangular
building with two rooms separated by a central hall, surrounded on
four sides by covered galleries or verandas _ a practice the French
adopted from the West Indies. The entire house and outbuildings
were surrounded by a stockade of cedar logs. Although Missouri and
Illinois were less dependent on slave labor than Southern states,
the outbuildings on these properties usually included slave
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The post-on-sill construction used for the Bolduc House involved
sinking tree trunks down to a layer of rock and squaring them off
above ground. For some other structures of the time, hard clay soil
provided a firm base. Walls of vertical oak timbers were set six
inches apart and insulated with some combination of horsehair,
manure, clay and straw. The high-peaked, hip-style roof is
supported by heavy oak trusses in a style reminiscent of medieval
France.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to stand on almost any corner in the 20-some
square blocks that make up historic Ste. Genevieve and feel
yourself at the center of life two centuries ago. Emerging from a
house operated as a historic site, on the other three corners of
the intersection one can see houses of the same era, which are
still private homes or businesses. At one such intersection, Second
and Merchant Streets, private historic homes sit flush to the
sidewalk on three corners; on the fourth is what was once the store
and residence of Felix Valle, now operated as a state historic
site.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1818 _ 33 years later than the Bolduc House and 14
years after Missouri became a United States territory _ the Felix
Valle House (French accents have been lost over the years)
represents a significant shift from the vertical-log construction
methods. Crafted of local stone instead of timbers, the handsome
pale structure also has a second floor, which was unusual in
earlier houses.
</P>
<P>
   What impressed me about the Valle house _ when the guide opened
the door to its commercial side _ was seeing the counters and
shelves where Valle and his father before him had received furs,
skins and lead in exchange for goods from Europe and the East.
Having just researched the Chouteau trading company at St. Louis,
including correspondence between the Chouteaus and the Valles, I
could easily envision Felix Valle and his clients talking about the
price of beaver skins in London, the cholera epidemics that so
often swept through these settlements, or the difficulties of
traders wintering among Indian tribes along the river.
</P>
<P>
   The first Valle in Ste. Genevieve _ Francois _ arrived in the
1740s from French Canada, and many of his descendants became
successful, so it was no surprise to find the family's name
attached to another historic house. The Maison Guibourd-Valle, a
two-story Norman truss house with a wide veranda, was built about
1806 for the Jacques Guibourd family, whose fortunes ran low after
three generations. In 1931, the house was sold to Jules Felix
Valle, one of the many descendants of Francois. Jules Felix had
become wealthy as a stockbroker in St. Louis and married a
beautiful showgirl, Anna Marie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
