<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2247 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NURSINGHHOMES-06-COX     09-05 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSINGHHOMES-06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GAO DOUBTS NEED FOR HIGHER FEES FOR NURSING HOMES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's ailing nursing home industry pressed
for a booster shot of Medicare funds Tuesday, even as federal
overseers told the Senate Special Committee on Aging that the
remedy is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   Current rates are ``likely to provide sufficient and in some
cases even generous compensation'' by Medicare to nursing homes,
said Laura A. Dummit, a health care cost expert with the U.S.
General Accounting Office (GAO) told the Senate Special Committee
on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, returning for year-end budget work, is considering
adding as much as $2 billion for Medicare services in nursing homes
to respond to a crisis that has sent 10 percent of facilities,
chiefly large chains, into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Industry defenders told the hearing that federal cutbacks in
Medicare two years ago set up the collapse. Charles H. Roadman II,
president of the American Health Care Association, which represents
the chains, said the reductions were $15.8 billion more over seven
years than Congress had intended.
</P>
<P>
   He brought a map showing the bankrupt facilities as red dots
across the country and said that nursing homes were caught in a
``squeeze'' by federal budget cuts, inconsistent state regulators
and private lawsuits alleging abuse and mistreatment of residents.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement submitted to the Senate committee,
Roadman was even more pointed, warning of ``the real potential for
absolute collapse that will put at risk care for all (skilled
nursing home) patients.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1.5 million Americans are served by nursing homes. About
half the costs are paid by Medicaid, about 17 percent is paid by
Medicare, and the rest is paid by private insurance or individuals.
</P>
<P>
   During the high-flying years of the mid 1990s, many of the
for-profit nursing homes aggressively expanded their services and
sought more patients under Medicare, whose loose rules provided
almost unlimited payments for therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare costs soared by 25 percent a year from 1990 to 1998,
and investigations uncovered massive waste, including unneeded
services, and fraud before the payment system was overhauled. With
the end of the prospects for huge profits and heavily in debt from
acquisitions, five of the 10 biggest nursing homes filed for
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Committee chairman Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, offered
little sympathy to the failed companies. ``Most nursing homes
appear to be able to operate under the new system,'' he told the
hearing, which was called to discuss the causes for the
bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, R-La., laid the problem at the failed efforts
by the government to ``micro manage'' the health industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this drives me crazy,'' Breaux said. He then asked
Roadman: ``How could an industry not make it with a 25 percent
(Medicare) increase every year?''
</P>
<P>
   The nursing home trade group president, speechless for several
moments, responded that Medicare comprised only ``9 percent of the
partient days and 17 percent of the revenue'' for the facilities
and urged the senator to look at the other problems, such as
underfunding for Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the financial problems, a Clinton administration
official offered assurance that bankrupt nursing homes are not
falling down in their care.
</P>
<P>
   States have been required to inspect those in bankruptcy, said
Steve Pelovitz, who is overseeing the failing businesses for the
Health Care Financing Administration. He said they have found ``no
systemic problems with those actually operating in bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassley, who has set a hearing for later this month on problems
in the nationwide inspection system, said after the hearing that
he, nonetheless, was satisfied that HCFA is watching the bankrupt
homes. ``Their heart is in the right place,'' Grassley said of the
federal overseers.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said that although the nursing home chains ``gambled''
on getting ever higher government fees and lost, he would back an
increase for Medicare later this month ``to protect the residents''
of nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   julia malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
