<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-MISSISSIPPI-2N     09-05 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MISSISSIPPI-2NDTAKE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Anna Marie.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They moved to Ste. Genevieve and devoted their time and money to
restoring and furnishing the old house. They installed heat,
running water and electricity. After Jules Felix died in 1949, Anna
Marie _ something of an outcast in the genteel town _ traveled and
shopped the world until her own death in 1971. She filled the
house, just a good-size cottage by today's suburban standards, with
museum quality Louis XV, Louis XVI and French Empire pieces, as
well as Venetian mirrors, Queen Anne chests, a 1790 crystal
chandelier and screens from China. She put jade plates around the
light switches and hung portraits of her husband's ancestors on the
walls.
</P>
<P>
   It's all there today, a stunning surprise on a quiet corner of a
quiet river town.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, it was a return to a more austere setting when
I followed the signs through Ste. Genevieve to the ferry and
crossed the Mississippi to Illinois, continued to Bluff Road and
drove south to the Fort Kaskaskia Historic Site. The town of
Kaskaskia (pronounced kass-KASS-kee-ah) was the first capital of
Illinois after statehood in 1818. It was a trading partner of St.
Louis and Ste. Genevieve until it was wiped out by a series of
floods in the late 1800s, and the town and fort are remembered with
the historic site, including a park and relocated cemetery, on
rolling hills overlooking the Mississippi and Kaskaskia Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is the handsomely restored home of Pierre Menard,
surrounded by rolling green lawns, gardens and fields. Finished in
1802, it survived the floods because it was on higher ground just
outside Kaskaskia.
</P>
<P>
   Menard, a trader and farmer, was one of the richest and most
appreciated men in French Illinois. A museum on the lower level,
below the floor with the family portraits and period furniture,
displays some remnants of his comfortable life _ like his pocket
watch and a white satin dancing slipper that belonged to one of his
daughters. A woolen carpet on display was woven for the 1825 visit
of the Marquis de Lafayette, when Pierre Menard was seated next to
him at a banquet at Sweet's Hotel in Kaskaskia.
</P>
<P>
   Menard's large family left many footprints. Not the least of
them belonged to a daughter, Therese Berenice, who went out from
Kaskaskia to marry a Chouteau and, with him, found the trading post
that eventually became Kansas City, Mo. Living to nearly 90, she
created her own legends of style and substance _ dragging
loose-living trappers and hunters into the church she built and
using her Paris gowns as shrouds to bury cholera victims.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the Menard home, I drove north about 15 miles to Fort de
Chartres, which rises out of farm fields like an ancient mirage
near Prairie du Rocher. This town's name brought to mind that the
French gave us the name we apply to the vast lands stretching from
Ohio to the Rockies _ the prairies.
</P>
<P>
   The fort was the center of French authority, both civilian and
military, in the mid-Mississippi Valley before the Illinois side of
the river passed first to England and later to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Today's massive limestone fort is mostly a reconstruction _
having been rebuilt from the 1920s on _ of a fort put up by the
French in the 1750s to replace a wooden stockade. The only original
building is the powder magazine _ there are also a few original
foundations _ but the stone walls and parapets seem authentic.
</P>
<P>
   While Civil War re-enactments are the rage in many parts of the
country, I discovered that the French and Indian War (1754-63) also
draws huge crowds of re-enactors to Fort de Chartres. On the day I
visited, a group of schoolchildren was acting out a battle for
teachers and parents manning video cameras. A teacher told her
charges that the English had proved their general ignorance of
frontier life by wearing red, a color that she said was
particularly distasteful to the Indians, thereby strengthening
their inclinations to sympathize with the blue-coated French.
</P>
<P>
   From her spin on the conflict, you would never know who lost.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling when the French ruled the Mississippi
</P>
<P>
   Ste. Genevieve, Mo., is about 60 miles south of St. Louis on
Interstate 55.
</P>
<P>
   The Great River Road Interpretive Center, at Market and Main
Streets, Ste. Genevieve, (800) 373-7007, offers information,
including maps and brochures of historic sites associated with the
French settlers in both Missouri and Illinois. It is open daily 9
a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   What to See
</P>
<P>
   Bolduc House, Main Street between Market and South Gabouri
Streets, Ste. Genevieve, dates to 1785. Open daily April 1 to Nov.
1, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. except 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Sunday. Admission:
$4, $2 for students through high school; (573) 883-3105.
</P>
<P>
   The two-story stone Felix Valle House, Second and Merchant
Streets, Ste. Genevieve, was built in 1818. Open daily 10 a.m. to 4
p.m., except noon to 5 p.m. Sunday. Admission: $2, $1.25 ages 6 to
12; (573) 883-7102.
</P>
<P>
   The Maison Guibourd-Valle, is at Fourth and Merchant Streets,
Ste. Genevieve. Open daily 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $3, $2 for
students; (573) 883-7544.
</P>
<P>
   The Pierre Menard Home, 4230 Kaskaskia St., Ellis Grove, Ill.,
includes a museum. Hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily March through
October, and 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. November to February. Suggested
donation: $2, $1 ages 17 and under; (618) 859-3031.
</P>
<P>
   Fort de Chartres State Historic Site, a reconstruction of a
1750s French fort, at 1350 State Route 155, Prairie du Rocher,
Ill., is open daily 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., except winter holidays; (618)
284-7230.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Cathedral, 209 Walnut St., St. Louis, Mo. The 1834
church's sanctuary is open daily 6:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.; the museum is
open 10 a.m. to 3:45 p.m.; (314) 231-3250.
</P>
<P>
   Places to Stay
</P>
<P>
   I stayed at the Inn St. Gemme Beauvais, an 1848 mansion at 78
North Main St., Ste. Genevieve, (800) 818-5744, fax (573) 883-3899.
The main inn has nine suites with a mix of antiques, reproductions
and things from someone's attic, for $89 to $179 a night; there are
four similar suites with whirlpool baths in an 1850 house across
the street for $175 or $185; full breakfast is included.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of other inns in Ste. Genevieve. The
Federal-style Southern Hotel, 146 South Third St., (800) 275-1412,
fax (573) 883-9612, has eight guest rooms, costing $88 to $138,
with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The Main Street Inn, 221 North Main St., (800) 918-9199, fax
(573) 883-9911, also has eight rooms, for $85 to $125, with full
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   I had a satisfying meal of deep-fried shrimp and a huge piece of
coconut cream pie at the Anvil Saloon, at Third Street on the
Square, (573) 883-7323, where the bar dates from 1855. Dinner for
two with wine runs about $45.
</P>
<P>
   I was disappointed not to find a good French restaurant in Ste.
Genevieve. For a fine French dinner, it was back to St. Louis and
the Cafe de France, 410 Olive St., (314) 231-2204, just five blocks
from the Old Cathedral. The menu features traditional French dishes
_ chateaubriand, pates, escargot. Dinner for four with wine came to
about $200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
