<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.06.00
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expect hot holiday online sales _ $19.5 billion
</P>
<P>
   GoTo.com pays $50 million for AOL's attention
</P>
<P>
   Weather _ on the Palm in your hand
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone and Microsoft make Internet pact
</P>
<P>
   PaperExchange yanks initial public offering
</P>
<P>
   HOT HOLIDAY$: Online holiday sales should reach $19.5 billion
this year, technology research firm Gartner Group said Tuesday.
That's an 85 percent increase over last year, when holiday Internet
sales reached $10.5 billion and nearly undid many online retailers
overwhelmed by the crush of first-time buyers. Undaunted, many of
those e-tailers have learned from their mistakes, spending much of
the year improving what happens after the customer clicks the
``buy'' button. Smart move: By the end of this year, e-business
research firm Forrester Research predicts the number of new online
shoppers should hit 11 million.
</P>
<P>
   MORE SEARCHING ON AOL: GoTo.com Inc., a Web search engine that
charges for placement in its listings, said Tuesday it will pay
America Online Inc. $50 million to be featured on the Internet
service provider's Web sites. Searches on AOL.com, Netscape
Netcenter and AOL proprietary sites will return two or three links
from GoTo.com alongside results from AOL's own search engine. Links
supplied by GoTo.com's will be marked as ``sponsored links.''
Companies wishing to be listed on GoTo.com's search engine can
place bids on how much they want to pay for each visitor. The
company with the highest bid is listed first in the search results,
and pays GoTo.com for each click on the link. This is the latest of
several deals AOL has made with Internet companies who want to
drive traffic to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   www.goto.com
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER ON YOUR PALM: Coming soon to your Palm VIIx _ the
Weather Channel. The company based in suburban Atlanta will give
Palm users immediate access to current weather, seven-day forecasts
and a unique feature _ ``My Weather'' _ that identifies the
customer's geographic location by the nearest cell tower and
automatically presents the weather for that tower's ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE, MICROSOFT GO WIRELESS: The world's largest mobile
phone company plans to team with Microsoft Corp. to develop
wireless Internet services. Vodafone Group PLC of Great Britain
said consumers will use familiar Microsoft Outlook functions to
send and receive e-mail from a range of mobile devices, as well as
access Microsoft Exchange-based calendar, contacts and personalized
Web content. Vodafone and rival British Telecommunications PLC, the
largest phone company in the United Kingdom, are in the race to
develop ways of accessing the Internet from mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   NO IPO FOR PAPEREXCHANGE: PaperExchange.com withdrew its initial
public offering for up to $115 million of common stock, citing
market conditions. The Boston-based company is a
business-to-business marketplace that enables buyers and sellers in
the pulp and paper industry to do business on the Internet. The
firm originally filed the IPO with the Securities and Exchange
Commission on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data
</P>
