<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2253 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-RELATIONAL-ARCHITECHT     09-05 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELATIONAL-ARCHITECHTURE- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN THAT COAXES BUILDINGS OUT OF THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
 $ ADV10-NYT  (Attn: Calif., Md.) 
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The term ``contextual'' having become debased by those who
fundamentally despise the whole idea of architecture, the time has
come to speak of ``relational'' design _ buildings that interact
with their surroundings in full dimension instead of dumbly
mimicking the scale and form of their next-door neighbors. We
should think of architecture as a supremely interactive art _ a
participatory medium that transforms configurations of scale,
dimension, shape, proximity, space, time, energy, cultural meaning,
economic value and land use.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, there will be many opportunities to enrich
the vocabulary for talking about architecture in relational terms.
Perhaps the most spirited of these projects is the continuing
development of SPARCity _ Eric Owen Moss' name for the
discontinuous loop of urban development he has been designing for
Culver City, Calif.. (The project is named for the air rights over
the former tracks of a Southern Pacific freight line).
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, Moss, supported by two enlightened clients,
Frederick and Laurie Smith, has been converting abandoned factory
buildings for use by firms specializing in graphic design,
advertising, film production and other post-industrial businesses.
This month, SPARCity reaches critical mass with the completion of
the Stealth Building, as it has become known, the ground-hugging
centerpiece of a newly redeveloped Culver City block. The building
vaguely recalls the bomber's tapered horizontal profile.This is the
authentic New Urbanism _ the productive future of the tattered
industrial center.
</P>
<P>
   The Tang Teaching Museum and Art Gallery at Skidmore College in
Saratoga Springs, N.Y., is the first project in the Northeast by
Antoine Predock, the architectural shaman of the American
Southwest. Designed to foster crossdisciplinary experiments in the
arts, the Tang is finished in stone, metal and concrete, and is
surrounded by a circle of white pines. Two giant staircases
converge to form a symbolic crossroads of culture and nature. Not
since the glory days of the Beaux-Arts have we seen such an
extravagant representation of the ascent to Parnassus.
</P>
<P>
   Since no relationship matters more than the unstable links
between older urban centers and the suburbs encircling them, the
most important event this season will be the presidential campaign.
Between now and November, we will find out whether either candidate
has anything substantial to say on urban policy. The past eight
years have seen declining crime rates and increased participation
from the private sector in urban life. But the Clinton
administration wasted the opportunity to invest in housing,
transportation and public space, or to revitalize the urban core as
an economic engine.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere have the shortcomings of urban policy been clearer than
in Baltimore, a city that has been at the forefront of innovation
for three decades. Despite urban homesteading, the Harborside
festival marketplace, the Camden Yards ball park and other
initiatives undertaken by the public and private spheres, Baltimore
continues to epitomize the city as a permanent invalid of modern
life. The Student Arts Center, designed by Tod Williams and Billie
Tsien for Johns Hopkins University, adds a new layer to the city's
cultural mix. Intended to bring art into an environment dedicated
to science, the three-winged building creates a new campus
landscape with courtyards, paths and views.
</P>
<P>
   Things are really cooking this year for Zaha Hadid. Her most
ambitious built work to date will open in December. A tramway
station and car park in the French city of Strasbourg, the project
is an infrastructural intervention designed to reduce car traffic
in the central district. Like Peter Eisenman's design for the
Staten Island ferry terminal, Hadid's forms are derived from the
motion patterns of different transportation modes. And what, by the
way, is the status of Eisenman's fine plan?
</P>
<P>
   Not one of these forthcoming projects is ``appropriate.'' Isn't
that great? Like ``contextual,'' the word ``appropriate'' has
ceased to be constructive. Buildings can be good, bad, mediocre or
pointless. But ``appropriateness'' is a useless gauge of
architectural value. Rather, it has become equivalent to the notion
of progress in the postwar decades. It represents the evasion of
responsibility for personal preference. ``Don't hold me
accountable. History made me do it. Peer pressure made me do it.''
Mediocrity loves company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
