u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT     09-05 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS VOTE ON CHINA TRADE BILL NEARS, SENATE LOOKS TO SMOOTH ITS
PASSAGE
</HEADLINE>
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As senators resumed debate on a major bill
establishing permanent trade relations with China, the Senate
majority leader, Trent Lott, said on Tuesday that he would try to
schedule a final vote by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has delayed consideration of the bill since the House
approved it in May, drawing criticism from Democrats that Lott was
trying to use one of President Clinton's top remaining legislative
priorities as political leverage in the last days of the
congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   But with the pro-Republican business community clamoring for
results on a bill that would give a boon to American farmers and
corporations, the foot-dragging is ending. Senators will debate 7
to 10 amendments this week and next before voting on the measure,
which would end Congress' annual review of China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the House, where supporters eked out a victory,
passage in the Senate is all but assured. About 70 senators are
expected to vote for the measure. But with only about five weeks
left before lawmakers leave for the year, supporters say they need
a clean bill, free from amendments that would force the measure
back to the House for a second vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bluntly, a vote to amend is a vote to kill this bill and, with
it, any chance that U.S. workers, farmers and businesses will
benefit,'' said Sen. William V. Roth Jr., (R-Del.) who heads the
Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest potential obstacle facing the bill is a measure
sponsored by Sens. Fred Thompson (R-Tenn.) and Robert Torricelli
(D-N.J.).
</P>
<P>
   Their measure, which Thompson said could be offered as an
amendment next week, would require the administration to monitor
China's record on the spread of nuclear, chemical and missile
proliferation. It would impose sanctions on China if there is
evidence of exports of certain type of prohibited weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has sought to modify the bill in response to
administration criticisms that the measure would hurt American
businesses, infringe on the president's authority and focus too
narrowly on China.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enough senators who feel very strongly that they do
not want to have to go through the House consideration again,''
Lott said on Tuesday. ``On the other hand, China is still doing
some very unsettling things. He's right on the substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Implicitly acknowledging he may not have the votes, Thompson
said that if his measure failed, he was considering a second
amendment that would simply condemn countries that traffic in
nuclear, chemical or missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the
Foreign Relations Committee, said few senators want to vote on
anything that could doom the trade bill. ``There are an awful lot
of Republicans and some Democrats who would like to vote for
Thompson, but they don't want to be responsible for killing this,''
Biden said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's action will overlap with President Clinton's
scheduled meeting on Friday with President Jiang Zemin of China at
the United Nations summit meeting in New York. The White House will
prepare Clinton to telephone senators on specific amendments this
week and next, if necessary, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast to Clinton's fiery rhetoric on campaign issues
like education, health care and taxes, he and his top aides are
deliberately keeping a low profile on the China bill to avoid
inflaming Republican critics.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor Tuesay, friends and foes of the trade bill
squared off in the first of several days of debate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, (R-N.C.) a North Carolina Republican who heads
the Foreign Relations Committee and opposes the trade measure, said
the United States should not reward a Beijing government that
intimidates its neighbors, sells sophisticated weapons to America's
enemies and persecutes its own people for their religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters like Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-N.Y.) warned
that the ``potential for estrangement and worse'' with China is
still real.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan for the first time suggested that racism might underlie
some of the bill's opposition: ``There is a long and rueful history
in the United States of our racial antagonism to Chinese emigration
to this country, which now appears as an antagonism to the arrival
of Chinese goods.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
