<P>
   &QR;  Sorry, ``Survivor'': This Pacific isle has the real hold on TV
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To: Spouse. From: Spouse. Re: Looks like we're through
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Soap ``4 O'Clock 4Play'' adds minute sizzle to the Web
</P>
<P>
   E-MERGING NATION: Curious about why the site formerly known as
www.emmys.org has a new URL on the eve of THE big show? Thanks the
island nation of Tuvalu, you can now slip to _ appropriately enough
_ www.emmys.tv to get an advance look at Sunday's event (8 p.m. on
ABC). As for the South Pacific island nation: It is using some of
the money it is making from licensing its country code Internet
address to California's dotTV for $50 million to join the United
Nations on Tuesday. DotTV arranged to pay the island for the right
to serve as the exclusive worldwide source for Web addresses ending
in .tv. The island's government also is spending the $18 million on
infrastructure improvements, medical personnel and _ yes _ Internet
connections.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER SPLIT: You've heard of marriages that start from a simple
e-mail or chat-room conversation, so why not use the Web for the
flipside: d-i-v-o-r-c-e? A new Internet-based business hopes to
make life easier for people considering or going through divorce by
providing anonymous online access to legal, psychological and
financial advice. Softsplit.com also plans to help children of
divorce through its Softsplit Kids portal, a nonprofit Web site
that has age-specific content. Occasional online chats also are
available. The company notes that it ``does not promote divorce.''
The mission: To help people ``navigate their way through the
complex issues associated with divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   www.softsplit.com
</P>
<P>
   60-SECOND SOAP: Who says soap operas move too slowly? Coming
Oct. 4: ``4 O'clock 4Play,'' a streaming video Internet soap opera
that will be on every day. For one minute. The target audience
includes soap fans too busy to sit down and watch a serial for an
hour each day and people logged onto computers at work. The show's
developers say the short Internet format significantly will reduce
the amount of time needed for advance production, allowing them to
include timely details and developments. Onetime ABC Director of
Daytime Programs Donna Sajewski has signed on to write and produce
``4play.'' _ Jill Vejnoska
</P>
