<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2272 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-BACKSTAGE06-CO     09-05 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BACKSTAGE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hip-hop film mostly fury, little insight
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's truth to the title ``Backstage.'' The new
behind-the-scenes film about the 1999 Hard Knocks Life tour is less
a documentary than a home movie, intercutting stage-show clips with
endless bad-boy behavior. We watch the hip-hop stars playing dice,
smoking endless blunts and getting lap-danced by groupies happy to
take their tops off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're gonna be a star,'' one rapper tells one breast-baring
girl, shortly before coercing her into a bathroom stall for some
quick sex.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, ``Backstage'' doesn't pull any punches. It never
tries to show its rapping crews as misunderstood artists. As Kevin
Liles, president of Def Jam Records, puts it, ``It's all about
getting the (expletive) money.''
</P>
<P>
   The musicians make no bones about their rough backgrounds,
including DMX, who ``epitomizes the have-nots,'' in the words of
one colleague. Many of the guys came to rap after years of dealing
drugs. Their goal is to get the multimillion-dollar home, a garage
full of Bentleys, security for their families ... and try to not
wind up a statistic, like slain rappers Tupac Shakur and the
Notorious B.I.G.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, first-time feature director Chris Fiore doesn't
try to probe his subjects' backgrounds or put the tour into the
larger context of hip-hop history.
</P>
<P>
   There is a no-rules circus atmosphere to the tour as it winds
across the country, starting with the initial attention from
journalists who wonder how so many rappers packed into three buses
can keep their egos (and anger) in check. In the words of DJ
Scratch, ``Everybody's waiting for something bad to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing really does in ``Backstage,'' except for a tiff between
Damon Dash, co-founder of Roc-a-Fella Records, and Liles. That
happens when Liles hands out Def Jam jackets, and Dash berates him
for making it seem that the tour is solely fronted by his record
company. Dash gets more screen time than some of the stars, who
include Jay-Z, Method Man and Beanie Siegel. The fact that he's the
movie's producer lends it the whiff of a vanity production, and
sometimes ``Backstage'' seems like nothing more than a long
commercial for the musicians it features.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backstage''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   A hip-hop documentary. Rated R for strong language, nudity and
drug content. 1 hour, 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A high-energy but incomplete backstage documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
