<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-DRUGS-COMPARE-AR     09-05 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DRUGS-COMPARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BETS THE ELDERLY FEAR THE GOVERNMENT MORE THAN THEIR HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUSH-DRUGS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT PEAR and ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush's proposal to redesign Medicare
and offer drug benefits to the elderly puts him squarely in line
with his party's drive to reshape the program by reducing the role
of government, increasing the role of insurance companies and
giving elderly people more choices.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is also meant to serve an important political
purpose: to fend off attacks by Democrats who contend that Bush has
no true commitment to elderly people squeezed by rising drug costs.
Elderly Americans, long a key part of the Democratic coalition, are
considered a critical swing vote this year.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Democrats, Vice President Al Gore sees Medicare as one
of the greatest achievements of American social policy, and
basically approves of the course it has followed since its creation
35 years ago. Bush, by contrast, sees Medicare as a prime example
of government regulation run wild.
</P>
<P>
   With his proposal, which he outlined in a speech Tuesday in
Pennsylvania, Bush has set the stage for a reprise of the health
care battles of the last decade, revolving around a fundamental
question: Do voters fear the government or the insurance industry
more?
</P>
<P>
   The Bush and Gore proposals would both offer some assistance
with drug costs to all beneficiaries, but by no means would they
relieve the elderly of the total cost.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says that under his plan, the government will pay all
pharmaceutical costs after a beneficiary spends $4,000
out-of-pocket on drugs in a year. Bush says that under his
proposal, the government will pick up all costs after a beneficiary
spends $6,000 on health care of all types.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would pump much more money into Medicare and drug benefits
for the elderly in the coming decade. But Bush's proposal would
cost far more than a bill passed by the House in June to offer drug
coverage to Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says his plan would offer assistance more quickly because
he would offer money to the states _ $12 billion a year for four
years _ to provide immediate assistance to people with low incomes.
Twenty-three states, including New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut, have programs to provide such assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, described the
difference this way: ``Governor Bush would provide seniors with
options and choices. Vice President Gore focuses on a
one-size-fits-all solution to the need for drug benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human services,
insisted that the uniformity of premiums and benefits under the
Gore plan was a virtue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Bush plan, there would be wide variations across the
country,'' said Shalala, serving as spokeswoman for the Gore
campaign. ``It simply is not a Medicare benefit. It's not available
to everyone in every part of country at the same price.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Shalala argued, ``George Bush suggests seniors have a
big problem with the bureaucracy of the Health Care Financing
Administration,'' the agency that runs Medicare. ``What they really
have a problem with is the bureaucracy of HMOs.''
</P>
<P>
   A summary of Bush's plan, issued by his campaign headquarters,
indicates that drug benefits would be offered to Medicare
recipients in the original fee-for-service program, as well as to
those in HMOs. All health insurers in Medicare, including
government-sponsored plans, ``will have to offer an expanded
benefit package, including outpatient prescription drug coverage,''
the document says.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer, the spokesman for Bush, said: ``Under Governor Bush's
proposal, the existing standard Medicare benefit package would be
expanded for the first time to provide prescription drugs for those
who remain in the fee-for-service program. You would not have to
leave Medicare to get prescription drug benefits. But you would be
free to shop around, choose and compare.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan was praised by insurance industry executives.
Charles N. Kahn III, president of the Health Insurance Association
of America, said, ``I think it's a serious proposal that will help
make prescription drugs more affordable for those most in need.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen M. Ignagni, president of the American Association of
Health Plans, which represents health maintenance organizations,
said her industry could ``play a role, definitely, in delivering
this benefit,'' though it needed to be paid more by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates and Democrats were just as quick to
criticize. Ronald F. Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a
consumer advocacy group, said the record of HMOs and other private
insurers in delivering drug coverage to the elderly was ``at best
spotty.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the broader market-oriented changes contemplated by Bush,
Pollack said, ``We fear that this would wither away the
fee-for-service system that five out of six seniors depend on
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bush's plan achieves its political purpose may depend
less on its specific details than on how skillfully he marshals
facts, figures and arguments in support of it _ both in televised
debates and his campaign advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In drafting his proposal, Bush drew heavily on ideas developed
by a federal advisory commission headed by Sen. John B. Breaux,
D-La., and Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to use private industry, including insurance
companies and HMOs, to deliver drug benefits and other medical
services to the elderly. But the government would still pay most of
the costs, and it would supervise insurers, approving or
disapproving all plans. In essence, it envisions a vast expansion
of the role of HMOs, which now provide coverage to 6.2 million of
the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's approach relies more on the traditional Medicare program
to deliver drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates agree that drug benefits should be voluntary
_ an option available for an extra charge. Under Bush's proposal,
the government would pay at least 25 percent of the cost of
premiums for drug coverage, even for the most affluent
beneficiaries. Under Gore's proposal, the government would pay at
least 50 percent of the premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The prescription drug issue looms large politically because it
is a top concern of a critical constituency _ the elderly, and the
generation aging just behind them. Republican strategists said
Tuesday that Bush's proposal had fundamentally changed the debate,
which had taken its toll in recent weeks on his support among older
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Female seniors will be critical to this election,'' said Linda
DiVall, a Republican pollster. ``Bush has been performing well with
them, but he's fallen off in the last couple of weeks. I think this
plan will allow him to be competitive with them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill McInturff, a Republican pollster who also works for the
pharmaceutical industry, said: ``Now, there's a legitimate debate
about which plan is better. That's a very different debate, with
significant merits on the side of what Governor Bush has
introduced.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats argued that Bush's plan had huge vulnerabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors are looking for the reassurance of guaranteed coverage
under a Medicare system they fundamentally trust,'' said Geoff
Garin, a Democratic pollster. The private sector marketplace that
Bush envisions is ``an abstraction and an unknown quantity that
provides no comfort or reassurance to seniors,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
