<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYSCOUT0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents to ask school board to ban Scout activities
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Years ago Carole Benowitz thought she
had a real Scouting family _ she was a Cub Scout troop leader, her
father had a coveted Silver Beaver Scouting award, and her son was
a Scout.
</P>
<P>
   Her gay son.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Benowitz and others will ask the Palm Beach County
School Board to prohibit Boy Scouts from using schools for
recruitment and meetings because the Scouts exclude gays from their
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using public property to discriminate, and this should
not be allowed,'' said Benowitz, Gulf Coast coordinator for PFLAG,
an organization of parents of gay and lesbian children. ``Gay kids
should have the same rights as other children.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely school board members will take any action at this
time, but principals should be told they can't ``endorse'' the Boy
Scouts, said Cynthia Prettyman, general counsel for the school
district. This year's U.S. Supreme Court decision allowing the Boy
Scouts to exclude gays basically permits them to discriminate
against gay students and teachers _ and that violates the
district's own nondiscrimination policies, Prettyman said.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean the Boy Scouts can't use the schools, but the
troops should be charged the regular $10-an-hour rental fee, she
said. ``We can't appear to be supporting them,'' she said. ``If we
do, we're violating a policy that the school board adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   Many principals waive rental fees for the Scouts because they
provide after-school activities for their students, said interim
schools Superintendent Ben Marlin. Just last week, the Boy Scouts
signed up 2,562 new Scouts during an annual ``School Night for
Scouting'' at more than 80 elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a group of people who do a lot of good stuff,'' said
Marlin of the Scouts. ``The question is: Should they be charged?''
</P>
<P>
   School board member Paulette Burdick said Tuesday she wants the
district to stop training teachers in the use of a character
education curriculum that she believes was written with the help of
Boy Scouts. But Burdick said she wouldn't kick Scouts out entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are aspects that I don't philosophically agree with, but
they are providing programs for our children,'' she noted. ``I
would hope Boy Scouts of America would work with communities and
school districts to change. I think there's enough community
pressure right now to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Directors of the United Way of Palm Beach County also are
considering how they will deal with the agency's $118,000
contribution to the Boy Scouts, as is the Palm Beach Community
Chest/United Way for its $62,000 allocation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: maryellenflannery(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
