<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GORE0906-COX     09-05 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore previews wide-ranging economic plan
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    and Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio - Democrat Al Gore previewed a wide-ranging
economic plan Tuesday aimed at keeping America's good times rolling
and making sure the prosperity touches those who have been left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's plan, which he said he would implement if
elected president, calls for:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Retiring the $5.6 trillion national debt by 2012 by balancing
the federal budget each year and using the annual surplus to reduce
debt accumulated over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Putting annual Social Security and Medicare budget surpluses
in ``lock boxes,'' assuring that there would be enough money to
keep Social Security solvent for 50 years and Medicare afloat for
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Doubling the number of American families with savings of
$50,000 or more by offering them ``retirement plus'' savings
accounts, in addition to Social Security, in which the federal
government would match personal savings with tax credits. The tax
incentives would be greatest for families with annual incomes below
$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Before Gore even unveiled his plan, U.S. Rep. John Kasich,
R-Westerville, House Budget Committee chairman, was tearing it
apart on behalf of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   The dueling presentations, held at nearby locations in downtown
Columbus, highlighted a frantic week of Ohio presidential
campaigning that emphasize the importance both sides place on the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will be at Cleveland State University today to lay out his
economic plan in detail. Tuesday night, after arriving in
Cleveland, he campaigned briefly with fans on their way to Jacobs
Field for the Indians game. Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., Gore's
vice presidential running mate, was in Toledo on Monday. Bush is
expected in the Dayton area Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No state is more important than Ohio,'' Gore said in his
meeting with reporters from Ohio newspapers with whom he previewed
his economic plan.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting followed Gore's appearance at a downtown Columbus
technology marketing company housed in a former plow factory that
was aimed at emphasizing his commitment to technology as an
economic development tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement I've felt in this room is what we need to make
our economy what it needs to be,'' Gore, accompanied by former U.S.
Sen. John Glenn, told several hundred employees and guests gathered
in the fourth floor of the brick building.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that retiring the national debt will mean ``lower
interest rates'' and ``stronger economic growth.'' He faulted Bush
for not setting a timetable for retiring the debt.
</P>
<P>
   He also contrasted his ``lock box'' plans for the Social
Security and Medicare surpluses with what he said was Bush's plan.
The Texas governor's proposed across-the-board tax cuts would take
``billions'' of dollars from Medicare, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office has projected a $2.2 trillion
budget surplus over the next 10 years, including $360 billion in
Medicare surpluses and a separate, additional $2.3 trillion Social
Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that his ``retirement plus'' savings plans are in
addition to Social Security, in contrast to Bush's plan, which
calls for allowing younger workers to invest part of their Social
Security savings in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that for families with incomes below $30,000, the
federal government would match savings of $500 with a tax credit of
$1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's an offer you can't refuse,'' said Gore, dressed for
the high-tech crowd in a black and white checked coat, knit shirt
opened at the collar and khaki pants.
</P>
<P>
   Families earning between $30,000 and $60,000 would get a $1 tax
credit for each dollar saved, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put $1,000 in a savings account, the federal government
will match it one for one with another $1,000 (tax credit),'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, coming off his Labor Day weekend campaign marathon,
misspoke during the meeting about the incentives the federal
government would provide to families with incomes above $60,000. He
said families in that wage bracket who put $500 in a savings
account would get a $1,500 tax credit _ the same as the low-income
families.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore aides corrected the information and said families
earning more than $60,000 would get only a $500 tax credit to match
savings of $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   In amounted to what was a GOP response, Kasich, considered a
leading force in balancing the federal budget, blasted Gore for
``employing an amazing tactic by buying people's votes with their
own money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do with the surplus? Gore wants to spend it. We
want to use it for a broad-based tax cut and give some back to the
people,'' Kasich said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Gore's plan would only empower Washington lobbyists
and bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, however, that he really wants to empower Americans
who have been left out of the economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not satisfied. We need to do much better. How do we do
better? ... The big limiting factor today is job training and
education. I think we need to do a much better job of getting
skills made available to people who need them,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Ned Hill of Cleveland State University said Gore's
economic plan could work but cautioned that it is based on
optimistic assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It essentially assumes there will be no real increase in
government spending which, of course, Congress is paying no
attention to lately,'' said Hill, senior research fellow at the
university's Urban Center.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan also ``assumes there is going to be no recession. It
assumes welfare reform continues on its path,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hill said, Gore has come up with a proposal that ``brings
the numbers together in a coherent whole. Bush hasn't done that
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Email: williamhershey(at)coxohio.com or
mikewagner(at)coxohio.com
</P>
