u w BC-CONGRESS-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      09-05 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL DEMOCRATS GO ON THE OFFENSIVE IN PUSHING THEIR
AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story was eliminated earlier, but is now restored) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats took the offensive Tuesday and said they
would remain on Capitol Hill as long as necessary this year to push
their agenda, from overhauling managed care to bumping up the
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are we going to hold the bar high enough, we're also
going to ensure that we have the time it takes to address these
issues,'' Sen. Tom Daschle, the Democratic leader, warned shortly
after a meeting with President Clinton at the White House. ``And
we're in no hurry to go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Senate Republican leaders were drawing their
own line in the sand, saying they would not approve a rise in the
minimum wage without accompanying tax cuts for small businesses and
assuring that a Democratic bill to overhaul managed health care
would go nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   And in a turnaround, Senate Republican leaders also pushed a
revised bill on prescription drugs, written by Sen. William V. Roth
Jr. of Delaware, that had gained little traction in July, a sign
both of the issue's potency among voters and of perceptions that
Roth is vulnerable in his campaign for re-election. The legislation
would immediately make drugs more affordable for the low-income
elderly, independently of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats propose a measure to help all of the elderly pay some
of the costs of prescription drug coverage. House Republicans have
already passed their own separate bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do it in such a way that it doesn't cause major
problems for Medicare,'' said Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader.
``The president wants to subsidize it for everybody. And he wants
to do it, and Al Gore wants to do it, without any Medicare changes.
That is a major problem. That's like putting more passengers on the
Titanic as it's headed down.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Daschle, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt and other
Democrats met Tuesday at the White House to discuss strategy for
closing out the congressional session before the November election.
Congress is officially scheduled to break on Oct. 5, a target date
that is likely to come and go.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the strategy appears simple: Push the Democratic
agenda, criticize Republican tax cuts as too expensive and hold the
Republicans' feet to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said Democrats were unlikely to embrace Roth's
prescription drug bill. ``We are unwilling to accept a bill that
does not meet at least the minimum criteria,'' he said. ``We've
said it had to be universal.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said he would push for another vote on a bill to overhaul
managed care that Democrats favor and that has already passed the
House. The bill could pass the Senate this time around, with the
arrival of Sen. Zell Miller, D-Ga., who replaced the late Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   As for minimum wage, Daschle expressed reservations Tuesday
about a Republican proposal to include tax breaks for small
businesses, which he said totaled $76 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the Senate said they were ready to do battle, if
necessary, and shot back at Democrats Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time an appropriations bill comes up, just about, we
have 100 amendments,'' Lott said. ``You know it's a magic number _
100.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned, he added, ``that the White House wants to
create a mess at the end of the session for pure political
reasons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
