<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2292 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-POP-MUSIC- &LR; $ &UR; ADV10-NY     09-05 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-MUSIC- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID THE QUICK HITS, A DOSE OF EARNESTNESS
</HEADLINE>
 $ ADV10-NYT (for release Sunday, Sept. 10)  
 By JON PARELES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is music a momentary thrill or is it a long-term companion?
Popular music has always answered yes to both options.
</P>
<P>
   Hits are disposable by definition, since nothing is permanent on
the pop charts. And the recording business isn't at all unhappy to
face the pop equivalent of attention deficit disorder, on the
theory that obsolescence means more opportunities to sell new
tunes. The proliferating sources for music and other entertainment,
from satellite television to the Internet, encourage potential
listeners to surf for the next bit of stimulation, not to give a
song a second chance. Napster, Scour and other free music-sharing
programs on the Internet also take the commitment, in money and
time, out of acquiring a piece of music; it's easy to download,
play and delete a song without a second thought.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many musicians hope their work will stay with listeners. To
spend long days and nights in studios, poring over every sonic
nuance, they have to believe that at least some of their listeners
will give the music enough consideration to let it sink in. They
still expect that a certain core of fans will spend enough time
with an album to hear all the details, to memorize songs, to take
the music and the performers to heart.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, those two kinds of ambition have been increasingly
polarized. Some musicians, contemplating youth demographics, are
reaching for quick hit singles, proffering smiley teenypop tunes to
the youngest fans and rude hip-hop and rap-metal to their older
siblings, hoping to cash in before they outgrow current styles. The
next season's platinum contenders include new albums by Limp Bizkit
and Ricky Martin in October. Other musicians, however, cling to the
idea that someone will still want to replay their albums in the
distant future _ say, six months or a year after they're released.
</P>
<P>
   Outkast, a hip-hop duo from Atlanta, has designed itself with an
ingenious balance between immediate gratification and lasting
messages. One of its two rappers, Big Boi, is a light-hearted
gangsta type, out for sex and excitement like many of the other
street characters who zoomed up and down the pop charts in the
1990s. But Outkast's other rapper, Dre, thinks about issues like
crime, drugs and illegitimacy. On its fourth album, ``Stankonia,''
which is due in October, Outkast embraces hip-hop as both a raunchy
boast and a community alert, refusing to split mind from body. Yet
their music makes it all sound like a party.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Outkast's duality is only a fraction of the
multifariousness of the Wu-Tang Clan, whose many members make it
more like a hip-hop coalition meeting than a standard group. With
its members reconvened after many solo albums, the Wu-Tang Clan is
slated to release its third album later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna's long career has refuted all attempts to dismiss her as
a short-lived pop infatuation, even as she used all the marketing
machinery that makes pop hits explode. For nearly two decades she
has caught musical styles on the upswing, even as she latched on to
fashions that made her worth watching. But she and her
collaborators also came up with songs that have outlasted the
trends they exploited. ``Music'' is Madonna's second album in
collaboration with the producer William Orbit, who merged
dance-floor propulsion with sensuous electronic dreamscapes for
``Ray of Light,'' as she continues her transit from earthly desires
to spiritual hopes and yearnings.
</P>
<P>
   Radiohead's 1997 album, ``OK Computer,'' deliberately defied
superficial listening. It was an album-length contemplation, and a
bitter critique, of how mass media and technology shape docile,
depersonalized consumers, and it took pains over every note as it
pondered why alienation festers behind comfort. Radiohead's next
album, ``Kid A,'' is due in October, and while it's not billed as a
concept album, it's even more introspective, almost begging for
headphones and undivided attention. Songs and instrumental passages
drift and hover, as if floating within some lonely, abstracted
intelligence. ``Kid A'' is half of a two-album set, to be completed
next year by a second album of material from the same recording
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Radiohead isn't the only band that's not afraid to appear
serious; U2, whose previous album confused potential fans by
putting a light-hearted title, ``Pop,'' on a set of brooding songs,
is to release a new studio album in October.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell, whose next album is due in November, can count on
longtime loyalty because his albums have a secure place on the
bedroom stereo. He has defined himself as something his fans long
for: a romantic, thoughtful, sensual and utterly monogamous lover,
completely devoted to his partner's happiness. Taking the Marvin
Gaye of ``Sexual Healing'' as his model, and merging Gaye's
undulating grooves with a touch of Sade, Maxwell comes across as
sweet but virile, with touches of mysticism and eccentricity giving
depth to his come-ons. D'Angelo's brilliant 1999 album, ``Voodoo,''
gave Maxwell serious competition in both music and
persona-building; with any luck, Maxwell will raise the stakes
again.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox of pop is that intentions rarely correspond to
results. The most carefully thought out, elaborately realized
musical opus may well be ignored or repudiated, while a casually
tossed off ditty can turn out to be timeless. Listeners, not
musicians, will make the final decisions about what's worth saving.
And in the meantime, fleeting pleasures will do just fine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
