<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-PROTEST-NYT &LR;      09-05 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZERS OF ANTI-GLOBALIZATION CONFERENCE HOPE U.N. HEARS THEIR
MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash.)  (sidebar with U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the 150 or so world leaders meeting this week at
the United Nations wanted answers to the question of globalization,
they had to do nothing more than walk a few blocks Tuesday to the
Town Hall, a concert auditorium in midtown Manhattan. There, plenty
of words of wisdom awaited them:
</P>
<P>
   ``The current stage of the world economy is the cancer stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We should continue in cutting back the powers of the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the global economy doing to the earth? It's killing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of remarks came during a daylong teach-in organized
by the International Forum on Globalization, a group based in
northern California that opposes the spread of an unregulated free
market economy.
</P>
<P>
   More than 900 people came to hear about the evils of U.S.- and
European-dominated financial institutions like the World Bank, the
International Monetary Fund and the World Trade Organization.
Issues mentioned in the forum, which was called ``Globalization and
the Role of the United Nations,'' ranged from dam-building in the
Philippines to the 1944 Bretton Woods monetary system agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the speakers and groups involved in the teach-in
participated in the mass protests last November that tied up a
meeting of the World Trade Organization in Seattle. In April, the
same people, who represent causes ranging from environmental
protection to the needs of indigenous cultures, took to the streets
of Washington during a meeting of international finance ministers.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no black masks or tear gas in evidence Tuesday,
and the attendees appeared as well-mannered as their counterparts
in the U.N. complex overlooking the East River. An usher took
tickets ($20 for general admission), a will-call line snaked out
the doors and organizers even handed out sheets the audience could
use to rate the panels (poor to excellent in various categories.)
Relative calm prevailed partly because the teach-in was intended to
be a discussion and not a demonstration, and partly because many of
the participants were not ready to write off the United Nations as
an unwitting tool of U.S. corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United Nations has traditionally had a mandate of social
justice and peace and human rights,'' said Jerry Mander, founder of
the International Forum on Globalization. ``But we've lately begun
to worry that that mandate was weakening, and that the same
ideologies that drive the WTO will appear in the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   For the anti-globalization movement, the teach-in was not only a
venue to assess the role of the United Nations in the world
economy, but also allowed participants to reflect on how far the
movement had come since Seattle, and how much further it had to go.
Many speakers said that they did not oppose globalization per se,
since the era of nation-states was coming to an inevitable end, but
that they opposed an emerging world economy where global policies
are made by large corporations. Those policies, the speakers said,
are paving the way for big business to exploit developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have entered the era of corporate rule,'' Mander said to
the audience, which was made up in almost equal parts of young
people and their elders. ``The familiar homily is this: the rising
tide will lift all boats. Actually, it lifts yachts.''
</P>
<P>
   The four speakers on a panel introduced by Mander congratulated
the movement for making its roar heard during the Seattle protests,
but also rattled off a list of goals and strategies. Several
panelists said that economic boycotts would be the most effective
way to get their message across to business executives. Victoria
Tauli-Corpuz, an advocate for indigenous people in the Philippines,
implored listeners to urge the United Nations to adhere to its
original goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, we are seeing that the United Nations is
abdicating its role in terms of social improvement, in terms of
poverty alleviation,'' Tauli-Corpuz said. ``It is our role to still
insist and assert that the United Nations is not a body that should
be siding with the interests of capitalists or the interests of
powerful corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the speeches made at the forum echoed the goals of
this week's Millennium Summit at the United Nations. The summit
meeting is intended as a forum where the voices of the smallest
countries can be heard alongside those of most powerful nations.
Hours before the Town Hall teach-in began Wednesday, President
Mohammed Khatami of Iran said in a speech at the United Nations:
``Global culture cannot and should not overlook the characteristics
and requirements of local cultures with the aim of imposing itself
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, a 23-year-old man named Matthew Garrington,
who had grown up in Olympia, Wash., a world away from the deserts
of the Middle East, picked up several brochures on a table outside
the teach-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously globalization is going to happen,'' he said, ``and I
want to make sure it happens responsibly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
