<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2309 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ANGELS-FILM-$ADV10-(T     09-05 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELS-FILM-$ADV10-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER ALL THESE YEARS, CAN CHARLIE'S ANGELS STILL FLY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By MOLLY HASKELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 1977. One of the talking points of the women's movement,
then in voluble high gear, was the treatment of women in films and
television.
</P>
<P>
   Every new picture was subjected to heated dissections of its
overt or covert offenses against women _ if the female sex was
represented at all.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this fairly dismal decade appeared ``Charlie's
Angels,'' with its spectacularly coiffed, pistol-packing cupcakes,
and we who were doing the agitating and analyzing didn't know
whether to laugh or cry. Or simply surrender to the show's dippy
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Having fallen, I'm ashamed to confess, into the latter category
_ I'm a sucker for mysteries and it was part of my professional
research (am I protesting too much?) _ I nevertheless can't warm to
the prospect of a 21st-century film spinoff (opening Nov. 3) with
three of Hollywood's hottest babes. Cameron Diaz, Drew Barrymore
(one of the movie's producers) and Lucy Liu, the smoldering Asian
femme fatale on ``Ally McBeal,'' are stars in their own right,
hence far more independently powerful than the members of the
original trio, then virtually unknown.
</P>
<P>
   But that sense of discovery was just one of the modest
enticements of the television show that can't be reproduced. Who
knew Farrah Fawcett-Majors, she of the three-toned tresses and
two-hand backhand; or Jaclyn Smith of the porcelain complexion and
honey voice; or Kate Jackson, who became known as ``the smart one''
because she had straight hair, more tailored clothes and could
actually act a little? (At least she could cock a pistol and say
``Freeze!'' without having us collapse in giggles.) They were, if
not revelations, at least brand-new, hence without baggage, and
could create a sort of girls'-night-out camaraderie as they went
along, and a very sweet if ephemeral tune it was.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which ran five seasons, wasn't one for the ages, and
its relatively poor showing in syndication, as compared with male
buddy crime solvers like ``Starsky and Hutch'' and ``Magnum P.I.,''
may or may not confirm the axiom that the female action picture is
a tough sell with general audiences. But then again, do Charlie's
pulchritudinous hirelings belong in the same category with
no-frills action heroines like Thelma and Louise, G.I. Jane, the
``Bad Girls'' western foursome, Warrant Officer Lt. Ellen Ripley
(``Alien'') and the various Femmes Nikita?
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie's Angels'' was very much an artifact of its time,
perched precariously on the borderline between snickering sexism
and feminism-lite, as dated now as the posters (and name) of Farrah
Fawcett-Majors. That it worked at all was one of those peculiar and
unpredictable phenomena of show business, an amalgam of high
concept and low chuckles, an alchemy of mythology, formula,
self-parody and chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the upgraded firepower we may expect from
``Charlie's Angels'' the movie, theirs was a low-tech enterprise,
operating in a world before cell phones, gyms and Attitude. The
sweet sensuality of the small-screen angels was a matter of halter
tops and slender brown arms; lithe, boyish figures and dazzling
white smiles; and a ready if not always Marivaux-level repartee. In
other words, the three Nancy Drews with the fabulous hair, who set
out each week to solve a crime and nab the perpetrators, were a
cunning blend of rear-guard cute and jockess competent, ``Beach
Blanket Bingo'' meets Title IX, a not inapt metaphor for the twin
modes, victim and aggressor, between which women were oscillating
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The show, offering three ``types'' of babe to choose from,
managed to strike sparks in crossover markets, from pubescent male
fantasies to Girl Guide role models, with a nod to us ``humorless''
feminists along the way.
</P>
<P>
   These ``girls,'' as they were called in tweaking defiance of the
taboo, were liberated women, but liberated from what? And by whom?
``Three little girls went to the police academy,'' announces
Charlie, the unseen pasha, at the beginning of each show. (The
orotund voice of John Forsythe will also be heard in the movie.) We
see the recruits going through their paces at the firing range,
jumping, wrestling, though, unlike Demi Moore's Marine Corps grunt,
never strenuously or for long enough to work up a sweat or build a
muscle. When they are immobilized (by the glass ceiling?) in
``hazardous'' jobs like typist, meter maid and crossing guard,
Charlie comes to the rescue, placing the damsels in real (and
titillating) distress in the path of blackmailers, murderers, con
artists and pornographers.
</P>
<P>
   The girls brush shoulders with the sleaze and decadence of a
modern L.A. without a speck of mud ever sticking to their
peachy-keen personalities or their off-the-rack jump suits, tank
tops and jeans. In one episode, a devoted son supports his aging
mother's orchid habit (shades of ``The Big Sleep's'' General
Sternwood) by churning out porn movies in his film lab. When the
girls are obliged to watch these movies or, in another episode, go
``undercover'' as prostitutes (Jackson as Sabrina) and masseuses
(Fawcett-Majors as Jill) or, in still another, sleepwalk around
town in a lacy negligee (Smith as Kelly), they are as unbesmirched
by sophistication as little girls dressed in Mommy's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Mediating between the angels and Charlie is his avuncular
factotum Bosley, played by David Doyle. Jaded critics, untouched by
the angels, saw these two gentlemen more as procurers than
protectors, noting that they and the girls fell into
pimp-prostitute roles along traditional gender lines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QC;  &LR;  But fairy tale analogies might be even more
to the point: ``Three Little Pigs'' and ``Goldilocks and the Three
Bears'' echo through the proceedings, the latter reversing neatly
into Three Gorgeous-Locks and a Bear. Or we might see in the
rivalry set up by their iconographic contrasts and implied
differences a replay of the judgment of Paris, wherein he opted for
Venus (Beauty, the fairest woman for a wife) over Minerva (Wisdom
and Renown) or Juno (Riches and Power). Dispensing with the
also-rans, Minerva and Juno, and getting right to the bottom line,
the show offers only the choice between Beautiful and Strong
(Smith), Beautiful and Smart (Jackson) and Just Beautiful
(Fawcett).
 &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In one of the wittiest commentaries at the time, Lois Gould
wrote a column in The New York Times in which she polled little
girls of 8, 10 and 12 on the impact of the angels and what she saw
as a sudden ``confusion about the difference _ if any _ between a
role model and a hair model.'' The message that little girls were
taking to their pillows at night was that one could be a president
or a detective or Amelia Earhart, a weight lifter or a nuclear
physicist, and still be ravishing. But if a choice had to be made,
it was beauty (i.e., highlights and sexy clothes) before business
anytime.
</P>
<P>
   Now, presumably, with the blurring of once-rigid boundaries
between male and female roles, and the prevalence of women, often
attractive women, in sports, politics and business, the action
heroine is no longer the anomaly who has to be softened, made
acceptable, by precisely those ``feminizing'' qualities that
undermine her plausibility, threaten to turn her into a harmless
joke.
</P>
<P>
   The new movie will no doubt give us the real thing: Powerful,
enterprising women who haven't got time to look perfect, whose
fingernails crack and whose roots grow out, who give their Bosley
(Bill Murray) not girlish giggles but power-grrrl guff.
</P>
<P>
   And if you believe that, you'll believe that there's a vast new
commercial frontier for women as heroines who play tough, crack
wise and shoot straight, who make no concessions to glamour and are
strangers to the hairdresser's art.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
