u i BC-U.N.-EAST-WEST-ART-75     09-05 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-EAST-WEST-ART-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT LISTENS AS IRAN CALLS FOR `DIALOGUE AMONG CIVILIZATIONS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT18,19 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ As a battle between supporters and opponents of
democratic reform rages at home, President Mohammad Khatami of Iran
came to the United Nations Tuesday to promote his campaign for a
global ``dialogue among civilizations'' and to praise his country
as one of the world's oldest.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, a midranking cleric who was swept to victory in a
popular election three years ago on a platform promoting the rule
of law, delivered a highly theoretical speech that offered no
concrete proposal on how to promote global dialogue, no talk of his
promises to promote reform at home and no mention of any country
except his own.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a clerical robe and cloak and the black turban
signifying that he is a descendant of the prophet Muhammad, Khatami
instead quoted from the Koran and the 14th-century poet Hafiz and
spoke of the importance of artists and poets, mystical thought and
Islamic civilization and of the lack of empathy and compassion in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us hope that enmity and oppression should end, and that
the clamor of love for truth, justice and human dignity should
prevail,'' Khatami told an audience of several hundred, including a
number of heads of state and invited Iranian expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   He also warned about the dangers of unlimited globalization,
saying, ``Global culture cannot and should not overlook the
characteristics and requirements of local cultures with the aim of
imposing itself on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated in the front row of the audience a few yards away from
Khatami was Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who came to New
York early Tuesday to hear his 30-minute speech.
</P>
<P>
   She applauded him twice _ when he was introduced and again at
the end of his speech _ and left the conference room before any of
the other speakers took the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the vagueness of much of the speech by Khatami, who was
trained in philosophy at the University of Isfahan, Albright later
called it thought-provoking and interesting.
</P>
<P>
   A senior State Department official explained that Albright had
attended because ``there is no official dialogue with Iran at this
point and we wanted t send a signal to the Iranians that we're
willing to listen to what they have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright also wanted to be present after she learned that
Khatami would be seated in the General Assembly hall on Wednesday
when President Clinton addresses the assembly's 55th session, the
official added.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright and Khatami steered clear of each other at a
reception just before the conference Tuesday, and Clinton will not
try to meet his Iranian counterpart on Wednesday, the State
Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has pressed Iran to open an official
dialogue as a first step toward drawing a ``road map'' for the
eventual normalization of relations, but Iran has repeatedly
refused.
</P>
<P>
   Since Khatami became president in 1997, one of his main themes
has been the need for a ``dialogue among civilizations,'' code
words for bridging the gap between an Islamic government like
Iran's, which is still subject to U.S. economic sanctions, and
secular nations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed making 2001 the year of such dialogue in his maiden
speech before the General Assembly two years ago. Tuesday's event
was the kickoff of that endeavor as well as the prelude to the
opening of the annual Assembly session and the three-day summit
meeting that will bring together more than 150 world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami's appearance Tuesday was dramatically different from his
U.N. debut two years ago. Back then he had been president for a
little more than a year, and he wooed a receptive global audience
with talk of how freedom-loving and law-abiding Iran was becoming.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Iran's reformist press is shut down, many of its reformist
journalists and clerics have been imprisoned and its judiciary,
dominated by ultraconservative clerics, is determined to punish any
behavior it considers un-Islamic.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Iran's spiritual leader, who
under the country's constitution wields much more power than
Khatami, stunned the nation when he directly intervened in the
affairs of the newly elected Parliament, ordering it not to
consider amending a restrictive press law.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, vigilantes forcibly prevented two reformist
leaders from speaking in the western industrial city of
Khurramabad, touching off days of rioting in which a policeman was
killed and more than 100 people were injured.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Near the Iranian mission to the United Nations Tuesday, about
the same time that Khatami was speaking, the Conference of
Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations sponsored a rally
demanding the release of 10 Iranian Jews convicted of espionage in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Among the speakers were Gov. George Pataki of New York, Rep.
Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., who is running for the Senate in New York, and
a number of Democrats including Rep. Nita Lowey, also of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to send a message to the president of Iran and the
people of Iran, Pataki said. ``The ten do not stand alone. We are
in solidarity with them.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City public advocate Mark Green said, ``No more caviar
and Iranian rugs while our brothers are kept in jail.'' He was
referring to the recent easing of the economic embargo against Iran
to allow the United States to import Iranian caviar, carpets and
pistachios.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away across the street from the United Nations,
more than 1,000 Iranian protesters representing the U.S.-based
National Council of Resistance of Iran stood under a cloud of red,
white and green balloons and protested Khatami's visit and demanded
the overthrow of the Teheran government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death to Khatami!'' the protesters chanted, as they waved the
flags of the Mujaheddin-e Khalq, Iran's main armed resistance
organization which the State Department defines as a terrorist
group. One of their signs read, ``Murder, torture and execution
continues in Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Khatami met with a hand-picked group of 500 Iranian
businessmen, academics, students and artists, stoking their Persian
pride and exhorting them to invest in their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts are beating for the love of one place, and this
place is Iran,'' Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Khatami spoke, five expatriates delivered their own
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cultural freedom is not relative,'' said R.K. Ramazani,
professor of government at the University of Virginia. He warned of
``national suicide'' if the Iranian people's demands for freedom
are overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Jahangir Ghaznavi, who heads a Pittsburgh investment company,
drew loud applause when he suggested ways to attract Iranian
expatriates back home.
</P>
<P>
   `` Mr. Khatami, open the economic doors,'' he said. ``Make
coming and going in and out of the country easier. Try to guarantee
investments as is done in other countries. Remove political
obstacles for investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Khatami held a similar meeting with hundreds of
Iranian expatriates. But that time, he allowed the audience to ask
questions in what turned out to be an extraordinarily free-wheeling
exchange. This time, in a sign of the times in Iran perhaps, no
questions were allowed. There was only a box into which guests
could deposit their questions and comments.
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
