<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS SHOW SYSTEM WORKS, IF PEOPLE DO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is never about the system. It is always about the people in
the system. If the system doesn't fit the people, it is the wrong
system. If the people fail, the system is doomed. And, of course,
the better the skill level of the people, the better the system.
</P>
<P>
   Football works that way. Everything works that way. Not that any
of us philosophers and deep thinkers needed additional proof, but,
if necessary, proof has been provided again this week.
</P>
<P>
   Some 24 hours after the massive destruction of both people and
system, as witnessed by horrified bystanders at Texas Stadium, that
same system was on national TV display. Except, of course, it was
in the hands of different people.
</P>
<P>
   See if this sounds familiar:
</P>
<P>
   An offensive outfit considered very high octane, wheels out a
nonmobile quarterback, going totally against that silly, yet
ever-so-trendy notion that the NFL game of today demands a Movin'
Jessie be playing the position.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons for this particular human tree stump of a
quarterback are very speedy wideouts, a big-time running back, and
a veteran offensive line. Hmmmm. A comparison pattern seems to be
developing.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. Providing the opposition for our
offensive friends on this particular Monday evening was a kamikaze
defensive unit that depends on the blitz to create both confusion
and concussions for nonmobile QBs, who, of course, have no business
playing the game anymore.
</P>
<P>
   So, what happened?
</P>
<P>
   This dinosaur of a quarterback, who answers to both MVP and Kurt
Warner, threw three awful interceptions and appeared to have cost
his team this particular game. Yes, the pressure shook Mr. Concrete
Shoes so much, he only managed to throw for 441 yards and three
TDs, and atoned for his own mistakes by leading the game-winning
touchdown drive. It was beautiful, it was entertaining. Even Dennis
Miller had a good night.
</P>
<P>
   So, why did this story have this particular ending, as opposed
to Texas Stadium on Sunday? For starters, this QB's offensive line
responded well to the blitz, and everything else the defense showed
it. There were no gutless pigs playing up front who went into
hiding when the blitz heat got heavy. And then this QB, with the
quickness of a fire plug, took his normal ``hot route'' three]-step
and five]step drops, dumped the ball off on the wings to receivers
and his running back, who 50, 60 and 70 yards later, had those
blitzers feeling like fools.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, the system works. And it's the same system in St. Louis as
at Valley Ranch. But you get the point; the difference came in the
people, despite the physical parts on offense being very similar.
With the right people, the system wins Super Bowls. In the wrong
hands, however ...
</P>
<P>
   The season is already over with a mere 15 games to play.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman is lucky to have gotten out alive. On the street, a
concussion would have been considered a minor injury, based on the
possible alternative his offensive line almost caused. For personal
health purposes, of course, Aikman's having his brain rattled again
is yet another warning sign that the point of no-football-return is
near.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he won't retire. There's too much personal
stubbornness for that, and too much loyalty to Jerry Jones, and the
salary cap situation that has developed over the past five years.
The day Aikman retires is the day the Cowboys join the 49ers on the
list of salary-cap-dead teams. Jones had cap-soaked his club's
contractual structure around Aikman, who has constantly agreed to a
contractual redo to free money in order to sign other players.
</P>
<P>
   Remember this: Aikman is on the Cowboys' financial ledger until
the year 2007. He might not last past next week. And don't be
surprised at all if he's playing Sunday night, as dumb as that may
seem after three concussions in his past 10 games. To start the
season with another brain bruise means the second one could end his
year, if not his career, if not his motor skills, at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   I have no advice for Aikman on what to do with himself; he's not
listening, anyway. But on Ring of Honor and Hall of Fame induction
days, hopefully, the ceremonies won't be delayed until someone can
empty a drool cup.
</P>
<P>
   While Aikman's departure is pending, Joey Galloway already knows
about his immediate future. There is no future, at least not this
season. What was supposed to be the high-priced offensive piece
that put the ``new/old'' system into gear, is facing knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Should Galloway have been on the field at that particular
fourth-quarter point? The easy second guess nails Dave Campo.
</P>
<P>
   But because this was strictly an artificial turf-type injury,
with no contact involved, Jones also pays the price for keeping
that stupid plastic grass in place all these years.
</P>
<P>
   One game _ one very lousy game _ and the 2000 season suddenly
vanishes. Elsewhere, the system keeps working. But here, the people
failed, and the consequences will stretch far into the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
