<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-TIMEOFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LAWYERS FIND PART-TIME PRACTICE BETTER SUITED TO PURSUIT OF
HAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEOFF BERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perry Nagle, 35, a lawyer specializing in corporate
finance, is taking the rest of the year off. Having already earned
more than enough money to tide him over until next year, he has
packed his bags and is heading for the beaches of Indonesia where,
he said, the ocean is ``bath-water warm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my goals for the year is to get in two good months of
surfing on the south coast of Java,'' Nagle said.
</P>
<P>
   Nagle practices law in Manhattan just a few months each year and
spends the rest of his time writing, performing stand-up comedy and
traveling. He makes $75 to $125 an hour doing free-lance legal
assignments for major firms. At that rate, 20 weeks of full-time
work can bring in up to $100,000, leaving the rest of the year open
for the pursuit of pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, the prospect of working just a few months each
year, or a few days each week, is nothing but an idle fantasy. For
a growing number of lawyers, though, it is an everyday reality. The
demand for their expertise and the high rates they can command make
it possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are talented lawyers out there who prefer not be on the
full-time track,'' said James Quinn, who is head of litigation at
Weil, Gotshal &AMP; Manges, one of New York's largest and most
prestigious firms. ``We've kept these types of people on board here
by developing a range of flexible arrangements.''
</P>
<P>
   For seven years, Nagle put in the long hours at Milbank, Tweed,
Hadley &AMP; McCloy, a prominent Wall Street firm. There, he
specialized in international finance and worked with clients like
the New York Stock Exchange and Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then, I've simplified my life tremendously,'' he said,
speaking recently from a summer home on Plum Lake, Wis., where he
was preparing for his trip to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, Milbank Tweed sent him to Jakarta, Indonesia's
capital, as liaison to an affiliated firm there. On the day he
arrived, the head of that firm died of a rare heart virus and the
firm dissolved, leaving Nagle in temporary limbo while his New York
bosses searched for another Indonesian partner.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he was making a Wall Street salary in a Third World
economy, and had plenty of free time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived like a colonialist, with servants and drivers,'' he
said. ``I also had some space to explore different ways of life. I
eventually found out that full-time law just wasn't the thing for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the United States in late 1996, Nagle used
the money he had saved overseas to buy a Manhattan loft, which he
now rents out during his travels. Soon afterward, he quit his
full-time job and began to take advantage of New York's growing
market for alternative-work arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that he dislikes the practice of law, he says. He has
his own legal Web site, alleylaw.com, and says he enjoys helping
new-media companies secure corporate financing. But, he says, his
outside interests are incompatible with 80-hour work weeks that
full-time practice often demands.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Nagle is working on a book, provisionally titled,
``State of Nature,'' about his experiences in Indonesia, which he
hopes to finish during his four-month stay there this year. He says
it will chronicle ``the effect of a chaotic Indonesia on the
orderly, over-civilized life of a typical young Wall Street
lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stand-up comedy gives Nagle another outlet. He says he has
developed a small following doing an act that friends describe as
``early Andy Kaufman,'' in which, for example, he imitates a piece
of toast by ``remaining stiff, jumping straight up and down, and
fanning my face as if I'm hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schlanger, president of Peak Counsel Inc., Manhattan's
largest privately held legal staffing agency, said it was not
unusual for lawyers to have such outside interests. ``Some people
are actors, some people are free-lance writers, others have young
kids they want to spend time with.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, said Lori Phelps, regional vice president of
Special Counsel, a legal staffing agency in New York, such people
can ``find work at major firms without committing to the classic
work-until-you-drop life style.''
</P>
<P>
   Connie Fratianni and Lisa Jacobs, both of whom make six-figure
salaries as partners at Sherman &AMP; Sterling, work reduced hours to
spend more time with their families. ``I guess what flex time means
in practice for me is that when my daughter has a 4 o'clock Girl
Scout meeting, I go,'' said Fratianni, whose Midtown Manhattan
office is adorned with poster-sized photos of her two boys and two
girls, ages 8, 6, 4 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Jacobs works a four-day week and takes extra time off
during school vacations. Catching up on errands during the week,
she said, ``gives me an opportunity to be a fun mommy on the
weekends.'' On Fridays, she stays home to prepare a traditional
Sabbath dinner for her family, although, she said, ``I may have to
partake in a conference call sometimes while I chop the
vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Talbert, a real-estate lawyer in Manhattan, gave up
full-time practice to pursue an acting career. Since completing
acting school seven years ago, he has supported himself by taking
temporary legal assignments at several big New York firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acting is what I love, and acting is what excites me,'' he
said. ``It's what I'd do full-time if I could.'' But, he said, ``a
big part of being an actor in New York City is being able to
survive economically. Legal temp work has helped me to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternative-work arrangements are not without their drawbacks.
Many part-time lawyers _ especially those working through agencies
or at junior levels _ forgo fringe benefits like health insurance,
401(k) plans and paid vacations. But the sacrifice, they say, is
worth the free time it buys. And, of course, earning $100,000 or
more for a half year's work is not exactly a life of hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the beginning of a sea change,'' Jacobs said.
``The legal community and Wall Street were loath to recognize that
people could have a family, a personal life, and a professional
life with none of them suffering. For the first time, the light
bulb is going off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
