u f BC-AETNA-APPOINT-405&AMP;ADD     09-05 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-APPOINT-405&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL CHIEF TO LEAD AETNA MANAGED CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. John W. Rowe, who oversaw one of the largest hospital
mergers in New York City and in the process became one of the
industry's most prominent executives, was named president and chief
executive of Aetna U.S. Healthcare late on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Rowe, the chief executive of the Mount Sinai-New York
University Medical Center and Health System, Aetna is hiring a
well-known geriatrics specialist who has helped his hospital, a
combined unit of the two prominent medical centers, stay afloat in
extremely troubled times.
</P>
<P>
   In Aetna, the country's largest health insurer, Rowe takes over
a company faced with the difficult task of improving customer
relations while raising prices for managed-care coverage. Last
month, the company reported a 17 percent drop in second-quarter
profits; in a preliminary proxy statement filed with the Securities
and Exchange Commission on Friday, the company reported profit
margins of less than 2 percent. Rowe will begin Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Through mergers, Aetna acquired U.S. Healthcare, the NYLcare
unit of New York Life Insurance Co. and Prudential Health Care,
which had lost money for Prudential Life Insurance Co. of America.
</P>
<P>
   Under its former chief executive, Richard Huber, Aetna became a
favorite target for angry doctors and other critics of managed
care. William H. Donaldson, Huber's successor, has tried to calm
the waters by relaxing controls on patient care, thereby risking
higher internal costs and reduced profits or losses.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts have urged Donaldson to find an experienced
chief for the health care business, no easy task when most HMO
companies had troubles of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Once Aetna completes the planned spinoff of its health care
unit, Rowe will become chief executive of the single company and
Donaldson will remain chairman, a spokeswoman for Aetna said.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna and Rowe come together after what was ostensibly a fairly
hostile relationship; Rowe, like all of his counterparts in New
York, have complained of financial stress in recent years, brought
on in part by what they have said was increased pressures from
managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of dissatisfaction with health insurance
processes,'' Rowe said, ``and I think that Aetna, because of its
strength as the largest health insurance company in the nation has
an opportunity to play a very significant role to change this. I am
very excited about this new platform.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Mount Sinai-NYU Center is in better shape than many other
medical centers in New York, though that is somewhat analogous to
being the healthiest patient in the intensive care ward. The center
earned only about $20 million on $1.7 billion in revenue last year
and expects to earn roughly the same on $1.8 billion in revenue
this year, partly through budget cuts like the elimination of
consultants and some management positions. The NYU hospitals ran a
deficit, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   While the merged entities have increased their market share
while others around them have lost patients over the last few
years, cash flow is still tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would characterize Mount Sinai-NYU Health as stronger than
most in the New York marketplace,'' said Liz Sweeney, a director in
health care ratings at Standard &AMP; Poor's, which rates the
hospital's bonds BBB-plus, or investment grade, with a stable
outlook. ``But from a national perspective, it is weaker than what
we see at other organizations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   New York trails its national counterparts in several key ways.
Managed care came late to the region. More important, the state had
a regulated pricing policy for hospitals until 1997, and when
deregulation was introduced in 1997, competition suddenly became
part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the Balanced Budget Act of the same year, which reduced
some payments to hospitals under Medicare, and the full
infiltration of managed care into the marketplace, and hospitals
were suddenly like retailers, battling for customers and increasing
their marketing budgets to sell things like pretty maternity wards
and high-profile doctors. Some centers have since filed for
bankruptcy. ``New York hospitals tend to be highly leveraged,''
Sweeney said. ``Their balance sheets tend to be thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowe, 56, has made many moves to help his merged center gain
strides. He came to Mount Sinai in 1988 as president of the
hospital and medical school and set his sights on a modernization
of the entire campus. A 1-million-square-foot inpatient center
designed by I.M. Pei was added in 1993, and two other buildings
went up later while others were overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   He also built up the center's home health agency, where revenue
increased to $59 million last year from $3 million in 1998. On
Rowe's watch, Mount Sinai's medical school gained stature with the
National Institutes of Health; in 1997, the school received $97.7
million in support from the federal agency. While New York
University and Mount Sinai did not meld their medical schools or
clinical departments, the merged unit has saved about $24 million
in administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe is among New York's more accessible hospital executives and
enjoys giving interviews on topics ranging from health care
economics to gerontology.
</P>
<P>
   A professor of medicine at Mount Sinai's School of Medicine, he
still often goes on rounds with residents, during which he has been
known to chat about acute renal failure, brag about the hospital's
savings on its meal program and recall banter once exchanged with
Pei.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Mount Sinai, he was the founding director of the
Division of Aging at Harvard Medical School and chief of
gerontology at Beth Israel Hospital in Boston. He has written
extensively on geriatric medicine and aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big win for Aetna,'' said James R. Tallon, the
president of the United Hospital Fund, a philanthropy group. ``The
issues facing the insurance industry and health care industry are
complicated long-term issues, and someone of Jack's stature can
only be positive for Aetna.''
</P>
<P>
   And while some could argue that Rowe is joining forces with a
semi-adversary of sorts, Sweeney said that could also work in
Aetna's favor. ``Health plans and hospitals sit across from each
other in negotiations,'' she said. ``So from that perspective I am
sure he is valuable to them. But it could seem like now he is part
of the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
