<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAJICEK SHOULD BREAK THE PATTERN AND TEST SAMPRAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's Pete and the pretenders now.
</P>
<P>
   This is Pete Sampras's US Open to lose, a tournament from which
notables have been purged like bold ideas from the Presidential
campaign, and he is left with seven other guys in the room who'd
better wear name tags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Pete, I'm Tom Johansson . . . uh, you know . . . of the
Linkoping, Sweden, Johanssons?'' one of them might introduce
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, no extrovert, and not much interested in anybody's game
but his diamond-encrusted own, would probably recognize Andre
Agassi, Yevgeny Kafelnikov, Thomas Enqvist, Mark Philippoussis,
Guga Kuerten, Alex Corretja, Tim Henman, and Cedric Pioline _ guys
who've beaten him, or given him a rough time. But they're gone,
without making any more impression at Flushing Meadows than a milk
commercial in a saloon.
</P>
<P>
   They've left Sampras lonely and unmussed in the quarterfinals,
three wins away from a fifth Open title, and a 14th major, almost
wondering whether he'll bump into a familiar face.
</P>
<P>
   Almost _ because the face in the floodlights tonight is, for
Sampras, right out of a horror movie called ``The Frying
Dutchman.'' It belongs to 6-foot-5-inch Richard Krajicek, a citizen
of the Netherlands who often makes Sampras feel as though he's
wearing wooden shoes. Krajicek has sauteed Sampras six of nine,
grilling him like Edam cheese on important occasions: Davis Cup,
1994; Wimbledon quarters, 1996; the Lipton, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A Sampras-Krajicek collision means that the title could be
decided Wednesday night. Suddenly, Sampras will have to lift
something heavier than his racket or a glass of the milk that he
hustles. He must raise his glorious game to hunt big game after
four rounds of dealing with mice.
</P>
<P>
   This has been take-a-stranger-to-lunch stuff as Sampras rolled
up Nos. 69-88-72-182 (Martin Damm, Justin Gimelstob, Augustin
Calleri, Hyung-Taik Lee) like rugs in the minimum 12 sets. During
his four previous championship journeys to the last eight (1990,
1993, 1995, 1996), Sampras had to take care of tougher prelims,
guys named Thomas Muster, Todd Martin, Aleksandr Volkov, Enqvist,
and (twice) Philippoussis. He lost sets along the way.
</P>
<P>
   But greats or grunts, it's Sampras's habit to bust them all.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sampras should be well-rested, if not tested,
considering his dream draw, the nightmare element is Krajicek. The
Dutchman appears fitter than usual and fully recovered from knee
surgery early in the year, ranked a deceptive No. 23. He gives
Silky Sampras a chance to glitter as no one else, the kind of
challenge that this Californian vacuumer of titles relishes.
</P>
<P>
   In their duel of heavy artillery at 25 paces, I wouldn't want to
be one of the three line judges at either end of the court. Suits
of armor would be the most appropriate attire for those poor souls
making the calls with these two serving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Returning serve will decide it,'' says Sampras. ``We both
serve huge, but the guy who gets them back low on the big points
wins. Richard's done that pretty well against me, but we haven't
played since Cincinnati last year where I beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, holder of the Open's ace record (49 in a losing
bombardmnent of Kafelnikov last year), says, ``Pete serves bigger
than me, but I'm happy with my serve-and-volley game. We'll see if
I can return. I think it's better to catch him early _ now _ than
after he's had tough matches and is grooved.'' Krajicek is
averaging 19 aces per gig, Sampras 15.
</P>
<P>
   There's more than heat to both of them. A couple of
smart-bombers, they move balls all over the service box, hook and
kick wide. Sampras's malevolent second serve sets him apart from
all others.
</P>
<P>
   If Sampras, the 19-year-old champ of 1990, can cruise to the
championship he last won over Michael Chang four years ago, he will
take on more historical luster, catching up with an ancient
Cornellian named Bill Larned, winner of titles a decade apart, 1901
and 1911. Nine-year spans belong to Big Bill Tilden, 1920 and 1929,
and Jimmy Connors, 1974 and 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras's counterpart in golf, a game he loves, Tiger Woods,
obviously gets much more ink and screen time. Comparisons are
silly. After all, tennis is a running game of infinite length and
exertion, golf a walking game of 18 holes, limited shots. Unlike
golf balls, tennis balls don't lie there crying ``Hit me! Hit me!''
in the manner of blackjack players. It takes two weeks to win a
major, and Sampras faces guys like Krajicek trying to take him
apart, not stationary foes: sand, water, vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   They're different disciplines. But, despite his renown, Woods
hasn't come close to 29-year-old Sampras's accomplishments over 11
years: 13 majors and 50 other titles across the world. Still,
curiously, Sampras has trouble getting his name into the paper,
except at the majors.
</P>
<P>
   But this is one of those majors, and the Sampras greatness for
the ages is on view. Take a look. Otherwise you're missing a unique
sporting treat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
