<HEADLINE>
BOULEZ AND THE VIENNA: OPPOSITES UNOPPOSED
</HEADLINE>
 $ ADV10-NYT (for release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  The cleft dividing the composers of the 19th century from those of
the 20th is arguably the most prominent geographical feature of our
musical landscape. Two attitudes _ on how music should sound, how
it should feel and what its purpose should be _ have split
audiences, musicians and commentators so decisively that in still a
third century, the 21st, the gap is only marginally narrower than
it was 100 years ago.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On consecutive days, March 2, 3 and 4, 2001, at Carnegie Hall,
the sides face each other in a format of rare concentration and
potency. The Vienna Philharmonic plays; Pierre Boulez conducts. The
orchestra is our guardian of Romantic self-absorption; the
conductor, a musician whose sense of beauty lies outside the
immediate self.
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna is famous for its stubborn identity: some of the
world's best conductors have tried to change its sound and
inflection, and have ended (wisely) by letting this orchestra do
what it does. Not even a Herbert von Karajan could persuade the
Vienna to make Stravinsky and Webern sound like Stravinsky and
Webern, and I heard him try. Central Europe has come a long way
since a frustrated Stravinsky complained of the difficulty of
making its orchestras accent off the beat. But the symphony
orchestra, at least in the Vienna's traditional configuration of
dense strings and warm woodwinds and brasses, is a distance from
the brilliant, hard surfaces favored by Boulez, his like-minded
contemporaries and his immediate predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Boulez, who in his 70s has become one of our most persuasive
conductors as well as one of our most interesting composers, brings
Bartok, Webern, Debussy and Stravinsky to the Vienna Philharmonic
on the first Friday in March. Afterward, the orchestra will be
operating on its own territory with Wagner and Bruckner on the
Saturday and the Mahler Third Symphony on the Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Will this be a contest? The effusive gesture against the
tight-lipped symmetry? The relaxed versus the tightly strung? The
id versus the superego? Will the Vienna players overcome Boulez's
cooler tendencies, or will he subtly channel them into an
unfamiliar world of sound? Given the strong personalities of both
parties, listeners should expect a certain movement at either end
and a meeting somewhere near the middle, as in past meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruckner Ninth Symphony is monumental, slow-footed and
patient in a way Boulez's ``Repons'' is not. The Mahler Third
Symphony, by one of music's most extraordinary imaginations, is
confessional, uncomfortably so at times. The score, as they say,
will spill its guts, but will its conductor be listening? To a mind
as fastidious as Boulez's, Mahler intrigues with its invention and
yet seems somehow vulgar for its self-indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   Boulez, at any rate, is not the conductor he was 30 years ago.
The defiant puritanism and the love of manifestoes have gone away.
He is by any measure one of the most accomplished conductors alive.
Players are awed by his command of any score, and they have learned
to trust his gestures in difficult situations. The Vienna
Philharmonic has no boss and no overriding administration. It hires
the conductors its players ask for, and one expects they have
responded to the qualities of a great man (for Boulez is one)
regardless of stylistic differences.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings of these two minds in March will not represent any
particular surprise for either. The Vienna knows precisely who
Boulez is and what he does. Boulez has a long history with the
Romantic repertory and has committed a lot of it to recordings. The
Prelude and ``Liebestod'' from ``Tristan und Isolde'' will remind
listeners that the conductor led the famously controversial
production of ``Der Ring des Nibelungen'' at the Bayreuth Festival
in 1976. Just as Patrice Chereau's starkly updated staging both
thrilled and rankled, Boulez's idea of Wagner troubled or pleased
just as many for its perceived objectivity and coolness. Bayreuth's
orchestra, indeed, was so disturbed at Boulez's suppression of the
operas' themes and leitmotifs that the conductor at one point in
the proceedings offered to resign. At the curtain calls of
``Gotterdammerung,'' the musicians traditionally take the stage,
but they refused to appear with this conductor.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, was a long time ago. Boulez has changed, and
music has changed. So, too, have we listeners, and that may be the
most important shift of all. So powerful has been the appeal of
Romantic and post-Romantic music that the 20th century as a whole
is seen by some as a defense against it, a recoiling from a
threatening force rather than a thing in itself. The defense has
not held. We still like Brahms and Tchaikovsky as much as we ever
did, though perhaps the musical aesthetic of a Pierre Boulez
inhabits our ears more than we know and subtly changes our
experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
