<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL STUDIOS AMONG MOST MOM-FRIENDLY EMPLOYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Universal Studios Inc. earned a spot among Working
Woman's 100 best companies for working mothers by accommodating
flexible schedules, the magazine reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Universal was the only Southern California company to make the
magazine's 15th annual list, although firms with a strong presence
in the region, including Aetna Inc., Bank of America, Prudential
and Target Corp., were also recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Each year hundreds of companies apply for the coveted
distinction, which gauges a firm's commitment to child care, leave
for new parents, advancement for woman and benefits, said
editor-in-chief Lisa Benenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies are all moving the bar up every year,''
Benenson said, adding that competition was particularly intense
this year, with 21 new companies making the list, about double that
seen in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a sign that more and more companies are finding it
necessary to have these programs in place,'' she said. ``The
economy is so hot now that if you don't have family-friendly
programs, your employees are going to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal was singled out for its efforts to make flex time more
widely available and easier to arrange for its 14,940 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Universal officials said they had no one available to comment,
and the person most familiar with these programs went out on
maternity leave last week.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is being bought by French water utility
Vivendi, expanded its long-standing flex time plan by adding a
``tool kit'' to help employees and their managers more easily draw
up the agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Also, women made up 35 percent of the company's top earners in
1999, up from 28 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Only the top 10 companies on the list are ranked numerically.
The complete list is posted online at www.workingwoman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list was Allstate Insurance Co., followed in order
by Bank of America, Eli Lilly and Co., Fannie Mae and IBM Corp.
</P>
<P>
   IBM has been on the list for the past 13 years. This year it
pledged to spread its family-friendly benefits to its employees who
work outside the United States, Benenson said.
</P>
<P>
   For all the strides made by these and other companies, more
needs to be done to help the nation's 26 million working mothers,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
