<SLUG> BC-U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM SUMMIT SIDESHOW STARTS WITH TRAFFIC JAMS AND PROTESTS
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for rewriting thruout, new byline)  
 (See also U.N.-ANNAN)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6,21,22,26 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEAN E. MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The summit meeting of world leaders gets under way
Wednesday at the United Nations, but most of New York and its
thousands of visitors could not wait to open the curtain on what
promises to be a world-class sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was backed up across the East Side Tuesday because of a
crush of limousines carrying VIPs everywhere from the U.N.P Plaza
Hotel to the Bronx Zoo. (Denis Sessou-Nguesso, president of the
Republic of Congo, skipped some pre-conference hobnobbing to tour
the ``Congo Gorilla Forest'' exhibit).
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators, some beating drums, some shouting with bullhorns
and some practicing silent meditation, squeezed into Dag
Hammarskjolkd Plaza at the United Nations, the global soapbox for
the week. Whether anyone was listening did not seem important.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no peace without Yahweh's 613 laws of peace,'' a
religious group from Texas chanted. The reply from a pro-Taiwan
group: ``Say no to China.'' And members of the Chinese spiritual
movement Falung Gong, kept the yelling to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just focus inside,'' one of the meditators said.
</P>
<P>
   Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary general, has called the three-day
conference a ``defining moment for the world's leaders and for the
United Nations.'' To be sure, some of the world's most vexing
problems, from poverty to disease, will be debated by presidents,
prime ministers, kings and crown princes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, President Mohammed Khatami of Iran delivered a speech
at a one-day conference ahead of the summit, in which he praised
Iran as one of the world's oldest civilizations and promoted his
campaign for a global ``dialogue among civilizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussions also began among four African presidents on
Zimbabwe's troubled land-reform program. More than 700 other
meetings, dealing with local issues around the world, are expected
to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, it was mostly hard to see the diplomacy past the
pre-summit spectacle, which spilled into every nook and cranny of
New York and promised to continue throughout the week. Even as
Khatami spoke, hundreds of demonstrators marched down 47th Street
in opposition to his government, their protests filling one slot in
a day of events and counter-events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen this in bits and pieces before, but never like
this all together,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, who joined the
ranks of attention-seekers by releasing a letter to Madeleine
Albright, the secretary of state, requesting that the city be
reimbursed for the $10 million it is spending on the summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, home for the week to
about 30 heads of state, including President Clinton, finished
installing an elaborate telephone network that includes 4 miles of
additional cable, untold pieces of high-tech gadgetry and several
rooftop satellite links. Maintenance workers at the United Nations,
meanwhile, rushed to shore up a rain-soaked ceiling in a meeting
room where breakfast is to be served Wednesday to more than 150
invited guests.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed every New Yorker, permanent or just passing through,
also had a gripe about the once-a-millennium inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   A German tennis player, Nicolas Kiefer, advanced to the
quarterfinals at the U.S. Open in Queens, but only after surviving
a sleepless weekend at his hotel, the U.N. Plaza. Kiefer said he
had ``a very bad night'' on Sunday because there were no fewer than
four security alerts during the night. The Palestinian leader,
Yasser Arafat, one of 18 dignitaries considered high security risks
by police, is among the hotel's guests.
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer said he moved to the Waldorf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tomorrow is the same thing again when Mr. Clinton is
going'' there, he said shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudoph Giuliani, who has a history of using U.N.
gatherings to dress down his least favorite world leaders, did not
go uncounted by attacking Fidel Castro of Cuba, who is making his
first visit to New York in several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand and sympathize with the sense of injustice that
much of the Cuban community feels with regard to Fidel Castro,''
Giuliani told a Midtown news conference. ``He's taken the land of
many people, displaced families, killed people.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro will get his chance to turn some heads Wednesday when he
addresses the summit meeting's opening session.
</P>
<P>
   North Korean leaders did not even make it to New York before
they started complaining. They abruptly returned home after being
subjected to security checks at the airport in Frankfurt, Germany.
Choe Su Hon, the North Korean vice minister for foreign affairs,
blamed the United States for the security measures, carried out by
American Airlines, which apparently caused the delegation to miss
its flight.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will shed tears about the absence of the North
Koreans: All the more attention for the rest of us out there.
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem, the main speaker was a no-show and the crowd outside
a funeral home across the street was bigger than the media
contingent on hand. But the Friends of Zimbabwe pressed ahead with
its publicity campaign, one of a gazillion organizations and people
across the city screaming, ``Hey, look at me!''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Wareham, a Brooklyn lawyer, unveiled a poster of Zimbabwe
President Robert Mugabe at the Mt. Olivet Baptist Church on Malcolm
X Boulevard. The Rev. Charles Curtis, pastor at the church, spoke
of an international political and media campaign to discredit
Mugabe. And Amadi Ajamu, the group's publicity chief, handed out a
press release announcing the Zimbabwean president's appearance
Thursday night at the church, a sort of coming out party for the
African leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that he is not really well known in the black
community,'' Wareham said. ``People know Fidel,'' he said referring
to Castro, ``but if they've heard of Mugabe in the mainstream
media, they think he is some kind of maniac.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Mugabe were not alone in their frustration, as
evidenced by the flurry of press releases, some written by hand,
sent to media organizations around the city.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady of South Korea would like it known that she will
help raise money for HIV-infected children at the YMCA in Flushing.
Ambassador Kamalesh Sharma, the Indian representative to the United
Nations, will be happy to answer questions about a book he has
edited, ``Imagining Tomorrow: Rethinking the Global Challenge.''
The American Anti-Slavery Group, with the help of the Guardian
Angels, will attempt to make a citizen's arrest on President Omar
Beshir of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Gorbachev will be talking about the ``state of the
world'' at a $5,000-per-person conference at the New York Hilton
and Towers.The Pakistan Muslim League USA will condemn military
rule in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Anderson did not write a press release, but she is starving
for some attention as well. She runs Al's Delicatessen at what has
become ground zero during Millennium Summit week, 44th Street
between First and Second avenues. Al's lies behind a barricade.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who requested Al's by name were allowed Tuesday to
slip past the police line, but none seemed to know this, and so
what would have been the 1 p.m. sandwich rush became a thin trickle
of secret service agents, police officers and the occasional
regular from the nearby Nigerian Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   After five years in the area, Anderson can tell the difference.
``I can see if they're secret service or state department or with
the detectives or with the policemen,'' she said. ``They all behave
different.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, three men whisked in, placed orders for sandwiches and
headed for a table in the back corner of the room. The one who
seemed to be in charge was clearly a figure of note, Anderson
determined, someone `` very down to business.''
</P>
<P>
   The customer was Leon Fuerth, Vice President Al Gore's national
security adviser, and he polished off a turkey sandwich and a side
of cole slaw over a confab with two staffers that one of them
described only as ``important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't care for his bagel from the Delta Shuttle,''
confided the staff member, who asked that his name not be used.
With its paucity of customers, Al's was the perfect place to talk
foreign policy on the down-low. ``It gave us an opportunity to
engage in our discussion in a typical New York environment,'' the
staffer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
