<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH FIRMS HELP SPONSOR ACADEMIC PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A hybrid between computer science and electrical
engineering courses at California State University, Northridge, is
teaching students about the software and hardware sides of
computers, a combo-talent sought along the Ventura Freeway
technology corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great demand from the industry for students that
have the mix of hardware and software education,'' said Sharlene
Katz, who led the faculty committee that created the curriculum.
``We're really giving them the full picture of computer systems so
it makes them useful to local companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The need, however, isn't limited to the corridor, which extends
from Burbank through L.A.'s San Fernando Valley to the Ventura
County communities of Thousand Oaks and Camarillo. The creators of
the major were driven by the federal rating of computer engineering
as the No. &UR;  &LR; 1 growth field nationally over the next 10 years. The
Bureau of Labor Statistics predicts the number of computer
engineering positions will double between 1998 and 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Hwang, chief operating officer of the Los Angeles
Regional Technology Alliance, said the hybrid is a natural
progression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have a category that is growing larger and larger,
it's prone to more niches like that,'' said Hwang. ``What
programmer hasn't opened up their PC and installed components? The
lines were always sort of blurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Interrante, an applications engineering manager at
Vitesse Semiconductor in Camarillo, said even experienced job
candidates have trouble grasping the new technologies in
development there. A member of the major's advisory board, he said
its curriculum would most come into play at Vitesse when it comes
to directing the operation of circuit boards, a task for engineers
requiring software knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to end up programming programmable logic devices,''
said Interrante. ``That's really where I see it coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to know how many students will be attracted to
the new major, which makes CSUN the ninth out of 23 California
State University campuses to offer it. The first declarations won't
be made until spring. Last year, CSUN issued a total of 363 degrees
to computer science and electrical engineering students.
</P>
<P>
   Some in those programs are expected to modify their course
selections and join the new major, which takes away the mechanical
and civil engineering classes that electrical engineering students
must take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited about the program,'' said Nagwa Bekir, chair of
the Electrical and Computer Engineering Department. ``We believe
we'll have a high turnout and at the same time make all the
companies around us happy.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
