<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-U.S.-ENERGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S NATIONAL GRID ACQUIRES NIAGARA MOHAWK FOR $3 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So far, the names have stayed the same among the small utilities
that serve communities from the Mississippi to the Atlantic, and
from Maine to Florida. But that masks the efforts of the large,
ambitious electricity concerns that are rapidly swallowing local
companies to fashion regional giants. Tuesday's acquisition of
Niagara Mohawk, in upstate New York, by the National Grid Group, of
Britain, highlights that trend.
</P>
<P>
   The $3 billion National Grid purchase, confirmed Tuesday, comes
on the heels of two other mergers. A month ago, FPL Group, of
Florida, merged with Entergy to create a Gulf Coast company with
more than 6 million customers, making it the nation's largest
utility. Weeks later, FirstEnergy acquired GPU, of New Jersey, for
$4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every utility in the country is willing to sit down
and talk with anyone who presents a serious proposal,'' said Tia
Barancik, a lawyer with LeBoeuf, Lamb, Greene &AMP; MacRae who
specializes in utilities .
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast, perhaps more than any other region, has become a
key staging ground for consolidation because it was among the first
places in the country where states deregulated the power industry.
That, in turn, created opportunities for utilities to streamline
their businesses, add new ones and generally make more money than
they had in the past. As a result, local utilities have been
hooking up, as Consolidated Edison is in the process of doing with
Northeast Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, deregulation has drawn the interest of outsiders like
National Grid. Within the last year, the company acquired two other
Northeast utilities, New England Electric Systems and Eastern
Utilities Association. Its purchase of Niagara Mohawk would give
National Grid about 3.3 million electricity customers, making it
the ninth largest electric utility in the country, and 540,000
natural gas customers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Grid acquisitions, analysts say, mark a shift in
the kind of mergers that will unfurl within the industry over the
next few years. Until recently, companies of similar size often
made deals, normally with little reason except to get bigger and
keep competitors at bay. As a result, their shares often took a
drubbing. Now larger companies are pursuing smaller companies to
build a position in a particular market and to fill certain niches.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, National Grid seems to be moving to create an entity
that will distribute power across one of most densely populated
parts of the country. None of National Grid's holdings, including
Niagara Mohawk, actually generate power. Under deregulation, they
sold their power plants and now buy electricity from various
plants, apparently with an eye to getting the lowest price for
themselves and the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the addition of Niagara Mohawk to National Grid's
earlier acquisitions will give the combined company more power to
bargain for cheaper rates when it buys electricity. National Grid
also stated that by streamlining staff and instituting more
efficient business practices, the expanded company would save about
$90 million in the first four years after the merger becomes
official.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk's customers could probably ``receive a healthier
company,'' said Barry Abrahamson, senior electric utility analyst
with PaineWebber. The company neared bankruptcy a few years ago
under the burden of about $3.5 billion in long-term contracts for
highly expensive electricity it had bought a decade earlier, as
part of a state and federal initiative. Niagara Mohawk has paid
about $900 million of that debt and National Grid will assume the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk's shares rose $1.88 Tuesday, to $15.75. That is
well short of the $19 a share the deal works out to, no doubt
reflecting that with all the regulatory hurdles, it could well take
a year before the acquisition is complete. In addition, it must
sell its Nine Mile Point nuclear plant in upstate New York before
the merger goes through.
</P>
<P>
   Despite National Grid's incursions into the Northeast, ratepayer
advocates remain somewhat wary of the deal, since they know little
about the British company. They point out, for example, that the
industry attrition rate is lower than what is expected in the
merger, and therefore the savings from the deal may be less than
predicted. Under an agreement with the state, Niagara Mohawk is
also allowed to keep most of the savings from a merger for five
years, rather than pass them along to customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
