<SLUG> BC-THEATER-SEASON-$ADV </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK THEATER SEASON OFFERS FEW BIG TREATS, BUT MANY SMALL
PLEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
 1 0-NYT (for release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Holding your breath in anticipation is rarely
healthy, and in the theater it is usually suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   A mere few months ago, an improbably rosy horizon seemed to glow
before those rich or fanatical enough to attend Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   That splendid London-born revival of ``Oklahoma!,'' directed by
Trevor Nunn; Donna Murphy recreating her peerless comic performance
in the rarely revived ``Wonderful Town,'' first seen last spring in
an Encores! concert production; and, most tantalizing of all,
Angela Lansbury back onstage, and in a Kander-Ebb musical (``The
Visit'') to boot: all of these mouth-watering prospects were to
materialize in the near future, making the 2000-1 Broadway season
look like a gloriously overstuffed Christmas stocking.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Claus, of course, is known to disappoint. So theater fans
shouldn't be terribly surprised to learn that none of the above is
now expected to reach a Broadway theater anytime soon, with the
possible exception of ``The Visit,'' which in any case will be
without Lansbury.
</P>
<P>
   But if the schedule of big musical treats suddenly looks
skeletal, there are more intimate and eccentric pleasures to be
found elsewhere, smaller productions that nonetheless merit great
expectations. One hesitates to mention them, for fear they might
evaporate before this list reaches print. Kindly remember that
nothing in theater is guaranteed to arrive, either dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there's the return of Edward Albee, one of the
handful of working American playwrights to whom the word ``great''
adheres easily: a dramatist who rarely fails to exasperate and
never fails to intrigue. Albee, whose last new production in New
York was the Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Three Tall Women'' (1993),
will be represented this fall or winter by ``The Play About the
Baby.'' If you think this sounds like a rejected title for Albee's
most famous work, ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?,'' you're not
on the wrong track.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Woolf,'' this dark cosmic comedy, which I saw in an
earlier version in London two years ago, features an older couple
and a younger couple, and a child who may or may not exist. If you
go with an open mind and limited hopes for things like a
straightforward plot, you're likely to have a good time. This
version stars Marian Seldes and Brian Murray, outsized theatrical
presences who, if they rein in their penchants for excess, could be
fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider another theatrical pair, one whose arrival from
England demands attention and arguably even fireworks. That's Alan
Bates and Eileen Atkins, who will be the entire cast of ``The
Unexpected Man,'' the latest offering from Yasmina Reza, who won
over Broadway audiences with her pithy and intermissionless
``Art.'' Atkins, whose natural incisiveness gives elegance to
anything in which she appears, has been seen to fine advantage on
these shores in the last decade in ``Vita and Virginia'' and
``Indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bates, the most soulful of the angry young
actors who dominated British film in the 1960s, hasn't been in a
major New York production in 27 years. That was when he appeared in
the surly title role of Simon Gray's ``Butley,'' and anyone who
remembers that performance will most likely already be ordering
tickets for ``The Unexpected Man.''
</P>
<P>
   You would also be well advised to sign up for the entire season
of the Drama Dept., the most ambitious and eclectic of the city's
young theater troupes and the creators of everything from a
flamboyant deconstruction of ``Uncle Tom's Cabin'' to the
commercial hit ``As Bees in Honey Drown.''
</P>
<P>
   Its latest schedule tentatively and temptingly includes new
works from Douglas Carter Beane, the author of ``Bees,'' and from
David and Amy Sedaris, the iconoclastic brother-sister team who
bill themselves, not without reason, as the Talent Family. (
Sedaris is the author of the current collection of essays ``Me Talk
Pretty One Day,'' while Amy Sedaris stars in ``Strangers With
Candy'' on Comedy Central.)
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, what sounded most promising of all from the
Drama Dept. was a new play by Richard Greenberg. This eloquent
chronicler of urban neuroses, as in ``Eastern Standard'' and
``Three Days of Rain,'' had taken on a subject he seemed born to
tackle: those ultimate urban neurotics and glamorously bad
housekeepers, the Collyer Brothers, in ``The Dazzle.'' The latest
word, however, has it that Greenberg and the Collyers have fallen
off the schedule. Which at least puts them in illustrious company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2358 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NATIONAL-DEBT-BOS &LR;      09-05 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-DEBT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL DEBT LOSES ITS STATUS AS ECONOMIC BOGEYMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York developer Seymour Durst sent every member of Congress a
holiday card in 1981. ``Happy New Year,'' it said, ``your share of
the national debt is $20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Durst took his battle against government
borrowing a step further, attracting headlines nationwide by
hauling a 12-by-20-foot clock up the side of his company's building
in Times Square. The National Debt Clock, he swore, would keep
passersby up to date on Uncle Sam's IOUs _ which were rising
$10,000 a second at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought our cultural and political systems were creating
problems for the future,'' Douglas Durst said of his father, who
died in 1995. ``I'm proud that he did something about it, that he
focused attention on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Durst will retire his father's creation Thursday. Call it a sign
of the times.
</P>
<P>
   With the government running at a surplus for the first time in
three decades, the national debt just isn't a big deal anymore. And
New Yorkers strolling through Times Square aren't going to be the
only ones who notice.
</P>
<P>
   At its current pace, the government could pay off its debts and
stop borrowing within the decade. If that happens, every American
who owns a retirement account, buys a house, finances a car, or
runs up a credit-card tab will feel the impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming the current trend persists, you could see the
Treasury Department stop issuing new debt within five years,'' said
Louis Crandall, chief economist at R. H. Wrightson &AMP; Associates in
New York. ``That's a big deal for just about everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   How big of a deal?
</P>
<P>
   Backed by the ``full faith and credit of the US government,''
Treasuries are a safe haven for investors ranging from pensioners
to pension-fund managers to overseas central bankers. They're also
a key component of money-market accounts, where investors park cash
they don't want to _ or can't afford to _ put at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional bank savings account, backed by a guarantee from
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., will still be there for people
willing to accept interest rates as low as 2 to 3 percent. But
investors who have gotten used to earning twice as much on
Treasuries will be forced to choose between the government's safety
net and higher returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lose the Treasuries and all of the financial markets become a
riskier place to do business,'' said F. Ward McCarthy, managing
director at Stone &AMP; McCarthy Research Associates in Princeton, N.J.
``The one place that doesn't suffer from potential default risk
will have been removed from the equation, and there is no perfect
substitute.''
</P>
<P>
   The quasigovernmental Federal National Mortgage Association
(Fannie Mae) and the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. (Freddie Mac)
have increased their own bond offerings to attract nervous
investors wondering where to stash their cash safely. Corporations
with the highest credit ratings _ such as General Electric _ may
also fill the demand for conservative investments by offering more
bonds to the public.
</P>
<P>
   CDs, or certificates of deposit, are also likely to change, as
banks try to make them more ``bondlike'' _ allowing investors to
cash out early without paying penalties, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to FDIC insurance, CDs offer the government's `full
faith and credit' guarantee in a different guise,'' said Crandall,
of Wrightson Associates. ``Individual investors will almost
certainly see an explosion of FDIC-insured products as Treasuries
are removed from the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Some borrowers, meanwhile, have begun to benefit from the
government's attempt to rein in debt. Mortgage rates and other
consumer loans are lower than they otherwise would be today, though
by how much it's difficult to say.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates have risen over the past year as the Federal
Reserve has attempted to slow the economy's growth. But with excess
money in the credit markets _ at least until safe substitutes are
widely accepted _ rates have risen only gradually, and home sales
have remained high.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the no-government-debt scenario is hardly a sure bet.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office says the Treasury Department
could retire virtually all of its $3.3 trillion in public borrowing
by 2011 if tax revenues and government spending continue at the
current pace. The department could stop issuing new debt years
before that, maybe as soon as 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole thing rests on a big ``if.'' For the numbers to
work, the economy has to stay strong and politicians have to ward
off the temptation to divert more money for tax cuts or additional
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economies cycle, so the trends (behind the debt reduction) are
unlikely to continue forever,'' said Sanjiv Ranjan Das, a finance
professor and bond-market researcher at California's Santa Clara
University. ``I don't think we're in danger of wiping out the
public debt anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, argue that government borrowing will be all but
eliminated within a decade even if politicians can't keep their
hands out of the cookie jar.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers chief economist Stephen Slifer, for example,
said the CBO numbers assume economic growth of 3 percent per year,
which he called ``a lowball forecast.'' Faster growth would allow
the Treasury to pay its debts before 2011, even if politicians help
themselves to some of the bounty.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the Treasury has already initiated a round of
cutbacks likely to continue for at least a couple more years.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the department started buying back 30-year bonds
with remaining maturities of 15 to 25 years. It has taken bonds
worth $19.75 billion off the market in the months since, and hopes
to reach $30 billion by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Treasury said it was actively considering whether to
stop issuing one-year bills altogether, and it has reduced the
frequency and size of the auctions in which it makes various types
of debt available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep whittling away,'' said Jack Kallis, manager of the
State Street Research Government Income mutual fund. ``I'm not yet
convinced that I'll be out of a job (in 2011), but the current
trend is going to continue for another year or two, at least.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, oblivious to what's happening in Times Square
or on Wall Street, another debt clock continues to track the
government's red-tape tally. The Bureau of the Public Debt, at
www.publicdebt.treas.gov/opd/opdpdodt.htm, updates the Web world
daily on how much debt the public holds and how much is owed the
Social Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   And Durst, despite the Manhattan ceremony planned for Thursday,
isn't actually taking his dad's famous chronometer down. He's just
hanging a red, white, and blue curtain in front of it for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has served its function,'' he said, ``but it will still be
there in case things go awry and the debt soars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
