<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2363 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DEATH-TV-$ADV10-2TAKE     09-05 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-TV-$ADV10-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WITNESS TO THE FINAL JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 10)  
Sherwin B. Nuland is clinical professor of surgery at the Yale
School of Medicine and the author of ``How We Die'' (Alfred A.
Knopf). His most recent book is ``The Mysteries Within'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, 2000). 
 
 By SHERWIN B. NULAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two gentle, unobtrusive voices unite the many seemingly
disparate threads that are woven into Bill Moyers' magisterial
documentary on death, ``On Our Own Terms,'' which begins Sunday
night on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the voice of Moyers himself, the temperate sound of
a compassionate understanding that never treads roughshod on the
boundaries of another's sorrow. It does not probe so much as it
simply asks and wonders. Though it is the voice of a stranger, it
speaks in the tones of a fellow seeker, which are tones not only of
one who yearns to know but also of one who yearns to ease the
burden of an inescapable passage, and an inescapable loss. It is in
the unaffected honesty of his questions and his spoken thoughts,
whether uttered to those who are to die or to those who are to lose
them, that Moyers brings to the harsh medium of television a level
of humanity and truth that will leave few viewers unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The other voice is one unheard and yet heard constantly, the
more powerful for being soundless, the more insistent for not
needing words. It is the background against which every sentence in
the entire six hours of the four-night series is spoken, and the
context in which everything must be understood. Were it possible to
set its truth to music, the tune would be played softly _ though
here and there in crescendo _ throughout each scene. By this I mean
the voice formed by the experience of witnessing the death of those
we love, or even of those whose lives have merely crossed our own.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, one or another poet or sage has tried to
express it in language, but its reality beggars the syllables. One
of those sages was the 17th-century physician Thomas Browne, and
this is the way he put it in his ``Religio Medici,'' a journal of
contemplations on the nature of man: ``With what strife and pains
we come into the world, we know not, but 'tis commonly no easy
matter to get out of it.'' For the mortally ill and those who love
them, Browne's aphorism gives voice to a sound that will ever
persist. Almost always, dying is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In this one thing, Moyers falters. He has chosen a misleading
title. Not one of the courageous men and women whom we are
privileged to meet in this documentary dies on his or her own
terms. For each of them, the terms change in the face of what is
permitted by the circumstances of disease, the setting in which it
takes place and the pragmatic necessity to modify expectations.
Compromise inevitably wins out over brave intentions. But this is
the way life is lived, and the way its final chapter is played out.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We do as well as we can, and those to whom we are introduced
here do far better than most.  &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The participants in this documentary represent a broad range of
Americans, and we meet them in a variety of settings, from
university teaching hospital to home, and even out on the Kansas
prairie. They are patients, caregivers and family members, all with
a single goal: a death as tranquil as medical science and
compassion can provide. Though the majority of those we see dying
have cancer, some are succumbing to such problems as liver failure,
degenerative neurological diseases and the destructive effects of
time on the aging body. They come to us as distinctive individuals
much like ourselves, all of whose journeys toward death are unique
to their own circumstances. Those who care for them are unique as
well, and it is in their interactions that we learn what it is like
to die in America today, when accompanied by empathetic men and
women, whether they be highly trained professionals or loving
members of one's own family.
</P>
<P>
   The great message of Moyers' work is not that people die on
their own terms, but that settings and circumstances are beginning
to change, and can change a great deal more. His is a call for
hope, and a demonstration that hope is justified, that each of the
dying may be given a level of comfort that far exceeds what has
been available until recently. The comfort to be attained is not
meant to be physical alone, but spiritual, social and even
existential. It extends to those who are left behind, and even to
the physicians, nurses and others who have consecrated their
careers to such work.
 &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.) &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Their aim, and the hope of all of us who wait to take our place
among the dying or their caregivers, is that compromises may in
time be ever lessened, and the realities come closer to the ideal
of Moyers' wishful title.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Consecrated'' is precisely the right word, in my view, for the
dedication and skill of the doctors and nurses who work in the area
known as comfort care. By letting us see them absorbed in the
moment-to-moment attentions they pay to those in their care, Moyers
helps us to understand the complexity of the problems they handle
with such sensitivity and technical expertise. It has been
extremely difficult for the vast majority of their colleagues to
reorient their efforts toward the relief of symptoms whose very
existence is a reminder of their failure to cure. The movement for
improved care of the dying has led to the founding of more than
2,300 American hospices and countless palliative care units in
hospitals. What may be most impressive to viewers is the relative
youth of the people involved in this new specialty. All but a very
few in the series appear to be no older than perhaps their early
'40s, an age at which the need to cure and the intense drive to
accomplish it _ going sometimes beyond the bounds of reason _ are
at their highest level.
</P>
<P>
   What is also impressive is the range of challenges with which
these new specialists concern themselves. Everything even remotely
connected with the patient's or family's welfare is fair game.
Complex methodologies of pain relief involving ultrasophisticated
pharmacological expertise are discussed in the same clinical
conference that emphasizes the provision of respite days for family
members, or strategies to help patients obtain financial benefits
from government or community sources. These experts are not only
doers but teachers as well, and one can sense that some of them
have already inspired their students with the importance of what
they do and the enormous emotional rewards of doing it. It is to
the example and energy of these young doers and teachers that we
can look for the vast changes that are needed.
</P>
<P>
   What is the best way for those of us who are not professionals
to take part in the campaign to improve the care of the dying?
Moyers and his medical specialists guide the audience to an answer
that follows directly from the evidence implicit in the entire
documentary. Even the finest efforts of the experts will not
suffice if there is no public structure to integrate their
contributions with those of the community and state. What will be
required is a public policy initiative to coordinate the care given
in hospitals, hospices, nursing facilities and the home, in order
not only to solve the comfort problems of the dying but also to
protect their families from bankrupting themselves. (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Much of the necessary government money is already being
ineffectively spent in a hodgepodge of scattered programs, and the
question is largely one of putting the system together and
providing smooth transitions from one part to the next. From where
will the momentum come? The answer lies in a basic principle hidden
within the sociology of medicine, which far too few people take
note of: great changes in the way health care is delivered never
originate with the profession itself but in the public demand for
betterment. When Moyers asks Dr. Joanne Lynn, the director of the
Center to Improve Care of the Dying and one of the nation's
authorities on such problems, why we don't change the system, she
smiles at her own spontaneous, self-evident answer: ``Let's do!
Let's do change it. We the people own the care system that we're
now unhappy with. So we could fix it.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The time for public clamor has come. Were there a great deal
more of it we might move far closer to the ideal of Moyers' title.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such considerations are the main agenda of only the last episode
of ``On Our Own Terms: Moyers on Dying.'' The ones that precede it
tell the stories of the men and women who allowed Moyers and his
camera crews into their lives, to share their final chapters with
him and with us. Although some of them are reasonably prosperous
and seem to be well educated, others are not. The one
characteristic they have in common is that almost all of them not
only are extremely articulate but also have given great thought to
the nature of their sufferings, as have the remarkably devoted
members of their families.
</P>
<P>
   It hardly needs to be added that these few whom we see are also
the lucky or knowledgeable ones who have found their way into the
system, no matter its many imperfections. We never find out much
about those many others left out by the confusion of partly
adequate resources, the squandered public financing and the
continuing avoidance of their problems by the majority of the
medical profession.
</P>
<P>
   Moyers' technique seems deceptively simple: he just lets the
cameras roll while the life of the family or the care unit is going
on. There are no abrupt transitions or endings _ everything is
allowed to complete itself no matter how long it takes, and no
matter the appearance of trivialities that few directors would
allow. It is in the trivialities _ like a child's gift of flowers
to his dying grandmother, or the taking of a family photograph _
that the real art of this production lies, and the real beauty.
</P>
<P>
   It is also in the seeming trivialities that we learn what it is
like to witness the dying of someone about whom we have come to
care, even through this peculiar medium of television. Not a single
participant in these many dramas seems so much as aware of the
filming. They are saying and doing the kinds of things they must
certainly say and do every day of the lives that they so generously
reveal to us.
</P>
<P>
   To accompany the dying is to find something of the divine within
ourselves. Somehow, by force of exquisite insight and a unique kind
of empathy for his subjects and his audience, Bill Moyers has
enabled us to do it. It is an extraordinary accomplishment. Through
it all moves Moyers himself, never prompting, never intrusive,
never more than the voice of the humanity that is in each of us,
and the witness to a particular form of grace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-DRUGS-ART-2NDTAK     09-05 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DRUGS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SCRANTON, Pa.: of 1997.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Health care issues _ most particularly the spiraling cost of
prescription drugs for the elderly _ are some of the most potent
ones on the campaign trail this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's entry into the debate now sets up a sharp competition for
the votes of the elderly who are concerned about health care. In a
sign of just how intent the Democrats are to hold on to their
traditional advantage on the issue, the Democratic National
Committee announced Tuesday that it would begin running a
commercial that seizes on a ruling by a federal judge that Texas
has violated a 1996 agreement to improve its Medicaid program for
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush says he has a plan to improve children's health
care, but why hasn't he done it in Texas?'' the ad asks. Texas is
appealing the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Gore came out with his own prescription drug plan months ago.
Showing the philosophical difference between the two parties, it is
more expensive that Bush's _ costing at least $253 billion over 10
years _ and it creates the prescription drug benefit inside the
traditional Medicare program. His coverage for people with
catastrophic drug costs would kick in after a beneficiary spent
$4,000 on medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan would pay all drug costs for the approximately 13
million uncovered Medicare recipients with incomes up to about
$11,300 a year. For those with higher incomes, his plan would pay
half of a Medicare recipient's drug costs up to $5,000 a year. Once
that cap is met beneficiaries would pay out of pocket up to an
additional $1,500. After that catastrophic coverage would kick in.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides say the uniform nature of their plan is part of its
appeal _ that it would effectively give Medicare vast purchasing
power and the ability to extract deep discounts from drug makers.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of
America, the trade group that represents the major drug companies
in Washington, said that the group's experts were still reviewing
the details of Bush's plan and could not say yet whether they
supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Neil B. Sweig, a drug industry analyst at Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co., said
that Bush's plan was clearly more ``favorable'' to the drug
companies and to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, much like the drug industry, criticized Gore's plan
Tuesday as a step toward government price controls. ``By making
government agents the largest purchaser of prescription drugs in
America,'' Bush said, ``by making Washington the nation's
pharmacist, the Gore plan puts us well on the way to price control
for drugs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
