<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2373 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-LEAN-SEASON-$ADV     09-05 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LEAN-SEASON-$ADV10-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE `SERIOUS' SEASON, AND OTHER MYTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 10)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every culture cherishes the myths and rituals by which it marks
the change of seasons, and associates different times of the year
with appropriate modes of expression. According to the literary
critic Northrop Frye, each of the four seasons of the Northern
Hemisphere has given rise to a correlative genre: satire belongs to
winter, comedy to spring, romance to summer and tragedy to fall.
Our present civilization has little appetite for tragedy, but a
wispy shadow of Frye's theory persists, as the coming of autumn
brings children back to school and putatively serious movies back
into the multiplexes. As the days grow shorter, the running times
grow longer. Special effects give way to feats of costume and set
design. The box office sprints of the Memorial and Independence Day
weekends, and the damaged-goods studio yard sales of late August,
are soon forgotten as the long march toward Christmas _ and the
Oscars _ begins. Hollywood, after a three-month revel in expensive
triviality, knits its brow and dons its glasses to signal a renewed
commitment to expensive importance.
</P>
<P>
   This, at any rate, is the myth, though a recent article in
Variety _ with the enchanting headline ``Fall Films Favor Frothy
Fare'' _ suggests that its power and relevance may be diminishing.
The film industry's autumnal hopes seem to be pinned, for the
moment, on a live-action adaptation, ``Dr. Seuss' How the Grinch
Stole Christmas,'' and an updating of the '70s television show
``Charlie's Angels,'' which not even those of us who decorated our
bedrooms with pictures of its crime-fighting stars ever considered
a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   There are further signs that cinematic seriousness has fallen on
hard times. In another article in the same issue, Variety reported
that ``art films'' _ art in the quantitative sense, meaning movies
shown on 600 or fewer screens nationwide _ had suffered a 14
percent decline in box office revenues so far this year, as
compared with 1999 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Among critics, the nervous high spirits of 1999 _ a year that
seemed to herald a revival of risky, innovative American filmmaking
(tribute to which was paid by the Academy's embrace of the tame,
derivative ``American Beauty'') _ have dissipated, leaving an air
of gloom and resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this pessimism reflects a momentary and recurrent mood
swing _ for most of its history, at least since the coming of the
talkies, the cinema has been reported by somebody or other to be in
decline _ or a true intimation of mortality remains to be seen. In
any case, the love of an art form that is the critic's first
obligation often expresses itself as a protective grumpiness about
the art's current prospects. But it does seem worthwhile to ask, in
the spirit of love as well as duty, what we mean by calling some
movies serious, and how we go about taking them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   These questions are more complicated than they sound, and any
attempt to address them risks tripping the buried land mines of
past debates _ between Sarrisites and Kaelites, between humanists
and formalists, between worshipers at the shrine of difficulty and
pagan celebrants in the cult of pop. The past century has witnessed
a series of attempts to draw, to blur and to erase altogether the
boundaries that separate high culture from low. The movies, which
have done more than any other medium to upend such lazy and
invidious distinctions, have nonetheless been irresistible to those
who rely on them. A reflexive snobbery based on uncritical
valuation of the foreign, the arty, the ``independent'' often
confronts an equally automatic sham-populist deference to mass
taste.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth _ a truth every moviegoer and honest critic
instinctively knows _ is that you can't judge experience according
to prefabricated categories. There are plenty of dull, meretricious
films dressed up (or down, given the current art house bias in
favor of the hand-held and the rough-hewn) in the trappings of art,
and just as many gaudy commercial toys that turn out to be vehicles
of aesthetic transcendence.
</P>
<P>
   Another myth that seems especially dear these days to critics of
literature and pop music as well as movies is the myth of the lost
heroic age, in whose shadow the sickly, pale inhabitants of the
present are doomed to labor. The memory of two such ages haunts
critics, audiences and filmmakers alike: the nearer one is the
golden, squandered moment of the New Hollywood, which unfolded in
the decade between ``Bonnie and Clyde'' and ``Star Wars'' _ the era
of ``Nashville'' and the ``Godfather'' movies, of ``Mean Streets''
and ``Chinatown'' and Pauline Kael. This moment, sometimes called
the era of American auteurism, saw the late flowering of seeds
planted in the first golden age, a decade or so earlier, which
witnessed, among other developments, the adaptation of the auteur
theory to an American context, the founding of the New York Film
Festival, the canonization of classic Hollywood, and the cresting
of the French New Wave.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '50s and early '60s, through the efforts of a
dedicated cadre of critics, editors, repertory programmers and
besotted cinephiles (or film buffs, if you prefer), a lively and
serious film culture began to emerge in the larger American cities,
filtering out onto college campuses and suburban film clubs. The
institutional and intellectual achievement of this culture was
substantial: its adherents led the way in efforts to preserve the
movies of the past, recognized the embattled craftsmen of the old
Hollywood as important artists, and made elevated critical
discussion of movies seem both urgent and chic. ``We looked to
filmmakers to be our novelists, our sages,'' Philip Lopate has
written in ``Anticipation of La Notte,'' his wry, clearsighted
essay on his own youthful movie mania. ``Film enjoyed as never
before (or since) the prestige of high culture.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. Lopate's reminiscence, happily, is concerned less
with prestige than with pleasure, and the critical essays collected
in his engaging 1998 book ``Totally, Tenderly, Tragically'' are,
like any criticism worth reading, evidence that seriousness is an
ennobled form of delight. Is it also an endangered one? Movies are
bigger than ever. Have our ways of talking about them gotten small?
Each year more of them flicker across our screens _ and there is,
suddenly, a glut of screens, with new megaplexes sprouting from
Times Square to Tulsa _ or illuminate our living rooms. But the
film culture whose heroic age Lopate celebrates survives in
fragments. The ``film generation,'' the transformative impact of
whose arrival the critic Stanley Kauffman hailed nearly 40 years
ago, has been succeeded, with breathtaking and brutal speed, by
generations reared on rock 'n' roll, on television and now online.
</P>
<P>
   The relations between these generations _ the tangle of envy,
impatience, admiration and bewilderment that informs their regard
for each other _ is a central and underacknowledged fact of our
culture and our politics. To those filmgoers born too late to see
``L'Avventura'' in its initial run, or who never set foot in the
Thalia or the old second-run theaters of Times Square, who first
saw ``The Godfather'' on video and ``Breathless'' on cable _ to
most of the movie audience, in other words _ the endless hymning of
the glories of the past can seem like a dropped gauntlet we
hesitate to pick up
</P>
<P>
   How can the delights of different ages be compared? Isn't my
formative enchantment with Molly Ringwald the equal of your
undergraduate lust for Julie Christie or Anouk Aimee? Is my ``Dazed
and Confused'' worth less than your ``Dolce Vita''? Isn't it all
just a matter of taste?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, but there's more to taste than knowing what you like,
and if lived experiences are incommensurable with each other, works
of art nonetheless demand to be ranked, judged and argued about _
that's part of the fun. It's also, I'm tempted to say, a fact of
human nature. Arguments about whether the movies are on the verge
of death or the cusp of a new golden age _ thanks to digital video,
computer-generated imagery, the internet, Dogma 95, globalization
or Adam Sandler _ are likely to continue. A new golden age _ the
indie moment, the Chinese new wave, the discovery of Iran _ may be
just behind us, or just ahead. (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL
MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   The more important arguments, the ones that will determine the
future of this protean and impatient (and still young) art form,
will be about particular movies. Here, perhaps, there is cause for
some concern. The rise first of the video store and then of the
Internet has made movies and the discussion of them more accessible
than ever before. These technologies have also contributed to the
fragmentation of audiences, and the triumph of niche marketing and
complacent subjectivism. The film industry, with serious money on
the line, helps to trivialize its product, drowning conversation in
bullying hype. Movies, whose expense demands that they remain a
mass medium, get bigger and smaller at the same time _ either gaudy
baubles or tiny diamonds in the rough. Some you can't see: a trip
to the new 12-screen movie palace ends in the discovery that half
of the screens are devoted to half-hourly showings of the same
blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   In the golden year of 1999, already receding into myth, several
brilliantly unlikely American movies _ ``Being John Malkovich,''
``Boys Don't Cry'' _ broke through to audiences. But a number of
others _ ``Election,'' ``Three Kings'' and ``Go'' _ foundered in
spite of the ardor of critics. Others arrive disfigured by the
sham-democracy of test-marketing and the bureaucratic
authoritarianism of top-down scriptwriting by committee. This year
has so far seen the release of a number of interesting movies _
``Jesus' Son,'' ``Chuck and Buck,'' ``American Psycho'' and at
least a half-dozen more _ that seemed to require, and to languish
in the absence of, the protective embrace and the critical scrutiny
of a devoted audience.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of the three films just mentioned _ Alison Maclean,
Miguel Arteta and Mary Harron _ have each now made two commercial
features that show them to be stylistically daring and
intellectually curious. They and other emerging voices, including
those who have been graced with the success to allow them their
choice of projects, are in need of defenders and debunkers. The
serious movies are out there, in search of a culture. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000905.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2376 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-R-SCI-ULTIMATE-LAPTOP     09-05 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-ULTIMATE-LAPTOP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPTOPS AREN'T BLACKHOLES _ YET _ BUT THE ULTIMATE ONE MAY BE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: SUBS to supply substitutions for numbers that should appear
in scientific notation, in 14th graf and throughout; e.g., `(10 to
the 16th) joules' sted `1016 joules')   By GEORGE JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the corporate enthusiasm over the unveiling of each new
generation of computer chip (last month Intel announced that its
Pentium 4 would be packed with 42 million transistors performing as
many as 8.4 billion operations per second), consumers may be more
apt to feel a sense of dread. Once again the expensive desktop
computers and laptops they were so proud of have become outmoded,
destined to join the scrap piles of unsalable equipment
accumulating in closets everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's law, which holds that computing power doubles
approximately every 18 months, therefore sometimes seems less a
blessing than a curse. But the law cannot hold forever, and Seth
Lloyd, an associate professor of mechanical engineering at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, offers hope that the end is
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper in the current issue of Nature, Lloyd describes the
ultimate laptop _ a computer as powerful as the laws of physics
would allow. So energetic is this imaginary machine that using it
would be like harnessing a thermonuclear reaction. In the most
extreme version of this computer supreme, so much computational
circuitry would be packed into so small a space that the whole
thing would collapse from its own gravity forming a tiny black
hole, an object so dense that not even light can escape its
gravity.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a rather dangerous device to hold on one's
lap _ ``Opening the lid,'' Lloyd warns, ``voids the warranty'' _
there is a serious purpose to his theoretical tour de force: to
plumb the absolute limits nature sets on computation.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like Lloyd's Ultimate Laptop is likely to ever roll off
the assembly line at some future Apple or IBM. But his effort, part
of a relatively new discipline called the physics of information,
gives computer engineers an ideal to aim for. More importantly,
this exercise in extreme computer science may help deepen the
understanding of the connections between physics and information,
and explore the notion, popular among many theorists, that the very
processes of nature can be thought of as computations.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's Law, named for its formulator Gordon Moore, a founder of
Intel, has continued to hold true because of the dexterity with
which engineers have been able to inscribe smaller and smaller
circuitry onto silicon computer chips. As the components of the
circuits are squeezed closer and closer together, they can exchange
information at increasingly faster speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been predicting the demise of Moore's law pretty
much since it was posited in the early '60s because some
manufacturing technology was about to run out,'' Lloyd said. ``But
Moore's law is a law of human ingenuity rather than of nature.
Predictions of its demise have been wrong because people are
ingenious.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, engineers have continued to find ways to make the
circuits smaller and faster.
</P>
<P>
   The vanishingly tiny components on a chip can be thought of as
switches that can be in two positions, either on or off _
representing a bit of information, 1 or 0. Minuscule as they seem,
each of these devices is typically made of about a billion atoms.
But laboratories are already experimenting with computers in which
a bit is stored by a single atom that can spin clockwise or
counterclockwise, indicating a 1 or a 0. And who is to say that the
grain could not someday be even finer with subatomic particles like
quarks or gluons or even the hypothetical superstrings harnessed to
encode and manipulate information?
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately the limits of nature must prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we believe the laws of physics,'' Lloyd said, ``then the
fundamental constants of nature should tell us where Moore's law
absolutely has to end, where we can't miniaturize any further.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd approached the problem like a consumer in the market for a
new laptop. ``If you're going out to buy a computer,'' he said,
``you have two basic questions: how fast is it and how much memory
space does it have?'' Those are the ingredients of computing power.
He assumed that his laptop would have about the same dimensions as
a contemporary one, weighing a kilogram, 2.2 pounds, and occupying
1 liter of space.
</P>
<P>
   First he set out to determine how fast his ultimate laptop could
compute. The limiting factor here is energy: the faster a computer
runs, the more voracious its appetite. So what would be the maximum
possible energy available to a portable machine?
</P>
<P>
   One could speculate endlessly on the future of battery
technology. Seeking a more fundamental answer, Lloyd looked to
Einstein's special theory of relativity. If every particle of the
laptop's kilogram of mass is converted into energy according to the
equation E(EQ)mc2 , the answer is 8.9874 x (10 to the 16th) joules
_ or in more familiar terms, 25 million megawatt-hours, the amount
of energy produced by all the world's nuclear power plants in 72
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine would be cannibalizing its own mass to perform its
operations,'' Lloyd mused. No engineer from Eveready or Duracell
could ever squeeze more juice from a chunk of matter.
</P>
<P>
   There would be obvious practical considerations to controlling
(and computing with) what would amount to thermonuclear fusion.
(Lloyd speculated that the computer's ``circuitry'' might consist
of electrons and antimatter positrons, signaling each other with
gamma rays.) But the details are unimportant. Ultimate computer
science is not about what is probable but what is possible. The
rest can be left to the engineers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
