<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   RAD-CHILDREN _ Ericka Brown-Abram thinks she had a typical
childhood. Her mother's friends were killed in police shootouts.
Her family lived under FBI surveillance. She was constantly
shadowed by a bodyguard, even when she ran after the neighborhood
ice cream truck. Brown, 30, the daughter of a Black Panther Party
leader, once thought there was nothing unusual about growing up in
a communal home and attending a grade school where students read
Mao Tse-Tung's Red Book. ``A lot of people had this swashbuckling
idea of the Panthers,'' she said. ``But when you're a child it all
seemed normal.'' Nothing was normal, though, about growing up in
the 1950s and '60s as a child of the civil rights movement. The
people at the center of the struggle led dramatic, often dangerous,
lives. So, too, did their kids. These children of the movement _
the offspring of black militants, nonviolent activists and even
segregationist leaders _ are now adults. The Children of the
Movement have followed many roads in recent years. Some continue to
carry on their parents' work. Others want only to forget their
childhood. Here are the stories of nine of them. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING _Arctic sea ice has thinned by 40 percent in the
last 30 years. This summer, there was open water at the North Pole.
From the Andes to the Alps, mountain glaciers are retreating. And
across North America, from the fire-scorched West to the
drought-parched Southeast, the last year of the millenium has given
millions a summer of discontent. As the signs of a warmer world
grow more apparent, there are some nagging new questions about ways
to prevent it. A new analysis by NASA physicist James Hansen, one
of the first scientists to sound the alarm over global warming 20
years ago, suggests that industrialized nations struggling to
implement a reduction in carbon dioxide emissions called for under
the proposed 1997 Kyoto Protocol, may be pursuing the wrong
villains in the global greenhouse mystery. (Toner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
