<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-BEST-WOMEN0906-CO     09-05 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-BEST-WOMEN0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four are fantastic for women's tour
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The real U.S. Open women's draw begins today.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams plays Lindsay Davenport in the quarterfinals,
where one of the Fab Four of the WTA Tour actually could lose.
</P>
<P>
   The other ``Fabs'' _ Martina Hingis and Venus Williams _ are
expected to meet in the semifinals Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The WTA Tour never has had at one time four players so good and
so evenly matched. The four have won 10 of the last 15 Grand Slam
titles. In the U.S. Open, they have won 34 of their 36 sets.
</P>
<P>
   And each one of them believes that she is the best female tennis
player on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I deserve to be No. 1,'' said Venus Williams, who
is No. 3 in the rankings. ``There's no way I'm going to say, `I'm
happy at No. 3; I like it here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has won a tour-leading 24 matches in a row. She also
has gone 4-0 against the other three, defeating each at least once.
</P>
<P>
   But her sister, Serena, is the defending champion here. Serena
was the tour's toughest to beat last year, with a leading 41-7
(.854) record. She is 7-2 against the other Fabs over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Serena's development has been impeded by the tendinitis in her
knee that kept her out of the Australian Open, and by the burden of
sibling rivalry; she is 1-4 against Venus.
</P>
<P>
   That record is not from lack of confidence. Serena picks herself
to win here and expects to see Venus in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an opportunity that would just be magnificent,''
she said. ``It's what we've wanted our whole careers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williams sisters are 42-1 since Wimbledon when not playing
each other, prompting Serena to add, ``Everyone wants to beat a
Williams sister now. It's the person to beat. That's just the way
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Jelena Dokic, whom Serena beat Monday, agreed. ``They're
probably the two players at the moment that are just _ they're
unbeatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that's what they were saying earlier this year about
Davenport when she won 36 of 37 matches over seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Through the Australian Open, Davenport had won three of the last
six majors. Then, an injury to her left ankle forced her out of two
clay-court tournaments, and a back injury ruined two more, leading
to a first-round loss at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Wimbledon, where Venus beat her 6-3, 7-6 in the final,
Davenport claimed she was just 70 percent. Then, she sprained her
foot three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so excited (in the U.S. Open) when I realized I was
going to be able to play 100 percent with no pain, being able to
give it all I got,'' Davenport said. ``The last Grand Slams, it
hasn't been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Hingis, merely the No. 1-ranked player. Head to
head against the others, Hingis' case is weak. She is 2-7 over the
past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hingis has been the most efficient through four rounds here.
She is averaging just eight errors per match. Hingis has no
double-faults; Venus has 37.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to beat Martina is if you overpower her,'' Monica
Seles said. ``She's the best at her style of game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis also leads the tour in wins (54) and could be No. 1 in
winning percentage by knocking off Venus in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Williamses, I think so far I've been better than them,''
said Hingis, noting that she has five major titles, the same as the
other three combined. ``I haven't been injured as them. It's just
the consistency. That's what counts to be No. 1, not who wins the
most tournaments or hits the ball the fastest.... So we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
