<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW THAT LOOK WORTH THE EXTRA WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 10)  
 By   CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a television season whose big names include Bette Midler,
Geena Davis and Gabriel Byrne, all starring in sitcoms, the most
promising series belong to Andre Braugher, David E. Kelley and some
guy who looks like David Letterman. Their shows are not entirely
original; let's be realistic, that is not what most television
series do. Yet they accomplish something equally good, breathing
fresh life into traditional genres.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital drama is obviously coming to the end of its cycle,
with ``Chicago Hope'' dead and ``ER'' old enough in television
years (six) to enter the geriatric ward. ``Gideon's Crossing''
(ABC, Wednesdays at 10) gives it a new depth by focusing on one
intense, humane doctor, played by Andre Braugher of ``Homicide.''
His character, Ben Gideon, may be softer than Frank Pembleton, the
uncompromising detective who was the vehicle for some of the best
acting on the air during that show's run.
</P>
<P>
   But Gideon and the new show have some similarities to Pembleton
and ``Homicide'' that are cause for optimism. Gideon, a widower
with two small children, shares Pembleton's soul-searching
tendencies. The show was created by Paul Attanasio, a creator of
``Homicide'' (and the writer of the film ``Quiz Show''). Though the
medical stories are crucial, with Ruben Blades playing Gideon's
friend and hospital colleague, the show promises to replace the
fast-paced, ensemble approach of ``ER'' with a sharper focus on
character and psychology. In most seasons one drama emerges from
the buzz of hype as the most intelligent (not the same as most
likely to succeed). This season that show is undoubtedly ``Gideon's
Crossing.''
</P>
<P>
   In general the dramas are more enticing than the comedies this
year, and another exceptionally promising one is created by David
E. Kelley, who may not be a movie star but is the biggest of
television names behind the scenes. He created the comedy-drama of
``Ally McBeal,'' but with ``Boston Public'' (Fox, Mondays at 8) he
tries to do for teachers in a Boston high school what his terrific
dramatic series ``The Practice'' does for lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Like the characters on ``The Practice,'' the teachers in
``Boston Public'' are imperfect, under stress, facing a range of
up-to-date problems. It has been 20 years since teachers were
television heroes, and then it was in second-rate '70s shows like
``Room 222'' or ``The White Shadow.'' ``Boston Public'' reflects
changing times with plots that include violence and a student Web
site that scatologically lampoons a teacher. Kelley's sensibility
and writing, smartly attuned to the ambiguity of social problems,
should distinguish this as more than a show about teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Among comedies, there is one clear standout: ``Welcome to New
York'' (CBS, Wednesdays at 8:30), set in a television newsroom that
is far away, in miles and in tone, from the Minneapolis station
that sheltered Mary Richards in ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, Christine Baranski plays the acerbic, jaded executive
producer of a morning news program. She hires a Midwestern
weatherman (a job David Letterman actually used to have), whose
culture shock includes the backbiting and paranoia of his ruthless
colleagues. The weatherman is played by Jim Gaffigan, who looks and
sounds a lot like the early Dave (same sandy hair, same round face)
without the sarcasm. Since Letterman's company, Worldwide Pants, is
one of the show's producers, let's assume this is intentional.
Gaffigan's engaging demeanor, Baranski's better-known comic edge
and the series' sharp writing allow ``Welcome to New York'' to rise
above its unlikely premise.
</P>
<P>
   While the most promising dramas and sitcoms do not come from the
season's most glittery Hollywood names, the most anticipated
miniseries does. Steven Spielberg and Tom Hanks are executive
producers of ``Band of Brothers,'' a 10-part miniseries (HBO,
starting in June) set during World War II. The setting evokes
``Saving Private Ryan,'' and the producers' cachet has made this
among the biggest-budgeted miniseries ever at $130 million. The
series is based on the historian Stephen Ambrose's book about an
Army rifle company that parachuted into France on D-Day. The
soldiers are played by a group of little-known actors, though the
various directors include Hanks and Phil Alden Robinson (``Field of
Dreams''). ``Band of Brothers'' is poised to tap into the
regenerated hero worship of those who took part in World War II,
the spirit that has made the title of Tom Brokaw's best-selling
book ``The Greatest Generation'' enter the language as a common
phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Don't anticipate any of this too soon. Because of the Olympics,
not to mention interruptions by the World Series and possibly
presidential debates, the networks have agreed that the new season
will not begin until October this year. Some new series will begin
as late as November. In a perfect world, that would give the less
promising shows time to whip themselves into better shape. Keep
dreaming. Keep in mind that having three new series to anticipate
with real enthusiasm is three more than you can find in some
seasons. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
