<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S ECONOMIC PLAN? HE COULD WRITE A BOOK ON IT, AND DOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Gore campaign released a detailed economic
blueprint for the next decade on Tuesday, including a $300 billion
hedge against overly optimistic budget projections, a commitment to
eliminate the national debt and a broad variety of socioeconomic
goals like increasing family income, reducing poverty and narrowing
the gap in wages between men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is to discuss the plan, much of it a synthesis of proposals
he has made over the last several months, in a speech here on
Wednesday. Details are being published in a 200-page book, unique
in modern presidential campaigns in that it is essentially a budget
proposal that will serve as an economic and political manifesto.
</P>
<P>
   The number-heavy and footnoted book, which was made available to
The New York Times, underscores Gore's determination to supply
specifics in his policy proposals and is intended to serve as a
counterweight to the campaign of Gov. George W. Bush, which the
Gore camp regards as light on policy and based largely on
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the book anticipates criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that what we are doing here defies conventional
wisdom, putting out a detailed economic plan, full of specifics for
our opponents to ridicule, attack or belittle,'' Gore and his
running mate, Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, wrote in the introduction.
``But we think that the American people are entitled to know what
we would do to grow our prosperity if elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers denied any suggestion that the release of the plan
was timed to offset Bush's issuance of his Medicare overhaul
proposal on Tuesday. The Gore campaign drafted its plan for months
with help from Clinton administration experts like Robert E. Rubin,
former treasury secretary; Laura D. Tyson, former chairwoman of the
Council of Economic Advisers; and Gene Sperling, President
Clinton's top economic adviser. Rubin is to join Gore for the
presentation here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign said its blueprint was the road to continued
economic expansion. And Gore's goals, like reducing the poverty
level to below 10 percent for the first time in history, and
increasing the number of college graduates depend on that
continuation.
</P>
<P>
   So does his plan to set aside $300 billion over the decade as a
cushion against shortfalls in projections by the Congressional
Budget Office, which estimates a surplus of $1.8 trillion, the same
estimates used by the Bush campaign. The Clinton administration has
used the more conservative estimates of the Office of Management
and Budget, which amount to $1.4 trillion. Senior Gore advisers
said that if the administration estimates proved correct, no
reserve fund would be set aside.
</P>
<P>
   But an analysis of the Gore budget prepared by the Senate Budget
Committee, headed by Sen. Pete Domenici (R-N.M.) says that Gore has
proposed such extensive spending that he would even have to dip
into Social Security to pay for his programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about the largest expansion of federal spending
since the days of Lyndon Johnson, and a significant portion will
have to come out of the Social Security surplus,'' said Bob
Stevenson, spokesman for the committee. ``Based on our analysis,
he's already devoured all of the available non-Social Security
surplus, so if his intention is to set up a $300 billion rainy day
fund, he would have to take it out of the Social Security
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign says that its program is sound and would
eliminate the publicly held federal debt by 2012, while Bush's, it
said, would leave the government $2.8 trillion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Gore described his plan as ``comprehensive and detailed and
chock full of specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan says that through increased productivity, a Gore
administration could raise family incomes by one-third over the
next decade. It estimates productivity growth at 2.8 percent
annually, by paying down the debt, investing in biomedical research
and computer technology and opening more markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing all these things, and much more, we can grow incomes
faster than any 10-year period ever recorded,'' the plan says. ``As
a result, after-tax incomes would grow by one-third over the next
decade.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign says that it has proposed targeted tax cuts
amounting to $500 billion over 10 years, but Republicans said these
are illusory and so complicated that no one can be sure how much
anyone will save. The Senate analysis says the proposals amount to
$300 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
