<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2392 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ANTIQUES-SEASON-$ADV1     09-05 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-SEASON-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME TIME   FOR PRIVATE   COLLECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By   RITA REIF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American collectors in the late 20th century went bonkers over
art. Week after week they chalked up records, buying Rembrandts,
Renoirs and Rauschenbergs and becoming instant celebrities at
black-tie auctions in New York and London. The consumer society had
met the art world head on, and collecting evolved into a sport of
mass buying more reminiscent of the style of William Randolph
Hearst than of Andrew Mellon.
</P>
<P>
   Once awakened, the obsessive appetite for art spawned more grand
acquisitors than the world had ever seen. Armed with the basics
from Art 101 and from visiting museums everywhere, many collectors
_ school teachers, salesmen, rock stars and Wall Street
arbitrageurs _ looked beyond the paintings and sculpture that had
once satisfied most elite art buyers. Instead they looked to
acquire exotic and everyday things. They amassed so much quality
French furniture, Chinese bronzes, Japanese screens, German toy
trains, Venetian glass, African masks and American folk art that
they sometimes surpassed the museums. Since it was no fun to play
alone with their adult toys, they lent, gave or sold their objects
to museums, and occasionally even paid for the galleries and wings
to accommodate the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The collecting phenomenon enriched most everyone _ buyers,
sellers, museums and the public. But there were drawbacks when
collectors gained too much power, lending art of lesser quality,
dictating how their art should be displayed or using an exhibition
as a launching pad for an auction. For the most part, though, such
practices are the exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In the year ahead there will be an amazing variety of private
art collections starring in exhibitions at museums across the
country. Three in New York illustrate why private art collections
are formed, why museums exhibit them _ and in some cases acquire
them _ and why museumgoers find them irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   When word gets around that a quintessential collection, of even
the most esoteric material, is about to go on view, the show
becomes a must see for serious art enthusiasts. One such show,
``The Embodied Image: Chinese Calligraphy From the John B. Elliott
Collection,'' opens next Friday at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
``The most important and comprehensive exhibition of its kind ever
assembled in the West,'' the press release announces.
</P>
<P>
   The 55 masterworks from the Elliott collection take center stage
in the show. It also includes works from the museum's own holdings
that were collected by John M. Crawford Jr., heir to an
oil-drilling fortune, and a group of rubbings of early engraved
calligraphies, lent by Robert H. Ellsworth, a New York dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Before he bought calligraphy, Elliott, a Wall Street financier,
dabbled in Japanese folk art. In 1967, he started at the top,
buying a dynamic work of bold, diagonal strokes by the 11th-century
poet Huang Tingjian, a work that remains the most important in the
collection. With the help of Wen C. Fong, a professor of art
history at Princeton University (later a consultant to the
Metropolitan Museum), Elliott had acquired the bulk of his
calligraphies by 1970, but added rarities as he found them until
his death in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott always collected ``with an institutional perspective,''
as Maxwell K. Hearn, curator of Asian art at the Metropolitan
Museum, put it. Elliott's interest in Asian art began while he was
a student at Princeton University in the 1950s. He had wanted to
build a pre-eminent collection and leave it to the museum at
Princeton (which he ultimately did). But his dream, which he shared
with Crawford, a bibliophile and arts patron who died in 1988, was
to have their collections exhibited together at the Metropolitan
Museum. Now their dream will be realized.
</P>
<P>
   Other collectors become involved with a museum at the start of
their collecting, consciously making selections with the needs of
the museum in mind. This approach is apparent in ``An Engagement
with Folk Art: Cyril I. Nelson's Gifts to the Museum of American
Folk Art,'' which will be on view through Jan.7.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson began collecting American folk art in 1972 while editing
a book on painted furniture. Soon he was buying works of great
virtuosity _ quilts, coverlets, stencilled watercolors, portraits,
landscapes, painted furniture and sculpture, produced from 1800 to
1940. In 1974, he joined the museum board, always looking for ways
to strengthen its collection. ``The quilts he favored are unlike
any we owned,'' said Gerard C. Wertkin, the museum director. ``And
we were very weak on Maine forms in furniture until Cy found an
elaborately painted 1830s blanket chest.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 113 objects that Nelson gave to the museum, 50 are in the
exhibition. The quirkiest, a late 19th-century wood sculpture.
``Dove,'' once sat atop a pole in a Kansas grainery.
</P>
<P>
   Museums today are quick to seize on objects they think will
attract new audiences. Collectibles, like baseball cards and
vintage eyeglasses, do just that. This season's ultimate pop
culture extravaganza, ``Robots, Astronauts and Space Toys: The
Robert Lesser Collection,'' will be an exhibition of 250 examples
at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, from Nov. 10 to Feb. 1. Lesser, a
retired electric-sign salesman, amassed one of the most extensive
collections of toy robots from the 1930s to the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Lehman, the museum director, came upon the robots while
visiting Lesser to see his collection of pulp art of the '30s and
'40s. The robots were chockablock in the apartment, and Lehman was
dazzled. He immediately persuaded Lesser to lend the collection to
the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, everyone is able to collect something,'' Lehman said.
``For me the kind of mentality represented in this collection is
totally fascinating. We talk about 19th-century American paintings
as the romance of the wilderness. Well, robots are about romance,
too _ the romance of outer space.'' &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
