<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF RACE WIDE OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Major League Soccer's marathon season is now
a sprint to the finish with five teams capable in the final week of
earning the best record.
</P>
<P>
   With two victories, the Los Angeles Galaxy (14-8-8, 50 points)
could do no worse than the fourth seed, which would earn Los
Angeles home-field advantage in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   However, a loss against either Dallas tonight at the Rose Bowl
or Friday at Colorado would end any realistic hopes the Galaxy has
of catching Western Division-leading Kansas City (15-7-8, 53
points).
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many possibilities, but we can't worry how the
other games unfold,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid. ``We have to
take care of our business, win our last two games, then find out
how the chips fell.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the five teams at the top, New York/New Jersey (16-11-3, 51
points) can do no worse than a third seed after wrapping up the
Eastern Division.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (16-12-3, 51 points) and Chicago (15-9-6, 51 points)
are tied for the Central Division lead, but the Fire has the edge
with two games left while the Mutiny has one.
</P>
<P>
   If the Galaxy finishes second to Kansas City, it will play the
Central Division runner up in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   But no use figuring this out now. The Galaxy will have a better
idea of what's in store after tonight. K.C. is at New England, then
finishes at Tampa Bay on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league did a good job with parity,'' said Galaxy
goalkeeper Kevin Hartman. ``This is how it should be, competitive
all the way to the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were too many meaningless games last season because some
teams clinched early. This way, everyone is sharp heading into the
playoffs because every game counts until the end.''
</P>
<P>
   This week is also a chance for Schmid to test his group without
Olympians Danny Califf, Sasha Victorine and Peter Vagenas, who will
miss the first round of the playoffs and possibly the second.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Caligiuri will step in for Califf while midfielders Brian
Kelly and Ivan Polic audition for Vagenas' spot. Up front, former
UCLA striker Seth George will share time with Sebastian Vorbe
replacing Victorine. Both George and Vorbe scored during the
Galaxy's 2-1 victory over San Jose last week. George will start
tonight, as he did against San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both played well last week, so I thought I would not
change anything,'' said Schmid. ``As far as the playoffs go, I'll
have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (12-14-4, 40 points), led by Galaxy killer Ariel
Graziani, is fighting for the eighth playoff seed along with
Colorado (12-15-4, 40 points).
</P>
<P>
   If either the Burn or Rapids stumble, Columbus and Miami, both
at 38 points, could sneak into the playoff picture with a pair of
wins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
