<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia hoping drink keeps it out of cramping pickle
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia is taking every precaution to avoid being
in, well, a pickle, in Saturday's Southeastern Conference opener at
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia trainers gave several of the players two ounces of
pickle juice before Tuesday's football practice. The NFL's
Philadelphia Eagles credit the briny liquid for not cramping in
Sunday's 41-14 win at Dallas in 109-degree temperatures. No Eagle
left the game with cramps while several Cowboys were dehydrated.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles had been drinking pickle juice in training camp.
Reportedly, pickle juice contains a combination of salt and
nutrients that help prevent cramps.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to convince Georgia coach Jim Donnan. Several
Bulldogs suffered cramping in last week's 29-7 victory over Georgia
Southern.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast for Columbia, S.C., on Saturday calls for
temperatures near 90 degrees.``We're going with that pickle
juice,'' Donnan said. ``We got a gallon of it and our guys are
going to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Georgia's players have acquired the taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't drinking any pickle juice,'' tight end Randy McMichael
said. ``I don't even eat pickles.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
