<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENNETT A FEW INJURIES FROM QB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Is Drew Bennett the next John Fox?
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway. When Cory Paus separated his shoulder, it meant
that the only quarterbacks left for the next three weeks are Ryan
McCann, Scott McEwan (who has completed two passes in his career)
and freshman walk-on Roman Ybarra.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former starting quarterback who was moved to linebacker,
returned to his old position last season and led USC to a victory
over UCLA, snapping the Bruins winning streak in the rivalry at
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The scene could be set for Bennett, who started two games at
quarterback last season before moving to receiver, to make a
similar move. It just won't happen yet.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff discussed the move but wants Bennett, who has
worked himself into the rotation at receiver and played sparingly
against Alabama, to stick to his position. For now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If disaster struck,'' Toledo said. ``He'd be our disaster
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Faoa returns: Strong-side linebacker Asi Faoa, who is
expected to back up Tony White this season, returns after his
one-game suspension for an off-campus fight. He's currently behind
White and true freshman Brandon Chillar after working with the
scout team for the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Faoa, a redshirt freshman, spent Saturday watching the game in
the stands, sandwiched between the cheerleaders and the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a load off my shoulders,'' he said of his return. ``It
was disappointing to put myself in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury report: Defensive end Kenyon Coleman (cold) and
receiver Brian Poli-Dixon (hamstring) didn't practice Tuesday.
Poli-Dixon suffered his injury early in the second half against
Alabama and didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Ken Kocher tweaked his sprained ankle in
practice Monday and his status is in doubt for Saturday. Kocher was
expected to play sparingly. Linebacker Marcus Reese (sprained foot)
also is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   __ Change that grade:! It turns out it wasn't right tackle Mike
Saffer who was beaten on the sack that separated Cory Paus'
shoulder, as was noted in Monday's report card. Alabama end Jarret
Johnson blew past Saffer, but the responsibility for blocking him
belonged to fullback Matt Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a quarterback gets sacked, everybody thinks it's the
offensive line's fault,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Foster honored: Tailback DeShaun Foster was named the
national player of the week by CNNSI.com and USA Today.com after
rushing for 187 yards and three touchdowns on 42 carries in the
victory over Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   After examining game film, Toledo said Foster gained 105 of his
yards after making contact with defenders. While Foster, who has
battled injuries the past two seasons, had never carried more than
24 times in college, Toledo thinks he's capable of handling such a
load.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't particularly want to run him 42 times a game, but if
that's what we have to do to win the game . . .'' Toledo said.
``Maybe I'll give him two scholarships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
