r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-AIKMAN-TE     09-05 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-AIKMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN FEELS OK, BUT STATUS UNCLEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Troy Aikman was said to be feeling good Tuesday
_ even better than he had hoped _ two days after receiving a ``mild
concussion'' against the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of that encouraging bit of news from Aikman, the
Cowboys are prepared to start Randall Cunningham on Sunday night
against the Arizona Cardinals at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly going about our business today as if Randall
Cunningham is going to be our starting quarterback,'' coach Dave
Campo said. ``I think that's the smart thing to do, and that's the
way we have to approach it.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo talked to Aikman on the phone and shared part of that
conversation at his weekly Tuesday news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy feels very comfortable,'' Campo said. ``I told him my No.
1 concern was his health. He agreed with that, and said that he's
definitely keeping all his options open.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the nature of post-concussion syndrome (headaches,
nausea, dizziness and lethargy), as well as the cumulative effect
of recurring head traumas, there has been much speculation since
Sunday that one of Aikman's options should be retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has had eight concussions with the Cowboys since 1989,
including three in his past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   But Campo said that Aikman never alluded to retirement Tuesday
or that retirement was out of the question, either. It just didn't
come up in conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strictly a health talk ... how he's doing,'' Campo
said. ``We did not discuss if he was playing this week, or next
week, or the week after, or what's happening. I just personally
wanted to find out how he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman took 15 snaps and was gone early in the second quarter
Sunday. He was sacked four times, knocked down eight times in all,
and finished 0-for-5 passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some symptoms prior to that with an inner-ear
infection,'' Campo said. ``So, he's not quite sure where he's at as
far as the \Rconcussion-like\S symptoms are concerned. He feels
very good today, let me put it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said as recently as three months ago that age (33) was on
his side. He said then that age was as attributable to forced
retirement of a player with a history of concussions as the number
of concussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Roger \RStaubach\S. The concussions he had, in
and of themselves, were not the reason that Roger retired,'' Aikman
said in June. ``If he had been 33 or 34 years old, he would not
have retired. We've talked about that. And if Steve Young were 33
or 34, I don't know if he would've retired. Likewise, if I were 38
and had had the concussions that I had last year, maybe I would
have retired. It's hard to say.''
</P>
<P>
   When they retired, Staubach and Young were 38 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman missed two starts last season with concussions received
Oct. 31 and Nov. 8. He visited two neurosurgeons who specialize in
sports-related head traumas. Tests were conducted and a base line
established for the purpose of comparative testing.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones talked this week to Aikman's neurosurgeons as
well as the team's medical staff.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: Before Aikman suits up again, a consensus
must be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a group decision _ including Troy, who will be the
biggest decision-maker,'' Campo said, adding that it will not be
Aikman's call alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be where we're trying to make a
\Rquarterback\S decision on Friday,'' Campo said. ``That definitely
is not in Troy's best interest, and probably not in ours, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham will get a personalized game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different style,'' said Campo, comparing the two quarterbacks.
``Obviously, Arizona will have to prepare for Randall's ability to
scramble now.''
</P>
<P>
   But because Cunningham joined the Cowboys on June 8 and never
before had worked in a timing-route offense, he is expected to
receive a scaled-down version of the playbook.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have an important ``Monday Night Football'' game at
Washington coming up after the Arizona game.
</P>
<P>
   The nod for Sunday night most likely will go to Cunningham,
unless Aikman walks into Valley Ranch today and gives the Cowboys a
reason to believe there's a choice to be made.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-00 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
