u s BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT &LR;      09-05 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SNAP SLIDE ON ZEILE'S HOME RUN
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The key, Todd Zeile said Tuesday afternoon, is to
realize you will come out of it eventually. Don't lose confidence.
Don't change the mechanics of your swing. Don't panic. The hits
have come before, said the Mets first baseman, and they will come
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are in an offensive free-fall, and Zeile has been one
of the fastest to plummet, batting .146 since Aug. 17. The slump
has largely been a mystery to a player who takes pride in
performing well late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this time of year,'' Zeile said. ``This is when I tend
to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile did well Tuesday night, and his heroics lifted the Mets to
their first victory in five games in September. Zeile drove in two
runs, including the game-winner on a home run in the 10th inning,
as the Mets beat the Cincinnati Reds, 3-2. The Mets managed only
six hits, but two came from Zeile, who knocked in two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell (7-4) nearly surrendered a game-winning homer to
Ken Griffey Jr. in the bottom of the ninth. But, with Wendell
waving the ball foul, Griffey's screaming liner landed about four
seats to the right of the foul pole, and the Reds slugger struck
out. Wendell survived the inning, and Zeile's homer off Scott
Sullivan (2-6) have him the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Benitez worked a 1-2-3 10th for his 37th save, and the
Mets won for the eighth time in Rick Reed's last 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   After laboring in his first start off the disabled list on July
17, Reed has been magnificent. In his last nine starts, Reed is 5-2
with a 2.80 earned run average, and he has gone at least six
innings with no more than three earned runs in every start but one.
</P>
<P>
   He worked only one 1-2-3 inning Tuesday night but avoided
trouble with fine defense and one Reds base-running blunder. Dmitri
Young led off the second with a single, and third baseman Robin
Ventura charged a Michael Tucker grounder and threw him out at
first. Young reached second on the play, and Chris Sexton singled
to right.
</P>
<P>
   Young chugged to third and was waved home by the third-base
coach Ron Oester. Timoniel Perez did not make an especially
accurate throw _ it was several feet up the line _ but Young was
even further away from the plate. Catcher Mike Piazza tagged him
for the out, and the inning ended one batter later.
</P>
<P>
   Reed held the Reds hitless until the fifth, when Sexton led off
with a double. Jason LaRue followed with a shot down the third base
line, but Ventura leaped to his right for a diving catch. Pokey
Reese singled in Sexton with two outs, but the damage could have
been worse had Ventura not prevented an extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is in an awful hitting slump _ he has not hit much all
year _ but he is still a superior fielder. Besides the charge and
dive, he made a strong, off-balance throw from behind third base,
bouncing it twice off the turf to catch the speedy Reese on a
grounder in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Reed left in the seventh after throwing his 100th pitch, which
was bunted for a sacrifice by Reds starter Pete Harnisch, who
worked seven strong innings. Rick White came in, got one out, then
allowed a single to Chris Stynes that tied the score, 2-2. John
Franco, in his first game since missing two weeks with a sore left
pectoral muscle, got out of the inning, then worked a scoreless
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Stynes' hit erased what had been a 2-0 Mets lead. The first six
Mets went down in order, but Jay Payton led off the third with a
single. Kurt Abbott flied to the warning track in center, and
Payton took second on the sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had been 0 for their last 12 with runners in scoring
position, but Benny Agbayani ended the string when he punched a
single to right, scoring Payton to give the Mets a 1-0 lead. It
also marked the Mets' first two-hit rally in 28 innings, since the
fourth inning on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They came right back with another two-hit rally. Edgardo Alfonzo
led off the fourth with a double, and after Piazza grounded out and
Ventura popped to left, Zeile rapped a single to left.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Young charged it, anticipating a throw home, but he
failed to get in front of the ball and it skipped past him, all the
way back to the wall. Alfonzo scored easily as Zeile pulled into
third. He was stranded there when Payton struck out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets had a 2-0 lead, and their offense seemed to be
breathing again. Zeile, who had been 7 for 49 with just three runs
batted in, had delivered. But the life-support machine started
whirring again, and the Reds held the Mets scoreless for the next
five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Harnisch out of the game did not help. The rookie John
Riedling struck out two of the three he retired in the eighth, then
Scott Sullivan struck out the side in the ninth, getting Perez,
Alfonzo and Piazza. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
