<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFF-DAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY IN THE LIFE: COWBOYS OFFENSIVE LINEMAN KEEPS GROCERY SHOPPING
SIMPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys offensive lineman Jorge Diaz spends his
weekend pushing around 300-pound defensive linemen. His off day is
spent pushing around a 100-pound shopping cart.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz's errands Tuesday included a stop at Albertson's, which is
located less than a mile from his apartment near Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said he eats breakfast and lunch at the team's complex, but
he usually eats dinner alone in front of the TV. So with his
refrigerator empty of almost everything except ``liquid
beverages,'' it was time for a trip to the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been two weeks since I've really shopped,'' Diaz said.
``I try to go every two to three weeks. The funniest thing about
grocery shopping is you go back to the house and say, `This is all
I got?' I get lazy sometimes and just start eating out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Diaz spent 45 minutes filling up his cart with
$118.54 in groceries, which he paid for with a debit card.
</P>
<P>
   He shops like the bachelor that he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's safe to say that,'' Diaz said. ``I'm not going to
lie. I've got to make stuff that's easy. The frozen foods section
is big for me, because it's easy to throw in the microwave or the
oven. I like things that come with not too much hassle. I keep it
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his mother is a good cook, Diaz never learned for
himself. He admits he needs microwave directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a rule: If it takes longer to cook than to eat, I
don't do it,'' Diaz said. ``I'll go to the drive-through instead.
You can never copy your mom anyway. Moms do it a certain way. ''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, 26, shops without the benefit of a list or coupons. He
knows what he needs, and, with a contract that will pay him a base
salary of $413,000 this season, he can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see a special, like two for a dollar, of course, I'll go
for it,'' said Diaz, who spent four seasons with the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers and owns a house in Tampa, Fla. ``You've got to find the
best buy. But I'm not going to flip through Sunday's paper and clip
out coupons. That's one of those things I don't mess with.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz's cart included five bananas, a pound of roast beef sliced
for sandwiches, Kraft Deli Deluxe cheese slices, large cans of Chef
Boyardee and Star Kist tuna, Ruffles and, from the frozen section,
jalapeno poppers, chicken teriyaki and stuffed chicken breasts. He
also bought two pounds of fresh shrimp, which he used in a
marinara-and-pasta dish he had for dinner Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my speciality _ shrimp marinara and pasta,'' Diaz said.
``That's about the only thing I can cook up real good.''
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, he also threw in two bottles of hot sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like salt and pepper,'' he said. ``Growing up in Texas, I
like hot, spicy food.''
</P>
<P>
   But the staple for Diaz is liquids. Lots and lots of liquids.
Enough fat-free milk, Gatorade, bottled water and Minute Maid fruit
punch to fill the back of his sport utility vehicle. But no pickle
juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say 75 percent of my groceries are liquid,'' Diaz
said. ``It's the most important aisle for me. It's so hot, I want
to make sure I replenish the fluids I lose at practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, who weighs 315 pounds, watches what he eats. The cookie
and ice cream aisles tempted him, but he resisted the urge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to watch the figure,'' Diaz said. ``I try to eat
right. I don't want to overdo it. There is a misconception that if
you sweat off 10 pounds, then you can eat whatever you want. But
you've only lost water weight, not those love handles some of us
have going.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz usually gets in and out of the grocery store without being
recognized, but with a reporter and a photographer tagging along
Tuesday, his excursion attracted a lot of attention.
</P>
<P>
   The butcher slicing Diaz's roast beef asked Diaz what he did for
a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play for the Cowboys, man,'' Diaz said. ``But after last
week, we don't want to talk about it. The tomatoes are pretty
close. People might start throwing them at me. We wouldn't want
that.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
