<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON SECURITY GATE MISFIRES, INJURING GERMAN   OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Germany's defense minister was injured and briefly
hospitalized on Tuesday after a steel security barrier sprang up
beneath his motorcade as it arrived for an honors ceremony at the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The defense minister, Rudolf Scharping, suffered a scrape on his
head and a cut on his foot when his Town Car was struck by the
retractable barricade, just after 4 p.m. The defense attache at the
German Embassy, Brig. Gen. Peter Goebel, and an American security
aide were also slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said that the injuries
were not serious but that all three men were taken to Arlington
Hospital in Virginia this evening for tests. ``His condition is, I
think, very good,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in two years that the Pentagon's security
system had injured a visiting defense minister. In September 1998,
Japan's defense minister, Fukushiro Nukaga, and five others were
injured in a strikingly similar accident at the same barricade.
</P>
<P>
   That accident, attributed to a faulty sensor, prompted the
Pentagon to install a new system for controlling the barricades,
which were installed in 1992 to prevent terrorists from driving too
close to the building.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon noted that thousands of cars had passed through the
barricades. ``We had no problems with the system until today,'' he
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred just before Scharping was to meet with
Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen. When Cohen arrived at the
gate, Scharping was lying on the ground outside the car, which
remained hoisted on the barricade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came right away and came to the gate and greeted him while
he was still lying down,'' said Scharping's spokesman, Detlef Puhl.
</P>
<P>
   A military surgeon treated Scharping, Goebel and the American
security aide, John Salazar, in Cohen's dining room before they
were taken to the hospital. None were wearing seat belts when the
barricade struck their car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
