<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAVERNS-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-CAVERNS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    KARTCHNER IN PERIL(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KATHLEEN INGLEY(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Kartchner Caverns is drying out, and state officials
are ignoring the threat to its delicate formations, say the two men
who discovered the underground fantasy world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been kind of sticking their heads in the sand,'' Gary
Tenen said Tuesday. He and fellow cave buff Randy Tufts, both from
Tucson, discovered Kartchner in 1974 when they wriggled through a
small hole in the ground near Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State Parks took elaborate and expensive steps to
protect the cave's moist environment before opening it to public
tours a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Ziemann, assistant director of Arizona State Parks, points
out that Kartchner was built and opened during a severe drought in
southeastern Arizona. He predicts recent rains will boost the
humidity.
</P>
<P>
   The state also is putting together a panel of scientists to
monitor data from the cave.
</P>
<P>
   Tenen worries that measurements show the evaporation rising
sharply from 1997 to 1999. The temperature also has climbed an
average of more than 1 degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we hear,'' he said, ``the more alarmed we get that
nothing has been done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
