<HEADLINE>
WHICH IS BEST?: DEBATABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ College football fans are debating whether USC or
UCLA is the best team in town. And who's to say it's too early for
that?
</P>
<P>
   Each team opened the season with an impressive, upset victory
over a ranked opponent from a well-thought-of conference. Each is
moving up in the Associated Press poll, USC to No. 11 and UCLA to
No. 16, the first time in five years that both have been this high.
Clearly they're on their way to the top 10 and a battle of
unbeatens Nov. 18 at the Rose Bowl. The winner will be crowned
champion of the Pacific-10, which turns out to be the nation's
strongest conference, as widely predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Who, this side of George W. Bush, wouldn't want part of this
debate?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Paul Hackett, for one. The Trojans coach recoiled in
apparent pain when I offered him a chance to weigh in on the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard for me to worry about a team we're going to
play in nine weeks!'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten weeks, but who's counting?
</P>
<P>
   So how do they stack up? Let's tackle the question from a few
different angles:
</P>
<P>
   __ Rankings: USC actually gained one spot while sitting idle
last weekend, even though Penn State, which it beat in the Kickoff
Classic, came back and lost to Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA gained 10 spots but remained lower than Alabama, which it
beat handily Saturday, because Alabama is still getting credit for
its undefeated offseason. Conclusion: UCLA has all the momentum and
poll voters need new glasses. !bold!Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Victories: USC jumped in front, returning a blocked punt for
a touchdown barely two minutes into the game, was in charge all the
way and barely was tested against Penn State. All we know for sure
about the Trojans' overall strength is that they're better than
Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had to come from behind twice and overcome an injury to
starting quarterback Cory Paus to beat Alabama behind backup Ryan
McCann. It was a gutsy performance. !bold!Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   !tvspt!Experience: USC is starting nine seniors and 14
upperclassmen. UCLA is starting seven seniors and 16 upperclassmen.
</P>
<P>
   Each side can argue that its team is more seasoned, but UCLA's,
with nine juniors in the lineup, enjoys more room to mature.
!bold!Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coaches: Hackett is 15-11 with no bowl victories at USC, and,
with his cap pulled down over his eyes on the sideline, is barely
distinguishable from an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Toledo is 30-17 with one bowl victory at UCLA, and his
prominent belly communicates an appealing image of ``power,''
``prosperity'' and ``excellent pizza in the student union.''
!bold!Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Passing game: USC quarterback Carson Palmer looked better on
the preseason magazine covers than he did on the field against Penn
State, going 10 for 20, for 87 yards, no touchdowns and one
interception.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has the best quarterback in town so far this season. He's
flanker Freddie Mitchell, whose one pass was a perfect strike for a
31-yard touchdown against Alabama. !bold!Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rushing game: USC's Sultan McCullough looked like a Trojans
tailback of old by carrying 29 times for 128 yards against Penn
State, which didn't allow a 100-yard game all last season.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's DeShaun Foster did an even better Anthony Davis
impression by carrying 42 times for 187 yards and three touchdowns,
breaking tackles all over the field, against Alabama. !bold!Edge:
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Defense: USC held the Penn State offense to three points.
Penn State came back to score six on Toledo. All we know for sure
about the Trojans defense is that it's better than Toledo's.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA held the Alabama offense to 10 points and pitched a
second-half shutout, holding the great receiver Freddie Milons to
18 yards. !bold!Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up, and it's pretty obvious who would win if UCLA and
USC played each other this week.
</P>
<P>
   USC would win. USC !ital!always wins when both schools are
top-10 quality. Look it up. It takes a bad UCLA team to beat a good
USC team.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has nine or 10 weeks to work on that.
</P>
</TEXT>
