<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS YET TO UNDERSTAND FULLY WHERE THEY WENT WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good thing the players' hallowed ``24-hour rule'' doesn't apply
to media.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, putting the opening-day meltdown against the Philadelphia
Eagles behind them after 24 hours and turning their attention to
Sunday's matchup against the Arizona Cardinals was probably the
highlight of the Cowboys' week so far.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo said the best thing about the Eagles
game is that the Cowboys have 15 games to go. And he's promising
that things will be different, starting in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Campo also said that the sloppy preseason performances
wouldn't be repeated on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but for those who chronicle the Cowboys' affairs, putting
the Eagles game in the rear-view mirror is not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   To move forward, you have to understand what happened. And even
the Cowboys don't know the answer to that.
</P>
<P>
   Saying ``we weren't ready to play'' and that ``we got whipped
physically'' doesn't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   Not being ready to play for the season opener after downplaying
the importance of preseason games brings into question the
preparation of the coaching staff and the internal fortitude of the
players. What's going to get them ready this week?
</P>
<P>
   Getting whipped physically by the Eagles makes one wonder about
the overall talent on the Cowboys, which, according to the coaches,
is the best since the 1995 Super Bowl team. Either the upstart
Eagles are Super Bowl worthy or there are talent-assessment issues
at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Blaming tackle Erik Williams, as Cowboys officials have, is foul
as well. Sure, Williams' 28-day holdout robbed him of conditioning
and robbed the offensive line of critical cohesion time.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, however, helped create that environment. They
didn't try to force Williams into camp with a fine. And upon his
return, they downplayed the significance of his absence. To bring
it up now, in an effort to explain breakdowns in the offensive
line, is hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, blitzing teams have given the Cowboys fits for the past
three years. Just ask the New Orleans Saints. A full training camp
by Williams wouldn't have made that much difference.
</P>
<P>
   Also, consider that many of the Eagles' sacks were not the
result of communication breakdowns on blitzes but ``look out''
blocks. You know, the kind when a player gets beat, then yells
``look out'' to the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's talent, huh?
</P>
<P>
   More troubling was the Cowboys' inability to offset the Eagles'
defensive stunts with quick passes and hot routes. The
beat-the-blitz thrills that the St. Louis Rams gave us Monday night
are what the Cowboys promised when they brought back their old
offense and signed receiver Joey Galloway to a $42 million contract
during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Campo blamed some of their blitz problems on his high-powered
stars at receiver and quarterback by saying they missed sight lines
and checkoffs _ things they worked on in practice. More quality
work in the preseason might have helped, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Now, a torn anterior cruciate ligament has turned Galloway into
an expensive fan. And quarterback Troy Aikman is in concussion
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Eagles game revealed that defensive end Kavika
Pittman (Denver Broncos) and middle linebacker Randall Godfrey
(Tennessee Titans) were bigger off-season losses than cornerback
Deion Sanders (Washington Redskins). At least that's what the stats
imply.
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain a rushing performance by Eagles running
back Duce Staley that invoked the names of Hall of Famers Jim Brown
and Eric Dickerson? Staley, who has yet to make the Pro Bowl, ran
through, around and over the Cowboys for 201 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Dat Nguyen, Godfrey's replacement, was the fifth-leading tackler
against the Eagles with eight. Among the people in front of him
were safeties Darren Woodson and George Teague, with 13 each, and
cornerback Ryan McNeil, with nine. Pittman's replacement, Ebenezer
Ekuban, tallied only two tackles and was platooned on rushing downs
with Alonzo Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   We also learned that a suspect pass rush remains suspect. Is
defensive end Greg Ellis healthy? The Cowboys still have problems
against mobile quarterbacks. Arizona's Jake Plummer will give them
more fits than Philadelphia's Donovan McNabb.
</P>
<P>
   And we still don't know if the Cowboys can cover anybody in the
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   However, none of that matters now. The Eagles game is in the
past and the Cardinals are all that's important.
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready for some football?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
