<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SIERRA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBEN SIERRA DONS RANGERS UNIFORM FOR FIRST TIME SINCE 1992
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Ruben Sierra walked into the Rangers' clubhouse right
at 4 p.m. yesterday. The broad smile on his face might have
revealed about what was going on inside him more than anything he
said or did.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled as he hugged trainers Danny Wheat and Ray Ramirez, and
equipment manager Zack Minasian, friends from the old days. He did
the same with hitting coach Rudy Jaramillo, who turned him into a
switch hitter way back in 1983, and outfield coach Bobby Jones, who
got sent down when Sierra was called up for the first time on June
1, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   He introduced himself to Mike Lamb, Chad Curtis and other
players he had not met before. He shook hands with bullpen catcher
Ken Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   Then he sat down at his locker and put on a Rangers uniform for
the first time in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a blessing,'' Sierra said. ``I'm very happy to be
here. I want to say thank you to the Rangers and thank God for
bringing me back.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a four-time All-Star, including 1994 with Oakland, and a
four-time Rangers Player of the Year. Manager Johnny Oates said he
once considered Sierra ``the all-around best player in the American
League.'' Now, at 34, he is a September call-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' Sierra said. ``I can't predict the future. I'm
here. I know what's happened. Right now, I feel good. I know I can
still play. I can still hit. I can still run.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra did not play last night in the Rangers' game against the
Chicago White Sox. Oates does not know how much he'll play, if at
all. Sierra is mainly a designated hitter, and Oates believes he
owes that time to Frank Catalanotto and Curtis. Sierra could play
the outfield, but Oates wants to keep looking at Gabe Kapler, Ricky
Ledee and Scarborough Green. Rusty Greer isn't going to sit,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with Ruben,'' Oates said. ``I've known him for a
long time. I don't know what will happen. Let's just watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra said, ``I can't tell you what's on their minds. But I
know what's on my mind. Help the young guys, try to do the best I
can and let them know Ruben is back.''
</P>
<P>
   He is back at least from baseball oblivion. Since the Rangers
traded him on Aug. 31, 1992, Sierra has played for six major-league
teams and three minor-league teams. He has been released four times
since the start of 1997. He played in an Independent League last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him in winter ball,'' Ledee said. ``He said `Look
at me as an example. I was in the big leagues. I was at the top of
the game. But I let myself down. Look at me. Don't let this happen
to you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That really got to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra said, ``I lifted weights and got too big. I lost my
conditioning to hit the ball like I used to. I've learned from
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians cut him in spring training. He asked the
Rangers for a job in spring training, but was turned down. General
manager Doug Melvin suggested Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But Sierra, who has lost much but not all of the bulk that
brought him down, was persistent, and the Rangers' injuries
mounted. He was signed May 1 and sent to the Triple-A Oklahoma
Redhawks. He was given three weeks to show something.
</P>
<P>
   He showed he could hit, with a .326 average, and 18 homers and
82 runs batted in. The Rangers also liked his humble attitude and
his willingness to help young players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was great,'' said shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt, who was also
called up Tuesday. ``He got along great with everyone. He was a
good leader in the clubhouse, especially with the young guys. If a
guy was struggling, he knew what to say. He handled himself well.''
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Dransfeldt said, ``He was awesome. The Ruben Sierra
I saw was the Ruben Sierra who played 10 years in the big
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers aren't sure about that; otherwise, he would have
come up earlier. They would have traded him during the season, but
only one team showed interest. Melvin said that team later backed
off.
</P>
<P>
   But Sierra still believes something is there. The kinder,
gentler Sierra still has his immense pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like Ruben,'' Sierra said. ``I did what I had to do.
They sent me down to prove I can play. That's what I did. They
signed me a month and a week into the season and I still drove in
80-something RBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could still be a full-time player and drive in 80 to
100 runs, Sierra said simply, ``''Si''.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a model to follow. Former Pittsburgh Pirates star Dave
Parker was one of the best players in the game from 1975-81. But,
brought down by drugs and injuries, he had six homers and 29 RBI in
1982, and 12 homers with 69 RBI in 1983. He appeared finished and
was dumped on Cincinnati where his career experienced a rebirth. He
led the National League with a career-high 125 RBI in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a chance,'' Rangers first baseman Rafael
Palmeiro said. ``He's here, man. Give him an opportunity; you never
know what's going to happen. He was good, man, one of the best. I
think it's great he's here. He deserves it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
