<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSIT-STRIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIALLY CRIPPLING L.A. TRANSIT STRIKE AVERTED, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A potential transit strike that could create havoc
in Los Angeles was again averted but unions held the threat of a
walkout at any time over Metropolitan Transit Authority officials.
</P>
<P>
   While unions representing most MTA workers agreed Tuesday to a
five-day breathing period, the Amalgamated Transit Union,
representing more than 1,800 bus and train mechanics, rejected the
extension, saying little progress has been made in negotiations.
The other unions have agreed to strike if the ATU strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking it day to day,'' ATU President Neil Silver said
Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave the MTA a comprehensive proposal. But they've got
brain gridlock. If they don't quit screwing around, you'll see a
strike.''
</P>
<P>
   The critical issues beyond a gap in wage and benefit offers are
work rules and workers' compensation policies that drive up MTA
costs and demands that possible creation of a separate San Fernando
Valley transit zone not impact MTA workers.
</P>
<P>
   The United Transportation Union and the Transportation
Communications International Union, which together represent about
4,950 bus and train drivers and clerical workers, agreed early
Monday to extend their contract deadline to Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   MTA officials said they were encouraged talks would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely happy and appreciate that our transit riders
can continue to depend on the MTA,'' MTA spokesman Barry Liden
said. ``We hope that the ATU will continue to bargain with us.''
</P>
<P>
   No time has been set today for negotiations, but both sides said
they want to meet again as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The MTA board of directors went into closed session Tuesday to
get an update on talks and to give negotiators directions on how to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor was leaning more toward the fact that although the
talks between the MTA and unions were positive, he wishes more
progress had been made,'' said Peter Hidalgo, spokesman for Los
Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made reference to the fact that the board is united in this
whole process and he's very confident in the management of the MTA.
His objective is to make our bus system more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   A strike would clog Los Angeles freeways and shut down bus and
train service to the MTA's 450,000 daily riders, hitting low-income
commuters, seniors, the disabled and students the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   The unions and the MTA have been negotiating for months over new
three-year contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis imposed a 60-day cooling-off period in July to
delay the possibility of a strike until after the Democratic
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The cooling-off period ended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The unions are seeking a variety of improvements to their
pension and benefit packages, as well as more than 12 percent pay
raises over three years, Liden said. The MTA is offering 8.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the major sticking points have to do work rules, work
schedules, creation of the San Fernando Valley transit zone,
subcontracting and workers' compensation. Hundreds of work rules,
some established in the 1930s, govern when someone can collect
overtime, who can do what kind of work and whether bus inspections
take place during rush hour or off-peak times, MTA spokesman Marc
Littman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a situation where a number of bus inspections are done
during peak hours instead of off-hours,'' Littman said. ``It's more
efficient to do bus inspections on off-peak hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The MTA is seeking to streamline those rules to save money and
make the transit system more efficient. But the unions are fighting
to preserve the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Reed, a member of the MTA's Passenger Advisory Committee,
said one rule prohibits bus service attendants who make $13 to $17
an hour from replacing lights that burn out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the lights are burned out, they have to write up a report
and get a $25-an-hour mechanic to come in with a screwdriver and
replace it,'' Reed said. ``This costs us huge amounts of tax
dollars and gives riders less service because they are not making
the most effective use of their resources and assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldy Norton, spokesman for the United Transportation Union,
said the work rules dispute is the major point of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this whole thing is about _ their attempt to
destroy our work rules,'' Norton said. ``I can't get specific about
it because no one would understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   The unions are concerned that the creation of a San Fernando
Valley transit zone _ which would require the MTA to turn its
Valley service over to a new transit service _ could cost union
employees their jobs. Davis has until Sept. 30 to sign a bill that
would protect those workers' jobs by requiring the new transit zone
to hire them.
</P>
<P>
   Another bone of contention involves work schedules. The MTA
wants to add more part-time employees and expand on a four-day,
40-hour work week to save money on overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Bus and rail operators already make an average of $50,000 a
year, not including up to $20,000 in overtime. Mechanics average
$56,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the primary bone of contention,'' Norton said. ``I
can't go into the details. The rules in the transit industry are
quite different from normal work rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The other issue involves workers' compensation claims, which
costs the MTA $70 million a year, six times more than of New York
City Transit. ``That's the equivalent of putting almost 300 buses
on the road,'' Littman said. ``We need to make the MTA safer so
there are fewer claims filed.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
