u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      09-05 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA CLUB ENDORSES HILLARY CLINTON FOR SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton Tuesday won the
endorsement of the Sierra Club, one of the nation's oldest
environmental groups, whose backing set off a duel between the
Senate candidates over who has done more to protect natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Club officials said Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican
Senate candidate, offered inconsistent support for environmental
matters in his eight-year tenure in Congress. And members of the
group said in an interview that Lazio did not demonstrate a firm
grasp of the environmental issues the group studies.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, said Rhea Jezer, the chairwoman of the club's New
York chapter, Clinton ``showed an unequaled depth of knowledge on a
plethora of state and national issues.'' Clinton told the group,
which is nonpartisan but has historically supported Democratic
candidates, that she had worked to push the Clinton administration
to take greater account of children's health in setting air and
water quality standards and, if elected, would pursue protecting
forests and drinking water supplies from development and industrial
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Club members said that although Clinton does not have a
legislative record, her attention over the years to children and
health issues, like breast cancer research and treatment, indicated
she would be a powerful ally for environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe she will continue Daniel Patrick Moynihan's
legacy,'' said Robert Cox, the Sierra Club's national president,
who stood with Clinton as she accepted the endorsement at a park
here bordering the Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio defended his record and suggested the club's endorsement
was politically motivated. Lazio said the club had not endorsed a
Republican for statewide office in New York in more than 10 years,
an assertion club officials did not dispute, though they said they
had endorsed other Republicans in statewide races outside of New
York and in Congressional races in and out of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to presume that it was not on merit, based on the
fact that I have such a strong record on the environment and my
opponent has no record on the environment,'' Lazio said after a
campaign stop in Rochester. ``So it's hard to make a judgment that
it was about anything but politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that although the group had endorsed Lazio in his 1996
congressional race, he later cast votes the club considered
detrimental to the environment. The club said Lazio voted for bills
that would weaken the Superfund toxic waste clean-up program and
reduce spending on measures to curb suburban sprawl, and voted
against attempts to strengthen protection of Utah's wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, his aides said, had believed he might win the club's
endorsement because of his support, among other things, for
legislation to clean up Long Island Sound. But Jezer said Lazio had
a mixed overall record on supporting environmental causes, and fell
short in his interview last month with club members.
</P>
<P>
   She said he did not seem knowledgeable about a variety of issues
and had to ask an aide about one of the issues on which the group
has been most vocal in opposing: New York City's plans to build a
water filtration plant under Van Cortlandt Park in the Bronx. The
club considers the project a misuse of public parkland.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, the group heavily weighs the opinion of
the local chapter nearest the candidate's home, and the Long Island
branch did not give a high rating to Lazio, who represents western
Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio pointed to endorsements by the League of Conservation
Voters, another national organization, in some of his congressional
races. Neither the group's national, nor its New York, directors
have announced an endorsement in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also pointed to his sponsorship of the Long Island Sound
Restoration Act, which provides $80 million annually to help clean
up pollution. He also said he supported legislation to provide
money to preserve open space, reduce gas emissions believed to
contribute to global warming, and explore the environmental effect
of the gasoline additive MTBE.
</P>
</TEXT>
