<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TECH-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TECHNOLOGY NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROADCOM CALLS INTEL PATENT SUIT SPECIOUS
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a patent infringement lawsuit filed last week by
Intel, Broadcom issued a statement saying the suit was specious
litigation aimed at discouraging Intel employees from seeking jobs
at Broadcom. Broadcom said that it had not infringed upon any Intel
patents. ``The notion that we need to misappropriate Intel's
technology to compete is nonsense,'' said Henry T. Nicholas,
Broadcom's president and chief executive, in the statement. He said
it was ``widely recognized in the industry and investment community
that Broadcom, not Intel, is the leader'' in digital cable TV,
cable modem ``and other key 21st-century technologies.'' Nicholas
said Broadcom would defend itself vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   WEB CONSULTANT ISSUES EARNINGS WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Echoing a familiar refrain in the Web consulting industry,
Xpedior warned that it expected revenue in the third quarter to
drop about 10 percent from the $62.9 million in the second quarter
of this year, largely because of diminished demand from dot-com
clients. Wall Street, in turn, reacted as it did when it first
heard that concern last week from two other companies: Xpedior's
stock dropped $2.56, or 23.7 percent, to close at $8.25, well off
its 52-week high of $34.75. It did not seem to matter that the
company estimated that third-quarter revenue would climb 65 percent
from the $34.5 million posted in the 1999 quarter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IBM TO USE AT&AMP;T DATA CENTERS
</P>
<P>
   To help meet growing demand from business customers that
outsource management of their Internet operations to IBM's Global
Services unit, IBM said it agreed to lease space in nine AT&AMP;T data
centers. IBM said that the deal, valued at $450 million, would
allow it to begin selling Internet services and computer capacity
at AT&AMP;T centers in the New York, Chicago, and Phoenix areas by the
end of the year and in six other cities by the third quarter of
2001. IBM now operates 12 Web-operation sites in the United States,
6 of them in partnership with other vendors. Earlier this year, it
announced plans to create 56 more sites around the world, including
28 sites in the United States with Qwest Communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
